<HEADLINE>
NO GOOD TECH PROFIT GOES UNPUNISHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The irony of this week's plunge by the Nasdaq
index was the New Economy market getting a dose of the Old Economy
market's medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Investors committed to traditional value plays have found to
their recent dismay that no good profit goes unpunished on Wall
Street. Even respectable performances by Old Economy blue-chippers
get hammered by money managers when otherwise respectable profits
are only a tad under expectations.
</P>
<P>
   This week, however, the Dow Jones industrial average recovered
spectacularly from a near-death experience, while Nasdaq struggled
to keep from going into a death spiral. The Dow was up almost 820
points Wednesday and Thursday, while Thursday's 135-point gain in
the Nasdaq recovered about 30 percent of what it lost the first
three days of the week.
</P>
<P>
   A snapshot from Wednesday's trading was perhaps a telling
example of how dramatically the tables have been turned. The
venerable financial institution and Dow component J.P. Morgan,
valued at only 11 times earnings, rose 6 percent. Across the way at
Nasdaq, techno-darling Yahoo, which was trading at 1,600 times its
earnings, saw its stock fall 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Was this turnabout a sign that fundamentals are catching up with
New Economy stocks? Not so as you can tell. The tech-laden Nasdaq
swooned even as one of its strongest components, Oracle, reported a
good profit gain. The Dow's pyrotechnics, meantime, have come in
the absence of any extraordinary revelations. Because most Dow
companies are the same sound enterprises they were last week, their
resurgence could be a sign that value is back in vogue.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq's 466-point clobbering from Monday to Wednesday was a
loss of more than 9 percent from Friday's record 5,049 close, and
Thursday's rebound came just in time to avoid a descent into
correction territory.
</P>
<P>
   Could Nasdaq's rocky week signal a leak in the high-tech bubble?
It's too early to tell, but the abrupt sell-off may mean investors
have begun to heed warnings about the dangers of speculation. Thus,
it may not represent the buying opportunity other Nasdaq market
breaks have offered.
</P>
<P>
   This high-tech stock slide extends far beyond America. Markets
in Asia and Europe as well have seen their tech sector battered
this week. Hong Kong's top securities regulator was prompted
Wednesday to echo recent warnings by his U.S. counterpart,
exhorting investors to evaluate profitability prospects before
buying a ompany's stock.
</P>
<P>
   One seeming anomaly may be instructive. Seven of Nasdaq's 10
most active issues Wednesday were up. This may be meaningful
considering how Nasdaq's dramatic rise in recent years has been
fueled by relatively few stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nasdaq comprises almost 4,800 stocks, only 35 accounted
for three-quarters of last year's 85 percent gain. Because some of
those premiere issues were prominent gainers Wednesday, this could
signal further weakening of the rest of the index's stocks.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the speculative dot-com mania could be winding down even
as Nasdaq's best companies remain good investments. The strength of
Nasdaq's leadership has more than made up for its narrowness. This
week's message may be that Nasdaq's structural weakness has become
too severe to be masked by the high-flying fortunes of a handful of
its components.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 0002EST &QL; 
