<SLUG> BC-HMO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMOS WARN OF HIGHER PREMIUMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DELLA DE LAFUENTE  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HMOs went on the attack Thursday, warning that health care costs
in Arizona will skyrocket and coverage will suffer if consumers are
given the right to sue their health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of Humana, PacifiCare and Blue Cross and Blue Shield
of Arizona made the dire predictions after three HMOs agreed
Wednesday to support a right-to-sue provision that could be
introduced Monday in the Arizona Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a bad policy,'' said Geoff Jaroch, a spokesman
for PacifiCare, which estimates that premium costs for the HMO's
members would climb 4 percent to cover the health provider's
anticipated legal liability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't feel it brings any value to employers or their
employees who would pay for it,'' said Humana President William J.
Howard, adding that premiums for Humana's 85,000 members could jump
10 percent to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross/Blue Shield opposes liability protections for
consumers as a public policy issue. It would support a compromise
over such legislation if an appeals process for resolving
consumers' concerns remained mandatory, said Richard Hannon, the
health plan's senior vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers leading the fight for a right-to-sue provision were
rankled by the HMOs' efforts to sink the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blatant last-minute attempt to sabotage a reasonable
agreement that will bring more protections to the consumer,'' said
Rep. John Verkamp, R-Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   The HMOs were using ``scare tactics'' to convince lawmakers that
costs would climb well beyond the 4.5 percent estimate that the
plans initially suggested, said Sen. Ann Day, R-Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Intergroup, Cigna and United Healthcare struck a
deal with the Arizona Trial Lawyers Association opening the door
for a right-to-sue amendment to be added to House Bill 2600. The
amendment would allow Arizonans in employer-sponsored group health
plans to sue their health maintenance organizations, with the
option of bypassing a system for appealing HMO decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Intergroup and United Healthcare signed on to the agreement
because consumers say they want more accountability frODGB:Sf
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
