<SLUG> BC-BMW-ROVER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMW TO ABANDON ROVER CARS AND SELL LAND ROVER TO FORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Adds quotes from Ford's chief executive. Grafs 3, 4 and 12
are new.)  
(with ROVER-OUTLOOK) 
(lh) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS with ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Six years and nearly $6 billion after
buying the Rover Group, BMW of Germany abandoned the British
automaker Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   BMW essentially gave Rover's money-losing car business to a
little-known group of British investors. And it negotiated a deal
to sell the Land Rover line of sport utility vehicles to Ford Motor
Co. for just under $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really can't think of a better group of brands and products
than the Land Rover Group,'' Jacques Nasser, Ford's chief
executive, said at Ford's headquarters in Dearborn, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Ford already owns another venerable British brand, Jaguar, and
Nasser said that Jaguar and Land Rover dealers worldwide would
probably team up to sell more of both brands. ``We've always
referred to the Range Rover as the Jaguar of off-road vehicles,''
Nasser said. ``They fit together in a showroom very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's moves by BMW marked a retreat from a strategy of
getting bigger and broader, at a time that rivals around the world
are merging and forming alliances.
</P>
<P>
   The ownership upheavals came as a shock to Rover's 30,000
workers in Britain as well as to the British government, which has
been hoping to salvage one of Rover's main factories with a
taxpayer subsidy of around $220 million.
</P>
<P>
   BMW, based in Munich, bought Rover in 1994 in the hope of
expanding beyond its market for luxury vehicles and of keeping up
with larger competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The steps Thursday represented a reversal for BMW and more
uncertainty for Rover's workers, whose new boss will be Alchemy
Partners, an investor group that includes a former Rover executive,
Kevin Morley.
</P>
<P>
   Because nearly half of BMW's shares are controlled by the Quandt
family of Germany, which has so far rejected all overtures, BMW's
independence seemed assured for now. But analysts say the pressures
are increasing. Volvo of Sweden sold its car business last year to
Ford. And earlier this week, the Agnelli family of Italy agreed to
sell 20 percent of Fiat to General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   Though BMW did not disclose the terms, Alchemy Partners is
expected to pay little, if any, money up front, and BMW will assume
many of Rover's debts.
</P>
<P>
   BMW said the expense of shedding the Rover car business would
cost about 3.15 billion euros, or $3.06 billion. As a result, BMW
will report an annual loss of about $2.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   BMW was officially silent Thursday on the future of Land Rover,
the profitable and growing sport utility business, but was expected
to announce the deal on Friday. Nasser discussed the deal with
reporters gathered in Dearborn Thursday after the boards of Ford
and the BMW Group approved a memorandum of understanding on the
sale.
</P>
<P>
   The jettisoning of Rover came as a relief to the parent
company's investors, who have viewed the British car line as a
black hole for money.
</P>
<P>
   Rover lost more than $1 billion in 1998 and $1.2 billion in
1999. Its annual car sales plunged 24.9 percent last year, to
251,000 vehicles.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
