<SLUG> BC-RAFTING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RAFT TO PLY COLORADO
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By PETER CORBETT
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An electric-powered raft will surge into white water next month
in a test run to silence critics of motorboats in the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades, environ mentalists have clashed with
com mercial river outfitters in a noisy debate over oar-power vs.
motors of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   And the ruckus isn't likely to end soon, despite outfitters
experiment ing with quieter, pollution-free elec tric motors and
switching from two-stroke internal combustion en gines, which spew
more fumes and oil, to four-stroke engines.
</P>
<P>
   An electric-powered raft will depart April 3 from Lees Ferry for
the 275-mile trip down the Colorado River.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's progress, but it's still not a wilderness experience
when you have a motor getting you through there,'' said Rob Smith,
Sierra Club South west staff director.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Club, Grand Canyon Trust and other environmental groups
want to rid the Canyon of motorized rafts, which carry the bulk of
river runners.
</P>
<P>
   Outfitters say they need motors to ease congestion and to give
time-strapped passengers a chance to see the entire stretch of
river in a week, half the time of an oar trip.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the divisive issue has long-term implications for
the Can yon, wilderness protection, the $25 million-a-year
river-running in dustry and Arizona tourism in gen eral.
</P>
<P>
   Braving the Colorado's white water to raft through the mile-deep
geolog ical wonderland is one of America's premier outdoor
adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Canyon National Park offi cials recently backed off the
issue because there was no consensus on a solution, said Maureen
Oltrogge, a National Park Service spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The service recommended eliminat ing motors in 1979, but
Congress halted the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the service shelved efforts to revise a plan to
address motor use and a controversy over private vs. commercial
river-use per mits.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen commercial river companies, half based in Arizona,
carried 19,090 passengers through the Canyon last year, said Mark
Grisham of Grand Canyon River Outfitters Association.
</P>
<P>
   Motorized rafts carried about 77 percent of them at an average
price of $218 per day, he said. Oar trips cost $215.
</P>
<P>
   Motors allow the outfitters to run the river at different speeds
so the boats aren't all bunched together, Grisham said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith of the Sierra Club argues that outfitters prefer motors
because it allows them to ``pump a lot of people through the Grand
Canyon.''
</P>
<P>
   Outfitters bristle at the criticism. They consider themselves
environ mentalists who have worked for decades on protection of the
river.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Seyler of Phoenix-based Ari zona River Runners Inc. says
the opposition is coming from ``right-wing-type environmental
groups.''
</P>
<P>
   He points to the voluntary conver sion to four-stroke engines
and, ultimately, electric motors, as indica tive of the outfitters'
commitment to reducing noise and emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Grisham said Canyon outfitters have converted 85 percent of
their engines to four-stroke and will complete the switch next
year, costing about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Next month's test will involve a second-generation electric
motor mounted on a 36-foot raft. Grisham said a diesel generator
will recharge batteries for the motor, which puts out the
equivalent of 21 horsepower, about a third less powerful than the
standard four-stroke engine.
</P>
<P>
   Recharging the batteries is the weak link in the system. The
outfitters association is pursuing development of fuel cells that
could ultimately power the boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The driving motivation is to see if technology can help us
solve the noise issue,'' Grisham said, adding that the outfitters
want to be ``good neighbors in the Canyon.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, it may be up to Congress to settle the issue as part
of wilder ness designation for the Canyon, said Oltrogge of the
Park Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
