<HEADER>
A9410 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-BARNEYKARBANK-KAN &LR;      03-17 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNEYKARBANK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 50 YEARS, DEVELOPER BARNEY KARBANK'S STRATEGY STILL STANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK P. COUCH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Real estate developer Barney Karbank doesn't
waste his good fortune at casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Karbank's luck, like his money, is too valuable to throw at
slots.
</P>
<P>
   So when Karbank's children treated him and his wife to a 50th
wedding anniversary celebration last December in Las Vegas, Karbank
bet a measly 25 cents, won $20 and stopped when the winnings were
gone.
</P>
<P>
   It's a safe bet that Karbank doesn't waste profits from small
wagers that pay off big. He usually heads straight to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   At 76, Karbank has been helping shape Kansas City for one-third
of the city's life _ developing property in all corners of town,
helping assemble the ground for the Truman Sports Complex, serving
on the Kansas City Plan Commission.
</P>
<P>
   For five decades, Karbank has survived the booms and busts of
real estate with a simple strategy: build and hold.
</P>
<P>
   Karbank occasionally buys a building, rarely sells and never
refinances a property once it's paid off. He has never lost a
parcel to foreclosure, he said, nor has he sold one to avoid a
creditor's noose.
</P>
<P>
   His office near the top of One Kansas City Place lets him survey
vast chunks of the property he has developed over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's at the top of the industrial real estate market heap in
Kansas City,'' said Roger Cohen, a former Karbank partner who now
heads his own firm.
</P>
<P>
   Even outsiders recognize that Karbank sits at the summit of
Kansas City's market.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when New York real estate and gambling impresario
Donald Trump was considering the purchase of the Flamingo Hilton
Casino, he asked Karbank to join the venture. The boat sits at the
edge of a Karbank property, one of more than 100 totaling several
million square feet.
</P>
<P>
   As with his recent trip to Vegas, Karbank didn't risk much with
Trump, passing on the offer. Karbank said he preferred to focus on
the warehouses and production plants he rents to other companies.
</P>
<P>
   But visiting Trump's lofty New York offices capped a remarkable
journey for Karbank, the son of a fish market operator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started without money, without education, without family
connections,'' said Karbank, who uses a cane because of a childhood
bout with polio.
</P>
<P>
   Karbank's father urged young Barney to consider the real estate
business after noticing that customers who were developers wore the
best clothes and drove the nicest cars.
</P>
<P>
   So he became an unpaid clerk for James B. Welsh Realty. In 1947
he joined Charles F. Curry Co., where he learned such niceties of
the trade as pushing brooms, running errands and selling houses.
</P>
<P>
   For Karbank, the experience was an education in what he didn't
want to do, and he vowed to find a corner of the business that was
a better fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided I wanted to own buildings that were as passive as
possible, and that was mostly industrial properties,'' Karbank
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950 he paid $25 for a desk and a swivel chair in Curry's
office and started B.A. Karbank &AMP; Co. He was 26 years old.
</P>
<P>
   He traveled to a conference in Chicago in 1952 that helped set
the course of his career. At the meeting he met Trammell Crow, a
budding legend in real estate circles, and had dinner with another
developer, Max Phillipson, whose bullish outlook revved Karbank's
ethic of hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Back in his hotel room that night, Karbank couldn't sleep, so he
flipped through the pages of the Saturday Evening Post. Gazing at
an advertisement for Borg-Warner Corp., Karbank noticed that the
company was next door to the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning he made a cold call on Borg-Warner executives,
offering to construct a building for the company's Kansas City
operation. The Borg-Warner executives said they had decided the
previous day to proceed with a Kansas City expansion.
</P>
<P>
   They sent Karbank back to Kansas City to meet a local
Borg-Warner employee. Back home, another coincidence: that
Borg-Warner official remembered attending third grade with Karbank.
</P>
<P>
   Luck and hard work paid off. Karbank constructed his first
building _ a structure at 2615 Holmes St. He charged Borg-Warner
$410 a month on a 12-year lease. The first $400 covered the
mortgage payment and $10 paid for a life insurance policy to pay
the mortgage in case he died.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a profit in that deal. But Karbank still owns the
building and rents it for at least $2,500 a month _ long after
paying off the debt.
</P>
<P>
   The build-and-hold strategy lets him drive a Mercedes and run
his real estate company like a bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of lending people dollars, we're lending people bricks
and mortar,'' Karbank said.
</P>
<P>
   While other developers borrow money against properties, Karbank
has used his leverage to build relationships with tenants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not merchant builders,'' Karbank said. ``If you're going
to come to the dance with us, you're going to leave the dance with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, General Electric Co. rented space from Karbank but
concluded that the property didn't fit its needs. Karbank said he
let the company out of its lease without a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Karbank said he could afford to let General Electric off the
hook because lease payments from other properties could bridge the
gap while he sought a new tenant. It also put him in good graces
with General Electric, which now occupies several Karbank-owned
properties.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric has been an important relationship that Karbank
has nurtured for decades.
</P>
<P>
   One of his original GE contacts resulted from a death-defying
visit to the doctor nearly 25 years ago when he had an allergic
reaction to an iodine solution used in a kidney test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a violent reaction,'' Karbank said. ``They really
thought I was a goner.''
</P>
<P>
   The physician revived Karbank, ``but he was so concerned he sat
there with me until I came back to life,'' Karbank said.
</P>
<P>
   In the conversation that followed, the doctor offered to
introduce Karbank to a GE division manager who was coming to town.
Karbank accepted the offer, which eventually led to a deal with
General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Such constant deal making _ even at death's door _ doesn't
surprise colleagues in the industry. Veteran Kansas City developer
Chuck Hunter simply said, ``It's in his blood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
