<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAS IMPACT ON BUDGETS FAR EASIER THAN IN '80S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LIDIA KELLY  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drivers who see only rising gas prices ahead are forgetting to
look in the rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Current prices are only 56 per cent of their level from the
early 1980s after adjusting for infla tion.
</P>
<P>
   Even more significant, the hit on our pocketbooks is much gen
tler than it was two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, 15 gallons of gas cost $20, 10 percent of the average
weekly per capita income of $200 in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Arizonans paid the same amount for gas but spent
only 4.5 percent of their income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Energy costs are a smaller portion of total costs than they
were in the '80s,'' said Tracy Clark, associate director of the
Arizona State University Eco nomic Outlook Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of expanding auto mation in our lives, there have been
more efficiencies making people less sensitive to energy prices
than 20 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with gas prices hitting an all-time high in Arizona this
week, some perspective on gas prices may do little to cool angry
motorists.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in less than a month, a convoy of inde
pendent truckers rolled through the streets of the nation's capital
Thursday, seeking relief from fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate cause of higher prices has been the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Coun tries' year-old decision to cut
production, after the cartel suf fered several years of low prices.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been soaring oil prices that have hit consumers
on all sides: higher airfares, higher prices to deliver FedEx
packages, and even lower prices for their stock investments.
</P>
<P>
   But why is gas in Tucson an average 3 cents a gallon higher than
in Phoenix? Car owners in the state's rural areas pay an average
$1.65 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   George Gaspar, who has fol lowed the petroleum industry for
decades at Milwaukee-based Rob ert W. Baird &AMP; Co., said differ
ences in sticker prices at the pumps are spurred by four fac tors:
</P>
<P>
   Competition: The more gas stations in the neighborhood, the
greater the likelihood of lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Storage capacity: Some stations have larger storage tanks, which
means they can stock more gas that they pur chased at lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Refineries: Some that supply gasoline have higher wholesale
prices than others.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation costs: The far ther the fuel travels from a
refinery, the higher the price at the pump. That doesn't hold true
for a place like San Francisco, whose higher cost of living can
cels out the lower price of fuel from nearby refineries.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity between Phoenix and Tucson prices shows the impact
of refineries, said Paul Oves, vice president for public affairs at
Tosco, which owns 350 Circle K convenience stores in Arizona, most
of which operate a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Tucson had lower prices than Phoenix, Oves said,
because Phoenix is supplied by California refineries and Tuc son by
western Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Some California refineries have been hit by fires that de pleted
their holdings, resulting in higher prices. Texas suppliers have
been operating smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when the shortage has touched all parts of the country,
competition has taken over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppliers are much more ag gressive in Phoenix than in Tuc
son,'' Oves said. ``(The disparities) are strictly a function of
the competitive nature of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The remote stations in the rural areas suffer the most. Gas
sellers pay a price that is im posed by the jobbers, or delivery
companies, to which they have to add at least 3 to 5 cents to cover
fixed costs.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the demand for fuel has not decreased, said Bruce John
son, director of external affairs at Atlantic Richfield Co..
</P>
<P>
   He added that after the March 27 meeting of OPEC, gas prices
should go down. But it may take awhile before lower numbers reach
the pump.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction in supply had caused the oil companies to draw on
their inventories, bringing them down by 15 percent from a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Daily consumption in the United States exceeds import and
domestic production by 600,000 barrels a day, approximately the
monthly fuel usage in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Even if OPEC decides to in crease its production, the oil will
go first to rebuild inventories, which could take three months
under the most optimistic sce nario, Gaspar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty difficult be cause everybody else in the world
is scrambling for oil,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only after inventories are be ing rebuilt would street prices
start to fall significantly.
</P>
<P>
   If crude oil prices, now float ing above $30 a barrel, fell to
$25 to $26, gas prices should drop by about 12 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then you need to remem ber that summer is coming and the
demand will increase,'' Gas par said. ``So, the earliest prices may
start coming down is early fall.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
