<HEADLINE>
WOMEN PLEAD GUILTY TO $1.58 EMBEZZLEMENT FROM BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOYCE SMITH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Two former employees at a Westport bank
facility pleaded guilty Thursday to a decade-long embezzlement of
about $1.58 million that, among other things, financed gambling
sprees and vacations in exotic locales.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Harris, 46, and Evelyn J. Morgan, 45, both of Kansas City,
waived indictment and pleaded guilty to single counts of felony
embezzlement by an officer of a federally insured bank, according
to Stephen L. Hill Jr., U.S. attorney for the Western District of
Missouri. The women appeared before U.S. District Judge Fernando J.
Gaitan Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America, which now owns the bank at 331 Westport Road,
had no comment on the embezzlement. The bank operated under several
different names and owners over the course of the embezzlement
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FBI, this wasn't a typical embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
   Most embezzlers work alone, not in teams. And although most
embezzlers are caught in a matter of months, this scheme went on
for 10 years. Moreover, the women had to confess to bring it to the
bank's attention.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most unusual factor was that the women stole the
funds independently, then began to cover for each other.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, the vault teller, and Harris, the backup vault teller,
both had worked for the banking facility for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records:
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1989 and continuing until their termination in March
1999, the women worked together to steal varying amounts of money
directly from the bank's vault. They concealed each other's thefts
through false records that allowed cash shortages to go unnoticed
during audits of the vault.
</P>
<P>
   Each woman said they took about half of the money that was
embezzled for personal use.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan was the first of the pair to pocket the money. But when
she took a vacation, Harris tried to balance the vault and came up
$19,000 short.
</P>
<P>
   While Harris suspected Morgan, she didn't report her. Instead
Harris took $10,000 herself and covered for the missing funds on
the vault blotter.
</P>
<P>
   When Morgan returned from vacation, Harris asked if she knew
about the shortfall. Morgan said she did.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Harris asked Morgan if she knew the vault was
short another $10,000. Morgan said she did.
</P>
<P>
   From then on the two were in a partnership to plunder the bank.
</P>
<P>
   To keep from getting caught, at least one of the women had to be
there nearly every day. During audits, they filled out ``cash out''
tickets for the amounts they had taken to cover up the shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Harris used some of the funds to take friends on trips to Las
Vegas, the Bahamas, and Mexico. She gambled as much as $30,000 a
trip on cruises. She bought a new Cadillac, was building a new
home, and invested in a mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   Harris's husband was out of town most of the time on business,
she said, so he did not notice that she was flush with extra cash.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Gorin, attorney for Morgan, said his client did not spend
any of the funds on herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could have bought a big house, a sailboat, vacations,
diamonds, but she didn't,'' Gorin said. ``She used the funds to
help people out.''
</P>
<P>
   The embezzlers' closest call came in 1996, when the bank
facility lowered the vault limit at the Westport branch. At the
time they had already stolen more than $900,000, according to court
records. The embezzled funds were insured by the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   They began using ``cash in transit'' tickets in addition to the
``cash out'' tickets to conceal their theft.
</P>
<P>
   By late 1998, however, both were struggling with their guilt.
They agreed to turn themselves in and went to Hill's office with
their attorneys. The bank terminated them in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got started on something that just snowballed and when
they realized how bad it was they decided to make things right and
turn themselves in,'' said Kurt Marquart, attorney for Harris.
``Their conscience was bothering them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill asked the FBI to investigate. Even though the women were
pleading guilty, evidence needed to be presented to show that they
would have been convicted in a court of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you have to reconstruct what happened,'' said Jeff Lanza,
special agent for the FBI in Kansas City. ``Given the situation of
the bank changing hands several times made it a little more time
consuming.''
</P>
<P>
   The women did not keep track of the total funds they took. But
the FBI and the bank used the ``cash out'' and ``cash in transit''
documents to come up with the $1.58 million figure.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plea agreement, it is estimated the women could each
serve 30 to 37 months in prison. They also could be subject to
restitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point they knew it was going to be discovered,'' Lanza
said. ``It must have been very difficult for them to carry it for
so long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
