<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SOFT ON CAMPAIGN FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, March 17:
</P>
<P>
   With each fund-raiser, this year's New York Senate race offers
new and brazen lessons in the nature of unrestrained political
money-raising. Both Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rudolph Giuliani are
scrambling for funds, speeding into the history books as
participants in what is expected to be the costliest race ever for
the U.S. Senate. Each new fund-raising gimmick expands the coffers
of these two candidates even as it chips away at their reputations.
The public is left to worry that big donors will be seeking a
payback later.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the first lady has spent a good deal of time this week
trying to explain away questions about a recent fund-raiser by
Pakistani-Americans who wanted President Clinton to visit Pakistan
and were willing to contribute $50,000 in individual donations to
Hillary Clinton in hopes she would help arrange it. She told the
Pakistanis she agreed that the president should go, and told the
press a few days later that if anybody thought contributions to her
were a route to influencing him, that was ``dead wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, however, she should know that appearance matters,
especially as she paves the first campaign trail for a president's
wife. As such she has a special obligation not to peddle, or even
appear to peddle, her connection to her powerful husband. She needs
to be more sensitive to the timing of her fund-raisers and should
make it clear to donors that their gifts will not buy her
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Next came the news that Giuliani had set up a ``victory''
committee to collect largely unregulated soft money, to compete
with a similar committee that Clinton established last year.
Giuliani had delayed for several months, thus raising hopes that he
would find a way to head off a soft-dollar-for-soft-dollar
competition with Clinton. Only a few weeks ago the Clinton and
Giuliani campaigns exchanged somewhat testy letters about the
possibility of a negotiated campaign-finance truce. The exchange of
notes, however, never led to the talking stage, and each side is
now busily blaming the other for the breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani talks about leveling the playing field, but there is
only one real way to do so at this stage. That is for both sides to
find a way to junk the soft-money provision that distorts the
nation's campaign finance laws by pretending the money is going to
the national parties when it is really intended to assist the
candidates. These his-and-her ``victory'' committees may be a
victory only for special interests. New York's Senate candidates
are political superstars, who should have no trouble raising money
under the regular federal limits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
