<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-TEACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GRAPPLING WITH THE TEACHER SHORTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, March 17:
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office and both houses of the New York State
Legislature have responded to the state's impending teacher
shortage with a flurry of proposals aimed at attracting people into
the profession, keeping them on the job longer and directing
qualified teachers where they are most needed _ to low-performing
schools. Although the most comprehensive plan so far has come from
the Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno, other participants have
some impressive ideas. But it is important that the various
measures be targeted to benefit the poorest students.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage is especially perilous in New York City, which
could lose as many as 50,000 of its 78,000 teachers to retirement
in the next five years. The Senate proposal offers several methods
for preventing the drain, the most crucial of which is a pension
incentive that allows senior teachers who would ordinarily retire
at age 55 to pay their pensions into an annuity and continue
teaching without an earnings limitation. In addition, the Senate
plan offers a $10,000 salary bonus for master teachers who become
nationally certified, and includes a provision that would allow
teachers to retain the seniority they now lose when they move from
neighboring states into New York. The Assembly version, meanwhile,
usefully proposes financial incentives to teachers who volunteer to
work in low-achieving schools. Both Gov. George Pataki and Bruno
have wisely offered plans that would defray the cost of college
tuition for new college graduates who turn to teaching. Brno has
suggested offering $3,400 cash grants.
</P>
<P>
   Both houses have wisely proposed expanding the Tuition
Assistance Plan, which helps many prospective teachers attend
college. But it is crucial that the Legislature remove the cap that
was placed on the program several years ago when times were lean.
Every dollar counts for students who are struggling to stay in
college.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
