<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9430 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-1STLD-W     03-17 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THORNTON KEEPS PEACE ON THE COURT FOR ST. JOHN'S
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Fla.)  (ADDS game result and details of Thornton performance in lede, 8th
graf and penultimate graf.) 
 (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Late Wednesday evening Darlene Grimes was
talking about the hectic week she had already had. While her son,
Bootsy Thornton, was in Tucson leading St. John's to a narrow
first-round victory in the NCAA basketball tournament, Grimes was
back in Baltimore, where she is a medical assistance specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes goes from hospital to hospital helping patients fill out
insurance paperwork. The hardest part this week has been carrying
around the heavy silver trophy her son won last week as the Big
East tournament's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   The trophy has become a great conversation piece. On Monday she
took it to Johns Hopkins University Hospital, where doctors, nurses
and patients admired it and offered their congratulations. Then
Tuesday it was off to Liberty Medical Center. Thursday she was
taking it to Union Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it with me when I got my shoes repaired,'' she said,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   In each place, faces lighted up because Darlene Grimes' face was
glowing. This was a happy story. Thornton was born in East
Baltimore, where he attended Dunbar High School and played for the
school's famed basketball program. He played at Tallahassee
Community College for two seasons before coming to St. John's. His
success is the story of a Baltimore youngster's thriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to me that he's made it this far,'' his mother
said by telephone. ``Since he was 8 years old this has been his
dream. He wanted to play college basketball, wanted to play in the
NBA. I wanted him to get a good education and be an artist. I never
thought he'd get this close.''
</P>
<P>
   What she is most proud of, she said, is her son's independent
mind. Earlier in the season, when teammates wore Band-Aids on their
cheeks to commemorate Erick Barkley's NCAA suspension, Thornton
went Band-Aid-less. With so many athletes sporting diamond studs in
their ears, Thornton refuses.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Thornton, in his typiacally cool fashion, bailed
St. John's out of a potential nightmare first-round elimination. He
hit key shots, grabbed critical rebounds and handed out timely
assists, and, finally, hit the last two points of the game.
Unfortunately for Thornton, a remarkable senior season _ one that
included a dramatic basket to beat Duke _ has been overshadowed by
NCAA investigations and daily disclosures surrounding Barkley, his
backcourt mate. For all his on-court accomplishments, Thornton
achieved national attention last weekend for a locker-room
altercation. He and Barkley exchanged heated words at halftime of a
Big East tournament semifinal game. Pushes nearly came to shoves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the paper that day,'' Thornton said with a hint of
humor. ``No matter how many good games I had, I never seemed to
make the back page; but one little negative thing happened and I
get headlines, `Erick and Bootsy Fight.' That bothered me a
little.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he and Barkley are friends, not just teammates. ``If
it's just on court and not off the court, it carries over on the
court,'' he said. ``So you have to have a great off-the-court
relationship as well as on-court.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton's real first name is Marvis. His mother, who separated
from Bootsy's father and was married several years ago, said when
she was pregnant she and Bootsy's father had debates over how they
would name the baby. ``At first he said he wanted the name Marvis,
because his name is Marvis and his father's name is Marvis; then he
said he didn't care,'' she said. ``I was thinking about naming him
Teon Terrell Thornton.''
</P>
<P>
   His father changed his mind again. ``So we named him Marvis
Thornton III,'' Grimes said. ``But I just couldn't call him Marvis.
So I tried to come up with different nicknames.''
</P>
<P>
   She settled on one inspired by Bootsy Collins, the trendsetting
bass player for Parliament-Funkadelic, the band that laid the
foundation for generations of rappers. ``I really liked him,'' she
said. ``I remembered songs he made that I liked, like
``Flashlight.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton is familiar with his namesake. ``I know he was back in
the day with George Clinton and everybody; people going to
concerts, wearing shiny suits,'' he said. ``Bootsy Collins wearing
those big star glasses _ that's what caught my attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Two decades later the nickname is fitting. Thornton has assumed
the bass player's role for St. John's. He moves without the ball,
deftly uses space, and has an economy of movement that keeps the
offense going. When nerves begin to fray, the understated Thornton,
standing in the back of the rhythm section, exhorts teammates to
keep a cool head, to channel the anger and frustration into the
game. Thursday night, he provided desperately needed offense,
scoring 20 points, handing out three assists and grabbing seven
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been the quiet, behind-the-scenes guy _ a calm guy
who gets the job done,'' he said. So far it has worked. The tempest
continues, the investigation continues. Bootsy Thornton is still
keeping steady time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
