<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAA-WEST-NYT &LR;      03-17 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-WEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S: BASKET AND STEAL WIN IT VS. NORTHERN ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCON, Ariz. _ After six weeks of investigations and a Bootsy
Thornton-Erick Barkley fight at halftime of a Big East tournament
game, who would have thought a 15th-seeded team would rattle
second-seeded St. John's in the West subregional of the NCAA men's
basketball tournament Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what Northern Arizona did before St John's prevailed,
61-56.
</P>
<P>
   Lavor Postell hit a driving runner in the lane with 10.9 seconds
remaining in the game to regain the lead at 57-56. He then hit the
free throw to complete a 3-point play as St. John's went up by
58-56, and the Lumberjacks, with their band of 3-point shooters,
had one last chance.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Land, one of the nation's deadliest 3-point shooters, got
the ball on the arc and squared up but Barkley's right hand slapped
the ball loose. Barkley scrambled for the ball, and with 2.6
seconds left went to the line and the Lumberjacks' stirring bid for
an upset before a hometown crowd was over.
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks had won 14 of their last 15 games and the Big
Sky Conference championship by mastering the art of 3-point
shooting. For the third year in a row, Northern Arizona had led the
nation in 3-point percentage _ a 39.4 percent this season _ and
boasted the fifth-most-accurate long-range bomber in NCAA Division
I history, the senior Land.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm muscled its way to a 28-25 lead at halftime, but
the Lumberjacks were staying close because of a 2-point shotmaker:
Northern Arizona's 7-foot center Dan McClintock. Land and his
backcourt mate, Adam Lopez, zipped passes into the agile big man,
who drop-stepped around 6-foot-7-inch Anthony Glover for a variety
of bank shots and jump hooks.
</P>
<P>
   McClintock scored eight of Northern Arizona's first 15 points
and finished the half with 10 points and five rebounds. He also
helped the Lumberjacks control the offensive boards so that Land
and company had second and third attempts.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't matter. Northern Arizona shot 37.9 percent,
hitting just 2 of 11 from beyond the 3-point arc.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm, however, had its own troubles offensively despite
shooting 46.4 percent from the field. After speaking to NCAA
investigators on Monday and in his view being cleared by them,
Barkley had said he could compete without worrying about the
investigation. But he shot very tentatively in the first half,
finishing 0 for 5 and barely drawing rim on two occasions. Postell,
who was also interviewed by investigators, was an equally dismal 1
of 5.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of those two, St. John's relied on the inside slashing
of Thornton, Reggie Jesse and Glover. The threesome managed only
one offensive board and were out-rebounded by 19-13, but they kept
going right at McClintock. They combined for 11-of-16 shooting as
Thornton scored 10 points and Jesse and Glover added seven and six
points, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue 62, Dayton 61
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers kicked, overthrew and traveled with the ball _
19 turnovers _ and allowed Dayton to think about a first-round
upset. ``With about seven or eight minutes in the game, I asked
Jaraan if he was going to make a shot today,'' Purdue coach Gene
Keady remembered asking his senior guard Jaraan Cornell.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for coach and Boilermakers, Cornell sank three
3-pointers in the final nine minutes and sixth-seeded Purdue
endured 11th-seeded Dayton in a barely officiated brawl between two
bump-and-shove teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an ugly game, but it was a hard-fought game where both
teams deserved to win,'' said Keady, whose 22-9 team will face
third-seeded Oklahoma on Saturday. ``We hung in there and made some
great defensive plays at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers (22-9) used a couple of free throws to take a 56-55
lead with 3 minutes 7 seconds left in the game after the
Boilermakers' Brian Cardinal had been whistled on the offensive end
for tossing a forearm shiver in the lane. When Dayton guard Brooks
Hall intercepted Carson Cunningham's pass at half court and took it
in for a layup and a 58-55 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Cornell, a 38 percent shooter, flashed to the top of the key
and hit his third 3-pointer and 13th point of the game. Cardinal,
who scored 15 points in the half, followed his fellow senior with
another 3-pointer from the right wing, and the Boilermakers had a
61-58 lead with 1:20 left.
</P>
<P>
   Keady and Purdue had to sweat out a grinding finish _ Yuanta
Holland slipped inside for a layup on an inbounds pass to bring the
Flyers within 61-60 with 40 seconds left. Then Purdue's Greg McQuay
missed one of two free throws with 23.6 seconds left. When Hall
launched a runner from the lane that bounded off the rim and into
the lane, he followed it and came up with the ball. He also was
fouled.
</P>
<P>
   Hall hit the first of his one-and-one, but missed the second.
This time Cardinal came out of the pileup with the ball and was
sent to the line.
</P>
<P>
   But Cardinal, too, missed the front end of the one-and-one. The
Flyers had 3.2 seconds to go 90 feet and get off a game-winning
shot. Flyers guard David Morris caught the ball before half court,
dribbled left, and launched a 40-footer with the 6-foot-8-inch
Cardinal on his hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a bump on him and he didn't get a good shot,'' said
Cardinal, who led the Boilermakers with 18 points. ``When he
released that ball, I was like, `Oh my gosh.' I was praying it
didn't come close, and it didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton coach Oliver Purcell said: ``They let us play. It was a
war.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma 74, Winthrop 50
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners (27-6) raced off to a 39-23 halftime lead behind
deadly 3-point shooting and cruised over the 14th-seeded Eagles.
They shot 51 percent, made 10 of 21 from beyond the arc and had
five players in double figures _ led by J.R. Raymond's 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously you want to win your first-round game _ the thing I
was most impressed with was how we won,'' Oklahoma coach Kelvin
Sampson said. ``I thought our halfcourt defense was tremendous. We
defended the 3-point line and kept them from running sets. We did
not let them do what they wanted to do. And we have kids who can
shoot the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive year, the Eagles (21-9) exited after
the first round by wilting under the Sooners' halfcourt defense.
They shot 26 percent and made a dismal 2 for 20 on 3-pointers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
