<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-REPEATING-FIXING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA GETS PAST BALL STATE
</HEADLINE>
 SCORE-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS - They swore it would be different this time. Their
practices were tougher, they claimed. Their preparation was better,
they said. Their focus was sharper. They vowed not to overlook
their opponent.
</P>
<P>
   And the UCLA Bruins were right - right as a Jason Kapono
3-pointer. There was no lethargy, there was no indifference, and
there was no first-round loss.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono drained three 3-pointers early in the second half to fuel
UCLA's 65-57 victory over Ball State on Thursday in the Metrodome.
The Bruins will play No. 3 seed Maryland in the second round
Saturday at approximately 5:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year the players were complacent, this year we're
hungry,'' senior forward Sean Farnham said. ``It's night and day
between last year and this year, from the coaches to the players to
the managers and t he trainer. We haven't accomplished anything
this year. This is our chance to get it turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   They did it with Kapono's 17 second-half points, nine of which
sparked a 14-0 surge that gave the Bruins control. They did it with
a stifling zone defense. They did it with dominant rebounding,
excellent ball movement and enough perimeter shooting to counteract
Ball State's 2-3 zone - the same zone Detroit Mercy used to upset
UCLA last year.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a Kapono makes - and a sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't talked about (Detroit), but it's been a motivating
factor,'' point guard Earl Watson said. ``We have a lot of
motivation coming into this tournament, a lot of unfinished
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins started well and took a 9-4 lead when Watson charged
through the defense for a layup. Three possessions later, JaRon
Rush buried a 3-pointer, then Jerome Moiso grabbed his own miss and
hit a soft jumper from the left baseline. When Rush tossed an
alley-oop pass to Dan Gadzuric for a mammoth one-handed dunk, the
Bruins had an 18-9 lead with 8:30 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Then their bad habits returned. Watson's errant alley-oop pass
to Rush off the backboard became Cedric Moodie's lay-up at the
other end - and a four-point swing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a 20-9 lead, UCLA's margin was 18-11, and the
momentum shifted for the remainder of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Rush missed a 15-footer on UCLA's ensuing possession. Then Ray
Young missed an ill-advised jumper. Gadzuric's turnaround gave the
Bruins a brief 22-20 lead, but Ball State countered with Moodie's
3-pointer from the left wing. With 1:18 left in the half, the
Cardinals had their first lead.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Jackson ended the half with a 3-pointer from the left
corner, increasing Ball State's lead to 26-22. UCLA had scored four
points in the final 8:30, most of its against the Cardinals' zone
defense.
</P>
<P>
   The second half began as the first ended. Theron Smith hit a
difficult jumper from the left baseline to give Ball State a 28-22
lead. The Bruins countered with a Moiso dunk, then went scoreless
for five posse ssions against the Cardinals' zone defense. The
problem wasn't execution - UCLA was plenty patient - as finishing
what they started. Both Gadzuric and Moiso failed to convert short
jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   With 16:40 left, Kapono broke UCLA's drought. He buried a
3-pointer from the left wing - his first basket of the game. After
a Ball State miss, Kapono drained one from the right wing. The
baskets gave the Bruins a 30-28 lead and forced a Ball State
timeout.
</P>
<P>
   The teams exchanged baskets for several minutes, then Kapono
struck again - this time from the right corner off a crosscourt
pass from Watson. The basket gave UCLA a 39-33 lead, and the
momentum it had lost in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Kapono) is one of the top freshmen in the country,'' Ball
State coach Ray McCallum said. ``He's a shooter, but he can do a
lot of other things.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's defense continued to smother the Cardinals each time they
entered the lane. Their fifth-consecutive scoreless possession
became a Rush 3-pointer from the left wing that expanded UCLA's
lead to 42-33. Evidently, Kapono's accuracy was contagious.
</P>
<P>
   A few seconds later, reserve Matt Barnes found Rush for another
3-pointer, and the lead was 45-33. The Bruins turned a Ball State
turnover into a Barnes dunk, and the lead was 14 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
