<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9442 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-RAMPART-DISPUTE-2TAKE     03-17 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMPART-DISPUTE-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPD, D.A. COOPERATE ON RAMPART SCANDAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _  &UR; T &LR; he LAPD and the District Attorney's Office
resumed cooperating in the Rampart Division corruption case
Thursday but Police Chief Bernard C. Parks and District Attorney
Gil Garcetti kept up their personal attacks on each other.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear whether the dispute over cooperation ever
was real or whether it was merely an escalation in the political
brinkmanship Parks and Garcetti have engaged in for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But the days of high tension since Garcetti publicly accused
Parks of freezing county prosecutors out of the case have left the
credibility of the investigation in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is out of control and I think it's irreparable,'' county
Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky said. ``My thoughts are the controversy
is not serving the people of the city in the least bit. The public
interest has to be put first. Both men are being diminished by
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's amazing is that here are two smart, intelligent men
with more than 50 years of public service and it's all gone by the
wayside because they decided to get in this fight. It's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressured by Garcetti and others, the Los Angeles Police
Commission has scheduled a special meeting for today to consider
ordering Parks to work with Garcetti an issue that now seems
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti spokeswoman Sandi Gibbons said the LAPD provided
investigative information Thursday to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern all along has been getting the information we need
to make criminal investigations,'' Gibbons said. ``As long as they
are cooperating, that's what we needed to see. The most important
thing is the LAPD working with us, and that resolves any dispute.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at the LAPD's Parker Center headquarters, Parks
said he was ``set up'' by Garcetti, who went public with his claim
the chief had refused to provide any new investigative information
to the District Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   He said he never refused to work with Garcetti but believed they
had reached agreement weeks ago on a plan for the LAPD to give its
reports to the U.S. Attorney's Office, which would turn over
evidence about criminal violations of state law to the local
prosecutors _ a claim Garcetti dismissed as a ``red herring'' to
cover up the decision to freeze out his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was a carefully orchestrated effort by (Garcetti)
when he woke up one day and found himself in a runoff election for
his seat,'' Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never told him that we would not cooperate with his
office. But what we were looking for was a proper procedure to
handle the cases that we all had agreed to. I was set up by him and
his campaign to look as if we were not willing to cooperate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Garcetti, in a telephone interview from an undisclosed
location outside of Los Angeles, vehemently denied any attempt to
embarrass Parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me make it very clear that since the moment it became
clear to us through his written communications he was no longer
going to be cooperating with us on the investigation of possible
state crimes, I have endeavored behind the scenes to convince him
he was legally obligated to cooperate with us,'' Garcetti said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not only me, it was the chief law enforcement officer
of the state, Attorney General Bill Lockyer, in a conference
call.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks offered a completely different account, saying he outlined
the approach he would take of working through the U.S. attorney and
it was generally agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   The chief also pointed to a Feb. 23 news conference, in which
Garcetti took part, where it was announced U.S. Attorney Alejandro
Mayorkas and the FBI would be joining the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we would have a task force, like we did on the
Buford Furrow case, and that we would be funneling all our
information to the U.S. Attorney's Office, and they would work with
the D.A. to determine where cases should be filed.''
</P>
<P>
   Furrow is accused of a series of crimes in the shooting spree at
the North Valley Jewish Community Center in Granada Hills last year
and the killing of a postal worker.
</P>
<P>
   Parks cited a memo he received from Mayorkas' office offering
advice on how to present ``clean'' cases to prosecutors, meaning
they would not see any self-incriminating statements officers were
required to make as part of the internal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the U.S. Attorney's Office refused to comment on
the procedures to be used in the Rampart case. Lockyer has said
Parks is required by law to cooperate with Garcetti.
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti left the city Wednesday afternoon for what was
described as a ski vacation. He denied that and said he would be
back in his office today. He would not say where he was calling
from.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons, his spokeswoman, pointed to differences between Rampart
and the Furrow case, in which a federal prosecution was allowed
because one of his alleged victims was a postal worker.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is Parks is talking about giving it to the U.S.
Attorney's Office first,'' Gibbons said. ``He has an obligation,
legally, to give it to us at the same time. He can give his entire
investigation to anyone he wants, but it has to come to us at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is up to this office to decide who to prosecute and when to
file charges. We could have filed charges and then lost the cases.
We want to make sure we have ironclad cases. We are looking for a
broad-based case that goes to the heart of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But Parks said he believes that the LAPD has given the District
Attorney's Office at least three good cases, one of which does not
involve testimony from Rafael Perez, the former anti-gang officer
who has admitted to stealing cocaine, beating and shooting
suspects, planting evidence and lying in court to win convictions
of suspected gang members.
</P>
<P>
   After publicly scolding both Garcetti and Parks on Wednesday,
Mayor Richard Riordan sent letters urging them to work together
professionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that we can only achieve our mutual goals of
justice and accountability if we put any personal feelings aside
and resolve to work cooperatively with all parties,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to Parks, he said the Police Department has to
cooperate with the local prosecutors, and he told Garcetti that the
department would cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said he also plans to write to Garcetti, saying his
officers will continue to provide the information requested.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Parks said prosecutors have not requested much
information in the past two months and he remains unconvinced that
Garcetti has assigned 30 deputy district attorneys to the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti disputed that, saying deputy district attorneys have
asked for specific information and have been told by LAPD
investigators that they were told not to provide the information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
