<HEADLINE>
MIHM'S EMOTIONS SURFACE AFTER LONGHORNS' VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Texas center Chris Mihm had held his emotions
inside until after the Longhorns defeated Indiana State on Thursday
in the first round of the West Region.
</P>
<P>
   After the 77-61 victory, the emotions all came bubbling to the
surface in the team's locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough two and a half days,'' said Mihm, who was
late coming to postgame group interviews after he gathered himself.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Mihm learned shortly before the team boarded a jet
for Salt Lake City that his maternal grandmother had died during a
visit to the Mihm's home in West Lake Hills. The funeral is Monday
in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hadn't been sick or anything,'' Mihm said later in the
hall outside the team's quarters. ``That's what makes it so hard to
take. It's been really tough on me to try and put it aside, but I
love this team so much that I really want to be there for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in the NCAA Tournament is such a great experience.
I've tried to put (his grandmother's death) aside and enjoy it, but
every once in a while, it creeps back in. I haven't been in much of
a laughing mood lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Mihm also was not at his best physically. He battled a
101-degree temperature overnight and said after the game he felt as
though he still had some fever.
</P>
<P>
   Because of foul problems, Mihm played only 11 minutes in the
second half. He scored 16 points, with eight rebounds and blocked
two shots, though he was officially given only one reject. He said
he found it especially rewarding that the Longhorns survived his
minutes on the bench during a crucial period in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone stepped up and did what it took,'' he said. ``I was
really pleased the way they took over the game and really handled
it the whole time I was out.'' MUONEKE'S TECHNICAL Texas forward
Gabe Muoneke dunked a pass from point guard Ivan Wagner with 10:48
left to give Texas a 56-44 lead. After Muonoke came down, he pumped
his arm and yelled, which he often does in similar situations, but
this time he was assessed a technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana State's Michael Menser sank both technical free throws
and a 3-point shot on the ensuing possession for a five-point
swing. A little more than a minute later, Indiana State crept
within 56-51.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (official) said I was taunting, but I didn't let it bother
me,'' Muoneke said. ``If (the call) had been justified, it probably
would have bothered me. But we're all human and he made a little
bit of a mistake. I've got great teammates who help keep me in the
game, and I didn't want to cause this team to lose that way.''
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas point guard Ivan Wagner's 10 assists tied his career
single-game high and set a school record for an NCAA Tournament
game, breaking the mark of nine by B.J. Tyler in a 91-77
first-round victory over Western Kentucky in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   _ Led by Chris Owens' 7-for-7 performance, the Longhorns shot a
season and team NCAA Tournament-record 61.2 percent, bettering the
58.5 percent performance the '91 Longhorns shot in a 73-65
first-round victory over St. Peter's.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Mihm's one official blocked shot put him at 90, tying
his single-season record set during his freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rick Barnes' NCAA Tournament record is now 3-7; UT is 8-2 in
the first round since the field expanded to 64 teams in 1985 nn
</P>
</TEXT>
