<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-SPURS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER GIANT FALLS: MAVERICKS ROUT SPURS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Tuesday night, the Beast in the East went down.
Thursday night, the NBA champs never had a chance to get up.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Mavericks clamped down on the San Antonio Spurs early
and never let up, whipping the defending league champions, 110-88,
in the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks (27-37) have taken care of three NBA heavyweights
in a span of five days, with a 111-90 rout of Indiana, which owns
the best record in the Eastern Conference, coming on Tuesday. The
Mavs started their three-game winning streak by topping Phoenix,
currently tied with the Spurs for fourth in the West, on Saturday.
Thursday night snapped a seven-game losing streak in the Alamodome,
dating to April 21, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes to show you, you never know where your wins are going
to come from or your losses,'' Mavericks coach Don Nelson said.
``We could have thrown in the towel before these three games, but
this team kept its spirit and good things have happened. It's
happened three times now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks played with more confidence as the game wore on,
quickly moving the ball along the perimeter to negate San Antonio's
formidable inside advantage. Spurs twin towers David Robinson and
Tim Duncan were reduced to mere spectators, netting only 10 points
combined after halftime, as Mavs' 3-pointers rained down from all
corners.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-point barrage was especially pronounced in the third
period, with the Mavs initially protecting and eventually extending
their 14-point (59-45) halftime advantage. Erick Strickland and
Steve Nash deflated the Alamodome crowd with a 6-for-6 showing from
behind the 3-point line in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're making every one of your shots and they are
missing most of theirs, that can get frustrating for the other
team,'' said Nash, who scored 10 points and handed out 11 assists.
``When we saw that happening, we did a good job of taking advantage
and did enough damage to convince (Spurs coach Gregg Popovich) to
pull on the reins a little and rest his guys for whoever they play
next.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs (41-24) and Mavs play again Tuesday at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs sank 12 of 23 3-pointers, with Strickland making five,
Dirk Nowitzki three, Nash two and Michael Finley a pair. Strickland
finished with a game-high 26 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shot the 3 extremely well,'' Nelson said. ``We got it out
of double teams and the ball movement was crisp and the most
important thing, we were making our shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, coming off an emotional high after Sean Elliott
returned from a kidney transplant on Tuesday, couldn't find a
spark. Finley didn't take it easy on Elliott, sinking four jumpers
over the Spurs forward, who didn't check back into the game after
playing eight minutes in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Spurs have yet to regain their championship form this
season, they hadn't taken many beatings like this. The 22-point
margin tied the season's previous-largest loss set Dec. 3 (102-80)
at Detroit and the Mavs nearly matched the Spurs' opponent scoring
high (111 by Houston). The most points the Spurs had allowed after
three periods before Thursday night was 83. The Mavs had 92 going
into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the worst games I've see us play,'' Robinson
said. ``We had terrible defense. We had terrible offense. There's
not much good that can be said about this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs got after the defending champs early, with Finley and
Strickland scoring 10 each as they built a 34-22 lead after the
first period. Three of Finley's four jumpers came from at least 18
feet. Strickland did half of his damage from the line, sinking all
five of his free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started defensively,'' Strickland said. ``We shaped our
focus defensively to stop them. We're a very confident team, but to
come in here and play like this is a little surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mavs owner Mark Cuban didn't rate Thursday night's win as
the biggest under his yet-to-be official tenure, he said it ranks
right up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I loved about it is how we played at the defensive end,''
Cuban said. ``We created a lot of opportunities for ourselves with
our rebounding and defense.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
