<HEADLINE>
UTAH'S PRAYER FINDS BASKET, TOPS BILLIKENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Utah, redefining the meaning of ``winning ugly,''
ended Saint Louis' magical postseason run with a 48-45 victory in
the first-round of the NCAA Midwest Region on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore reserve guard Jeff Johnsen sank a 25-foot 3-point
prayer to beat the shot clock with 1:41 remaining to give the
eighth-seeded Utes (23-8) a 46-44 lead with 1:41 remaining. The
Billikens (19-14), who won four consecutive games to gain
Conference USA's automatic bid, had a chance to tie, but Dave
Fergerson's 3-pointer bounced out.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moves Utah into the second round Saturday. The Utes
will face top-seeded Michigan State, a 65-38 winner against
Valparaiso in the first game of Thursday night's session.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate when Johnsen threw that shot in,'' said Utah
coach Rick Majerus, whose team played the second half without
injured starters Jeremy Killion and Nate Althoff. ``I couldn't be
more proud of the effort our players gave. With all the injuries,
we had guys playing out of position all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams combined for 37 turnovers, 31 field goals and missed
23 of 41 free throws. Saint Louis was 9-of-22 from the line.
MICHIGAN STATE 65, VALPARAISO 38
</P>
<P>
   Top-seeded Michigan State, playing a frenetic and focused
defense, started their Final Four quest with a commanding victory.
The Spartans had a 20-3 lead before the Crusaders had their second
field goal. The Crusaders got within 37-24 early in the second half
before the Spartans went on a 17-3 run to close it out.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State (27-7) turned Valpo into Zero. The Crusaders set
a Midwest Regional record for fewest points scored. Valparaiso
(19-13) missed 14 of its first 15 shots to start the game. Starting
the second half, the Crusaders missed 14 of their first 18. For the
game, Valpo shot 25 percent, had six assists and 13 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense got our offense going,'' said Michigan State
senior guard Mateen Cleaves, who had a team-high 15 points and
eight assists. ``We did a great job on defense. That got our fast
break going. We pretty much picked up off our offense with our
defense.'' SYRACUSE 79, SAMFORD 65
</P>
<P>
   Samford couldn't find a way to stop Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen had four players in double figures and made 54.7
percent of their shots in an opening-round victory. The
fourth-seeded Orangemen (25-5) will play fifth-seeded Kentucky
(23-9) in Saturday's second round. The Wildcats beat St.
Bonaventure, 85-80, in double overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just kept making shots that kept breaking our heart,''
Samford senior forward Will Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, one of the nation's top shooting teams, trailed
41-37 early in the second half. Samford's Princeton-like offense
couldn't match the Orangemen, who made 16 of 24 second-half shots
(.667 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Jason Hart and Preston Shumpert each had 17 points for Syracuse,
while Etan Thomas had 16 points, seven rebounds and four blocked
shots. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
