<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' BARNES DELIVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS - Perhaps the suspensions and the injuries and the
lineup shuffles and the random substitution patterns actually
helped UCLA's late-season charge.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's what Bruins coach Steve Lavin believes.
</P>
<P>
   Most coaches strive for consistency in their starting lineups
and their substitution patterns. But Lavin believes the flux has
forged depth and resiliency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, you have five (starters) and five bench warmers,''
Lavin said. ``But with this team, every player knows he could be
called on at any moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, that man was reserve forward Matt Barnes, who
had six points and four assists and helped spark UCLA's 65-57
first-round victory over Ball State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt gave us a big lift,'' Bruins assistant Jim Saia said.
``He was huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes played just three minutes in the first half - not enough
to find his rhythm. But when Dan Gadzuric committed his third foul
with 15 minutes left and UCLA leading 32-31, Barnes checked in and
turned the game.
</P>
<P>
   Stationed at the foul line (high post) in UCLA's zone offense,
Barnes attacked the basket and made crisp passes to wing men JaRon
Rush and Jason Kapono for 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   With Barnes was on the court for five minutes, UCLA's one-point
lead expanded to 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just needed to get warmed up,'' Barnes said. ``In the first
half, I was in (for three minutes) and out. I just needed to get
warm. Then I tried to attck (Ball State center Lonnie Jones). He's
a shot blocker, and we had to attack him. He got one of my shots,
but we couldn't let him control the tempo.''
</P>
<P>
   Band man: As promised, Kapono unveiled a custom-made headband
for the NCAA Tournament. It was a bright yellow version of the
white and black issues he's worn throughout the season.
</P>
<P>
   And it didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dormmates' mom used spray paint, and that turned it loose
and saggy,'' Kapono said. ``It was hanging by my ears. It turned a
band on my head into an earpiece.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapono tossed the yellow and grabbed a white headband a few
minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Pass happy? Another source of UCLA's late-season success has
been its propensity to pass before dribbling.
</P>
<P>
   Check the numbers: In a nine-game stretch from early-January to
mid-February, the Bruins didn't have a 20-assist game.
</P>
<P>
   In their last nine regular-season games, they had at least 20
assists four times.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, they had 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become pass-oriented,'' Saia said. ``Our past teams
created more off the dribble. There was a reason why. We had guys
like Baron Davis and Toby Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we thought this team would be more effective offensively
if we were pass-oriented. That's been a big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Not again: Gadzuric had 10 points and grabbed 12 rebounds
despite a mildly sprained left thumb suffered Wednesday in practice
- an injury that rekindled bad memories for Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he got hurt, part of me was thinking, `That's par for the
course,''' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins played without their starting center for most of the
past three tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Jelani McCoy played sparingly in the Elite Eight
against Minnesota because of a bruised sternum. In 1998, McCoy quit
the team weeks before the tournament. Last year, Gadzuric was out
with a knee injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
