<SLUG> BC-RAPBROWN-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 DEPUTIES ARE SHOT WHILE SEEKING ARREST OF EX-BLACK PANTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two sheriff's deputies were shot and seriously wounded
near downtown Atlanta late Thursday night while serving a warrant
at the home of a Muslim cleric who was known in the 1960s as H. Rap
Brown, a leader of the Black Panther party.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Fulton County Sheriff's Office said they did
not know whether Brown, now known as Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, shot
the two deputies. The gunman escaped after being wounded by one of
the deputies, and sheriff's officials said they were looking for
Al-Amin. They released a description of the man that seemed to
match that of the former militant.
</P>
<P>
   An intense manhunt was under way in a four-block area of
southwest Atlanta surrounding Al-Amin's mosque and home. SWAT teams
and police dogs searched homes in the area, at one point following
a trail of blood that led to an empty house.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Jackie Barrett said the deputies were serving a warrant
issued in suburban Cobb County for aggravated assault and weapons
possession. The deputies were shot with a semi-automatic weapon
when the door was opened, she said. Both men were wearing
bulletproof vests; one was in critical condition and the other in
guarded condition at Grady Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin has lived in Atlanta for about 25 years, leading the
Community Mosque and running a small grocery store. In the 1960s
and 70s, he led the Student Non-Violent Coordinating Committee and
was justice minister of the Black Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a neighborhood resident accused Al-Amin of shooting him
but later recanted, saying police had pressured him into making the
identification. Al-Amin's lawyer said at the time that police were
looking for any excuse to charge Al-Amin with a major crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
