<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAGGED ZAGS REKINDLE THEIR TOURNEY FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ For awhile, it looked as if Gonzaga had returned
to the NCAA tournament just to do some dirty dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Goodness knows, it was not all pretty.
</P>
<P>
   With senior swingman Mike Nilson on the bench with a ruptured
Achilles tendon and their rotation on a leash short enough to choke
the breath out of them, the Bulldogs were piling up turnovers
faster than a crew of Pillsbury Dough Boys. They were in danger of
imploding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd wasn't safe,'' senior guard Matt Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the first half, Louisville ran up a seven-point
lead, and somehow it seemed like all the karma and all the magic
and all the deja vu all over again just wasn't going to happen this
time for the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   But then what would we know?
</P>
<P>
   These are the Zags, right?
</P>
<P>
   Ornery, determined, hard-nosed with a winner's mentality. Did
someone dare suggest the Zags were almost down and out in Round 1
of this year's NCAA tourney because of a little first-half hiccup?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it was only seven points, and the reason we were down was
because we were doing some things that are very uncharacteristic
for us,'' Santangelo said afterward, with a grin, but not all that
sweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been down in games before. We knew once we settled down,
we'd be all right. Seven points is not anything to start calling
home about.''
</P>
<P>
   No, that would have been very premature.
</P>
<P>
   And as much as the Zags like the serenity and security of their
Bing Crosby-John Stockton-neat-little-city-by-the-river out there
in Washington's Inland Empire, they just didn't figure it was time
to head back. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   We could get used to this, couldn't we?
</P>
<P>
   Or, rather: We have gotten used to all this Gonzaga stuff. It's
not really March Madness anymore as much as it's Zag Madness.
</P>
<P>
   And here they go, here we go again.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, riding the same No. 10 seed they used as a
jet-propulsion magic carpet one year ago, the Zags refused to let a
mess of 24 turnovers shoot down their latest mission.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the second half, the Zags turned up the heat on
No. 7-seed Louisville, riding senior shooting guard Richie Frahm's
31-point blastoff and nifty defense to, yes, another ``upset''
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 49-48, Louisville's Quintin Bailey was off on a
breakaway only to find his dunk attempt stuffed from behind from
Frahm. The momentum shift was enormous as Frahm broke back down
court, taking a pass on the right baseline from Santangelo and
burying a 3-point grenade.
</P>
<P>
   In the stands at the McKale Center, the legions of Gonzaga fans
erupted in glee.
</P>
<P>
   The Zags' lead was 52-48 and they were not done salting this one
away.
</P>
<P>
   Back down under the Louisville basket, it looked as if
Louisville coach Denny Crum had reason to be miffed when the Zags
roughed up one of his shooters. But without a call against Gonzaga,
Crum and his bench were instead whistled for a technical when the
refs called a foul on Reece Gaines on the Zags' next possession.
</P>
<P>
   Frahm hit one of the two free throws, and the Zags never looked
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just huge. It was more than just a five-point
turnaround,'' Santangelo said. ``That was a huge shift in momentum.
It got the crowd back into it. It got Richie playing with a lot of
emotion and with high energy, and it lifted the team up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When one of your players goes out and makes a play that's pure
effort, that wasn't about skill. That just pure heart that got that
done, and it let us open up a little bit of a lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that would explain the circus alley-oop jam Casey
Calvary threw down from a pin-point pass from Frahm to push the
Zag's lead to 58-52. And it would explain Calvary's ensuing blocked
shot _ the one that sent a Louisville jumpshot attempt into orbit
north towards Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the second half was rolling to a close, Louisville
had folded up its cards, crumbling under a 37-percent shooting
performance while the Zags, led by Frahm, hit for 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, the turnovers were a mere footnote to the way Frahm
shot the Zags out of trouble and the way the entire team buckled
down to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   But what else would you expect from these guys?
</P>
<P>
   ``This group is made up of a lot of winners,'' coach Mark Few
said.
</P>
<P>
   Which means the Zags are not done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is actually nice to get that one win out of the way,''
Santangelo said. ``There's a little bit of weight off our
shoulders, but we didn't come here to play and get one win and go
home. We came to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of have a chip on our shoulder. We're still fighting
for a little bit of respect, I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   We know how it is with these guys. We've all been here before,
as in exactly one year ago. That's when the 10th-seeded Zags
knocked off seventh-seeded Minnesota at KeyArena and then rolled
through No. 2 Stanford and Florida in the Sweet 16 before falling
to UConn in the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of comforting to be the 10 seed playing the 7
seed, truthfully,'' Santangelo said. ``I just felt very comfortable
with it, like we had been in this position before.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the motivation against Stanford a year ago was immense.
The West Coast Conference champs wanted to prove something. The
Zags know the Cardinal like the back of their hands.
</P>
<P>
   But what the heck. If this year's No. 2 seed waiting for the
Zags is St. John's, the Zags say bring them on. They've been down
this yellow brick road before.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 0140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
