r s BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN     03-17 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE MAY HAVE EDGE IN QUICKNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. - It's fitting that the Buffalo Naval and Service
Park is adjacent to the Mainland Midland Arena, where Pepperdine
opens the NCAA Tournament tonight against Indiana in the East
Regional.
</P>
<P>
   The battleships on display provide an appropriate reminder for
what the Waves must do to beat the Hoosiers: Aggressively defend
Indiana guard A.J. Guyton, attack on offense and, most important,
not be intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   Tipoff is scheduled for 7:20 PST. Pepperdine (24-8), the West
Coast Conference regular-season champion, is making its first
appearance in the tournament since 1994 and 12th overall. Indiana
(20-8), the sixth seed, finished fifth in the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a quick, aggressive, well-put-together team,'' Indiana
coach Bob Knight said. ``It's a team that I'd like to watch play.
Now how much I'm going to want to watch them tomorrow night, I'm
not sure. But they're a team that, if I was going to go watch a
team, this is one I'd enjoy watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is the NCAA Tournament, and if the Waves weren't
sure about the magnitude prior to arriving here, they are now.
</P>
<P>
   The electric buzz around the city, abundance of national media
and the beautiful, vast arena they'll play in are impossible to
overlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely going through our head right now,'' said
sophomore guard Brandon Armstrong, the Waves' leading scorer. ``But
we had a good season this year, we played a tough schedule, been in
some big games. So, once (we get settled), it will calm down.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong is a big reason Pepperdine is here, averaging 14.1
points in his first year playing with the Waves. He, along with
point guard Tezale Archie and reserve guard Craig Lewis, give
Pepperdine a versatile, three-pronged look in the backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indiana's probably more physical then we are, but I think our
quickness is to our advantage,'' said Lewis, who averages 7.7
points off the bench. ``We'd like to get the game up-tempo, try to
pressure the ball and take the ball out of the hands of their main
players and make some other players (handle it).''
</P>
<P>
   If the Waves manage more than 70 points against Indiana, they'll
have a chance. The Hoosiers are 6-6 when allowing opponents more
then 70 points.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's best player is senior A.J. Guyton, the Big Ten co-
player of the year and a first team All-American. Guyton, 6-2,
presents a number of problems defensively. He's a darting,
penetrating guard equally strong from the outside as on drives to
the basket. Indiana is 13-4 when Guyton scores 20 or more points,
and he's at his best in big games, averaging 24.1 points this year
against nationally ranked teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously the key to their team,'' said Pepperdine coach
Jan van Breda Kolff.
</P>
<P>
   But there are others to watch out for. Kirk Haston, a 6-10
center, averages 15.8 points and point guard Michael Lewis,
Indiana's career assists leader, is averaging 10.5 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's their unsung hero,'' van Breda Kolff said.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves, who spent considerable time in practice this week
concentrating on Guyton, will use their fullcourt press to minimize
the time Indiana has in halfcourt sets. When the ball is in
Guyton's hands, they want to force him to the sidelines. Although
he's a terrific scorer, he is just an adequate ballhandler.
Pepperdine forward Tommie Prince, its best defender, will guard
Guyton most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to do is limit his touches and stay aggressive on
defense like we have all year,'' Prince said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
