<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANEES: NO SALE? NO SWEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA - Alex Hassinger doesn't seem to be distracted. Anees
certainly doesn't seem to be.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer and his big horse concentrated on getting ready for
the 2-year-old champion's first start of the season even as his
ownership underwent a change - and a change back - this week.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Saudi Prince Ahmed Salman's Thoroughbred Corp.
announced it had sold a 50 percent interest in Anees to Silicon
Valley executive David Shimmon for a reported $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Shimmon, a newcomer to the racing scene,
had paid $2 million for a colt at the Barretts March sale in Pomona
to match the record auction price for a 2-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, the Anees sale was reported to have fallen through
under unclear circumstances, Shimmon backing out even though the
horse passed a veterinarian's check. Thoroughbred Corp. racing
manager Richard Mulhall did not return telephone calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, preparations went on for the first step toward
the Kentucky Derby for Anees, a son of 1990 Derby winner Unbridled
and grandson of 1978 Triple Crown runner-up Alydar.
</P>
<P>
   After having his training interrupted for three weeks in January
by a left hind foot bruise, delaying the start of his 2000
campaign, Anees is scheduled to run in the $250,000 San Felipe
Stakes at Santa Anita on Sunday. Jerry Bailey replaces retired
jockey Gary Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition is expected to consist of Fusaichi Pegasus (Kent
Desormeaux), the $4 million yearling purchase; The Deputy (Chris
McCarron), the Irish-bred Santa Catalina Stakes winner; Commendable
(Chris Antley), trained by D. Wayne Lukas for Bob and Beverly
Lewis, and Promontory Gold (Corey Nakatani), who is 2 for 3 in turf
races for Bobby Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   None of the four had beaten winners by Nov. 6, the day Anees
rallied from 14th to win the Breeders' Cup Juvenile at Gulfstream
Park at 30-1 odds.
</P>
<P>
   But because of Anees' winter setback, and the assumption he
won't be 100 percent fit for Sunday's 1 1/16-mile race, both
Fusaichi Pegasus and The Deputy are expected to go lower in the
betting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably would have liked one more race before this one,''
said Hassinger, who will have to hope this race and the April 8
Santa Anita Derby are enough to get Anees ready for the May 6
Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the ultimate goal with this horse is to have him at
his best in the Kentucky Derby,'' Hassinger said. ``Just as last
year we wanted him at his best, if he was good enough, for the
Breeders' Cup. I think the program we set up for him last year was
perfect, from his maiden win to the Norfolk (Stakes) to the
Breeders' Cup. And I think this program we have set up is very
similar. I think the mile-and-a-16th, mile-and-an-eighth,
mile-and-a-quarter (progression) is a perfect scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Hassinger is confident that Anees, because of his light frame
and his running style, can get into racing shape faster than most
horses. He's also certain Anees is good enough to compete in the
Derby, something many trainers are still trying to prove with their
3-year-olds in a year when the Triple Crown picture is slow to come
into focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can really make a call on it (the Derby),''
Hassinger said the week after Mighty upset Captain Steve in the
Louisiana Derby and Hal's Hope edged High Yield in the Florida
Derby to become the first 3-year-old male to win two graded stakes
this season. ``I think there's three, four, five horses who seem
very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Hassinger thinks those horses include Surfside, the leading 3-
year-old filly, although her Santa Anita Oaks victory Sunday was
less impressive than future-book bettors would have liked to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has one important factor (going for her): She keeps
winning,'' Hassinger said. ``It's really hard to take a lot away
from her.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Hassinger thinks the ``interesting'' 3-year-olds
include Anees. The rest of us can decide for ourselves Sunday when
he races for the first time since the Breeders' Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Also this weekend: In what might be termed the horseback Ryder
Cup, four-man teams representing the United States and Europe will
compete Saturday at Santa Anita in the third International Jockey
Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   It's Chris McCarron, Laffit Pincay, Pat Day and Mike Smith for
Team USA, which won the competition in 1998 with a dramatic 1-2-3-4
finish in the final race, and Frankie Dettori, Kieren Fallon,
Michael Kinane and Gerald Mosse for Team Europe, which evened the
score in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The teams assign riders to horses in races 3 through 5, and the
competition will be settled on a points basis. Santa Anita will
offer a special pick-four bet.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the tragedy: The California Horse Racing Board continues
to investigate the accident that killed jockey J.C. Gonzalez last
Sept. 9 at Fairplex Park.
</P>
<P>
   Among the revelations so far: Gonzalez's mount, Wolfhunt, whose
breakdown triggered the accident, was treated legally with
cortisone and two other therapeutic drugs two days before the race
after veterinarian John Araujo found inflammation in a foreleg; and
Araujo was fined $200 for failing to report the medications as
required.
</P>
<P>
   The eventual findings could determine whether there will be
legal action by Gonzalez's family, which has used the Public
Records Act to acquire the preliminary necropsy report on Wolfhunt
produced at UC Davis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
