<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER'S RETURN SPARKS SONICS TO SEASON SWEEP OF GRIZZLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Vancouver Grizzlies have probably seen enough of
the Sonics for one week.
</P>
<P>
   Vin Baker, on the other hand, apparently had seen enough of his
closet and the Sonics' training room. Baker stepped out of street
clothes Thursday and back into the lineup after missing two games
with a strained left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics then yanked the welcome mat in KeyArena and bounced
the Grizzlies, 117-103, in the teams' second meeting in four days.
The victory was the Sonics' fourth against Vancouver, completing a
season sweep that included a 113-103 victory Monday at General
Motors Place.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Sonics spared no offense _ and not much defense,
for that matter _ in sending Vancouver to its 10th straight loss.
The Grizzlies, who shot 54 percent, made an occasional threat but
the Sonics remained in command from the time both teams peeled away
warmup gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those professional wins,'' Sonics coach Paul
Westphal said. ``It was a game you had to take care of, and we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal's crew maintained its sixth-place standing in the
Western Conference playoff picture. The Sonics are behind three
games in the loss column to idle Phoenix (40-23) for the fifth seed
and are still within striking distance of fourth seed San Antonio
(42-23).
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are ready for a Pacific Division showdown Saturday as
the Portland Trail Blazers visit KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary (Payton) and I were talking in the showers,'' Sonics
guard Vernon Maxwell said. ``We have to make a statement in that
game. We haven't beaten those guys all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' record against winning teams is 16-19, but they
usually flex a little muscle against subpar opponents. Thursday
night, the Sonics improved to 23-7 against losing teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supposed to beat those guys, but we knew it was going to
be a tougher game,'' center Horace Grant said. ``We can't take
these teams under .500 for granted. We lost to Atlanta here (on
Feb. 25). We learned our lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics led by double digits most of the second half, but the
Grizzlies twice got to within seven. Each time the Sonics answered
Vancouver's run with a quick score. A Brent Barry 3-pointer put the
Sonics ahead 108-98 with 1:26 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember the last time we guarded anybody,'' Vancouver
coach Lionel Hollins said. ``We're just not guarding. I don't know
if we can get back to guarding people before the season ends, but
we have a few days to work on it.
</P>
<P>
   Barry finished with 21 points, and Payton led the Sonics with 30
points and 16 assists. Baker's game obviously wasn't hurt by the
time off. Despite picking up his fifth foul with 5:14 to play in
the third, Baker had 21 points and seven rebounds in 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a lot of discomfort,'' Baker said. ``The time
off helped my knees a lot. It gave my legs a chance to rest so it
was like starting over again. ... I was really overzealous. It was
a nice rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   As rhythm goes, the Sonics began the game much like their
meeting earlier this week. Payton fueled a dominant first quarter
by hitting seven of his first 10 shots. The Sonics' offense simply
ran through the Grizzlies' defense with Payton and his teammates
driving hard to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   With Payton resting on the bench, the Sonics' offense bogged
down at the start of the second quarter. The Grizzlies took
advantage of lagging defense as well and scored eight consecutive
points to pull within 40-34.
</P>
<P>
   A Greg Foster jumper then started a quick 7-3 run that put the
Sonics back in front 47-37. Payton later made two free throws that
gave the Sonics a 64-54 advantage just before the end of the
second.
</P>
<P>
   Payton tallied 23 points by halftime and the Sonics led 64-57 at
that point.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics jumped out to a 40-26 lead in the first, the most
points Seattle had scored in a quarter all season. The 40 also tied
a Vancouver record for the most points allowed in one period.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle shot 73 percent in the opening frame and 54 percent for
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put the ball in the basket but we were able to find more
ways to get the ball in the basket,'' Westphal said. ``We did what
we had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012 or
ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
