<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, March 17.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-DIPLOMACY (Tokyo) _ In the space of a short few weeks,
North Korea has gone from one of the world's most politically
reclusive states, to one of the most diplomatically active. With
little fanfare, but with a speed that has surprised many observers
of the Communist country, the government in Pyongyang has
established diplomatic relations with Italy and has resumed
diplomatic discussions with Japan and Australia for the first time
in years. It has also recently sent out discreet feelers to at
least two other major Western nations, Canada and Britain. And
according to diplomats in the Philippines, it has approached their
country about joining the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
Regional Forum. By Howard French.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-ELECT (Taipei) _ Exuberant elections are a sign of
Taiwan's recent transition from dictatorship to democracy, but an
unsparing and hilarious satire of the politicians that is airing
weekday nights on cable television here may be the ultimate proof.
By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NO-INSURANCE-DOCS (Undated) _ A growing number of doctors have
severed their ties to HMOs and insurance companies. In return for
cash payments, the doctors often offer a lavish level of service _
uncrowded waiting rooms, uninterrupted office visits and an office
staff that knows the patients. Nearly a decade after President
Clinton's failed effort to remake health care in America, the
health care market is remaking itself. For those with insurance or
the money to pay for health care, there is evolving a two-tiered
system. One tier is made up of doctors who have cut their prices at
the insistence of health insurers and who make up for the reduced
prices by increasing their volume. The other tier is made up of
those who offer time and attention _ but at a cost. By Lawrence K.
Altman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT21,22) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NJ-SPRAWL (Hopewell, N.J.) _ Gov. Christine Todd Whitman has
said that she would make New Jersey a national model for
controlling growth in ways that protect open space and serve the
cities. But as the most recent census figures once again show,
talking about sprawl is easier than limiting it, particularly in
the boom times of Central New Jersey. By Iver Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT30) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-ABRAM (Undated) _ Morris B. Abram, a small-town boy from
Georgia who went on to play a role in the civil- rights movement,
become a leader of the American-Jewish community, serve as an
embattled president of Brandeis University and fill posts on a
variety of commissions and panels under five presidents, died
Thursday at a hospital in Geneva, Switzerland. He was 81. By
William Honan.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-RAMSEY-MURDER (Denver) _ After 3 years of virtual
seclusion, the parents of a 6-year-old girl who was killed in
Boulder have emerged to make the case that they were not involved
in her death. Coincidentally, they have a book coming out.
Meanwhile, an investigator in Colorado Springs who worked for them
is promoting the idea that an intruder was guilty. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION-ANTITRUST (New York) _ Sotheby's and Christie's, the
world's two most powerful auction houses, swapped confidential
lists of superrich clients who were spared from paying fees charged
to other sellers, people close to the companies and to a federal
antitrust investigation of them said. By Ralph Blumenthal and Carol
Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   GENE-ALTERED-FOOD (Sioux City, Iowa) _ David Howe, a corn and
soybean farmer near this town nestling the Nebraska border, says he
is tired of people treating his genetically engineered crops as
freaks of nature. To him, genetically modified seeds and the foods
they produce are entirely safe. He has been planting such seeds for
three years and expects to do so for years to come. By David
Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ-NORRIS-COLUMN (New York) _ The signs are that Nasdaq has
been too busy promoting itself as the home of all those high-tech
wonder companies to bother spending enough money on its services.
The move toward decimal prices for stocks is going to be delayed,
perhaps for many months, because Nasdaq computer systems are
inadequate. And Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the Securities and
Exchange Commission, said yesterday that Nasdaq's SelectNet system,
which matches orders electronically, ``continues to be plagued with
shortcomings, delays during heavy trading volume, and even
outages.'' By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   DUPLICATION-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Two beverage marketers are
running television commercials that no doubt have many viewers
wondering whether they are seeing double. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
