<P>
   MAPLE-SYRUP (Whitingham, Vt.) _ Early spring quickens in this
state's southern mountain hamlets with the first rising curls of
wood smoke from roadside sugar houses and the sweet fragrance of
newly boiled amber maple syrup served pure and plain in thin paper
cups. Unlike a winery, a sugar house gets just one chance a year to
prove the mettle of its maple with fresh tastings for amateur
connoisseurs: for only about 45 days in the spring, when the nights
are cold and the days are warm enough to coax the sap to flow. And
it is a fleeting opportunity for tourists to experience the
small-town spell of a pancake breakfast flapped by the local Lions
or an afternoon luncheon or ham supper prepared a la maple by
groups like the Ladies Benevolent Society of Whitingham or the E-Z
Riders Snowmobile Club. Vermont is, after all, the top producer of
maple syrup in the United States, with 370,000 gallons last year,
or more than a third of all the maple syrup in the country. By
Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV; Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLES-SYMPHONY (new York) _ The most persistent complaint
among potential classical music listeners _ and regular
concertgoers as well _ is that ticket prices for the best-known
ensembles and soloists are so high as to discourage
experimentation. But there are venues that offer knowledgeable
listeners superb music at budget prices. One of the most notable is
the Peoples' Symphony Concerts, which for a century have been
giving knowledgeable listeners a break. Founded in 1900 by Franz X.
Arens, an immigrant conductor who found high ticket prices
objectionable even then, Peoples' Symphony these days presents
mostly recitals and chamber music in a schedule balanced between
established performers and promising newcomers. This season, the
Juilliard, Guarneri and Colorado String Quartets and the pianists
Ignat Solzehnitsyn and Orli Shaham have already appeared on the
series. Tickets now cost dollars rather than pennies, but the
prices remain remarkably low. A subscription to six Saturday
evening concerts costs $19, with single tickets going for $5. By
Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   MAT-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Beyond The Mat'': Barry W.
Blaustein, director; a documentary. Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
