<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAPONO SPARKS UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS - They swore it would be different this year. Their
practices were tougher, they claimed. Their preparation was better,
they said. Their focus was sharper. They vowed not to overlook the
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   And the UCLA Bruins were right - right as a Jason Kapono
3-pointer. There was no lethargy, there was no indifference, and
there was no first-round loss.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono drained three 3-pointers early in the second half to fuel
UCLA's 65-57 victory over Ball State on Thursday before 20,127 in
the Metrodome. Winners of seven consecutive games, the Bruins will
play No. 3 seed Maryland on Saturday in the second round - a round
further than last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a relief,'' UCLA guard Earl Watson said. ``I'd say
it's a step forward. We came in here thinking we had to win six
games (to win the national title). Now we have to win five.''
</P>
<P>
   For that they can thank Kapono, the smooth-shooting freshman.
Scoreless in the first half, he had 17 points in the second -
including the 3-pointers that helped turn a 28-22 deficit into a
47-33 lead with 11 minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason's our leading scorer, and when he started going, that
brought the whole offense along,'' said Bruins forward JaRon Rush,
who made three 3-pointers himself and finished with 14 points. ``He
gave us the spark.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins made 6-of-11 3-pointers in the second half. They
outrebounded Ball State 46-34. They had four players in double
figures, and their zone defense held the Cardinals to 35.8 percent
shooting. In charg ing to the 14-point lead, they played with the
same energy and efficienc y used to upset Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   But turnovers and bad foul shooting turned the apparent rout
into a close game, and with three minutes left, Ball State trailed
55-51. Kapono hit four free throws in the final minutes to seal the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the type of game we planned on playing,'' Kapono
said. ``It was a funky first-round tournament game. We weren't
nervous, but we had a tough time getting a feel. JaRon and I hit
some 3s, and then o ur post guys got some looks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (20-11) started well and held an 18-9 lead when their
bad habits surfaced. Watson's errant alley-oop pass to Rush off the
backboard became a Ball State lay-up - and a four-point swing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a 20-9 lead, UCLA's margin was 18-11, and the
momentum shifted for the remainder of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Gadzuric's turnaround gave the Bruins a 22-20 lead, but Ball
State countered with Cedric Moodie's 3-pointer from the left wing.
With 1:18 left in the half, the Cardinals had their first lead.
Reserve guard Patrick Jackson ended the half with a 3-pointer from
the left corner, increasing Ball State's margin to 26-22. UCLA had
scored four points in the final 8:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very calm at halftime,'' Rush said. ``We got loose
defensively and let them come back. But we've been in those
situations before. We didn't panic.''
</P>
<P>
   The second half began as the first ended. Ball State's Theron
Smith hit a difficult jumper from the left baseline for a six-point
lead. The Bruins countered with Jerome Moiso's dunk, but they went
scoreless for five possessions against the Cardinals' zone defense.
</P>
<P>
   With 16:40 left, Kapono broke the drought, and brought out.
First, he buried a 3-pointer from the left wing - his first basket
of the game. After a Ball State miss, Kapono drained one from the
right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Bruins had a 30-28 lead and Ball State called time
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame we let Kapono get away from us,'' Ball State
guard Mickey Hosier said.
</P>
<P>
   The teams exchanged baskets for several minutes, then Kapono
struck again - this time from the right corner off a crosscourt
pass from Watson.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-pointer gave UCLA a 39-33 lead and the momentum it had
lost in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``(At halftime) I told (Kapono) to let the game come to him,''
Watson said. ``When he started doing that, it opened up everything
we wanted to do. Once Jason got started, our team got started.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's defense smothered the Cardinals each time they entered
the lane. Their fifth-consecutive scoreless possession became a
Rush 3-pointer from the left wing - and a nine-point lead. A few
seconds later, reserve Matt Barnes found Rush for another
3-pointer, and the margin was 45-33.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
