<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVIN BARELY HOLDS OFF CRITICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS - You could sense the critics circling Steve Lavin
as though he were a candy-filled pinata, waiting for their chance
to take another whack.
</P>
<P>
   For eight-and-a-half minutes Thursday night, UCLA's season
looked like it was going to pieces. The Bruins couldn't crack Ball
State's 2-3 zone and were defending their basket like the Keystone
Cops.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as quickly as you can say Detroit Mercy, the Bruins
frittered away an 18-9 lead. They made Ball State's zone look like
Temple's, missing 11 of their final 13 shots before intermission to
fall behind 26-22.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA appeared clueless on offense and disorganized on defense.
It looked like last year's game against Detroit Mercy (a 56-53
loss) all over again. From 1,500 miles away you could feel Pauley's
posse turning its louring eyes to Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   That the Bruins came out in the second half and built a double-
digit lead before settling for a too-close-for-gloating 65-57 win
will appease Lavin's critics a little.
</P>
<P>
   But probably not a lot.
</P>
<P>
   With the possible exception of Kentucky's Tubby Smith, there
might not have been a lonelier winning coach on the opening day of
the NCAA Tournament than Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   Say this for the Bruins' fourth-year coach: Sometimes it looks
like he has about as much control over his players as Alan
Greenspan does the Dow Jones industrial average. But whatever he
said at halftime on this night clearly got UCLA back on track.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins found the seams and gaps in Ball State's zone and
their shooting rhythm quickly followed. Behind the hot hand of
freshman Jason Kapono, who contributed all 17 of his points in the
second half, the Bruins embarked on a 15-0 run in the sixth minute
to wrest the lead away from the Cardinals for keeps.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono made one of his four baskets from beyond the arc in that
span. JaRon Rush added two 3-pointers to open the inside
effectively for Jerome Moiso, Dan Gadzuric and Matt Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   As far as strategies go, it was a lot more effective than the
one guard Earl Watson employed in the first half; he stubbornly
kept lobbing alley-oop passes for highlight finishes. They turned
out to be grenades that blew up in the Bruins' faces. None did more
damage than the off-the-backboard pass Watson threw to Rush in an
effort to extend UCLA's lead to 20-9 in a manner that would raise
the roof of the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The ball bounced long, Ball State got it and Cedric Moodie drove
for a layup at the other end to start the Cardinals on a 17-4 run.
</P>
<P>
   Some coaches would have yanked Watson right away and filled his
ear with loud wisdom. Indiana's Bob Knight might have gone a lot
farther than that. Lavin left Watson alone to figure it out
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Different strokes for different folks.
</P>
<P>
   After the game a contrite-sounding Watson said any stern lecture
Lavin delivered would have merely been echoing his inner voice. ``I
don't need coach Lavin to tell me I need to keep things simple,''
said Watson, who had nine of his 12 assists in the second half.
``If the plays went down, obviously it would have been a great
spark for our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Bruins learned there can be exhilaration in
simplicity. Because if they aren't really careful with the ball
Saturday, they'll get strangled by Maryland's pressure defense. ``I
know I have to handle the ball better against Maryland,'' Watson
said, ``or we're going to be down by 10 or 15 points.''
</P>
<P>
   It would help, too, if Moiso could shoulder part of the
rebounding load. On Thursday he finished with one defensive
rebound. Gadzuric grabbed 12.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year, the Bruins have a second chance to impress the
naysayers. They can only hope they make more of it than they did
Thursday, when they allowed Ball State more points on putbacks than
they got.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, as Lavin was quick to point out, is the Bruins
survived and advanced. He also said the nail-biting game against
the 11th-seeded Cardinals ``went kind of the way we expected.''
</P>
<P>
   That is probably not going to impress Bruins fans much. A No.6
seed is supposed to go into a first-round game expecting to put
away its opponent handily, not let it hang within two baskets of
the lead with a little over two minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But we digress. UCLA's victory Thursday was its seventh in a row
so, yes, one basketball winning streak in L.A. remains alive. But
not for much longer unless the Bruins practice what Lavin is going
hoarse trying to preach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
