<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA FINDS COMFORT ZONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS - Talk about advanced notice. UCLA saw this coming
for a year. Its first-round opponent - in this case, Ball State -
was going to play a zone defense. After watching Detroit Mercy zone
the Bruins into early elimination last year, how could Ball State
not give its zone a shot?
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent half our practice time this week on zone offense,''
said Bruins assistant Jim Saia, who oversees the offense. ``We
(begin ital)knew(end ital) they were going to zone us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Ball State started the game in a man-to-man defense
and switched to its 2-3 zone midway through the first half. The
logic was solid: The Cardinals weren't as big as UCLA and could not
stop the Bruins inside, so why not play a compact zone and force
them to score from the perimeter?
</P>
<P>
   Detroit did it. Gonzaga did it earlier this year, as well, in a
16-point victory at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins were ready. After a sputtering first half, they
found their groove and shot their way into the second round with a
65-57 victory Thursday in the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers tell the story: In the second half, UCLA shot 55.6
percent from the field, 54.5 percent from 3-point range and had 12
assists. They whipped the ball inside and out, over the zone and
through it. One sequence, which ended with a JaRon Rush 3-pointer,
featured five bullet passes to open men.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked on the zone offense all week,'' Rush said, ``so we
knew exactly what to do: Get the ball into the middle and hit the
corners.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were so effective, they actually forced Ball State
out of the zone, a dramatic change from the events of last March.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half, we weren't really in the flow,'' Saia said.
``We were settling for jump shots. I thought, `Oh, no, it's deja
vu.' But we finally got some rhythm shots (from Rush and Jason
Kapono), and we got the ball moving from side to side.''
</P>
<P>
   For Saia, the results were especially gratifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had no problems with the zone except in the Gonzaga
game, and now I think we're prepared for all kinds of zones,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Detroit, we had a hard time attacking it. But the
coaching staff has helped the guys so that now I think we can
attack zones better than at any time since we've been together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every zone has holes, you just have to know where to find
them. We educated the players about where the gaps in the zone are
and what passes are open. Now they can instantly recognize where to
attack. Zones are beatable.''
</P>
<P>
   Point proven.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
