   &UR; BOEING STRIKERS: FLYING IN THE FACE OF A HARSH NEW REALITY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Grainger hardly looks like a tough union type. Yet the
aerodynamics engineer, who has spent 32 years working for Boeing,
is now more than six weeks into the longest, biggest white-collar
strike in American history. The strike has exposed the growing gap
in America's skilled classes. For many of the engineers, the bigger
change has been the way that Seattle man has given way to Redmond
man in Seattle's hierarchy. The explosive growth of Microsoft,
Amazon.com and other ``new economy'' firms has left the Boeing
engineers looking old and poor. &QL;
