   &UR; `ASIA'S NELSON MANDELA' FACES TOUGH REELECTION APRIL 13 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What now for Kim Dae Jung, who restored South Korea's fortunes,
bolstered its democracy, tried to make friends with the communist
North _ and yet stands to be rejected by many voters when his
country goes to the polls on April 13? When he was decisively
elected South Korea's president in 1997, he was considered
something of a maverick, but nevertheless the right man for the
time and the job. &QL;
