<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CASINO-BRIBES (Baton Rouge,La.) _ Former San Francisco 49ers
owner Edward J. DeBartolo was evidently launching a bid to become a
gambling powerhouse in northern Louisiana, when an intercepted
wiretap conversation that surprised FBI agents investigating
corruption in the riverboat casino licensing process tripped him
up. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   UNRULY-PASSENGER (San Francisco) _ Passengers and crew aboard an
Alaska Airlines jet subdue an unruly passenger who freaked out. By
The San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-RAISES (Sacramento, Calif.) _ With meager public comment
during a sparsely attended meeting, a state commission voted again
to give healthy raises to California's top elected officials,
making them among the most highly compensated public servants in
the nation. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   SAFER-WEAPONS (Albany, N.Y.) _ New York Attorney General Eliot
Spitzer is calling for a national coalition of governments whose
firearm purchasing power he hopes will pressure the gun industry to
adopt a ``code of conduct'' that would include making safer
weapons. By JAY JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRANTS-CENSUS (San Francisco) _ In an attempt to prevent an
anticipated undercount of immigrants and others in the U.S. Census,
San Francisco Bay Area immigrant rights groups are working closely
with census officials to encourage minorities and immigrants to
participate in the national survey. By VENISE WAGNER.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DESERT (San Francisco) _ A coalition of environmental
groups filed a lawsuit against the U.S. Bureau of Land Management,
charging that the agency is not fully protecting endangered animals
on 10.2 million acres in the California desert. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-INDICENT (El Paso, Texas) _ U.S. Border Patrol agents say
the incursion into the United States by two vehicles loaded with
Mexican soldiers was more serious than reported, and that shots
fired could be linked to a reported bounty on agents by a major
drug-trafficking cartel. By JODI BIZAR.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIAN-DEATH (San Antonio) _ Seven years after a shootout in a
pasture near Waco's Mount Carmel, a justice of the peace is
renewing his investigation into the death of Michael Schroeder, a
young Branch Davidian killed there. By DICK J. REAVIS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RICKY-MARTIN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Tom Jones and Ricky Martin, who
are scheduled for separate performances in New York's capital city
Monday, are both hip-swivelin' superstars, ridin' high at the top
of the charts and sure to woo female fans. And while there's no
denying that Martin, 28, is hot, the 59-year-old Jones isn't ready
to relinquish his crown just yet. In fact, his latest single, ``Sex
Bomb,'' is a major hit in Europe. By GREG HAYMES. (For release
Sunday, March 19.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-ERIN (Undated) _ In the delightful legal-eagle movie
``Erin Brockovich,'' Julia Roberts brings her corn-fed ebullience
to the brassiest, most irresistible role she has had in years.
Tramped-up in necklines that head south, hemlines that head north
and cleavage that heads everywhere, Roberts' titular heroine is the
sort of ballsy broad who knows what she's got and uses it without
apology. Yet she's still, somehow, Julia Roberts _ the girl next
door with with the self-effacing laugh who can play a hooker and
still seem wholesome. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CUP (Undated) _ Such a sweet, soft-hearted film is
``The Cup'' that you might want to bring your 4-year-old to see it
_ it's rated G, it boasts a scrappy juvenile protagonist and it
features significantly less violence than either ``Pokemon'' or
``Power Rangers.'' The catch is, it's in Tibetan and Bhutanese.
Either junior has to be fluent in Asian languages or old enough to
read subtitles at a fevered clip. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE-CARLIN (Undated) _ The actor George Carlin is now an
institution. Closing in on age 63, the artist did not really find
his voice until the 1980s, long after his bit on the seven words
you can't say on television got him in trouble with the mainstream
suits. Then came cable. No cable, and Carlin would have remained a
funnyman on the fringe. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' CATEGORY)
</P>
<P>
   CARDAMOM (Undated) _ India's ``Queen of Spices'' is indeed
considered royalty in the world of flavor. Cardamom's versatility
enhances the taste of everything from soups to desserts. Its
aromatic, spicy-sweet and warm flavor goes well in both hot and
cold foods. By LISA STEVENS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPRING-BREAK (Albany, N.Y.) _ Students used to hold up signs
reading, ``Hi Mom &AMP; Dad. Send Money.'' These days, they are sending
post cards that say, ``Wish you were here.'' The booming economy
means college students _ kids that have grown up using cell-phones,
surfing the Internet and wearing logo-laden designer duds _ are
spending thousands for more elaborate spring break trips than their
parents could have imagined. By KERI P. MATTOX.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTING (Undated) _ Whimsical lighting is made of any
unexpected, amusing shape, from animals in clothing to a carved
wooden toy. ``People are loosening up with light fixtures, to
introduce more personality into a room,'' said interior designer
Michel Patterson, owner of Hudson River Fine Interiors in
Loudonville, N.Y. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ETHNIC-CELEBRATIONS (Monrovia, Calif.) _ Children used to make
paper chains of red and green in anticipation of Christmas, even if
they came from Jewish, Muslim or non-observant families. Now we are
multicultural. Everyone is included. We still take a week or two
off at Christmas but we call it the ``winter break'' or ``winter
solstice.'' It doesn't really matter, the entire country takes Dec.
25 off _ believers or not, religious or not, observant or not. By
KATHLEEN VALLEE STEIN.
</P>
