<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Racetrack may provide safer haven than freeways in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ ``You must have found something unusually
interesting in the newspaper,'' she said while I stirred no-calorie
sweetener into my third cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's this series about everybody in Georgia driving about 50
miles an hour above the speed limit,'' I answered. ``Maybe it will
get the public riled up to do something about insanity on our
highways.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean somebody besides us thinks they ought to enforce the
law?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure,'' I admitted. ``The politicians seem to be on
the side of speeders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think public officials would be more concerned about
high speeds killing and injuring people and accidents increasing
the cost of insurance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember when our semi-city son moved from Washington back to
Atlanta and the insurance on his car almost doubled?'' I asked.
``They told him Atlanta is about the most dangerous place in the
country to drive an automobile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they got the city confused with Atlanta Motor
Speedway,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt it,'' I replied. ``After reading this series, I think
I could give up gardening and take up another hobby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd certainly go for that,'' she said. ``What hobby do you
have in mind?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stock car racing,'' I replied. ``If we didn't have beans to
can and Silver Queen to cut off, we could spend our Saturdays at
Senoia Raceway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're being facetious,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No I'm not. People my age and older drive on Ga. 400 all the
time. They routinely do 90 and 100 mph. According to a motor sports
writer of my acquaintance, that's about the same as average speeds
at Dixie Speedway, where cars have roll bars and drivers wear
helmets. It's safer than going to Buckhead for dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're stretching it a bit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not. Race drivers are sober when they're on the track.
They're not gossiping or selling insurance on cell phones.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do get irritated when we're in the HOV lane, and somebody on
our bumper blinks their lights and blows their horn unless we are
doing at least 80 or 90,'' she said. ``Isn't the speed limit 55 mph
on interstates within a city?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yes,'' I said, ``but if Indianapolis can have the 500, I
guess we can have the Ga. 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to what it says in the paper: `The number of Georgians
convicted of speeding 90 to 99 miles per hour nearly tripled in the
1990s. Drivers who do 100 increased more than 80 percent.'''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said more than 80,000 Georgians were busted at 90
mph or faster in the past 10 years, with 10,000 traveling 100 mph
or faster. The record-holder was clocked at 152 mph on Interstate
85 in DeKalb County. Nearly 600 people in the metro area are killed
every year. ``Don't they have traffic cops like we do here in
Fayette County?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're mostly observers,'' I explained. ``The theory is that
stopping drivers in 90 mph traffic causes accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people must get injured and killed when wrecks happen
at those speeds,'' she replied. ``Maybe the newspaper series will
get the public stirred up and force our elected officials to do
something about it,'' I said. ``When we read that automobiles and
trucks kill 42,000 a year while it took 10 years of Vietnam to kill
58,000, it's time to do something as simple as enforcing the law.''
</P>
<P>
   For my money, gun control, the Confederate flag and teacher
tenure can take a back seat until road carnage is under control. In
today's political climate you may be wasting time writing
legislators, but you can write, call or e-mail a very powerful
governor, who has sworn to uphold the law, which as last I heard,
includes speed limits.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
