r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN18-COX     03-17 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daytona Beach Bike Week had everything _ and some fine racing
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Half a million bikers roared into this
town for Bike Week 2000.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen were shipped home in coffins. Untold numbers
of motorcyclists went home in bandages and casts.
</P>
<P>
   That left several hundred thousand bike riders who left town
with good memories, souvenir T-shirts, thinner wallets and ringing
ears.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Harleys racking their pipes for a solid week
becomes exhausting, as it were.
</P>
<P>
   For a relative handful, Daytona Beach Bike Week is about the
best motorcycle racing this nation has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest, Bike Week is about booze, breasts and
exhibitionism. See and be seen. Party time.
</P>
<P>
   The daily Main Street parade of bikers and trikers is a fantasy
show of two- and three-wheeled machines and their bizarre owners.
</P>
<P>
   Some bikers exercised improper traffic judgment after a night of
swigging beer while watching wet T-shirt and cole-slaw wrestling
contests at local clubs.
</P>
<P>
   While police paid particular attention to bared breasts, they
ignored both men and women whose bare butts protruded from black
leather chaps.
</P>
<P>
   A chap named Bob was featured in a front-page photo in the
Daytona Beach News Journal leaning on his ape-hanger handle bars
with his glistening fanny on display.
</P>
<P>
   Bike Week is like Mardi Gras with motorcycles for most people
who make the annual March pilgrimage to Daytona Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of Bike Week, in my opinion, is located inside the
Daytona International Speedway where the American Motorcycle
Association kicks off its racing season on the Speedway's 3.56-mile
road course.
</P>
<P>
   These motorcycle racers reach the same speeds as NASCAR racers
except they do it while dragging knees and elbows leaned over on
two wheels without the benefit of four fat tires, steel cages, roll
bars and four-point seat harnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Why the Daytona Speedway does not pack the stands for Superbike
racing like it does for Winston Cup racing is a mystery. Race fans
looking for physics-defying thrills and skills cannot do better
than motorcycle road racing.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the Daytona Speedway fills every available seat for
NASCAR races is because nearly everyone drives a car. They can
relate to a stock car race.
</P>
<P>
   That does not explain why 75 percent of the motorcycle riders
who come to Bike Week ignore some of the best motorcycle road
racing in the world. Their motorcycling interests must be geared to
chrome, fringed leather and loud pipes, not to high-speed
performance and state-of-the-art technology.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere in the Speedway pits during Bike Week is just the
opposite of the non-stop revelry on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   Pit crews are constantly studying computer printouts and tearing
down and rebuilding their race bikes.
</P>
<P>
   Motorcycle manufacturers who sponsor race teams spend millions
of dollars preparing just for Daytona each year.
</P>
<P>
   Tire manufacturers develop special dual-compound tires just for
the Daytona races to accommodate track conditions that include more
high-speed left turns than right turns.
</P>
<P>
   There's an atmosphere of serious anticipation in the pits that
builds until the final checkered flag is thrown.
</P>
<P>
   If Bare-Bottom Bob missed this year's 200-mile Superbike race,
he missed one of the most exciting motorcycle races he ever held in
America, and that's saying a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
