<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIN-WEEKEND18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Researchers say it's true: Weekends get more rain
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Question: What do you call it after two days of
rain in most cities?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It's no joke. Researchers at Arizona State University have found
something golfers have always suggested: It rains more on weekends.
The study found there is as much as a 22 percent greater chance of
rain on Saturdays and Sundays than during the week.
</P>
<P>
   The culprit could be pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Smog, formed when nitrogen oxides and particulate matter mix
with sunlight, builds up through the work week, when there are more
cars and trucks on the road. By the weekend when people are driving
less, the researchers think, this buildup can cause a cloud-seeding
effect. The result: rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that cities have an effect on local weather,'' said
Randall Cerveny, one of the study's authors. ``But nobody had ever
looked at the in-between area of large-scale regional weather. We
appear to be affecting global weather on a scale that is comparable
to El Nino.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Cerveny and research partner Robert Balling were
studying weather patterns on the East Coast, the pattern could
apply to the Midwest as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just looking at that right now,'' Cerveny said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers studied daily rainfall from 1979 to 1995. A
seven-day pattern emerged, with rain amounts steadily increasing
Thursday through Saturday, then falling off Sunday through
Wednesday. Cerveny and Balling found the same kind of seven-day
cycle in pollution levels, leading to the hypothesis that man-made
emissions affect the weather on a regional basis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
