A9600 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD18-COX     03-17 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hand planer has its pros and cons
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Along with all this back-and-forth over planers and
jointers on the Internet comes a fellow who wants to know if he can
finish his pieces with a hand plane and avoid sandpaper.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, is the method made popular by James Krenov in
his series of highly inspirational, persuasive and sometimes
mean-spirited books. If you haven't read any of them, you should.
Chief among them are ``The Fine Art of Cabinetmaking'' and ``The
Impractical Cabinetmaker.'' Krenov pursues woodworking more as a
religion than a vocation. He spends days deciding how to match two
pieces of wood for cabinet doors. He uses only wooden planes of his
own making, and he avoids sandpaper.
</P>
<P>
   His work is astonishing; jewel-like. There is no mistaking a
Krenov cabinet.On the other hand, as is usual with fanatics, it is
his way or the highway. He takes thinly veiled, nasty little
pot-shots at other noted woodworkers.
</P>
<P>
   His repertoire is also the most limited of any of the big-name
woodworkers, confined almost entirely to small display cabinets,
freestanding or wall hung.
</P>
<P>
   Krenov's books enraged a small cult of planemakers, and it's
easy to see why. Of all the evolutions in woodworking, none is so
physically and emotionally satisfying as using a well-tuned plane
with a razor-sharp iron. Having made that plane yourself, to fit
your hands only, makes it that much better.
</P>
<P>
   As for wood with the finish left by that well-tuned, razor-sharp
smooth plane, it is incomparable. A plane iron cuts; sandpaper
abrades. Fine Woodworking magazine once ran an article on the
subject, with microscopic photographs of smooth-planed and
fine-sanded wood. The sanded wood was furry and indistinct. The
planed wood was mirror-like, every nuance of figure enhanced as if
with a spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   So why doesn't everybody work that way? 'Cause 't'ain't easy,
McGee.
</P>
<P>
   You have to become the Horowitz of the smooth plane, a virtuoso
among virtuosos, to plane a board so perfectly that you don't leave
a little cut here, some tearout there.
</P>
<P>
   It helps if you learn to use a scraper. Scrapers are remarkable
little tools; easy to use, hard to prepare for use. A good Sandvik
scraper cost about $5 last time I looked, and if you spend some
time learning to get the hook worked into the edge, it will do a
remarkable job of cleaning up these defects, especially tearout.
</P>
<P>
   But until we all get our doctorates in the construction and use
of smooth planes, the sandpaper makers will continue to rake in the
money.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
