the Confederate flag and teacher tenure can take a back seat until
road carnage is under control. (Jim Minter is a former editor of
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-FUTURE _ LOS ANGELES _ Americans participated in two great
migrations in the 20th century. First, they moved by the millions
from farms to cities, seeking jobs, and after World War II, they
moved again, this time from central cities to suburbs. In the new
century, yet another demographic pattern may emerge: immigrants and
young people will leave suburbs everywhere to find work in the
nation's booming high-tech clusters. Certain states, including
California, Texas, New York, Florida and Georgia, will get a surge
of growth from Asians, Hispanics and others seeking jobs, while the
majority will become relatively whiter, older and less prosperous.
Will we become, in essence, two countries, one old, white and
slow-growing and the other younger, multicultural and more
entrepreneurial? (Geewax, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With TECH-FUTURE-DATA.
</P>
<P>
   Moved Thursday in (f) financial and (k) commentary categories.
(Geewax, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Good news. Beer is health food. To thank for
this welcome intelligence, we have, oddly, the organization People
for the Ethical Treatment of Animals. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ As with the American economy, the rich of the
Dominican Republic are getting richer and the poor are getting
poorer, even desperate. Santo Domingo is undergoing a building
boom, tourism is at its best ever and the Dominican Republic is
seen as the area's fastest-growing economy. Why, then, are there
boat people? (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News
Service.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ A ruling from U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson would force Microsoft to fend off a raft of private civil
suits, which could carry triple damages. The plaintiffs would hold
the high ground, armed with the presumption that the wealthy
defendant had broken the law. (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox
News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YOUNGVOTER _ MOSCOW _ We talk to an 18-year-old who will
be voting for the first time in this month's presidential election
and get his/her thoughts on its importance, Vladimir Putin and the
overall state of Russia. (Coker, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO and
box attached to end of story.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Wed., March 15, in (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: This story is meant to pair and run with a similar story
done by each Cox newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INDIA _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will be traveling
to the volatile region of South Asia during the week of March 20,
2000, primarily visiting India and Bangladesh. He will be the first
President to visit India since 1978 and the first ever to visit
Bangladesh. At the last minute, he has also decided to add a
stopover to the visit the new military government in neighboring
Pakistan. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH itinerary info attached to end of story.
</P>
