<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV19-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRY REGROUTING BEFORE COVERING TILE SHOWER STALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 19, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My shower stall is 37 inches square, tiled with a formed pan
of what looks like concrete. The house is 35 years old. Now, water
is leaking through the grout and dripping into the basement. Can I
put a sheet of acrylic or Formica along the three sides of the
shower to stop the leak?
</P>
<P>
   LARRY ROOT, Stow, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. I suggest you contact a company that puts acyrlic shells
over old tubs; such a company also will handle a shower. I think
that would be better than Formica; for one thing, the shell for the
shower is in one piece.
</P>
<P>
   While you can do this, why cover up good tile? Consider
regrouting the tile to stop the leak, or regrout between tile and
shower pan edge. First, line the shower with curtains or other
waterproof tarps, then shower up a storm to see if the leaks
continue; if they do not, you know it's the grout that needs
redoing. If the leaks continue, it may mean the pan is leaking;
have a pro check it out.
</P>
<P>
   To redo the grout, chip and gouge it out (there are tools for
this purpose; one is calld a grout ripper) and insert new grout.
After the grout sets, apply a tile sealer to make the grout
waterproof. If that works, you'll be set for another 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't, and the pan doesn't leak, then the shell would be
OK.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I had a roto man clean out the roots in my sewer line, but he
only bored a small hole in the root-filled line, not clearing it
totally. He suggested high-pressure water to clean the rest. But
the city feared that the high pressure might damage the line, and
suggested chemicals to do the rest of the roots. What are those
chemicals, and what is best to do?
</P>
<P>
   LINDA CRONIN, Peabody, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The chemicals are one, copper sulphate, a potent poison, sold
by chemical supply stores and some lumber stores. Put in the line,
the chemical will kill the roots and allow them to decay, when they
can be washed away by a low pressure stream or ordinary use of the
sewer. This will take quite a while.
</P>
<P>
   The recommended dose is 5 pounds of copper sulphate in the
sewer. Put it in the cleanout, not in a fixture. Place part of the
dose and allow time for crystals to dissolve before adding. When
the sewer is cleared, it can be maintained clear by treating with
one pound of cppper sulphate every 3 months.
</P>
<P>
   Before you do this, I suggest you find a Roto-Rooter man (they
advertise a lot and are widely available) to see if the line can be
entirely cut out. If not, go with the chemical. If the problem
persists no matter what you do, consider rebuilding the line or
removing some of the trees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am finishing my basement, and I wonder if could put in an
indoor-outdoor carpet with rubber backing? We have allergies, so I
have to be careful what goes down there. What is an alternative to
carpeting?
</P>
<P>
   J.A., Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The indoor-outdoor carpeting is a synthetic, so should be OK,
but be sure to check it out. But do not use rubber backing, nor any
rubber pad of any kind. This rubber is a vapor barrier, and you
cannot use a vapor barrier like that on a cellar floor; water vapor
will get trapped under it and condense into water. The carpeting
will allow water vapor to go up through it; so will the pad if it
is a synthetic jute, which also may be non-allergenic.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is vinyl tile or ceramic tile. Then you can put
non-allergenic area rugs down. In the greater scheme of things, I
think the indoor-outdoor carpeting will give the best service at
the best price.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have to replace my garage roof, a corrugated asphalt
roofing that failed after 10 years. I forget its name, but it
should have lasted more than 10 years. It is a one-slope roof, 21
by 32 feet, with a 3 or 4/12 pitch. Can I use shingles, or roll
roofing? A neighbor has a similar slope with shingles, and is
always replacing blown-off shingles.
</P>
<P>
   DAN TRASK, Essex, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I too forget the name of that asphalt corrugated roofing, but
when it came out many years ago, it looked (and was touted) to be a
great barn roofing.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, you could put on a rubber roof that will give good
service. Roll roofing will be OK, too, but may not last beyond 10
years. That 3 to 4/12 pitch is OK for shingles. I would specify as
heavy duty a shingle as practical, and an organic (not fiberglass)
one. In fact, the roofing makers are touting a hurricane resistant
shingle, but all asphalt shingles are self-sealing and resistant to
high winds. I'll bet your neighbor's shingles (the ones that are
flying off) are fiberglass.
</P>
<P>
   I would opt for the shingles; they will look better and are
probably less expensive than the rubber roof.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
