<HEADLINE>
A SENSE OF SECURITY, YET A CONCERN FOR SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Safety: It's something you can't ignore when thinking about a
truck or sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Safety is one reason many buyers turn to an SUV. Most feel safe
driving one, especially the larger ones, with all that bulk around
them. Many SUVs are also built on a truck frame for added strength,
rather than the unibody construction used in cars. SUVs and most
trucks are also higher off the road, providing better visibility
(unless you're in a car riding behind one _ a major complaint of
non-SUV owners). Another way SUVs and trucks provide safety is on
models equipped with all-wheel-drive, providing a secure footing on
slippery surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   But the way these vehicles handle has become a major safety
concern. All SUVs come with warnings of possible rollovers. While
any vehicle can tip in a sudden manuever, such as trying to avoid
another vehicle, sport utilities are particularly prone to this
because of their design _ being higher off the road.
</P>
<P>
   The rollover issue came to a head when Consumers Union, after
placing vehicles through a double-lane change emergency avoidance
test, labeled the 1995 and '96 Isuzu Trooper and the 1998 Suzuki
Samura as unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of an SUV should be aware that the vehicles tend to be
top heavy _ some more than others _ and care should be taken while
making sharp turns or in emergency situations. Also, drivers should
be careful when using antilock brakes in such a situation.
Anti-lock brakes require a vehicle to be going in a straight
direction during an emergency-braking situation. A sudden twist of
the wheel during braking could cause the vehicle to become
unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of any truck should look for safety features such as
front and side air bags, ABS, and child safety features; trucks
often lag behind automobiles in safety equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Not all SUVs are created equal. Some are designed to go
anywhere, do just about anything; others are designed just for the
road. Some have full-time four-wheel-drive designed to send power
to which wheels need it; others, with part-time four-wheel-drive
are designed only for use on snow or off road, not for high-mileage
highway driving.
</P>
<P>
   However, many manufacturers are adding additional safety
features.
</P>
<P>
   Land Rover recently introduced an Active Cornering Enhancement
on its Discover series that reduces body lean to make the vehicle
more responsive under cornering situations. It is a $2,000 option.
(Land Rover also produces an interesting book comparing all SUVs,
including drivetrains, off-road capabilities, and pricing. Copies
are available at dealerships.)
</P>
<P>
   A concern to non-SUV owners is the fear of being hit by a
sport-utility and having the vehicle ride up over the smaller car.
Mercedes-Benz has placed bumpers on its M series SUVs at the same
level as cars to avoid those situations. The Lincoln Navigator has
a secondary bumper system underneath to also prevent similiar
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Ford will introduce air bags to protect occupants' heads in the
event of a rollover in Explorers and other models next year. The
air bags provide a curtain that will inflate over front and side
windows and stay inflated for up to 6 seconds to cushion driver's
and passenger heads long enough to outlast a multiple rollover.
Most air bags deflate immediately after opening; only Mercedes-Benz
has side air bags that stay open a few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford system uses sensors, which measure how far the vehicle
is tipping. If a rollover is imminent, inflators are triggered,
filling a long air bag on each side of the vehicle with cool gas.
Ford says the new bags are not connected with any federal
investigation, but found that 80 percent of its owners said they
wanted such a feature.
</P>
<P>
   Rollovers are the most common fatal truck accident. The National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration is now working on a scoring
system to tell consumers how likely different SUVs are to roll
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ultimate Car Book 2000'' by Jack Gillis (A HarperResource
Book, $19.95) offers many safety tips and has a rollover rating
guide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
