<SLUG> BC-TRUCKS-BRIEFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARLEY, FORD OFFER A SPECIAL EDITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the line between cars-trucks-and SUVs is blurred, here's one
special edition that will be unmistakable: Ford's Harley-Davidson
F-150 pickup. Up to 7,500 of the $32,995 trucks will be built,
beginning on April 10 at Ford's Ontrario Truck Plant. It will be a
4x2 SuperCab (black, naturally) with Harley-Davidson orange
pinstriping, a chrome grill and a flareside box topped by a hard
shell tonneau.
</P>
<P>
   Under the hood will be a 5.4-liter Triton V-8 producing
260-horsepower and turning massive 20-inch tires. The suspension is
lowered one inch with special shocks and (naturally) sport-tuned 3
1/2-inch slash cut exhaust tips.
</P>
<P>
   Inside will be more of the H-D touch, including a dashboard
ornament, black leather-trimmed seats, and a ``spun metal''
instrument cluster. Additional options are slim: a six-disc CD
changer ($400), sliding rear window ($125) and engine block heater
($90) are it.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's George Magro says, ``This is the first of more exciting
products to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, special editions aren't anything new. Ford continues
its Eddie Bauer edition with the Expedition and Explorer, and Chevy
has a neat Warner Brothers Edition of its extended-length Venture
minivans,
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Truck tracks
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Word out of the Geneva Auto Show is that Dodge will stop using
Cummings diesel engines in its big Ram pickups in favor of a
Mercedes-Benz diesels. The change should begin with the next
generation Ram pickup, scheduled out in 2002 as a 2003 model . . .
GM reported record retail truck sales in February _ 227,298 units,
up 20 percent and the third straight month of double-digit growth
in truck sales . . . DaimlerChrysler reported February minivan
sales up 26 percent from a year ago. Dodge trucks were up 9 percent
. . . The folks at Nissan were happy with truck sales up 61.7
percent versus February, 1999 . . . Nissan Pathfinder buyers will
be equally happy to hear that the 2001 SUV (it went on sale March
15) will have a bunch of updates, most notably a beefier V-6 that
should solve complaints about it being underpowered. The new
3.5-liter V-6 is based on the technology used in the acclaimed
Maxima V-6. How big a change is it? The 3.3-liter V-6 in the 2000
model put out 170 horsepower, the new version is 240 when coupled
to an automatic transmission and 250 with the 5-speed manual.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Top-notch group
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It will be an impressive Class of 2000 that gets inducted into
the Automotive Hall of Fame this Oct. 17 at the Ritz-Carlton in
Dearborn, Mich. The lineup:
</P>
<P>
   Warren Avis: Founder of Avis Rent-a-Car.
</P>
<P>
   Ettore Bugatti: Manufacturer of legendary luxury automobiles and
racing cars.
</P>
<P>
   Enzo Ferrari: Auto racer and founder of the Ferrari racing team.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Fraser: Former UAW president.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Parks: First editor of Hod Rod magazine and founder of the
National Hot Rod Association.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Ramsey: First woman to motor cross country, driving from
New York to the West Coast in 1909.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
