r l BC-EVANGELISM-COX     03-17 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVANGELISM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Evangelical leader to speak at conference
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CENTERVILLE, Ohio _ For evangelical Christians, the directive is
clearly laid forth in the Gospels. It's their job to spread the
word of Jesus Christ to ``unreached peoples,'' even people of other
faiths.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 has given that evangelization effort new urgency
as Christians celebrate the second millennium of Christ's birth. In
the past 10 years, grass-roots prayer movements have sprung up,
linking individual Christian churches with ``unchurched'' corners
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those efforts have been coordinated through AD2000, a
Colorado Springs-based organization that provides information and
resources to evangelistic efforts around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Bush, the group's international director, will speak about
that effort this weekend at Fairhaven Church. His appearance is
part of the church's twice-annual International Missions
Conference. The conference is a resource for other local churches,
according to the Rev. David Smith, pastor of international
ministries.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelism is more important to Christians and Muslims than to
any other religious group, according to William Shea, a theology
professor at St. Louis University. ``Conservative, evangelical
Christians believe salvation is attained only through faith in
Christ,'' he said. ``The 19th and 20th centuries have been
high-water marks in the attempt to convert the world.''
</P>
<P>
   At AD2000, the motto is ``A Church for Every People and the
Gospel for Every Person in the Year 2000.'' The organization was
started in 1995 by Bush, an Argentinian-born evangelist.
</P>
<P>
   It's an ecumenical effort, he says, with Presbyterians, Southern
Baptists, Anglicans and others working together.
</P>
<P>
   At its Web site, www.AD2000.org, the stated goal is to reach 2.2
billion people in 1,739 ethnolinguistic groups by the end of the
year. The methodology is precise: ``Prayer teams'' travel to the
area to take photographs and make maps to bring back to their
congregations. Then, the prayer effort begins. Churches can also
``adopt'' specific groups of people whom they support through
visitation, prayer, money and other resources. Bush says these
efforts have netted ``over 50,000 pieces of information on 110
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   A particular geographical focus is what Bush calls the ``10/40
window'' _ an area of North Africa, the Middle East and Asia that
is between 10 degrees and 40 degrees north latitude. Bush says this
region contains the world's least evangelized and poorest people.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, Bush says, 21 million people have prayed for the 62
nations in this area, and about 200 prayer teams have travelled to
pray on site.
</P>
<P>
   The 4,000 members of Fairhaven have adopted the Mien people of
Asia. Prayer, money and other resources flow to Mien Christians who
are evangelizing non-Christian Miens.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the people in this part of the world are Buddhist,
Muslim or Hindu. Bush avoids use of the word ``conversion,'' but
``the Scripture says very clearly that there is no other name ...
by which man can be saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to communicate the fact that God loves them,
that Jesus loves them and died for them. Their greatest spiritual
need is the Lord Jesus Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Kathy Whyde Jesse at kathywhydejesse(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
