<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9675 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-RICKY-MARTIN-$ADV19-H     03-17 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICKY-MARTIN-$ADV19-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TOM JONES NOT READY TO SURRENDER TO THE RICKY MARTIN CRAZE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 19)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GREG HAYMES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ He's a hip-swivelin' superstar singer.
</P>
<P>
   He's ridin' high at the top of the charts.
</P>
<P>
   He's roarin' into New York's state capital Monday night, where
he's sure to deliver an explosive, high-energy show that's
guaranteed to have his female fans swooning in the aisles.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Ricky Martin ... and Tom Jones.
</P>
<P>
   While sexy, Latin, la-vida-loca-livin' Man of the Moment Ricky
Martin is wowing fans at the Pepsi Arena on Monday, his counterpart
from a generation ago, Tom Jones, will be knocking out his
followers at Proctor's Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   To most, it might seem to be the passing of the torch from a
once-glorious, high-wattage crooner to the next generation's
musical sex symbol.
</P>
<P>
   And while there's no denying that Martin, 28, is hot, hot, hot
right now, Jones isn't ready to relinquish his crown just yet.
Although he launched his career way back in 1965 with the smash hit
``It's Not Unusual,'' the 59-year-old Jones isn't just a sex symbol
for grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   Jones hasn't released an album of new material in the United
States since his underrated ``The Lead and How to Swing It,'' was
released in 1994. And his last bona-fide hit was in 1988, when he
scored with a remake of Prince's ``Kiss,'' backed by the
electro-dance combo Art of Noise.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's hard to tell here in America, Tom Jones' career is
hotter than it's ever been in Europe. His latest single, ``Sex
Bomb,'' is a super-smash hit. It's currently No. 7 on the charts in
Germany, No. 4 in Spain and Austria, No. 3 in Belgium, No. 2 in
Italy and No. 1 in France and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, his current European album, ``Reload,'' is also in
the Top 10 in every one of those countries.
</P>
<P>
   The album _ which unfortunately is not yet scheduled for a U.S.
release _ finds Jones in a collaborative mode, as he shares the
microphone with such partners as Van Morrison, the Pretenders'
Chrissie Hynde (on a razor-sharp rendition of Iggy Pop's ``Lust For
Life''), Barenaked Ladies, Stereophonics (on Randy Newman's ``Mama
Told Me Not to Come'') and Simply Red's Mick Hucknall, to name a
few.
</P>
<P>
   The first single from the album, a hot-wired remake of the
Talking Heads' ``Burning Down the House'' recorded with the
Cardigans, was a smash all across Europe, too.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, after almost a year on the charts, Martin's
self-titled English-language debut album is still securely in the
Top 50 of Billboard's best-selling album chart. So far, the album
has sold more than 7 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   And while the inescapable ``Livin' La Vida Loca'' was one of the
best-selling records of last year, Martin's follow-up single,
``Shake Your Bon-Bon,'' was only a modest hit, failing to crack the
Top 20.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's spectacular live performances have turned more than a
few non-believers into fans, however. His electrifying performance
last year at the Grammy Awards show was an absolute career-making
moment, winning him the adoration of millions of TV viewers as well
as superstar Madonna, who immediately concocted a duet with the
Latin sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Martin didn't take a trophy home with him at last
month's Grammy Awards ceremonies, his performance was something of
a three-ring circus, complete with aerial acrobats, slinky,
barely-clad dancers and even an actual ring of fire.
</P>
<P>
   The charismatic Martin also wowed television viewers with his
first-ever television special, ``One Night Only,'' which aired on
CBS in November. The concert, recently released as a home video,
was filmed outdoors in New Jersey's Liberty State Park with the New
York City skyline as a backdrop, and while the spectacle was
undeniably dazzling, Martin's considerable singing talents often
seemed overshadowed by his nonstop gyrations and the
everything-to-excess production values of the performance.
</P>
<P>
   As successful as both singers have been, their careers have been
dominated by their sexy, larger-than-life images rather than their
musical talent. And Jones' experience in combating the public's
perception of him could serve as a cautionary tale to the
up-and-coming sex symbol Martin, who is igniting quite a
combustible reaction among his fevered fans these days.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the early days of Jones' career, when he was churning
out his initial string of hit records _ including ``What's New,
Pussycat?,'' ``The Green, Green Grass of Home'' and ``Delilah'' _
Jones worked his primarily female, underwear-tossing fans into a
frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that in my case, the image overshadowed the talent in
a lot of people's eyes. I've had to get over the whole panties
thing,'' explained Jones during an interview a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time in the '70s, I'd read reviews of my shows where
the writers wrote about how many pairs of underwear were thrown.
Sometimes, the writers were so busy documenting the crowd's frenzy
that my voice would not even be mentioned in the review. They'd be
reviewing the audience's reaction instead of my performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole panties thing really got out of hand. I used to not
exactly encourage it, but go along with it,'' Jones admitted.
``Pick them up, wipe the brow and do the business, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   ``But if people throw things at me now, I don't pick them up.
They just stay where they land. And believe me,'' he adds with a
resounding laugh, ``sometimes the stage is quite littered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1202EST &QL; 
