<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9681 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-CUP-HNS &LR;      03-17 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `THE CUP' RUNNETH OVER WITH DELIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Such a sweet, soft-hearted film is ``The Cup'' that you might
want to bring your 4-year-old to see it _ it's rated G, it boasts a
scrappy juvenile protagonist and it features significantly less
violence than either ``Pokemon'' or ``Power Rangers'' (Uh, what
doesn't?). The catch is, it's in Tibetan and Bhutanese. Either
junior has to be fluent in Asian languages or old enough to read
subtitles at a fevered clip.
</P>
<P>
   That being said, ``The Cup'' offers proof positive that films
need be neither obvious nor vulgar to woo the viewer's attention.
This little film about soccer-crazed Tibetan monks exiled in India
bewitches without being pushy, relying on none of the usual
moviemaking conventions to nudge the story along.
</P>
<P>
   Put ``story'' in quotes: What plot there is concerns nothing
more labyrinthine than a bunch of young monks scheming to watch the
1998 World Cup. No fatal catastrophes befall them along the way, no
moments of violence or heartbreak or deus-ex-machinal plot twists.
We don't even see much soccer _ brief snatches of two televised
games, total.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``The Cup'' delights on its own, offering an unsentimental,
unexpectedly prankish view of a world not quite cut off from
Western civilization. Filled with actual Tibetan monks, the film
was written and directed by Khyntese Norbu, a Bhutanese filmmaker
doubly known as one of the most important incarnate lamas in the
Tibetan Buddhist tradition.
</P>
<P>
   He's not the only one with an interesting resume: Among the
cast, the press kit explains, is the fourth reincarnation of an
18th-century Buddhist master, a ceremonial hierarch so daunting
that ``it was challenging to find a Tibetan actor willing to
wrestle with him.'' (The press kit also explains that one cast
member ``has never washed his hair.'')
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the film is Jamyang Lodro as Orgyen, the puckishly
naughty novice monk who sneaks off into the woods for nocturnal
rendezvous with a village television set. There he watches World
Cup soccer games with his confreres, who eventually get caught and
disciplined. But it isn't long before Orgyen and his mates have
convinced the monastery's aged Abbot (Lama Chonjor, an actual
abbot) and stern disciplinarian, Geko (Orgyen Tobgyal, an incarnate
lama and Jamyang Lodro's father), for permission to rent a boob
tube and satellite dish to watch the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the plot _ granted, a bit thin. But the movie's charm
boils down to its honeyed mix of East and West, the exotic and the
mundane: the sight of monks, their rust-red robes gathered around
their ankles, chasing a soccer ball in the dirt; an old lama who
turns empty Coke cans into devotional candles; the monks who pore
over smuggled sport magazines; Orgyen's room, a shrine to soccer
players, or his undershirt emblazoned with the name and number of
Brazilian superstar Ronaldo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cup'' pairs its young monks' pop-cultural savvy with the
old Abbot's quiet endurance of exile (``Do you think these monks
will know what Tibet was really like?''), a counterpoint familiar
to any tale of immigrants abroad: As Americans know full well,
whippersnappers assimilate. Lengthen their hair, paint freckles on
their cheeks and swap their robes for rosaries, and Geko's
misbehaving monks could be Catholic boys launching spitballs at
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Warren's bright, straightforward cinematography captures
both the harsh Indian landscape of jagged mountains and wide,
yellow fields of grass (the film actually was shot in Bhutan) and
the humdrum details of life in the monastery. Norbu seemed to
realize, while making the film, that Westerners would comprise his
main audience, and he lets the movie dwell on tidbits: the making
of tea, the twisting of wicks, the shaving of heads.
</P>
<P>
   Humor sneaks in with little fanfare. When a newcomer asks Orgyen
why he can't watch World Cup matches during the day, the young monk
quips: ``It's something to do with the world not being flat.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on, while the abbot mulls the monks' request to rent a TV,
he ponders the illogic of two civilized nations ``fighting over a
ball.'' As Abbot asks Geko what the winner receives, he pours a cup
of butter tea. And as the old man raises the vessel to his lips,
Geko answers: ``A cup.'' They smile. We smile. The film smiles,
too, as peacefully and contemplatively as a monk in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
