<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9691 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-RAP-BROWN-MAIN-COX     03-17 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAP-BROWN-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Victim says former H. Rap Brown was gunman
 &HT;    By Joshua B. Good
 &HT;    and Doug Payne
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Police today identified former Black Panther leader H.
Rap Brown as the man who shot two deputies in Atlanta Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators showed one of the wounded deputies a photo
line-up, which included pictures of Brown, now know as Jamil
Abdullah Al-Amin. Deputy Algernon English identified Al-Amin as the
shooter, Atlanta Police Chief Beverly Harvard said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Chief C.B. Jackson said Al-Amin was charged with two
counts of aggravated battery in connection with the shootings.
Al-Amin had not been captured by early afternoon. The Atlanta
police are leading the investigation into the shooting. Jackson
heads the department's criminal investigation section.
</P>
<P>
   The two Fulton County sheriff's deputies were shot by a
.223-caliber assault rifle late Thursday when they attempted to
serve a warrant on Al-Amin at an address in West End, said Capt.
David Chadd of the Fulton County Sheriff's Department.
</P>
<P>
   The deputies saw a black Mercedes parked in front of the
address, Harvard said. The deputies ordered the driver to show his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, here they are,'' the man in the Mercedes said as he opened
fire, English told investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred at the intersection of Oak Street and West
End Place, in the street near a grocery store run by Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   The two deputies were taken to Grady Memorial Hospital. They
both underwent surgery, which concluded shortly after 1 a.m., and
were in the intensive care unit, said Barbara Vogel, a hospital
night administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kinchen was in extremely critical condition after being
shot in the abdomen and leg. English, listed in serious condition,
was shot four times _ twice in the left arm, once in the left thigh
and once in the right side.
</P>
<P>
   Both deputies were wearing protective vests as well as a metal
plate inside the vest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ballistic shield may have saved English's life,'' Cook
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the kind of guy you want backing you up,'' Corporal John
Watson of the Fulton County Court Services said of English. Watson
said English had been in working in warrant services for about six
months.
</P>
<P>
   The deputies had been attempting to serve a Cobb County warrant
when the shooting started, said Chadd.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton Sheriff Jacqueline Barrett said it was ``almost an ambush
situation they walked into.''
</P>
<P>
   The address where the warrant was served, 1128 Oak St., has a
sign over the door: ``In the Name of Allah, Most Gracious, Most
Merciful, the Community Store.''
</P>
<P>
   At 1126 Oak St. is the Al-Fajr Trading Co., which sells incense,
books, oils and clothing. A sign reads: ``Welcome to Islam, Worship
the Creator, not the Creations.''
</P>
<P>
   Chadd said it looked as if the gunman ``had a vendetta for
police officers or deputies.''
</P>
<P>
   The officers returned fire and may have wounded the suspect,
Chadd said.
</P>
<P>
   Police seeking the shooter thought they had him cornered in the
store at 1128 Oak. When officers entered, they found signs that the
man may have been wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're following a blood trail,'' Chadd said. SWAT teams were
conducting a house-to-house search of a four-block area south of
downtown Atlanta. The neighborhood being searched was around the
Oak Street area near West End Place.
</P>
<P>
   Police brought in a helicopter and dogs. West End Place was
blocked off through the night. Al-Amin, 56, moved to the West End
area in 1976 after he was released from prison on a robbery
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   He converted to the Muslim faith while in prison and changed his
name to Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   The grocery store he runs is about 100 feet from, and on the
other side of West End Place from Al-Amin's mosque, which is housed
in a large blue frame building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been knowing him (Al-Amin) since '77,'' said Jerry
Stegall, a taxi dispatcher who lives next to the mosque. ``I don't
believe he would have been shooting a police officer. I know he was
in the Black Panthers, but that was 30 years ago and people
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Stegall said he had been in the grocery store often, but the
former activist turned Muslim never tried to convert him. ``It was
up to you. If you wanted to talk about Islam, he'd listen, but he
never tried to talk you into his religion,'' he said of Al-Amin,
who he described as a calm-natured person.
</P>
<P>
   William Abdur-Rahim, representing the Council of the Iman, a
group of about 20 mosques in the Atlanta area, was at Grady
Memorial Hospital early this morning.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke to Mayor Bill Campbell, who was also at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Abdur-Rahim said he has known Al-Amin for several years and that
he believes police were being too quick to try to convict him,
saying there is no proof Al-Amin is the person who shot the
officers.
</P>
<P>
   He described Al-Amin as ``a pillar of the Muslim community and a
pillar of the African-American community. He's valuable in the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Cobb County police arrested Al-Amin on May 31, 1999, during a
traffic stop on Cobb Parkway near I-285. Al-Amin was driving a
stolen 1992 green Ford Explorer. He told Officer J.J. Mack that he
had bought the Explorer earlier in the month, according to the
police incident report.
</P>
<P>
   When Al-Amin pulled out his wallet, he had what appeared to be a
police badge, the report said. When Mack asked if he was a cop,
Al-Amin said yes, he was an officer in White Hall, Ala., the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   But when police checked it out they couldn't find proof Al-Amin
was an officer, the report said. He was also charged with no proof
of insurance and arrested.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Cobb County jail booking report, Al-Amin was
released on $10,000 bond within hours of his arrest. He was
indicted on all three charges on Sept. 3, according to court
records.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin failed to appear in Cobb County Superior Court on Jan.
24, and Judge Mary Staley issued a bench warrant for his arrest
four days later, according to the warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
