<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9694 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-ERIN-HNS &LR;      03-17 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-ERIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `ERIN BROCKOVICH' PROVIDES PATHOS BATHED IN HUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is probably stating the obvious, but you have to love Julia
Roberts. No, literally you have to. It's in the penal code
somewhere. (Section 115-D: No person shall engage in such conduct
or opinion that would constitute an insult to Julia Roberts, her
movies, person, boyfriends or hair.)
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is by now such an American icon that it's hard to
imagine the last decade of moviegoing without her. She seems so
permanent, so fixed in our joint consciousness, that each new film
she releases carries a curious air of inevitability. We know what
to expect of her because we own her: Like Shirley Temple before
her, Roberts' stardom is as much a product of our frontier optimism
as her own exuberant gifts. She's ours.
</P>
<P>
   Never has this been clearer than in ``Erin Brockovich,'' in
which Roberts brings her corn-fed ebullience to the brassiest, most
irresistible role she has had in years. Tramped-up in necklines
that head south, hemlines that head north and cleavage that heads
everywhere, Roberts' titular heroine is the sort of ballsy broad
who knows what she's got and uses it without apology. Her breasts
are weapons; her language is trash. Yet she's still, somehow, Julia
Roberts, the girl next door with the self-effacing laugh who can
play a hooker and still seem wholesome. ``Pretty Woman'' is never
far away.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is perfect for this kind of contradiction, and she's
perfect for ``Erin Brockovich,'' an unexpectedly delightful
legal-eagle movie that embraces convention while twisting it
craftily on its ear. Keen viewers, and even a few not-so-keen
viewers, will spot the obvious parallels with last year's ``A Civil
Action'' _ Big Bad Corporation Fouls Water, Gets Sued _ but ``Erin
Brockovich'' is neither as gorgeous to look at nor as fatally blah.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's an eco-crusade with spunk, the true story of a
broke, spirited single mom who joins forces with a lawyer (a
splendiferously discombobulated Albert Finney) to bring down
California utility giant Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric.
</P>
<P>
   The film was directed by Steven Soderbergh, the former indie
wunderkind whose work runs from the off-kilter (``Out of Sight,''
``The Limey'') to the ecstatically odd (``Schizopolis''). It was
scripted by Susannah Grant, who wrote the revisionist fable ``Ever
After,'' and her collaboration with Soderbergh boasts the same
winning self-awareness; she seems to specialize in films that tweak
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   A few tweaks are inherent to the story, as Erin (whose real-life
counterpart pops up in a cameo) is neither a legal authority nor
one of the plaintiffs poisoned by PG&AMP;E's toxic chromium outwash.
She's just a nobody with a filing job in a small private firm. But
what a nobody: By film's end she's found 634 people whose lives
were ruined by the utility company's malign neglect. Both Erin
Brockovich and ``Erin Brockovich'' confound expectations, imbuing a
long, sad tale with lightness and warmth. When was the last time
someone made a comedy about people dying from contaminated
groundwater?
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Erin Brockovich'' isn't strictly a comedy. It is a very
funny film, but it's a funny film that pulls laughs from character
and human drama rather than boilerplate sitcom set-ups. One of the
more startling punchlines in the film occurs about halfway through,
when Erin, gathering evidence for the suit against PG&AMP;E, interviews
a housewife (Marg Helgenberger) who's just learned she has uterine
and breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   It's a brutally affecting scene, prefaced by a brief, dark clip
of the woman's husband thrashing in anger at the plant across the
way. But just as the scene is about to erode from pathos to bathos,
Soderbergh slaps it with humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think,'' asks the housewife, ``if you've got no uterus
and no breasts, you're still technically a woman?'' Half a beat
passes before Erin's reply. ``You're a happier woman,'' she says,
``because you don't have to worry about maxi-pads and underwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's something even more extraordinary: It gets a laugh. A
confused laugh, a shocked laugh, a guilty laugh, but nevertheless a
laugh. Although ``Erin Brockovich'' is by far the most linear movie
Soderbergh has ever made _ even ``Out of Sight'' had more tricks up
its sleeve _ it retains his spirit of contrary independence.
Despite a hefty running time (131 minutes), he whooshes things
along, elbowing past the standard narrative techniques that usually
clutter such films. It has, for instance, no courtroom climax.
</P>
<P>
   While some of this may irritate traditional-minded viewers,
``Erin Brockovich'' is beyond question a crowd-pleaser _ an
eccentric anti-blockbuster masquerading as mainstream fodder.
Although Roberts gets plenty of mileage from her push-up bra, her
crossfire with co-stars is as nuanced and sneaky as anything she's
done. (Aaron Eckhardt, best known as the white-collar scum from
``In the Company of Men,'' is a dish of soft butter as Erin's
sensitive-biker beau.) Just look at her scenes with Finney, his
great, soft loaf of a face flushed with amazement; he's never seen
a creature like this before, although we have. It's our Julia. And
oh, how we love her.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
