<HEADER>
A9696 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-ETHNIC-CELEBRATIONS-H     03-17 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHNIC-CELEBRATIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THREE CHEERS FOR THE RED, WHITE, BLUE (AND GREEN) 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KATHLEEN VALLEE STEIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROVIA, Calif. _ Holiday are important to small children. They
provide elementary school teachers an opportunity to teach ``art''
by having their small charges pick the correct color crayon for
each holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Children used to make paper chains of red and green in
anticipation of Christmas, even if they came from Jewish, Muslim or
families who do not observe the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Now we are multicultural. Everyone is included. We still take a
week or two off at Christmas but we call it the ``winter break'' or
``winter solstice.'' It doesn't really matter, the entire country
takes Dec. 25 off _ believers or not, religious or not.
</P>
<P>
   What are we to make of St. Patrick's Day? No one gets a day off
work, but elementary school children use green crayons to color
four-leaf clovers and cartoon versions of St. Patrick. Adults drink
green beer and New York has a big parade. Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   My Irish-German mother loves St. Patrick's Day. When I was a kid
she made ``blarney stones'' out of white squares of cake covered in
green frosting, rolled in crushed peanuts. My brothers and sisters
and I devoured them. They were a family tradition and delicious.
</P>
<P>
   I grew up in a small town in the Midwest in the late 1950s, safe
in the knowledge that everyone in the world was white, Christian
and just like me. Some may call my upbringing homogeneous. I call
it deprived. I didn't eat a taco until I was 24, the same year I
attended my first symphony concert.
</P>
<P>
   I moved to California in 1982. I heard Spanish and learned the
important words. I got a taste of real Mexican food, a la
California, and loved every bite. I was introduced to Chinese,
Korean, Vietnamese and Cuban food. I drew the line at sushi.
</P>
<P>
   Being German, Irish and French (my dad's side), in other words,
``white,'' I have often felt left out in this multicultural world.
As a child I ate Wonder Bread, Spam, Tater Tots and fish sticks. I
found a peanut butter and jelly sandwich in my lunch box every day
at school, along with three pennies so I could buy a carton of
white milk.
</P>
<P>
   Although I didn't really think about it much as a child, I
didn't have an ethnic identity of my own.
</P>
<P>
   After moving to California, I felt deprived and left out. I was
just plain white. My ancestors had come from Europe more than a few
generations ago; I was simply a WASP, a white Anglo-Saxon
Protestant. I had no food (other than my grandmother's blarney
stones), language or dress to claim. Or so I thought.
</P>
<P>
   I was so busy being envious of my co-workers, neighbors and
friends who took pride in their ethnic heritage, I didn't look hard
enough for my own. I owe my compulsive need for neatness to the
German side, my love of laughter and writing to the Irish side and
my occasional snootiness, and love of Chardonnay, to the French
side.
</P>
<P>
   One bright St. Patrick's Day morning a few years ago I went to
work sporting a huge, plastic, fluorescent green bow tie. It was
like a party hat, and the tiny elastic band held the clown-size bow
tie securely to my neck. I was a big hit. I claimed my heritage. I
belonged!
</P>
<P>
   Some of my co-workers wanted a green bow tie too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' I exclaimed, ``you're not Irish.''
</P>
<P>
   They felt left out. Oh, my.
</P>
<P>
   On another St. Patrick's Day, I no longer needed to wear a green
bow tie to work. I know who I am, where I belong and how I got
here. I arrived as almost all of us did, with hope, optimism and a
deep sense of who I am: an American.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
