<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9699 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-YOUNGVOTER-$AD     03-17 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YOUNGVOTER-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRACY, JOBS IMPORTANT TO RUSSIA'S FIRST-TIME VOTERS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Nadia Gorovaya is a 19-year-old Russian architecture
student who counts The Verve and The Beatles among her favorite
musical groups. She loves art, and spends free time hanging out
with friends in Moscow's budding cafe culture. She and her mother
live in a tidy one-bedroom apartment on this city's northern
outskirts. On March 26, Nadia will be able to cast a vote for the
first time choosing the person who will lead Russia for the next
four years. She spoke recently with Cox Newspapers Moscow
correspondent Margaret Coker on her thoughts about politics and
teen-age life in her country.
</P>
<P>
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   Question: Your generation is the first to come of age after the
Cold War. How are you and your friends different from your parents?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: We are very different. Me and my friends have a much
wider outlook and have access to much more information. We also
have more responsibility and more choice. Previously, (your life)
was more or less pre-determined. You graduated and knew what was in
store for you. You did what was required. Now, even though life is
rather hard, more depends on the person's own effort.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is your view of America and the rest of the world
different?
</P>
<P>
   A: The borders are now open and many of my friends and I travel
a lot. It's one of the things I like most. I get a fresh look at
things and new impressions. (This opportunity) is much more
realistic for us than it was for our parents.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you think are the best, and the worst changes in your
country since the end of the Soviet Union?
</P>
<P>
   A: To me, the best thing is democracy, the ability to say what
you think freely even if the government doesn't like what you say.
Now, we have some freedom of choice. The worst thing is that all of
this is not yet properly protected. Our laws don't really work all
of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would your older relatives answer this question the same way?
</P>
<P>
   A: In principle, they all agree with me. Although my father, for
example, who belongs to the democratic camp and does not want the
restoration of the old regime, believes there were some advantages
in the Soviet times, like free education and free health-care.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you think about the political situation in Russia?
</P>
<P>
   A: I do not like what is happening now. I think the authorities
are thinking for the most part about power, money, prestige and
very little about what they ought to be thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you think your leaders should be paying attention to?
</P>
<P>
   A: In the first place, to social programs, raising people's
living standards because the majority of the population are very
poor. The government must develop the economy, private business,
promote private property.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you discuss politics with your friends?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, with some. Not of all my friends are interested. I've
found they usually share the views of their parents. In these
elections, I think many of my friends are going to vote like their
parents
</P>
<P>
   Q: For whom will you vote?
</P>
<P>
   A: For Gregory Yavlinsky (the leader of the liberal political
party Yabloko).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think he is the most democratic candidate. His party, I
think, is the most honest and the most decent. His program is aimed
at the development of all of Russia, especially promoting private
property. There are so many issues I like. For example, Yavlinsky
opposes the war in Chechnya and says it should be stopped.
Unfortunately, I know he will lose. There is no alternative to
Putin in these elections, but I do not want to vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you think the winner is obvious, then why bother voting at
all?
</P>
<P>
   A: If I do not go to the polls, my ballot may be used somehow to
falsify the results. It is my choice. I do not want to vote for
someone else only because everybody else votes for him. I do not
want this to happen. There will be few of us voting for Yabloko,
but maybe it will give rise to the hope of this happening in
future.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where did you first learn about democracy?
</P>
<P>
   A: We studied it a bit in history class in high school, but, of
course, it is not enough. We studied the American system some. I
read books for myself to find out what the principles are.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have visited America. Did you like our way of life? Do
you think it is better?
</P>
<P>
   A: You have a higher standard of living compared to Russia. Of
course, that is better. Your college graduates know they will be
able to find a job. It is hard for U.S. families to pay for
education, but at least you have a banking and loan system that
makes it possible to repay all costs. Americans can travel, change
jobs, feel the police protects them. Your courts are really
unbiased in most cases.
</P>
<P>
   My friends really like America. They think everything is great
there. But I think there are negative things about your country,
too. People pay too much attention to superficial things, not to
culture or the soul. You can find anything in the stores, sometimes
even 100 kinds of soap. But what about theater or good books?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you follow the news? Read newspapers?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, I do. Not very regularly, but I do.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you know about the American elections?
</P>
<P>
   A: That you have now two candidates _ Democrat Al Gore and
Republican George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you were an American for whom would you vote?
</P>
<P>
   A: I know less about American politics ... Not that I do not
care at all, but I know much less about your candidates than mine.
I don't know who I would vote for, honestly. I think Democrats, as
a party, are closer to my views.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you see your life in five years?
</P>
<P>
   A: I do not know. What makes life in Russia both fascinating and
a little frightening is that you do not know what's in store for
you tomorrow. You do not know what life is going to be like in one
or two years, let alone in five. I do hope it will get better. In
principle, I am an optimist. But judging by what is happening now,
I'm not sure. If Putin comes to power it will be a regime based on
a ``strong hand.'' I do not think he'll bring about more reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
