<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9700 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-COMMUNISTS-$AD     03-17 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-COMMUNISTS-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA'S COMMUNISTS ARE ROAD BUMP FOR PUTIN PRESIDENCY
 &HT;    (850&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With chart information attached at end of story.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULA, Russia _ At 9 a.m. one day last week Stanislav Petrovich
was well into his working day. He already had answered a two-hour
barrage of phone calls and organized a daily schedule for an
adrenaline-packed group of volunteers assembled at the Tula
regional Communist Party headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   With Russian presidential elections less than one week away,
many Moscow pundits have already called the vote, saying it's not a
question of whether Acting President Vladimir Putin will win, but
by how many votes.
</P>
<P>
   But don't tell this to Petrovich and the rest of the
half-million Communist Party faithful toiling to make their
candidate Gennady Zyuganov Russia's next president.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are calling from all over wanting to know how they can
help defeat Putin,'' said Petrovich, a clean-cut 46-year-old
economics teacher and the party chairman in the Tula region. ``They
don't believe this election is a done deal.''
</P>
<P>
   While Putin's lead is undeniably strong _ he leads Zyuganov, his
nearest competitor, by a 2-to-1 margin _ nearly half of the Russian
electorate will not be voting for the 47-year-old former KGB
officer on March 26, according to the latest poll figures.
</P>
<P>
   Some voters say they don't like Putin's secret service past.
Some think he's a dictator in disguise. But for Zyuganov and his
constituents, Putin represents the corrupt system of government
that flourished under former President Boris Yeltsin and led the
country into its current state of disrepair and depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin is supported by the oligarchs that robbed our country of
its wealth. He's tied to all that by virtue of the fact that
Yeltsin anointed him as his successor,'' Zyuganov said in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
   This feeling runs strong throughout Tula Oblast, a largely
agricultural region roughly the size of Ohio. Only 200 miles south
of Moscow, the opportunities of open markets and democracy have
passed by most of the region's population.
</P>
<P>
   Besides farming, defense factories like the one that builds
Kalashnikov rifles kept people employed in the Soviet days. But in
the last 10 years, this economic infrastructure has rusted to a
halt, leaving people disenfranchised and impoverished.
</P>
<P>
   In December's parliamentary elections, about 30 percent of the
region voted for the Communists, while less than 10 percent voted
for Putin's electoral bloc, Unity. Like-minded voters across the
country handed the Communists more seats in parliament than any
other single party.
</P>
<P>
   Zyuganov attributes this popularity to the fact that he and
other leaders have redefined the party's ideology away from
classical Marxism and towards a socialism practiced by many
European countries. He says he wants to increase social spending,
but at the same time increase tax collection and stem capital
flight to pay for the expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not looking to turn back the clock, or repeat mistakes
of the past,'' the solid, ruddy-faced former schoolteacher said in
a recent interview. ``We want to go forward, like Lenin said.''
</P>
<P>
   But while travelling past snow-whitened wheat fields and
tumble-down wooden houses with Communist Party campaign volunteers
to deliver election literature to the small towns in Tula Oblast
last week, visitors see it's nostalgia that seems to be driving
voters to turn toward Zyuganov.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Semonov, a 50-year-old unemployed miner from Kiryevsky,
said he's watched his town die a slow death. Since 1990, 10 of its
12 iron mines have closed, and the population has dwindled from
105,000 to less than 80,000, as young people leave in droves.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've heard of the Stalin gulags? Well, I'm living in a
Yeltsin gulag. I have no job, but there is nowhere for my family
and I to go. Even if I could find work in some other town, where
would we live? I can't sell my apartment and I have no money to
rent another. I'm trapped,'' Semonov said.
</P>
<P>
   His neighbor Yelena Antonova, 42, said she didn't trust Putin,
even when he promised to crack down on corruption, and increase
minimum wage and social security payments for the elderly _ three
promises Zyuganov has also made to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zyuganov isn't in it for the money or the prestige. He's
running for the people. With Putin, I just don't know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Tula's provincial capital, where signs of economic resurgence
flourish along the tree-lined main street called Lenin Prospect,
citizens feel less inclined towards the Communists. They tend to
shy away from Putin also for economic reasons, but for different
ones than the Zyuganov electorate, who hope the government will
guarantee employment once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I lived poorly under the Communist system, but now
I've found a different way to live,'' said 46-year-old Valery
Ivanov, the assistant director of a private publishing company, a
business he and a group of friends started five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voting for Putin is madness. Only a fool would vote for a
candidate without an economic plan. I have no idea what he stands
for,'' Ivanov, an earnest man with ink-stained hands, added.
``(Gregory) Yavlinsky (the leader of the liberal Yabloko party) is
the only solution. He's the only intelligent person who can help us
now.''
</P>
<P>
   ------------------------------------------------------------
</P>
