<SLUG> BC-LIGHTING-$ADV19-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRY A TOUCH OF WHIMSY TO LIGHT UP YOUR LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 19)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Whimsical lighting is made of any unexpected,
amusing shape, from animals in clothing to a carved wooden toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are loosening up with light fixtures, to introduce more
personality into a room,'' said interior designer Michel Patterson,
owner of Hudson River Fine Interiors in Loudonville.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally known interior designer Mario Buatta is fond of
injecting a touch of whimsy into many of his interiors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to overdo it, because it can get tiresome,''
Buatta said. ``But it's fun to add a funny touch of whimsy in a
room by placing something that's a little fun on a telephone table
or desk, like a secretary desk. ... For one room I used a monkey
lamp with three monkeys representing see, hear and speak no evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Whimsical lighting is a decorative accessory that's like a piece
of art, said interior designer Denise Maurer of Troy. ``It's to be
used mainly as accent or mood lighting. You might place a fun lamp
on a piano, kitchen counter or even in the powder room. This type
of lamp is always good for adding a little interest to a dark
corner of the room. But you can also use a whimsical fixture in a
formal room.''
</P>
<P>
   Because whimsical lighting fixtures have a personality of their
own, make sure that it's appropriate to the room.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find a lamp you like or that's in your price range,
use your imagination and create your own. You can transform
anything into a lamp, from a favorite teapot to an antique brass
coffee urn, soup tureen (in an animal shape), piece of machinery or
fun sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to transform something into a lamp, but can't or
don't want to bore a hole through it for wiring, simply mount it on
a base with the rod (encasing the wire) coming up behind it,
Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   The designers also noted that decoupage, which is coming back
into style, offers another way to add a light touch to a lamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep your eyes open for things that look whimsical,'' said
Carol Dexter, an interior designer with Hudson River Fine
Interiors. ``Get a glue gun to enhance the shade and create your
own whimsical lamp, chandelier, sconce or candlestick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
