<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9704 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MIDEAST-POPE-$ADV18-C     03-17 2122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-POPE-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PAPAL VISIT TO HOLY LAND A PERSONAL PILGRIMAGE WITH GLOBAL
ASPIRATIONS
 &HT;    (1650&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With box information attached at end of story.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., March 11 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Pope John Paul II comes to the Holy Land next week
as an elderly pilgrim determined to change the world.
</P>
<P>
   He begins his visit Monday in Jordan, then visits Israel and the
Palestinian territories until the following Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He will see the Mount Nebo in Jordan, where Moses looked upon
the promised land. He will pray above the Bethlehem cave where
tradition says Christ was born. He will deliver mass above the Sea
of Galilee, in the hills where Christ gave the speeches that became
known as the Sermon on the Mount.
</P>
<P>
   The journey presents a monumental moment in the already
remarkable life of this pontiff.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, at 79 years of age, is the most media savvy
and well-traveled of all the popes. He scores high in U.S. public
opinion polls despite stands on issues with which many Americans
disagree _ against abortion, the death penalty and contraception.
</P>
<P>
   Long ago an amateur actor, the pope now steps onto a stage that
has the most holy sites in Christianity as its backdrop _ in the
very places Christ himself walked. It is his first trip here as
pope.
</P>
<P>
   With the pope in the twilight years of his pontificate, this
91st trip abroad could be the hallmark of a legacy that is hinged
on the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The pope has declared the year 2000 a ``Jubilee'' and ``Holy
Year.'' He asks that Catholics begin the third millennium since
Christ's birth by reflecting on their past, and building a new
future.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, the first of the Catholic Lenten period of
penitence, the pope took the unprecedented step of asking
forgiveness from God for a sweeping list of sins committed by
followers of the church.
</P>
<P>
   This week's trip is part of that renewal or, as the pope calls
it, the ``purification of memory.'' Ultimately, he aims for nothing
less than sweeping away centuries of bitterness between Jews and
Catholics _ and within different branches of Christianity itself.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere are the divisions more clear than here. Israelis and
Palestinians are still logjammed in a tense peace process. Arab
Christians _ some 180,000 of them _ are an uncomfortable minority
between the Jewish state and Muslim-dominated areas under control
of the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Some Jews accuse the Church of ignoring the Holocaust. Some
Muslims bear grudges from the Church's medieval crusades. Greek
Orthodox Christians here view the Catholic Church with suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Amid it all, the pope brings his message of reconciliation with
the hopeful enthusiasm of a pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a strong desire to go personally to pray in the most
important places which, from the Old to the New Testament, have
seen God's interventions,'' the pope wrote in June of last year.
``I say to everyone: Let us set out in the footsteps of Christ!''
</P>
<P>
   He came here in 1965, before he was pope, and commemorated the
``unforgettable experience'' in poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it took the warming relations between Israel and its
Arab neighbors to make the new trip possible. Others protest that
the time is still not right, since many issues between Israelis and
Palestinians remain unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   But, the pope has talked about the Jubilee year since he
ascended to the papacy in 1978. Now appearing to suffer from
Parkinson's disease, it may be that no political circumstance could
have stopped him from making the trip _ which he insists is not
political.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an exclusively religious pilgrimage in its nature
and purpose, and I would be saddened if anyone were to attach other
meanings to this plan of mine,'' he wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   But politics are super-imposed on any high-profile trip to the
region, and the pope's is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians worry his visits to Arab areas of east Jerusalem _
under Israeli security protection _ will be seen as a recognition
of Israeli occupation there. Israelis fear his trip to
Palestinian-controlled areas will be tantamount to a recognition of
Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is inevitable that it is going to be politicized. What will
please the Palestinians will upset the Israelis, and whatever
pleases the Israelis will upset the Palestinians,'' said Harry
Hagopian, executive director of the Jerusalem liaison office for
the Middle East Council of Churches.
</P>
<P>
   But Archbishop Pietro Sambi, the Vatican's representative to
Israel, suggested the pope's visit could ease the political
bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the pope speaks of a spiritual pilgrimage, he is not
talking about just coming to say prayers,'' Sambi said. ``He means
to make a new consensus, a sense of responsibility, a principle of
truth and justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The ground is more fertile for that than it was during the only
other papal visit to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, Pope Paul VI visited for a day. Relations were so
chilly between the Vatican and Israel that he insisted on a special
entry point into the country rather than recognize any of Israel's
official border points.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Israeli officials still bristled at the Church's
silence during the Holocaust. Church doctrine seemed to blame Jews
for the death of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Church officials were sympathetic to Israel's Arab
neighbors. They worried that cozy relations with Israel would
endanger Christian communities in Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1960s, the church officially retracted the
accusations of Jewish involvement in Christ's death. Then, Pope
John Paul II went even further.
</P>
<P>
   He has sought forgiveness for Catholics' misdeeds during the
Holocaust and has condemned anti-Semitism dozens of times. While
church teachings used to call the Jews treacherous, this pope has
dubbed Judaism the ``elder brother'' among the Christian, Jewish
and Muslim faiths.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi David Rosen, head of the Israel office of the
Anti-Defamation League, said the pope has ``turned upside down the
whole traditional attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, with the way paved by the Oslo peace process, Israel
and the Vatican exchanged their first ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
   Of primary concern to the Vatican are the followers of the pope
in the region. There are about 70,000 Arab Christians in Israel and
the Palestinian areas who are Roman Catholics or Greek Catholics,
known also as Melkites.
</P>
<P>
   They comprise a little less than half the Christians in Israel
and the Palestinian areas _ including Greek, Syrian, Armenian
Orthodox and some Protestants. They have been overwhelmed by the
growth in the Jewish and Muslim populations.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago, Christians made up about 9 percent of the
population, but now they are about 2 percent. Christians emigrate
at higher rates than non-Christians do.
</P>
<P>
   The pope is expected to encourage the local Christians to stay
in the place where Christianity began.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe he will have special blessings,'' said 77-year-old
Labibeh Abdel-Noor, leaving a Roman Catholic Mass in Jerusalem's
Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Sunday. The pope is scheduled to
hold a Mass in the church, believed by Catholics to be where Christ
was crucified and entombed, on March 26.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five years ago, Abdel-Noor was among the crowds that
greeted Paul VI. Just maybe, she said, this pope's visit can bring
people closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people can start to get united, it is easier to have
peace. We pray for peace,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But, the pope's message could be less well-received by those of
the majority religions.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials welcome the visit and say it will be a
breakthrough in Christian-Jewish relations. They have laid out more
than $10 million in roadwork and construction for the visit.
</P>
<P>
   A poll this month showed most Israelis see the visit positively.
</P>
<P>
   But, a fringe of right-wing Israelis have threatened to disrupt
the visit if they can. Signs and graffiti in Jerusalem have labeled
the pope a ``pagan'' who should be shunned.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Chief Rabbi Israel Meir Lau said he hopes the pope will
use a visit to the Yad Vashem Holocaust museum to apologize for the
silence of Pope Pius XII during the Holocaust. He said the pope's
Lenten confession of sins, which did not mention the Holocaust,
showed ``serious historical myopia.''
</P>
<P>
   An apology for Pius XII is extremely unlikely. He is in the
running for sainthood and popes are considered infallible under
Catholic doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   But, the pope has asked for 15 minutes to speak at Yad Vashem
and is using the event to meet Jews from his hometown in Poland who
fled the Holocaust. Some were among the pope's childhood friends.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, officials of the Palestinian Authority _ which
controls the Palestinian areas _ have warmly welcomed the visit,
while some Muslims chose to bear their own grudges. One Muslim
leader called for the pope to apologize for the Crusades.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his trip, the pope will be surrounded by 18,000
police in the largest security operation in Israeli history. Entire
neighborhoods will be closed when the pope is nearby, prompting
concerns that the isolation will frustrate local Christians and
deprive the pope of the crowd contact from which he draws strength.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his ``Pope Mobiles'' are being flown in and a smaller one
has been constructed to navigate the narrow streets of Jerusalem's
Old City. He will spend his nights in the house of the Vatican
delegation here, an old mansion with Arab tile floors and a small
chapel. A helicopter pad was built nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's itinerary includes time alone at Holy sites for
meditation. He will also give a Mass before about 100,000 near the
Sea of Galilee, and another to an expected 7,000 in Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   The pope is also visiting the Holocaust museum and a Palestinian
refugee camp _ two sites that are not destinations for religious
pilgrimage. They are his nod to the trip's tense political
backdrop, where he can show sympathy for suffering on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to present a model for how you go about
reconciliation,'' said the Rev. Drew Christiansen, a Jesuit advisor
for international affairs to the United States Catholic Conference.
``It's a moment of grace and, God willing, everyone will be open to
the grace _ wherever they stand.''
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS FROM POPE JOHN PAUL II'S SCHEDULED VISIT TO JORDAN,
ISRAEL AND THE PALESTINIAN TERRITORIES:
</P>
<P>
   Monday, March 20:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mount Nebo, near Madaba, Jordan. This mountaintop monastery is
said to be the place where Moses looked upon the promised land.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, March 21:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Amman, Jordan: Holy Mass in the Amman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wadi Al-Kharrar, Jordan: Jordanian officials and some
archeologists say this site, in an offshoot of the Jordan River,
could be the location of Christ's baptism.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tel Aviv, Israel: Arrival at Ben Gurion International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, March 22:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bethlehem, West Bank: Holy Mass in Manger Square, outside the
Basilica of the Nativity.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Visit to Dheisheh Refugee Camp. Here, Palestinians have lived
since 1948, when they left lands now in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, March 23:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jerusalem(cq no country): Prayer in private in the Chapel of
the Cenacle, the traditional site of Christ's Last Supper.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Visit and speech at Yad Vashem Holocaust museum(cq lower
case).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Discussion with Christian, Jewish and Muslim leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, March 24:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Korazim, Israel: Holy Mass on the Mount of the Beatitudes.
Nearly 100,000 people are expected for this mass on the same hills
where Christ preached.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sea of Galilee, Israel: Private visits to the Church of the
Multiplication of the Loaves and Fishes; private visit to the
Church of the Primacy of Peter; private visit to the Sanctuary of
the House of St. Peter in Caperneum.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, March 25:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nazareth, Israel: Holy Mass in the Basilica of the
Annunciation. This Arab city, where it is believed an angel told
the Virgin Mary that she would be mother to the son of God, has
been the site of recent friction between Muslims and Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, March 26:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jerusalem: Visit to the Western Wall, a sacred Jewish site.
</P>
<P>
   Visit to the Al-Aqsa Mosque, one of the holiest sites in Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Holy Mass in the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, believed to be
the site of Christ's crucifixion and entombment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tel Aviv, Israel: Departure from Ben Gurion International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
