<HEADER>
A9718 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-SPRING-BREAK-HNS &LR;      03-17 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRING-BREAK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COLLEGE STUDENTS PAYING MORE FOR FUN IN THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KERI P. MATTOX  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Students used to hold up signs reading, ``Hi Mom
&AMP; Dad. Send Money.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, they are sending post cards that say, ``Wish you
were here.''
</P>
<P>
   The booming economy means college students _ children who have
grown up using cellular phones, surfing the Internet and wearing
logo-laden designer duds _ are spending thousands for more
elaborate spring break trips than their parents could have
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Florida beaches aren't drawing today's jet-set students.
Instead, they are hopping planes to places like Cancun, Jamaica,
the Bahamas and other Caribbean islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of parents have never been to a tropical island, ever,
and now their kids are going there every year for four years of
college spring break,'' said Eric Sunila, office manager of college
trip organizer Inter-Campus Programs, based near Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disposable income the students have is amazing and kind of
bizarre,'' said Sunila, whose company plans between 10,000 and
12,000 student vacations each year. ``There are still kids that are
going to South Florida and Texas, but over the past six years,
there are definitely more coming to us with more money to spend and
they're going to the islands.''
</P>
<P>
   One State University of New York at Albany student just returned
from Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so, so much fun. But I spent a lot of cash. I mean a
lot,'' said the tanned freshman who pleaded that her name not be
used because she spent double what her parents think she did. ``I
just wanted to go somewhere more fun, more exotic than the Florida
beaches.''
</P>
<P>
   To pay for the upscale seven-day getaway, the first-year student
used money from a part-time job, funds sent weekly by her parents
and her credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Average prices for the spring break trips can start as low as
$200 to $300, agents say. But these days, many students are going
for the higher-end getaways, with beachfront accommodations and
price tags around $1,250 per person _ and that's with four in a
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, if we have the money, we might as well take the trips and
spend it,'' said the SUNY-Albany student as she walked off,
hurrying to the tanning salon to keep up her vacation glow.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Milian, an agent at Central Travel in Albany, noted that
cruises are popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cancun is always a big seller, and the Bahamas. Previously it
would be Myrtle Beach or Fort Lauderdale because they would drive,
pack in the car for a road trip,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1259EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9722 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-CADAMOM-HNS &LR;      03-17 0335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADAMOM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `QUEEN OF SPICES' OFFERS FLAVOR FOR THE MASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LISA STEVENS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   India's ``Queen of Spices'' is indeed considered royalty in the
world of flavor. Cardamom's versatility enhances the taste of
everything from soups to desserts. Its aromatic, spicy-sweet and
warm flavor goes well in both hot and cold foods.
</P>
<P>
   Cardamom is the third most expensive spice (behind saffron and
vanilla) in the world, but a dash goes a long way. The spice gives
Danish pastries, Swedish coffee cakes and Norwegian Christmas cakes
their distinctive flavor. Cardamom also spices up Swedish meatballs
and flavors that country's popular hot spiced wine served at
Christmas. It is also widely used in many American processed foods
such as hot dogs, sausages and salami, as well as in soda, liqueurs
and sweets.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Norman, the author of ``The Complete Book of Spices,''
writes: ``The (cardamom) seeds were prized in India long before the
birth of Christ. Gradually the spice reached Europe along the
caravan routes.'' Cardamom was used in perfumes in ancient Greece
and Rome. It was also used as a breath freshener and to calm
digestive problems.
</P>
<P>
   According to tradition in the Bedouin culture, before guests are
served cardamom coffee, the spice is displayed, Norman writes.
``The pods imply esteem and respect for the guests.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IS IT: Aromatic pods with a warm, spicy-sweet taste,
cardamom is a member of the ginger family.
</P>
<P>
   FORM: Pods, seeds, ground
</P>
<P>
   LOOK FOR: Hard, dried pods that are greenish in color.
</P>
<P>
   STORE: In an airtight container in a cool, dry place. Pods can
be stored for up to a year; ground cardamom for several months.
</P>
<P>
   USE IN: Fruit and pasta salads; soups; curried fish, meat,
sausage and poultry dishes; vegetables such as carrots, pumpkin,
squash and sweet potatoes; bulgur, polenta, rice and couscous
dishes; cookies, cakes and pastries; teas; mulled wine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1307EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9728 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-CARDAMOM-HNS &LR;      03-17 0335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDAMOM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `QUEEN OF SPICES' OFFERS FLAVOR FOR THE MASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LISA STEVENS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
