</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9729 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-CHANEY-BOS &LR;      03-17 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CHANEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANEY IS ONE WISE OWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)The world according to John Chaney: Point guards.
</P>
<P>
   After a game against Fordham Jan. 12, the Temple coach was
explaining the qualities he looks for in a floor general.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know who was a good point guard? Jesus. Jesus was a good
point guard because he gave to the multitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone joked that Jesus could not go to his left.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have to,'' Chaney fired back, ``because he was
always right.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   There are a growing number of people pulling for Chaney. They
may never say so publicly, but they do exist _ in the same way
folks wanted John Elway and Julius Erving to get championship rings
before they retired.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sentimental favorite to reach the Final Four and it
is John Chaney. The colorful, outspoken 67-year-old sage has taken
teams to four regional finals, losing each time. The squad he takes
to this year's NCAA tournament is the best since his 1987-88 team
that went 32-2 and lost to Duke in the East Regional final. Some
say this year's team is better.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney, whose second-seeded Owls (26-5) meet Lafayette Friday in
the East Regional's first round, became a sentimental favorite last
season when his team made an unexpected run to the East final,
where, again, it lost to Duke.
</P>
<P>
   The coach's press conferences were heavily attended and Chaney
used them to expound on such topics as NCAA rules, basketball
philosophies, and racism.
</P>
<P>
   The mentor was often followed off the podium and into the Temple
locker room by reporters, some of whom walked away with a different
view of a man famous for entering a postgame press conference and
trying to attack then-University of Massachusetts coach John
Calipari.
</P>
<P>
   Many had heard Chaney tell the same stories and offer the same
viewpoints. But you don't tire of Chaney.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, what is often best about him is that he seems out of
place with the fanfare and high drama of big-time college sports.
</P>
<P>
   He runs a tepid half-court offense and a zone-trap defense that
frustrates even the best of teams. He holds practices at 5:30 a.m.
to keep from interfering with class schedules. He'll stop practices
for discussions on current events.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (itals)The world according to John Chaney: The NCAA and
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   After Temple's win over UMass in the Atlantic 10 semifinals,
Chaney was asked about the importance of playing in postseason
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly everybody thinks it's about money, but kids get
excited about this time of year. And look at this room. It's filled
with you guys. Aren't you excited? You've got jobs because we've
got jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, moderator Ray Cella opened the floor for
questions and a reporter posed one to Temple guard Pepe Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pepe,'' he said, ``can you talk about the pace of the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me finish my statement just one more time,'' Chaney
interjected. ``The other day there was this guy picking up after
reporters, talking about what a terrible time of year this is. I
got a guy picking up my trash outside my door, all up and down the
street, I can hear him cussing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I flipped the window and I said, `Let me tell you something
(expletive). You better be glad there's trash because you got a
damn job.' How many of you guys would be in this room if it wasn't
for athletics?''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Chaney is as old school as the two-handed set shot, as stubborn
as your grandfather when he knows he's right. He is also eighth
among active Division 1 coaches (and 20th all-time) with 631
victories. This year's NCAA tournament is Temple's 10th straight
and 16th in 17 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls annually play one of the toughest schedules in college
basketball and are 6-6 against teams ranked in the top 5 in the
last five regular seasons, including a win over then-No. 1
Cincinnati Feb. 20. This season, 11 of Temple's opponents (39
percent of its regular-season schedule) have advanced to postseason
play, including seven top the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Temple's trip to the Elite Eight last season put it among eight
schools to have reached that round at least four times in the last
12 years. All the others _ Connecticut, North Carolina, Arkansas,
Michigan, Kansas, Duke, and Arizona _ have won the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls are led by Sanchez (6 points per game, 7.8 assists per
game), the A-10 player of the year, and junior Mark Karcher (15.4
ppg, 4.5 rpg). They are coming off one of their most impressive
outings of the season, a 65-44 trouncing of St. Bonaventure in the
A-10 final, where the Owls grabbed the first 16 rebounds, sank
seven first-half 3-pointers in a row, and raced to a 32-4
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Even Chaney admitted to being impressed. ``I never had a team
shoot the ball that well,'' he said. ``It was frightening to see
it. That's why I kept my mouth shut. I was afraid that if I had
opened my mouth and complained we would have stopped shooting and
lost the game.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (itals)The world according to John Chaney: NCAA rules. The coach
was asked, on a conference call, to respond to the NCAA's
suspension of Temple sophomore center Kevin Lyde, who had to sit
out the March 4 game against George Washington while the governing
body investigated whether an AAU coach paid for a summer class in
1997 _ when he was a junior in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard of such a rule in my life,'' Chaney said. ``I
guess next time they'll be looking at 7-month-old babies, seeing
what's in their diapers . . . How is this a law and how do you
enforce such laws? You can't even stop the state of South Carolina
from flying that (Confederate) flag. That's where (presidential
candidate George W.) Bush and those guys want to play.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Chaney's ways aren't always popular. He is known for making his
team, when it loses the A-10 championship game, watch the winning
squad cut down the nets. That happened five times in the 1990s. But
when the Owls beat the Bonnies last Saturday, they did not cut the
nets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most of his players buy into his philosophies, and you can
always see former Temple players in the stands at the Owls' games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you have to be a worthy winner you have to be a
worthy loser,'' said Chaney. ``I always make my team sit there,
even with tears in their eyes. It's important to do that, to show
respect for the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the coach, who won a Division 2 national championship
with Cheyney State in 1978, has had to watch, as UMass replaced
Temple as the A-10's dominant team and as URI beat the Owls on a
last-second 3-pointer last season in the conference tournament
final.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney said he appreciates this season's A-10 title because of
the second-place finishes in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you understand a lot more of what this thing is about
from losses,'' he said. ``It's almost like having a lot of friends
when you have a lot of money in your pocket. You'll learn who your
friends are when you're broke. When you're sick, you learn a lot
more about what kind of resolve you have and what kind of friends
you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney said he has told his players that despite what happens in
the tournament, all they can lose is one more game this season. If
the Owls continue to play as they did against St. Bonaventure, that
lose won't come soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played like a Final Four team,'' said Bonnies coach Jim
Baron. ``And we played them three times this year. In the
tournament, you don't have a chance to prepare.''
</P>
</TEXT>
