<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTING IN A DIFFERENT LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While laboring in New Zealand for most of the winter, I afforded
myself one immense pleasure (though also actually on the job) by
venturing to see first-hand if the trout fishing in that country's
pristine bush land could live up to its legend.
</P>
<P>
   It did. And how. Try wild native brown and rainbow trout up to
about 10 pounds, as finicky as bone fish and pursued with about the
same stalking method. ``Hunting fish'' is how our guide, Simon
Dickie, described it.
</P>
<P>
   The first story I wrote about this fishing trip to the bush and
farming country a few hours south of Auckland met with some
skepticism back home, even though it was accompanied by two photos
of an 8-pound brown, one showing the magnificent gold side covered
with bright black speckles.
</P>
<P>
   We New England anglers have a hard time relating to such fish.
They resemble something we recognize in a smaller and dingier form.
One of the American anglers staying at the Poronui Ranch with us,
Greg Kelley, comes from the Midwest and has flyfished from Idaho to
Montana to Scotland. He pronouced this ``the finest fly fishing in
the world'' as, with a cheer of Wild Turkey, he toasted the day
past and the one to come.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the next day Kelley helicoptered to a stream hidden in
the half-million-acre Maori land that backs up to the ranch, and
there encountered a 10-pound rainbow, the catch of that day.
</P>
<P>
   At one point we hiked back into the bush and stopped at a high
banking overlooking a 50-yard stretch of the Taharua River in which
we spotted about eight browns ranging from 6 to 10 pounds. These
were wild, native fish, as unimaginable as that is to those of us
living in places where stocked fish half that size are considered
prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing in New Zealand was an exercise in self-discovery. In
this paradise _ where the fish are not pressured for 10-day
stretches and so must be approached with great subtlety and care _
my skills were woefully inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Like most people who grow up saltwater casting, my habits are so
ingrained that the considerable touch required to present the fly
to fish such as this had to be learned, like some skill totally
unrelated to what I previously knew fishing to be.
</P>
<P>
   Dickie, who owns the Poronui Ranch, explained to us with a note
of impatience that an angler has no more than one or two chances to
cast over a fish, and that once one fish is spooked it will spook
the rest. Therefore, said Dickie, the fly must be almost perfectly
cast.
</P>
<P>
   Right.
</P>
<P>
   The line must roll silently onto the water, and deposit the No.
14 Caddis silently upstream of the trout, and as it drifts
downstream the angler must take slack out of the line
progressively. At the very hint of a nibble, the angler must strike
hard and never again permit the slightest slackening of the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``He who hesitates is lost,'' said Dickie, though all my
instincts were backward. Back home, we let bass and bluefish nose
around for a while, and a striper may tail-slap your lure a few
times before taking it.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the only counterintuitive move when a lifelong
heavy-reel spin-caster meets a fresh water flyrod. I managed a few
casts in the right direction, but all in all my one Orvis school
week did not bring back the subtleties of wild trout fishing on the
Poronui Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   So I came home determined to improve my flyfishing skills.
Nothing in a shelf of old trout fishing books was very helpful, but
a new book out this spring has actually helped me make noticeable
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Maine flycasters Macauley Lord (writer) and Jim Rowinski
(photographer) have authored a 126-page book, ``L.L. Bean
Fly-Casting Handbook.'' It may be the best instructional book on
the subject I have ever seen, due in part to the generous devotion
of space to Rowinski's photos.
</P>
<P>
   They are big, colorful shots with clear detail showing the cause
and effect of many motions that Lord describes as the book's
thesis:
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote this book to take you closer to the perfect cast, the
cast that seems to make itself while you stand by and watch in awe.
Physicists speak of an elegant theory, one that is precise, neat,
simple. That is what I hope for your casting: that, though falling
short of perfection, it may be precise, neat, and simple, without
excess motion. The elegant cast is the simple cast, the one that
quiets the body and the mind, making room for reverence of fishes
and waters.''
</P>
<P>
   Desribing himself as ``a fly-fishing generalist,'' Lord takes us
through the presentation, starting with a pantomime casting with an
unrigged rod, before moving on to the first backyard lesson. He
ends up with tricky reach casts, roll casts, aerial mends, and
shooting line.
</P>
<P>
   Every point is illustrated in a series of photos that Rowinski
renders clear, bright, and nearly always highlighting rod and line
against a contrasting deep shadow.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so most of us know that almost no one flyfishes to catch
fish. It's a Zen thing, and after all his extremely clear technical
advice, Lord leaves us with this picture of a teaching colleague
practicing in a casting pool:
</P>
<P>
   ``For the sheer fun of it, Craig and I are flycasting. After
teaching casts for 14 years, Pat is on the casting pool, quietly
making four-part casts: pickup, back cast, forward cast,
presentation. Time and again they are beautiful, elegant casts, yet
perfection eludes him, as it does all of us. But on this soft
summer evening, he moves a little closer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain covers the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
