<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLY FOR CNN/SI, SHAME ON KNIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when it was almost safe for the media to interview the
volatile Bobby Knight, along comes a report charging that the
Indiana coach not only subjected his players to verbal and physical
abuse but also once threw the university president out of a
basketball practice.
</P>
<P>
   The arrogance amid March Madness is seldom addressed, but CNN/SI
captured the dark side of the price of winning in Tuesday's solid
piece on the man whom Boston broadcaster Gerry Callahan has dubbed
``Coach Satan.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a hatchet job, as some Knight supporters suggest, but
rather a revealing look into Knight's bizarre coaching style.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Robert Abbott worked on the piece for a year. His boss
at the cable service, Steve Robinson, wanted a report on why top
recruits were leaving one of the nation's most prestigious
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Luke Recker was one such player. He was basketball-crazed
Indiana's top high school player, then one of the best players on
Knight's team before transfering after his sophomore year. Recker's
departure came on the heels of the transfers of two other High
School All-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN/SI report revolves around the charges of another player,
Neil Reed, who played at Indiana between 1995-1997. He accused
Knight of, among other things, once grabbing him by the throat.
``He had me by the throat for probably, say, about five seconds,''
Reed said. ``I grabbed his wrists and started walking back, and by
this time people, coaches . . . grabbed Coach Knight and pulled him
away. . . . People came in and separated us like we were in a
schoolyard fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Another former player, Richard Mandeville, told a story about
one of Knight's pep talks. ``In our locker room,'' he said, ``there
is a bathroom attached to it and Knight came out, pants down around
his ankles, and just wiped his (expletive) and said, `This is how
you guys are playing.' And he just stuck out his hand with toilet
paper and kind of showed everyone and then walked back into the
stall.''
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, no one was immune to Knight's tantrums. Not even
university president Myles Brand. During one practice, Reed told
CNN/SI, Brand and a guest were sitting near courtside. ``Coach
Knight could hear him and just stopped practice and said,
`(Expletive), quit that talking. I don't come into your office and
talk while you are working. Get the hell out of here.' The
president kind of looked, grabbed his stuff, and walked out,'' Reed
said.
</P>
<P>
   Brand and Knight refused three CNN/SI's request for interviews.
When told the details of the story, Indiana officials still refused
to react to the charges. Abbott said he spelled out the charges
shortly before the piece aired and Brand's response was ``he didn't
think it was necessary (to respond) if Knight didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I call Knight the emperor of Indiana,'' Murray Sperber, a
Indiana University professor of English and American Studies, told
CNN/SI. ``And there is no one in this state, really, who will stand
up to him, and certainly there is no one in this university who
will. And so, in a sense, if you are the emperor, you are allowed
to do what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the report aired, two Indiana players, A.J. Guyton and
Michael Lewis, have defended Knight and blamed Reed for not
accepting responsibility for his own problems. ``We voted him off
the team,'' Lewis told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   And CBS analyst Billy Packer went on WEEI in Boston Wednesday
morning to defend his criticism of the CNN/SI report after Callahan
had accused him of being a Knight apologist. He claimed that the
three main charges were all denied by the very people alleged to
have been involved. Packer said Brand denied being kicked out of
practice, both assistant coaches denied pulling Knight off Reed,
and the team's head trainer vowed to take a lie detector test to
prove that Knight didn't pull his pants down in front of the team.
Packer further said that the video of Knight swearing at players in
the locker room was from 1991 but CNN/SI presented it as new.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing new in the report,'' Packer said. ``And of
the three main charges, all have been refuted by credible people.
I'm not saying Reed is lying, but someone is. Knight will be judged
on his record. But CNN/SI set out to create some news by printing
charges from disgruntled players.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Booming reaction
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has reached a compromise on its policy of forcing
coaches to wear microphones _ a boom microphone placed near the
reluctant coaches' benches. The softening of the league edict comes
after weeks of daily criticisms from coaches, players, and
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The latest salvo came from Yankees manager Joe Torre. ``It's
probably the worst thing a manager or coach has to do,'' he told
the Associated Press Wednesday. ``You can be misunderstood. And
it's nobody's business.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto forward Antonio Davis had one of the best reactions to
the NBA's other new policy of placing a camera in the locker room.
``What if I decide to scratch my butt?'' Davis told Bloomberg News.
``It's like that eye is always watching you. It's bad enough the
league controls our conduct and emotion on the court. Now we can't
be ourselves in the locker room. I'd be shocked if this goes over
well.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ahead of the pack
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts/Rhode Island Associated Press Broadcasters
awarded the Channel 5 sportscast, anchored by Mike Lynch, as best
sports program and also designated the station's coverage of the
Boston Marathon as the best.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
