<SLUG> BC-BKC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA: SOONER THAN LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ It's always very nice to encounter a clear-thinking
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep reading that 20 teams have a chance to win this
thing,'' said Oklahoma coach Kelvin Sampson. ``That's just not
true. Maybe five or six teams, plus a sleeper. That's all. And has
anybody seen Michigan State? Are there 63 teams here that could
beat Michigan State? You'd have to have a virus in the Michigan
State locker room for most of these teams to beat Michigan State.''
</P>
<P>
   How else can I put this, except to say, ``My sentiments,
exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   I was starting to wonder if I really was inhabiting some
parallel universe myself. Where are all these great teams? As
Sampson implied, the list of real honest-to-God contenders numbers
about a half-dozen. The odds are overwhelming that the next
national champion will be one of the following: Duke, Temple, Iowa
State, St. John's, Arizona, Stanford, or, of course, Michigan
State. I wouldn't even discount a Kenyon Martin-less Cincinnati.
That makes eight, which is a lot fewer than the 15 or 20 some
people have been talking about.
</P>
<P>
   This really isn't different than any other year. The Final Four
will almost certainly consist of three logical high seeds and a
mystery guest. The trick, as always, is to identify the 2000
mystery guest.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. There is a lot to like about Kelvin Sampson's
third-seeded Sooners, starting with Kelvin Sampson himself. If you
are the type who stays up late on January nights to watch the
midnight game on ``Big Monday,'' then you know who Kelvin Sampson
is. If you're the type who kind of floats into March having paid
limited attention to the sport of college basketball, then you
don't know who he is. You don't know about the nice job he did at
notoriously difficult Washington State (you try inducing a kid to
spend four years in Pullman), or about the outstanding job he is
doing at Oklahoma. You don't know that in the business, 44-year-old
Kelvin Sampson is very well respected.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to like any team that can score inside and out, that
routinely thinks pass before shot, that plays an excellent helping
man-to-man defense, and whose best player is a smart, versatile,
dynamic 6-foot-8-inch player who just happens to be something of a
national phenomenon below the border.
</P>
<P>
   Will Eduardo Najera (accent on the first syllable) become a star
in the NBA? Who knows? That's not the issue today. For his sake,
and his family's sake, you hope so. How could you not root for a
great kid from Chihuahua, Mexico, a kid who is burdened with the
responsibility of being a role model for Mexican youth on top of
being asked to lead his team deep into the NCAA tournament? He
really is a great college player.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-8 and 240 pounds, he can handle the ball, shoot the ball,
rebound the ball, and pass the ball. He throws his body around on
defense, too. He is a throwback, and never mind if he's a 3 or a 4
or a 3 7/8. What was Larry? He's not Larry, but he's not easily
categorized, either. He may be the best all-around forward in
college basketball, and that should be good enough for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   When Sampson recruited Najera out of San Antonio's Cornerstone
Christian High School, where he spent his senior year, he was 6-7
and 215, and you'd have to say he was a small forward. ``Now he's
6-8 and 240,'' said Sampson, ``and he still handles the ball like a
small forward. He has sincere versatility. It's not like some of
these guys who can handle the ball a little so they automatically
want to stay outside. If you're a 4, and you can handle the ball,
that's an asset if you stay inside, isn't it? Eduardo is able to do
what he does because he has real basketball instincts. He has a
very high basketball IQ.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the story in Oklahoma's 74-50 conquest of 14th-seeded
Winthrop at the University of Arizona's McKale Center Thursday. He
had modest 10-point, 5-rebound, 5-assist numbers because the game
wasn't going his way, and he saw no need to force anything, not
with his teammates connecting on 10 of 21 3-pointers. Oklahoma also
had rather nice balance, with five men scoring between 10 and 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you want to win your first-round game,'' said
Sampson, ``but the thing I was most impressed with is the way we
won it. We defended the 3-point line, and we defended their
halfcourt sets. We didn't let them reverse the ball. On offense,
our best friend was the 3-point shot.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first NCAA test for freshman point guard Hollis
Price, a skinny kid who, according to Sampson ``is the kind of kid
that makes you want to coach in the first place.'' Price was raised
in a New Orleans project by his grandfather (``There were some real
problems with the parents'' _ Sampson), and in very short order he
has become a Sampson favorite. Playing in the rugged Big 12, which
sent six teams into the NCAA tournament, put some hair on the young
lad's chest.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing, too, because guard play is crucial in this
tournament. ``You go nowhere without a good point guard,'' said
Sampson. ``It was no accident last year that you saw Khalid
El-Amin, Scoonie Penn, William Avery, and Mateen Cleaves in the
Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin Sampson isn't predicting anything for his team other than
a rugged game Saturday against Purdue. He worries about rebounding
(Winthrop helped itself to 19 offensive rebounds) and about the
fact that his team doesn't ordinarily block any shots. But he knows
he came out of a tough league _ ``Four very good teams in Iowa
State, Oklahoma State, Texas, and us, plus two more right there in
Kansas and Missouri'' _ and that he has the kind of great player in
Najera who might win a big game all by himself.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, Oklahoma could be that ``sleeper'' he was talking
about. But it is pretty clear that if Kelvin Sampson were backing
one horse in this race it would be the one coming out of East
Lansing wearing green and white.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
