<SLUG> BC-BKC-STANFORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL STANDS FOR SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ It wasn't supposed to happen like this, of
course. At least, not at this level.
</P>
<P>
   After all, when a team loses four seniors after going 26-7 and
getting upset in the second round of the NCAA tournament, you don't
automatically think Final Four, much less national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Or do you?
</P>
<P>
   It's not like Stanford is a basketball factory that turns out
blue-chip players like widgets on an assembly line. After all, this
is a program that won the national championship by beating
Dartmouth in 1942 and went 47 years before even making another NCAA
tournament appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one day into the 2000 NCAA tournament Stanford will take the
court at the Birmingham-Jefferson Civic Center as not only the No.
1 seed in the South Regional, but as one of the favorites to win
the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   This is no soft No. 1. Other than a pair of losses to Arizona,
only a buzzer-beating basket by UCLA marred Stanford's record,
which comes in at 26-3.
</P>
<P>
   All of this with only power forward Mark Madsen returning from
last year's starting unit.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the program was drained. One thing Mike Montgomery has
learned to do in his 14 seasons as Cardinal coach is restock.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery simply plugged in new talent such as precocious
freshman forward Casey Jacobsen, who contributed more than anyone
could have expected. He handed the starting point guard job to
Michael McDonald, who has done more than an adequate job of
replacing Arthur Lee. He has worked the West Coast version of the
Twin Towers, 6-foot-10-inch Jarron Collins and 6-11 Jason Collins,
into the rotation as solid contributors. He has channeled shooting
guard David Moseley's talents as a scorer.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing. Montgomery has toughened the Cardinal to the
point where their attitude shows through when they take the court.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: Stanford led the nation in defense, allowing
opponents a shooting percentage of only .352. Marquette set the
NCAA record of .358 during the 1994 season. Only six times has a
Stanford opponent hit more than 40 percent of its shots.
</P>
<P>
   All of this and Montgomery has graduated 100 percent of his
players and hasn't encountered even a sniff of an off-court
incident involving his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's one of the great stories in college basketball
over the last 20 years,'' said longtime Pac-10 observer George
Raveling, who coached against Stanford at USC and Washington State.
``I never thought Mike would be able to sustain this the way he
has. He found the magic formula that allows the university to be
the best academically and athletically.''
</P>
<P>
   Sustain is the right word. This marks the sixth consecutive
20-win season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal, which faces 16th-seeded South Carolina State in
Friday's fourth game, have done it without the flare of a
Cincinnati or even an Arizona or Connecticut, each of whom can turn
a basketball court into a laser show of fast-break points, slam
dunks, and end-to-end excitement. ``We're definitely not like the
`Showtime' era,'' said McDonald. ``But we have the same amount of
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery says the Cardinal style is more suited to the long
run. ``We wouldn't have any one thing that people would say, `Wow,'
said Montgomery, ``but we grow on you.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this team is a throwback, featuring good size up
front, tenacious defense, and smart, if unspectacular, basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mantra from day one has been that if we rebound and play
defense, we're going to win games,'' said Madsen, who has had a
solid, and at times standout, season. ``Shooting is going to come
and go.''
</P>
<P>
   Most often it has come, although the impression that sticks in
the mind of many people in New England is the way UConn has
physically manhandled the Cardinal in the teams' last two meetings,
including a 70-59 pounding at Maples Pavilion last season.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery says all a coach can ask of a program is the
opportunity to string together four wins in March and make the
Final Four, then take your chances. ``If you can consistently get
your program into the tournament and consistently in the Top 20,
you've got a chance,'' he said. ``We're a strong team, one of about
16 teams that can get into the mix. Ultimately, for any team it
comes down to performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting now, the Cardinals will be judged critically on each
performance, with the success of the season determined not by what
they have done over the last four months, but by what they will do
during the next two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
