<HEADLINE>
DOW, NASDAQ DECIDE IT'S TIME TO PARTY AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ted English wins this week's award for the luckiest man on the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days ago, English, a 17-year employee, was officially
named the successor to TJX Cos. chief executive Ben Cammarata.
Shares of the Framingham, Mass. retail company, pounded for no
particular reason over the last year, suddenly became caught up in
Wall Street's furious ``old economy'' rally.
</P>
<P>
   The forgotten were instantly invited to the party. Retailers,
banks, insurance companies, and other battered stocks finally began
to climb back. TJX shares soared 31 percent in just four days this
week and, sorry Ted, the move didn't have much to do with executive
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The story of this week's stock market had been surprising but
straightforward and reassuring, in a way. Investors had finally
become wary of the rocket-propelled rally of Nasdaq's technology
stocks and moved money into established names that were for sale at
amazingly reasonable prices.
</P>
<P>
   It felt like everyone at the casino had begun to sober up a
little. Tech stocks took a hit, but they were already up a ton and
the day of reckoning everyone really feared, when a correction
would crush every single thing in the market, seemed a little less
likely.
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes Thursday harder to explain.
</P>
<P>
   The session started just as the rest of the week had gone: the
Dow Jones industrial average climbed smartly and the Nasdaq index
gave back a bit more. But then money started flooding everything.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, the Dow's 499-point gain had set a record
and Nasdaq finished up nearly 3 percent. Bond prices were up.
Everything was up.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the backdrop, not dire but hardly conducive to a
furious rally. A report on wholesale prices was sharply higher,
though oil accounted for most of the problem. Now consumer
inflation numbers were due Friday and the Federal Reserve is
scheduled to raise interest rates next week.
</P>
<P>
   There are some important facts that could explain away a lot of
Thursday's activity.
</P>
<P>
   Dow stocks and other out-of-favor issues have been beaten so far
down that even Friday they remained far behind the prices of their
best days. FleetBoston Financial gained nearly 25 percent in the
first four days of this week, but still traded more than 20 percent
below its best prices of last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Among high-tech stocks, prices bounced back only after a decline
of about 9 percent in just a few days. A snap back, even a
temporary recovery, shouldn't come as any shock.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the highest fliers were still down substantially for the
week, even after Thursday's bounce. Locally, stocks including Open
Market Inc., Akamai Technologies Inc., and Art Technology Group
Inc. were all down more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The more compelling story lies in the continuing gap debate.
That's the difference between valuations of fast-growing technology
companies and the established businesses that hate to be saddled
with the ``old economy'' tag.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts pointed to the gap between the Dow and the Nasdaq as
the easiest way to see what was happening, and most agreed the new
economy stocks had gotten too far ahead. But exactly what that gap
should be, the premium investors should pay for faster growth, is a
continuing debate. Like everything else in this market, it is
shaped by dramatically greater velocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our markets are starting to operate at warp speeds,'' said Ned
Riley, chief investment strategist at State Street Global Advisors.
He calls the tech-stock credo GAAP, or ``growth at any price,'' and
welcomed the swing toward the Dow stocks this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to think we were going to continue that
rotation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some money managers saw Thursday's late Nasdaq rally as a
reevalution of the old-to-new adjustment of the week, when some
investors thought enough was enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the valuation gap between new and old began to close a
little, people said maybe we should be buying back the new again,''
said John Wilson, manager of the $3.5 billion State Street Research
Investment Trust.
</P>
<P>
   John Ballen, president of MFS Investment Services in Boston,
sees a broader and relatively healthy market that is undergoing
adjustments by ``rolling corrections.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think you'll have a broadening of the market and
earnings growth will be rewarded at the companies that come
through,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of Thursday's trading, it was hard to avoid the
feeling you had returned to the casino and this time there were
just more games to play. Good luck, Ted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
