<HEADLINE>
MORE LIP FROM SKIP: NO BIG DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of Boston boys have gotten in a tangle out San
Francisco way.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the setup, parts of which were reported earlier this week
in the California edition of the Wall Street Journal: Last year,
developer Richard Friedman bagged a contract to build a $200
million luxury hotel on an extremely desirable plot right outside
his pal David Ross's new Museum of Modern Art in downtown S.F.
Remember David Ross? He ran the Institute for Contemporary Art here
and then moved his bourgeois-shocking act to New York's Whitney
Museum during the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his deal, Friedman agreed to dedicate a fraction of
his space _ 20,000 square feet _ to an African-American cultural
museum. Ross suggested that Friedman hire Thelma Golden of Harlem's
Studio Museum and Harvard's own Henry Louis (Skip) Gates, both of
whom had ties to the Whitney (Golden used to work there; Gates is
on the board), to help set up the proposed cultural center.
</P>
<P>
   Problem Number One: San Franciscans openly wondered why geniuses
had to be imported from New York and Boston to plan their museum.
``This is Skip Gates and friends,'' Claudia Polley, president of
the San Francisco-based National Association for African American
Heritage Preservation told me. ``Gates isn't a historian, he's not
a museum person, and he's not an exhibit designer. We may not be
the best experts in the world, but we do know something.'' In fact,
Gates's specialty is literature.
</P>
<P>
   Problem Number Two: As recently as Feb. 1, Gates was proposing
to call the museum ``Africana: The San Francisco African American
Cultural Institute.'' Not surprisingly, some San Franciscans viewed
this as a crass brand extension of a for-profit company that Gates
has been working hard to promote nationwide. He is the co-creator
of the print and digital/interactive versions of Microsoft's
Encarta Africana, an encyclopedia that has morphed into a Web site,
africana.com. Africana would like to be to African-Americans what
iVillage would like to be for women: a multi-service ``portal,'' or
gateway to the Internet for their respective constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman and the Skipper assure me that their intentions have
been misinterpreted. As for Problem Number One, Friedman says:
``It's not going to be our museum, it's going to be the community's
museum. It's premature for anybody to be worried about this.'' As
for Problem Number Two, Gates explains that S.F. mayor Willie Brown
said he wanted an interactive museum, which prompted Gates to demo
his Encarta Africana CD-ROM for the museum crowd. ``Africana was
just a working title,'' Gates says. ``It had nothing to do with
Microsoft. And that's the truth, Ruth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Author's Corner
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Didja ever whack anybody for Whitey? Maybe you should be
thinking about a book deal.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure Eddie Mackenzie ever whacked anybody, but he does
claim to have broken a leg or two for the Whitey Bulger-controlled
Irish mob. South Boston's own Eddie Macke, as he calls himself, got
busted for drugs in 1992 and cut a deal with the law that got him
out of his 13-year sentence. The quo pro which he got the quid was
helping the feds on a successful sting operation against a Latin
American drug gang.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, agent Helen Rees signed a lucrative deal with
HarperCollins for Mackenzie's life story, called ``The Redemption
of Eddie Macke.'' I'm assured there's enough blood and guts to
interest the Rupert Murdoch-owned publishing house, and Mackenzie
will be getting some writing help from Marblehead's own Phyllis
Karas, who also helped out on a 1998 book called ``The Onassis
Women.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how fast Mackenzie and Karas can write, they may
catch the tail end of the Whitey Bulger wave. Three Globe writers
have books planned for this year: Gerry O'Neill and Dick Lehr will
be publishing ``Black Mass'' later this spring, and Ralph Ranalli
hopes to have ``Blood Brothers'' in the stalls before the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   The word on the street is that John Martorano may try to do a
book, Henry Hill-style. Martorano was a Whitey triggerman who has
turned state's evidence and is now in the witness protection
program. Hill was the similarly protected mobster who sold his
story to Simon &AMP; Schuster for the book ``Wiseguy'' and the
subsequent movie ``GoodFellas.'' Martorano's lawyer Francis DiMento
says doing a book ``is completely out of the question,'' mainly
because his client hasn't yet testified in court. What about after
his testimony? ``Years down the road,'' muses DiMento, ``I suppose
he could do what he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
