<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9751 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-GEORGE-CARLIN-HNS &LR;      03-17 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-CARLIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOR `NICE GUY' GEORGE CARLIN, THE INSULTS KEEP ROLLING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Carlin is not an angry man; he just plays one on TV. In
fact, he's not even ticked off. No, you have to care to be ticked
off, and Carlin long ago detached himself from messy attachments
like, oh, an affiliation with the human race.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it really amounts to is a contempt and disillusionment
and a distaste for all the things this species has gone through,''
Carlin explained in a telephone interview from California. ``It is
more of an impatience. It is an accumulation of grievances on the
parts of these humans.''
</P>
<P>
   These humans. George Carlin has met the enemy _ well, at least
the perpetrators _ and they are us. Or, if you like, them. And he
wants no part of it, except to observe from afar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who's doing art is better served if they are
emotionally detached from the subject matter,'' he said. ``For me,
the best way is no emotional involvement. This way I can see it
more objectively.''
</P>
<P>
   But try as he might to irk the audience with a list of their
transgressions, he will not succeed _ since his fans naturally
exempt themselves from his contempt. ``You try to insult them and
it doesn't work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his fifth decade of performing, Carlin does a stage show
that he splits in half, the first part being bits from his last HBO
show, while the second half features new work from his next HBO
special, slated for spring 2001.
</P>
<P>
   That show will be his 12th for the cable network, to go along
with 130 appearances on ``The Tonight Show with Johnny Carson.'' He
was a network variety show staple in the late 1960s, although his
Fox sitcom in the mid-1990s never hit its stride. (Still, he's the
answer to a great trivia question, having served as the first host
of ``Saturday Night Live.'')
</P>
<P>
   But Carlin is the outsider who is now an institution. Closing in
on age 63, the artist _ the word fits without pretension _ did not
really find his voice until the 1980s, long after his bit on the
seven words you can't say on television (the inside joke is trying
to think of all seven) got him in trouble with the mainstream
suits.
</P>
<P>
   Then came cable. Carlin, even more than ``The Sopranos,'' is a
perfect match for HBO. No cable, and Carlin would have remained a
funnyman on the fringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a much more limited deal,'' Carlin said.
``I would have been stuck with albums. It still would have been a
healthy career.''
</P>
<P>
   But he wouldn't have been an icon. Cable television allowed
Carlin an outlet Lenny Bruce never had, and gives him the mantle as
arguably the most influential comic of the last third of the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin's 1997 book ``Brain Droppings'' was a best-seller; he
plans to release another tome, ``Napalm and Silly Putty,'' next
year. The latter title shows the juxtaposition in Carlin's act
between his rants on the ``big world'' _ war, politics, race, death
and the like _ and the ``little world'' _ food, pets, stuff, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The third component of his persona is his love-hate relationship
with language, heard in his riffs on the oxymorons (``jumbo
shrimp,'' ``original copy'') we take for granted. Words are
Carlin's tools, and he hates it when they're used as haphazardly as
a neighbor's borrowed ratchet set.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's religion. A former Catholic (``lapsed'' doesn't do
justice to his disdain for the religion), Carlin doesn't say he is
an atheist, or even an agnostic: He believes it's futile to try to
comprehend the concept of a god. Carlin, who played a cardinal in
the controversial comedy ``Dogma,'' thinks God would get the joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the joke,'' Carlin said. ``It's all a big joke.''
</P>
<P>
   This cosmic prank _ and you know he has a better four-letter
name for it _ leaves Carlin sounding bemused but angry. One hundred
nights a year, he goes out to towns like Charleston, S.C., while
another 13 weeks are spent packing the casino halls, all the while
mocking the morons who surround all of ``us.''
</P>
<P>
   A two-time Grammy winner, Carlin last fall released a box set,
``George Carlin: The Little David Years (1971-77).'' It's a
seven-CD period piece from the time when Carlin was honing his
stage character, years before his sharpest writing and sharpest
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-two and still peaking, still acerbic, still provocative,
still unafraid. Lines? Boundaries? Yeah, like he cares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look for where the line might be and deliberately cross
it,'' Carlin said. ``Then I bring the audience across the line with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   And we go, wherever this nice man takes us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
