<HEADER>
A9753 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FISHERMEN-MEMORIAL-BO     03-17 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHERMEN-MEMORIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING NAMES TO A FISHING PORT'S LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLOUCESTER, Mass. _ About all history recalls of Jeremiah Allen
is that he was 18 years old, a resident of Gloucester, on his way
home from a fishing trip off Sable Island when his schooner sank in
a storm on Oct. 14, 1716.
</P>
<P>
   There was no burial; his body was never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Not much, but it's all Allen needs to earn the dubious
distinction of heading the list of 5,230 fishermen who hailed from
Gloucester, or sailed from Gloucester, never to return, except in
name.
</P>
<P>
   Now a dozen volunteer archivists have officially finished their
seven-month project documenting the deaths of every fisherman lost
at sea who either came from Gloucester or shipped aboard a
Gloucester-based vessel.
</P>
<P>
   The list is scheduled for publication in the Gloucester Daily
Times, which hopes residents will come forward to report any
corrections or omissions. Then the list will be sent to a foundry
and the names will be cast in bronze, eventually to become the soul
of a $110,000 addition to the Gloucester Fishermen's Memorial
statue.
</P>
<P>
   The famous statue of the fisherman at the wheel _ its base
inscribed, ``They that go down to the sea in ships'' _ was
dedicated 75 years ago. In August, a cenotaph, a memorial to people
buried elsewhere, will highlight a rededication ceremony for the
statue.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps in a private moment, people will be able to run a
finger over the raised bronze letters naming someone who, at least
in name, will have returned to Gloucester.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin ``Benny'' Interrante, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Interrante disappeared with five mates aboard the fishing boat
Captain Cosmo in 1978. He took the trip on a lark, talked to his
family by marine radio on his 22d birthday, then failed to return
to port two days later for his sister's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be good to see him,'' his mother, Mary, said the other
day, her fragile voice a reminder that the pain lingers. ``There
was nothing. Now there will be something.''
</P>
<P>
   Memorials are nothing new to Gloucester, a community of 27,000
on Cape Ann. In 1997 the city hosted the traveling version of the
Vietnam Wall Memorial. The names of 17 men from Cape Ann
communities are on that wall. But, just since that war ended,
Gloucester has lost more men at sea.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Gloucester has been at war with the sea for more than
three centuries. The city's reputation, its profits, and, because
of recent fish shortages, its frustrations, have been defined both
by what the sea offers and what it claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``These fishermen are what made Gloucester famous,'' said Gaspar
``Gap'' Lafata, who is chairman of the committee overseeing the
memorial project. Like so many of his fellow residents, Lafata has
direct connections to death at sea, an uncle and first cousin lost
on a 1978 fishing trip.
</P>
<P>
   Half the money already has been raised for the privately funded
cenotaph, Lafata said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten granite slabs will be aligned along the periphery of the
existing oval in front of the statue, located between a sea wall
and Stacey Boulevard. Bronze plaques affixed to the stones will
list the names of those killed and the years they were lost. Only
men _ and to date, researchers have documented only men _ lost at
sea will be included.
</P>
<P>
   Last on the centotaph will be the four men lost aboard the
vessel Italian Gold in 1994. Next to last will be the six men lost
aboard the Andrea Gail in a 1991 tragedy that Hollywood has
dramatized in ``The Perfect Storm,'' slated to debut in June.
</P>
<P>
   Gloucester has compiled names of its sea deaths before; a
partial list of losses from 1874 to 1975 is displayed on a mural in
City Hall. But to get all of them, and to get them right, became
Lafata's goal when the former city councilor realized that this
summer would mark the statue's 75th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more excuses,'' he recalled saying to himself. ``You've got
the time; you've got the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Research began last September when Lafata introduced a few key
players.
</P>
<P>
   He knew that Alan and Mary Ray had been organizing vital records
in the basement of City Hall since 1988, and he knew that Roberta
Sheedy had been working for several years sifting through old
newspaper clippings. Sheedy had planned to flesh out her family
genealogy, but got so drawn into the harrowing fishing stories she
kept running into that she created a Web site, www.downtosea.com,
to sort and display them.
</P>
<P>
   From those stories came a rough tally of who died when, where,
and how. And the tally became the jumping-off point for the Rays
and a dozen other volunteers to check, double check, append, and
cut. Their tools were sources such as burial records, ship logs, US
Customs and Coast Guard archives, church annual reports, and
undertakers' documents.
</P>
<P>
   Sheedy, who works days as a computer technician for a Danvers
fish company, would update her Web site each night with new
findings from the archivists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We quickly developed a working premise: None of us is as smart
as all of us,'' Mary Ray explained as she nudged a reporter's pen
away from a 300-year-old document and replaced it with a pencil.
</P>
<P>
   One could mark each hour in the basement by the momentary
evacuation as archivists disappeared to plug quarters into their
parking meters.
</P>
<P>
   For them, the dusty records helped put faces on the statistics.
Fog and freak storms frequently separated men in dories from the
schooners that had brought them hundreds of miles offshore to fish.
The 1983 saga of Howard Blackburn is famous. the man intentionally
freezing his hands to his oars so he could row with the frozen,
dead body of his partner for five days and 60 miles to shore.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps less well known were the struggles of Sweeny McKenzike
and Charles Coleman, who in 1879 clung so hard to the upturned
bottom of their capsized dory that they left claw marks in the
wood.
</P>
<P>
   Six men died in 1913 when the ocean liner Sagamore sliced
through the schooner Olympia in dense fog. Eight lucky survivors
climbed to the rigging of their sinking vessel in time to jump
aboard the liner.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 21, 1897, the schooner Yosemite ran up on a rock off
Nova Scotia in a blizzard. Nine survivors spent the night clinging
to the rock as waves washed over them. The next day eight of them
afflicted by sundry broken limbs eventually swam more than a mile
to a deserted shore. When rescuers eventually got back to the rock
to collect the dead, one man was fozen so solidly into the cracks
he had to be chipped off.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's most amazing,'' said Sheedy, ``is that time and time
again you find instances where survivors turn right around and go
to sea again.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst year was 1879, when 268 men were lost aboard 15
schooners sunk by storms on Georges Bank. The runner-up was 1883:
17 schooners, 264 men.
</P>
<P>
   From 1860 to 1900, 3,597 men were lost, which is 68 percent of
all the men confirmed lost from Gloucester. This period of heaviest
loss was partly a result of the high number of people fishing at
the time, spurred by an influx of immigrants drawn to the sea and
the growth of railroads able to distribute the product.
</P>
<P>
   But it also had to do with the heightened risks that boat owners
forced the fishermen to accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greed,'' replied Joseph Garland, a Gloucester author who has
written several books on the local fishing trade. It was an era
when boat owners purchased a new class of schooner that forfeited
safety for speed and carrying capacity. The shallow, fat hulls were
fast, but water flooding through a carelessly handled vessel could
swamp the schooner, according to Garland.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually a cry for safer design, coupled with the introduction
of auxillary engines, reversed the death curve. Still, fishing
remains, per capita, the nation's most dangerous occupation,
according to federal statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there's one fish left, someone will risk their life
trying to catch it,'' Garland said.
</P>
<P>
   As if bearing him out, designers of the new Gloucester memorial
have left two columns blank on the last plaque of the last slab of
granite. There will always be, Garland said, ``men that go down to
the sea in ships.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
