<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FINAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FINAL DESTINATION' NEVER ARRIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
FINAL DESTINATION 
Directed by: James Wong 
Screenplay by: Glen Morgan &AMP; James Wong, Jeffrey Reddick 
Satrring: Devon Sawa, Ali Larter, Kerr Smith, Tony Todd, Kristen
Cloke, Seann William Scott, Chad E. Donella, Amanda Detmer, Daniel
Roebuck, Roger Guenver Smith 
Running time: 93 minutes 
Rated: R (violence and terror, and for language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Final Destination'' begins as a better than-average-teen scare
movie. But then, like the exploding 747 that becomes its central
image, it self-destructs. The exercise in would-be teen terror is
launched when Devon Sawa's senior on his way to Paris with his high
school class has a premonition of the plane being blown apart by a
fireball. While the plane is still on the ground at JFK, he freaks,
and is ejected with a handful of other high schoolers and a
teacher. While they're sitting in the terminal, grousing, the
aircraft does explode moments after takeoff. The survivors don't
feel lucky. They feel haunted in this film that isn't likely to be
shown on airplanes carrying the vacationing young.
</P>
<P>
   At least the six surviving teens aren't chased by a
knife-wielding maniac in a mask. Instead, they start dying one by
one as lethal fluids mysteriously appear, as well as live
electrical wires and loose gas connections, making it look as if a
series of household accidents is knocking them off. The
ever-shrinking band of survivors doesn't have to look at the
spooked expression on Sawa's face to arrive at the conclusion that
death itself is coming after them, after having missed them the
first time. Sawa's teen, Alex, figures there's a pattern, and that
they can outwit death. Ali Larter, as the spunky girl who feels
close to him after their narrow escape, is optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they start dying one by one, in various but equally
gruesome ways, and the questions are who'll die next, and how, and
who, if anybody, will be left. ``Final Destination'' also plays to
teen persecution fantasies via a pair of FBI agents who keep
hounding Alex, convinced that he's somehow behind the deaths. But
while the decapitations, electrocutions, and explosions
enthusiastically continue, the film runs out of suspense. The
ongoing carnage is unable to avoid seeming contrived, then campy,
right down to an ending on the streets of Paris that utterly
demolishes any last frisson of terror that ``Final Destination''
might have salvaged. It starts by cheating death and ends by
cheating us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
