<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING CLEANING FOR YOUR COMPUTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Before 1994, I knew a lot about DOS and working
with programs on the microcomputer. Then I lost touch with
technology for a couple of years, and Windows buried DOS. Last
year, I bought a Pentium III with Windows 98, and even with the
instruction book, I feel less informed than I did 15 years ago. How
do I remove unwanted programs and clean up my hard drive? Should I
ignore them? My 6-gigabyte hard drive is already half-full.
</P>
<P>
   _ Waist-Deep
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DEEP: Ahhh, but I see it as half-empty. Imagine all the
unneeded files, program remnants, cached Web files and other
useless garbage you can store on those remaining three gigs!
</P>
<P>
   Think of Windows as a tourist leaving cigarette butts, candy
wrappers, beer cans and used Huggies all over the pristine
landscape of your hard drive. A typical Windows program
installation scatters support files in several directories, so you
can't simply lay waste to a single folder to get rid of all the
litter.
</P>
<P>
   Well-written Windows software registers how to uninstall either
in the Add/Remove Programs utility in the Control Panel or in the
folder it builds in the Programs menu. Using an uninstaller
generally gets rid of most traces of a program, but it can leave
things like shared support files or saved games or data behind.
</P>
<P>
   You can clear a little more space by dumping your temporary
Internet files, but not really enough to make a big difference. You
can also go on a search-and-destroy through every folder on the
drive using Windows Explorer, but don't kill anything you're not
absolutely sure about or you could wind up with a very expensive
paperweight.
</P>
<P>
   Win98 also has a utility that's supposed to automatically dump
useless files. Go to the Programs menu, then Accessories, then
System Utilities and pick Disk Cleanup. Or, you can take the Bombay
scorched-earth approach: My PC gets so bogged down by all the stuff
I download that every six months or so I nuke the drive. Usually I
just reformat and load the essentials _ Office 2000, Unreal
Tournament and my Claudia Schiffer wallpaper _ and I'm ready to
start cluttering things up again.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: You had a column some time back about how to
erase the contents of a hard drive to render them permanently
unreadable. Could you point me to this column?
</P>
<P>
   _ Top Secret
</P>
<P>
   DEAR TOP: Yes, it's over there under the couch. Hmmmm. I see the
mice have been at it. You should have taken better care of it,
because this is the most-asked question I receive. And that only
reinforces my opinion that either (a) everybody in the world is
afflicted with rampant, unfounded paranoia, or (b) we all have
nothing but porn, bootlegged software and incriminating e-mail on
our hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, nobody's going to dig much deeper than a reformat.
Create a bootable floppy disk with Format.com on it, boot with the
floppy, then type in Format C: /u at the prompt (assuming it's the
C: drive you're killing). Everything goes bye-bye.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still worried that United Nations troops will be able
to decipher your plans for a plutonium generator, get a utility
that overwrites your files with random data. I found several at
www.hotfiles.com by searching for ``wipe.'' Judging by the number
of hits, I guess I was right about the paranoia. Or the porn.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay wouldn't be ashamed for anybody to inspect
the contents of his hard drive, as long as he gets 20 minutes'
advance notice. Reach him at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com
(snail-mail: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101). Fax: (817) 390-7257. In the nonvirtual world, he is Michael
Gerst, editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
