<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9757 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      03-17 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN COCKBURN CONTINUES TO EVOLVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Musicians rise and fall at a shocking rate today, so few will
ever scale the plateau that Bruce Cockburn just reached. He has
issued his 25th album _ one of the best in a career that has often
placed him outside the mainstream, though he ranks among the
keenest singer-songwriters of his time.
</P>
<P>
   He has been called Canada's Bob Dylan, and there's some truth to
that. Both men are prolific writers, both have a profound social
conscience, and both have a sense of humor that is sometimes
unappreciated but keeps their work from slipping over the line to
pretentiousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I marvel sometimes at how long I've been around,'' says the
Toronto-based Cockburn, whose first album came out in 1970. ``In
commercial terms, I've never set my sights that high. But I try to
keep the music always evolving _ maybe slowly in some people's
eyes, but I continue to learn more and apply it to what I'm
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cockburn's new album, ``Breakfast in New Orleans, Dinner in
Timbuktu,'' is a gem. The album boasts his biggest radio single,
``Last Night of the World,'' since his political ``If I Had a
Rocket Launcher'' more than a decade ago. The new hit purrs along
with a verse about how ``the radio is playing Superchunk and the
Friends of Dean Martinez'' (yes, Cockburn is a major fan of both
groups) and builds to the climactic line, ``If this was the last
night of the world, what would I do that was different unless it
was champagne with you?''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of sipping champagne at the apocalypse actually came
from singer/songwriter Sam Phillips, who toured with Cockburn in
1992. They talked about the apocalypse one day and she mentioned,
``What do you need for the apocalypse except for champagne and two
glasses?'' As Cockburn says today, ``She forgot she said it, but
the image was too perfect. It stuck with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The new CD includes several backup vocals from friends Lucinda
Williams and Margo Timmins (of the Cowboy Junkies). It features
other standout songs such as the contemplative ``The Embers of
Eden,'' the minor-key ballad ``Isn't That What Friends are For?,''
the meditative instrumental ``Deep Lake'' (Cockburn continues to
impress with his canny folk-jazz guitar style), and a once-common
but now-rare Cockburn political rant in ``Let the Bad Air Out.''
Its central verse: ``Take a walk by Parliament, smells like
something died . . . Open up the window, let the bad air out.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the decrease of politics in his material _ replaced by a
greater focus on love songs _ Cockburn says, ``There are a lot of
issues that I could be writing about, but for them to be turned
into songs, there has to be an emotional flash. Maybe it's from
being years around it, but there's less flash action in the
political arena of late for me. But I try to avoid being
pigeonholed one way or another. That's another reason why I've
probably stayed around as long as I have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grant Lee on his own: A few years ago, the alt-rock band Grant
Lee Buffalo made some noise with the albums ``Fuzzy,'' ``Mighty Joe
Moon,'' ``Copperopolis,'' and ``Jubilee,'' plus opened tours for
REM, the Smashing Pumpkins, and Pearl Jam. But that was yesteryear.
``A lot of folks are just finding out today that Grant Lee Buffalo
has reached its final legs,'' says Grant Lee Phillips, the band's
singer and songwriter.
</P>
<P>
   He says the group became ``disillusioned'' with record company
troubles, having moved from Slash Records to Reprise to Warner
Bros., where ``we weren't being told we were dropped, but they
weren't picking up our option, either.''
</P>
<P>
   So Phillips opted to go it alone. He just released a CD of
acoustic songs, ``Ladies' Love Oracle'' (named for an antique
parlor game), which he's selling over the Internet at
www.grantleephillips.com. He'll mix old and new songs at his solo
gig at the Middle East on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Describing his entourage, he says, ``It's just basically my wife
and I and a guitar and too much luggage. . . . But this seems like
a natural step and it's much less complicated than I imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   The new album brings out his softer side, from sweet love song
``Heavenly'' to the more sobering ``Nothin' Is for Sure.'' Some
songs have problems and are wispy attempts to reinvent himself, but
there is promise in the above-named tunes and in the finger-picking
``Lonesome Serenade'' and ``Squint,'' where he sings, ``I'll keep
squinting for something.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, he'll keep squinting on his solo tour, trying to
reconnect with Grant Lee Buffalo fans. ``It's as if I were playing
in my living room,'' says Phillips, who plays guitar and piano each
night. ``At some point, all the Buffalo songs began with me sitting
at a piano or guitar, so this is a full-circle exercise to take it
back to its original inspiration. I'm enjoying the immediacy of
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
