<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DETERRENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL-CRAFTED TENSION IN `DETERRENCE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
DETERRENCE 
Written and directed by: Rod Lurie 
Starring: Kevin Pollak, Timothy Hutton, Sheryl Lee Ralph 
Running time: 101 minutes 
Rated: R 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a whopper of an unlikely scenario for the year 2008, in
which the nuclear thriller ``Deterrence'' is set: A certain
Buchanan _ Pat, it would seem _ has become president, but died in
office. Vice President Walter Emerson (Kevin Pollak) has taken over
and is in the midst of a primary campaign against this Trump fella
(the movie was made before The Donald floated his campaign 2000
trial balloon and then dropped it). Emerson is Jewish, our first
Jewish president.
</P>
<P>
   Stop there. Could this happen? Buchanan and a Jewish VP? All
right, keep suspending your belief. Emerson has been stranded by a
blizzard inside a diner in the rural Colorado town of Aztec. He's
with some of his advisers, the military guy who carries the
football (nuclear-code-equipped detonator), a TV camera guy, and a
bunch of locals, some nuts, some not.
</P>
<P>
   President Emerson is seeking shelter from the storm, but a storm
of international proportions awaits him. Saddam Hussein's son is
now running Iraq and bullying its people, and has pulled a
like-father-like-son act on Kuwait. His surprise attack has crushed
the US (or US-backed) troops in his way, and he is sitting pretty
and mean, waving his arms in the air and threatening Israel,
Greece, Turkey _ hey, pretty much the world as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   This warmongering takes place off camera. ``Deterrence,'' a
quickly paced number written and directed by former film critic and
investigative reporter Rod Lurie, is a nuclear thriller in the
guise of a one-act, one-room play. Call it ``The Hunt for Red
October'' Jr. Do you push the button or not push the button? Do you
succomb to the ethnic baiting? Do you want to be responsbile for a
world where only cockroaches and Cher survive? The tension is well
crafted _ the Iraqis' refusal to deal with a Jewish president is a
knotty imbroglio _ and we see Emerson grow in stature and command,
even as he makes decisions furiously questioned by chief of staff
Marshall Thompson (Timothy Hutton) and National Security Adviser
Gayle Redford (Sheryl Lee Ralph). The locals in the diner get to
have their time with the prez and his cohorts too. This ultimate
high-stakes chess _ bluff or strike? live or die? _ escalates until
Emerson must decide to drop the big one on Baghdad or not. If he
does, how does Hussein respond?
</P>
<P>
   ``Deterrence'' is a small-scale movie about a large-scale issue.
The notion that the fate of the earth is decided in this
out-of-the-way diner _ where the dynamics among these disparate and
desperate people fuel the tension _ brings a certain down-home
quality to these high-level bureaucratic decisions. ``Deterrence''
does feel claustrophobic, but it's intended to. It moves quickly;
there's not a lot of down time. There is a palpable
edge-of-the-seat tension and a number of complex ethnic issues that
linger after the movie ends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
