<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9760 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TRUCKS-CROSSOVERS-BOS     03-17 1787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUCKS-CROSSOVERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSSOVERS TAKE A TURN IN HOT MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Is it a car, truck, SUV, or minivan? That was the question
when DaimlerChrysler first introduced the PT Cruiser at the Detroit
Auto Show in January, 1999. Now, we have the answer, well make that
answers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a truck, says DaimlerChrysler. If only all the vehicles now
in production or coming out soon were that easy to categorize. But
as the line between car, truck, sport utility and minivan has
blurred, and the era of crossovers has taken hold, that matter is
further confused by the recent EPA ruling that deems the PT Cruiser
a car. Meanwhile, the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, which administers the corporate average fuel
economy program (CAFE), says that, for now at least, Chrysler can
call the Cruiser a truck.
</P>
<P>
   It is this ever-changing, vibrant segment of the automotive
industry that is fueling the continued growth in sales and products
being offered by the many manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the X5, BMW's entry into the sport-utility field,
isn't called a sport utility vehicle but, rather, a sports activity
vehicle. BMW wanted a vehicle that would ride and handle like one
of its cars, yet also offer the advantages of a sport utility
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, trucks were basically designed for their
payload and what they could do in a work environment. Pickups were
judged by their cargo bed and how many sheets of 4x8 plywood,
sheetrock, or other goods they could carry.
</P>
<P>
   Pickup trucks gained popularity in the late 1970s as
manufacturers made the trucks more car-like in ride, conveniences,
and features. Then, in the 1990s, along came the sport utility
vehicle _ designed to carry people, go anywhere, do just about
anything, and have a good-sized cargo area.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in this new century, there's a blending of sport utility
and truck to meet the wishes of a new generation of buyers.
</P>
<P>
   There's a good reason for these changes. The truck market is
fast overtaking the car market, with some analysts predicting that,
by 2002, trucks will outsell cars. Trucks already are entrenched at
the top of each year's list of best-selling vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers see a new generation of buyers coming along.
Ford feels its No. 1 priority is to make all its vehicles
``aspirational to the next generation.'' One Ford executive said,
``You have to make sure the vehicle brands connect emotionally to
the next generation. You cannot just provide technology and
performance, you need to connect emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, for example, sold 1.10 million cars and 2.31 million
trucks in 1999. Even with those figures, Ford envisions problems.
For example, its market share for trucks slipped from 29.9 percent
in 1998 to 28.2 percent in 1999. Ford blames some of that slippage
on the company being too slow to retool for new vehicles. It hopes
to regain its market share with the introduction of new models this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is spending more than $1 million surveying buyers of sport
utility vehicles to find out who they are and what they want in an
SUV. They found many with the attitude that ``I can do anything I
want to do.'' So Ford is developing the ``Ford Outfitters. No
Boundaries'' theme for its vehicles and dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   New models coming soon from Ford are the Explorer Sport Trac,
Explorer Sport two-door, and F-150 SuperCrew sport utility pickup.
These vehicles with traditional cargo boxes and sport utility
cabins are aimed at the buyers who like the outdoors environment;
they are models that can go anywhere and carry all sorts of outdoor
gear. The Sport Trac, which is an Explorer with a short bed,
includes a fold-out bed extender, nautical bed cleats for tying
down equipment and mud-proof rubber floor coverings. Its cab has
full-sized room for five passengers. This makes the Sport Trac both
a pickup and an SUV.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet is taking the SUV-pickup idea one step farther with
its upcoming Avalanche. This vehicle will compete head-on with the
Ford Sport Trac, but will also offer a sliding door between the
cabin and the cargo bed, which will allow people to haul even
bigger loads with the back seats folded down.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's new Xterra comes with features such as bike-carrying
racks both inside and outside the vehicle, compartments to stow
muddy boots and outdoor gear, and a boast that it can go anywhere.
Some dealers have even put a premium price on the Xterra, since it
is a hot seller in the current market.
</P>
<P>
   All the manufacturers are rushing to get their new models out.
General Motors originally planned to hold off on new models of its
Chevrolet S10 and GMC Sonoma lines but has decided to rush extended
cab versions for these vehicles into production this summer. Nissan
is hoping to boost sales by bringing out a more macho design of its
Frontier in July.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of these models are being designed to draw in younger
buyers. Toyota's StepSide sport truck is one. ``This StepSide model
was conceived to broaden the appeal of Tacoma by attracting a
significantly younger, more style-conscious buyer,'' said Don
Esmond, general manager of Toyota Motor Sales. To make this model
more attractive, Toyota dropped the base price by almost $1,200 to
$13,750.
</P>
<P>
   The Tacoma compact pickup is an important part of Toyota's
overall truck strategy. Its platform lends itself to new
derivatives. ``The Tacoma StepSide is one such derivative that will
help us attract a younger buyer base. Look for more in the near
future,'' said Esmond.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota, which last year came out with its first full-sized
pickup, the Tundra, now can't keep up with the sales demand. Toyota
is going to increase production at its Indiana plant so that it can
build 300,000 Tundras by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   With the Tundra, Toyota became the first foreign company to
actively compete with American full-sized pickup trucks. In the
2001 model year, it will enter the full-sized sport utility field
with the Sequoia.
</P>
<P>
   For 2000, General Motors completely redesigned its Chevrolet
Tahoe/Suburban and GMC Yukon/Yukon XL (GMC has replaced the
Suburban name with Yukon). Rather than make them larger, as Ford
did with its huge Excursion, GM just made these models better. All
are based on the Silverado pickup platform and have stiffer bodies
for better ride and handling. While the Yukon XL and Suburban may
not be a large as the Ford Excursion, for 2000 they offer more
passenger room than last year.
</P>
<P>
   Early reports on the Chrysler PT Cruiser give it good marks for
performance and people- and cargo-hauling. Road &AMP; Track reports
``While the PT Cruiser definitely stands out in the crowd on
styling, it runs with the pack in performance. The clincher is
interior flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons DaimlerChrysler puts the truck mark on the
Cruiser, and other manufacturers push small pickups is not for
profit, but for CAFE (Corporate Average Fuel Economy). With
automobiles, the average CAFE requirement is 27.5 miles per gallon
for all the company's makes. For trucks, it is 20.7 miles per
gallon, and since many trucks get poor mileage, selling lots of
small pickups allows makers to meet the CAFE requirements without
being fined while still being able to sell big profitable trucks
with big fuel appetites.
</P>
<P>
   Having the EPA say the PT Cruiser is a car means Chrysler will
have to make some changes for tailpipe emissions standards. Having
the National Highway Safety Administration allow Chrysler to call
it a truck helps the company meet the CAFE standards. One federal
definition of a truck is that it has seats that can be removed for
cargo.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler isn't the first to have this dual ruling. The
Lexus RX 300 is a car by EPA standards, and a truck by NHTSA.
</P>
<P>
   Dodge has upped the ante among the more practical pickup trucks
with the Dodge Dakota Quad Cab. Already the biggest in-class
compact pickup, the new Quad Cab adds four full-sized, front-hinged
doors. The rear doors even open almost 90 degrees for more
convenience. And while Dodge has shortened the bed to 5.25 feet
from the regular Dakota's 6.5 feet, it has added an optional Bed
Extender. This lengthens the bed when needed, and, when it's not in
use, it creates a smaller cargo area to contain loose items that
otherwise might move about the bed. A few years ago, a less than
6-foot bed would not have been considered acceptable or marketable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how many segments there are in the light truck
category,'' says George Murphy, Ford division general marketing
manager, but we do ``think there are still a few opportunities to
define a segment with a new vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   And there seems to be no end to the ever-growing sport utility
field. This year there are 46 different SUV models on the market
alone, and, by 2005, industry analysts predict more than 70
different models of SUVs will be competing for your dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The next Mitsubishi Montero, due in dealer showrooms this month,
has a totally new design. It gives up its truck frame construction
for the unibody design common on car platforms. This will give the
vehicle a quieter ride. Among new features is a third row of seats
that folds flat into the floor. In earlier models, these seats
folded against the windows and took up cargo space.
</P>
<P>
   In the small sport utility field, General Motors, with its
Chevrolet Tracker, expects annual sales to reach 500,000 units this
year, up from 440,000 last year. Coming out this year, are the Ford
Escape, Mazda Tribute, Hyundai Santa Fe, and a redesigned Toyota
RAV4. Already in showrooms are the Suzuki Grand Vitara (sister to
the Tracker), Honda CR-V, Jeep Wrangler, Subaru Forester, and Kia
Sportage.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Brooks, Tracker brand manager, sees sales of the new
model, with an optional 155-horsepower V-6 engine and new trim
packages, increasing by 25 percent and predicts a potential market
for small SUVs of 1 million units in three to four years.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the confusion as to what constitutes a sport utility
are the new breed of models, exemplified by the BMW X5 and the
Lexus RX 300, neither of which looks like your typical SUV. In
these days of high gasoline prices, one compelling reason to look
at one of these is fuel economy. The Lexus RX 300 with 4WD has an
EPA rating of 19 mpg in the city, and 22 mpg on the highway. The
BMW X5 gets 13 mpg in the city and 17 on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors will soon be introducing its versions of this new
breed of SUVs with the Pontiac Aztec and Buick Rendezvous. GM,
which recently took full ownership of Saab, said it plans to
produce a Saab sport-ute based on the Rendezvous platform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
