<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9763 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-STUART-BOS &LR;      03-17 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-STUART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VIGOROUS, MODERNIST TAKE ON `MARY STUART' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MARY STUART 
Play in five acts by Friedrich Schiller. Translated by Michael
Feingold. 
Directed by Carey Perloff. Set, Ralph Funicello. Lights, Peter
Maradudin. Costumes, Deborah Dryden. Lighting, Peter Maradudin.
Music, David Lang. Sound, Garth Hemphill. Produced by the
Huntington Theatre Company with the American Conservatory Theater. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Altman gave some thought to staging one of Tom Stoppard's
later plays, ``India Ink'' or ``The Invention of Love,'' in his
final season. The problem was that the logical person to direct was
Carey Perloff, who had staged their premieres at San Francisco's
American Conservatory Theater, where she is artistic director, and
Altman was already sold on another production he had seen her do,
``Mary Stuart,'' Friedrich Schiller's turn-of-the-19th-century play
about those killer queens, Elizabeth I of England and Mary, Queen
of Scots.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why Altman, producing director of the
Huntington Theatre Company, went with ``Mary Stuart.'' Perloff and
translator Michael Feingold have fashioned a knockout of a
production that, like the best of classical drama, feels rooted in
its origins while resonating with the political and personal issues
of the day. That is what makes it a classic, as one character says
in ``Art.'' If Perloff and Feingold have sacrificed Schiller's
heroic idealism for a more modernist spin, then at least the
production makes its case with such vigor that it's hard to object.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Stuart'' bristles with psychological tension in every
character, and the ACT production team makes the three hours seem
shorter than plays half its length. Ralph Funicello's movable
columns create diverse claustrophobic sets indoors and out while
Peter Maradudin's lighting, David Lang's music, and Garth
Hemphill's sound are both nuanced and dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   It's the clash of personalities, of course, where ``Mary
Stuart'' lives and dies (literally). But it isn't Mary who carries
the play, or at least this production. It's Caroline Lagerfelt's
Elizabeth who commands the stage as well as the kingdom. Lagerfelt
makes Elizabeth's doubts, confidences, vanities, and compromises
play off one another with a Shakespearean agility until her final
cruelties leave her in a realpolitik prison of her own. Lagerfelt's
performance compares with Judith Light's in ``Wit'' as the best by
an actress in Boston this season.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth's skills as a survivor are matched by Marco
Barricelli's Machiavellian Leicester. In love with Mary but
determined to stay in Elizabeth's good graces, he can change
stories faster than you can say, ``I did not have sexual relations
with that woman.'' Richard Ziman matches him as Burleigh, his
political rival, but Firdous Bamji's Mortimer is no more admirable
as Mary's, and Catholicism's, fanatical standard-bearer. It's left
to Richard Ooms's Shrewsbury to find a semblance of a moral center
amid the wreckage, although much of the strength of this production
and its fine cast is to explore an inner logic amid all the noble
knavery. Would we have acted any differently in their places, been
any less moved by flattery and any less motivated by fear?
</P>
<P>
   And what of Mary amid all this double dealing? She is less
admirable than Elizabeth through most of the play, a vain and
vengeful power seeker, despite a radiance that draws people to her.
Schiller meant for the part to be played melodramatically, but Rene
Augesen overdoes it with an off-putting tremulousness that is out
of character with the rest of the production. As a result, her
religious freedom at the end is less the spiritual breakthrough
Schiller intended as a moral guidepost for the audience than one
more act of desperation among many.
</P>
<P>
   Or have modern audiences become too cynical of power and its use
of religion to accept such transcendence, no matter how it's
played? However one interprets it, this ``Mary Stuart'' does work
on its own sublime merits of political inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the relationships that Altman has built, perhaps the two
most important are with August Wilson, whose ``King Hedley II''
ends Altman's tenure in May, and with Perloff. Let's hope new
artistic director Nicholas Martin maintains them. ``Mary Stuart''
whets the appetite for Stoppard's ``India Ink'' and ``Invention of
Love'' all the more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
