<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GHOST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GHOST' SHOWS ONLY A FEW SIGNS OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
GHOST DOG 
Written and directed by: Jim Jarmusch 
Starring: Forest Whitaker, John Tormey, Cliff Gorman, Henry Silva,
Isaach De Bankole, Camille Winbush, Victor Argo, Tricia Vessey,
Gene Ruffini 
Running time: 114 minutes 
Rated: R (strong violence and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It can at least be said that Jim Jarmusch's ``Ghost Dog''
represents a partial return to vitality from the nadir of ``Dead
Man.'' The latter was more than flat; it approached absolute zero,
the point at which molecular motion ceases. ``Ghost Dog'' is best
when it's playful, toying with the fact that the Mafia has in a
single generation been transmogrified from myth to joke. But it
leaves largely unexplored its biggest asset, namely Forest
Whitaker's implacable, inscrutable hit man, Ghost Dog, living an
ascetic life on the roof of an abandoned building, alone except for
a coop full of pigeons and a Shinto shrine. Disciplined, adept, he
slides through the night, an unstoppable killing machine of
arresting stillness.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Jarmusch would have us believe, a principled killing
machine. The film is punctuated by title cards from the
18th-century samurai manual known as the ``Hagakure.'' Ghost Dog
lives by its precepts, although the frequent punctuation of the
action by the ``Hagakure'' excerpts stops being merely irritating
and starts seeming pretentious. What saves ``Ghost Dog'' from
degenerating into a sentimental attempt to put a gloss of nobility
on essentially psychotic behavior is Whitaker's soft gravity and
all-around grace in the title role. He's a figure of mournful
dignity and doomed integrity, but ultimately an inverted white
version of the subjugated black men who have gained so much favor
with the Academy of Motion Picture Arts &AMP; Sciences in ``The Green
Mile'' and ``Hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ghost Dog'' shows us a potent black man, but one bent on
abnegation. That's because in the story, Ghost Dog has interpreted
the samurai code to mean that he owes his allegiance and his life
to a low-level mobster who years ago saved him from a bunch of
murderous white thugs. The joke is that Ghost Dog is more skilled
and more dignified than John Tormey's designated master, a
none-too-respected soldier in a mob family that's coming apart at
the seams. So toothless has the family become that it is being
bounced from its clubhouse for nonpayment of rent by a landlord
obviously unafraid of consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath Jarmusch's characteristic deadpan surfaces, ``Ghost
Dog'' is sentimental through and through, although not where the
pigeons are concerned. Ghost Dog uses them to communicate with his
clients, including the one he has sworn to serve. Their respective
dying cultures intersect when Ghost Dog is given an assignment to
kill a made man who has had the poor judgment to become sexually
involved with the don's daughter. The assignment is child's play to
Ghost Dog. However, the daughter not only sees him, but gives him
the copy of ``Rashomon'' she was reading between watching Betty
Boop cartoons on TV. As Henry Silva's almost but not quite
brain-dead godfather sees it, that means Ghost Dog must in turn be
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Silva's performance is slyly involving in a reptilean way. You
think he's out of it, unable even to comprehend the violent
cartoons he too stares at unblinkingly on TV. Then he'll flicker to
life and croak a malignant command. Jarmusch has fun playing the
film's violence against TV cartoon versions of violence. The
problem is that they eventually become interchangeable as Ghost Dog
singlehandedly takes on the dysfunctional Mafia family. ``Ghost
Dog'' isn't the first film to transpose Pierre Melville's memorable
Parisian hit man movie, ``Le Samourai'' (1967). But something gets
lost along the way as ``Ghost Dog'' works at establishing its
gangsta bona fides by pulsating to a score by The RZA of The
Wu-Tang Clan. To back up a generation, and paraphrase Thelonious
Monk, the hip-hop score, and the movie, have beauty, but no smack.
</P>
<P>
   Things grow more devitalized with the introduction of a
sentimental friendship Ghost Dog strikes up with Isaach de
Bankole's ice cream vendor and Camille Winbush's icon of purity, an
adolescent girl Ghost Dog meets in a park and to whom he passes the
copy of ``Rashomon.'' But there's no real sense of passing along a
code, or a tradition. Good thing, because Ghost Dog's
interpretation of the samurai code results in just one more black
man's death after a lifetime of service to an unworthy white lord.
He can accommodate Jarmusch's laconic irony. But not his cultural
perch. ``Ghost Dog'' thinks it's hip. But it's only a hipper
version of the black subjugation that today's hipsters deride in
mainstream movies. Ghost Dog is given the moves of an outlaw, but
not the soul of one. His veneer of dignity and spirituality is just
another gloss on self-perpetuating slavery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1351EST &QL; 
