<HEADER>
A9772 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-BROCKOVICH-BOS &LR;      03-17 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BROCKOVICH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELL-RAISER IN HIGH HEELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
ERIN BROCKOVICH 
Directed by: Steven Soderbergh 
Screenplay by: Susannah Grant 
Starring: Julia Roberts, Albert Finney, Aaron Eckhart, Marg
Helgenberger, Cherry Jones, Peter Coyote, Scotty Leavenworth,
Gemmenne De La Pena 
Running time: 132 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roberts puts it all together in ``Erin Brockovich,'' reminding
us what star power can do when it's hitched to the right material.
Roberts is a big personality, ``Erin Brockovich'' is a big story,
and Hollywood bigness is a perfect delivery system for them.
Roberts has been looking for something more substantial since
becoming the queen of romantic comedy. ``Erin Brockovich'' gives
her the dramatic and emotional depth she's been trying to
regenerate ever since ``Steel Magnolias'' _ which it surpasses in
every way.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts could hardly go wrong in this fact-based story of a
single mom who empowered herself when nobody else wanted to, went
to bat for a townful of people clobbered by a large corporation,
and fought a spectacular David-and-Goliath legal battle against
Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric on behalf of the residents of a California
desert town it had poisoned with toxic waste, then lied to in a
cover-up attempt.
</P>
<P>
   If this is starting to sound like ``A Civil Action,'' but with a
much sexier protagonist, it is. From start to finish, Roberts's
warmth and energy pour off the screen in this film, which is boldly
contoured enough to accommodate her outsize persona. Tapping
brilliantly into her high-strung maverick side, Roberts really
makes this film stand up and march, or, rather, totter fearlessly
ahead on 8-inch heels. Never has she filled a role with so much
fire and conviction. Utilizing fashion advice from the best
possible source _ the real Erin Brockovich (who can be seen as a
waitress in a cameo) _ Roberts's Erin assertively plays the sex
card, dressing in miniskirts and low-cut jerseys that help her talk
her way past reluctant record-keepers in dusty municipal archives.
But the strength of Roberts's commitment and the unstoppability of
Erin's moral outrage count for a lot more here.
</P>
<P>
   Erin's earthiness is amplified by her salty talk, which
sometimes makes her reluctant-lawyer partner squirm. As played by
Albert Finney, he's a gruff softie who's experienced enough and
shrewd enough to let Erin run her mouth after he realizes that her
genuineness gets people to open up to her in ways they won't to
other lawyers. Erin pushes her way into a job as a law office clerk
after the lawyer, Finney's Ed Masry, loses a personal injury case
brought on her behalf. When looking over documents related to real
estate sales in a small Mojave Desert town, she wonders why a lot
of medical records are mixed in with them, and notices that a lot
of the people involved had become seriously ill. After driving
there and investigating, she suspects that the giant utility that
accounts for most of the economic activity there is behind it.
</P>
<P>
   As she doggedly and unswervingly keeps digging, and wins the
confidence of blue-collar townspeople who see her as one of them,
her suspicions deepen. But pointing a finger at a giant utility
with deep pockets and taking it to court are two different matters.
And Erin has battles on several fronts. She's got to prod the
lawyer, who had been entertaining visions of retiring to Palm
Springs to play golf, to stay on the job and go with her unorthodox
procedures. So good a foil is Finney, so expert at seeming barely
able to avoid total domination by Erin, that when he asks her how
she got copies of certain documents, and she flashes her cleavage
and says, ``They're called boobs, Ed,'' we wince with him. Finney
inscribes a number of little grace notes that further humanize the
film. But there's a lot of easy-to-overlook work from others, too.
</P>
<P>
   Erin finds another indispensable ally to solve the problem of
day care for her two young children _ Aaron Eckhart's next-door
neighbor, who's willing to switch from being a biker to being Mr.
Mom. Not that there aren't a few ruffled feathers to be smoothed
out on the home front. But you know, and don't really mind, that
the decks are being cleared for Erin's showdown with the bullying
utility on behalf of people who have been ingesting chromium
flowing out of the company's power plant and being told it's good
for them. As the most prominent of the poisoned, Marg
Helgenberger's delicate soul, who wears dresses with little
flowered prints, and Cherry Jones's angry neighbor are
heartbreaking in their modesty and decency. Their niceness had been
making them victims, as Erin realizes when she asks Helgenberger's
longtime resident why she didn't make some noise. ``I didn't want
to be a pain in the butt,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Director Steven Soderbergh, screenwriter Susannah Grant, and
cinematographer Ed Lachmann resourcefully and imaginatively put the
right kind of environment around Erin and the others. Shrewdly,
courtroom confronatations _ and the cliches that go with them _ are
minimized. Repeatedly, Soderbergh finds ways to yank the film away
from the deadening juggernaut of formula. When the legal verdict
comes, for instance, it is played out quietly and on an intimate
scale. With this script, Grant becomes Hollywood's foremost writer
of strong, smart women's roles, and Lachmann works the same wonders
with the atomizing light of Southern California that he did in
Soderbergh's ``The Limey.'' Roberts and ``Erin Brockovich'' have
Oscar contender written all over them. She made ``Notting Hill''
work by incorporating her star persona into the film's antics.
``Erin Brockovich'' taps into passions of hers that we haven't seen
before. She's dynamite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
