<HEADER>
A9784 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-TIGERS-BOS &LR;      03-17 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATTHIESSEN'S `TIGERS' BURNS BRIGHTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
TIGERS IN THE SNOW 
By Peter Matthiessen 
North Point Press, 174 pp., $27 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a surefire pairing: Peter Matthiessen, an author who leans
toward the poetic, writing about tigers, animals that are the
essence of poetry themselves. Further, ``Tigers in the Snow'' is a
handsome volume that includes maps, historic artwork, and photos.
</P>
<P>
   The story is built around Matthiessen's two visits with the
American and Russian scientists running the Siberian Tiger Project.
In a world in which there are more Siberian tigers in captivity
than out on the taiga, this band of maverick scientists has had to
cobble a big plan. First, a huge challenge: getting to know these
cats intimately _ how they hunt, what they eat, when they mate, how
far they travel _ without disturbing them. And then another
enormous goal: to preserve as much tiger habitat as possible to
sustain a viable wild population large enough to avoid problems
such as inbreeding and to withstand others such as occasional
poaching.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the numbing cold (temperatures that routinely reach 40
below), the lack of personnel and equipment, and the challenge of
trying to track these elusive animals without disturbing them, the
program is working. In the Sikhote-Alin Reserve, a national park
the size of Yosemite, 300 miles northeast of Vladivostok, Siberian
tigers are on the rebound. While there were only 50 tigers there in
1936, the latest census in 1996 showed a population of 450.
</P>
<P>
   To give all this work context, Matthiessen provides an overview
of the state of tigers around the world. At the turn of the
century, there were something like 100,000; today, that figure is
4,600 to 7,700. Matthiessen's lively primer includes all tiger
subspecies, from recently lost races to those that are on the
brink, to those we may be optimistic about _ Javan, Bali, Caspian,
South China, Siberian, Indian, and Indochinese.
</P>
<P>
   Tigers were nearly wiped out in China where, under Mao Tse-tung
in 1959, they were declared ``an enemy of man,'' and targeted for
eradication. In India, at the same time, Indira Gandhi sponsored an
active conservation program to save them. Still, they are under
great threat.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, what had been perceived as a victory for tiger
conservationists in the late '80s and early '90s turns out to have
been merely a hiatus on poaching due to large secret stockpiles of
tiger parts, which are used in traditional Asian folk medicines.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, with its desperate economy, there is continued
poaching and, worse, the loss of habitat due to logging rights sold
to other countries. Matthiessen reports that the country is
``selling off the future of Siberia at bargain rates.''
</P>
<P>
   While time is short, the questions about an animal that one
might have assumed was well known are surprisingly large.
</P>
<P>
   Are tigers really solitary? One expert isn't so sure it's their
nature. He believes that habitat degradation, with the loss of prey
animals, forces tigers to spread out. And prey densities vary in
different countries. A male Siberian tiger who eats 10 pounds of
meat a day requires 150 square miles for adequate hunting, while an
Indian tiger in Chitwan needs only eight square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Matthiessen also must cover a lot of ground on the status of
tigers around the world before he gets to what he does best: giving
you a ticket to the seat right next to him as he explores foreign
lands and nimbly negotiates complicated matters.
</P>
<P>
   The real joy of the book begins far in, as the author wings
toward his destination. ``The sun set at last over Manchuria, and
the deep blue of the wild horizon was fired by a dragon light of
crimson. To the east, where night had fallen over the Japan Sea,
Orion rode on a clear void of black sky.'' If you've read other
nature tales by Matthiessen such as ``The Snow Leopard'' or
``African Silences,'' you'll think, ``Now he's getting warmed up!''
</P>
<P>
   But Matthiessen here never quite ignites with that combustible
combination of evocative prose and deep understanding of all things
natural. He doesn't seem as engaged as in his best work. My guess
is that he just didn't get enough time on the ground to do so. But
most fans of his work will agree that even a low-key Matthiessen is
a fine read.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, we learn that actually sighting Siberian tigers is
a rare event for those who study them. Most carnivore researchers
must puzzle out a great deal of their subjects' lives through
footprints and feces. Matthiessen spins even these simple signs
into elegant stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the river ice, most of the snow had been taken by the wind,
and the pugmarks were crisp, as if incised in steel. In one place
the tigress had lain down and stretched, leaving behind a ghostly
outline of the True Spirit of the Mountains, even to the big head
and long tail, the leg crook, the big floppy paws. All that was
missing was the stripes.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthiessen seems to be missing his stripes a bit, too, with
``Tigers in the Snow.'' But nonetheless, where writing about
animals is concerned, he is still one powerful cat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
