<SLUG> BC-TRUCKS-SUVS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT YOU WANT DETERMINES THE RIGHT SPORT UTILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're the hottest vehicles in the marketplace, and, while
sales of SUVs reportedly are a little soft right now, that's not
stopping manufacturers from introducing even more models. About the
only companies that haven't produced an SUV are Volkswagen and
Porsche _ and both are about to enter the market.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with sport utilities is deciding what an SUV means
to you. Is an SUV a monstrous Ford Excursion or a Suzuki Grand
Vitara or perhaps a Jeep Grand Cherokee? Even the manufacturers
don't help: the new BMW X5 is called a sport activity vehicle by
its maker.
</P>
<P>
   During the winter months, SUVs are particularly attractive.
Their four-wheel-drive capabilities, coupled with their greater
road clearances, enable them to handle whatever snowstorms Mother
Nature tosses our way better than regular cars.
</P>
<P>
   The new BMW X5 was the clear winner in a recent test of vehicles
by the New England Motor Press Association. For the first time in
its three-year history of evaluating winter vehicles, the NEMPA
members' selection was unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   NEMPA jurists especially liked the way the BMW blended real
world off-road capability with some of the best creature comforts,
yet retained the intrinsic fit, feel, and finish of the marque in a
totally new vehicle. Among comments by members were ``BMW X5 _ a
great mix of sedan and SUV''. . .``a 5-Series with a better seating
position and as much fun to drive as any of BMW's cars,''. . . and
``clearly a winter techno-achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty high praise, but at a price of $51,000-plus, this vehicle
isn't for everyone. Which is why there's such a wide selection of
SUV types out there. Shoppers will find models from the Kia
Sportage with a list price of $14,445 on up to a Range Rover at
around $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   New this year is the Ford Excursion, the biggest SUV yet; it can
easily carry nine passengers. It's so big that it won't fit in most
garages, yet sales are doing quite well. Giving it a run for the
money are the newly redesigned Chevrolet Suburban and GMC Yukon
(formerly the Suburban), until now the largest SUVs. The newly
redone GM models are stiffer, quieter, more comfortable and more
powerful than earlier versions.
</P>
<P>
   The Nissan Xterra is also new with a price range of $17,300 to
$25,500. This is a vehicle designed definitely for the young,
active lifestyle. If you're looking for hot rod performance in an
already great SUV, the Mercedes-Benz ML55 is the one to have. It
can do 150 miles per hour, handle corners, and still handle the
utility of an SUV.
</P>
<P>
   Also new this year is a revamped Infiniti QX4. The 2001 model,
which has just been introduced to the market, offers more power, is
stronger, quieter and luxurious.
</P>
<P>
   In checking out SUVs, it's best to remember that not all are
created equal. Some are designed for off-road use while others are
for highway driving. Some have full-time all-wheel drive while
others offer a choice of two- or four-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking at cargo capacities, some can handle just
about everything you toss at them, others can't handle any more
cargo than a regular sedan.
</P>
<P>
   The safety issue is a major concern. SUVs can, and have, rolled
over. Those warning stickers inside SUVs are there for a good
reason. Because of their relatively high center of gravity, SUVs
don't hold the road like automobiles, which are lower and closer to
the surface. For this reason, taking a sharp turn to avoid
something or going fast around a corner can cause an SUV to roll
over.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest danger in owning an SUV is overconfidence _
the attitude that these vehicles can go anywhere, do anything.
Drivers need to drive these vehicles with care.
</P>
<P>
   Other sport utility winners in the New England Motor Press
Association's winter vehicle test were the Toyota Land Cruiser,
which tied with the Range Rover 4.6 HSE in the full-sized category;
the Lexus RX300 in the compact class and the Nissan Xterra in the
mini-SUV class.
</P>
<P>
   Not all winners were SUVs, which proves you can have a winter
vehicle with all-wheel-drive without going the SUV route. In the
all-wheel-drive class winners were the Audi A8 sedan; the Volvo V70
XC in the wagon class; and the Porsche C4 in coupe. The best people
mover was the Chrysler Town &AMP; Country Lxi all-wheel-drive minivan,
and the Subaru Outback received the value award.
</P>
<P>
   Winner of the pickup class was the Toyota Tundra. The Ford
Excursion received the extreme vehicle award.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
