<HEADLINE>
LEASE OR BUY? A LOT DEPENDS ON HOW YOU'LL USE THE TRUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To buy or to lease: that is the question consumers must consider
before they're ready to acquire a new vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to trucks or sport utility vehicles, it may appear
that leasing is a better deal. But depending on how you will use
the vehicle, leasing could be a costly mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Leasing a vehicle does offer an attractive monthly payment with
no down payment usually required. These factors would seem to make
leasing a better option than buying, which normally requires both a
down payment and a higher monthly payment.
</P>
<P>
   With leasing, however, you never do own the vehicle. And therein
lies the problem. Two of the predetermined conditions of a leased
vehicle are that there is a set number of miles allowed (go over
that limit and you pay for each and every mile) and the vehicle
must be returned in good condition.
</P>
<P>
   With a truck or SUV, especially the new breed that mixes the two
types of vehicles, chances are you'll be enjoying it so much,
you'll go over the stated mileage limit. And that could be very
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it's likely you will abuse the truck or SUV more than you
would if you owned a car. That situation could be expensive when it
comes to turning in the vehicle. Jack Gillis, a noted consumer
advocate and author of ``The Ultimate Car Book'', notes ``when it
comes time to turn in the car, it has to be in top shape _
otherwise, you'll have to pay for repairs or body work.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing leasing vs.buying, Gillis warns consumers: ``Don't be
deceived _ in general, leasing costs more than buying outright or
financing. When you pay cash or finance a car, you own an asset;
leasing leaves you with all the headaches and responsibilities of
ownership with none of the benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Gillis provides the overall cost of leasing and
financing a vehicle with a price tag of $22,000 over three and six
years. Gillis says holding the vehicle for three years, leasing has
an overall cost of $12,941.64 while financing costs $11,879.83. If
you hold the vehicle for six years, the cost of the lease jumps to
$25,883.28 while the price of ownership jumps only to $15,898.51
</P>
<P>
   Gillis says the example used for leasing has a residual value
(the value of the vehicle at the end of the lease) of about 54
percent after three years and 36 percent after six years. Few
vehicles have a 54 percent value after three years, so, should you
still wish to lease, it is wise to check a current Blue Book of
residual values to see what the future value of the vehicle in
question will be.
</P>
<P>
   If leasing still appeals, Gillis offers a few tips:
</P>
<P>
   --Find out the annual mileage limit. Don't accept a contract
with a lower limit than you need.
</P>
<P>
   --Avoid ``capitalized cost reductions'' where you are asked to
essentially put up a down payment to lower monthly costs.
</P>
<P>
   --Ask about early termination fees. Between 40 and 60 percent of
four-year leases terminate early.
</P>
<P>
   --Retain your option to buy the car at the end of the lease at a
predetermined price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ultimate Car Book 2000'' is filled with good advice for
anyone considering buying any vehicle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
