<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9791 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-CLINTON-INDIA-$ADV19-     03-17 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INDIA-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON HOPES CONTROVERSIAL TRIP TO INDIA, PAKISTAN WILL DIFFUSE
TENSION
 &HT;    (900&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    EDs: The add is deal for itinerary box.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For a president driven by a quest for policy
remedies to the world's most intractable problems, the Indian
subcontinent always seemed inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it's begun to look like an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton arrives Sunday in New Dehli, becoming the
first president to visit the region in 22 years, he faces a clear
and daunting challenge: to try to defuse mounting tensions between
India and Pakistan, before crisis escalates into catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after the uneasy neighbors declared themselves the
world's newest nuclear powers, tensions between India and Pakistan
are at a 30-year high.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are engaged in almost daily skirmishes over the
disputed territory of Kashmir. Neither side is talking to the
other. And the risk of a miscalculation that could trigger a
nuclear exchange hangs like the sword of Damocles over the region.
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan have already fought three wars over Kashmir,
a territory that fell through the geopolitical cracks when the
British partitioned the subcontinent into Muslim Pakistan and Hindu
India half a century ago. Fighting just last summer left more than
1,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Pakistan's deeply flawed but democratically elected
prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, has been overthrown by a military
dictator, chief Army Gen. Pervez Musharraf. He quickly set about
the normal business of setting up a junta: forcing chief justices
to swear their allegiance to him, placing Sharif under house arrest
and threatening unfriendly journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Sober analysts don't lightly raise the specter of atomic
Armageddon in a region that takes in one-fifth of the world's
population and abuts China, the Middle East and the southern edge
of the former Soviet Union. Experts say, though, they can't rule
out the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this very, very dicey period, where the stakes are high,
where tensions are rising, and in the face of a nuclear world, the
situation becomes extremely dangerous,'' former U.S. Ambassador to
India, Frank Wisner, said this week in an Asia Society briefing.
``Quiet diplomacy is extremely important.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomacy is non-existent at the moment between Musharraf's
junta and the government of Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee. Even back channels have iced over, replaced, analysts
say, with a chilling sense of fatalism in New Dehli and Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S.-Soviet relationship, at its worst point in the Cold
War, had greater interaction than India and Pakistan do now,'' said
Richard Haas, director of foreign policy studies at the Brookings
Institution, a Washington think tank. ``That is simply, I think, an
unacceptable situation, given the stakes, given the history of
conflict, and given the fact that now you have a nuclear overlay on
top of the entire Indo-Pakistani relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely because of those concerns, Clinton's foreign
policy aides say, that the president plans to visit Pakistan next
weekend, after a week-long swing through India and neighboring
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sign of how high the regional stakes have become, in
fact, that Clinton plans to pay a visit to Musharraf, whose coup
last October flew in the face of Clinton's efforts to promote
democracy around the world and risks sending a troubling signal to
fragile democracies in places like Indonesia and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``In no way is this a decision to endorse the military coup or
government led by Gen. Musharraf, and no one should interpret it as
such,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said in a speech here
last week(CQ). ``We are going to Pakistan because the United States
has interests there which are important and urgent.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarely has the White House applied either word to the Indian
subcontinent. No president has been there, after all, since Jimmy
Carter visited India in 1978. Richard Nixon was the last American
president to visit Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has offered to mediate the Kashmir dispute, a proposal
that Pakistan supports.
</P>
<P>
   India, though, has made clear that it wants no part in a
U.S.-brokered peace process. That, Vajpayee's government worries,
would risk placing Pakistan, a nation of 135 million people, 97
percent of whom are Muslim, on equal footing with India, a nation
of 1 billion, 82 percent of whom are Hindus.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations for Clinton are not high on this score. It's no
secret that he's got 10 months left in office _ seven until
November elections make him officially a lame duck. And the Kashmir
issue suffers from complexity as well as neglect by the world
community.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say, though, it would be a significant step forward if
Clinton can get the two neighbors to recognize that they can't
change geography, that they must resolve the Kashmir issue, first
by talking to each other about it.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Clinton's week-long swing will be focused on
geopolitics.
</P>
<P>
   After spending Sunday night resting in Dehli, Clinton begins the
official portion of his trip Monday, spending the day in
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   A country where per capita income is less than $1 a day,
Bangladesh is ground zero for the global war on poverty. It was
there that a young economics professor named Mohammmad Yunus forged
the concept of lending small amounts of money, in increments of $50
or $100 or so, to the poor. He later institutionalized the practice
with his revolutionary Grameen Bank, the symbol for the
micro-credit movement that's since become a mainstay of the world
development establishment
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's day in Dhaka, where he will become the first American
president ever to visit the 19-year-old state, is built around a
visit to a nearby village to spotlight the Grameen movement, as
well as health and education projects that work in concert with
micro-credits to help promote empowerment for women and progress
for their families.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add begins.)
</P>
<P>
   Returning to New Delhi late Monday, Clinton begins his state
visit to India the next day, meeting with Prime Minister Vajpayee,
and attending a state dinner in his honor hosted by President
Kocheril Raman Narayanan.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Clinton addresses the Indian Parliament, then goes
to nearby Agra to tour the Taj Mahal, the most famous work of
Islamic architecture in the world.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of Clinton's trip will be the contrasts and
contradictions inherent in India, the world's most populous
democracy and home to one-sixth of all humankind , more than half
of whom are among the poorest anywhere on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will pay tribute, for example, to the father of Indian
independence, Mahatma Gandhi, and the profound impact that his
doctrine of non-violent protest had on the seminal political force
of Clinton's own career: the American civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will travel to the burgeoning high-tech center of
Hyderabad to stress the growing technology base helping to fuel an
economic expansion in India, which is projected to grow by 5.9
percent this year. And he'll spotlight the increasing commercial
and trade ties between the United States and India, which did $12.8
billion in two-way trade last year.
</P>
<P>
   He'll go to the vibrant commercial and cinema capital of Mumbai,
formerly called Bombay. He'll pay homage to the contributions
Indian people have made to the United States, where more than 1
million Americans of Indian descent now play vital roles in
technology, medicine, science, education, business and law.
</P>
<P>
   At each juncture, though, Clinton will find India staring back
with its inexhaustible insistence to be taken in on its own terms.
</P>
<P>
   There simply is no way to conceal or to clean up the myriad
manifestations of misery in a country whose national pastime is
daily survival in an economy that allots the Indian people with, on
average, the local equivalent of $1.25 a day; where 48 percent of
people over the age of 15 can't read; where one person in five,
day-in and day-out, can expect to be sick simply because they lack
access to safe drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is overcome by the swill of India's poverty, he is
certain to convey the message that to dwell only on that would be
to sell short a civilization that has endured continuously for
4,600 years, surviving one invasion after the next, centuries of
tyranny, feudalism and colonialism and, having rejected them all,
has built its own freewheeling democracy, the imperfect miracle of
government by one billion people, overlaying a world of ideas atop
a distinctively Indian design.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
