<P>
   IRAN-U.S. (Washington) _ In a cautious but warmly worded
overture to Iran, Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright on
Friday announced the lifting of a ban against some Iranian imports
_ carpets, pistachios, and caviar _ and said the United States
wants to settle the remaining legal disputes between the countries.
By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-ELECT (Taipei) _ The presidential election on Saturday is
expected to usher in a new phase of relations with China _ perhaps
a very tense one _ and whatever the result, Taiwan politics will be
very different in the future if, as expected, the Nationalist Party
suffers a severe setback or even loses the presidency. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-VOICES (Taipei) _ What some voters are saying.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-SMITH (Washington) _ Facing a threatened suit from the
federal government over shooting deaths of public housing
residents, Smith &AMP; Wesson agrees to a number of new safety
measures, including a push for smart technology that means an
individual gun is programmed to work only in the owner's hand,
longer waiting periods, and other steps. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BROWN-SHOOTING (Atlanta) _ The former black militant once known
as H. Rap Brown was being sought Friday after two deputies were
shot, one critically, as they tried to serve a warrant accusing him
of theft and impersonating an officer. It's believed that the
suspect also was shot. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   With photos from Cox News Service, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   VT-GAYS (Montpelier, Vt.) _ Now that Vermont is on the brink of
giving gay and lesbian couples all the benefits __ and legal
complications __ of marriage, gay couples reflect on what it's like
to face a decision that's never been an option for them. By Carey
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHBISHOP-APOLOGY (Milwaukee) _ Rembert G. Weakland, the
archbishop of Milwaukee, issued his own apology for the wrongdoings
of Catholics four months before Pope John Paul II did. And unlike
the pope, Weakland went so far as to use the word Holocaust. By
Gustav Niebuhr
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By Peter
Steinfels. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ST-PATRICKS-PARADE (New York) _ Rudy Giuliani, Hillary Clinton
and others brave a snowy day for the annual St. Patrick's Day
parade. By Elisabeth Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-SHOOTING (New York) _ Folo on the shooting Thursday of
an unarmed man by undercover police officers in midtown Manhattan.
By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECOMMERCE (Tokyo) _ Want to buy a concert ticket or book a
hotel room? Stroll into a Lawson, Japan's second-largest
convenience store chain, punch into its online store, Loppi, and
pay at the register on your way out. How about a book? Hop online
at the nearest 7-Eleven and find your title at e-Shopping! Books, a
site the chain owns with Softbank, Tohan and Yahoo, Japan's largest
book distributor. A day or two later, on your way home from work,
you can pick up and pay for your selection at the store. Accustomed
to adding new items to its merchandise mix every day, the Japanese
convenience store is fast grabbing hunks of cyberspace to expand
its limited shelf space. At the same time, recent deregulation is
allowing it to encroach on territory long out of reach, like
over-the-counter pharmaceuticals and banking. ``Without the
convenience store, e-commerce in Japan would have more trouble
taking off,'' says an official with the Ministry of Trade and
Industry. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-STRIKE (Undated) _ Boeing and the union representing
nearly 20,000 engineers and technical workers reach a tentative
three-year agreement, ending a 38-day strike.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks extend their gains on the first
triple-witching day of the year. At 2:00 p.m., the Dow Jones
industrial average was 31 points, the S&AMP;P 500 was up 10 points and
the Nasdaq composite index wass up 63 points. Treasury prices were
rallying as expectations of a supply shortage of longer maturities
grow. The yield on the 30-year bond was at 6.01 percent after
dipping as low as 5.99 percent. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Consumer prices rose 0.5 percent in
February, higher than expected and more than doubling January's 0.2
percent increase. But rising oil prices accounted for most of the
gain. Excluding energy and food costs, the core CPI rose 0.2
percent last month, matching January's increase. The core rate has
not risen more than 0.2 percent since September. By Louis
Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   PANAM-PENSIONS (Undated) _ Former Pan Am workers win a ruling in
a pension case. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   BMW-ROVER (Longbridge, England) _ The BMW deal is greeted with
anger and bafflement at Rover's main automotive plant outside
Birmingham. The British government, meanwhile, continues to express
anger at the way BMW handled the sales, while both BMW and Alchemy
partners hold press conferences. Shares of BMW fall 7 percent in
Frankfurt trading. Other developments. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-EUROPE (London) _ America Online will pay $8.25 billion to
buy out its European partner, Bertelsmann, to take full control of
AOL Europe as well as another joint venture, AOL Australia. By
Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
