<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9853 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-UNRULY-PASSENGER-HNS &LR;      03-17 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNRULY-PASSENGER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PASSENGERS HELP THWART COCKPIT ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUSTINO AGUILA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Passengers and crew members aboard an Alaskan
Airlines jet headed to San Francisco subdued a man who broke into
the cockpit and attacked a pilot, airport officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Joe Reilly of the San Francisco police said it was unclear
why the passenger, David L. Bradley, 40, of Blue Springs, Mo.,
acted so erratically. He speculated that Bradley might have been
under the influence of drugs or alcohol, or in need of psychiatric
medication.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred at 7:10 p.m. Thursday on Flight 259 when
the airplane was about 160 miles south of San Francisco, coming
from Puerto Vallarta, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had been speaking nonsense and took off his socks and
his shirt, Reilly said. He repeatedly switched seats, disobeying
flight attendants and the captain, who told him to stay put.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley eventually sat in first class, where, Reilly said, he
made this threat: ``I'm going to kill all of you; keep away from
me,'' while simulating a gun with his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger Robert Benjamin, 56, of West Linn, Ore., who helped
restrain the man until landing, said people on board were very
horrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them didn't think they were going to make it,'' he
said. ``Families were crying.''
</P>
<P>
   The co-pilot, whose name was not released, already had been
alerted and armed himself with a tool in case of attack, Reilly
said.
</P>
<P>
   As flight attendants continued to coax the man back to his seat,
he became angry and threatened them. Soon after, he forced open the
cockpit door and lunged at the controls of the MD-83 jet, the
police said. The co-pilot tried to block the passenger from the
controls and the two men scuffled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The co-pilot was able to do a body block,'' Reilly said,
adding that Bradley weighs about 250 pounds and is 6 feet, 2 inches
tall.
</P>
<P>
   As the two men fought, the co-pilot suffered cuts to his right
hand as the passenger tried to get the tool _ described by the
police as a pick-like instrument _ away from him.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot called for help and was quickly aided by seven
passengers. They and the crew subdued Bradley and forced him to the
floor where he was bound with plastic restraints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately all the guys moved quick and he ain't dead and
we're not dead,'' Benjamin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really scared me was when he tried to open up an exit,''
said Chris Honochick, 37, of Salem, Ore., who also helped tackle
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot requested an emergency landing at the San Francisco
International Airport, where law enforcement officers met the
flight shortly before 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the jet landed, airport tower officials already had
received an ``alert 1'' message, meaning there was an emergency on
the plane, said Philip Meginness, an airport duty manager.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was taken into the custody of FBI agents. Threatening
the crew of an airplane is a federal offense.
</P>
<P>
   Meginness said Bradley was taken by ambulance to Mills-Peninsula
Hospital in Burlingame with bruises and cuts to his face. The
co-pilot also was taken to a hospital for treatment of cuts to his
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't overemphasize the heroics that went on tonight,'' said
Reilly, referring to the passengers' and crew's actions. ``They
averted a tremendous disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin's wife, Donnie, said Bradley was speaking nonsense
during the flight.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Bradley said, ``It's not what's on the floor, it's
not the love you lost,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft went on from San Francisco to Portland, Ore.,
arriving at 12:50 a.m. Friday. The plane was carrying 43 passengers
and five crew members, according to Alaska Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley faces several federal charges including interfering with
a flight crew, assaulting crew members and failing to follow their
directions, Reilly said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
