<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9861 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-ERIN-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      03-17 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ERIN-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRITTY WOMAN: ROBERTS SHOWS TRUE PLUCK AS `ERIN BROCKOVICH` 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Julia Roberts hits a career high-water mark with ``Erin
Brockovich.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the dull title, the movie is near perfect:
entertaining, instructive, emotional, expertly directed and funny.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is so right as Erin that it's hard to imagine anyone
else playing her. The role is beautifully written (by Susannah
Grant, who did the Cinderella update ``Ever After''), moving
naturally and seamlessly between drama, pathos and reality-based
humor, and Roberts is in complete control at every moment. She's a
delight to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, directed by Steven Soderbergh, long a favorite of
actors and film buffs, is just as pleasing, and should be his first
blockbuster hit.
</P>
<P>
   Like the recent John Travolta drama ``A Civil Action,'' this is
a true story about a lawsuit against a huge company that is
knowingly damaging its neighbors' health by environmentally
dangerous practices. But the films could hardly be more different.
``A Civil Action,'' though good, wasn't fun. ``Erin Brockovich,''
while suspenseful and delivering its theme clearly and
dramatically, is a pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   It focuses not on the lawsuit (there is no trial scene) or
injured families or the lawyers, but on the unlikely woman who
became the heroine of the tale by uncovering the misdeeds and the
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Erin has three young kids, little education and few skills.
She's way behind on her bills and she cannot find a job. After a
car accident, she hires a lawyer to sue the doctor who hit her, but
her foul language and inappropriate clothes do not please the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate, Erin browbeats the lawyer, Ed Masry (Albert Finney)
to give her a job as a file clerk. She is shunned by the women in
the office, who understandably don't cotton to her loud, aggressive
style, see-through tops and up-to-there skirts. When Masry suggests
she rethink her wardrobe, he gets back talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just so happens I think I look nice,'' she tells him
flatly. ``Maybe you should rethink those ties.''
</P>
<P>
   But Erin takes her work seriously and does it well. She uncovers
oddities in a minor real estate case involving a homeowner and a
major utility company. As she investigates, she discovers
horrifying proof that the company has been polluting a town's water
system, causing major health problems. She then convinces Masry to
begin a major class-action suit.
</P>
<P>
   While this is happening _ and the story is much more involved _
we are focusing on the high and low drama of Erin's private life,
from finding day care for her kids to considering a cautious
romance with the biker/carpenter next door, George (Aaron Eckhart).
</P>
<P>
   Erin makes a great character, albeit a pain in the neck at
times. Loud and foul-mouthed, she steamrolls over people _ though
sometimes she tries flirting first. Her treatment of lawyers, both
on her side and theirs, is one long lawyer joke.
</P>
<P>
   Her relationship with George adds more dimension to her
personality. At first, Erin judges George the same way the women in
her office judged her, by appearance. Eckhart, so good as the
button-down misogynist of ``In the Company of Men,'' gets to make
amends in this role.
</P>
<P>
   Though the movie is really about Erin, by the end we are quite
involved in the suit and concerned for the victims _ such as Donna
(Marg Helgenberger, of ``China Beach'') as a woman who pays a great
price for trusting the polluting company.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has sad, painful moments. Erin is a tremendously
empathetic person _ that's the reason the country folk of the movie
trust her when they don't trust lawyers. A scene where she tries to
cheer up a young girl with cancer is a heart-tugger.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Erin Brockovich is a real person _ watch for her
playing a waitress early in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Director Soderbergh (``sex, lies and videotape,'' ``Out of
Sight,'' ``The Limey'') deserves huge credit for perfectly
balancing the humor and drama, the large events and the personal
moments. Soderbergh eschews his trademark stylistic flares to keep
this grounded in the character and reality of the story, but it's
just as much his movie.
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh wonderfully captures the desperation Erin feels, the
austere terrible beauty of the desert where the pollution takes
place, the suspense of the danger (real or imagined) Erin may be
in. He handles the sad parts without letting the film turn maudlin.
And he gets strong performances from the entire cast. (The film has
many gemlike small parts.)
</P>
<P>
   Finney, who at first seems strange casting as a small-time
American lawyer, is just as wonderful and funny as Roberts. Much of
the film's humor is his response to Erin, and when he learns to
give as well as he gets, it's a treat.
</P>
<P>
   The movie does have a slight, only infrequent, tendency to turn
a bit cutesy in its humor, but really, not much. And while it's
been called a ``Rocky in miniskirts,'' it doesn't over-hype its
victories.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Erin Brockovich'' will be Roberts' personal triumph. After
a string of five box-office hits (even ``Conspiracy Theory'' and
``Stepmom'' did more than $100 million worldwide) Roberts has
completely re-established the momentum and popularity she lost in
the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Now she is stretching herself in a serious dramatic role, albeit
with a lot of humor and fun. She has, of course, done much drama
(``Mary Reilly,'' ``Michael Collins''), but this should be the
first since ``Steel Magnolias'' in which she makes a huge
impression on the public.
</P>
<P>
   It's great that ``Erin Brockovich'' has come along to brighten
up a pretty bleak spring at the theaters, but it will be too bad if
this movie and ``Wonder Boys'' are forgotten when Oscar time rolls
around next year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
