<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DESERT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ENVIRONMENTALISTS SUE GOVERNMENT OVER DESERT PROTECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Three environmental groups have sued the Bureau
of Land Management, charging that the federal agency is not fully
protecting endangered animals on 10.2 million acres in the
California desert.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has not implemented a conservation plan or considered
the plan's overall effects on at least 24 plant and animal species
in the high Mojave Desert and the low Sonoran Desert, the lawsuit
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Biological Diversity in Tucson, Ariz., the Sierra
Club and the Washington, D.C.-based Public Employees for
Environmental Responsibility filed the suit Thursday in the U.S.
District Court in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Doran Sanchez, spokesman for the Bureau of Land Management in
Riverside, said he could not comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is preparing four plans to protect the imperiled
species, including the desert tortoise, Peninsular Ranges bighorn
sheep, Inyo California towhee, Desert pupfish and rare plants,
Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   Two plans would be ready in early summer, and the other two
would be available later in the year, according to Bureau of Land
Management officials. Completion of the proposals would bring a
20-year-old conservation plan up to date, Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of the four major plans is for the protection and
preservation of all the sensitive or threatened species,'' Sanchez
said. ``We have spent years collecting data, so when we make
management decisions, we'll have the data to back them up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Land Policy and Management Act of 1976 included the
California Desert Conservation Area, which stretches over 400
miles. The Bureau of Land Management completed the original
required plan by 1980. The law requires updates, and the agency has
missed the deadlines, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rare desert plants and animals are suffering as the BLM keeps
its eyes closed,'' said Daniel Patterson, a desert ecologist for
the Center for Biological Diversity. ``Thriving on Earth for 67
million years, the desert tortoise has been decimated in just over
100 years by livestock grazing, mining, off-road vehicles, utility
projects and urban sprawl.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
