<HEADER>
A9918 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-JULIA-ROBERTS-COX     03-17 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JULIA-ROBERTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roberts' `Erin Brockovich' flashes skin as she saves town
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've never seen Julia Roberts quite like this, promises
costume designer Jeffrey Kurland.
</P>
<P>
   In Roberts' new film, Erin Brockovich, the actress sprints
through desert sand in 3-inch heels and shows off plenty of leg in
leather mini-skirts slit up to there.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, she's suddenly got major cleavage, the result of some
heavy-duty brassieres stitched right into her costumes.
``Understructure had to be made to feature whatever needs to be
featured,'' Kurland says delicately.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of it all, Kurland says, is that the wild woman
whom Roberts portrays is real.
</P>
<P>
   `A character dropped down from heaven'
</P>
<P>
   Erin Brockovich is a twice-divorced mother of three who, as a
file clerk in a small law firm, stumbles upon a coverup involving
contaminated water in a small desert town. She persuades her boss,
played by Albert Finney, to let her investigate. The payoff:
Without any formal legal training, Erin helps win a $333 million
lawsuit for the citizens of the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was like a character dropped down from heaven,'' Kurland
says. ``She did this amazing thing for these people, and she's so
much fun to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Steven Soderbergh-directed drama, Roberts wears 52
costumes, most of which are characterized by plunging necklines,
loud prints and big, flashy earrings. Erin is ``an extraordinary
character who dresses rather extraordinarily,'' says Kurland, who
met the real Erin before he started sketching.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Roberts was more than willing to dress like, well,
a tramp, and spend countless hours tottering on stilettos, Kurland
says. ``If you've ever tried to run in high heels, you know that
those calf muscles are aching at the end of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   A Northwestern University grad, Kurland lives in Los Angeles
with his wife and two children; his parents have lived in Boca
Raton for the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Many Kurland credits on Woody Allen films
</P>
<P>
   Before beginning his career in film in the late '70s, Kurland
designed for the Metropolitan Opera, American Ballet Theatre and
the New York City Opera. The bulk of his movie credits are Woody
Allen features. Kurland created the costumes for Mighty Aphrodite,
Hannah and Her Sisters, Crimes and Misdemeanors and many others,
and he previously dressed Roberts in My Best Friend's Wedding and
Everyone Says I Love You.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very trusting of me,'' he says. ``I would never make her
uncomfortable, that's first and foremost.''
</P>
<P>
   And because Roberts is in such great shape, the Erin Brockovich
fittings were a study in efficiency. ``She looks good in so many
things, you spend the correct time looking for the character,''
Kurland says. ``You spend your time wisely.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, the real Erin still dresses pretty much the same,
Kurland says. ``Of course, there's a little more money behind it,
and the clothing is probably a little better quality.''
</P>
<P>
   stacisturrock(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
