<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9945 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-ISSUE-ADS-$ADV19-HNS &LR;      03-17 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISSUE-ADS-$ADV19-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ALLIES OF BUSH AND GORE READY `ISSUE ADS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 19)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If you missed the broadcast advertising campaigns
that George W. Bush and Al Gore waged in early primary states to
help secure their parties' presidential nominations, a
multi-million dollar replay is headed your way.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican and Democratic parties _ and allied organizations
theoretically acting independently of the candidates _ are on the
verge of mounting the most expensive advertising blitz in U.S.
history in hopes of shaping the political landscape for the fall
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Their plans are inspired by the Democrats' success in using the
post-primary, pre-convention phase of the 1996 campaign to inundate
the nation with thematic advertising that set the stage for
President Clinton to become the first elected Democrat to win a
second term in 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   By the time GOP nominee Bob Dole emerged broke and politically
weakened from GOP primaries to accept the Republican nomination,
Democrats had already augmented Clinton's $37 million in
permissible pre-convention campaign spending with an independently
financed, $45 million campaign that didn't count against Clinton's
spending limit because the ads never explicitly called for
Clinton's re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans saw ads such as ``Values'' that extolled
Clinton's efforts to protect Medicare and cut taxes for ``working
families.'' The ads claimed that a ``Dole-Gingrich budget''
masterminded by the prospective GOP nominee and House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., had ``tried to cut Medicare $270 billion'' and
``raise taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say they won't get caught by surprise this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to let the Democrats pull off what they did to
a fare-thee-well in 1996,'' warns Mike Collins, a GOP spokesman.
``We're prepared to respond to the Democratic onslaught.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee, armed with $15 million in the
bank and more on the way, hopes to raise $177 million in private
donations and federal matching funds to underwrite efforts to
reclaim the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, buoyed by their success in 1996, have $3.5 million in
the bank and millions more being raised to enable the party to
``keep all its options open'' for an aggressive advertising
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect an `air war' and we're ready,'' says Jenny Backus,
spokeswoman for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Issue advertising is especially appealing to presidential
candidates because the ads trumpet their political message and help
shape the political debate without the cost being counted against
their total permitted campaign spending.
</P>
<P>
   Ads qualify as ``issue advocacy'' as long as they do not overtly
endorse a candidate. The ads have extra appeal because they can be
financed with unlimited, unregulated ``soft money'' contributions
from corporations, unions and wealthy individuals. The spending
does not count against a candidate's spending limit because the ads
are ostensibly for public education by independent political
entities rather than to benefit individual candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Texas software billionaire Sam Wyly was able to weigh in on
Bush's behalf before the 13 GOP contests on March 7 with a $2.5
million privately financed advertising blitz funneled through an
organization he created, ``Republicans for Clean Air.'' Wyly's
television ads in New York, Vermont, Ohio and California belittled
the environmental protection record of Bush's hard-charging rival
for the GOP nomination, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   W. Russell Neuman, a professor of communications at the
University of Pennsylvania's Annenberg School of Communications,
says allies of Bush and Gore are preparing to hit the nation's
television airwaves with just such ``issue ads.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The cannons are loaded,'' says Neuman, a communications
scholar who studies campaign advertising. ``Both sides are going to
launch _ and launch soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Allies of Republican and Democratic candidates and other
independent organizations already have spent or committed more than
$114 million for issue ads in the 1999-2000 presidential election
cycle. The spending far outpaces comparable spending at this point
in the last two presidential campaigns, according to a study
released Friday by the Annenberg Public Policy Center at the
University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore and Bush campaigns are now engaged in a stare-down over
which candidate will start the barrage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore challenged Bush last week to ``reject the use of soft money
to run issue ads'' as part of his bid to court McCain's
reform-minded supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats will ``not run any issue ads paid for by soft money
unless and until the Republican party uses money for advertising''
in an effort to avert ``the ad war arms race,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush rejected Gore's offer, challenging the vice president
instead to address Democrats' questionable fund-raising practices
in 1996 such as accepting $2.8 million in donations from foreigners
that was subsequently returned and Gore's participation in a 1996
fund raiser at a Buddhist temple in California where $55,000 of
$160,000 in donations was funneled through ``straw donors'' such as
Buddhist monks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clear the air on some serious charges'' stemming from such
``fundraising abuses,'' the Texas governor urged Gore. ``It is
important for Americans to know whether the current campaign
finance laws have been obeyed and enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are preparing to copy their approach in 1996. One
possible Democratic target: Bush's failure to return $25,000 in
foreign money funneled to his gubernatorial campaign through the
Republican National Committee in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in fighting form,'' vows Backus, the Democrats'
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats expect the first salvo in the post-primary phase
of the campaign to be launched by the centrist Republican
Leadership Council. The quick-firing independent operation aired
advertising during the Republican primary campaign that challenged
magazine publisher Steve Forbes to drop negative attacks against
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The timetable is ``sooner rather than later,'' says spokesman
Matt Well.
</P>
<P>
   Grover Norquist, of Americans for Tax Reform, also vows an
activist advertising campaign that could help Bush. The
organization, which placed $4 million in ads in seven states last
summer, has joined Bush in calling for the federal government to
repeal ``the Gore gas tax'' _ the 4.3 cent-per-gallon fuel surtax
adopted in 1993 when Gore cast the deciding vote in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans note that whatever they do, the Democrats allies in
organized labor have already launched broadcast campaign ads in
selected congressional districts on behalf of labor-backed issues
being debated in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The ads by the 13-million member organization, part of its $46
million election campaign effort this year, are tied to looming
votes such as opposition to normalized trade status for China and
support for stronger legal rights for patients served by health
maintenance organizations, says AFL-CIO spokeswoman Deborah Dion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
