A9959 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-IMMIGRANTS-CENSUS-HNS     03-17 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANTS-CENSUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IMMIGRANTS URGED TO PARTICIPATE IN CENSUS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VENISE WAGNER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In an attempt to prevent an anticipated
undercount of immigrants and others in the U.S. Census, immigrant
rights groups in the San Francisco area are working closely with
census officials to encourage minorities and immigrants to
participate in the national survey.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of reprisals from the Immigration and Naturalization
Service, limited proficiency in English and a lack of understanding
of the census pose major obstacles in making sure the count of
immigrants and minorities is accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone, every immigrant, whether documented or undocumented,
should participate in this census,'' said Mark Silverman, a lawyer
with the Immigrant Legal Resource Center in San Francisco. ``We
have ironclad guarantees from the INS that census information is
confidential.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law prohibits the Census Bureau from sharing information
with any government agency or individual.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations participating in the outreach campaign with the
Census Bureau include the Immigrant Legal Resource Center, the
California Rural Legal Assistance, the Asian Law Caucus, Asians for
Affirmative Action, the California Institute for Rural Studies and
the Northern California Coalition for Immigrants Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Language may keep some immigrants from filling out the forms.
Translators and other census workers will be on hand at the
bureau's 40 Questionnaire Assistance Centers around San Francisco
to help people fill them out. The forms are due April 1.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, census takers will comb the area's homeless
shelters and less conventional homes, such as trailers, to make
sure those residents are counted. Starting April 27, census takers
will try to collect data from residents that did not respond to the
original form.
</P>
<P>
   Billions of federal dollars, whose distribution is based on
census figures, are at stake. In the 1990 census, officials
estimate they missed about 835,000 people in California, which cost
the state close to $2.2 billion in federal
</P>
<P>
   According to a Census Bureau study released Thursday, an
undercount similar to 1990 could cost California $5 billion in
federal funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The census is about ... money and justice,'' said Johanna
Silva, who is coordinating the U.S. Census Bureau's outreach
efforts with organizations here. ``This is about transportation,
housing, school lunches, WIC (Women Infants and Children). These
are services we depend on as a city. Participating in the census
guarantees you'll get your fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   Those most likely to be undercounted are the poor or non-English
speaking or both, the very groups most in need of these services,
said Isabel Alegria, the regional census director for the Mexican
American Legal Defense and Educational Fund, or MALDEF.
</P>
</TEXT>
