<P>
   CIA-PROPAGANDA (Undated) _ ) _ Watch the 1955 animated version
of ``Animal Farm,'' and you'll notice the ending is different than
in the book. Another example of Hollywood butchering great
literature? Yes, but in this case the film's secret producer was
the Central Intelligence Agency. The CIA, it seems, was worried
that the public might be too influenced by Orwell's
pox-on-both-their-houses critique of Capitalism and Communism. So
after George Orwell's death in 1950, agents were dispatched to buy
the film rights to ``Animal Farm'' from his widow in order to make
its message more overtly anti-Communist. Rewriting the end of
Animal Farm is just one example of the often absurd lengths to
which the CIA went between 1947 and 1967 that are recounted in a
new book. By Laurence Zuckerman. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (With an ``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PAINTINGS-PHOTOS (Undated) _ When photography first arrived in
the middle of the 19th century, with all its vaunted truthfulness,
painters and sculptors did not like it one bit. They were
threatened. They were miffed. They were scornful. And finally they
took the matter into their own hands. They turned photography
inside out. A look at the influence of painting on photography. By
Sarah Boxer. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY-FUTURE (Undated) _ Why should a sober warning about
technology's dangers be treated as a revelation after being
featured on the cover of the April issue of Wired magazine? In the
last week, Bill Joy, the author of the article, ``Why the Future
Doesn't Need Us,'' has been interviewed on television, written
about in newspapers, and argued about on the Internet. Yet there is
not a single point in the essay that has not already been made
elsewhere. By Edward Rothstein. (975 words)
</P>
<P>
   (With an ``a'' code)
</P>
