<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9976 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     03-17 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA SHOULD AVOID SHOOTING ITSELF IN THE FOOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With friends like Wayne LaPierre, the National Rifle Association
doesn't need enemies.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre is the NRA executive vice president who suggested that
President Clinton sort of likes the idea of people getting shot to
death because the killings help Clinton promote his anti-gun
political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   There are politicians who could fairly be accused of such
coldhearted cynicism; Clinton isn't one of them. The president
often behaves like a manipulative, duplicitous, prevaricating creep
_ but he owns one of the great bleeding hearts of our time.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about the nation's mourner in chief, a man who
tears up at the drop of a hat and who won two presidential
elections by convincing voters that he cares about their problems
and their ``needs.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is one thing that most Americans are willing to give
the president credit for, it's compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Disheartening though it may be to those of us who believe that
the right to bear arms is every bit as important as all the other
rights guaranteed by the U.S. Constitution, the public's perception
is that Clinton and the anti-gun crowd occupy the moral high ground
on this issue. The argument about guns is no longer an intellectual
disagreement over nuances of the Second Amendment; it's an
emotion-drenched showdown over life and death.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton talks about guns, he surrounds himself with gun
violence victims and their loved ones. He insists that gun control
can save lives _ especially the lives of innocent children _ and
professes bewilderment that any reasonable person could fail to see
the value of more and more gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   The other side finds itself defending a 208-year-old legal
precept that is vague enough to allow vast differences of opinion
about its meaning. When that defense is left to a spokesman as
combative and controversial as LaPierre, it's easy to see why some
folks jump to the conclusion that he is representing a dangerous
army of gun-happy fanatics.
</P>
<P>
   I should point out that I'm not a gun owner and have no
immediate plans to become one _ although I absolutely believe that
the decision to own or not own a gun should be mine, not the
federal government's. We could argue all day about the Second
Amendment's reference to a ``well regulated militia'' but there is
no ambiguity in the part that says that ``the right of the people
to keep and bear arms shall not be infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it all depends on your definition of ``infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the question at hand. Do requirements such as
trigger locks and background checks and waiting periods
``infringe'' upon the right to bear arms? If so, are such
infringements reasonable when weighed against the recurring menace
of gun violence?
</P>
<P>
   What I find objectionable about most proposed gun laws is that
they miss the point. If we pass a law requiring trigger locks, we
pat ourselves on the back and say, ``OK, now we'll save some
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe we will. Maybe trigger locks will prevent some deadly
accidents, and maybe that will compensate for the times when a gun
owner can't defend himself against a criminal because his gun has a
trigger lock and the criminal's gun doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   But all the trigger locks in the world won't stop an armed
robber from gunning down a convenience store clerk, and all the
background checks and waiting periods that society can devise won't
stop the bad guys from buying guns on the street and using them
against law-abiding citizens. The real problem isn't guns _ it's
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   We can pass gun laws until the cows come home, and criminals
will find a way to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   But most Americans don't want to hear about all that. They want
to do something _ anything _ that might prevent one more child from
being gunned down in a classroom.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe it's time for the NRA and other gun-rights proponents
to compromise, to go along with some reasonable restrictions.
Otherwise, a frustrated public might eventually be persuaded to
support far more drastic remedies.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
