<HEADLINE>
&HT;     N.Y. ATTORNEY GENERAL SEEKS TO PUT PRESSURE ON GUN MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JAY JOCHNOWITZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Attorney General Eliot Spitzer is calling for a
national coalition of governments whose firearm purchasing power he
hopes will pressure the gun industry to adopt a ``code of conduct''
that would include making safer weapons.
</P>
<P>
   An industry spokesman called the effort ``naive'' and
``ill-conceived,'' and said manufacturers would not produce the
kind of weapons or adopt practices Spitzer seeks.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate matter, the Clinton administration announced
Friday that Smith &AMP; Wesson, the nation's largest gun maker, agreed
to provide safety locks on handguns within two months.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's announcement, made Thursday, came in a week of
increasing support for tougher gun controls in New York. Gov.
George Pataki, a Republican, called Wednesday for such measures as
mandatory trigger locks, raising the age for handgun sales from 18
to 21, instant background checks on buyers at gun shows, banning
assault weapons and ``fingerprinting'' by manufacturers of the
unique markings each gun's barrel leaves on a bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are preparing a similar proposal, and, while Senate
and Assembly Republicans prefer stiffer penalties for gun-related
crimes, they are looking at an assault weapons ban and trigger lock
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer proposes to use economics instead of politics as the
weapon of choice. Police departments and other government agencies
by about one-quarter of the handguns sold in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Stating that governments have so far tended to rely on laws or
lawsuits, Spitzer said, ``Today, we are offering a third way, and
that is for governments ... to use their immense financial leverage
to encourage gun companies to do what is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the key elements of the code are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Discontinuing models or features popular with criminals, such
as fingerprint resistant guns and pistols that can accept magazines
with more than 10 rounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Including a second hidden serial number on handguns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Internal and external locking devices, safety disconnects that
make pistols impossible to fire, and designs that make guns
difficult to use by children under six.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ceasing sales to dealers who sell at gun shows or whose
weapons turn up in a disproportionate number of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Delfry, president of the National Shooting Sports
Foundation, a Newtown, Conn.-based trade group, called it ``a very
naive code of conduct'' and described several measures as little
more than window dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Delfry, who has been involved in discussions between Spitzer's
office and manufacturers since last summer, said criminals would
easily find hidden serial numbers and can alter barrel markings
with a file. Nearly 95 percent of all guns now made have trigger
locks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because some safety designs could make a gun useless in an
emergency, he noted, the code has exemptions for law enforcement.
That means, Delfry said, that officials would not do business with
a manufacturer unless it produces guns for the general population
that no police officer would use.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that any honest, responsible government official
is going to sign on to this document because it's too
hypocritical,'' said Delfry. And, he said, the ban on transactions
with certain dealers could lead to restraint-of-trade lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, however, is sending letters this week to President
Clinton, the mayors of the 100 largest U.S. cities, all the
governors and attorneys general of all 50 states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
