<SLUG> BC-TRUCKS-PICKUPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOUNTY OF PICKUPS TO BOGGLE THE MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A pickup truck zips by you on the highway and you barely notice.
Oh, just another pickup truck, you think.
</P>
<P>
   On that level, a pickup truck is a pickup truck is a . . .
</P>
<P>
   But suppose that one day you decide that you need one . . . or
an SUV?
</P>
<P>
   Well here's some advice. It's free, and it might save you from
being overwhelmed when you go out looking at trucks. Do your
homework first.
</P>
<P>
   That's it.
</P>
<P>
   Homework? Yes. Because buying a truck or SUV can be a lot more
complicated than walking onto a lot and saying, ``I'll take that
one.'' Of course, that's exactly what you eventually want to do,
except that you want to know all about ``that one'' before you
point at it.
</P>
<P>
   The configurations available in trucks and SUVs can boggle the
mind. A good bit of self-evaluation of your wants, needs and
pocketbook can cut down a lot of time and frustration in trying to
make those decisions at a dealer's.
</P>
<P>
   For example: Let's say you want a Ford SUV. Do you want small
(the soon-to-be-available Escape), regular (Explorer), large
(Expedition), or extra large (Excursion)? Or would you prefer a
2-door Explorer Sport or the new Explorer Sport Trac (is it an SUV
with a small pickup bed? Or is it a pickup with an extra-large
four-door cab and small bed)?
</P>
<P>
   Are you confused yet?
</P>
<P>
   We haven't even begun to talk about two-wheel-drive vs.
four-wheel-drive or trim levels. Explorer, alone, comes in 13
configurations.
</P>
<P>
   If you walk into a dealership big enough to offer all the
variations on these themes, instead of a symphony, that sound in
your ears will be a cacophony of confusion.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, we'll offer a recent trip to Liberty Chevrolet in
Wakefield. Salesman Jim Marino provided a guided tour through the
Chevy line, along with some interesting tidbits.
</P>
<P>
   One: Trucks (including SUVs and minivans) make up 85 percent of
the dealership's sales.
</P>
<P>
   Two: Sales seem to be rising at approximately the same rate as
the price of gas.
</P>
<P>
   Three: I saw sticker prices from $12,815 (a base S-10 with the
radio deleted) to $50,000 (one of the custom conversion vans the
dealership is renowned for selling).
</P>
<P>
   The points here are that trucks are continuing to outsell cars
and bigger continues to be the better seller.
</P>
<P>
   Marino was overseeing the maneuvering of a 2000 Suburban
($44,000) onto the showroom floor. ``That sticker doesn't even
include all the extras you see on it,'' he says, gesturing to the
ski bag attached to the roof rack, the custom bicycle rack attached
to the trailer hitch and a protective bra on the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff is all there so you can see what's available as
dealer-installed options,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For all the time it took to place the Suburban in line on the
showroom floor, don't expect it to stay there long.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last Suburban we have out of 12,'' said Marino of
the new millenium edition of the heavyweight champ of the Chevy
lineup. ``We sold five before any arrived, then we had more three
sold before the next shipment of five arrived and two more went out
the day they did come in.. And these weren't stripped: They were
$42-43,000 units.'' Still, that price was without the optional
moonroof now offered on the Suburbans for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Chevrolet redesigned its full-sized pickup for the
first time in more than a decade, a big step because the model was
a solid No. 2 seller in the market (behind Ford's perennial No. 1
F-150).
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the old C/K designations, the Chevy pickups now are
called Silverado (formerly the top trim line on the older body
styles).
</P>
<P>
   Want one? Which one? Here's where you realize that all pickups
aren't created equally and no two on the lot are the same.
</P>
<P>
   Let's run down a checklist of decisions to be made in picking a
pickup. Each choice is much more significant than ``paper or
plastic?''
</P>
<P>
   1. Regular cab or extended cab (all extended cabs soon will have
four doors).
</P>
<P>
   2. Box (that's the bed). Three choices here: Fleetside long box
(97.6 inches _ long enough for that 8-foot sheet of plywood or
wallboard); Fleetside short box (78.7 inches long) or Sportside box
(also 78.7 inches long, but narrowed considerably for the flared
rear fenders. Of course, you can buy the chassis-only version and
send it out for a custom box.
</P>
<P>
   3. Trim level. There's standard, an LS upgrade, and on top-end
models, an LT (as in leather) option.
</P>
<P>
   4. 1500 series (1/2 ton) or 2500 series (3/4 ton).
</P>
<P>
   5. Two-wheel drive or 4WD.
</P>
<P>
   6. Transmission. 5-speed manual, 4-speed automatic, heavy duty
versions of each are optional on the 3/4-ton trucks.
</P>
<P>
   7. Engine. Vortec 4300 V-6, 4800 V-8, 5300 V-8, 6000 V-8. If the
numbers are confusing, move the decimal point three places to the
left and you have the size in liters: 4.3, 4.8, 5.3 and 6.0.
</P>
<P>
   8. 2WD or 4x4.
</P>
<P>
   9. Dress-up accessories. Sliding rear window, running boards,
splash guards, tonneau cover, bed liner, off-road package.
</P>
<P>
   10. Suspension. Standard, heavy-duty, off-road, ride-control.
</P>
<P>
   11. Packages. Trailering, off-road, snow-plow prep.
</P>
<P>
   12. And more: You do have to talk such minor details as colors,
extra doors, perhaps a sliding rear window or traction contol in
addition to four-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   So the next time you see a pickup truck, you might be looking at
a one-of-its-kind vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, about that homework . . .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1558EST &QL; 
