<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0012 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TEENSINGERS-TEX     03-17 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENSINGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLONDE VS. BLONDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
and MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was confusing enough when Christina Aguilera and Britney
Spears were both nominated for the Best New Artist Grammy this year
(Aguilera won), but now this blond-teen singer thing is getting out
of control. Spears has a new single, ``Oops ... I Did It Again''
scheduled to hit the airwaves this month, and fellow blonde Jessica
Simpson has a duet due out (''Where You Are'') that we expect to be
huge. Aguilera's ``What a Girl Wants'' is solidly in the Billboard
Top 20; then there's LeAnn Rimes, who's practically old-school by
now even though she can't drink legally, and Mandy Moore, the baby
of the bunch. With all these under-20 blond singers out there, we
thought we'd provide a reader service and sort them all out. So we
did.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BRITNEY SPEARS
</P>
<P>
   Age: 18
</P>
<P>
   Major-label debut: ``... Baby One More Time,'' 1998
</P>
<P>
   Signature song: ``... Baby One More Time''
</P>
<P>
   Distinguishing characteristic: To quote Teri Hatcher on a
``Seinfeld'' episode, ``They're real _ and they're spectacular.''
At least that's close to what Britney says, when discussing her
breasts, which are rumored to have been surgically augmented.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like: Amateur night at a karaoke bar.
</P>
<P>
   Before she was a star: Appeared on ``The New Mickey Mouse Club''
at age 11, along with such future stars as ``Felicity's'' Keri
Russell and 'N Sync's Justin Timberlake; ``Star Search'' champion
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Best move: Being the first of the pop blondes out of the gate
makes the others look like imitators.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest mistake: Planning to record cover of the Rolling Stones'
(''I Can't Get No) Satisfaction'' is going to cause arguments
between her fans and their parents _ and in some cases,
grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``I have really strong morals, and just because I look
sexy on the cover of Rolling Stone doesn't mean that I'm a naughty
girl.'' (From People Almanac.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTINA AGUILERA
</P>
<P>
   Age: 19
</P>
<P>
   Major-label debut: ``Christina Aguilera,'' 1999
</P>
<P>
   Signature song: ``Genie in a Bottle''
</P>
<P>
   Distinguishing characteristic: Near-platinum hair coloring makes
her blonder than the other blondes.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like: Typical assembly-line pop. Beneath the gloss,
though, is a fairly impressive voice.
</P>
<P>
   Before she was a star: Appeared on ``Star Search'' at age 8;
performed for two years on ``The New Mickey Mouse Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Best move: Appearing genuinely surprised and humbled when she
won the Best New Artist Grammy. Did NOT lip-sync on the recent
American Music Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest mistake: Not performing at the Grammys, letting Britney
Spears grab the spotlight instead.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``Being (young) does put more pressure on you if you want
to be taken seriously as an artist. ... You have to be way sharper
than anybody else because people expect you to be this bubble-gum
airhead.'' (From Fort Worth Star-Telegram files.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MANDY MOORE
</P>
<P>
   Age: 15; turns 16 April 10.
</P>
<P>
   Major-label debut: ``So Real,'' 1999
</P>
<P>
   Signature song: ``Candy''
</P>
<P>
   Distinguishing characteristic: Younger than the other blondes.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like: She thinks Britney Spears is a roots artist.
</P>
<P>
   Before she was a star: Was known as ``National Anthem Girl'' in
Orlando, Fla.,
</P>
<P>
   because she sang ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' before so many
major sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   Best move: Learning to play guitar and planning to write her own
songs.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest mistake: None yet, although admiration of Mariah Carey
could lead to critical disdain.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``I don't feel I've missed out on anything about growing
up because I feel so fortunate. There are so many kids that would
love to be doing what I'm doing!'' (From unofficial Web site,
AmandaMoore.com.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   JESSICA SIMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Age: 19
</P>
<P>
   Major-label debut: ``Sweet Kisses,'' 1999
</P>
<P>
   Signature song: ``I Wanna Love You Forever''
</P>
<P>
   Distinguishing characteristics: A Dallas native, Simpson is 5
foot 3 and is dating Nick Lachey from boy group 98 Degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like: Celine Dion on the single; Mariah Carey on the rest
of the album
</P>
<P>
   Before she was a star: Developed singing skills in church;
auditioned for ``The New Mickey Mouse Club'' at 12; worked for
three years on a small-label gospel album, only to have the company
fold.
</P>
<P>
   Best move: Touring with 98 Degrees, which helped her hook up
with Lachey personally and professionally. Their duet ``Where You
Are,'' on the soundtrack to the upcoming movie ``Here on Earth''
(starring Fort Worth's Chris Klein), is poised to be a huge hit.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest mistake: None yet, but blending in with the teen crowd
rather than capitalizing on a distinctive voice is a bad trend.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``I feel like I can bring a freshness, no matter what age
the person listening to my music is. And I think that freshness and
that innocence is something that is missing from a lot of young
female singers. I'm certainly not denying that I'm young, but I'm
not fluff.'' (From official Web site.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   LEANN RIMES
</P>
<P>
   Age: 17
</P>
<P>
   Major-label debut: ``Blue,'' 1996
</P>
<P>
   Signature song: ``How Do I Live''
</P>
<P>
   Distinguishing characteristics: New hairstyle gives her a more
mature, cosmopolitan look than teen peers. Plus, she sings country;
they sing pop.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like: Patsy Cline in high school
</P>
<P>
   Before she was a star: A longtime Garland, Texas, resident,
Rimes performed at Johnnie High's Country Music Revue in Arlington;
appeared on ``Star Search'' at age 8
</P>
<P>
   Best move: Singing ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' at a Texas
Rangers game, which led songwriter/disc jockey Bill Mack to send
her the song ``Blue,'' her first hit.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest mistake: Remaking Prince's ``Purple Rain.'' Some great
songs should remain untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``People are going to criticize anything anyone does, no
matter what, so I don't let it get to me anymore. I used to think,
`Oh my God, I'm so bad.' Now I'm like, `Whatever.' '' (From
``InStyle'' magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
