<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW PROTEST, BUT MOST ISRAELIS POSITIVE ABOUT POPE'S VISIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Not everyone is happy that Pope John Paul II is
traveling to Israel next week on a historic peace mission.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 other journalists attending a Religion and Media 2000
Conference in Jerusalem before the pope's visit ran into a few
sign-carrying demonstrators Thursday outside the office of Israel
Meir Lau, chief rabbi of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting into herd-journalism mode, the reporters among us began
questioning the bearded men who were carrying hand-drawn signs,
including one decorated with a picture of a cross with an X drawn
through it. Other signs were decorated with the Star of David and
said ``Cross Out'' and ``Pagan Worship Out.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators are clearly in the minority. Yellow and white
papal banners are all over Jerusalem streets. A Gallup poll done
for Israel's Interreligious Coordinating Council indicates that
nearly 60 percent of adult Israelis see the pope's visit as
positive. Only 12 percent view it as negative.
</P>
<P>
   But those few are vocal.
</P>
<P>
   The sign-carriers said they were a part of the Committee to Stop
the Visit of the Pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a group of people from all kinds of organizations, and
we have already come here several times to demonstrate,'' said
Teran Pollock, one of the protesters. ``We hope to have thousands
next week demonstrating, if the police will let us.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the demonstrators was Baruch Merzeo, who said two of his
sisters died in the explosion of a bomb planted in Jerusalem. He
blames the terrorist act on Yasser Arafat, the Palestine Liberation
Organization leader who is seeking a peaceful agreement with Israel
over a Palestinian homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators said they are particularly unhappy that the
pope, when he makes a pilgrimage to Bethlehem, will meet with
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also can't understand why the chief rabbi, who was a part
of the Holocaust, will be greeting the pope,'' said Pollock, who
said he is a member of Kach, a right-wing group.
</P>
<P>
   While emphasizing the demonstrators' freedom to protest, Lau
said during a news conference that he expects his talk with the
pope to be a historic moment of reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   The bearded rabbi, wearing a large-brimmed black hat, said that
Israel is a democracy and that many who are concerned about the
pope's visit remember the history of persecution of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appreciate that this was the first pope to ask forgiveness
from the Almighty for the past sins of the church,'' Lau said,
referring to last Sunday's prayerful papal apology for Catholic
Church transgressions against Jews and others during the past 2,000
years. ``You must be a great man to ask for forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Lau, who survived the Holocaust and, like Pope John Paul, is a
native of Poland, was among those expressing regret that the pope
did not specifically mention the Holocaust in his apology.
</P>
<P>
   But Lau has high hopes that John Paul will specifically
apologize for the Roman Catholic Church not being more outspoken
against the Holocaust when the pope visits Yad Vashem, the
Holocaust memorial in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The two have personal ties. John Paul knew Lau's grandfather,
who was a rabbi in Poland. The pope secretly studied for the
priesthood while working under Nazi occupation in Krakow.
</P>
<P>
   Lau visited the pope at John Paul's summer residence in
Castelgandolfo near Rome as a preliminary to next week's visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shared many memories of our experiences of the Holocaust,''
said Lau, whose father, also a distinguished rabbi, died at the
Treblinka death camp in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   No pope has ever visited Israel's chief rabbi on his home turf
in Jerusalem. The rabbi said it will be a far-reaching symbol that
the pope recognizes Israel as a state and respects the Jewish
people.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
