<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Let's Eat! But can the cabaret
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ This past week I was rejoicing with Sister
Sharion.
</P>
<P>
   The week before I had mourning for her _ and for me, too,
believing what I'd heard to be true.
</P>
<P>
   What I'd heard was that Sister Sharion had closed down her
little soul food cafe, Let's Eat.
</P>
<P>
   No more of her turnip greens and hot water cornbread . . . peas
and rice . . . mashed potatoes and gravy . . . her meat loaf, fried
chicken, pot roast, catfish . . .
</P>
<P>
   It was bad news for everybody who loves down-home, country
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the good news:
</P>
<P>
   The rumor was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Sharion had been under the weather for a couple of a
days. As a result, she closed down until she was feeling better.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's just fine, all smiles as always. The lunch was
luscious, as usual, on the day I stopped by.
</P>
<P>
   I had a serving of catfish, yams, peas and rice -- what some
call Hoppin' John -- and a couple of pieces of her hot water
cornbread, which some call the best in town.
</P>
<P>
   Good food, good crowd. You'll see most everybody you know at
Let's Eat Cafe, from the country club crowd to people from the
projects.
</P>
<P>
   If I were running for office, that's where I'd do my
campaigning. Politics and pot licker, not a bad combination.
</P>
<P>
   But as good as the Let's Eat Cafe is, I've always thought I
could improve on it.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's fine as far as it goes. But why not go whole hog in a
place where no telling how many hogs have been sacrificed simply
for seasoning?
</P>
<P>
   Awhile back I put this idea to Sister Sharion:
</P>
<P>
   First we'd get a license to sell influential beverages of the
wit-enhancing variety.
</P>
<P>
   Next we'd open up the back part of the building for candlelight
dinners, a special place where ladies and gents could be together
for a special evening.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we'd have a band playing toe-tapping tunes for
dancing. Best way I know of to work up an appetite.
</P>
<P>
   Put it all together and what do you have? A soul food gold mine,
the likes of which we we could franchise all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   All I was asking was for Sister Sharion to give it a try.
</P>
<P>
   What she gave me instead was a hard look.
</P>
<P>
   Put it all together, she said, and she knew what we'd have:
</P>
<P>
   A cabaret!
</P>
<P>
   Sister Sharion, being the good church-going lady that she is,
wanted no part of a cabaret.
</P>
<P>
   But, as I tried to explain, we wouldn't have to call it cabaret.
</P>
<P>
   The name would be the same. Well, almost. We'd simply add on to
the existing sign.
</P>
<P>
   Make it: Let's Eat, Drink and Be Merry.
</P>
<P>
   She gave me another hard look. After that, I gave up.
</P>
<P>
   So it is when the proprietor of the establishment is the soul of
piety.
</P>
<P>
   Looks like I'll have be satisfied with the Let's Eat Cafe the
way it is.
</P>
<P>
   Turnip greens and cornbread . . . peas and rice . . . mashed
potatoes and gravy . . . meat loaf, fried chicken, pot roast,
catfish . . .
</P>
<P>
   Oh well. I guess I can live with that.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice)
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
