<HEADER>
A0017 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TRUCKS-COMBATT-BOS &LR;      03-17 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUCKS-COMBATT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ALMOST TOO-PERFECT TRUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The military is great for creating acronyms that make their way
into our everyday lives.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, ASAP (as soon as possible) and NLT (not later
than) were part of my first orders for reporting to basic training.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, military vehicles such as the venerable Jeep and
Humvee, tried and proven by military use, have become popular
crossover civilian successes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ford unveiled a military adaptation of its heavy duty
F-350 Super Duty Crew Cab pickup complete with the appropriate
acronym COMBATT (Commercially Based Tactical Truck). Just
wondering: Does a Ford poohbah think of the acronym and adapt a
vehicle to fit it or does a team develop a vehicle and then have
brain(?)storming sessions for the name?
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious that this vehicle will give a whole new meaning to
``Built Ford Tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurminder Bedi, vice president, Ford North American Truck, said,
``Ford has a long, proud history of supplying vehicles to the US
military and other branches of government. In addition, this
program allows us to explore technologies that we may be able to
adapt to our regular production trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Really now? Couldn't this become the ultimate Urban as opposed
to the Suburban?
</P>
<P>
   I can see plenty of civilian applications that would make this a
sensational daily driver.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, it will have a powerful onboard computer with an
advanced global positioning satellite navigation system, night
vision system, collision warning system and upgraded electrical
system, proving 12-volt, 24-volt and 110-volt power.
</P>
<P>
   Wow. I can use the computer to write stories while sitting in
traffic on the Central Artery. After all, I see other folks
applying makeup, reading books &AMP; papers or talking on the phone as
they inch along.
</P>
<P>
   The advanced GPS means never having to say I got lost on the way
to an assignment. (Well, it means I'd at least know where I am,
though not necessarily where I'm going).
</P>
<P>
   Night vision. It will certainly help spot and avoid those deer
and coyotes that are starting to dot our urban landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   The collision warning system should be a great addition.
Imagine! It will go off a split second before I get rammed by a Big
Dig 18-wheeler whose driver has been highway hypnotized while
trying to set the records for most loads of fill delivered in an
eight-hour shift.
</P>
<P>
   And imagine the stereo system you could install with that
110-volt electrical system!
</P>
<P>
   The truck also can be outfitted with a covered pickup box and
seats for carrying troops (in this case reporters). I can imagine
the paper renting out this truck to convey its army of reporters
and photographers for such big events as the Ryder Cup, political
conventions and the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   I'm starting to think I want to open a dealership for this
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   It also will have upgraded suspension, electronically controlled
high performance shock absorbers, supplemental air springs, a
central tire inflation system and 37-inch tires with a run-flat
capability.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I'm signing up for a long-term road
test through Big Dig country. It sounds like a match for Boston's
spring potholes.
</P>
<P>
   You can't doubt it's perfect. Ford even says ``The vehicle's
ride height, tire pressure and firmness automatically adjust to the
challenging dirving conditions a military vehicle encounters.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration truck is said to have met or exceeded the
ratings of existing Army vehicles while carrying greater payloads.
It's designed to be able to ford 30-inch deep water and operate in
temperatures from 50 below zero to 120 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   I have some questions for Ford before I trade in my 1961 Falcon
on this baby.
</P>
<P>
   1. How much a month to lease one?
</P>
<P>
   2. Will it run on regular gas?
</P>
<P>
   3. Does the camouflage paint job mean no one can see me coming?
</P>
<P>
   4. Can I get it with heated seats?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1605EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
