<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-ELECT-650(TRIM     03-17 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ELECT-650(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPECTING POLITICAL FIREWORKS, TAIWAN PREPARES FOR ELECTIONS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Taiwan's voters prepared to vote for president
on Saturday for only the second time ever in a contest that has
drawn menacing threats from mainland China and is likely to produce
the weakest, most divided government since Chiang Kai-shek's
Nationalists fled to the island in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   At fervent rallies that brought hundreds of thousands of
flag-waving people into the capital's streets tonight, the three
main candidates made their final appeals in a race that appeared
too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   The contenders are Vice President Lien Chan, of the ruling
Nationalist Party; James Soong, a former Nationalist official
running as an independent; and Chen Shui-bian of the Democratic
Progressives, the country's main opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polling has not been allowed in the final 10 days,
adding to the suspense of an election that has been fought with all
the exuberance of a young democracy facing profound choices.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging over the campaign were heavy handed warnings from
Beijing, which considers Taiwan a wayward region and said it will
go to war if the island indefinitely delays talks on reunification.
</P>
<P>
   The outgoing Nationalist president, Lee Teng-hui, has outraged
Chinese officials with his insistence on Taiwan's equal status with
the mainland, a position that is widely shared here. But in recent
days, Beijing has pointedly attacked Chen, the opposition party
challenger, warning that his victory would be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Alone among the candidates, Chen long championed a Taiwanese
declaration of independence, but he now says it is unnecessary
because Taiwan is effectively sovereign. While he has tried to
press an anti-corruption theme, he has had to spend much of his
campaign trying to assure voters that he will not act recklessly
and will seek peace.
</P>
<P>
   Given China's deep suspicions, his election would open a period
of serious tension, anxiously watched in Washington because the
United States has pledged to help defend Taiwan and would be drawn
into a cross-straits war.
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalist candidate, Lien, is in serious danger of losing
in a three-way, winner-take-all race that has disastrously divided
the party's traditional majority. With a wide sense that Chen was
gaining ground, Lien started trying to scare voters with warnings
that electing Chen would court a military attack.
</P>
<P>
   Holding high Lien's hand at Friday night's rally, Lee continued
this line of attack, shouting that Chen ``is inexperienced and
everything he says will give jitters to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chen's generally ardent supporters, including many younger
citizens who yearn for a fresh and cleaner government as well as an
independent Taiwanese identity, have not been deterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taiwan, stand up!'' was a loud chant at the Chen rally Friday
night, the largest and most frenzied of the three, which spilled
far into the streets from a packed football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Considered by many to be a weak candidate, Lien, who has an
American doctorate in political science and has held several top
government posts, has offered little more in his campaign than
appeals to experience and stability.
</P>
<P>
   After being pushed aside by his former mentor, Lee, Soong, once
a Nationalist stalwart, has made an independent run, attacking the
corruption of the party he long served and billing himself as a
more competent leader than Lien.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Soong, who also has an American doctorate in
politics, is more willing to discuss the mainland's core principle
of ``one China.'' He says he would be the best able to negotiate
with the mainland, but the independence-leaning supporters of Chen
fear he would sell out Taiwan's interests.
</P>
<P>
   All three candidates say they will seek to broaden economic ties
with the mainland. But whether any of them can meet Beijing's
demands for unity talks is unclear, since the vast majority of
Taiwan voters prefer their current status of undeclared
independence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the Nationalists, who have firmly ruled Taiwan through 51
years of dictatorship and then a democracy they ushered in, the
election is a wrenching turning point that could transform the
island's politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is focusing so much on the cross-straits problem,''
said Steven M. Goldstein, an expert on Taiwan politics at Smith
College. ``But no matter who gets elected, there's going to be a
constitutional crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if its own candidate, Vice President Lien Chan, gains a
plurality on Saturday, the formerly impregnable Nationalist Party
will be weakened and will face new challenges to its vast business
holdings and freewheeling political deals.
</P>
<P>
   Both Chen and Soong have gained from their campaigning against
``black gold'' in politics, the term here for the business
manipulations, alliances with mobsters and vote-buying that have
plagued Taiwanese politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get rid of the corruption and organized crime and
vote-buying,'' said Lu Chiu-chien, 42, a social worker from Keelung
city who was furiously waving a Chen flag here Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Soong's credibility was hurt by evidence, released by the
Nationalists, that he diverted party money to personal accounts in
the past. But supporters like Mary Lu, a 45-year-old housewife who
was out cheering for Soong, say he has been persecuted by a
vindictive Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Chen or Soong, if elected, would have to contend with a
Nationalist majority in the legislature, which is not up for
reelection now.
</P>
<P>
   Also, though he is stepping down as president, Lee has said he
wants to serve out his remaining one and a half years as chairman
of the Nationalist Party, a position that has arguably been more
powerful than the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, the same person will no longer be both president and
chairman of the party,'' said John Hsieh, Taiwan-born director of
the center for Asian Studies at the University of South Carolina.
``A serious confrontation is likely.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The campaign has brought out festering animosities within the
Nationalist Party, and between those who basically favor Taiwan's
independence and the majority who want to leave well enough alone.
</P>
<P>
   Many supporters of Chen and Soong are united in disgust at what
they call the continued corruption of the Nationalists under Lee.
</P>
<P>
   But attitudes toward Taiwan's independence remain the
fundamental cleavage in the electorate, said Hsieh, an expert on
public opinion here.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng Yin-fu, a 41-year-old furniture seller who was wildly
waving a Chen Shui-bian flag at the stadium Friday night, expressed
the attitude that China _ and some worried Taiwanese _ dread to
hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spiritually and morally I support independence,'' he said.
``But as for the actual action, we can wait for a while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
