<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE WORKERS FORM VIRTUAL UNION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Clever ideas are sometimes born out of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Courtney was a contractor at Microsoft and got upset two
years ago when the software industry successfully lobbied the
Washington Department of Labor and Industries to allow high-tech
companies to pay straight time instead of time-and-a-half overtime
to workers who earn more than $27.63 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Microsoft contractors, the former Seattle test
engineer was used to working 60- and 80-hour weeks and depended on
the overtime for a big chunk of his pay.
</P>
<P>
   So Courtney started the Washington Alliance of Technology
Workers (washtech.org) to address the issues of contractors who
work at Microsoft. Last year, the group affiliated with the
Communication Workers of America.
</P>
<P>
   Washtech.org is a union _ sort of. It isn't a direct employee
representative because the 6,000 contractors work for many
different companies, so they can't bargain collectively. Federal
labor law requires that workers represented by a union have a
``commonality of interests'' _ such as the same employer, same pay
and same benefits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ORGANIZING AROUND ISSUES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Washtech.org acts like a union in that it organizes around
issues of interest to contractors. For example, the organization
learned that Microsoft did evaluations of its contract workers and
told them how to access online the information that was kept in a
secure company database.
</P>
<P>
   When Microsoft discovered the contractors were reviewing their
evaluations, it resecured the database.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft maintains the evaluations were only ``routine customer
feedback,'' information intended for the firms that actually
employed the contractors. Further, the company says, the
evaluations are common throughout the temporary employment
industry.
</P>
<P>
   But Courtney argued they were personnel files and contends the
state's labor department agreed in January that the contractors
have a right to examine the records.
</P>
<P>
   It's a new model of how to organize a union outside of
collective bargaining, Courtney said. And he claims its tactics are
working: Before Washtech.org was formed, Microsoft had no minimum
benefits for its temporary workers. Now, he said, Microsoft has
rules on minimum time off, health care and training.
</P>
<P>
   Independent truck drivers in Houston are facing some of the same
union organizing hurdles: They can't organize into a traditional
union because they don't work for the same company, said Orell
Fitzsimmons, state director of the Service Employees International
Union in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But they can hold big rallies, like the one they had last month
in Houston, and they can picket in front of two trucking terminals
to generate support for pay raises and fuel surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like you need to be ordained by the federal
government,'' Fitzsimmons said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of thinking outside the box and relying on tools
other than the National Labor Relations Act, said Fitzsimmons. But
more people are organizing the growing number of contract workers
by, among other things, sponsoring mass work stoppages.
</P>
<P>
   The new emphasis is a throwback to the confrontational spirit of
the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HOW DO YOU COLLECT DUES? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unions can represent members in lots of ways, such as ensuring
they get the minimum wage and representing them in workers'
compensation cases.
</P>
<P>
   But there are hurdles to this new model of organization. For
example: dues, the lifeblood of a union.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, unions have collected dues through a payroll
deduction, but that doesn't work when there are multiple employers.
Some of the unions now collect dues through bank drafts, said
Fitzsimmons.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney said he thinks of Washtech.org a bit like the Sierra
Club. Members pay dues voluntarily. And he knows members want
valuable services in exchange, so the group is considering a
training program.
</P>
<P>
   Until it can build a financial base of support, the
Communication Workers of America is footing the bill.
</P>
<P>
   This is a hard thing for unions to do because temporary workers
tend to be transitory and traditionally don't have much allegiance
to their work sites or unions, said Kerry Notestine, an employment
lawyer who represents management with Littler Mendelson in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It's more of a risk for employers when the temps are long term
and when the whole industry relies on them, Notestine said. And
that pretty much describes the software industry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
