<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0021 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-17 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAPSTER CHANGING MUSIC DISTRIBUTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In the seven years that I've been writing this column,
I've seen a lot of hype from companies and promoters of different
products breathlessly proclaiming that their offerings are
revolutionary and will change the way people work, play or
interact.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this seldom is the case. Only a handful of technology
products have been that transforming. E-mail was one; the World
Wide Web was another; so is instant messaging.
</P>
<P>
   And now, I believe, there's a new one _ Napster.
</P>
<P>
   I've written about Napster before _ in a Jan. 28 column about
software and a new service from MP3.com. (See
www.chron.com/cs/CDA/story.hts/tech/439487.) Since then, however,
I've been using the software more, talking with other users and
hearing from readers responding to that first column.
</P>
<P>
   It's made me realize that this software is more than just an
easy way to find music in MP3-file format online. It is, in its
most primitive state, the future of music distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Napster lets those with MP3 music files share them easily with
others. The software allows a user to designate a shared folder on
a hard drive, then connects the user with one of several Napster
servers.
</P>
<P>
   The software makes a list of files to be shared and uploads the
list to a central database. Users connected to the server can
search the database and see who has what songs. Transfers occur
directly between users _ in fact, you can disconnect the software
from Napster's server and still receive a file from an individual.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MUSIC INDUSTRY CONCERNED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have not been this excited about a piece of software since the
first time I saw Mosaic, the original World Wide Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   Napster is a portent of things to come. It's not unthinkable
that, 20 years from now, Napster and its progeny could be as
powerful as today's traditional music labels.
</P>
<P>
   The powers-that-be want to, as Eric Clapton once sang, ``kill it
before it grows.'' That's not uncommon for revolutions _ the status
quo seeks to nip dramatic change in the bud. And the threats
against Napster's success are real.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the legal challenge mounted by the recording
industry, which alleges that Napster's sole intent is to foster
piracy. The San Mateo, Calif.-based company responds that Napster
stores no music on its own servers, and that it can't be
responsible for what its users do with the software.
</P>
<P>
   However, since the lawsuit was filed, the company has posted
warnings on its Web site and in the software itself saying that it
will cancel the account of anyone illegally trading copyright
material. Its unknown whether this actually will be done.
</P>
<P>
   Next is the bandwidth problem. Napster is most popular with
college students, who are big fans of popular music. Many colleges
offer high-speed Internet access in dorm rooms. Napster works best
on a fast connection, because MP3 files _ while smaller than other
audio formats _ are still hefty, about a megabyte per minute of
music.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BANS MAY BACKFIRE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   University network administrators have been complaining that so
many people are using Napster on their networks that available
bandwidth is being squeezed. As a result, the software has been
banned on some campus networks.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what's the best way to ensure the popularity of
something among kids? Tell them they can't use it! The bans have
spawned petition drives, and even Web sites, demanding an end to
what the students see as censorship. And Napster becomes even more
popular at campuses that haven't gotten around to banning it.
</P>
<P>
   It also turns out that the recording industry has been
encouraging some of these bans, even though the universities insist
they've taken action because of bandwidth concerns, not because
students might be illegally sharing copyrighted material.
</P>
<P>
   The ham-handed response by the recording industry is typical of
an established entity that doesn't ``get'' the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Some have tried introducing their own proprietary method of
digitally distributing music. For example, Sony, which both owns a
record label and makes consumer electronics, has begun selling a
digital music player.
</P>
<P>
   However, it does not use the MP3 file format, but one of its own
that limits how often you can play a song. In fact, it's so
restrictive that Walter Mossberg, the computer columnist at the
Wall Street Journal, said it ``treats every user like a potential
criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other music formats that can limit how long a
downloaded song can be played or whether it can be moved to another
computer. These either have been developed by the recording
industry or offered in hopes the industry will pick up on them. Not
surprisingly, they have not been as widely adopted as MP3. An open
standard almost always will prevail over systems with restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   What the MP3 trend and Napster have done is expose a flaw in the
way music is delivered. Most Napster users aren't grabbing whole
albums _ they are just getting individual songs.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, if you want just one song from an artist's CD, you
have to buy the whole CD. Digital distribution and trading of music
has allowed people to get just the song they want.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect most Napster users would be willing to pay, say, 50
cents or $1 for a song they really wanted. However, right now they
don't have that option. I don't think they would be willing to pay
if there were any restrictions on being able to transfer the song
to another computer, or other devices.
</P>
<P>
   After all, when you buy a CD, a tape or even an LP, you can play
that music on any player designed for the respective formats. You
can even copy it from one format to another. Why should digital
music be handled any differently?
</P>
<P>
   The smart recording industry move would be to offer individual
songs for small amounts over the Internet, and do so using an open
format such as MP3. Yes, there will be some illicit trading and
copying, but there is now. That goes with the territory.
</P>
<P>
   To see what I'm talking about, I urge you to try Napster if you
have not done so. It's available at www.napster.com. You'll never
think of music the same way again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
