<HEADLINE>
PRINTING ACROSS NETWORK TAKES A LOT OF POINTING AND CLICKING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Now that we have two computers in the house, I have set up a
home network. Mostly we play games on the network, but the other
day I wanted to print something from the computer that does not
have the printer connected to it. I couldn't figure out how to do
this across the network. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   A: Being able to print across a network is one of the handiest
aspects of linking your home computers. Unfortunately, making it
work is not intuitive.
</P>
<P>
   First, you must enable file and print sharing, which you may
already have done if you are moving files between the computers.
Right-click on the Network Neighborhood icon on your desktop and
choose Properties (or use the Network module in the Control Panel)
and then click the File and Print Sharing button. Check the boxes
for both file and print sharing, and click OK.
</P>
<P>
   Next, you'll need to designate a method or protocol the
computers will use to communicate. Still in the Network properties
box, click Add and then Protocol. Click on the Microsoft entry in
the lefthand pane. You'll see a list of different protocols in the
right pane.
</P>
<P>
   Here I'd recommend you use NetBeui for security reasons. If
either of these computers is connected to the Internet and you are
using TCP/IP or IPX for file and print sharing, it is possible for
a hacker to gain access to your computer. Click on NetBeui, and
click OK.
</P>
<P>
   Now, scroll through the list of devices in the Network
properties window until you see your network card combined with
TCP/IP. Double-click on this entry, click on the Bindings tab and
uncheck the File and Print Sharing and Client for Microsoft
Networks boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Click OK, then OK again to close the Network window, and your
computer will reboot.
</P>
<P>
   When your system is running again, go to the Printers folder and
find your regular printer. Right-click on it and choose Sharing
from the menu that appears. Click the check box to enable sharing,
then click OK.
</P>
<P>
   In the Printers folder, you should now see a hand cradling the
icon for your printer, which is Microsoft's warm-and-fuzzy way of
indicating that others can now access the device.
</P>
<P>
   On the other computer, open Network Neighborhood and find the
printer's host computer. Open it, and you should see the printer
there. Right-click on it and choose Install. In most cases, this
will bring over the drivers from the other computer, and run a
quick install dialog that will let you name it as the default
printer. In some cases, you may be asked for a print-driver disk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a notebook computer and a desktop computer. Both have
the same software installed on them. I use both to check my e-mail,
but I notice that some e-mail messages that I see on the desktop
never make it onto the portable, and vice versa. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: You have your e-mail software set to delete e-mail from your
Internet provider's mail server on both systems. When you get your
mail, it's deleted from the server. Then, when you use the other
computer to get your mail, it's already gone.
</P>
<P>
   With almost all e-mail programs, you can tell the program to
leave mail on the server. But Internet providers have a limit on
how much mail you can keep on a mail server. If both your computers
are set to not remove mail, you'll exceed your quota and won't be
able to receive more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
