<HEADLINE>
WIMBERLEY
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by WIMBERLEY-ITINERARY) 
HILL COUNTRY HAVEN: NEW B&AMP;Bs, ARTY SHOPS CAN'T TAKE COUNTRY OUT OF(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBERLEY, Texas _ Five years ago, Siri Hutcheson bought 66
acres of the old Moody Ranch, in the heart of the Hill Country, so
she could build a small weekend house there. A deserted,
9,000-square-foot hunting lodge with an abandoned swimming pool and
tennis court was part of the deal, but it was largely an
afterthought; the formerly grand lodge was so run-down, cows were
sleeping in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just bought it because I fell in love with it,'' Hutcheson
says of the land, bisected by the intriguingly named Lone Man
Creek. ``I just feel like I'm in paradise out here.''
</P>
<P>
   But slowly, like so many newcomers to Wimberley, she and partner
Camille Cook came to consider the possibility of sharing their
piece of paradise with others.
</P>
<P>
   The lodge was perched on a rise all by itself, overlooking a
rolling, rocky terrain of cedar and oak trees, cactus and
wildflowers. Doing much of the design and the work themselves, the
women turned the front third of the building into three suites,
with stylish stained-cement and tile floors, upscale ranch
furniture and exposed rock walls. They refinished the pool and
restored the grand rock porch, with its built-in stone picnic
tables. In September, their Wimberley Lodge at Lone Man Creek
opened for guests.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of story that has been repeated again and again in
recent years _ and one of the examples of how Wimberley is making a
run at Fredericksburg for the unofficial title of B&AMP;B Capital of
the Hill Country.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, nearby Fredericksburg, with more than 300 small
lodges, still probably holds that title. But with more than 100
bed-and-breakfast inns and cabins _ the majority of them having
opened in just the past five years _ plus a revitalized shopping
area and a longstanding reputation as an artists' colony, Wimberley
has become one of the Hill Country's tourism boom towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here 10 1/2 years, and Wimberley has changed
radically. The shops, the business atmosphere, the quality of
merchandise _ the whole tenor of it has been raised,'' says Neil
Mallard, who since 1989 has sold pies and cheesecakes out of a
converted gas station called the Wimberley Pie Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wimberley still has its own way of doing things, but it has
recognized the way the rest of the world does things now.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Wimberley, about 45 miles southwest of Austin on Ranch Road 12,
is nestled in a pretty part of the Hill Country, between Cypress
Creek and the Blanco River. In some respects, it's an unlikely spot
for a tourist town. An unincorporated village with a population of,
at best guess, about 9,000, it doesn't even have a square _ its
downtown business district is an unwieldy strip that lacks a focal
point or a unified theme.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, is part of its charm; Wimberley hasn't yet
built itself into a too-precious, or too-expensive, theme-park kind
of tourist town. It can still be a bit charmingly rough around the
edges. While many of the new cottages and cabins have luxe
furnishings and amenities, others are more rustic. And only a few
offer a real breakfast beyond rolls, coffee and juice.
</P>
<P>
   The town dates back to the mid-1800s but took its name from a
mill owner named Pleasant Wimberley who arrived in 1874. It was a
typical small Texas ranch community; by 1947, when civic volunteer
M.F. Johnson moved here after marrying Bill Johnson, only about 500
people lived here, she remembers. And it was so remote that even as
late as the 1980s and early '90s, the town became a refuge for a
handful of ``chemically sensitive'' people who moved there to
escape cities and city buildings oozing man-made chemicals that
they said made them ill.
</P>
<P>
   But it also had a few unique selling points. Drawn by its cool
riverbanks, Houston and San Antonio families had vacationed here as
far back as the turn of the century. The Blue Hole, a swimming spot
with a strong following today, was first opened as a commercial
swimming hole and campground in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   And Wimberley has a long history of being hospitable to artists.
In the 1930s, painter and sculptor Buck Wynn, renowned for his
murals, was one of several artists to move here. A restored portion
of a mural he originally painted for the Lone Star Brewery in San
Antonio now decorates the local visitors' center.
</P>
<P>
   More artists began coming to the town in the '50s, lured partly
by Aulgerina Lange, a real-estate agent and local booster who
promoted local artists, opened a gallery and dreamed of building an
artists' colony here. The formal colony never really happened, but
artists and craftspeople continued to move in. Today, shoppers can
find local artwork, pottery, jewelry and textiles in many of the
125-plus shops and boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the shops are destinations in their own right, such as
The Wimberley Glass Works, where artisans conduct free
glass-blowing demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
