<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-BESTACTOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON'S `HURRICANE' FORCE SUGGESTS AN UPSET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Up till now, calling the Academy Awards races has had a lot to
do with educated guessing _ a mixture of gauging standard academy
reactions to movies, audience response and personal tastes. But
predicting the Best Actor race includes a factor that the other
races didn't: The Screen Actors Guild Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The awards were announced Sunday, and Kevin Spacey took the top
movie prize for ``American Beauty.'' Since the SAG Awards are
considered an Oscar barometer _ the five previous SAG Best Actor
winners have all taken home Best Actor Oscars _ Spacey's win seems
like a lock. And if you don't think it's a good bet, remember that
Roberto Benigni won the SAG award last year before his ``surprise''
Oscar win for ``Life Is Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing standing in Spacey's way is politics, and the
Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences faces pressure that the
Screen Actors Guild doesn't: The academy has been accused, during
the past few years, of overlooking African-American actors (in
fact, Delroy Lindo, who was not nominated for his edgy, heartfelt
performance in ``The Cider House Rules,'' has complained that he
was overlooked this year, blaming his miss on poor promotion by
Miramax, ``Cider House's'' studio).
</P>
<P>
   This year, the academy has an amazing performance to consider:
Denzel Washington's turn as beleaguered, wrongly imprisoned boxer
Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter in ``The Hurricane.'' It's almost odd
that Spacey and Washington are nominated in the same category;
aside from playing besieged males, their performances have so
little in common that comparing them seems specious. Except that
they're both playing men trying to regain their dignity under
trying circumstances: Washington's Carter in a literal prison;
Spacey's Lester Burnham in a metaphorical one, his suburban malaise
from which he's trying to break free.
</P>
<P>
   My pick between the two would be Washington, for a couple of
reasons: One, he is the main _ perhaps the only _ reason to see
``The Hurricane.'' Much has been made of the dignity of his
performance, but few people have noted the vigor and anger of his
portrayal of Carter's early days, his ability to keep a
solitary-confinement scene from lapsing into hallucinatory
silliness, and his softening at movie's end. And two, although
Spacey's performance is wicked fun to watch, he strikes some false
notes, especially in a bedroom argument after onscreen wife Annette
Bening catches him in an onanistic act. Blame that on director Sam
Mendes, who allows a little too much shrillness to creep into
``American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics may work against Washington, though. Although
fact-based movies are often accused of twisting the truth, it's
hard to remember one that underwent an onslaught of deconstruction
as quickly as ``The Hurricane.'' The movie hardly portrays Carter
as a saint, but it does add gloss to his image, and critics _ not
necessarily film critics _ complained that it left out information
about Carter's troubled youth and about his unconventional
lifestyle since his 1986 release from prison.
</P>
<P>
   Similar complaints seem likely to scuttle Russell Crowe,
nominated for his performance as a tobacco-company whistle-blower
in ``The Insider.'' The movie depicts ``60 Minutes'' squelching a
Mike Wallace report in which Crowe's character, Jeffrey Wigand,
flatly states that tobacco companies intentionally make their
products addictive. Wallace and ``60 Minutes'' accused the movie of
truth-bending, but Crowe's biggest obstacle to an Oscar win is that
not many people saw his film.
</P>
<P>
   More people saw Crowe in ``The Insider,'' though, than saw
fellow nominees Richard Farnsworth and Sean Penn, in ``The Straight
Story'' and ``Sweet and Lowdown,'' respectively. These are small
movies, and if they'd made more noise at the box office, Farnsworth
and Penn would have more buzz behind their nominations. Farnsworth
is especially affecting in ``The Straight Story,'' David Lynch's
fact-based movie about an old man who journeys from Iowa to
Wisconsin on a riding mower to reconcile with his estranged
brother. And Penn switches back and forth from jerk to genius in
``Sweet and Lowdown'' as a 1930s jazz guitarist who is great
onstage, but a mess offstage. For most people, no doubt including
some academy members, their work remains to be seen _ and in the
case of ``The Straight Story,'' offers many rewards for thoughtful
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Going to go against the grain here and say that
Denzel Washington is going to take the Oscar from Spacey, breaking
the SAG string.
</P>
<P>
   Personal pick: Washington.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
