A0029 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-WIMBERLEY-2ndTake-TEX     03-17 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBERLEY-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
WIMBERLEY, Texas: glass-blowing demonstration. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still more local artists sell their wares at the monthly Market
Day, a kind of upscale flea market and bazaar, with up to 450
vendors in outdoor booths at a 16-acre park. A tradition for 35
years, it is held the first Saturday of the month, from April
through December, starting at dawn and ending when the last
merchant packs up and goes home.
</P>
<P>
   All of the businesses feed off each other, locals say; better
shopping has brought more tourists, who brought an increased demand
for lodging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, you could drive up and down (main artery) Ranch
Road 12 and see maybe two cars,'' says Terrie Bursiel, owner of All
Wimberley Lodging, a bed-and-breakfast booking agency. ``It's not
like that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mallard began his pie business in '89, he sold most of his
pies wholesale, to restaurants. Now, because there's so much foot
traffic, he sells more than 80 percent of his pies to retail
customers. He added his first tables for eat-in customers just last
year and is trying to figure out how to squeeze more in at the
small shop.
</P>
<P>
   Food, indeed, is the weak link. The town has about a dozen
restaurants, ranging from coffeeshops to pizzerias to unpretentious
spots serving anything from chicken-fried steaks to burgers to
German food to Mexican. But they tend to be fairly simple and
haven't caught up with the sophistication of the town's lodging and
shops.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Not that it matters all that much. One of the best things to do
in Wimberley, honestly, is not much at all.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there's hiking. Many of the lodges are on private acreage
large enough to explore. Or visit the landmark known as Mount
Baldy, a limestone hill with an elevation reaching about 1,200
feet; it has a path and sculpted steps to the vista.
</P>
<P>
   When the weather's warm, there's swimming, especially at the
Blue Hole, so picturesque it was used for scenes in ``Honeysuckle
Rose,'' the 1980 movie starring Willie Nelson. An old-fashioned
Texas swimming hole, it has banks lined with ancient cypress trees,
from which you can swing on ropes into the water; there's even a
shallow end, lined with smooth pebbles.
</P>
<P>
   (If you don't have the energy for that, there's always sitting;
as you cross the bridge over Cypress Creek, which winds through
town, you might see someone drag a lawn chair right into the
shallow water to catch some rays.)
</P>
<P>
   And there's driving. One of the state's most scenic drives, the
Devil's Backbone, begins just south of Wimberley on Ranch Road 32;
it's a twisting, hilly stretch of about 25 miles heading to Blanco.
</P>
<P>
   But many visitors come just to do nothing. Bursiel says her No.
1 request from visitors is for romantic, secluded cabins,
preferably set off by themselves and overlooking the hills.
</P>
<P>
   Such as the lodge renovated by Hutcheson and Cook. The lodge has
some vestiges of its former days as a property of the wealthy Moody
family; an old airstrip, helpfully marked with ``yield to
aircraft'' signs, is within walking distance of the suites. And the
tennis court and pool have been restored to their former glory.
</P>
<P>
   The women paid good attention to detail, furnishing the rooms
with leather sofas, king-size beds with feather duvets, and antique
claw-foot tubs. There's a telescope for stargazing and binoculars
for bird-watching. The movies stacked near the VCR include a copy
of ``Giant.'' There are Aveda products in the bathroom, plush
towels and linens, and fresh coffee beans and a grinder in the
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   But those are city touches you'd expect from an upscale lodge;
the best part of the property, like many of those in Wimberley, is
in the great outdoors. In the morning, listen for songbirds or hike
in the surrounding hills, watching for white-tailed deer; in the
evenings, gaze at the stars from the open-air hot tub.
</P>
<P>
   Stay here a couple of days, and you understand why the Wimberley
Chamber of Commerce officially bills the town as ``a little bit of
heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com, Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
