<HEADLINE>
U.S. MAKES OVERTURE TO IRAN, LIFTING BAN ON SOME IMPORTS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a cautious but warmly worded overture to Iran,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on Friday announced the
lifting of a ban against some Iranian imports and said the United
States wants to settle the remaining legal disputes between the
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring is the season of hope and renewal, of planting the
seeds for new crops,'' the secretary said. ``And my hope is that in
both Iran and the United States, we can plant the seeds now for a
new and better relationship in years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright made no specific promises regarding the settlement of
legal claims left over from the American seizure of Iranian assets
two decades ago, in response to the 1979 takeover of the U.S.
Embassy in Tehran and the holding of American hostages for more
than a year. Rather, she talked about ``eventually concluding a
global settlement of outstanding legal claims.''
</P>
<P>
   Settling those claims, she said, would ``put this issue behind
us once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright made official what had been rumored for several days:
that the United States would allow Americans once more to import
carpets, caviar, nuts and some dried fruits from Iran. She said,
too, that the United States would explore ways to promote more
contacts between scholars, artists and athletes of the two nations.
</P>
<P>
   But the secretary did not address the continuing American
prohibitions on imports of Iranian oil, or Washington's continuing
opposition to major loans to Iran by the International Monetary
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's speech, delivered to the Conference on
American-Iranian Relations, was a delicate blend: of mea culpas for
past American support of a repressive government in the name of
Cold War strategy; of reminders that Washington, too, has
grievances; and of the belief that there is much good in common
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   The people of both countries, she said, ``are idealistic; proud;
family-oriented; spiritually aware; and fiercely opposed to foreign
domination.'' The full text of Albright's speech is available on
the State Department's web site, www.state.gov.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no illusions that the United States and Iran will be
able to overcome decades of estrangement overnight,'' she said.
``We can't build a mature relationship on carpets and grain
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the direction of our relations is more important than the
pace,'' the secretary said. ``The United States is willing to
proceed patiently, on a step-by-step basis. Or to move very rapidly
if Iran indicates a desire and commitment to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   That last remark was an unmistakable signal to Iranian
moderates, who made big inroads in recent parliamentary elections
and whose success Washington is eager to nurture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the trend towards democracy, control over the
military, judiciary, courts and police remains in unelected hands,
and the elements of its foreign policy about which we are most
concerned have not improved,'' she said of the current situation in
Iran. ``But the momentum in the direction of internal reform,
freedom and openness is growing stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   The symbolic steps announced on Friday, Albright said, are meant
to show the people of Iran _ ``craftsmen, farmers and fishermen'' _
that the United States bears them no ill will.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary sounded a note of cold pragmatism in calling for
better relations between the countries, in view of what she
described as ``Iraq's lawless regime'' and the ``instability and
illicit narcotics being exported from Afghanistan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Iran lives in a dangerous neighborhood,'' Albright said. ``We
welcome efforts to make it less dangerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
