<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-IRAN (Washington) _ Hoping to ``plant the seeds of a new
relationship'' with Iran, the Clinton administration announces
plans to lift a ban on some Iranian goods and promises to seek
settlement of Tehran's financial claims against the U.S. The
initiatives will not affect U.S. sanctions against American
investment in the Iranian oil industry. JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-LOCKS (Washington) _ The gun maker Smith &AMP; Wesson says it
plans to provide trigger locks on its handguns within 60 days and
to make them child-resistant within a year. The moves are part of a
deal in which legal action will be dropped by the Clinton
administration and 30 cities and state governments. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   POLL-2000 (Washington) _ As the curtain rises on the 2000
general election campaign, voters are in a pessimistic mood over
stock market fluctuations, gas prices and killing of a six-year-old
by a six-year-old in Michigan, a new poll says. The bi-partisan
``Battleground'' poll puts Texas Gov. George W. Bush ahead of Vice
President Al Gore 47 percent to 44 percent. But Gore has improved
his image with voters and leads Bush on issues such as Social
Security, health care and education. By DAN FREEDMAN. (To be filed
in the ``w'' and ``p'' categories.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GORE (Undated) _ In the first ad salvo of the general
election, George W. Bush goes after Al Gore on education. The TV
commercial is filled with smiling children but the message is
sharp: ``Clinton and Gore had eight years, but they've failed.'' By
JOHN W. GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SOLD (San Francisco) _ The Hearst Corporation announces
it has agreed to sell The San Francisco Examiner to a company
affiliated with the publisher of the San Francisco Independent.
Following a four-month transition period, The Examiner, which is
currently published under a Joint Operating Agreement with the San
Francisco Chronicle, will be published separately as an independent
newspaper. By The Hearst Newspapers. (1stld-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Houston) _ I've seen a lot of hype from
companies and promoters of different products breathlessly
proclaiming that their offerings are revolutionary and will change
the way people work, play or interact. Of course, this seldom is
the case. Only a handful of technology products have been that
transforming. E-mail was one; the World Wide Web was another; so is
instant messaging. And now there is a new one _ Napster. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Houston) _ A reader asks, ``Now that we have
two computers in the house, I have set up a home network. Mostly we
play games on the network, but the other day I wanted to print
something from the computer that does not have the printer
connected to it. I couldn't figure out how to do this across the
network. Can you help?'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ Clever ideas are sometimes born out
of frustration. Marcus Courtney was a contractor at Microsoft and
got upset two years ago when the software industry successfully
lobbied the Washington state Department of Labor and Industries to
allow high-tech companies to pay straight time instead of
time-and-a-half overtime to workers who earn more than $27.63 per
hour. So Courtney started the Washington Alliance of Technology
Workers (washtech.org) to address the issues of contractors who
work at Microsoft. Last year, the group affiliated with the
Communication Workers of America. By L.M. SIXEL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
