   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-FOREIGN-POLICY (Washington) _ Balancing moral values
against a company's right to do business overseas, the U.S. Supreme
Court this week examines whether cities and states can have their
own foreign policy and impose economic sanctions on countries with
repressive regimes. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ISSUE-ADS (Washington) _ If you missed the broadcast advertising
campaigns that George W. Bush and Al Gore waged in early primary
states to help secure their parties' presidential nominations, a
multimillion dollar replay is headed your way. The Republican and
Democratic parties _ and allied organizations theoretically acting
independently of the candidates _ are on the verge of mounting the
most expensive broadcast advertising blitz in U.S. history. By
STEWART M. POWELL. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EMPTY-TRUCKS (Brownsville, Texas) _ A government study says
nearly half the cargo trucks crossing from Mexico into the United
States are empty, contributing to chronic traffic problems and the
slow movement of commerce across the border. But federal officials,
ever wary of the drug trade and illegal immigration, say they must
inspect commercial vehicles _ empty or not. By ALISON GREGOR.
(Filed Thursday.)
</P>
