<HEADER>
A0039 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-WIMBERLEY-ITINERARY--     03-17 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBERLEY-ITINERARY--TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU GO TO WIMBERLEY ...
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanies WIMBERLEY) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY
</P>
<P>
   Wimberley is about a four hours' drive from Fort Worth-Dallas,
on Ranch Road 12 southwest of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Several agencies book cottages, inns and bed-and-breakfast
lodgings:
</P>
<P>
   All Wimberley Lodging Reservation Service offers 85 properties.
(800) 460-3909; www.texhillcntry.com/wimberley
</P>
<P>
   Hill Country Accommodations lists 50 locations; (800) 926-5028
or www.texasvacation.com
</P>
<P>
   Texas Hill Country Retreats represents 40 properties; (800)
236-9411 or www.homestead-tx.com/texashillco.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Market Day, the outdoor bazaar that runs sunup to sundown, the
first Saturday of the month, April through December; information at
www.visitwimberley.com/lions.
</P>
<P>
   For general information on Wimberley, contact the Chamber of
Commerce &AMP; Visitor's Center, (512) 847-2201 or www.wimberley.org.
More information is at www.visitwimberley.com.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO DO
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY:
</P>
<P>
   After checking into your bed-and-breakfast inn, it's time to
think about dinner. Wimberley's restaurant selection is slender,
but options include the Creekview Grill, (512) 842-3663), serving
salads, burgers, steaks and pasta on a covered patio that overlooks
pretty Cypress Creek. At the Cypress Creek Cafe, (512) 847-2515),
across the street, there's a menu of steaks and sandwiches and a
full bar; a bonus is live music on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   If you're up for more driving, you're within 30 minutes of
Gruene and its famous dance hall, where the Flatlanders, Pat Green,
Hot Club of Cowtown, Junior Brown and Kelly Willis have all played
recently. Information from (830) 606-1281 or www.gruenehall.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY:
</P>
<P>
   If breakfast isn't included with your lodging, head to Jitters
coffee shop, (512) 847-6101), for a latte and pastries. Afterward,
you can easily kill a couple of hours wandering through the shops
on the ``square,'' an elongated strip of stores and restaurants in
what passes for downtown Wimberley.
</P>
<P>
   Try Lady of the Lake for jewelry, cards, music, candles and
metaphysical gifts; you can also get a crystal reading there.
Designs in Wax has hand-poured scented candles, made locally;
Rancho Deluxe has crosses, furniture and interior-design fixtures
in a mixture of cowboy, Mexican and Latin American motifs.
</P>
<P>
   We recommend skipping lunch and going straight for the pie at
the Wimberley Pie Co., (512) 847-9462, where nearly 20 varieties,
including pecan, chocolate fudge, Key lime and coconut custard go
for $8.50 to $11 for a whole pie. Eat it there, in a converted gas
station just south of the square, or take it with you to find a
sunny spot for a pie picnic, perhaps on the banks of the Cypress
Creek.
</P>
<P>
   After that, you'll need to work off the calories; one option is
to hike to the summit of Old Baldy, off Ranch Road 2325. If that's
too much effort, make a reservation for a massage, a manicure or a
body treatment in one of the day spas that are rapidly springing
up. These include Touched by Angels, (877) 847-7568,
www.apstx.com/touched), with nail treatments, aromatherapy
treatments and massage; and Serenity, (512) 847-8985, with
Japanese-style body treatments and hot tubs.
</P>
<P>
   For dinner, make reservations at The Blair House, (512)
847-1111, www.blairhouseinn.com,) a country inn that offers a
five-course dinner on Saturday nights only. Chef Jonnie Stansbury,
who also teaches cooking class and is working on a PBS cooking
show, whips up gourmet fare from seasonal ingredients; meals might
include fresh-baked focaccia with kalamata olives, roasted corn
soup with chipotle cream, beef tenderloin and roasted new
vegetables, with a fresh strawberry torte for dessert. Dinner is
$50 per person and includes wine.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY:
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast, enjoy more of the Hill Country scenery by
taking a drive. The best known is Devil's Backbone, which stretches
along Ranch Road 32 for 25 miles just south of town, but there are
good views on nearly every road out of town.
</P>
<P>
   If it's warm enough, stop by the Blue Hole swimming area for a
dip, (512) 847-9127. A temporary membership gets you in for $5 per
person per day; it's open sunup to sundown, and brave souls were
already testing the waters in March.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
