r a BC-BORDER-INCIDENT-HNS &LR;      03-17 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-INCIDENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AGENTS WORRY ABOUT MEXICAN BORDER INCURSION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JODI BIZAR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ U.S. Border Patrol agents say that the
incursion into the United States by two vehicles loaded with
Mexican soldiers was more serious than reported, and that shots
fired could be linked to a reported bounty on agents by a major
drug-trafficking cartel.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was no accident,'' one agent, who asked that his name not
be used, said of the Tuesday night incident near Santa Teresa,
N.M., northwest of El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol said Wednesday that the Mexican army vehicles
entered the United States about 10:30 p.m. Tuesday after straying
across the poorly marked boundary. Two shots were fired from one of
the Mexican vehicles, but no one was wounded.
</P>
<P>
   One vehicle retreated into Mexico, but the nine soldiers riding
in the second were detained temporarily by the Border Patrol before
being returned to their country Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   An agency spokesman continued to downplay the incident, saying
it ``was apparently accidental, and we don't know why they fired
the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials said the soldiers were on an anti-drug patrol
and that the whole episode was under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   However, some rank-and-file Border Patrol agents said things
were not as simple as the official statements made them sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came more than a mile into U.S. territory and were
driving around for a while,'' one agent said of the Mexican
soldiers in Humvees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They figured they could sneak up on an agent and collect the
$200,000,'' said the agent, who asked not to be identified. He was
referring to an internal Border Patrol memo last month stating that
the Juarez, Mexico, drug cartel had placed a $200,000 bounty on the
head of every U.S. law enforcement officer on the border.
</P>
<P>
   George Swank, a spokesman for the patrol's office in Marfa,
Texas, said at the time that he could not discuss the memo
``because it is a sensitive issue. It's a credible threat, and it
extends all along the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Agents in El Paso said that memo and the incident in Santa
Teresa have many agents nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's heating up out here, and it's all about that bounty,''
one agent said. ``More (agents) are signing out automatic weapons
than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the agents' concern for their safety, Border Patrol
spokesman Doug Mosier said: ``There is always concern for agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no evidence that this was not an accident, and there's
no evidence to connect the bounty with this (Tuesday's) incident,''
Mosier said from his El Paso office.
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol officials said the memo and the trespassing by the
Mexican military are under investigation by the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Emilio Anchondo Paredes, a spokesman for the state
government in Chihuahua, Mexico, said an internal affairs unit of
the Mexican military was looking into the Tuesday incident ``to see
if it was an illegal, intentional act.''
</P>
<P>
   Marco Antonio Fraire, a spokesman for the Mexican Consulate in
El Paso, called the incident a ``regrettable mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   As to why shots had been fired, Fraire said: ``We don't have any
details on that. We are still getting information on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1637EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0049 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NITEOUT-LIFESTYLE-ART     03-17 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-LIFESTYLE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OUT WITH DAVID SCHISGALL: SEX ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THE
HILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to New York Times photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, March 19) 
(DW) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's not often that 150 20-somethings get together to
watch a dirty movie _ at least, not one that involves a cast of
60-somethings.
</P>
<P>
   But that was what was happening on Thursday night at the
premiere of ``The Lifestyle,'' a new documentary about swingers in
the suburbs that opened at the Pioneer Theater in Manhattan's East
Village. The film, which has been well received, follows the
exploits of what Stephen Holden, a critic for The New York Times,
called ``gray-haired, potbellied, cellulite-jiggling, over-60
orgiasts.''
</P>
<P>
   That demographic was not in evidence on Thursday. The premiere
and the post-screening celebration at Two Boots restaurant on
Avenue A drew a large crowd from another odd subculture: the
independent film scene. Young men in heavy black spectacles, and
the young women who love them, were everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the audience seemed a little shaken by the film _
there was a noticeable rush on the red wine _ most of the downtown
film buffs seemed singularly nonchalant about all the naked sex
among people old enough to be their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say the subject matter is shocking,'' said Todd
Solondz, the director of ``Happiness,'' the suburban satire about
incest. Wearing heavy dark spectacles, he said in a voice that
sounded like Woody Allen on tranquilizers, ``The subject matter is
the subject matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Solondz was flanked by David Schisgall, the 32-year-old director
of ``The Lifestyle,'' and Schisgall's girlfriend, Evgenia Peretz.
She insisted Schisgall was not a swinger. ``Absolutely not,'' she
said. ``He's just a director.'' She added, however, that she had
warned her parents about the film before introducing them to him to
avoid that ```So what's your movie about?' moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Schisgall, also wearing heavy black glasses, confirmed that he
was not a swinger, though he admitted that he and his crew got
naked several times on the set. ``Every time they were naked, we
were naked,'' he said. ``When you go to a black-tie event, you want
to dress the part.''
</P>
<P>
   David Samuels, another writer in heavy spectacles, cornered
Schisgall to rave about a scene that involved a 70-year-old man,
another man's wife and a hammocklike contraption called a sex
sling. ``That is an image that has never ever been on screen
before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some strove to discuss the film in more high-minded terms. Rufus
Griscom, a founder of nerve.com, the erotica Web site, said he
detected a sense in the audience of ``young people coming to terms
with their own sexual prejudices.'' Yeah, and that sex sling thing.
</P>
<P>
   Schisgall spent most of the evening shaking hands, but found
time to discuss the film with someone he called his toughest
critic: Jane Papish, his mother. Was she concerned when her son
told her what his film was about? ``I was more concerned that he'd
taken a job without health insurance,'' Papish said. ``David's
always done his own thing.''
</P>
<P>
   While most felt Schisgall had created an intriguing portrait,
few saw a similar lifestyle in their immediate future. Heather
O'Donnell, a friend of Schisgall's, asked jokingly, ``How long you
think before everyone at this party starts to swing?'' Hilary
Liftin, a writer, replied, ``Not for a long, long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
