<P>
   IRAN-U.S. (Washington) _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
on Friday lifted a narrow slice of America's broad economic
sanctions against Iran and declared a commitment to take far more
extensive steps toward ending two decades of hostility ``if Iran
indicates a desire and commitment to do so.'' In a speech here
Friday that Clinton administration officials described as their
most explicit overture to the moderates who won Iranian
parliamentary elections last month, Albright described a road map
for economic normalization of relations. Without naming them, she
held out the prospect for ending bans on American investment in
Iran's oil industry and the blockage of major loans to Tehran by
the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank. But she made no
mention of a resumption of full diplomatic relations. By David E.
Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-ELECT (Taipei) _ Regardless of who wins the presidential
election on Saturday, relations with China and politics in Taiwan
will never be the same. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-SMITH (Washington) _ The nation's largest gun manufacturer,
Smith &AMP; Wesson, has agreed to provide safety locks on its handguns
within 60 days and to make them child-resistant within a year, the
Clinton administration announced Friday. Under the unprecedented
deal reached with the company by the departments of Housing and
Urban Development and Treasury and officials representing state and
local governments, Smith &AMP; Wesson agreed to a ``code of conduct''
for sales and distribution of handguns. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BROWN-SHOOTING (Atlanta) _ Two sheriff's deputies were shot and
seriously wounded near downtown Atlanta late Thursday night while
serving a warrant at the home of a Muslim cleric who was known in
the 1960s as H. Rap Brown, a leader of the Black Panther party.
Officials of the Fulton County Sheriff's Office said they did not
know whether Brown, now known as Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, shot the
two deputies. The shooter escaped after being wounded by one of the
deputies, and sheriff's officials said they were looking for
Al-Amin. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   With photos from Cox News Service, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RAIL-MERGER (Undated) _ Regulators in Washington Friday blocked
a plan to create an enormous cross-border transcontinental railroad
_ combining Burlington Northern Santa Fe and the Canadian National
_ by slapping a moratorium on all rail mergers until rules are
rewritten over the next 15 months. In deciding to impose the
unusual moratorium, the three members of the Surface Transportation
Board contradicted Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater, who
opposed a delay, and supported the position of competing railroads
that feared a merger at this time would trigger a wild round of
deal making that would end, finally, with just two huge rail
systems left to serve all of North America. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-STRIKE (Seattle) _ Its profits and share price sagging
and its customers clamoring for delayed jets, Boeing cut a deal
Friday to end a 38-day strike by its engineers, one of the largest
ever by white-collar workers. The tentative 3-year contract grants
wage increases of at least 9 percent and cash bonuses of up to
$2,500, while the company has dropped a demand that workers
contribute toward their health insurance. (Summary from wires) By
Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-OSCARS (Hollywood) _ Police are being asked to keep an
eye out for several dozen bald, shiny men standing about 13 inches
high and weighing 8 pounds each, with strangely erect posture,
vaguely Cycladic features and a tendency to make motion picture
professionals gush, weep and suddenly remember their parents. Just
two weeks after the Academy of Motion Pictures Arts and Sciences
was forced to resend 4,200 of this year's Oscar ballots because the
first batch had been mislaid by the U.S. Postal Service, the
academy had to announce Friday morning that somebody has stolen the
entire shipment of 55 gold-plated statuettes that were to be used
in this year's ceremonies on March 26 at Los Angeles' Shrine
Auditorium. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   CIA-PROPAGANDA (Undated) _ ) _ Watch the 1955 animated version
of ``Animal Farm,'' and you'll notice the ending is different than
in the book. Another example of Hollywood butchering great
literature? Yes, but in this case the film's secret producer was
the Central Intelligence Agency. The CIA, it seems, was worried
that the public might be too influenced by Orwell's
pox-on-both-their-houses critique of capitalism and communism. So
after George Orwell's death in 1950, agents were dispatched to buy
the film rights to ``Animal Farm'' from his widow in order to make
its message more overtly anti-communist. Rewriting the end of
Animal Farm is just one example of the often absurd lengths to
which the CIA went between 1947 and 1967 that are recounted in a
new book. By Laurence Zuckerman. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3.
</P>
<P>
   (With an ``a'' code)
</P>
