<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, March 19, and thereafter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-LIFE-COACHES (New York) _ Enrollment is up at Coach U.,
an online educational company that trains people to be ``life
coaches,'' members of a growing profession that instructs clients
in so-called life skills. More than 5,000 life coaches are now
practicing, said Sandy Vila, president of Coach U., which began
with a few students in 1992 and now boasts a yearly enrollment of
about 1,300. Coaches in training study topics like relating,
listening and empowering, the better to offer clients advice on the
fine points of managing their lives: take a nap, take a bath, write
a letter, pay your taxes. By Penelope Green. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THREE-OH-BIRTHDAY (New York) _ The Big Three-Oh is a milestone
that many approach with a mixture of ambivalence and dread. It
marks the twilight of youth, a bringing down of the curtain on
life's first act, and many chose to observe it very quietly or
ignore it altogether. By Monique P. Yazigi. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HIRSHBERGER-SALON (Undated) _ Sally Hershberger was slaloming
around the limos in the parking lot of the Ron Herman/Fred Segal
Melrose store in Los Angeles. Hershberger, the Hollywood
hairstylist who has become something of a celebrity in her own
right coiffing stars like Meg Ryan, Michelle Pfeiffer and Tom
Cruise, was on a high-speed mission: to outfit both herself and her
new Los Angeles salon, Sally Hershberger at John Frieda, for its
opening party this coming Friday. By Ellen Tien. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LEATHER-PROTEST (New York) _ It may seem surprising that the
animal rights group is trying to make leather the new fur now,
considering the setbacks it has suffered this last season. Dozens
of designers returned to fur and overall fur sales rose 10 percent
this winter. One might think the group would go after more modest
game. Instead, activists are girding for what they call ``The Big
One.'' They are convinced they can coax and sloganize leather into
a state of political incorrectness. But that seems unlikely.
Leather hasn't been as popular since the Paleolithic period. By
Nancy Hass. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-LIFESTYLE-FILM (New York) _ It's not often that 150
20-somethings get together to watch a dirty movie _ at least, not
one that involves a cast of 60-somethings. But that was what was
happening on Thursday night at the premiere of ``The Lifestyle,'' a
new documentary about swingers in the suburbs that opened in
Manhattan. The film, which has been well received, follows the
exploits of what Stephen Holden, a critic for The New York Times,
called ``gray-haired, potbellied, cellulite-jiggling, over-60
orgiasts.'' By Jesse Mckinley. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Creating a garden on table tops and
windowsills in an apartment in Copenhagen. By Marty Ross. &QL; 
 &QL;
