<P>
   The following is a menu for New America News Service stories
that are for release Fri., March 17, 2000, or anytime thereafter:
</P>
<P>
   -------------HAPPY ST. PATRICK'S DAY------------
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL'S GOAL AT STILLMAN: BUILD CHARACTER. After a 50-year
hiatus, football has finally returned to historically black
Stillman College. Why? In addition to boosting alumni interest in
the 124-year-old campus, President Earnest McNealy wants to
increase the number of males on campus. However, as a Division III
program, Stillman cannot offer athletic scholarships or establish
endowments. Players must find financial aid, loans and other
assistance to attend Stillman. In other words, they must have a
burning desire to attend the school and play football. In this
article, Bill Maxwell explains how, instead of exploiting black
athleticism, Stillman is dedicated to grooming young people for
bright futures. (slugged:
BC-NEW-AMERICA-WHEN-FOOTBALL-BUILDS-CHARACTER-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   CHANGE SPINS FASTER THAN TIME. Today, the average car has more
computing power in its glove compartment than did the Lunar landing
craft. Just more than a decade ago, only the wealthy could afford a
cellular phone at a cost of $1,500. Now these phones are
practically free. Everything around us is changing _ and changing
fast, writes Nat Irvin II in this feature from Emerge magazine. And
from the looks of things, the changes of the future will only come
faster. Irvin ponders the wonders of the technological innovations
that have occurred within the last 30 years and peers into the
future. For example, by the year 2020 your grandchildren will be
born with their DNA encoded and will likely be implanted with some
kind of genetic DNA chip and can expect to live to 2120. (slugged:
BC-NEW-AMERICA-RAPID-SOCIAL-CHANGE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   AND NEXT TO THE TEN COMMANDMENTS, A LAKOTA SUN DANCE POLE. Last
week, South Dakota's Gov. Bill Janklow, a Republican, signed Bill
HB1261 permitting South Dakota public schools to display the Ten
Commandments, along with other objects and documents of cultural,
legal or historical significance. In this commentary, columnist Tim
Giago writes: ``The centerpiece of the Lakota spirituality is the
sweat lodge or inipi. If my understanding of HB1261 is correct,
then the public schools of South Dakota would have to allow the
Indian students who practice their traditional Lakota spirituality
to construct sweat lodges in the schools. The most sacred of
ceremonies is the Sun Dance. Should the Lakota and Dakota students
be allowed to build a Sun Dance pole in the school hallways?''
Giago traces the destructive consequences of mixing church and
state. (slugged: BC-NEW-AMERICA-LAKOTA-JOURNAL-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   THE OTHER TEXAS REPUBLICAN ON THE RISE: HISPANIC TONY GARZA.
There's another Texas star in the Republican party: Texas Railroad
Commissioner Tony Garza. Some say he is the real future of the GOP.
Not your average Republican, Garza, whose four grandparents were
Mexican, hails from Brownsville, Texas _ a poor, predominantly
Hispanic city along the democratically entrenched Texas-Mexico
border. A down-home guy, Garza speaks English and Spanish, and
despite his law-school education and party affiliation, he's a
south Texan to his core. This profile from Hispanic magazine looks
at the policies and politics that have set Garza on the road to
national prominence during his 11 years in public office. Garza's
good buddy? You guessed it. Gov. George W. Bush. (slugged:
BC-NEW-AMERICA-TEXAS-STAR-GARZA-NYTSF)
</P>
