<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-TEN-COMMANDMENTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NEXT TO THE TEN COMMANDMENTS, A LAKOTA SUN DANCE POLE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By TIM GIAGO (NANWICA KCIJI)  
 &HT;    We knew Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson long before they were
born. Back then they were called missionaries.
 &HT;    When you consider that several generations of Indian children
were forced _ at a very early age _ to go to church six days a week
and twice on Sunday, the posting of the Ten Commandments on a
school bulletin board seems a bit trivial. But that was then and
this is now.
 &HT;    Last week, South Dakota's Gov. Bill Janklow, a Republican,
signed Bill HB1261 permitting South Dakota public schools to
display the Ten Commandments, along with other objects and
documents of cultural, legal or historical significance that have
influenced and helped form the nation's government and legal
systems. But the Ten Commandments may not be posted more
prominently than other objects and documents.
 &HT;    Believe it or not, the legislative supporters of this nonsense
actually think it will stand up to constitutional scrutiny. (The
U.S. Supreme Court outlawed the posting of the commandments in
public schools two decades ago.) What does the Constitution say?
 &HT;    The First Amendment says Congress shall make no law respecting
an establishment of religion, which has been interpreted to require
a separation of church and state.
 &HT;    The separation of church and state held no meaning to Congress
when it came to the indigenous people of this land. In the 19th and
20th centuries, the Indian reservations were sliced up like pieces
of pie. Different sections were awarded to various religious sects
to build churches and schools. The object was to Christianize the
Indian.
 &HT;    Kill the Indian and save the child was the edict coming from the
U.S. Congress. In many instances, not only did the church kill the
Indian adult's spirituality, it also killed the culture, language
and traditions of the child.
 &HT;    The centerpiece of the Lakota spirituality is the sweat lodge or
inipi. If my understanding of HB1261 is correct, then the public
schools of South Dakota would have to allow the Indian students who
practice their traditional Lakota spirituality to construct sweat
lodges in the schools.
 &HT;    The most sacred of ceremonies is the Sun Dance. Should the
Lakota and Dakota students be allowed to build a Sun Dance pole in
the school hallways?
 &HT;    Isn't it a wonder that the U.S. Congress only allowed Christians
and Mormons to build schools and churches on the Indian
reservations? Why weren't the Muslims or Buddhists given the same
option? Probably because, as Gov. George W. Bush is so fond of
saying, ``This is a Christian nation.''
 &HT;    Is it? Who gave the Christians the right to call this a
Christian nation?
 &HT;    But the real question is why were different religious
organizations allowed to build churches and schools on the
reservations at all? Separation of church and state? Get real!
 &HT;    Generations of Indian children have grown up in the clutches of
the ``Religious Right.'' The religious zealots who moved onto the
reservations arrived with a vengeance. They used the wrath of the
Lord as their weapon of choice.
 &HT;    If there was a blizzard with snow drifts 6 feet high and wind
chill factors at 50 degrees below zero, the Indian students at the
mission boarding schools still marched in military ranks from their
dormitories to attend the daily church services.
 &HT;    We had our Jerry Falwells and Pat Robertons long before there
was a Jerry Falwell or Pat Roberton. These missionaries _ in their
fervent zeal to save our souls _ took thousands of Indian children
from their parents and ``adopted out'' the children to white
families.
 &HT;    The Mormon Church was famous for this practise. They practically
stripped certain reservations of their children and turned these
young captives into little slaves.
 &HT;    Did the parents of these children care? You bet they did, but
they had no say about what happened to their flesh and blood. They
could only sit at home and cry.
 &HT;    I suggest the Christians practice their religion at home or in
their churches. Keep it out of the schools. I do not care what
religion you belong to or if you belong to one at all. Just don't
force your beliefs on those who do not want it.
 &HT;    The smallest minority in this nation, the minority that used to
be the majority, has experienced first hand the damage that forced
religion can have upon a people. We didn't become the smallest
minority by accident. The religious zealots had a lot to do with
it.
 &HT;    In a classic example of gobbledygook, Gov. Janklow explained his
support for Bill HB1261. ``If you don't believe in God, it's not
any problem to suggest whether or not you have any other gods
before you. To the extent you do, you get to pick who it is because
it doesn't tell you who god is.''
 &HT;    Say what?
 &HT;    Sounds like something I heard in catechism class many years ago.
Yes, religious instructions were a regular part of our school
curriculum, but of course, our lessons were often spoken in Latin.
I never knew the governor was bilingual.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Tim Giago (Nanwica Kciji _ ``Stands up for Them'') is an Oglala
Lakota. He is editor and publisher of the weekly newspaper, The
Lakota Nation Journal. He can be reached at: P.O. Box 3080, Rapid
City, S.D. 57709-3080 or e-mailed at: editor at
lakotanationjournal.com
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 The Lakota Nation Journal 
