<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-RAPID-SOCIAL-CHANGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE SPINS FASTER THAN TIME  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate's NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE is for use only by arrangement
with New York Times Syndicate/Special Features. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By NAT IRVIN II  
 &HT;    ``When do you think things are going to slow down?'' a friend
recently asked me as we discussed the realities of rapid social
change taking place around us.
 &HT;    ``How about by 2020?'' I responded with a certain inexact
wryness. I understood exactly how my friend felt. Everything around
us is changing _ and changing fast. And from the looks of things,
the changes of the future will only come faster.
 &HT;    Jaron Lanier, who coined the term ``virtual reality,'' says,
``There's a perception that things are going to change at such a
rapid rate that at some point (in the future) something very
dramatic will change about the fundamental situation of people in
the universe.''
 &HT;    Futurist Stephen Bertman says we are feeling the effects of
``hyperculture,'' where the social environment becomes so fluid
that the acceleration of one activity tends to induce acceleration
in other activities.
 &HT;    Much of what we are experiencing is a result of technological
innovation that has occurred in just the past 30 years. Speed
begets speed.
 &HT;    When the O jays recorded ``For the Love of Money'' in the early
1970s, the first microchip had barely been created. Today, the
average car has more computing power in the glove compartment than
did the Lunar landing craft, which landed on the moon in 1968, the
year Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. was assassinated.
 &HT;    In 1977, the president of Digital Computing told the World
Future Society that ``there was no need for anyone to own a
personal computer in their home.'' In 2000, we already are in the
post-PC world and into the world of www _ the World Wide Web,
protocol for which did not even exist until 1993, after Bill
Clinton became president.
 &HT;    Just more than a decade ago, only the wealthy could afford a
cellular phone at a cost of $1,500. Now these phones are
practically free and the number of wireless customers in the United
States has jumped to 79 million from 16 million a decade ago, says
the Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association.
 &HT;    Cell-phone manufacturer Nokia estimates there will be 1 billion
wireless phone users around the world by 2002. In Tanzania and
Ghana, school kids keep in touch using a wireless local loop with a
combination of pagers and wireless pay phones. And while many of us
still cling to the African adage, ``It takes a village to raise a
child,'' we now find ourselves on the Web creating a
``cybervillage'' in chat rooms instead of sitting on the front
porch.
 &HT;    After hearing the latest hit record by the Supremes, teen-agers
used to run to the nearest H.L. Green's drug store to purchase a
single 45 record. Perhaps as early as 2002, teen-agers will create
their own personalized, ubiquitous music streams of digital radio
featuring Sam Cooke, Otis Redding, Marvin Gaye, Lauryn Hill or
anyone from any source on the globe.
 &HT;    When the Voting Rights Act of 1965 was passed, who could have
ever imagined that blacks would one day vote without leaving home?
E-voting (electronic voting) is already being tested in three
states, and, by as early as the next election cycle in 2002, some
states may offer voters the convenience of casting their e-ballots,
not only from their home, but from their job, church or any place
in the world.
 &HT;    You could be able to use your phone, television or even your
digital Web TV browser.
 &HT;    Remember when politicians used to spend money to get out the
vote, or people worried that blacks might stay home on election
day? Wonder what Dr. King would say if he were alive today?
 &HT;    But look at what other changes lie ahead. By the end of 2000, we
may see the completion of the Human Genome Project, the
international effort to locate, decode and sequence the estimated
100,000 genes that comprise the human genome.
 &HT;    By March 2005, IBM expects to complete development of its
computer ``Blue Gene'' that will be 1 million times faster than the
average desktop computer and 500 times speedier than the fastest
computer today. It will perform 1 million billion mathematical
operations per second. This will be the first computer capable of
solving one of the most baffling mysteries of the human body: how
proteins are formed.
 &HT;    By 2007, computer programs will not only be written, but will
actually be grown fusing biology and technology to create computer
programs trained to do certain diagnostic tasks, including
correcting itself.
 &HT;    By 2020, your grandchildren will be born with their DNA encoded
and will likely be implanted with some kind of genetic DNA chip and
can expect to live to 2120.
 &HT;    When will things slow down? Not anytime soon.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Nat Irvin is a contributing columnist to Emerge magazine.) 
 &HT;    -----
 c. 2000 Emerge magazine  
