A0148 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-ONLINE-LIFE-COACHES-$     03-17 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-LIFE-COACHES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T GET A LIFE? GET A LIFE COACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, March 19) 
(DW) 
 By PENELOPE GREEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time INC., the publisher of In Style magazine, has
just created its antidote: a new publication called Real Simple. I
subscribed immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine comes on the heels of a book, ``Home Comforts: The
Art and Science of Keeping House'' by Cheryl Mendelson (Scribner,
1999), which explains in patient detail how to make hospital
corners, fold laundry, remove stains, freeze food, tune a piano and
build a hearth fire. The 884-page manual is No. 11 on Amazon.com's
best-seller list. Let me repeat: a book on housekeeping basics is
ranked No. 11 on a best-seller list. I bought it, too.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fascinating aspirational trajectory, from House Beautiful
to House Clean.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Glamour magazine suggests ``50 Tricks for
Outstanding Orgasms.'' Please, who has the time? Besides, I have to
do my taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Which may explain why enrollment is up at Coach U., an online
educational company that trains people to be ``life coaches,''
members of a growing profession that instructs clients in so-called
life skills. More than 5,000 life coaches are now practicing, said
Sandy Vila, president of Coach U., which began with a few students
in 1992 and now boasts a yearly enrollment of about 1,300.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches in training study topics like relating, listening and
empowering, the better to offer clients advice on the fine points
of managing their lives: take a nap, take a bath, write a letter,
pay your taxes. Old-school motivational gurus like Tony Robbins
exhort clients to ``Awaken the giant within!'' Life coaches just
want you to take it one day at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a coach does is help people deal with the world at
large,'' said Cheryl Richardson, a bubbly life coach who publishes
a weekly Internet newsletter called Life Makeover for the Year 2000
and is the author of ``Take Time for Your Life: A Personal Coach's
7-Step Program for Creating the Life You Want'' (Broadway Books,
1999).
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like practical strategists that help people learn new
life skills,'' she said. ``It's obvious stuff, really, like saying
to a client, as I've done, `It's OK to tell your friends not to
send you any more junk e-mail.' The larger picture is that in an
adrenaline-based culture like ours, people's adrenal systems are so
fried they almost can't physically slow down. They come to life
coaching to learn how to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Beck, another life coach, who is the author of ``Breaking
Point: Why Women Fall Apart and How They Can Re-Create Their
Lives,'' said: ``Life is just too damn hard right now. There are no
rules, and in some ways it's tragic, and in some ways it's magical.
Let's see what you can make out of it. I think this is the reason
you're hearing a lot about life coaches right now. The workplace is
specifically set up to take all the energy of a single person. You
combine that with the needs of young children or elderly parents,
and it's a tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaching is a profession of the new media. Coaches train at the
virtual Coach U. and advertise their services on the Web. Most
sessions are phoners _ clients pay $200 to $900 a month for four
half-hour sessions _ with bonus e-mails between calls. There are
coaches with degrees in business, law, sociology, psychology and
social work. And there are coaches with no degrees at all. It is an
unregulated, can-do profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you feel stressed out?'' one coach asks. ``Achieve
balance,'' another coaxes. ``Discover your natural talents and core
values and have more time, energy and fun!'' Buzzwords like
self-care and authentic come up again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Who doesn't need a life coach? I had a sample session not long
ago, more than an hour's worth of phone time with Richardson, who
no longer takes private clients. A lot of life coaches are full up.
Beck told me she ``runs from clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was funny and prescriptive: The ZIP drive you bought
last summer? Unwrap it and plug it in, she told me. You say your
brain is fried? No more Page Six after dinner. No magazines in the
bathtub. Read a novel. Call your friends. Call four friends. Call
me!
</P>
<P>
   Choking on work? Take a walk. Get a tape recorder. Use it. Don't
be negative, even in jest. Change your language. Don't say
``loser.'' Say anything else. Say ``jelly bean!''
</P>
<P>
   Jelly bean?
</P>
<P>
   ``Jelly bean. Need a resource? Call me, I've got the best data
bank in the country. Need to connect? I've got a teleconferencing
bridge I hardly use. You try it, it's yours.''
</P>
<P>
   It was marvelous. Perhaps I could just move in with Richardson.
I bet she sends her laundry out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1713EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
