<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-THREE-OH-BIRTHDAY-$AD     03-17 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THREE-OH-BIRTHDAY-$ADV19-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY WHAT? YOU WISH! 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The invitation last month promised a big birthday
bash in a private room at City Hall, a TriBeCa restaurant. The
fashion designer summoned nearly three dozen friends from New York,
East Hampton and Palm Beach to witness as she blew out the candles
on a tarte Tatin, marking what she announced was her 29th birthday.
This was to be the last year of her go-go 20s, and she wanted the
world to know.
</P>
<P>
   There was just one problem. The birthday girl's arithmetic was
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could she be turning 29 when we were in the same class in
kindergarten and I'm turning 31,'' said one of her friends, who
asked not to be named to save the birthday girl embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Three-Oh is a milestone that many approach with a
mixture of ambivalence and dread. It marks the twilight of youth, a
bringing down of the curtain on life's first act, and many chose to
observe it very quietly or ignore it altogether.
</P>
<P>
   But not so another kind of birthday baby increasingly common in
New York. She kicks up as much fuss as possible, inviting friends
and acquaintances to a blow-out. It's all a charade, because the
real milestone being passed is 32 or 33 or 34, but this celebrator
hopes to shave a few years off her age in as public a display as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of women I know on the Upper East Side wouldn't dream of
celebrating their 30th birthday until they are at least 34,'' said
Kristina Stewart, the society editor of Vanity Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Fibbing about one's age is nothing new, of course. Women have
long done it, giving rise to the taboo against asking a ``lady''
her age, and the coy expression ``a woman of a certain age,'' which
refers to anyone from 50-ish to 70-ish.
</P>
<P>
   But lying about age seems to have become more aggressive, more
elaborate and _ most surprising _ the province of ever younger
women, including many in their 20s who would seem to be so dewey
with youth that lying should be unnecessary. Yet they do, at ever
more tender ages. And men are beginning to join them.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Peregrin and Kristie Tippner, both 22-year-old seniors
at Syracuse University, have already started telling people that
they are still 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long, we wanted to be older,'' said Peregrin, an
economics major. ``You can't wait to drive at 16. Then you can't
wait to leave home at 18. You can drink at 21. But then after 21,
it's all about buying beauty cream.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friend, Tippner, an advertising major, said, ``I'm already
looking at the lines under my eyes in pictures and it bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Hanley, another Syracuse student, who is majoring in
public relations, is still 21. ``I'm going to say I'm 21 until I'm
30,'' she said. ``What's the advantage of being older? Your health
declines, your husband leaves you for another woman and you can't
find a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere Naomi Wolf, the author of ``The Beauty Myth'' (Morrow,
1991), is softly weeping. She and countless other feminists have
spent decades trying to convince women, men and society at large
that a woman's worth transcends appearances. But to hear many young
women tell it, those efforts have changed little.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-something women who fudge their birthdays say they get
the message that they must be younger, ever younger, to succeed at
love, at work and in the marketplace as a catered-to consumer. And
many cultural critics back them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Girl _ capital T, capital G _ is it,'' said Susan Faludi,
author of ``Backlash: The Undeclared War Against Women (Crown,
1991). ``It is what is most valued and what is rewarded with fame
and fortune, because we live in a visual, entertainment, ornamental
culture. What is valued is image and appearance and youth, and it's
what makes the consumer culture run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Ally McBeal compared to the women on `Cagney and
Lacey.''' ``They were not conventionally cookie-cutter attractive;
they were basically middle-aged and looked it. But now you're
supposed to be middle-aged and look like you're 15. Ally McBeal
doesn't look like any grown-up lawyer. She looks like a teen-ager
dressed in career-mommy clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood, our most potent image factory, worships youth
on-screen and off. It is an industry that pairs over-50 male stars
like Harrison Ford with under-30 love interests like Anne Heche,
and it's a town where not long ago a 32-year-old television writer,
Riley Weston, famously pretended to be 19 to get work on
``Felicity,'' the WB show dealing with teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Actresses have always been expected to ``play younger'' than
they really are, so their fictions about age hardly raise an
eyebrow. But what is new is how many people in nonpublic walks of
life feel pressured to play younger, too.
</P>
<P>
   Deserving some of the blame may be the playground called the
Internet. The business pages are full of dot-com wunderkinds who
have made a million by age 30. Investment bankers bring home
six-figure compensation packages in their mid-20s. So workers in
other industries feel pressure to demonstrate that they, too, have
achieved impressive success very early in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're 27 and doing well, then it's OK to say you're 27,''
explained Stephanie DiIorio, who is in fact 27 and a restaurant
consultant in New York. ``But if you're not. ... Well, let's say I
could see getting to 30 and being 30 for five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ploys to shave off years and deceive friends, lovers and
colleagues have become more elaborate, like the 30th-birthday-party
charade. Another ploy, useful to those in the public eye, is to
give a fictional age to a newspaper or magazine; the fake statistic
is inevitably picked up and repeated so often it becomes part of
the record and a fact checker's truth.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Taylor Stein, a party-loving young woman about town who until
recently ran the restaurant Brown's on East 61st Street, told The
New York Times she was 29 for a profile last April. Stein now
admits that she fibbed _ and that she does so regularly when it
comes to age. (Stein still will not reveal her age. ``Age is a
number; mine's unlisted,'' she said.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as your age goes up, your market value goes down,
unlike real estate,'' Stein said. She admitted the foolishness of
the effort: ``It's all about insecurity. Do you think two years
makes a difference?''
</P>
<P>
   James Tully, 31, an artist in Manhattan, described a woman he
dated for a number of years who had a remarkable ability to reverse
time. ``The first year we started dating she was 27, and her age
progressed naturally for three years,'' he said. ``Then all of
sudden, when she hit 30, she went down to 28. I kept getting
confused because she kept getting younger and younger.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever he tried to pin her down, she would get upset. ``She
was so insistent, and unless you wanted to invite an irrational
harangue, you would leave the subject alone,'' he said. ``In my own
mind, I'm keeping track, and she must be about 35 now, though she
pretends to hover around 30.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached for a comment while driving down a highway in
California, the woman insisted she had to pull over before
addressing Tully's version of events. She promised to call back on
her cell phone, but never did.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, one group of Manhattanites who were classmates at the
Nightingale-Bamford School, the all-girls private school on East
92nd Street, made a pact to collectively revise the year of their
graduation. Instead of admitting they graduated in 1986, which pegs
them as 31 today, these half-dozen women all cite 1991 as the date
they received their diplomas, making them 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us more time,'' said one of the women in the group,
who is single, doesn't work and volunteers on junior charity
committees. ``When you're not married and don't have a career, New
York can be harsh on women. Men can be harsh on women.''
</P>
<P>
   Many women make no apologies for lying about their age. If
society _ men, the workplace, popular culture _ is going to
conspire against them, they reason, then they will make up whatever
age suits them.
</P>
<P>
   Eve Packer, a tutor who works from her Manhattan home, said she
lies always, changing her age each day depending on her mood. ``I
feel like it's a weapon used against women; it's like a club,'' she
said. ``If you're 29, then they look at you like, Why aren't you
19? Or if you're 39, then they say, `Why aren't you 25?' People
size you up by your age.''
</P>
<P>
   When Marie Claire magazine recently polled 100 men and 100 women
about everyday lies they tell, Michele Lavery, the deputy editor,
was shocked by the results. ``The degree to which people lie
unconsciously is really surprising,'' she said. The survey found
that people lie about almost everything: whether they are working
late, if they thought the sex was great, and yes, how old they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women only lie about being younger than they are, while men
lie up and down depending on who they are trying to impress,''
Lavery said.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Vasquez, 32, a home attendant from Paramus, N.J., has no
qualms about pretending to be 25 to attract younger women. ``I tell
them I'm 25 so I don't scare them off,'' he said. ``Young girls
don't like older men, because they think older men are possessive
and like to control young girls. I like them to think I'm on their
level.''
</P>
<P>
   He eventually reveals the truth. ``I tell them after I've been
with them,'' he said. ``After I've bought them things. You have to
buy them things, then you have them.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that lying about one's age is so pervasive, and accepted
in some quarters almost as a matter of course, can there be
anything wrong with it?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, said Sissela Bok, author of the 1978 book ``Lying: Moral
Choice in Public and Private Life'' (Vintage Books). Lying about
one's age puts one on a slippery slope toward more serious
falsehoods, she said. ``Once a person engages in a series of lies,
then they have to keep telling more and more lies to support the
first one,'' said Bok, who is an interim director of the Harvard
Center for Population and Development Studies. ``Now that they've
started, it becomes very hard to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Although small lies may not not seem to hurt anyone, Bok said,
the liar is frequently the one who suffers. ``People trust
themselves less if they know others cannot trust them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Bok said, it erodes one's credibility on larger
matters; once someone learns you've lied about your age, they will
be disinclined to trust you on larger matters. All this lying leads
to ``a kind of pollution to society,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And how old is Bok?
</P>
<P>
   She hesitated a long moment.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she answered: ``65.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
