<HEADER>
A0163 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     03-17 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS YOUR PC POSSESSED?   
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   My favorite kind of newspaper headline is the one that asks a
question to which anybody in his or her right mind already knows
the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can New York save itself?'' (Of course not.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Do special interests control our government?'' (Of course they
do.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Are our kids exposed to too much TV violence?'' (Only when the
set is turned on.)
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I was so smitten by a headline I recently saw in
Weekly World News, the New York Times of tabloid journalism: ``Is
Your Computer Possessed by a Demon?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there are one or two people out there who do not think
their computer is possessed by a demon. Maybe they don't like the
word ``demon.'' Maybe they'd prefer ``poltergeist'' or ``fiend'' or
the rather generic ``evil spirit.'' It is possible, of course, that
different kinds of demons inhabit different computers.
</P>
<P>
   The demon in my computer, for instance, is rather predictable
and unimaginative. (I have no idea where he picks that up from.)
His favorite line, regardless of the circumstances, is ``You have
performed an illegal operation and the computer will be shut
down.'' There is no discussion, no debate and no amount of
pleading, whining or crying will make my computer's demon change
its mind.
</P>
<P>
   This is not unusual. According to the Reverend Jim Peasboro,
author of the upcoming book, ``The Devil in the Machine,'' one in
10 computers in America contains some sort of evil spirit or demon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any PC built after 1985 has the storage capacity to house an
evil spirit,'' Peasboro told the newspaper. The Savannah, Ga.,
clergyman said he became aware of the problem from counseling
churchgoers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that many members of my congregation became in touch
with a dark force whenever they used their computers,'' he said.
``Decent, happily married family men were drawn irresistibly to
pornographic Web sites and forced to witness unspeakable
abominations.'' (You decent, happily married family men may want to
try this excuse on your wife who up until now probably assumed that
your witness of unspeakable abominations was strictly voluntary.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you're going to get to the cold, dark,
silicon-encrusted heart of computer demons, you've got to meet the
beast in person, and that's what Peasboro did. He logged on to a
parishioner's computer himself and immediately an
``artificial-intelligence'' program fired up without him even
clicking on it. (This happens to me all the time, by the way.)
</P>
<P>
   After typing out a few brief insults, just to get warmed up, the
computer then ``went haywire'' and printed out what looked like
gobbledygook. ``I later had an expert in dead languages examine the
text,'' the minister said. ``It turned out to be a stream of
obscenities written in a 2,800-year-old Mesopotamian dialect!''
</P>
<P>
   (This certainly is a plausible explanation for the strange stuff
that appears on my computer screen, but I wonder if it would be
worth it to keep an expert in dead languages on 24-hour call.)
</P>
<P>
   So what's the solution? Peasboro advises that if you suspect
your computer is possessed (and, of course, you know it is), you
consult a clergyman or, if the computer is still under warranty,
take it in for servicing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technicians can replace the hard drive and reinstall the
software, getting rid of the wicked spirit permanently.''
</P>
<P>
   Permanently or until such time as your new computer starts
spewing ancient Mesopotamian obscenities, whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
