<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, March 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The storm that produced as much as eight inches of snow in
Portland, Maine, and brisk winds between 20 and 35 miles an hour at
Boston Friday will slide farther off the Northeast Coast Saturday,
setting the stage for ample sunshine and diminishing winds. In its
wake, a halcyon high pressure system will build over the Northeast
Seaboard, paving the way for clear skies and calm winds Saturday
night. As a result, temperatures will fall into the teens and
single digits across much of the Northeast by dawn Sunday, with
some readings in the 20s in traditionally warmer large urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, showers and thunderstorms will likely develop over
east Texas later Saturday or Saturday evening in response to a jet
stream disturbance arriving from the southern Rockies. Saturday
night, showers and thunderstorms will forge east toward the
Mississippi Valley. Ahead of this disturbance, earlier in the day,
broken areas of rain will form across the western Gulf States as
moist air from the Gulf of Mexico flows inland.
</P>
<P>
   Areas of rain and mountain snow will develop early Saturday
across western Washington and western Oregon as a cold front
arrives from the west. Rain will then graduate into more sporadic
showers as a jet stream disturbance trailing the cold front
arrives. A rumble of thunder is possible in northwest Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The northern Plains will turn milder this weekend as Pacific air
warms on its eastward descent from the Rockies. Temperatures Sunday
afternoon could reach 60 degrees as far north as South Dakota. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Nipped in the Bud
</P>
<P>
   Last week, record-setting warmth enveloped areas of the Middle
West and Northeast that typically are just emerging from months of
wintry chill at this time of year. But, there can be a price to pay
for premature warmth. Blossoms on many trees swelled last week,
coaxed from their winter hibernation by several days with afternoon
temperatures in the 70s and low 80s. Now, a surge of wintry chill
has spread over the same area, which can cause damage to some kinds
of flora. Later in the spring when blossoms are more advanced,
frosty nights can be especially devastating to fruit trees. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
