<P>
   NOTE: CORRECTED VOTE CHART WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions
regarding this transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100,
ext. 227. WASHINGTON, March 17 -- The following chart shows how
senators and representatives voted on key bills and amendments
within the last week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the
measure; an ``N'' means the member voted against the measure; a
``?'' means the member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member
voted ``present.''
</P>
<P>
   THERE ARE NO SENATE VOTES THIS WEEK.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: AVIATION
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 319-101, a three-year $40
billion authorization for the Federal Aviation Administration for
programs through 2003. The bill, which has been approved by a
conference of House and Senate lawmakers, provides nearly $10
billion for airport improvements and safety grants, and allows
airports to increase flight traffic and raise passenger taxes.
Supporters said the bill would make airports safer and help
low-volume airports become more economically viable. Opponents said
the bill would increase the amount of flights at busy airports. A
``yes'' vote favors the authorization.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: PROPERTY
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 226-182, a measure that would
permit land developers to appeal state and local zoning decisions
in federal court. Private property owners would be able to appeal
cases if initial development applications are denied at the local
level. Supporters say it prevents private land owners from getting
caught in years of state-level litigation. Opponents say it
benefits big development companies who can circumvent local
authorities and take their case to federal coaurts. A ``yes'' vote
favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
