<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-SHOOTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER ACTIVIST H. RAP BROWN SOUGHT FOR SHOOTING OFFICERS IN
ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT1 and 2 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta's police chief said Friday that one of two
sheriff's deputies who were wounded in a shootout while trying to
serve a warrant has identified his assailant as a Muslim cleric who
was known in the 1960s as H. Rap Brown, a leader of the Black
Panther party. And the chief, Beverly Harvard, said authorities had
initiated a nationwide search for him.
</P>
<P>
   The two deputies from the Fulton County Sheriff's Office were
shot and seriously wounded near downtown Atlanta late Thursday
night while serving a warrant at the home of Brown, now known as
Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin. Authorities said the shooter escaped after
being wounded by one of the deputies, and sheriff's officials said
they were looking for Amin.
</P>
<P>
   They released a description of the man that seemed to match that
of the former militant: 6 feet, 4 inches and thin, with graying
hair.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Aldranon English was conscious but in serious condition
Friday at Grady Memorial Hospital and the second deputy, Ricky
Kinchen, was in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday, Harvard said English had
``positively identified'' Amin ``as the person who fired upon the
two deputies.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Sheriff Jackie Barrett said the deputies went to a
community store owned by Amin to try to serve a warrant against him
issued by suburban Cobb County for failing to appear in court in
January on charges of theft by receiving stolen property,
impersonating an officer and having no proof of insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff said the officers did not know that Amin was the
former Black Panthers militant. He was imprisoned for five years in
the 1970s in New York, convicted of attempted armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both officers kind of walked into this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said that after no one answered their knocks at the
door, the deputies noticed a black Mercedes nearby and approached
the car. She said they told the driver they could not see his hands
and ordered him to step out of the car. She said when the driver
stepped from the car he declared ``here are my hands'' and then
opened fire with an assault rifle, striking both officers, who were
wearing bullet-proof vests. The driver continued to fire at the
officers after they fell to the ground, Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
   The officers were able to return fire as their assailant fled
and English told investigators that he believed the man was hit.
</P>
<P>
   English identified his assailant as Amin after he picked him
from a collection of photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police conducted an intense manhunt in a four-block area
of southwest Atlanta surrounding Amin's mosque and home. As
helicopters hovered overhead, SWAT teams and police dogs searched
every home in the area, at one point following a trail of blood
that led to a neighbor's house, which turned out to be empty.
</P>
<P>
   Amin has lived in Atlanta for about 25 years, leading the
Community Mosque and running a small grocery store. In the 1960s
and '70s, when he was known as H. Rap Brown, he led the Student
Non-Violent Coordinating Committee, and was justice minister of the
Black Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a neighborhood resident accused Amin of having shot
him, but later recanted the accusation after saying that police had
pressured him into making the identification. Amin's lawyer said at
the time that the police were looking for any excuse to charge Amin
with a major crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
