<SLUG> BC-LIFE-MAGAZINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE MAGAZINE WILL CEASE REGULAR PUBLICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DANIEL J. WAKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Life magazine, which died in 1972 as a weekly
publication only to be resuscitated six years later and showcased
generations of prominent photographers as America's premier picture
magazine, will cease regular publication after its May issue, its
parent company, Time Inc., said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Life will still come out periodically in special issues, some of
which will commemorate ``milestone events,'' Time said in a
statement. Life will continue to publish books and will launch a
web-based business.
</P>
<P>
   Life, which was once a pillar of Henry Luce's publishing empire,
becomes a traditional media casualty in an industry with an
increasing Internet presence. In a statement, Don Logan, chairman
of Time Inc., and Norman Pearlstine, the company's editor-in-chief,
called Life a valuable and honored franchise whose name deserves to
be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, despite the exceptional efforts of a number of
talented publishers and editors, the publishing formula for a
monthly general interest magazine was just not sustainable,'' they
said.
</P>
<P>
   Logan and Pearlstine said the ``new strategy would be the best
way to maintain the Life brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Luce conceived Life in 1936 and published the first issue on
Nov. 23. The start-up team included Alfred Eisenstaedt, who became
one of the century's most influential photo-journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Life ceased publication as a weekly in 1972, but continued to
appear as special issues before returning as a monthly in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The original magazine distinguished itself in refining the craft
of modern photojournalism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER18-COX     03-17 1662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Where the voters are
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a march of thousands _ and a key event in New York for Rudy
Giuliani and Hillary Clinton. The Irish Gay and Lesbian
Organization was banned from marching in the St. Patrick's Day
parade, but the two New York Senate candidates were in the
spotlight. Giuliani, the city's mayor, was near the front as usual.
Before Friday, Clinton had never walked up Fifth Avenue on St.
Patrick's Day.
</P>
<P>
   SCORING POINTS WITH THE ECONOMY
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has convinced much of the public that he can keep the
strong economy going, and that has helped him gain ground on George
W. Bush, suggests a new survey by Republican and Democratic
pollsters. A Voter.com-Battleground poll released Friday showed
Bush ahead 48 percent to 44 percent. But Gore, who decided last
summer to focus more heavily on his economic role in the Clinton
administration, is getting more credit for his abilities on that
issue. And that has played a role in cutting the double-digit
margin Bush held last year, the poll indicated. The poll has a 3
percentage point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT ABOUT THOSE LOCAL SCHOOL BOARDS?
</P>
<P>
   Taking direct aim at Al Gore, George W. Bush is kicking off the
general election ad wars with sharp criticism of the Clinton
administration's education record in a TV spot in a few
battleground states. Bush is charging that reading scores have
stagnated and American students have continued to rank near the
bottom in math tests. ``Gore and Clinton had eight years, but
they've failed,'' the 60-second ad says. It also touts Bush's
record in Texas on education and his goals for the presidency. The
ads will run through Tuesday in southern Illinois stations that
reach into Kentucky, Iowa and Missouri. Illinois' primary is
Tuesday, but the ad is clearly intended as early groundwork for the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   SHOULDERING THE GUN ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   After George W. Bush aligned himself with conservative groups
during the primary campaign, he is trying to shift back toward the
political center for the general election. Al Gore says Bush does
the bidding of the gun lobby; Bush strongly denies it. Bush's
effort at fence-mending came as he fended off fresh criticism from
Gore and waded into the nasty dispute between the National Rifle
Association and President Clinton. He said the NRA had ``gone too
far'' by accusing Clinton of having ``blood on his hands'' for
failing to enforce gun laws before a deadly shooting last year in
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   MENDING FENCES WITH THE VANQUISHED
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush put the positive spin on his relationship with
John McCain after seeming dismissive of his defeated rival in a
published interview. Bush demonstrated respect by saying that he
and McCain could make a dynamic duo in Washington, with the senator
and would-be president working together on issues such as
overhauling campaign financing and shoring up Social Security.
Earlier, Bush said things like this to the New York Times: ``Well,
then, how come he didn't win?'' and ``No, he didn't change my
views.'' McCain supporters said such ``macho talk'' had harmed
hopes for an early endorsement of Bush that could be vital to a win
in November.
</P>
<P>
   AT LEAST ONE BATTLE LEFT IN THE WAR
</P>
<P>
   John McCain also may decide to withhold an endorsement of George
W. Bush if Bush tries to replace McCain delegates with his own
supporters at the national convention in Philadelphia. Although it
may seem like little more than a parliamentary issue, having loyal
delegates at the convention is a matter of necessity and pride for
McCain. By having supporters fill the 239 delegate slots he won, he
could use his convention soldiers for one last stand: to influence
platform issues such as campaign finance reform or to suspend
convention rules.
</P>
<P>
   SELLING TAX CUTS, COMPASSION
</P>
<P>
   Feeling comfortable after winning the GOP nomination, George W.
Bush acknowledged that he needs to do a better job selling his
tax-cut plan to the American people, as well as to the Republicans
who narrowly control the House. In an interview with the Chicago
Tribune, Bush also conceded he must reach out to John McCain's
supporters to defeat Al Gore in the fall. And while he insisted
that he had not abandoned his message of compassionate conservatism
to appeal to the party's social and religious right during the
primary campaign, he indicated he plans to move back toward the
center.
</P>
<P>
   CRANKING UP THE MONEY MACHINE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's Illinois swing marked his return to the
fund-raising circuit for the first time since mid-December. His
$1,000-a-person event in Wheaton on Thursday was expected to raise
$100,000. The Bush team plans to raise up to $10 million in the
next two months because his record-shattering $73 million campaign
fund has been largely depleted by the contest with John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   WATCH SOME HOOPS THIS WEEKEND?
</P>
<P>
   Both contenders, George W. Bush and Al Gore, were taking a long
weekend off the campaign trail, with Gore staying at home in
Washington and Bush spending the time at his ranch outside Waco,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   EIGHT MONTHS LEFT TO SPEND A LOT MORE
</P>
<P>
   More than $114 million has been spent or committed to
advertising by outside groups seeking to influence elections this
cycle _ a record, according to a report released Friday. One in
four ads deal with health care, principally efforts to defeat the
patients' bill of rights and to influence the debate over including
prescription drugs in Medicare, according to the study by the
Annenberg Public Policy Center at the University of Pennsylvania.
There are more attack ads than in previous years, with about 40
percent of them attacking a candidate or specific legislation. In
the 1995-96 election cycle, the center estimated that $135 million
to $150 million was spent on issue ads by 27 organizations.
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S THIS KENNEDY CHALLENGER?
</P>
<P>
   Jack E. Robinson III, 39, the Republican challenger who just
jumped in against 38-year Sen. Ted Kennedy (D-Mass.), is a
Boston-born African-American businessman whose father once headed
the city's NAACP chapter. He's seeking to become the third
popularly elected African-American U.S. senator. He has never held
political office. State Republican leaders, though, see him as the
party's last best hope to go against Kennedy, in part because the
state has a strong civil rights record, but also because they
believe his fiscally conservative, socially moderate approach to
politics, including support for abortion rights, will appeal to a
broad spectrum of Massachusetts voters. The last African-American
senator, Edward Brooke, also was from Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   IRS AS POLITICAL WEAPON
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush said an unsuccessful attempt by Al Gore's vice
presidential office to get IRS information for a labor union raises
``serious ethical questions.'' Bush called on Gore to further
explain the 1997 contacts, which were deemed improper by
investigators for Congress' bipartisan Joint Taxation Committee.
Gore's office called the 1997 contacts by two aides ``a simple
status check.'' But the committee report said the information the
aides sought appears to have been protected by tax confidentiality
laws. The report's main focus was to answer allegations from
nonprofit conservative groups that they were audited because of
their anti-Clinton views.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION AS A POLITICAL WEAPON
</P>
<P>
   Republican national Chairman Jim Nicholson re-injected religion
into partisan politics this week by calling on Al Gore to repudiate
two abortion-rights organizations _ the National Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League, known as NARAL, and Women
Leaders Online _ that have called for a review of the Vatican's
status at the United Nations. ``As a Catholic, I am appalled that
Al Gore has courted the support of two groups trying to throw the
Vatican out of the United Nations,'' Nicholson said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   YOU ALWAYS HURT THE ONES YOU LOVE
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan acknowledged that his White House bid may hurt the
Republican Party he has loved, but said he must run to promote the
causes he believes in. A two-time GOP presidential candidate now
seeking the Reform Party nomination, Buchanan said his candidacy
may syphon votes away from Republican George W. Bush, possibly
hurting the party's chances of reclaiming the presidency. But he
said his causes would be ignored if he didn't run.
</P>
<P>
   AFTER RUNOFF, THERE'S A TOUGHER FIGHT
</P>
<P>
   A runoff next month will determine which Democrat will take on
Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison (R-Texas) in the general election this
fall. Retired Air Force lawyer Gene Kelly was the top vote-getter
in the Democratic U.S. Senate primary Tuesday, but didn't receive
the majority needed for outright victory.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly got 35.8 percent in the five-way race, according to
unofficial final results from the secretary of state's office.
Charles Gandy, a former one-term state legislator, got 22.7
percent, one-tenth of a point above the third-place finisher.
</P>
<P>
   ORGANIZING FOR OFFICE-HOLDING
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney was in New York to promote an
ambitious effort by big labor to have at least 2,000 union members
run for office nationwide this year _ from campaigns for school
boards to campaigns for Congress. Too many of the nation's elected
officials, he said, come from big wealth, with at least one of
every four members of Congress being a millionaire. But, he
declared, big labor's ``2,000 in 2000'' program would help rectify
that by ensuring that the voices of the less well-off were
represented in the halls of power.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
