A0230 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-GORE-HNS &LR;      03-17 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AD ATTACKS GORE ON EDUCATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ George W. Bush's first television commercial of
his general election presidential campaign against Vice President
Al Gore promises a ``crusade'' to improve education while giving
Gore a failing grade when it comes to helping the nation's schools.
</P>
<P>
   The ad is airing through Tuesday only in Illinois but is
reaching viewers in three surrounding states. Populated with
smiling children, the ad has decidedly negative comments about
Gore, although a Bush spokesman insisted the dominant message was a
positive one about Bush's plans to offer ``a fresh start for
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign blasted the minute-long advertisement as a
distortion of Gore's record.
</P>
<P>
   An ad by the Gore camp hits right back.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush _ from South Carolina to New York he used dirty
politics to trash John McCain's record. Now he's running attack ads
against Al Gore,'' the ad says.
</P>
<P>
   ``No amount of negative advertising can hide the fact that
Bush's only real agenda item is a risky tax scheme that would leave
nothing to invest in schools and could force deep cuts in
education,'' Gore spokesman Doug Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has challenged Bush to forgo television advertising, but
Bush refused the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The ad, which is timed to stir interest in next week's
inconsequential Illinois GOP presidential primary as well as to
influence November voters, poses this question: ``Is the status quo
in America's schools good enough?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Al Gore and Bill Clinton, national reading scores
stagnated. America's high school students placed almost dead last
in international math tests. The achievement gap between poor and
non-poor students remains wide. Gore and Clinton had eight years,
but they failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the positive pitch, the ad states Bush will ``fight
for reforms hailed as the most fundamental in a generation,''
including more accountability for teachers and students, and
increased federal funding for public schools without jeopardizing
local control.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said ``this is the first ad of the
fall campaign and we think it is never too early to talk about the
importance of education. It's a positive education spot, while Al
Gore is masquerading as somebody who's done well on education,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer said the negative statements about Gore were based on
U.S. Department of Education data from 1996 and 1998, including
nationwide math and reading scores.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
