<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0235 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-UNRULY-PASSENGER-1STL     03-17 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNRULY-PASSENGER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PASSENGERS HELP RESTRAIN MAN WHO THREATENS FLIGHT CREW 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Complete writethru, adds details, quotes  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUSTINO AGUILA and SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A man described as a well-respected in his
Missouri hometown was in federal custody Friday for allegedly
threatening the crew of an Alaska Airlines flight and breaking into
the cockpit of a San Francisco-bound jet.
</P>
<P>
   Peter L. Bradley Jr., 40, of Blue Springs, Mo., was released
from Mills Peninsula Hospital after treatment for injuries and
taken into custody by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   During the bizarre incident Thursday evening aboard Alaska
Airlines Flight 259, the highly agitated passenger alternately
muttered about ``love lost'' and threatened to kill everyone aboard
the plane, according to the police and passengers.
</P>
<P>
   But no motive was apparent, said Sgt. Joe Reilly of the San
Francisco police, who speculated that Bradley might have been on
drugs or alcohol, or in need of psychiatric medication.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who answered the phone at Bradley's home Friday morning
said she was stunned by the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not in his character. He's a wonderful person,''
said Janice McGrath, who described herself as a close friend of the
Bradley family for more than 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   She said Bradley was a professional who was well respected in
his community, though she declined to give further details.
</P>
<P>
   The incident began about 7:10 p.m. Thursday, as the jet,
returning from Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, was some 160 miles south of
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had been acting in a strange manner early in the flight,
repeatedly changing his seat, talking nonsense to other passengers,
sweating profusely and taking off his socks and shirt, Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   The crew, including the pilot, asked him to remain seated
several times, but he disobeyed them, Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley eventually took a seat in the first-class section, he
said. There he simulated a gun with his hand and allegedly
threatened, ```I'm going to kill all of you; keep away from me,'''
Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers were horrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them didn't think they were going to make it,'' said
passenger Robert Benjamin, 56, of West Linn, Ore. ``Families were
crying.''
</P>
<P>
   As flight attendants continued to coax Bradley back to his seat,
he became angry and threatened them. Soon after, he forced open the
cockpit door and lunged at the plane's controls, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The co-pilot, whom the authorities did not identify, already had
been alerted and armed himself with a tool in case of attack,
Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   As flight attendants continued to coax the man back to his seat,
he became angry and threatened them. Soon after, he forced open the
cockpit door and lunged at the controls of the jet, the police
said. The co-pilot tried to block the passenger from the controls
and the two men scuffled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The co-pilot was able to do a body block,'' Reilly said,
adding that Bradley weighs about 250 pounds and is 6-feet-2-inches
tall.
</P>
<P>
   As the two men fought, the co-pilot suffered cuts to his right
hand as the passenger tried to get the tool _ described by the
police as a pick-like instrument _ away from him.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot called for help and was quickly aided by seven
passengers. They and the crew subdued Bradley and forced him to the
floor where he was bound with plastic restraints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately all the guys moved quick and he ain't dead and
we're not dead,'' Benjamin said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot requested an emergency landing at the San Francisco
International Airport, where law enforcement officers met the
flight shortly before 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the jet landed, airport tower officials already had
received an ``alert 1'' message, meaning there was an emergency on
the plane, said Philip Meginness, an airport duty manager.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was taken into the custody of FBI agents. Threatening
the crew of an airplane is a federal offense.
</P>
<P>
   Meginness said Bradley was taken by ambulance to Mills-Peninsula
Hospital in Burlingame with bruises and cuts to his face. The
co-pilot also was taken to a hospital for treatment of cuts to his
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't overemphasize the heroics that went on tonight,'' said
Reilly, referring to the passengers' and crew's actions. ``They
averted a tremendous disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft went on from San Francisco to Portland, Ore.,
arriving at 12:50 a.m. Friday. The plane was carrying 43 passengers
and five crew members, according to Alaska Airlines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
