<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0272 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-POLL-2000-HNS &LR;      03-17 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLL-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLL SHOWS RISING PESSIMISM, A PLUS FOR BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the curtain rises on the presidential campaign
between Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a new
bipartisan poll shows that voters are in an increasingly
pessimistic mood about the state of the nation _ a trend that could
help Bush if it keeps up.
</P>
<P>
   Rising gas prices, stock market gyrations and the shooting death
of a six-year-old girl by a boy of the same age last month in
Michigan led 43 percent of respondents in the Voter.Com
Battleground 2000 Poll to say the United States is on the wrong
track. Forty-four percent said the nation is on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   That split compares to the same poll in January when 49 percent
saw the country heading in the right direction while 40 said it was
going wrong. Throughout the economic boom of the 1990s, polls
generally have tracked an upbeat mood which in turn fueled
President Clinton's re-election in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, ``a little nervousness is a good thing for Al
Gore,'' said Celinda Lake, a Democratic pollster who is part of the
team that has done the Battleground Poll for nine years. ``When
voters are a little jittery, they are less likely to jump ship and
more likely to look for experience to continue prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   But a continued downturn in the national mood, ``then obviously
that would be bad for the Democrats,'' Lake said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the poll of 1,000 voters found Bush, the likely
Republican presidential nominee, leading Gore, the presumptive
Democratic nominee, 47 percent to 44 percent, with 9 percent
undecided. The survey was conducted Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With Democrats vying to regain a foothold of power on Capitol
Hill, the poll showed that the congressional race was an even
41-percent-to-41-percent split between Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   With a 3.1 percentage point margin of error, the poll's
presidential result also is a virtual tie.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush advantage, however, is in line with other recent polls.
The latest USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll earlier this week, for
instance, found Bush leading Gore 49 percent to 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With the primary battle now over, the opening act of the
head-to-head 2000 campaign poses more immediate problems for Gore
than Bush, the poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   With key constituencies that have been Democratic in recent
elections, Bush is either ahead of Gore or dead even. Among these
constituencies are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mothers with children at home. The so-called soccer moms,
mostly white suburbanites who voted heavily for Clinton in 1996,
are favoring Bush over Gore by 55 percent to 37 percent. But
overall among women _ including African-Americans, women over 65
and working women _ Gore has a four point lead over Bush.
</P>
<P>
   _ Catholics, a traditional Democratic constituency. Despite some
negative fallout for Bush after his Feb. 2 appearance at Bob Jones
University, a conservative Christian school in South Carolina whose
leaders have made anti-Catholic statements, Bush and Gore split
these voters at 47 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hispanics, another strong Democratic group. Hispanics favor
Bush by a margin of 51 percent to 45 percent. But Gore's showing
has improved since the January poll, when Bush led Gore 51 percent
to 38 percent. And by a better than 2-to-1 margin, Hispanics voted
for Gore over Bush in California's March 7 primary.
</P>
<P>
   So far, ``there's not any obvious one or two issues grabbing the
attention of the voters,'' said Ed Goeas, a Republican pollster who
heads up the GOP side of the Battleground Poll.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case in other polls, moral values ranks as the
No. 1 issue among respondents at 18 percent. Among mothers, 28
percent said moral values was their top issue. ``Moral values'' is
a catchall category that incorporates such things as Clinton and
the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal, X-rated rock lyrics, as well as
the shootings in Michigan last month and at Columbine High School
in Littleton, Colo., last year.
</P>
<P>
   Voters concerned about moral values tend to favor Bush. On the
question of personal characteristics, Bush leads Gore in terms of
``strength,'' ``trustworthiness'' and ``vision.'' But Gore leads
Bush on ``experience'' and as the candidate who ``cares about
people like you.''
</P>
<P>
   Among issues, education is No. 2 with 13 percent. Education is a
slim plus for Gore, with 44 percent of respondents favoring Gore as
the candidate who can do a better job, compared to 42 percent for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also leads Bush on health care and propping up Social
Security. But Bush leads Gore on holding the line on taxes and
maintaining economic prosperity. On gun control the two are evenly
split.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The two recently departed challengers, Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., and former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, a Democrat, would
have only a small impact as running mates to their respective
parties' nominees.
</P>
<P>
   McCain would bump Bush's overall number up slightly _ from 47
percent to 48 percent. Bradley, however, would drag Gore down two
points to 42 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1818EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
