<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0279 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-FOREIGN-POLICY-     03-17 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-FOREIGN-POLICY-$ADV19-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT TO DECIDE WHETHER STATES CAN SET TRADE POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 19)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Balancing moral values against a company's right to
do business overseas, the U.S. Supreme Court this week examines
whether cities and states can have their own foreign policy and
impose economic sanctions on countries with repressive regimes.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a Massachusetts law that prevents the commonwealth
government from making purchases from companies that do business
with Myanmar, also known as Burma. The court will hear arguments on
the case Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The broader issue in the case is whether trade restrictions
imposed by states and local governments infringe on the federal
government's constitutional role as the nation's arbiter of foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court is going to have to decide whether the United States
speaks with one voice on foreign policy or if each state will be
able to make its own, at least in terms of economic sanctions,''
said Peter Spiro, an expert on international law at Hofstra
University in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of state and local governments have passed laws that
restrict business with firms operating in such countries as China,
Cuba, Nigeria and Sudan. Some cities also have said they will not
do business with global firms that operate sweatshops abroad or
that fail to pay a living wage.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the statutes say cities and states are making foreign
policy decisions that should be left to the federal government. In
1998, a coalition of 34 firms represented by the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce and the National Foreign Trade Association (NFTA),
challenged the Massachusetts law.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the companies had business ties to Myanmar, which
prevented them from bidding for contracts with the commonwealth
government.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts enacted the so-called Myanmar law to protest the
government jailing in 1996 of Nobel Peace Prize winner Aung San Suu
Kyi, who overwhelming won a 1990 presidential election but was
never allowed to take the post.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union and Japan also joined the lawsuit, saying
firms in Britain, Germany or Japan should not be forced to choose
between doing business with Myanmar or Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The founding fathers did not intend for Massachusetts to make
foreign policy,'' NFTA Vice President Dan O'Flaherty said.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, the First Circuit Court of Appeals in Boston agreed
and struck down the law. Writing for the appeals court, Judge
Sandra L. Lynch said that while there was no dispute over the
``deplorable'' conditions imposed by the military government in
Myanmar, a state had no constitutional authority to regulate
conduct beyond its borders. Myanmar _ one of the world's poorest
countries, according the United Nations _ has been ruled for 38
years by a military dictatorship that has brutally put down several
democratic movements.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said the Massachusetts law was a ``direct attempt to
regulate the flow of foreign commerce,'' an activity that was the
responsibility of the federal government under the foreign commerce
clause of the Constitution. That clause of Article I gives Congress
the power to ``regulate commerce with foreign nations.''Lynch,
noting that there are 39,000 different state and local governments
in the United States, said there was the potential for trade chaos
if many others followed the Massachusetts model.
</P>
<P>
   The commonwealth law ``interferes with the ability of the
federal government to speak with one voice,'' Lynch wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In its appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court, Massachusetts argued
that nothing in the Constitution ``requires the states to trade
with dictators.''Commonwealth attorneys also noted that 23 states
and 80 cities once had laws restricting purchases from firms with
interests in South Africa to protest that country's policy of
racial Apartheid. ``Nothing in our federal Constitution denies to
the states the right to apply a moral standard to their spending
decisions,'' the commonwealth brief said.Several state and local
governments as well as nonprofit and human rights organizations
asked the court to overturn the decision by the appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the people of Massachusetts want to use their economy to
punish a dictatorship, they should be allowed to do that,'' said
Nick Penniman, spokesman for the Alliance for Democracy, a
Boston-based, human rights group.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups, which won the case in lower courts, also asked
the high court take the case so that the ruling by the appeals
court would be binding on the rest of the country. ``Burma is not a
big deal in terms of money, but other laws around the country have
restrictions on companies doing business in China and other
countries with huge markets,'' O'Flaherty said.
</P>
<P>
   Spiro said the case poses a tricky choice between two court
doctrines: the preeminence of the federal government in foreign
policy and trade, and the court's growing interest in
reinvigorating the role of states at the expense of federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Spiro said he expects the court will come down on the side of
state sovereignty and rule in favor of Massachusetts. He said that
with the Cold War over, foreign policy issues have taken a back
seat to domestic debates in the eyes of the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, if Massachusetts offended the Soviets, the
next thing you know we're in the World War III,'' Spiro said. ``But
today, with the Cold War over and huge amounts of foreign
investment across the United States, foreign governments are used
to dealing with state and local governments.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Spiro said that because economics has become so
important in global relations, giving states the ability to impose
trade sanctions would mean the federal government would lose one of
its most power weapons in dealing with other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about it, it's not that often that the
president or Congress orders our military into action to force
another country to do something,'' he said. ``Most of the time, the
U.S. government uses economics sanctions, and this case could
change all that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
