<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0283 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GAS-PRICES-$ADV19-HNS     03-17 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-PRICES-$ADV19-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LEADERS HOPE TO ZIP `GAS CRISIS' PAST VOTERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, March 19) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gas prices may be high, but Republican leaders hope
to get a lot of mileage by creating an election-year ``gas crisis''
campaign they can use against the Democrats and Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressional leaders, led by House Majority Whip Tom
DeLay of Texas, staged a protest last week at a Washington, D.C.,
Exxon station to spin a tale about a Clinton administration they
said has no energy policy to deal with rising gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, joined by House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas and
GOP Conference Chairman J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, accused the
administration of holding down domestic oil production, which he
said has caused an over-dependence on foreign oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``These gas prices are out of control,'' DeLay said, standing
near a sign advertising regular gas at a $1.68 a gallon. ``In the
real world skyrocketing costs like these cause real pain to working
Americans and families who are forced to absorb the hit of
needlessly high prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This administration has done nothing to alleviate the
problem,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The staged protest is an example of how Republicans are trying
to exploit the plight of car-dependent Americans in an effort to
turn the price increase into a serious political problem, which
could help them defeat likely Democratic presidential nominee Gore
and Democratic incumbents this fall. But at the moment, they seem
as uncertain about what to do about high prices as the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If gas prices maybe yo-yo ... and end up with prices going up
significantly more ... that could turn into a serious issue (for
Gore),'' said congressional scholar Norman Ornstein, a senior
fellow at the American Enterprise Institute in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But at the moment, he said Republicans can't expect to raise
doubts among voters about the solidness of the economy with
``antics'' such as holding a news conference at a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now most Americans seem to think this a temporary thing
... because they understand the laws of supply and demand,''
Ornstein said, adding that Americans also understand that Congress
has some responsibility, along with the president, for setting
energy policy.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart made a similar
observation when he was asked to comment on DeLay's demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Republican Congress that for a long time ... hasn't
wanted to move on things like energy efficiency,'' Lockhart said.
``And it's time (for them) to get ... out of the gas stations for
your, you know, political grandstanding, and start getting to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the steady rise in gas prices since last summer, the
Republican leadership has shown little incentive to tackle the
problem with congressional action of their own, such as rolling
back the 4.3-cent federal gasoline tax or approving alternative
energy proposals designed to lessen U.S. consumption and dependence
on oil.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, they have dusted off and reintroduced
legislation that would allow drilling in the Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge, but that measure is not expected to make it to a
vote anytime soon. The administration is still opposed to that
approach because of environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic lawmakers called last week for a halt in the export
of Alaskan crude oil to Japan and other Asian countries, which
began in 1995 after a heavy lobbying effort by Republican lawmakers
from Alaska. The Democrats said a halt in the Alaskan exports,
which amount to about 60,000 barrels a day, could help ease prices.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumed
Republican presidential nominee, appeared last week to endorse the
idea of a temporary gas tax roll back while urging the
administration to take a stronger hand with oil-rich Middle Eastern
states the United States rescued from Saddam Hussein's grip in the
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   At first, GOP lawmakers sounded like they would go along with a
roll back on the gas revenue, which they've taken to calling the
``Gore tax'' because the vice president cast the tie-breaking vote
in the Senate that put the tax in place in 1993 to help balance the
federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   But by week's end, they joined Bush in backing away from the
idea because it might force states to increase local taxes to pay
for highway and bridge projects that are now funded in large part
by the federal gasoline tax. Republicans also heeded the warning of
consumer experts who advised that cutting the small federal tax
would not help much to lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Armey, for example, cautioned his GOP colleagues against getting
``bogged down,'' as he put it, ``on only one dimension of the
problem.'' He called a temporary repeal of the gas tax ``a
short-term dimension that offers scant relief.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the position Gore has staked out on the campaign trail.
In a series of interviews last week, he rejected the roll back
proposal precisely because it would force some states to increase
their own taxes on gasoline. The state and local taxes on gas are
already much higher than the federal tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're talking about is not the solution,'' Gore said,
adding that he hopes that ``tough negotiations'' now being
conducted with the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
will result in increased production, which will drive prices lower.
</P>
<P>
   The OPEC group meets March 27 and Gore said statements from its
oil ministers in recent days seem to indicate that they will vote
to raise production.
</P>
<P>
   He said the administration had emphasized in its talks with the
ministers that stable oil prices are not only important to the
economic well-being of the United States, but to the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has not ruled out other options for bringing
down prices, however, including possible trade and other sanctions
against OPEC nations and the possible release of U.S. oil reserves
stockpiled for use in wartime or some other national emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans in Congress hope to force a vote this week on
legislation that would force Clinton to withhold U.S. aid to
countries that engage in oil ``price-fixing.'' But Clinton already
has that authority under an executive powers statute granting him
unilateral powers to deal with national emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Even if OPEC ministers decide to increase production, it may be
several months or more before prices begin to come down and
stabilize. Democrats fear that if the high oil prices continue much
longer, they could give rise to inflation in other economic
sectors. There are already signs of that happening with increases
last month in producer prices and a hike in interest rates to help
keep inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   There will likely be another interest rate increase this month
to help fend off inflation and slow the economy, and financial
experts say there could be one or two more before the November
elections. That could create a huge political problem for Gore,
whose presidential campaign is built in part on a gamble that the
unprecedented U.S. economic boom will continue at least through the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   If the boom starts to show serious signs of sputtering before
then, it could give Bush and Republicans the opening they need to
challenge Gore on economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, public opinion is still on Gore's side.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans, according to a CNN/Gallop poll last week,
believe the current rise in gasoline prices is only temporary and
has not yet reached the level of a ``crisis,'' as Republicans are
attempting to portray it.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent demonstration against high diesel fuel costs by
truckers on Capitol Hill was another indication that public opinion
could quickly turn if relief from the higher prices doesn't arrive
soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
