<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-LEATHER-PROTESTS-ART-     03-17 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEATHER-PROTESTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHING THE LEATHER CROWD HOW TO STRAY FROM THE HERD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By NANCY HASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Outside a Gap store near Rockefeller Center late last
week, People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals kicked off its
new multimillion dollar campaign against leather. Flanked by a few
dozen protesters, Chrissie Hynde, the lead singer of the
Pretenders, in black microfiber boots and a cowboy hat, held up a
sign deploring the chain's use of leather from Indian cows.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, two teen-agers from Westchester County, just outside New
York, were battling out the question that has been bugging fashion
insiders in recent weeks: Can the animal rights group make leather,
of all things, unfashionable?
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally believe that leather is totally disgusting,'' said
Sarah Stearns, 16, who became a vegetarian on New Year's Eve. She
was dressed in a vintage peasant blouse and jeans. ``I think it's
barbaric. It makes me want to throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sister, Hannah, 15, shuddered beneath her oversize black
leather jacket. She was wearing imitation Fendi pony skin slides
and fingering a butter-colored suede shirt on the rack. ``You,''
she said, glancing at Sarah venomously, ``make me want to throw
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Their mother, Melanie Stearns, a social worker, smiled
painfully. ``Great,'' she said, her voice weary. ``We need a whole
new source of fights in the house. After all, the girls don't have
any fur to argue about. But I'm standing here thinking about shoes.
And belts. And how much I don't want to hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   It may seem surprising that the animal rights group is trying to
make leather the new fur now, considering the setbacks it has
suffered this last season. Dozens of designers returned to fur, and
overall fur sales rose 10 percent this winter. One might think the
group would go after more modest game. Instead, activists are
girding for what they call ``The Big One.'' They are convinced they
can coax and sloganize leather into a state of political
incorrectness.
</P>
<P>
   But that seems unlikely. Leather hasn't been as popular since
the Paleolithic period. Not only do most people consider it
synonymous with high-quality footwear, but this spring stores are
bulging with leather and exotic skins. Once seen as a winter
fabric, leather is now even being made into thin pastel suedes for
summer, washable white leather shirts and whisper-light calfskin
tankinis. Kidskin capris, Pucci slacks in pink and blue and python
sling-back shoes are best sellers at Jeffrey, the latest downtown
temple of style.
</P>
<P>
   Commune, a new restaurant in the Flatiron district, is set to
open in April with a 28-foot all-leather bar. And the April cover
of Harper's Bazaar will show the model Gisele, navel bared, in a
white Armani leather jacket. The magazine has never before put
leather on the cover so late in the year. ``Before, leather was
only seen as a sort of tough fabric, communicating only coolness
and fierceness,'' said Bazaar's editor in chief, Kate Betts. ``Now
it means everything.'' The Leather Apparel Association, a trade
group, said that leather sales have nearly tripled this decade, to
$2.7 billion last year from about $900 million in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some signs of a dissenting faction bubbling within
the core of the fashion world. People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals, or PETA, says it hopes that Stella McCartney, the Chloe
designer, will become an icon of leather-free chic. There is
widespread belief that McCartney _ the daughter of Paul and the
late Linda McCartney, staunch animal rights campaigners, and
herself a supporter of the group _ was offered the job as Gucci's
top designer but turned it down because of her aversion to working
with leather and fur. The idea that a young hot designer could
declare leather inessential to fashion sent a chill down Seventh
Avenue. ``Stella is our hero,'' said Dan Mathews, a spokesman for
PETA.
</P>
<P>
   To zero in on the mass market, the animal rights group is
targeting the Gap in spite of the fact that the chain is not the
country's biggest leather retailer and gets only 10 percent of its
leather from India. The Gap offers a public relations opportunity.
Some months ago, the company, unfamiliar with Hynde's longtime
public support of animal rights, wrote the singer a letter, seeking
permission to use one of her songs in a commercial for its
``Everyone in Leather'' campaign. PETA orchestrated a media blitz,
releasing the letter just as it began its first nationwide round of
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Why single out Indian imports when China has also been
criticized roundly in the international press for its treatment of
cows and sells more than 10 times the amount of leather to
manufacturers in the United States? Because in many parts of India,
cows are sacred. Making martyrs of Indian religious symbols is
meant to appeal to those who embrace such fashionable spiritual
concerns as yoga, Free Tibet and Cabala.
</P>
<P>
   Even the spiritually stylish may balk at surrendering their
skins. Unlike fur, leather is a byproduct of meat. Many people
sympathetic to the plight of furry little chinchillas seem to draw
the line at cows and sheep, whose flesh is also put to use. ``I
have raised money for PETA, and I don't wear fur,'' said Marie
Carr, a shoe designer from Seattle who was in Manhattan last week
on a scouting trip. ``But I'm sorry: I'm not a vegetarian, and I
just don't have a problem wearing leather. I'm comfortable with
that line.''
</P>
<P>
   That distinction has been echoed lately by several models,
including Trish Goff and Audrey Marnay, who have told designers
that they will wear only the fur or skin of animals that are eaten.
Mathews said he got fed up with fickle models and designers during
the anti-fur campaign of PETA. Bruised by the defections of former
supporters like Naomi Campbell and Donna Karan, the animal rights
group is cultivating new Hollywood friends like Drew Barrymore and
Pamela Anderson Lee.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who once wore plenty of leather herself and has been in an
on-again, off-again marriage with Tommy Lee, the leather-loving
member of Motley Crue, narrates the group's new video about the
abuse of Indian cows.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, whether leather can be rendered unfashionable may
depend less on moral arm-twisting or celebrity cheerleading than on
technology. There are more leather alternatives available now than
ever before. Gone is the cheap vinyl, plastic-looking pleather and
stifling rubber of the 1970s and 80s. Huge advances in fabric
technology have produced new artificial materials that are almost
indistinguishable from real animal skin and are somewhat cheaper.
Other cellulose-based products, which are in fact a little more
expensive than leather, even breathe like natural fibers,
manufacturers claim.
</P>
<P>
   Some young, urban companies _ often bellwethers for wider trends
_ are churning out fake-leather goods to meet popular demand. In
January, Dr. Martens, the London-based company whose hulking black
leather lace-up boots came to define the punk movement, began to
make a nonleather ``vegetarian'' version of its two most popular
models. Made of Lorica, a cellulose-based fiber from Spain, they
are 15 percent more expensive than leather Dr. Martens, retailing
for about $135. Now available in only 50 stores and on some Web
sites, the shoes are set to get wider distribution as soon as Dr.
Martens can meet demand. The shoes are sold out until June.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Thome, a Dr. Martens spokesman, said that for years the
company had been getting an escalating number of requests for
nonleather Dr. Martens, but until recently, there was no material
sufficiently comfortable and enough like leather to use. He said he
saw no conflict in a company's built on the nihilistic anti-hippie
ethos of punk now making a so-called vegetarian shoe. Most Dr.
Martens employees, including Thome, are 30 or younger, and he said
the company prefers to think of the new shoes as ``yet another way
we're rooted in alternative culture.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes that ``the anti-P.C. thing is very two years
ago,'' adding, ``Social consciousness is set for a comeback as soon
as the stock market tanks.''
</P>
<P>
   The rap impresario and clothing designer Russell Simmons, whose
Phat Farm apparel is among the most sought-after by boys in the
'hood and in the 'burbs, said he is also producing two new ``PETA
friendly'' lines. No Animal Phat Farm, a collection of ``extremely
expensive,'' real-looking fake furs for his women's line, will be
introduced this fall. Skins, a men's line of jackets and suits made
from cottons and vinyls but treated to look like leather, will soon
be shipped to stores. The crown jewel of that collection will be a
vinyl suit with Phat Farm logos. The inspiration, Simmons said, was
``my childhood obsession with Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Armstrong. Vuitton.
</P>
<P>
   But Simmons, whose interest in producing nonanimal product lines
came from his recent conversion to veganism, the strict sort of
vegetarianism (no dairy, no wool clothing, no fish) espoused by
PETA, acknowledges that it will be tough to wean urban youths from
their love of leather. Even his own business plan points up the
essentially quixotic nature of the anti-leather quest. Much of the
Phat Farm line is made of leather and will continue to be. Despite
his own bias, the sales are too robust to pass up ``just yet,'' he
said, adding that he is committed eventually to abandon it.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Simmons' own life, leather is a hard habit to break. ``I
admit I'm wearing leather shoes,'' he said in a phone interview.
``And sometimes at a party I may even go for a shrimp. I'm not
perfect, but I'm striving to be, like we say in yoga. Basically,
life is aspirational. I think you can still be against leather
while you are wearing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1824EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BMW-ROVER-885&AMP;ADD-NYT     03-17 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BMW-ROVER-885&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AUTOWORKERS UNEASY ABOUT ROVER ACQUISITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGBRIDGE, England _ Around the same time that Jon Moulton, the
British venture capitalist who has just acquired Rover cars from
BMW of Germany, was laying out his strategy in London on Friday,
Andy McNeil, a worker at the Rover plant here, was pondering how he
would pay the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Moulton, 49, appeared before reporters in a button-down shirt
and business suit at an auditorium near the Strand. He told them
job reductions were inevitable as the Rover brand faded, to be
replaced by the MG marque under his new MG Car Co.
</P>
<P>
   McNeil, 37, fretted that he might be one of the losers. With
tattoos on his arms, gold rings in his ear, and hair plaited in a
slender ponytail, McNeil sipped a soda from a can under the chilly
gray skies outside the plant in central England and wondered out
loud what had happened since _ just five weeks ago _ BMW had hosted
an open day in the sprawl of Longbridge and had invited workers,
spouses and children.
</P>
<P>
   ```The future is here,' they said. `Everything's rosy,' they
said. But they've been negotiating this behind our backs for
months,'' McNeil said. ``And all they have been doing is telling us
lies.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's nothing new about downsizing caused by
deal-making. There's nothing unusual about the shock of cultures
and perceptions between the pin-striped barons of the boardroom and
the oil-stained grunts on the shop floor.
</P>
<P>
   But here, in a region that once was the emblem of the British
auto industry, the abrupt and secretive nature of BMW's exit has
led to a blend of emotions _ shock, betrayal, anger and despondency
_ that reverberates not just among the 9,000 workers here but
beyond to the 50,000 people who depend on the auto industry for
their livelihoods and on to the highest levels of the British
government.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those feelings are directed against BMW. Someone even
spray-painted a BMW dealership here with a single word: ``scum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really feels as if they have stolen our heritage,'' said
Nigel Hastilow, the regional director of the Institute of
Directors, a London-based business advocacy group, as the British
government traded accusations with BMW about who really was to
blame.
</P>
<P>
   The disposal of this Rover plant was part of a broader move by
BMW to quit a disastrous six-year effort to turn money-losing Rover
around. Apart from its deal with Moulton's Alchemy Partners venture
capital firm, BMW also sold Rover's profitable Land Rover sport
utility vehicle division at nearby Solihull to Ford Motor Co. for
$2.9 billion, retaining only a new line of Mini to be built at its
Oxford plant.
</P>
<P>
   Joachim Milberg, BMW's chief executive, blamed the strength of
the British pound, which rose in value from 2.2 Deutsche marks to
3.2 during BMW's tenure here, for much of the problem. Rover cars
became more expensive in Europe, while cheaper imports undercut
Rover's home market.
</P>
<P>
   Milberg went further at BMW's Munich headquarters on Friday,
saying Britain's decision to remain outside the European single
currency system did not help. ``The British government complicated
BMW's position with the ongoing debate over the euro,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That drew a furious response from Britain, which accused BMW of
excluding the government from the discussion about Rover's future _
a debate laden with extensive political fallout when thousands of
jobs may be lost in a region where the 9 percent unemployment rate
is almost twice the national average.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Prime Minister Tony Blair said his office had
expressed to BMW ``the prime minister's anger at the way we have
been treated.'' He added, ``The government has been kept in the
dark about BMW's intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Byers, the trade and industry minister, visited this
plant on the outskirts of Birmingham and said he was angry, too.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Rover workers who expressed the anger of those
who stand to lose the most. Mark Gardner, a 35-year-old
production-line worker at Longbridge, said that after BMW arranged
its upbeat open day last month, he decided to buy a house. He had
been due to sign the contract Friday night, he said, but was now
too uncertain of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last five years, we really slogged,'' Gardner said.
``We gave this company everything. We got nothing. But it didn't
matter how hard we worked: We had a future. What kind of a future
do we have now?''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the workers have been toiling harder, the Longbridge
plant, a 94-year-old sprawling patchwork of assembly shops
interspersed with some advanced BMW facilities, has failed to
improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   While each worker at Longbridge produces 31 cars per year,
Nissan workers in Britain's northeast each produce 105 cars per
year. Honda scores 64 and Toyota 72, industry figures show.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the cataclysmic changes looming in Longbridge may
not be as great as they might once have been. In the 1970s and
early 1980s, Longbridge's stubborn, strike-prone labor unions kept
staff levels at 25,000. The city is not as dependent on the motor
industry as it once was, partly because of a shift toward service
industries such as conference centers. But it is still a major
employer.
</P>
<P>
   Hastilow at the Institute of Directors estimated that up to
25,000 jobs in the supply business might be lost from the shrinkage
at Longbridge.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Worries about job security have been compounded by the lack of
information about the new owners. ``People know so little about
Alchemy that there's bound to be a great deal of skepticism and
anxiety about what they plan to do,'' Hastilow said.
</P>
<P>
   Moulton sought to offer some faint solace for the survivors,
saying that while some will inevitably lose their jobs, those who
remain ``are about to get a great opportunity'' in a company
focused on producing fewer than 100,000 aluminum-bodied cars,
compared with the 343,000 cars that Longbridge produced in 1997 and
180,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   People like McNeil and Marsden, though, said they saw
opportunities shrinking. Their pessimism was reinforced by a
colleague who handed them a management directive saying that they
would work shorter hours starting next week. ``It's the beginning
of the end, isn't it?'' McNeil said with a shrug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
