<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, March 17, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   ASBESTOS-AGENCY (Washington) _ Davitt McAteer has spent a lot of
time agonizing about how his agency, the Mine Safety and Health
Administration, should have done more to prevent the slow, painful
deaths of hundreds of miners, processing plant workers and their
families who died of exposure to asbestos. He says he's going to
``make damn sure that it doesn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Schneider. (Story will move in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS (Seattle) _ Four years ago, a new class of anti-AIDS drugs
brought hope that the deadly disease could become a chronic,
manageable condition such as diabetes. A few even spoke of a cure.
Today, a grim realization is dawning that for many people, the
``miracle'' drugs are only buying time. Precious little time.
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Paulson. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-CAMERON (Seattle) _ Timm Cameron is waiting for a miracle.
It wouldn't be his first. Cameron, 38, has AIDS. He's been on every
possible combination of currently available drugs, but they aren't
working for him any more. It isn't the first time for that, either.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-MIGLIORE (Burien, Wash.) _ Pat Migliore, 47, is one of the
few survivors of her generation of people with HIV. She has had HIV
since the early 1980s, the advent of the epidemic, and AIDS since
the early 1990s. So far, the ``miracle drugs'' of the 1990s are
working for her.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
