<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TITUS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 On FOX, `TITUS' LOOKS FOR THE `FUN' IN `DYSFUNCTIONAL'  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christopher Titus isn't the first to try to find the ``fun'' in
``dysfunctional.'' ``Married ... With Children'' tried it for 10
seasons on Fox, the same network that presents the series premiere
of ``Titus'' Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   While I never warmed to that meanwhile-back-at-the-raunch style
of ``Married ... With Children,'' I've now seen three episodes of
``Titus'' and must admit it just might grow on me. Like a fungus.
(Hey, another ``fun'' word!)
</P>
<P>
   ``Titus'' has fun with the sorts of things you're not supposed
to have fun with on television: mental illness, physical abuse,
alcoholism. It's all based on his own life, Christopher Titus
insists, as if that somehow makes bad taste excusable. Then again,
as he explains in one episode: ``Once you've driven a drunk father
to Mom's parole hearing, what else is there?''
</P>
<P>
   What else, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Titus, a successful stand-up comic and hot-rod enthusiast in
real life, plays the owner of a custom-car shop in his show, which
has an appealing impertinence at the same time that it might make
you go, ``Eew, I can't believe he said that!'' For instance, here's
Titus' father remarking on the fact that his ex-wife _ Titus's
mother _ has been hospitalized for manic-depressive schizophrenia:
``Your mom is shacked up in the wacko basket!''
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Keach, playing the hard-drinking dad who treats matrimony
as a sport in which the one with the most trips down the aisle is
the winner, makes it work with a brutal delivery of black humor.
Credit, too, a smart supporting cast featuring Zack Ward as Titus'
zany stepbrother, Dave; Cynthia Watros as his too-good-to-be-true
girlfriend, Erin, and David Shatraw as his anal-retentive best
friend, Tommy.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many new shows these days, this one knocks down the
fourth wall so Christopher Titus can address the audience directly.
It's fast becoming a threadbare device, but in Titus' standup-savvy
hands it's an amusing way to provide all the back-story details
that can gum up the works if a show is poorly scripted. The idea of
having Titus deliver this personal information in black and white,
from what appears to be an interrogation room illuminated by a
single lightbulb, is also a clever touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titus'' is a little like Fox's short-lived ``Action'' in its
willingness to go where TV comedies fear to tread. Its style is far
more conventional, with laughter from a studio audience punctuating
the funny lines. (Titus promises the laughter we hear is the real,
``unsweetened'' variety. If a particular episode is weak, he says,
it won't be juiced with a phony laugh track.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When we set the bar,'' Titus told critics recently, ``we
actually said, `Let's go back to ``All in the Family'' and the
great shows on television and try to do something like that as
opposed to smart-ass people yelling at each other.'''
</P>
<P>
   The danger lies down the road, if Titus the creator runs out of
real-life fodder for Titus the character. At that point, ``Titus''
could become a sitcommy caricature of itself. But, in the early
going, Titus is on the money when he says, ``Anything is funny if
the setup is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Titus. Half-hour comedy celebrating a dysfunctional family.
Starring Christopher Titus, Cynthia Watros, Stacy Keach, Zack Ward
and David Shatraw. Series premiere Monday night on Fox. Parental
guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1834EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
