<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUCKS-FEATURES-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEATURES TO CONSIDER WHEN TRUCK SHOPPING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Clarifies that not all all-wheel-drive models offer low range. l
and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why should you buy a truck-like vehicle? Conveniences,
flexibility, and safety are three good reasons. Trucks, according
to manufacturers, fall into three categories: pickups, sport
utilities, and minivans.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the things you should be considering when
shopping:
</P>
<P>
   Premium or regular: With gasoline prices nearing $1.80 a gallon
for premium fuels, check out the octane needs of the vehicle you
are looking at. Many SUVs require premium fuel. There are plenty
good SUV models which take just plain old regular octane gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Size: Your personal preferences will determine what size vehicle
you need. Are the truck's features only going to be used
occasionally? What will you be hauling: Lots of kids, cargo, or
some other combination? A pickup with a larger cab and an open
cargo bed could be used for family activities as well as hauling
yard trash or camping gear. A minivan might also serve your
purposes just as well. Consumer Reports found it could pack more
goods in the back of a minivan than a Jeep Grand Cherokee. The
Subaru Forester is a great choice for people who aren't looking for
a huge mass of vehicle, but one that offers all the plusses of an
SUV without being a gas-guzzler.
</P>
<P>
   Interior space: Newer pickup truck models which have rear
seating are now the rage. But not all these vehicles are created
equally when it comes to space. Even some supercab styles may offer
cramped seating for rear-seat passengers. Sport utilities come in
every size imaginable. If you really want space, consider the new
Chevrolet Suburban Tahoe or GMC Yukon. These are real people
carriers, and with rear seats removed, you can place sheets of
plywood on the floor inside. If you really need lots of room, look
to the Ford Excursion, with room for nine passengers plus cargo.
But size can be deceiving. Automobile magazine notes the Excursion
is only slightly bigger inside than the Suburban, and, because of
its size, cannot carry as much payload.
</P>
<P>
   Doors: The four-door pickup is here. But watch those doors. Some
are full-sized _ just like on cars _ and even open like car doors;
others are smaller and may only have door latches on the inside.
Consumers should also note how wide the doors open. The Dodge Quad
has rear doors that open to 90 degrees, making it easier to put
cargo as well as passengers in the back. The upcoming Chevrolet
Avalanche is designed to include a fifth door that opens onto the
bed, allowing extra-long items to be placed on an otherwise short
bed.
</P>
<P>
   Many minivans now have two side sliding doors which are
electrically controlled. The Chrysler Town &AMP; Country will soon
sport not only two electrically controlled side doors but also an
electrically controlled rear door.
</P>
<P>
   On SUVs, the Chevrolet Suburban and GMC Yukon are the only
models with a choice of rear doors. Buyers can choose between a
lift gate or a side-hinged rear cargo door.
</P>
<P>
   What drive? Two-wheel, four-wheel, all-wheel, part-time or
full-time: These are the choices. Just about every pickup truck and
SUV is available with a standard two-wheel-drive, similar to cars.
</P>
<P>
   Permanent four-wheel-drive vehicles have no two-wheel drive
option; these systems are effective in snow and mud and have a
differential that shifts power to wheels needing it. A low-range
drive is usually also found on these vehicles for off-road
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   All-wheel-drive handles all road conditions automatically. Power
is shifted between wheels as needed. Not all model models offer
low-range.
</P>
<P>
   Part-time four-wheel-drive operate on the road in
two-wheel-drive. If conditions call for four-wheel-drive, the
driver must select that mode with a lever or switch. Vehicles with
part-time 4WD do allow for ``shift on the fly'' to engage the
system. However, on these vehicles, the four-wheel-drive mode is
not suitable for use on dry pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Warranties: Check out what is covered on your vehicle and for
how long. Isuzu has expanded its powertrain warranty to 10 years,
120,000 miles on its Amigo, Rodeo, Trooper and VehiCross to cover
engine, transmission, steering assembly, suspension and axles.
Adjustment and maintenance items are not covered. The warranty is
only transferable to members of the original owner's family,
otherwise it reverts to a three-year, 50,000-mile warranty.
</P>
<P>
   Suspension: Isuzu's Rodeo and Amigo now have smart suspensions,
a new semiactive suspension system previously used only on luxury
cars and the Lexus LX470. The system increases comfort and reduces
oscillations in body roll. It is standard on models with Ironman
package and the top trim level of the Rodeo. It is not available on
the Trooper.
</P>
<P>
   On SUVs based on a car platform, the ride is much smoother than
on a vehicle with a truck platform. ABS: Antilock brakes prevent
lockups and provide straighter, quicker braking.
</P>
<P>
   Construction: Trucks originally were built on a solid frame,
cars on a unibody frame. The new Mitsubishi Montero has switched
from a frame construction to a unibody one for a more car-like
ride. In 1996, 31 of the 32 SUVs on the road had a truck platform;
by 2006, it is predicted that there will be 70 SUV nameplates, with
37 having truck-based platforms and 33 having car bases.
</P>
<P>
   Cargo bed: Once there were but two choices for pickups _ short
(6 feet) or long bed (8 feet). Then manufacturers built compact
pickups with narrow beds. Now come the blended pickup/SUV with even
shorter beds. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Notes: Minivans are almost all front-wheel-drive. Chrysler Town &AMP;
Country and the Dodge Caravan have all-wheel-drive options. Only
the Chevrolet Astro and GMC Safari are rear drive. All-wheel-drive
options are available on these models . . . Mercedes Benz has a
solid four-wheel independent suspension on its sports utilities,
giving these models a more carlike ride than othe SUVs.)
</P>
</TEXT>
