<HEADER>
A0310 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV19-B     03-17 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV19-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BAKSHEESH-POVERTY LINK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 19, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big problem of the poor is they don't have enough money. And
a large part of that problem is they can't get the help they need
because their local government is corrupt. Dr. Tom Durant of Mass
General, who left Boston for flood-stricken Mozambique Thursday for
the American Refugee Committee, said in virtually every disaster
relief operation of his 40 years experience, the problems are
exacerbated by ``the three `B's: bribery, bureaucracy, and
baksheesh,'' the term for petty payoffs to officialdom.
</P>
<P>
   To try to get a handle on what the poor want for themselves,
beyond more money, the World Bank commissioned a massive study
interviewing 60,000 poor people in 60 countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voices of the Poor'' found that poor people are victimized by
some of the very systems intended to ameliorate their lot. It's
Murphy's Law compounded on a global scale: if it ain't one thing,
it's another, and whatever can go wrong will.
</P>
<P>
   Pervasive and systemic corruption at the grassroots level on a
global scale among civic and governmental organizations makes it
very difficult to lift the congenitally poor our of poverty,
declared World Bank President James D. Wolfensohn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corruption hampers economic growth, burdens the poor
disproportionately, and undermines the effectiveness of investment
and aid,'' he told a global forum on corruption.
</P>
<P>
   And because corruption erodes trust, ``Poor men and women often
do not trust government officials,'' said Deepa Narayan, leader of
the World Bank study team. ``This is based on their daily
experiences with corrupt officials, their attempts to get teachers
to teach their children, their inability to get medicines from
health clinics even after they have paid for them. It's also based
on their efforts to seek justice, get police to protect them, and
get institutional assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The famous scene in ``The Godfather'' where an Italian immigrant
seeks the intervention of the Don exemplifies the inability of
people at the level of the peasantry to obtain relief from
governmental agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The poor have an almost universal fear of the rudeness,
humiliation or outright abuse that can result from a request for
help. ``They constantly say government has an important role to
play in their lives,'' said Narayan. ``But they are fed up with
being asked to participate, which takes time and costs them money,
without producing any returns.''
</P>
<P>
   The Archbishop of Canberbury, George Carey, critiqued the study,
and said ``The book communicates in a powerful way, the corruption
and often inhumane behavior of institutions that have direct
contact with the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   The poor have an all-too-keen understanding of how they are
being ripped off. A Bosnian testified about how local officials
stole the stove he'd been given by a UN program. A Ugandan woman
told of a long list of petty payoffs to get medical treatment.'' A
Ukranian worker amplified the mindset of those who find it morally
justified to steal from the state: ``The state steals from us all
the time so deceiving the state is not a sin.''
</P>
<P>
   How do you teach governments and peoples to be more honest? If
the World Bank could figure that out, it would succeed where the
world's religions failed. Constructing norms for human nature is
like building sand castles below the high tide mark. The study
focuses on identifying grass roots level corruption as a major
problem; stressing accountability and transparency in establishing
guidlelines; and rewarding honest behavior
</P>
<P>
   A different approach to alleviating poverty in the
hunger-fighting effort is being launched by Oxfam, which won a $2.9
million grant from the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, the
charitable donor arm of mighty Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are disadvantaged know what they want,'' said
Adrienne Leicester Smith of Boston's Oxfam America's headquarters.
Unlike the Peace Corps, which sends volunteers abroad, Oxfarm
focuses on grants to help local and national non-profits which have
ongoing programs at the local level.
</P>
<P>
   The Gates' grant will go for a project to train young American
college students under the rubric ``Campuses Helping Achieve a New
Global Environment.'' Not by accident, the acronym spells CHANGE.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have no idea that other people don't have food like we
do,'' said Smith. Oxfam already conducts the annual hunger banquets
on college campuses to raise awareness and channel the idealism of
young people to combat world hunger.
</P>
<P>
   There are 100 million Americans under the age of 24. These are
the people Oxfam must convert if it is to make substantial inroads
in the food shortgage that affects the planet's poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our population is not the cause of hunger,'' said Smith.
``There is actually a surplus.'' But getting the food to the hungry
has always been the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is campaigning in Congress for
legislation that would forgive some of the debt amassed by the poor
nations, many of whom cannot cope with explosive population growth,
shifting tides of economic well-being triggered by globalization of
the world economy, and natural disasters like the floods that have
just devastated Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Globe interview, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers
said the Clinton administration believes debt relief is one of the
best ways for America lift the world's poor. With one billion
humans living on the equivalent of a dollar a day or less, taxing
those desperately poor people to pay back loans to international
bankers or wealthier countries makes little sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the largest moral issue facing mankind,''
said Summers. He linked debt relief with the moral obligation of
wealthy nations to pay for vaccines that could save millions of
impoverished people. The US is owed about $920 million of the $28
billion in debt packed under the Cologne Debt Relief Initiative.
Last year, Congress appropriated $110 million for debt relief, and
the Clinton administration wants to bump that up another $210
million.
</P>
<P>
   So the Clinton crowd, the Catholic bishops, the Anglican and
Episcopal Churches and other Protestant denominations, have joined
with outfits like Oxfam to urge the forgiveness of debt.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's trying to do something; what are you doing?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist. Globe editorial assistant
Christian Meagher of Northeastern University contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
