<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, March 18 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-SMITH (Washington) _ Smith &AMP; Wesson has agreed to provide
safety locks on its handguns within 60 days and to make them
child-resistant within a year, the Clinton administration announced
Friday. Under the unprecedented deal reached with the company by
the departments of Housing and Urban Development and Treasury and
officials representing state and local governments, Smith &AMP; Wesson
agreed to a ``code of conduct'' for sales and distribution of
handguns. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6.
</P>
<P>
   WACO-REENACT (Waco, Texas) _ Early this Sunday, a select group
of government officials and private lawyers will meet at nearby
Fort Hood military base to watch an extraordinary experiment
intended to answer a question that has raged from Internet chat
rooms to the halls of Congress: Did federal agents fire gunshots
into the Branch Davidian compound occupied by David Koresh and his
followers shortly before the wooden structure burned to the ground
on April 19, 1993, claiming the lives of 80 men, women and
children? The furor over the incident at Waco remains one of the
most vexing issues still facing the Department of Justice in the
waning months of the Clinton Administration. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-U.S. (Washington) _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
on Friday lifted a narrow slice of America's broad economic
sanctions against Iran and declared a commitment to take far more
extensive steps toward ending two decades of hostility ``if Iran
indicates a desire and commitment to do so.'' In a speech here that
Clinton administration officials described as their most explicit
overture to the moderates who won Iranian parliamentary elections
last month, Albright described a road map for economic
normalization of relations, but she made no mention of a resumption
of full diplomatic relations. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ICONS (Pskov, Russia) _ God moves in mysterious ways,
except, maybe, in Pskov, a city that has monasteries and grand
churches and religious artifacts the way Americans have
remote-control clickers. It suggests why the Rev. Andrei Davydov
was plucked out of a parish in Latvia six years ago and deposited
in Pskov, in a troubled little church _ a church that, when the
Russian Orthodox patriarchate regained it in 1991, was found to
harbor several skeletons in the vestibule, a single bullet hole in
each cranium. Every church needs a good priest. But an artist, it
turned out, was what this church needed most of all. In Andrei it
got both. For him, icon art became an almost transcendental
obsession. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   VT-GAYS (Montpelier, Vt.) _ Now that Vermont is on the brink of
giving gay and lesbian couples all the benefits __ and legal
complications __ of marriage, gay couples reflect on what it's like
to face a decision that's never been an option for them. By Carey
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   CLOTHING-OPTIONAL-DORM (Middletown, Conn.) _ When a Wesleyan
University freshman applied to live in a dorm that advertised
itself as diverse, multicultural and politically active, she
thought it would be a welcome change from her small hometown in
California. But she soon found out what diverse and multicultural
really meant at the dorm: clothing optional. By Neil MacFarquhar.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-APPLIANCE (Undated) _ A Texas company called Netpliance
has spent millions to reach its target market: non-technical folks
who want a simple, inexpensive device that will connect them to the
Internet without the need for a full-fledged personal computer. So
it came as something of a surprise this week when an insatiable
demand for its product emerged from a network of self-described
geeks. They had figured out how to tweak the company's $99 device,
the I-opener, so that it works like the fancy PCs it is supposed to
transcend. The army of I-opener modifiers may provide some low-cost
computers to those who can't otherwise afford them. But they may
also spell trouble for Netpliance, which just started offering
shares to the public Friday. The company loses money on each
machine it sells. Profits come from the $21.95 it charges customers
to connect to its Internet service. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-OSCARS (Hollywood) _ Police are being asked to keep an
eye out for several dozen bald, shiny men standing about 13 inches
high and weighing 8 pounds each, with strangely erect posture,
vaguely Cycladic features and a tendency to make motion picture
professionals gush, weep and suddenly remember their parents. Just
two weeks after the Academy of Motion Pictures Arts and Sciences
was forced to resend 4,200 of this year's Oscar ballots because the
first batch had been mislaid by the U.S. Postal Service, the
academy had to announce Friday morning that somebody has stolen the
entire shipment of 55 gold-plated statuettes that were to be used
in this year's ceremonies on March 26 at Los Angeles' Shrine
Auditorium. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
