<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0318 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TV-VCHIP-BOS &LR;      03-17 1381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-VCHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS IGNORING V-CHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (e and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every day, television salesman Howard Raphel is peppered with
questions from customers about visual clarity, sound quality, or
features like picture-in-picture.
</P>
<P>
   But the one thing no customer asks about is the V-chip.
</P>
<P>
   Of the thousands of customers Raphel has dealt with in the nine
months since TV sets containing the V-chip became available, not a
single one has raised the issue with him. ``Most of them don't even
know what it means,'' said Raphel, who works for a suburban Boston
appliance store.
</P>
<P>
   What it means, at least in theory, is that parents now have a
technological tool to block violent or racy TV programs they don't
want their children to see. But in practice, to judge by interviews
with parents and retailers, the ``V'' in the much-ballyhooed V-chip
could stand for the gaping void in public awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard of it,'' said 47-year-old Debbie Nelson as
she shopped with her 13-year-old daughter in the electronics
department of Sears in Natick, Mass. Ten yards away, 44-year-old
Bill DiCarlo echoed that refrain, while salesman Jeff Dennis
remarked that only one person has asked him about the V-chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one cares about it,'' said Anne Marie Bouchet, spokeswoman
for the Tweeter Home Entertainment Group, which owns 15 stores in
Massachusetts. ``No one's asking for it. No one's basing their
purchase of a TV on the V-chip.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to be this way.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when President Clinton signed into law a bill
authorizing the V-chip, it was envisioned by its champions _
prominently including US Representative Edward Markey (D-Mass.) _
as a way for parents to defend their children against a TV industry
seemingly intent on swamping them with violence, sex, and
profanity.
</P>
<P>
   But now that TV sets containing V-chips are flooding into the
stores _ adding up to $50 to the overall price tag _ those same
parents appear to be oblivious to its existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main problem is there's no awareness of this,'' said
Federal Communications Commissioner Gloria Tristani, who chairs the
FCC's task force on the V-chip. ``I'm getting a little impatient,
hoping there can be a good public education campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   As of last July, the FCC required all manufacturers to include a
V-chip in half of all TVs with screens larger than 13 inches. Since
Jan. 1, a V-chip has been mandatory in all TVs over that size.
</P>
<P>
   Its use, however, is entirely optional. TV owners can block
objectionable shows by following a series of written and on-screen
instructions culminating in a menu of the ratings (such as TVMA for
Mature Audiences Only, or TV-PG for Parental Guidance Suggested)
that the networks agreed to put on their programs under pressure
from Congress. Once at the menu, viewers can activate the V-chip
and screen out any programs rated at a level they consider
inappropriate for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Though national TV sales are up 7 percent this year, retailers
don't pinpoint the V-chip as the reason, according to Lisa Fasold
of the Virginia-based Consumer Electronics Association. She says
the V-chip hasn't caused ``that much of a difference in the selling
of TV sets.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even as it struggles for acceptance, the V-chip
already faces competition from other technologies. Cable companies
like MediaOne and Cablevision, as well as satellite TV companies,
now offer customers set-top boxes that enable parents to block out
certain channels _ but not individual programs _ as part of their
cable package.
</P>
<P>
   ``The V-chip is almost redundant,'' said Bruce Leichtman,
director of media and entertainment strategy at the Yankee Group, a
Boston consulting and market-research firm. ``It's a little
ludicrous. This is what happens when government gets involved and
it shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The apparent public indifference to the V-chip is gratifying to
those who always opposed it as a form of governmental coercion.
``It at least has demonstrated that this is not going to be the
end-all and be-all that the government thought it would be,'' said
Marv Johnson, legislative counsel of the American Civil Liberties
Union.
</P>
<P>
   But Markey, who was principal congressional sponsor of the
V-chip legislation and popularized its name (``V'' standing for
violence), says the device was never intended to be more than ``an
option for families with small children.'' He argued that ``by
establishing the V-chip as a principle, we created a competition''
to create technologies that parents could use to block
objectionable programs, such as the set-top boxes the cable and
satellite industries devised.
</P>
<P>
   As for the V-chip itself, Markey argued that it will eventually
be embraced by ``a new generation of younger parents, more
technologically savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As television continues to lower its standards, I think that
we can expect more and more parents of this next generation of
children to take advantage of the technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, however, proponents of the V-chip are
disheartened, puzzled, and angry at the tepid reception for a
technology they believed parents would eagerly embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe how little publicity it's getting, given how
revolutionary it is,'' said Joanne Cantor, a communications
professor at the University of Wisconsin and author of ``Mommy, I'm
Scared: How TV and Movies Frighten Children and What We Can Do to
Protect Them.'' She contends that the V-chip ``could languish''
because the TV industry is ``keeping parents in the dark about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not to their advantage if a lot of people use the
V-chip,'' she said. ``Because the more people who use the V-chip
effectively, the fewer eyeballs will be delivered to advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   Tristani of the FCC faulted manufacturers, retailers, and some
newspapers for not making more viewers aware of the V-chip, and
said the networks have been erratic in airing public service
announcements about the V-chip. ``Some months they run a lot, some
months they haven't run any,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Montgomery, president of the Washington-based Center for
Media Education, agreed, saying the networks ``haven't really
promoted it effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the networks don't see it that way. At ABC, spokeswoman
Julie Hoover notes that the networks encode their programs with the
ratings that are vital to the V-chip, and insisted: ``The PSAs have
gotten exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   At CBS, senior vice president Martin Franks said PSAs regarding
the V-chip have run during such popular prime-time programs as
``Touched by an Angel'' and ``Diagnosis Murder.'' Franks said ``the
V-chip is as heavy in our current (PSA) rotation as about any other
cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the finger-pointing, there are signs that many consumers
still like the concept of the V-chip. Robyn Williams, the mother of
a 2-year-old daughter, said she favors the V-chip because ``there's
so much violence on TV that I don't think (children) should be
subjected to.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-year-old Evon, who declined to give her last name, said
she had not heard of the V-chip but can see its usefulness, noting
that her 7-year-old niece ``knows too many things, and I know it's
from TV.'' A mother of three shopping in the Chestnut Hill Mall
near Boston, who declined to give her name, said she likes the idea
of the V-chip because ``there are a lot of times we're out and
can't monitor all that they're watching.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for V-chip proponents is that though the public has
overwhelmingly supported the idea of the device in polls, their
words haven't yet been borne out by their actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes what the audience says they want doesn't necessarily
correspond with their behavior,'' said Meryl Marshall, president of
the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences. ``They'll tell you
they don't want violence, and then they'll watch the World
Wrestling Federation or Jerry Springer.''
</P>
<P>
   Tristani said that due to high-profile episodes of real-life
violence ``a very legitimate parental concern'' remains about TV
violence. She is convinced the V-chip will eventually catch on.
``I'm going to keep up my optimism,'' she said. ``This is still the
beginning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
