<HEADER>
A0320 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRAN-ALBRIGHT-BOS &LR;      03-17 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-ALBRIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT OUTLINES STEPS TO ELIMINATE BARRIERS WITH IRAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans will soon be able once again to buy
Persian carpets, Caspian caviar, and pistachio nuts from the fields
of Iran. But Secretary of State Madeleine Albright hopes that's
just the beginning of a new relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by Iran's ``refreshing'' youth-driven reform movement
and its third democratic election in three years, Albright
delivered a ground-breaking address Friday that the Clinton
administration hopes will eventually lead to the sight of two
enemies talking for the first time in 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   For Iranians, her most important words were likely those
recalling the two countries' poisonous history. She pointed not
only to the Iranian takeover of the US embassy in 1979, but also to
the Americans' ``significant role in orchestrating'' the 1953
overthrow of leftist Prime Minister Mohammed Mossadegh.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in Iran to this day blunt any inquiry about the US
embassy takeover and hostage-taking with anger over the way CIA
operatives crushed their nascent democracy nearly a half-century
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three hours after Albright spoke before the
American-Iranian Council, formed only three years ago to foster
better ties, Iranian Ambassador to the United Nations Mohammed Hadi
Nejad-Hoseinian told the same group that he welcomed the US measure
and said it ``will be reciprocated by Iran with a positive and
proportionate measure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian ambassador declined to offer specifics and took no
questions, but he cautioned not to expect a breakthrough, such as
the start of official talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems with the offer of dialogue is that the US
has made it in an insolent and domineering spirit, and not in a
real and practical spirit of mutual respect,'' Nejad-Hoseinian
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the extraordinary display of public diplomacy in a
ballroom of a northwest Washington hotel raised some hope for
breaking down what Albright and Nejad-Hoseinian each termed a
``wall of mistrust.''
</P>
<P>
   As a gesture of goodwill, US officials emailed copies of
Albright's address to Iranian officials in Tehran and New York
before she spoke, enabling Nejad-Hoseinian to offer a direct
response.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said the US would now take three steps: partially lift
sanctions to allow trade in carpets, caviar, nuts, and dried fruit;
find ways to end ``unnecessary impediments'' such as invasive
searches of Iranians at US airports; increase contacts between
Iranian and American scholars, artists, and athletes; and attempt
to settle all outstanding legal claims between the two countries
before a tribunal at the Hague.
</P>
<P>
   Still, US sanctions remain on Iranian oil, which provides Iran
with 85 percent of its foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
   And Albright's hopeful words were balanced by demands that Iran
end its alleged support for terrorism. ``It's important to us to
see some changes in terms of the policies on proliferation, their
desire to acquire weapons of mass destruction, their support for
terrorism and their lack of support for the Middle East peace
process,'' she said in a news conference after the speech.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, she said the two countries shared a
number of goals, such as wanting a more moderate government in
Afghanistan, guaranteeing the free flow of oil in the Persian Gulf,
and stopping narco-trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   In her speech, Albright also said the US-backed government of
Mohammed Reza Shah Pahlavi ``brutally repressed political
dissent,'' and that US support for Iraq during the eight-year
Iran-Iraq war was ``regrettably shortsighted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither Iran, nor we, can forget the past,'' Albright said.
``It has scarred us both.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, she explained why she raised the history of the
countries' relations: ``I think that it's important for the
American people and the Iranian people to know that there has been
a difficult history . . . on both sides, but I also said that it
was important not to be frozen by the past and to look toward the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``If all our policies were simply based on past
history, we wouldn't be speaking to the United Kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Such remarks should be well received in Iran, said Ali Sajjadi,
editor of Par Monthly Journal, which examines Iranian issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the eyes of Iranians in Iran, you have to be clear about
the past before starting a new relationship,'' Sajjadi said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what effect the US overture might have, Sajjadi said,
``God knows. The situation in Iran is so tense right now. The
speech is important, but this is not the first priority in Iran.
The first one is to solve the domestic problems, such as the
hardliners versus the reformers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Suzanne Maloney, a research associate at the Brookings
Institution who has spent four months over the past year in Iran,
said Albright's speech ``went far beyond'' what many expected in
terms of supporting a new US-Iranian relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Since reformist President Mohammed Khatami won election in May
1997, the administration has reacted cautiously on Iranian policy.
By comparison, Albright seemed bold Friday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always the potential for gestures like this to push
things forward, to shake things up very quickly,'' Maloney said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's speech drew mixed reaction in Congress, winning
support from three influential Republican senators _ Arlen Specter
of Pennsylvania, Chuck Hagel of Nebraska and Richard G. Lugar of
Indiana _ but Republican Senator Connie Mack of Florida denounced
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Principled foreign policy stands up to terrorism,'' Mack said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright herself remained cautious about what's ahead. But she
couldn't hide her hope that carpet-and-grain diplomacy could start
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something that happened inside Iran that indicates
that conceivably, maybe, they might wish to react,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
