<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLPHINS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT DOLPHIN GRIN GETS US EVERY TIME _ AND HAS THROUGHOUT HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The smile is as permanent as The Joker's. And the wild animal
wearing it is not, as romantics might suggest, a mystical, gentle
giant from the lost continent of Atlantis, but rather an extremely
efficient predator.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tim Cahill was suckered in by the Flipper grin as he swam
alongside a bottlenose dolphin for the first time off the Japanese
island of Mikura.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dolphin moved with me. I could see her round, black eye
and the anatomical smile that meant precisely nothing at all.
Still, one feels obliged to smile back,'' writes the
philosophizing, humorizing adventurer in the new coffee-table book
``Dolphins'' (National Geographic, 216 pages, $35).
</P>
<P>
   His book is a companion to the Imax giant-screen documentary
film of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   That first dolphin encounter left Cahill mulling the
complexities of an animal that humans have revered through history,
yet still barely understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think dolphins are intelligent, social, highly verbal and
seem to take an inordinate pleasure in sex, especially after a fine
meal,'' Cahill said in a recent phone interview. ``In short, they
are very much like us.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is, Cahill notes, a dark side to this happy affinity.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins can be brutes, tossing live prey into the air and
ramming them with their beaks, like a cats playing with a mouse.
Certain bullying bottlenose will harass and kill smaller harbor
porpoises simply for fun, not food.
</P>
<P>
   Males have been observed killing infants in order to mate with
their mothers or engaging in what Cahill describes as ``gang rape''
of females in estrus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dolphins are not all peace and love,'' says Cahill, ``and they
are not above a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Those fighting instincts can kick in when humans fail to mind
their manners in the company of dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins have bitten, bumped, severely injured and even, in one
case, killed humans who engaged in such social faux pas as touching
or aggressive pursuit of the animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to let the dolphins approach you,'' says
Cahill.
</P>
<P>
   He minded his underwater manners during that first encounter,
swimming belly to belly with the graceful creatures and coming away
from the experience with what he calls a ``dreamy feeling'' and a
lasting ``mush-headed affection.''
</P>
<P>
   The human-dolphin bond is long. Stories of interspecies
friendships wind back to ancient times. Cahill recounts the tale of
a small boy and dolphin told by Roman naturalist Pliny the Elder.
In the story the boy rides the dolphin to school every day across
the Bay of Naples. One day the boy dies. Only a few weeks later the
animal washes up on shore, dead.
</P>
<P>
   Was it heartbroken? Stories of Man's Other Best Friend
inevitably stir up such anthropomorphic emotions. For good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill tells the story of JoJo, a solitary bottlenose dolphin
that hangs near beachside resorts in the Caribbean and is often
injured by personal watercraft and speed boats. JoJo befriended a
professional naturalist named Dean Bernal, who learned to
communicate with the dolphin and treat its injuries.
</P>
<P>
   JoJo had a chance to repay the kindness one day when Bernal was
diving. The naturalist didn't notice a large hammerhead shark
approaching him, but JoJo did. The dolphin quickly moved in front
of Bernal to protect him, then pressed its head against the back of
the shark and drove it 200 feet down to the bottom of the sea.
Bernal grabbed his videocamera and returned to the scene to capture
JoJo repeatedly harassing the dangerous man-eater. His footage is
incorporated into the Imax film.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill _ whose lively writing is familiar to readers of Rolling
Stone, Esquire, Men's Journal and Outside magazine, as well as fans
of his numerous adventure books _ served as co-writer on the
documentary produced by MacGillveray Freeman Films, creators of the
box-office hit ``Everest.''
</P>
<P>
   In book and film, the writer follows the exhilarating and
exasperating work of marine mammal scientists attempting to
document dolphins in the wild and to break their communication code
through analysis of movements and vocalizations.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike traditional researchers who work with captive dolphins
under controlled conditions, young marine biologist Kathleen
Dudzinski and her team must work on animal time. Wild dolphins show
up when they want to. And boat time costs big time.
</P>
<P>
   ``During a five- to six-month season in the Bahamas, Kathleen
got 20 hours of useful videotape,'' says Cahill. ``That's 20 hours
out of about 2,000, or a 1 percent return on the investment of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In waters off the United States, pursuing wild dolphins for any
purpose can be read as harassment under the 1972 Marine Mammal
Protection Act. So the scientists headed to the Bahamas, Patagonia
and Japan for their documentary work, using specially adapted film
and audio equipment to record the bottle-nose, the Atlantic spotted
dolphin and the elusive dusky dolphin.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill spent four years on the dolphin project, a feather in the
baseball cap for the rumpled Montanan, whose adventures have left
him lying on his back counting stars in the Sahara Desert and, as
he recounts in the most recent edition of Men's Journal, narrowly
escaping a volcanic eruption in Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   He did not, he points out, escape that country's political coup.
</P>
<P>
   Coming up is a dog sled trip into Lapland. But no doubt dolphins
will still be swimming through his imagination as he swooshes
across the snow. ``Once you encounter a dolphin in a personal and
visceral manner, they invade and engage your conscience,'' says
Cahill.
</P>
<P>
   That could be a two-way engagement, he theorizes. Man studies
dolphin. Does dolphin study man?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dolphins are one of the few wild creatures that approach
humans in a friendly and apparently curious manner. The fascination
seems to be mutual,'' says Cahill. ``We think, `What's it like?
What's it like to be intelligent and live in the sea?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And maybe they think, `Hey you, you two-leggeds. What is it
like to be intelligent and live on the land. Can we talk?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1857EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
