A0323 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-TV-BIAS-SPI &LR;      03-17 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BIAS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERY: BIAS LEAVES ITS MARK ON EVERYONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do we hate? Let us count the ways.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe ``hate'' is too strong. But bias, prejudice,
intolerance _ call it what you will _ manage to creep into behavior
no matter how ``neutral'' we think we are. Virtually no one is a
walking, talking Switzerland, it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery Channel offers startling evidence Monday in ``How
Biased Are You?'' The first in a yearlong ``Hate and Violence: No
Simple Answers'' initiative, the program was produced by ``Dateline
NBC'' and is hosted by Forrest Sawyer. It takes an academic
approach to the question, focusing on psychological experiments
aimed at understanding perceptions of race differences among
children and adults.
</P>
<P>
   In the children's experiment, a subject is asked to interpret
what's happening in several pictures. In one, for instance, a boy
seems to be falling down the stairs while another boy behind him
has his arm outstetched. One interpretation could be that the boy
with the outstretched arm pushed the other boy. Another is that he
is reaching out to stop the boy from falling.
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting and troubling is how often the second
interpretation _ the ``good'' interpretation _ is offered if the
boy with the outstretched arm is depicted as being white, and how
often the first comes up if the same character is portrayed with
dark skin. Although the drawings are otherwise identical, it's also
instructive to see youngsters ascribe certain expressions to the
dark-skinned boy that they don't see in the light-skinned.
</P>
<P>
   Another study, this one targeting adults, asks people to pair
white faces with positive-sounding words and black faces with
negative-sounding words in rapid-fire order. Subjects of either
race have little trouble doing so, but when they're asked to pair
white faces with ``bad'' words and black faces with ``good'' words,
it's a different story altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Even among people who have spent their lives working for human
rights, the incidence of an unconscious preference for whites is
unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   What this says about us is eye-opening. Ideally, it may be
mind-opening.
</P>
<P>
   How Biased Are You? One-hour program examining everyday
situations in which prejudice and hate manifest themselves, hosted
by Forrest Sawyer. Monday night on the Discovery Channel. Parental
guideline rating: TV-G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1857EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
