<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GERMANY-MERKEL-800&AMP;AD     03-17 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-MERKEL-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GIRL' IS SET TO LEAD GERMANY'S DOMINANT POLITICAL PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ In paternal, if not quite patronizing, tones, Helmut
Kohl liked to call her ``das Maedchen'' _ ``the girl.'' Now the
wide-eyed girl from the east has turned on the former chancellor
and is about to usher in a German political revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Angela Merkel, and in the space of a few weeks all
resistance to her nomination as the next leader of Germany's
dominant postwar political force, the Christian Democratic Union,
has fallen away.
</P>
<P>
   With endorsements pouring in from all levels of the party, it is
now inevitable that the executive board of the Christian Democrats
will nominate her as the next party leader at a meeting here on
Monday, opening the way for Merkel to become the first woman to
head a major German party.
</P>
<P>
   But the change Merkel represents is much greater than one of
gender. It is religious, generational, moral and geographical. With
one of those strange lurches that characterize the way this
generally conservative country moves forward, Germany is reaching
out for entirely new political blood.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the lurch lies the financial scandal that has engulfed
the Christian Democrats, tarnishing the reputation of Kohl, who has
admitted accepting more than $1 million in illegal payments, and
ultimately obliging his party to look in directions unimaginable
until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Where Kohl comes from the Rhineland, home of Konrad Adenauer and
the heartland of the postwar Republic, Merkel grew up in the
formerly communist east. Where he is Catholic, she is Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   Where he is almost 70, a man indelibly marked by the Nazi years,
she is 45, a woman shaped by another trauma _ Germany's division
and unification. Where Kohl is domineering, she seeks grass-roots
consensus with a cool precision that seems to reflect her
physicist's training.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of the Christian Democrats' problems that this
radical change is being made through an overwhelming consensus. One
by one, Merkel's potential opponents for the leadership, including
heavyweights like the former defense minister, Volker Ruehe, have
dropped out with no more than a whimper.
</P>
<P>
   ``She represents a new departure, a totally new type of
political figure at the top,'' said Karl Kaiser, a political
analyst. ``To have a woman from the former communist East Germany
leading the country's foremost conservative party is a measure of
the political rupture of recent months.''
</P>
<P>
   It was precisely because he was Kohl's protege, and because he
himself also admitted taking secret donations, that Wolfgang
Schaeuble, the former chancellor's immediate successor as party
leader, was obliged to quit last month after just over a year at
the helm.
</P>
<P>
   Merkel, the party general-secretary, was waiting. From the start
of the financial scandal late last year, she had distinguished
herself by her evident dismay at the party slush funds, by her
determination to root out such practices, and by her indignation at
Kohl's insistence that his ``word of honor'' prevented him from
revealing the names of anonymous donors.
</P>
<P>
   In a much-noted article in the Frankfurter Allgemeine last
December, she wrote: ``Mr. Kohl's admissions have damaged the
Christian Democrats. Putting a word of honor above the law is not
comprehensible when one has committed a criminal act.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued: ``The Christian Democratic Party must learn to
walk by itself, without its old war horse, as Mr. Kohl often
referred to himself. Like someone in puberty, it must make the
break from home.''
</P>
<P>
   The words were literally stunning. They carried all the
straightforward indignation of an easterner who had absorbed years
of post-Cold War moral lessons on the iniquity of the communist
system only to discover abruptly that the venerated ``chancellor of
unification'' had been ready to place himself above the law.
</P>
<P>
   Merkel's clean break with Kohl _ made before that of any other
prominent party members _ impressed many people because the former
chancellor himself had plucked her from relative obscurity to
become his trophy easterner after unification.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Hamburg in 1954, Merkel moved as a child to the former
East Germany, where her father, a pastor with left-leaning ideals,
worked in Brandenburg. She trained as a physicist and worked as an
academic before beginning her political career as the deputy
spokeswoman for the first and last freely elected East German
government of Lothar de Maiziere in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In the same year, she joined the Christian Democrats and, after
unification, was named minister for women and youth by Kohl. It was
then that he adopted the epithet ``das Maedchen'' for a woman whose
placid appearance and air of innocence belie intelligence and
ambition that are evidently fierce.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even after she became general-secretary of the party in 1998,
there was no suggestion that she might rise further until the old
guard _ and a fair swath of the younger party guard from the west _
were swept away by tales of Swiss bank accounts, cash in plastic
bags and rampant dishonesty.
</P>
<P>
   Picking her way through this debris in recent weeks, Merkel has
quietly undone the critics who once considered her too young or too
Protestant or too moderate or simply too female by emerging as the
only credible voice of change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to accept the consequences of what has happened,'' she
said on more than one occasion. ``And they are drastic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela Merkel is courageous,'' said Christian Wulff, one of
the first party members to promote her. ``She has the authenticity,
credibility and truthfulness that people are looking for in the
party.''
</P>
<P>
   That is certainly true. It is also true that Merkel has the
potential to emerge as a formidable opponent to the governing
Social Democrats and Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder because she will
appeal to women and to voters from the former east.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, she is a little-known quantity who owes her
meteoric rise as much to what she symbolizes as to what she has
said. Conservatives, especially Bavarian conservatives, suspect her
of standing too far to the left on economic issues, and she will
have a hard job shoring up the right wing of the party. Her long
cohabitation with the man who eventually became her second husband
in 1998 also raised concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But Merkel is no liberal. She campaigned last year against the
government decision to offer German citizenship to immigrants on
easier terms. More recently she has supported the bizarre electoral
slogan of Juergen Ruettgers, the Christian Democrat leader in North
Rhine-Westphalia.
</P>
<P>
   The slogan, whose xenophobic undertones appear clear, says,
``Kinder statt Inder'' _ ``Children not Indians'' _ a reference to
Schroeder's suggestion that Indians with talents in the field of
high technology should be offered residence permits as one way to
spur the German economy.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Merkel joined Kohl in parliament for a ceremony
marking the 10th anniversary of the first free election in east
Germany on March 18, 1990. It was the former chancellor's first
appearance in the Bundestag since November 24; his decline since
then was symbolized by his relegation to a less prominent seat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
