<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0331 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-BOSTON-BOS &LR;      03-17 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-BOSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWANESE ABROAD RETURN TO SUPPORT REFORM CANDIDATE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   TAIPEI _ Chi-Tien Chang has never been so excited about an
election in his life. Never mind that he's an American now and
can't even vote here.
</P>
<P>
   In Taiwan's election Saturday what's at stake is not just
electing a president but the very future of Taiwanese democracy,
said Chang, one of a half dozen Taiwanese-born friends from Boston
who came back this week. What drew them was their desire to help
the first candidate with a realistic chance to break the 56-year
monopoly on power of the Kuomintang nationalist party.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, a pathologist at Boston's Beth Israel Deaconess Medical
Center, was barred from returning to his homeland for three decades
after speaking out against Taiwan's military dictatorship when he
was a student in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But things have changed since the martial law was lifted in 1987
and free speech guaranteed in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, at the final rally for the independence-minded
Democratic Progressive Party, Chang joined a crowd estimated by
organizers at 400,000 people to shake green banners and cheer
themselves hoarse under a shower of confetti, fireworks, and
balloons at a muddy soccer stadium in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the headquarters of opposition candidate Chen Shui-bian,
a former mayor of Taipei and stubborn opponent of political
corruption, hundreds of taxis blocked four lanes of traffic,
blowing their horns in support. Elsewhere in the city, rallies for
the ruling party's candidate, Vice President Lien Chan, and
independent rival James Soong lasted well after midnight, drawing
about the same numbers of supporters in a last push in the
neck-and-neck three-way race.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 15 million Taiwanese heading to the polls, why
would Chang and thousands of others who settled in the United
States and elsewhere spend their money and vacation time to rally
in the rain on the other side of the world, when they can't even
vote?
</P>
<P>
   Simple, said Chang, 56, who is on only his third visit since his
exile ended: ``I tasted freedom in Boston years ago, and I want the
same for my homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   The nationalist party, which bought up all the available
programming and commercial time on the three main TV networks,
boasts voters from overseas as well. But advertisements in The
Liberty Times, a Chinese-language newspaper in the United States,
state that supporters of the ruling party were offered ``a big
present'' and a ``gold medal'' to come back for the elections. When
asked about the apparent payment for votes, Charles Wu, head of
public relations for Lien's campaign, sputtered uncomfortably,
saying, ``This is a Chinese habit: When you receive visitors, you
give gifts . . . I'm certain it was only a small gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen's camp alleged that some supporters of independent James
Soong, who broke from the ruling party a few months ago, also paid
just $100 toward the cost of the trip and were given free
accommodation to lure them back to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's party had little in its campaign coffers, and his
supporters had to buy their own green party vests, T-shirts, and
even campaign hats.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every taxi in Taipei was festooned with banners of their
favored candidates. The driver who brought the Boston group to its
rally wasn't flying a Chen flag on his antenna, but when he heard
they had come from the United States to support the opposition
leader, he confided that he did too, and would not accept the fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just a very small part of a group in Boston who fought
the dictatorship for years,'' said Tun-Hou Lee, 46, a professor of
virology at the Harvard School of Public Health. ``We all have
relatives here _ my parents and brothers are here _ and we'd like
to see Taiwan become a real democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   If Chen wins, it would be ``a clean slate. He could eradicate
all this corruption,'' Lee said. ``Even today, we know (the ruling
party) is buying votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee and his friends are not members of Chen's party, but along
with some 200 families in Greater Boston, they belong to the
Taiwanese Association of America, most of whose members support
permanent independence from China. The group has been meeting twice
a month to raise money and support for Chen.
</P>
<P>
   Some here criticize overseas Taiwanese for advocating
independence, despite threats of a military attack from communist
China, since they live in safety thousands of miles away and hold
foreign passports.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our hearts, we really wish Taiwan could be an independent
country, but we don't say it to our Taiwanese friends, because they
are really worried about the China threat,'' said Chen-Yuan Wang,
43, a transportation planner from Lexington, Mass. who will vote
Saturday since he still holds Taiwan citizenship. ``My response is
that my mother, my dad, my brothers all live here. Why would we
want anything to harm our own parents?'' Wang asked.
</P>
<P>
   As a candidate, Chen, who openly advocated independence for
years, has tempered his stance, promising not to declare Taiwan a
state, nor to change the flag or name of ``The Republic of China on
Taiwan,'' unless Beijing attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest threat to Taiwan now is not the (nationalists),
but China,'' said Wang. Here for their third trip in 13 years, Wang
and his wife took their son out of school for two weeks to witness
the election.
</P>
<P>
   None of the group has ever visited the mainland, and ``as long
as China threatens Taiwan, I don't want to,'' said San Lien, 58, a
Newton, Mass. engineer.
</P>
<P>
   If Chen loses, ``we will all cry together,'' said Mei Tsai, 53,
an accountant from Milford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But she expected to be celebrating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
