<SLUG> BC-IMF-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKELY NEW HEAD OF IMF OUTLINES GOALS FOR FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The presumptive new leader of the International
Monetary Fund gave a general outline of his goals Friday, promising
to listen to criticism from outsiders and to make the fund ``a
cornerstone for promoting growth and stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Horst Koehler, whose way to become the IMF's managing director
was cleared when U.S. and Japanese rivals for the post dropped out
on Thursday, said he was committed to a dialogue with the U.S.
Congress, some of whose members have been sharply critical of the
fund in the past, and with the public in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think that it's an obligation to explain IMF policy,
better maybe than we have in the past,'' Koehler said at a
get-acquainted news conference at the fund headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
   The fund was founded in 1946 to promote economic stability
around the world, partly through loans to countries in need. From
time to time, it has been accused of straying from its original
mission and trying ineffectually to bring about profound social
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler's remarks came just 10 days after a study commissioned
by Congress recommended that the fund and its sister organization,
the World Bank, be trimmed back. The commission further suggested
that the fund emphasize short-term, emergency aid to countries as
opposed to trying to effect profound social changes, like relieving
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a question, Koehler said Friday that he would try
to keep the IMF focused on ``crisis prevention'' in individual
countries.
</P>
<P>
   On an especially sensitive subject, Russia, Koehler said he was
``open for a constructive dialogue'' with Russia's acting
president, Vladimir Putin, whom he met in December, and was willing
to give him the benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The fund has met political resistance in Russia and has
repeatedly delayed disbursing its funds there. Moreover, the
institution that Koehler is leaving to head the IMF, the European
Bank for Reconstruction and Development, has had a series of bad
loans in Russia under Koehler's watch.
</P>
<P>
   Taking care not to appear over-confident, even though most of
the representatives of the fund's 182 member nations have signaled
their support for him, Koehler said he was ``honored by this
expression of confidence.'' He said he had had fruitful discussions
with Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and with Stanley Fischer,
the deputy managing director who was in the running for the
directorship.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler praised Fischer's ``intellectual brilliance and
experience'' and said he was pleased that Fischer had said he would
stay at the agency. The other man Koehler beat out was Eisuke
Sakakibara, a former Japan finance ministry official.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to the weeks of controversy in which he emerged as the
top contender after the United States rejected German's first
choice, Caio Koch-Weser, Koehler said, ``I agree that this process
was really not the best I could imagine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
