<SLUG> BC-EMC-PROXY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMC GAINS LUCRATIVE FOR EXECUTIVES, TOO, PROXY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares in data-storage maker EMC Corp. have more than doubled
over the past year as e-commerce companies have snapped up its
products. Among the biggest winners: EMC's top executives, who
received stock-option awards based on EMC's share price before the
run-up.
</P>
<P>
   EMC last year gave its co-founder and chairman Richard J. Egan
options for 474,300 shares in the Hopkinton, Mass. company, while
chief executive Michael C. Ruettgers was given 280,000 options,
according to the company's proxy filing to the US Securities &AMP;
Exchange Commission Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The document values the options based on EMC's price of $63.3125
on July 21. Assuming a 10 percent appreciation rate in coming
years, Egan's grant was worth $47.8 million and Ruettgers' was
worth $28.3 million, according to the filing.
</P>
<P>
   But both stakes would be worth more than twice those amounts
based on EMC's closing price Friday of $128.75; shares reached a
high of $132.125 earlier this month. The options are exercisable
over a multi-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Ruettgers also received a salary of $800,586, payments worth
about $70,000, and a bonus of $1.3 million tied to the company's
success meeting profitability goals, according to the filing.
</P>
<P>
   Egan received a bonus of $663,200, according to the filing, and
consulting and life insurance payouts worth $538,243. He transfered
the options he gained last year to a family trust.
</P>
<P>
   Few shareholders might complain so far, given the rise in the
company's total valuation as it rides a wave of interest in
Internet infrastructure. Based on Friday's closing price EMC was
worth $134 billion, the highest valuation of any public company in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   EMC dominates the market for ``Enterprise Data Storage,'' the
disk-drive systems that allow corporate computers to access vast
amounts of information and share it among many desktop PCs.
</P>
<P>
   These systems are in high demand from companies trying to create
e-commerce systems and applications. While the Internet sector is
seen as risky, EMC has attracted a broad following essentially as a
building-block maker for the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an insatiable demand for storage, and there aren't a
lot of companies that can fill that demand,'' said SunTrust
Equitable Securities analyst Mark Kelleher. He rates EMC a ``strong
buy.'' ``They've pretty well dominated the market'' by investing
heavily in research, he said.
</P>
<P>
   EMC's competitors include IBM Corp. and Hitachi for large
customer. IBM has been heavily promoting its system, known as
`Shark,' recently; Friday, however, analyst Gary Helmig of
SoundView Technology Group reported IBM will delay by up to six
months some software improvements to its Shark system. (IBM said
the upgrades will be available sooner to some customers.)
</P>
<P>
   Last year EMC bought Westborough-based Data General Corp. for
$1.05 billion in an effort to expand its sales of data-systems to
mid-sized businesses.
</P>
<P>
   EMC has set a revenue target of $12 billion by 2001. Last year
it earned $1.18 billion on revenue of $6.72 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
