<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-PORN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BARS SOFTWARE THAT DEFEATS ANTI-PORN FILTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Opponents of a popular Internet filtering program say they won't
be stopped by a federal court order to stop promoting a method for
bypassing the software.
</P>
<P>
   Cyber Patrol of Framingham, Mass., a division of toymaker Mattel
Inc., obtained a temporary restraining order against computer
experts in Canada and Sweden who figured out a way to defeat Cyber
Patrol software. Cyber Patrol is used to block out access to
Internet sites that feature violent, prejudiced, or
sexually-explicit content.
</P>
<P>
   Many homes and schools use Cyber Patrol and similar products to
prevent children from visiting pornographic Web sites. Cyber Patrol
blocks Internet pages based on a list of unacceptable sites
included with the software. This list has been encrypted, so that a
user can't see exactly which sites are considered unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of Internet activists are opposed to all efforts to
restrict access. Two of them, Eddy Jansson of Sweden and Matthew
Skala of Canada, managed to decipher Cyber Patrol's list of blocked
Internet sites and publish it. The two also created a program that
allows users to bypass Cyber Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Cyber Patrol went to federal court in Boston,
charging that the cracking of their software amounted to a
copyright violation. On Friday, Judge Edward Harrington issued a
temporary restraining order forcing the two men and their Internet
providers to stop distributing the material. On March 27,
Harrington will consider whether to issue a preliminary injunction
against the activists.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the two men say they'll sidestep the judge's
order by setting up copies of the information on ``mirror sites'' _
Internet servers based outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if Cyber Patrol is successful in shutting down the
original site in Sweden, they will not be able to shut down all
mirror sites around the world,'' said Bennett Haselton, operator of
the anti-censorship Web site Peacefire.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1910EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
