<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ICONS-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ANCIENT, SACRED ART REVIVES AN ANCIENT, SACRED CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PSKOV, Russia _ God moves in mysterious ways, except, maybe, in
Pskov, a city that has monasteries and grand churches and religious
artifacts the way Americans have remote-control clickers and
half-read copies of People magazine. This is a town where you can
stand in one square _ they call it the square of seven churches _
and see, yes, seven churches. This sort of thing a god would
appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   It suggests why the Rev. Andrei Nikolayevich Davydov was plucked
out of a parish in Latvia six years ago and deposited in Pskov, in
a troubled little church _ a church whose front door opens onto a
Soviet radio condenser factory, a church with no heat and a dirt
floor, a church used in communist times as a garage for the KGB. A
church that, when the Russian Orthodox patriarchy regained it in
1991, was found to harbor a number of skeletons in the vestibule, a
single bullet hole in each cranium.
</P>
<P>
   This was a church in a jam. But Father Andrei and the church
have turned out to be a holy union of problem and solution, of
labor and love, of canvas and _ literally _ artist.
</P>
<P>
   Every church needs a good priest. But an artist, it turned out,
was what this church needed most of all.
</P>
<P>
   In Father Andrei, 43, intense, balding and bushy-bearded, it got
both. He grew up in Moscow. His father was a philosopher and
author. But from the very start, the son was an uncommonly talented
painter.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's just a part of my biography,'' Father Andrei said
during a long conversation over tea in a spare, white-walled studio
next to the church. ``If I were not given a chance to paint, I
would probably die.''
</P>
<P>
   He began painting landscapes and other common scenes as a child.
As a young man, he graduated from the Moscow Art Theater, the
nation's top art institute, and worked as an illustrator of
children's books. But while most artists his age honed their
talents on bowls of fruit or portraits, he was somehow drawn to
paint religious icons: saints, Madonnas, crucifixions,
resurrections _ all on lacquered wooden panels, just as in medieval
times.
</P>
<P>
   These were not just knockoffs. For the young Andrei, icon art
became an almost transcendental obsession.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out to be so interesting that I realized that I
needed nothing else,'' he said. ``This is a way of depicting in
human terms the secrets of God's kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``What strikes me about icons is this ability to create an image
of someone you're conversing with. I think all our lives are a
search for interlocutors. You decide after years of searching that
you can't talk to this person; or that person cannot talk to you.
And after more years, you finally decide that the only one you can
have a real conversation with is your God.''
</P>
<P>
   It was icons that brought Father Andrei to the church, first in
an effort to better understand his art, then as a student of the
priesthood and, finally, a dozen years ago, as a priest. As he
became closer to his subject, he said, his icons improved _ ``just
as if I'd been making Fords, I'd understand much better what goes
into cars.''
</P>
<P>
   As icons go, Father Andrei came to produce not Fords, but
Bentleys. He makes rich, luminous images on parched spruce and fir:
portraits medieval in their primitiveness, but so finely wrought
and brightly shaded that they almost leap off the wood with life.
</P>
<P>
   He became well known, if not famous, for his work. His icons
came to be in demand in some European churches. None of this had
any real impact on his career as a priest, which took him and his
wife, Marina _ Russian Orthodox priests can marry _ out of Moscow
to a tiny parish in Lithuania, then to Latvia.
</P>
<P>
   In Latvia, feelings against the nation's former Soviet occupiers
were strong, and life as a Russian priest was difficult.
Immigration officials there demanded that Father Andrei choose
between Latvia and his legal residence in Moscow. Then, in 1994, he
was offered a post in Pskov _ a tiny cathedral laid low by 74 years
of Soviet occupation, with a factory on the outside, old scaffolds
and a dirt floor on the inside, and no money to do anything about
either.
</P>
<P>
   St. John the Baptist Nativity Cathedral, as it was called, is
not your average house of worship. It dates to 1124 _ the oldest
cathedral in Pskov, one of the oldest cities in all Russia.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Eleven princes and princesses of Pskov were interred in its
walls and in a six-acre monastery added in the 1200s.
</P>
<P>
   Architecturally, it is a singular example of Russian design in
the years before Ghengis Khan swept across the steppes: compact and
simple, a white stucco box with unassuming caps on its three drums
instead of the more flamboyant and common onion domes.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Its uniqueness probably saved it. The Communists tore down all
but two monastery buildings to build the radio parts factory, but
kept up the church's exterior as a tourist site. The interior was
left to decay: under communism, the little church was a KGB garage,
a peat store and a tannery.
</P>
<P>
   That was a historical tragedy, for St. John had been lavishly
decorated in frescoes and icons of the so-called Pskov school, from
the 1100s to the 1500s, among the world's leading examples of icon
design. Pskov icons became prized for their brilliant reds and deep
greens, their blending of religious and folk art and their
delicate, elongated depictions of people and animals.
</P>
<P>
   Once there were scores. But inside the old church, nothing was
left _ not even the traditional icon-hanging wall, called an
iconostasis, which separates Orthodox church altars from the nave
where worshipers gather. The cathedral's white stucco walls were
effectively as bare as a vast untouched swath of artist's canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Which was, of course, exactly what they were.
</P>
<P>
   Father Andrei says he was not brought to Pskov for his artistic
talents. But once he saw the church, he said, he knew he had found
a life's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not so many 12th-century churches in Russia, you
know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that it was totally empty _ no frescoes, no iconostasis _
meant that I had to work here,'' he said. ``Had there been old
frescoes, there would have been a question of restoration, of how
to do some things. But this was an offer I could not turn down.''
</P>
<P>
   His art has proved to be the decaying church's other savior. To
buy and install an insulated spruce floor, Father Andrei produced
an intricate gold-on-copper icon for a Belgian church. A school of
iconography, now housed in the nave, produces other paintings that
are sold to finance renovations. Growing interest among Pskov's
elite has led the city to donate 30,000 rubles _ about $1,000 _ for
double-pane glass in the cathedral's 49 windows. A pine balcony,
the choir's home, has risen in the rear, up a flight of impossibly
steep 900-year-old stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, icons and frescoes are reappearing. Father Andrei
and his family make their own paints from original materials,
hand-grinding lapis lazuli, malachite and cinnabar on glass plates
into deep blues and greens and reds _ big grains for bright colors,
fine dust for soft ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I use synthetic paints,'' he said, ``I don't get the same
crystalline structure and the icon doesn't reflect light the same
way. With paints I could buy, this blue'' _ he pointed to the
lining of a saint's robe _ ``would be black in the darkness of the
church. But with these paints, just with a candle, it's deep and
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The iconostasis, a glowing work in progress, already boasts
life-size portraits of Mary and Jesus, smaller depictions of John
and a Pskovian princess who founded the church, and the beginnings
of 12 icons depicting Christian holidays. On the left wall, in
recesses over tombs of early royalty, are two frescoes of biblical
scenes; on the right wall, another fresco shows the church's
founding, some of which can be seen on the Internet at
www.geocities.com/Paris/Pavilion/8345/english.html.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   St. John is by no means the only Pskov site with new icons.
Across the Velikaya River, the Mirozhsky monastery, also in
disrepair, has turned an abandoned building into a showcase of new
icon art; a church some 25 miles down the road has a flourishing
school of icon painting. Pskov's art museum is a center of icon
restoration.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There are lot of blank walls still to fill: this city of 200,000
has 56 cathedrals built in or before the 17th century, less than
half of them open.
</P>
<P>
   A challenge for some ambitious artist, perhaps, but not for
Father Andrei, whose own church remains largely an untouched
canvas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for my entire life,'' he said. ``I could be finished here
in a month. ``But I'm in no hurry at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
