<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-FIAT-GM-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER GM DEAL, WHEREFORE ART THOU, ALFA ROMEO?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MARCIA RUFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The partnership announced last week between General Motors and
Fiat opens a window for the return of Alfa Romeo to the United
States. Until it withdrew in 1995, the Italian sports car maker was
best known for two-seat convertibles like the Duetto that Dustin
Hoffman drove in ``The Graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, Alfa Romeo, which is part of Fiat, still sells a
sporty two-seat Spider convertible, as well as other models. Its
156, a successful small sport sedan, was voted Europe's 1998 Car of
the Year by auto journalists.
</P>
<P>
   This month, at the Geneva auto show, the company introduced its
156 Sportwagon, which goes on sale in Italy this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Alfisti, as Alfa enthusiasts are known, would love to see
these cars come to the United States. ``They are fantastic
vehicles,'' said Vic Cerami, chapter president of the Long Island
Alfa Romeo Owners Club. ``There is definitely an opening for
entry-level Italian sports cars here.'' But while reimporting Alfa
is under consideration at Fiat, it seems but a footnote to the
multibillion-dollar GM-Fiat agreement.
</P>
<P>
   As announced in Turin last week, GM will acquire 20 percent of
Fiat Auto in exchange for $2.4 billion of GM stock, which will make
Fiat the largest single shareholder of GM, with a 5.1 percent
stake. GM will also have the right to make an offer in the future
for the remaining 80 percent of Fiat Auto.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies will coordinate behind the scenes to cut costs
while continuing to be rivals in the marketplace. Fiat Auto's
European brands, including Fiat, Alfa Romeo and Lancia, compete
with the Opel and Vauxhall brands of GM.
</P>
<P>
   Each company brings different strengths to the partnership.
Fiat, the world's sixth-largest carmaker, has a strong line of
small cars, builds well-regarded transmissions and engines,
particularly small diesels, and is a market leader in Latin
America. GM, the world's largest car company, can offer products
that Fiat lacks, like a small pickup for Latin America; finance and
marketing expertise; and the ability to generate cost savings
through combined puchasing, finance and research operations.
</P>
<P>
   A common small-car platform _ with the potential to be the
world's biggest seller _ is a possibility by mid-decade, according
to a presentation Fiat made last week to securities analysts. Fiat
and GM said annual savings from the partnership could reach $1.2
billion after three years and $2 billion by the fifth year.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership also makes it possible for Fiat to consider
bringing Alfa back to the United States, where low sales could not
justify an independent dealer network. Access to GM's dealers
changes that equation.
</P>
<P>
   Paolo Vannini, a Fiat spokesman in New York, said the Spider
could come in 2003. The 156 does not meet American standards, but
the next-generation car could be designed with the United States in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   But distributing Alfa Romeos ``isn't even on the radar screen,''
a spokesman for GM, Tony Cervone, said. He said other parts of the
agreement were on the front burner.
</P>
<P>
   One barrier is choosing an appropriate partner among the GM
brands. ``I think the hardest part is coming up with a coherent,
sensible way to get the cars out,'' said Jim Hall, an analyst with
AutoPacific Group, a consulting firm. He said the logical partners
were Saab or Oldsmobile, GM's most internationally focused brands,
but neither would make a perfect fit with Alfa.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Fiat nameplates, Ferrari and Maserati, are unaffected
by the partnership since they are part of the larger Fiat Group _
and are not under the umbrella of Fiat Auto.
</P>
<P>
   Maserati, which left the United States in 1990, will return next
year with two models: the $70,000-and-up 3200 GT coupe, currently
on sale in Europe, and an all-new Spider, which will cost slightly
more. They will be sold by Ferrari dealers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
