<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, March 19, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-POLITICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ OPEC has displayed startling
muscle in the past year, sending oil and gasoline prices soaring.
Whether the oil cartel continues on this course will touch directly
on American wallets and politics, by determining just what kinds of
prices American voters confront all spring and summer and into the
fall, right up to Election Day. Little wonder, then, that oil is
quickly becoming an issue in the race between George W. Bush and Al
Gore. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   HI-TECH-DOOMSDAY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Amazing advances in
computers, genetics and other sectors of high technology have led
many enthusiasts to predict the dawn of vast new information-age
utopias. Given the hype and relentless optimism, perhaps it's not
surprising that serious scientists and researchers have begun to
explore darker, less inviting visions of the future. A look at some
high-tech doomsday scenarios involving robotics, nanotechnology and
genetic engineering. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   COACHES-MIKES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The never-ending rush for
``inside access'' to sports personalities hit a speed bump last
week: Several NBA coaches risked fines by refusing a league edict
to wear microphones during games. Their reasoning was that as much
as fans would love to hear snippets of how they sketched out that
last pick-and-roll or lit a fire under a sullen superstar, some
parts of their jobs can't be done properly with the specter of
millions of eavesdroppers. Rather than embrace what the media can
do for them, they fear what it can do TO them. By Alan Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-TRANSFORM-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ The sale of the Los
Angeles Times drove home the reality that Los Angeles' old civic
architecture has been largely dismantled in recent years, with no
one quite sure what will replace it. By selling its company, the
Chandler family seemed to acknowledge that it no longer had a stake
in a city it helped build, and that _ no longer dominated by a
white majority, shorn of most of its old-line corporate giants, and
whose public school students predominantly speak English as a
second language, no longer needed them. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   MOST-WANTED-REVIEW (Washington) _ The FBI marked the 50th
anniversary of its 10 Most Wanted list with of pride and purpose,
and a touch of nostalgia. Of 458 people who have made the list, 429
have been caught, with several choosing to go down shooting it out
with their would-be captors. Cases against 15 people who were never
caught were eventually dropped, and another 4 fugitives were
removed from the list because others were deemed more deserving. A
look at some of the more famous cases. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   GASOLINE-MOTORISTS-REVIEW (Detroit) _ Car drivers probably feel
avenged when they see a hulking sport utility vehicle lumber up to
a gas station. Every bing and clank from the pump is another
reminder of the higher cost of filling a gas guzzler: up to $70 for
the biggest models. But higher gas prices actually hurt car owners
as much _ or more _ than SUV owners, who tend to have higher higher
incomes. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-RACE-REVIEW (Washington) _ The U.S. racial and ethnic mix
is undergoing radical change, and this is reflected on the census
forms that are being mailed to more than 120 million households
this month. A look at some of the race/ethnic questions on the
form. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-FITNESS-REVIEW (London) _ Even among the Britons who go
to health clubs to work out, there is often a lackadaisical
attitude toward fitness and health. Most of the truly
body-conscious gym-goers are foreigners. Most Britons would freely
confess that they don't care much about their physiques, and that
they don't want to give up the sort of habits that would upset the
U.S. surgeon general. Just as it is no surprise that many Americans
are clinically obese, it is no surprise that, by many standards,
Britons are stunningly unhealthy, and proud of it. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN-ARMS-REVIEW _ There's been much talk of war between
China and Taiwan recently, but the rhetoric obscures the fact that
military preparations remain modest in both countries and are
likely to stay that way. While China has slightly beefed up its
arsenal against Taiwan, there has been no dramatic increase in
spending that would signal a shift toward a war economy, since
China is not yet willing to risk the cost to its economic growth.
That may explain the increase in saber-rattling. By Craig Smith.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-TENSIONS-REVIEW _ After 21 stressful years of living under
the clerical dictatorship imposed by the Islamic revolution that
overthrew the shah, most Iranians would happily settle for a more
normal life. But last week, just as they were celebrating the
reformist landslide in February's parliamentary elections and the
hope it brought of a peaceful progression towards a more democratic
society, an assassin's bullet on a Tehran street provided a
shocking reminder of how grim and uncertain a struggle may yet lie
ahead. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-MUSLIMS-REVIEW (Rome) _ When Pope John Paul II goes to the
Middle East this week to begin a Holy Year pilgrimage to retrace
the steps of Jesus, he will pursue his longtime dream of
reconciling Christians and Muslims after centuries of hostility and
mistrust. A look at the history of relations between the Catholic
Church and Islam. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
