<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-AURORA-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDSMOBILE AURORA: OLDS WISHES ON A SMALLER STAR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ If you had walked into an Olds dealership five years
ago, you would have seen the same familiar nameplates: Ninety
Eight, Eighty Eight, Cutlass Supreme, Ciera. These were mostly your
father's Oldsmobiles.
</P>
<P>
   You would also have seen a decidedly different car, the Aurora.
Introduced as a 1995 model, this was an all-new, radically styled
sedan intended to signal a profound change in direction for Olds, a
General Motors division that had lost its way.
</P>
<P>
   Known in the '40s and '50s for innovative engineering, Olds
captured the public's imagination in the '60s and '70s with its
powerful 4-4-2 and innovative front-drive Toronado. By the
mid-1980s, the division was selling more than a million cars a
year; its Cutlass Supreme was one of America's favorites.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, Olds was a shadow of its former self; its sales
had fallen by two-thirds. In desperation, GM decided that
Oldsmobile would zero in on affluent buyers who were opting for
imports.
</P>
<P>
   The '95 Aurora was the first stab at fulfilling that tall order.
In its wake, Olds has built an entirely new lineup. The old cars
are gone, replaced by the compact Alero and the midsize Intrigue,
which both borrowed watered-down styling cues from the Aurora. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now Olds has a second-generation Aurora, a 2001 model that went
on sale in January 2000. Import shoppers are still the target; Olds
hopes to sell 40,000 Auroras annually. The '99 model found just
20,000 buyers.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the least expensive Aurora is now $6,000 cheaper
than the '99 model, on which GM had to offer large discounts. And
the styling, though it still has the horizontal headlamps and
sloping hood of the original love-it-or-hate-it design, has gone
conservative. The distinctive wide, rounded rump is now a
conventional Taurus-like design with individual taillamps flanking
the trunk lid.
</P>
<P>
   When Olds first displayed the new Aurora, at the New York auto
show last year, it seemed like yet another plain-vanilla GM car,
handsome enough not to offend but not stylish enough to turn heads.
So I was surprised at the attention the production version got on a
road test in Michigan. During a particularly hectic week of social
engagements, every valet who parked the car commented positively.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe how many people wanted a look at this
car,'' confided the attendant at a steakhouse near Ford
headquarters in Dearborn.
</P>
<P>
   Another change intended to attract more buyers is a choice of
engines. The Aurora 4.0 has an updated, 250-horsepower version of
the dual-cam V-8 that made its debut in the original Aurora. This
engine, a smaller version of Cadillac's famous Northstar, now runs
on regular gas, not just premium.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a V-6, and in contrast to the old pushrod power
plants used by two Aurora cousins, the Pontiac Bonneville and Buick
LeSabre, the Aurora 3.5 has the sophisticated twin-cam,
215-horsepower engine that made its debut last year in the
Intrigue. Both engines are coupled with electronic four-speed
automatic transmissions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 3.5 V-6 is surprisingly peppy, and its lighter weight means
the car feels better balanced between front and rear, so the
handling is more nimble. If I were buying an Aurora, I'd opt for
the 3.5. The V-8 is faster, but it is also $4,000 more expensive
and less fuel-efficient at a time when higher gas prices make a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   The front-drive Aurora rides on an entirely different
architecture than the previous model, which shared its basic
structure with the Buick Riviera, since discontinued. The more
rigid foundation should result in better crash protection and
higher quality, with fewer squeaks and rattles. While those
benefits are yet to be proved, I can attest to the quietness of the
car, which seemed nearly as hushed as a Lexus.
</P>
<P>
   The new structure also results in a car that is 6 inches shorter
than its predecessor and has a smaller trunk and noticeably less
legroom. Front-seat passengers complained that they felt cramped,
with a seat that could not be moved back far enough. Perhaps that
was by design; already, the rear-seat passengers have limited
legroom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although it is still a full-size car, the Aurora has shed a
couple hundred pounds. Olds hopes the smaller dimensions, lighter
weight and greater agility will appeal to women. Indeed, I found
the car easier to park and far more pleasant to drive than the last
Aurora.
</P>
<P>
   While this is a car aimed at people who like to drive, some of
my passengers felt overlooked. My daughter protested that she
couldn't take charge of the radio or climate controls, which are
are on a section of the dash angled toward the driver.
</P>
<P>
   Despite my passengers' complaints, the cabin seemed competitive,
in terms of design, quality and quietness, with competitors like
the Lexus ES300, the Acura TL and RL, and the Lincoln LS.
</P>
<P>
   Trimmed in real walnut, rich leather and soft-touch surfaces,
the Aurora also has plenty of amenities. Standard features include
a driver information center with 27 functions; a power driver's
seat, an audio system with a CD player; keyless entry; side air
bags and daytime running lights. The 4.0 model also has 17-inch
wheels, separate climate controls for driver and passenger and
traction- and stability-control systems.
</P>
<P>
   The 3.5 starts at $30,800, including the shipping charge; the
4.0 is $34,975. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although I initially thought the styling lacked distinction, I
was surprised by how much I enjoyed driving the new Aurora. In the
end, even the look had grown on me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Something Olds is new again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
