<HEADER>
A0351 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ARCHBISHOP-APOLOGY-NY     03-17 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHBISHOP-APOLOGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILWAUKEE PRELATE FINDS HARMONY IN APOLOGY TO JEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Pa.)  (lb) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ In the living room of the 19th-century brick house
that serves as the residence of Archbishop Rembert G. Weakland
stands a studio grand piano, with sheets of Chopin waltzes spread
out above the keys.
</P>
<P>
   For a visitor, it is a reminder that the archbishop, the
spiritual head of nearly 700,000 Roman Catholics in southern
Wisconsin, was recently notified by Columbia University in New York
that he will soon receive his doctorate in music, completing a
degree he began working on in the 1950s and then halted, only to
resume a few years ago. His first music teacher, a nun at a
parochial school in Pennsylvania, would no doubt have been proud.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday morning the talk turns from music to the spoken
word _ to two highly unusual homilies, one given by Pope John Paul
II last Sunday, the other four months earlier by Weakland. Both
were apologies for errors committed by Catholics against others.
</P>
<P>
   While the pope's remarks were broad and were timed for the first
Sunday in Lent, the archbishop was more specific, directing his
statements to Jews, in Milwaukee and elsewhere. Speaking in a local
synagogue last Nov. 7, Weakland said that conversion, the change of
attitude that precedes an effort to change one's life and society,
must include acknowledgment of wrongdoing, a request for
forgiveness and a resolve to reform.
</P>
<P>
   Both the timing of the speech and its ``interactive quality,''
in which the archbishop asked the Catholics who were listening to
say ``amen'' as he made his points, marked the occasion as a major
event, said Rabbi A. James Rudin, interreligious affairs director
of the American Jewish Committee. ``That Nov. 7 speech electrified
the Jewish community, not only in Milwaukee but throughout the
United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although other prelates have since offered apologies (notably
Cardinal Bernard Law, archbishop of Boston, and Cardinal Roger
Mahony, archbishop of Los Angeles), Weakland's homily ``was the
first of the millennial season, of the run-up to the year 2000,''
Rudin said.
</P>
<P>
   In his homily last November, Weakland said that ``we Catholics''
had acted ``contrary to God's law'' in dealings with Jews in the
past, that the Jewish community had been harmed as a result, and
that by preaching ``that the Jewish people were unfaithful,
hypocritical and God-killers,'' Catholics had reduced Jews' human
dignity. And that, he said, ``contributed to attitudes that made
the Holocaust possible.'' He called on members of both faiths to
work together to heal the world.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Weakland said: ``The ideas of apologies for the
past are difficult. We have only the sense of personal sin and
personal guilt.'' But he added that he did not think people could
move ahead unless they regarded themselves as part of a group and
were responsible for its actions. ``Otherwise,'' he said, ``the
fear remains that history will repeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Weakland said he did not want to be accusatory. But neither is
he finished with this process. He plans apologies to
African-Americans and probably to others as well. These must be
made on appropriate occasions, he said, lest the intent of the
message be lost and the apology be reduced to mere words.
</P>
<P>
   In a larger sense, he said, he sees the major religions as
standing at a unique juncture in history, when modern
communications have brought them into much closer proximity than
ever. ``How much must we hold in common in order to live in
common?'' he asked, adding that what religions contribute
positively to society will depend in part on how their members
cooperate with one another.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1977, when Pope Paul VI appointed him to the
archdiocese here, Weakland found an interfaith group already
established. His homily last November was timed for its 25th
anniversary. ``I was talking to a group that knew each other well,
that I knew well,'' he said, responding to a question about why he
had felt he could be more specific in his remarks than the pope
would be later. ``The pope had to be general, because he's talking
to the whole church,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Weakland has become known for a certain
outspokenness, perhaps more obvious now that the United States'
Catholic hierarchy, in its annual meetings, seems far more cautious
than it was a decade ago, when the bishops issued major pastoral
statements on peace and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Weakland said he could recall no single
instance that persuaded him he needed to preach the apology. But
then he recalled a trip that he made with parishioners to Poland in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting the city of Krakow, he said, they saw a wall with
anti-Semitic graffiti. When he asked a guide why the statements
were not painted over, she replied that whoever did it would just
put them up again. ``I had a feeling that what caused the Holocaust
was not completely over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop will turn 73 in April. He became a Benedictine
monk at 22 and was ordained a priest two years later. He was, for a
time in his 30s, a music teacher at a Catholic college.
</P>
<P>
   His roots lie in Pennsylvania coal country, where he was one of
six children in a family that received public assistance. ``The
only possessions the family had,'' he said, ``were an upright piano
and 10 volumes of music.'' He tinkered at the keys, but it was his
fourth-grade teacher _ the nun _ who really taught him how to play.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any relationship between playing music and the
awareness that one needs to apologize for errors? Well, yes,
Weakland replied. Music, especially pieces like those that Mozart
composed, can be very difficult to get right. ``You realize that no
human being is perfect,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
