<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers)  
 PRIMARY RESULTS SHOW GORE DISADVANTAGE IN SOUTHERN NUMBERS GAME   
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore underscored his plan to make a bold stand
in the South by visiting Florida Tuesday to await the presidential
primary returns. But those same results give ample evidence of the
daunting task the Democrat faces in trying to pry Southern states
away from Republican George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans voted in larger numbers than Democrats in four of
the five Southern states that held primaries _ Florida, Louisiana,
Texas, Tennessee and Mississippi _ demonstrating the strength of
the GOP base.
</P>
<P>
   In total, about 2.3 million Republicans trooped to the polls to
vote in what were perfunctory elections given the absence of
serious opposition to either Bush or Gore. In comparison, about 1.8
million Democrats voted. Only in Louisiana did Democrats outnumber
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are simply more energized,'' said GOP Chairman Al
Cardenas of Florida, where about 700,000 Republicans out-polled
586,000 Democrats despite a Democratic edge in overall
registration.
</P>
<P>
   Gore nevertheless vowed he would mount a charge on the regional
Republican stronghold, declaring in Tallahassee that ``this Son of
the South'' would keep ``fighting for every vote and every state.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, most analysts put certain segments of the South off
limits to Democrats _ Alabama, Mississippi and South Carolina
particularly. The best Gore can probably hope to do is pick off
Tennessee and possibly another state or two, targeting Georgia,
Florida and perhaps Louisiana though the latter's proximity to
Texas might make it Bush territory.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats like to note that President Clinton took Louisiana
twice, Georgia in 1992 and Florida in 1996, giving hope to Gore.
But in those races, Clinton got help from Ross Perot, who siphoned
votes away from Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A HEARTBEAT AWAY
</P>
<P>
   With the presidential nominations settled, speculation now turns
to the question of running mates. Although selections are not
usually announced until the respective party conventions, that
hasn't stopped supporters and pundits from throwing out a host of
names as vice presidential material.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Southerners figure into the talk. On the Democratic
side, Sen. Bob Graham of Florida is viewed as a contender because
of his popularity in a key electoral state. Democrats believe his
selection could cause Republicans to spend time and money in
Florida where Gov. Jeb Bush was expected to easily deliver the
state for his older brother, George.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt, who is retiring this
year, remains enormously popular in what is otherwise a
Republican-leaning state. While unlikely, his selection could again
force Bush to spend more time in a state he probably figured he
could take for granted. Former Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia could bring
foreign policy and defense expertise.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, retiring Sen. Connie Mack of Florida has
been touted as a contender, but that's seen as a long shot because
Bush already has a strong Florida connection through his brother.
Sen. Fred Thompson of Tennessee, who was a McCain supporter, could
help the Texas governor reach out to moderate and independent
voters.
</P>
<P>
   MOBILE HOME LAW IMPROVEMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Congress is advancing proposed mobile home standards that a
watchdog group says have been improved to the benefit of consumers
who rely on this popular Sunbelt housing option.
</P>
<P>
   Key House and Senate panels gave consumers a larger role in
recommending federal mobile home standards, established minimum
installation requirements and allowed states to determine whether
installers or manufacturers are responsible for fixing defects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there has been real progress,'' said Roy Green, a
lobbyist for AARP, which opposed an earlier proposal.
</P>
<P>
   He credited Sens. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., and John Edwards,
D-N.C., with helping negotiate the improvements. The standards have
not been upgraded since the mid-1970s and are based more on motor
vehicle laws than housing codes.
</P>
<P>
   A TAXING STORM
</P>
<P>
   This just might be the only silver lining for victims of last
year's Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service will expedite tax refunds for
hurricane victims claiming loses in their 1999 tax returns. All
taxpayers must do is write ``HURRICANE FLOYD'' in red on the top of
their return and mail it to the IRS Memphis Service Center at P.O.
Box 2079 in Memphis, Tenn. The ZIP code is 38101.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another small step towards helping our neighbors fully
recover from Floyd,'' said Rep. David Price, D-N.C. He has been
leading efforts on Capitol Hill to secure more federal aid for
eastern North Carolina, which got battered by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
