<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NASDAQ CORRECTION; NOW BACK TO BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Questions may be italicized)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Did last week's stock market hubbub change anything?
Of course, the highflying Nasdaq market has suffered repeated
sinking spells but the latest one _ last week's three consecutive
triple-digit declines amounting to just under 10 percent _ was
accompanied by a revival in industrial stocks of the Old Economy.
The Dow Jones industrial average soared nearly 500 points on
Thursday, the most ever.
</P>
<P>
   This sharply divergent performance inspired much talk that
perhaps investors had finally decided technology valuations had
stretched to the breaking point. Maybe, the thinking seemed to be,
it was time to scoop up some workaday stocks that had become too
cheap to ignore any longer.
</P>
<P>
   The market's sharp reaction to a statement by President Bill
Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair on biotechnology
policy seemed to demonstrate Nasdaq's fragility and make it seem
plausible that such a shift in sentiment had begun.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew W. Johnson, 34, chief trader of Nasdaq stocks for Lehman
Brothers, took some time early Friday to express his own, somewhat
different, view. Here are excerpts from the conversation:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you think there is a sea change under way in the market? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. No. The Old Economy stocks got to levels that were way
oversold. If the move lasts more than a couple days, it's
predicting that the Fed will be out of the picture, either out
completely without raising rates next week _ which I don't think is
totally out of the question _ or will raise only one more time. I'm
sort of going against the trend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So the pyrotechnics were not signaling the end of Nasdaq's
ride? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Right. I think Nasdaq's short-term correction was certainly
necessary. They had moved too far, too fast. And these stocks could
consolidate, could move sideways until we see what first-quarter
earnings will look like. But every indication is that the numbers
are going to be good, in some cases very, very good for tech
stocks. It looks like our bull market continues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. But prices in many cases are still sky-high. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The hardest part for a lot of us on Wall Street who have
taken traditional valuation measures, if you try to apply them
today you'd probably never buy a stock. I'm a believer in the new
paradigm. Traffic on the Internet is doubling every 100 days; if
you think about that, you begin to understand the magnitude of this
technology revolution and you can understand investors' willingness
to take the risks they're taking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are investors taking on too much risk? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The brokerage community used to look at the general public as
ignorant _ not understanding companies, valuations, how the market
works. But with the Internet and the tremendous interest in stock
investing, the public has become more educated and has a stomach
that can absorb more risk than they ever have before. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there a bubble here, with too much bought on credit? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Nothing about the market worries me except the speculation
that has been taking place within the Bulletin Board in penny
stocks. I don't consider what has taken place within Nasdaq to be
speculation. It reflects the promise of tomorrow and the belief
that this is a technology revolution that will change the world
economy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What does the biotech blowup tell us? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It reflects high valuations. Biotech has been one of the best
performers. When you have the threat of government intervention,
certainly they're vulnerable. Am I surprised by the magnitude of
the drop? No. There's a lot more talk about huge drops than the
huge gains. These things have had unbelievable moves; 12 biotech
stocks represent the entire gain in Russell 2000 this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the effect of huge gyrations, day trading and
skyrocketing volume, which has recently hit 2 billion shares a
day? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure, I imagine volatility causes some investors angst and
consternation, absolutely. But day traders add liquidity and while
some on Wall Street disdain them, it takes a lot of guts to do what
they do. And there are some good ones out there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there more business than can be properly handled? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We are so busy that our technology and our people are being
pushed to the limit every day. When people ask me what will be the
catalyst, if there is one, to set this market in a spiral downward
_ which I don't think will take place _ I say we will need to pause
for awhile to give the infrastructure a chance to catch up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. And would decimalization make the strains worse?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The investment community as a whole, including the public,
cannot handle decimalization right now. This is a 200-year-old
pricing dynamic that we're planning to change overnight _ and that
scares me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
