<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0356 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-WORLD-SWISSWATCH-     03-17 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WORLD-SWISSWATCH-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE SWISS WATCH TRADE, A NEW FACE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ On a winding country road near here, a century-old
mansion set in impeccably manicured grounds overlooking Lake Geneva
houses what may be Switzerland's unlikeliest factory.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, watchmakers labor over high wooden tables, peering
through microscopes to fashion the precise and complicated luxury
watches that are the stock in trade of Franck Muller Watchland, as
music plays and breathtaking views of the Alps beckon through
mullioned windows.
</P>
<P>
   The company is swimming against powerful tides in more ways than
just its sumptuous headquarters, set in a village-like campus. For
all its importance to the country's economy, the $10 billion Swiss
watch industry is going through a profound transformation.
</P>
<P>
   The making of movements _ the mechanical working parts _ has
been steadily migrating out of the country in search of cheaper
labor, leaving only the most expensive models made entirely in
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a once-clubby, insular industry populated by
scores of family-owned companies with 200- and 300-year pedigrees
is rapidly being consolidated. A handful of corporations like
Swatch Group and LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton have been
assembling stables of venerable brands while the total number of
manufacturers has dwindled to fewer than 100.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall alone, LVMH acquired Tag Heuer and Ebel, two prominent
luxury brands, as well as Zenith International, a component maker;
it also bought Chaumet, a French watch maker.
</P>
<P>
   Swatch, the world's largest watchmaker, recently bought one of
the most prestigious names in Switzerland, Group Horloge Breguet,
whose watches can cost up to $1 million. Both companies are said by
analysts to be actively searching for more acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is not growing quickly in terms of the number of
watches sold. Exports fell 3 percent last year, to around 31
million watches, and are forecast to manage only 2 percent or 3
percent growth this year, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The financial state of the industry is hard to gauge because
only two of its companies, Swatch and Compagnie Financiere
Richemont (which also has tobacco and direct-marketing businesses),
are publicly held.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as unpromising as this climate would seem for a start-up,
Franck Muller thought there was room for a maverick, especially at
the top end of the market, home to what growth there is.
</P>
<P>
   Since its founding in 1992, his company has grown to 120
employees turning out 16,000 watches a year, ranging in price from
$3,000 to $100,000, depending on the watch's complexity. The
company's specialty is complicated mechanisms like the Master
Banker, which tracks three time zones at once, and the World
Premiere, which combines all of the company's most inventive
specialty features. It has introduced a total of 10 new models this
year, too.
</P>
<P>
   In the villa, Muller said, he can oversee ``watches being made
from beginning to end'' _ both the traditional, painstaking hand
work and the computer-aided design systems used to develop watch
mechanisms. Muller particularly prides himself on one such
component, a tourbillon, which compensates for gravity's effects on
time-keeping.
</P>
<P>
   Muller, 41, restored antique watches before beginning his own
company, and decorates his elegant office with an extensive
collection of antique watchmaking tools. Their modern equivalents
are seen busily fashioning some of the company's more exotic
products during a tour of the Watchland workshops.
</P>
<P>
   One large watch encrusted with black diamonds was being fitted
with a new gold-and-black diamond dial. Muller would not say who
had ordered it or how much it cost, though the watch face, engraved
with a Moscow landmark, gave a clue.
</P>
<P>
   Up in the eaves of the villa, across from an engraver working on
a watch face with an erotic theme, engineers sat at computer design
workstations. The company buys some movements from foreign
suppliers, but designs and makes most of its components itself, as
Swiss firms have done since the days four centuries ago when John
Calvin turned Geneva into a magnet for Huguenot craftsmen driven
from France by religious persecution.
</P>
<P>
   When Asian markets took a nose-dive two years ago, the luxury
watch business turned wobbly, but prosperity in the United States
has helped shore it up since then. Total American spending on
luxury watches rose 14 percent in 1999, according to the Federation
of the Swiss Watch Industry.
</P>
<P>
   Swatch's results for the second half of 1999, announced last
Thursday, reflect that trend. Profits were up sharply from the same
period in 1998, thanks largely to strong demand for luxury goods in
North America and the company's success in raising prices,
especially for its Longines and Omega brands.
</P>
<P>
   About 7 in 10 customers at the top end of the market are men,
for whom a prestigious watch serves the same purpose that jewelry
does for women. Indeed, Calvin's religious proscription against
jewelry in the 16th century spurred the development of the
beautiful decorated watches that built Switzerland's enduring
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   To reach men, manufacturers like TAG Heuer often sponsor
sporting events. Others, like Omega, also market their wares to
women; Muller said women bought 40 percent of his watches.
</P>
<P>
   The industry believes the era of ``one watch for life'' has
largely ended, and it is counting on many customers to buy several
expensive watches _ typically a sports watch and a dress watch, at
minimum. Some analysts predict the industry's future will see a
melding of watch and jewelry making, bringing it full circle,
historically speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be more mergers. This phenomenon will go on,'' said
Jean-Daniel Pasche, director of the industry federation. Pierre
Tissot, vice president of Lombard Odier &AMP; Cie bank and a specialist
in the industry, said economies of scale were the reason _ not so
much in making watches as in marketing and distributing them.
``Size does matter, because it is difficult for a single company to
find its way to the customer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There will always be exceptions like Franck Muller, which
confines itself to a specific market niche and does as much work as
it can in-house. But, Tissot said, ``If you want to be global and
offset economic downturns in various regions, you need to be
larger.''
</P>
<P>
   Muller would not provide figures for the company's performance,
saying only that ``my cash flow is good.'' But he said he had no
intention of selling his business to a larger company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a family organization,'' Muller said. ``I can do
everything I want to do now, with no reporting to anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
