<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-DYLAN-SONG-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DYLAN SHINES ON `WONDER BOYS' SOUNDTRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL DEAN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days, any new music from Bob Dylan is eagerly awaited by
those who pine for the days when poetry blew in the wind and
brilliance knocked on heaven's door.
</P>
<P>
   With just one new Dylan song, the soundtrack for the new film
``Wonder Boys'' offers only a morsel of freshness from the original
genius of folk rock.
</P>
<P>
   On this compilation of essentially like-minded material, the new
Dylan song ``Things Have Changed'' plays welcome quarterback to a
CD of 12 older tunes from various artists, including three other
songs by Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things Have Changed,'' is basically a mid-tempo, 12-bar blues
song with sprightly played acoustic guitar licks. It serves the
soundtrack's melancholy mission well, and Dylan's voice is in full
Popeye-drunk-on-ripple-wine mode.
</P>
<P>
   The movie stars Michael Douglas as a successful novelist
dreading the prospect of failure; in other words, fear has stalled
his progress on a followup.
</P>
<P>
   Producer-director Curtis Hanson (``L.A. Confidential'') packed
his soundtrack with revealing tales from the ``wonder boys'' of
music to match Douglas' portrayal of a literary wonder boy.
</P>
<P>
   In the album's liner notes, Hanson says he chose such tunes as
Neil Young's ``Old Man,'' John Lennon's ``Watching the Wheels'' and
Van Morrison's ``Philosophers Stone'' because they ``underscore the
bittersweetness of success (and its aftermath) as well as the
yearning for purpose ... that connects the movie's central
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   And he calls Dylan, also represented here with songs from 1975's
``Blood on the Tracks,'' 1989's ``Oh Mercy'' and 1997's ``Time Out
of Mind,'' the ``consummate `wonder boy' of rock whose miraculous
creativity has ceaselessly amazed us all over four decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanson could only have penned that after hearing the new
``Things Have Changed,'' in which Dylan breathlessly sneers of dead
ends and desperate situations.
</P>
<P>
   In one verse, he's ``standing on the gallows with my head in the
noose; any minute ... expecting all hell to break loose.''
</P>
<P>
   That sets up the chorus: ``People are crazy and times are
strange; I'm locked in tight, I'm out of range. I used to care ...
but things have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   With his own ``Shooting Star,'' ``Not Dark Yet'' and ``Buckets
of Rain'' filling out the soundtrack (along with Clarence Carter's
``Slip Away,'' Leonard Cohen's ``Waiting For the Miracle'' and
others) Dylan proves Hanson right.
</P>
<P>
   He also makes happy those nibbling on ``Wonder Boys,'' the
soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dean writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., which is a
member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This article
was distributed by The New York Times News Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
