<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-R-TECHNOLOGY-FUTURE-N     03-17 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TECHNOLOGY-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WARNING FROM THE BRAVE NEW WIRED WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no originality in imagining science's horrors. Since
the Romantic era, it has been difficult to imagine anything else:
Science creates machinery of destruction. It spawns mutants. It
spews radiation. Its objective pose is a cover for callous
indifference. Scientists murder (as Wordsworth once said of Newton)
to dissect.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the premises of many science fiction novels and most
science fiction films. They help motivate the new discipline of
``science studies.'' They erupt into public life, in debates about
disarmament and the environment. And since the Manhattan Project,
some misgivings are justified: science has now put human survival
in human hands.
</P>
<P>
   So why should a a sober warning about technology's dangers be
treated as a revelation after being featured in the April issue of
Wired magazine? In the last week, Bill Joy, the author of the
article, ``Why the Future Doesn't Need Us,'' has been interviewed
on television, written about in newspapers and argued about on the
Internet. Yet there is not a single point that has not already been
made elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Joy, who is a co-founder and chief scientist of Sun Microsystems
and one of the most respected idea men in the computer field,
anticipates this dd objection, admitting that ``all this has been
written about before'': ``This is nothing new.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not even new that he turns his attention from old
technology nuclear threats to new technology dangers of genetic
engineering, or turns from imaginings of ecological disaster to the
threat of ambitious, hyper-intelligent robots. Who is in the dark
about the ethical problems involved in cloning, the genome project
and genetic testing? What science fiction writer has neglected the
theme of rebellious robots?
</P>
<P>
   But what is new is that Joy's essay appears in Wired, a magazine
that is more used to celebrating the brave new wired world. In a
piece written about Joy in August 1998 by Kevin Kelley _ one of
Wired's founders _ and Spencer Reiss _ a Wired editor, the
Internet, for example, is glowingly imagined as a ``vast planetary
system'' of interacting machines, ``expanding by its own internal
logic.'' It is a ``global nervous system.''
</P>
<P>
   As it evolves it will alter human life as we know it. Wired has
published speculations that this global nervous system may actually
lead to a new life form, currently beyond imagining. This
enthusiastic expectation is not the exception. Internet visionaries
of the 1990s often indulged in ecstatic imaginings of human
transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Joy's comments are also related to the exuberant arguments in
Ray Kurzweil's recent book, ``The Age of Spiritual Machines.''
Kurzweil, a prolific and brilliant inventor, argues that not only
are computer speeds increasing and computer sizes decreasing at
exponential rates, but that this kind of explosive change will
continue without foreseeable limits. By the year 2030, Kurzweil
suggests, computers will be about a million times more powerful
than they are today; they will start to resemble life forms. Humans
will also contain machines: miniaturization will allow nanobots _
microscopic robots _ to be injected into the bloodstream and heal
their host organisms. Humans will merge with their machines; we
will all be cyborgs. This, Kurzweil argues, is good news.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that in a world of surging entrepreneurial
energy, the prospects of technological change are being celebrated.
Even Joy is ordinarily somewhat of a utopian visionary in his work
for Sun. Fortune magazine called Joy ``The Edison of the
Internet'': he designed crucial system software, three of Sun's
microprocessors, and developed the Java programming language. More
recently he has been working on a computer-based system known as
Jini, which will allow household appliances to ``talk'' to one
another: use a Palm Pilot to start a car, have a computer send a
warning e-mail when the refrigerator gets too warm or ask a
camcorder to transmit pictures through a cell phone. Sun promised
Jini appliances last year, but they still aren't even close. I
don't see a compelling need for Jini, but no matter: it is utopian
because it makes the impossible seem possible.
</P>
<P>
   So it is no surprise that out of such an inventive and innocent
world, Joy's dissent would seem thunderous. What, then, is to be
done? Joy's proposals _ that we ``take personal responsibility'' or
hold Aspen Institute-type conferences _ will not make much of a
difference. Knowledge will increase; so will applications; so will
temptations. Any evil that grows out of technology will not arise
through nefarious plotting, but unpredictably and incidentally: by
letting Jini-like innovations out the bottle, by increasing human
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems, in fact, might not be in technology itself,
but in the ways in which technological culture has already undercut
the special status of the human. In studying computer simulations
of life, some theorists have argued that sophisticated simulations
are themselves primitive life forms. Among other thinkers it is
also becoming more common to think of humans as ``hosts'' for
``memes'': memes are ideas _ like ``justice'' or ``evil,'' the
opening of Beethoven's Fifth Symphony, or the taste for tatoos _
that replicate and spread from body to body like genes; their
particular meanings are unimportant. These sorts of speculations
treat human nature as a sophisticated form of information
processing. Why should tampering with such codes matter? Genetic
engineering is just another form of re-programming.
</P>
<P>
   This view of human life grows directly out of the culture Wired
celebrates. It does not encourage experimental restraint. Instead,
it encourages speculation about how we can control our memes and
genes, and encourages optimism that the possibilities are
unlimited. So Joy's argument needs amplification: there are not
only risks latent in technology, there are risks latent in certain
celebrations of technology. The dangers lie not in our technology
but in ourselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
