<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0365 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-HERSHBERGER-SALON-$AD     03-17 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERSHBERGER-SALON-$ADV19-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING WITH SALLY HERSHBERGER IN THE VERY FAST LANE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to New York Times photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, March 19) (DW) 
 By ELLEN TIEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sally Hershberger was slaloming around the limos in the parking
lot of the Ron Herman/Fred Segal Melrose store in Los Angeles.
``Just so you know,'' she said, pausing at the entrance, ``I am the
fastest shopper.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershberger, the Hollywood hairstylist who has become something
of a celebrity in her own right coiffing stars like Meg Ryan,
Michelle Pfeiffer and Tom Cruise, was on a high-speed mission: to
outfit both herself and her new Los Angeles salon, Sally
Hershberger at John Frieda, for its opening party this coming
Friday. ``Generally, I live in black leather pants and a T-shirt,''
she said. ``But for the party I might try something more vivid.''
</P>
<P>
   Something, no doubt, epitomizing what appear to be her three e's
of style: easy, edge-pushing, expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go!''
</P>
<P>
   No dawdling. Hershberger, 40, who resembles a cross between
Annette Bening and Mackenzie Phillips, seems to be in perpetual
motion, chop-chopping between Los Angeles, where she grew up; the
John Frieda Salon in New York; her homes in Los Angeles, New York,
Connecticut and East Hampton; promotions for the John Frieda Sheer
Blonde line of hair products she helped develop; and on-location
jobs for her star clients. While she is renowned for her signature
undone hairdos, it is through her combination of charisma and blunt
confidence that she has managed to pull away from the pack of
fame-hungry cut-and-colorists and corner the glam hair market. When
Hillary Clinton was going on the cover of Vogue, Hershberger got
the call. The first woman to achieve the status of an Oribe or
Frederic Fekkai, Hershberger can command $400 for a regular haircut
and a day rate of $4,000 for fashion shoots. But she has not
adopted the schmoozy, cosseting approach of her male counterparts.
She issues style dictums and fashion tips to clients with the
authority of a hip generalissimo. When one admired her vintage
Gucci bracelet at her salon recently, she replied: ``Maxfield's.
You must go. Go! Right now!''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a town like Los Angeles, where salons double as social
scenes, Hershberger will be put to a new test. Her name is now on
the building, and her reputation will be scrutinized afresh. Hence
the importance of her opening party. It has to set exactly the
right tone. While this prospect might make fainter hearts flutter,
it appears to be having the opposite effect on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never ponder, never agonize,'' she said, galloping up the
stairs at Fred Segal. Racing by a long shelf of cashmere sweaters
with graphic designs, she tapped her finger on each sweater and
sprinted through her commentary: ``Love, don't love, love, kind of
love,'' Then, pausing at a $600 cream ribbed crew neck with a large
blue heart on the front: ``Looooove.'' At that instant, a $110
glitter-appliqued ``I Love You'' baseball T by Chloe caught her
eye. ``Oh, really love. That's faaaabulous.'' She grabbed it and
turned on her heel. ``OK Downstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Back on the first floor, she made a beeline for the Bedazzled
section, a line of embellished vintage denim, where she ran into
two friends, the actress Peggy Lipton and Lulu, the British singer
best known for ``To Sir, With Love.'' Furiously rifling through the
racks, Hershberger held up a pair of $1,100 dirty-denim jeans
studded with colored rhinestones in an elaborate floral pattern.
``I die over these,'' she said to the two women.
</P>
<P>
   Lulu clapped her hands. A quick spin in and out of the dressing
room and it was settled: the jeans and shirt would be Hershberger's
opening-night ensemble. ``Done,'' she said. ``On we go!''
</P>
<P>
   Total shopping time: 18 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop: Fahey/Klein, a Los Angeles gallery that specializes
in fashion photography. There she met with John Frieda to choose
art for their salon. ``I want photographs of models, I want
fashion, I want beauty,'' Hershberger declared.
</P>
<P>
   One of her first celebrity connections was the photographer Herb
Ritts, who met Hershberger when she was 23 and a few years out of
beauty school, working on Olivia Newton-John's ``Let's Get
Physical'' tour. ``He was shooting the concert, and I was doing
hair,'' Hershberger recalled. ``One day, he said we should do
editorial together, and we ended up working together, like, every
day after that for years.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also through her association with Ritts that Hershberger
solidified her aesthetic sensibility, which she described as
follows: ``All things simple and beautiful, but eminently livable.
It doesn't matter whether you're talking about hair or houses or
clothes _ they should be clean, glamorous, but not too perfect.
Perfection should be a little wrecked. It has to be lived in.''
</P>
<P>
   As obliging Fahey/Klein employees brought out a succession of
Irving Penn and Helmut Newton prints, Hershberger shook her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``No _ what else? No _ what else? Too small. We need big. Big.
Bigger. Bigger _ and in color!'' She and Frieda did a quick huddle
on the couch, leafing through catalogs and books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adoring this David Bailey,'' Hershberger remarked, pointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Frieda said, ``except if we want it, we can just call
David. What about this one of Twiggy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, except if we want it, we can just call Twiggy,''
Hershberger said.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, their very plugged-inness seemed to paralyze them.
If they knew all the artists, what were they doing at the gallery?
The tepid breath of indecision threatened to descend _ until
Hershberger snapped out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough,'' she said. ``Let's move.'' She selected several
(great big) Irving Penn black-and-white shots of Amber Valetta,
Shalom Harlow and Naomi Campbell, ranging from $6,500 to $19,000,
to be held for eventual purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Elapsed art-buying time: 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Back at the salon, a team of party planners waited. Along with
two John Frieda publicists, they stood awkwardly clustered in the
entrance to the airy white and glass 3,600-square-foot structure,
staring at the three sleek black marble fireplaces, the indoor pool
and the flowing water wall that serve as the visual centerpieces.
Even when Hershberger and Frieda joined them, they remained
standing. Hershberger seems to prefer conducting business on her
feet, as if perpetually poised for a speedy exit _ perhaps the same
reason she chose a career that requires her to stand.
</P>
<P>
   The party planners began with a list of potential food styles:
Japanese, Asian-fusion, Indian. It soon became clear, however, that
the real issue was less about eating and more about chic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indian,'' Hershberger declared. ``Indian is sexier than
Japanese. Really sexy Indian food with really sexy waiters. All
good-looking guys not wearing a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Drinks?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine and beautiful juices, maybe mango Bellinis. Do Bellinis
match Indian?''
</P>
<P>
   Music?
</P>
<P>
   ``Indian music, but not too mellow. Upbeat Indian music.''
</P>
<P>
   And decoration?
</P>
<P>
   ``Incense, lounge pillows, candles everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, with the hushed importance and deliberation of a
military invasion, possible dates for the party were discussed.
``When is Barry Diller's party?'' Hershberger asked. ``When is
Elton's party? Find out.'' An assistant was dispatched to draft a
top-secret, off-the-record guest list. Party-planning time
expended: 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, Hershberger was in New York to continue her
quest for the perfect salon furnishings: Arts and Crafts-style
chairs for the reception area, '60s-modern floor lamps, mirrors to
hang over fireplaces. The salon, she said, should have ``a New York
feel within a California structure.'' Hershberger hurtled out the
revolving door of her West Village apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   So what was she looking for at Wyeth, the by-appointment vintage
furniture store on Franklin Street? ``Important pieces!''
</P>
<P>
   At Wyeth, Hershberger threw her black Tse cashmere coat on a
chair and stalked the room in a black Jil Sander T-shirt and
leather pants. She eyed an $80,000 set of urns and an Annie
Leibovitz photograph that, she was informed, was already sold.
``Well, if it's sold, why do you have it out?'' she asked, piqued
at having wasted 40 seconds looking at it.
</P>
<P>
   After shooting Polaroids of a $3,800 wall mirror and a $4,400
floor lamp, she asked the manager to hold them for her and whisked
uptown in a hired car to Troy, on Greene Street, where she put
aside a $9,500 Alexander Vethers abstract black-and-white image of
a fashion runway _ ``for the wall behind my station, it's
geeenius!'' _ and bought several $380 glass block vases.
</P>
<P>
   Salon furnishings time: 42 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With a little jig of impatience, Hershberger ducked into Louis
Vuitton to pick up a $1,260 logo suitcase on wheels (``Perfect for
shoots _ kind of over the top, but that's why it's funny''), and
share her yoga mantra with the manager. ``It's Oon namah shivaya,''
she said. ``Here, let me write it down for you. Oon namah shivaya,
oonnamahshivaya.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, people think that yoga is all mellow and laid-back,
but they're wrong. To be yogic is to be precise. It's to know what
you want, figure out how to get it and take action. It's about
clarity. Clarity gives you energy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And energy,'' she said, spinning around and heading for the
door, ``is, you know _ gooorgeous.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiritual exploration: three minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
