<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-HELMS-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL MEMBERS WEIGH HELMS' INVITATION TO WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Should they or shouldn't they?
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Security Council are pondering an invitation to
Washington from Sen. Jesse Helms, the North Carolina Republican who
is chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, and Sen.
Joseph R. Biden Jr. of Delaware, the ranking Democrat on the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone on the 15-member council is thrilled by the
prospect. Helms has been a leading critic of the United Nations,
and diplomats are also concerned about how the image of this
powerful panel trundling off to Capitol Hill would play around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials are trying to broaden the scope
of the visit, adding meetings with high-level State Department and
perhaps White House officials, capped by a social evening with
international guests, according to some private groups helping with
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of day would be different, several Security Council
members said. But some are eager to go even without the add-ons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, there has been an estrangement between the U.S.
and the U.N.,'' a diplomat said. What is important, he added, is
``getting back together.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright sent her own
invitation to the 15 ambassadors on the Security Council, urging
them to make the trip to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Helms first extended the invitation to meet his committee when
he spoke to the Security Council in January during an extraordinary
session in which he criticized the United Nations and said he was
speaking for the American people. Early this month he proposed a
date, March 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``We very much appreciated the warm welcome extended to us
during our visit to the United Nations in January, and the
constructive discussion at that time,'' he and Biden said in a
letter to this month's council president, Anwarul Karim Chowdhury
of Bangladesh. ``It will be a pleasure to repay your hospitality.''
</P>
<P>
   All council members were sent identical letters. A few diplomats
have already responded to the committee, which made the point of
inviting them as individuals rather than as an official body.
Senate committee members are prepared to see a few decline the
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Helms felt that we began a very constructive dialogue
in New York, and he wants to continue that dialogue,'' said Marc
Thiessen, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee spokesman. ``He
said in his speech that the only way we're going to be able to fix
the U.S.-U.N. relationship is if we understand each other better.
He felt that we had stated that up in New York, and he didn't want
it to be a one-time thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard C. Holbrooke, the U.S. representative, who arranged
Helms' appearance in New York in January, is expected to do his
utmost to persuade wavering diplomats to accept the invitation to
Washington in the interests of what one waverer acknowledged Friday
could be ``a useful exchange of views.'' Holbrooke, whose powers of
persuasion diplomats say they never underestimate, is now in Asia
arguing the case for lower U.S. payments to the United Nations, a
subject dear to Helms.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There was also some chemistry in New York in January between the
Security Council and Helms and his committee members, many of them
Senate veterans accustomed to the traditional, even exaggerated
courtesies of earlier, less partisan years in Congress. The
Security Council sits in a chamber replete with ceremony and
diplomatic niceties. Before Helms left New York, he had donned a
U.N. cap and was exchanging toasts with council members at the
staid Metropolitan Club.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Albright reminded the Security Council that
the administration made foreign policy and did not always share the
views of Helms. In their letter to Chowdhury, dated March 3 but not
released by Helms' staff until two days ago, the senators suggested
a morning tour of the Capitol, a lunch with the committee and an
afternoon round-table discussion. Events planned by the
administration would have to fit around that schedule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
