<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAPLES EFFORT PACKS A PUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The official announcement will come Monday at a
scheduled press conference at Staples Center, but the most
lucrative boxing match in California history _ Oscar De La Hoya
against Sugar Shane Mosley _ will be staged at the new Los Angeles
arena on June 17.
</P>
<P>
   And I can't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't think Staples Center _ or any other arena outside Las
Vegas _ would wind up with such an appealing match, especially when
places like Caesars Palace, the MGM Grand and the Mandalay Bay all
reportedly desired it.
</P>
<P>
   But I guess I underestimated the resolve of Staples Center
president Tim Leiweke and his top lieutenant, Bobby Goldwater, in
wanting to make the downtown edifice a major new player on the
boxing scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fight that belongs in L.A., and we're going to bill
it as `California Destiny,' '' says Bob Arum, the promoter who
negotiated the deal with Leiweke.
</P>
<P>
   It might belong in L.A. because De La Hoya is a native of the
city and Mosley hails from Pomona, but one idly wonders why the
shrewd Arum would pass on Las Vegas casinos who routinely fork out
$6 million site fees for a fight of this caliber.
</P>
<P>
   Is Staples Center coming up with such a sum?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' answered Arum firmly. ``What we've agreed to do is share
receipts with Staples Center from the gate. Staples Center also
will guarantee that a certain amount of tickets will be sold. We
look for the gate to be in the seven million dollar range.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be slightly more than the California record
established a few years ago in Sacramento by Tony Lopez and Jorge
Paez when their fight pulled in more than $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Arum wouldn't be specific on what the percentage take
would be for his Top Rank organization, but you can be sure it will
be high if Staples Center indeed hasn't put up a seven-figure
offering to hold such a high-profile event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've wanted to take this fight from the start to L.A.,'' says
Arum. ``And the Staples people wanted it. The only holdup was the
tax situation. L.A. has a three percent city tax, which we can live
with. But, as it stands right now, there is a five percent tax on
fight tickets that goes to the California State Athletic
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just too much taxation. You can't have eight percent of
the gate going to taxes. It just cuts into the profit margin too
much. A bill soon will be introduced in the California state
legislature that would put a $50,000 ceiling on the taxes that
would go to the athletic commission from this fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what they did in New York before the Lennox
Lewis-Evander Holyfield heavyweight fight. If the bill fails,
Staples Center has agreed to make up the monetary difference with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Arum has scaled the house at $900, $700, $300 and, showing he's
the milk of human kindness, even will have 2,300 tickets priced at
$100 and 3,200 at $50.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard complaints now for years from Oscar's fans in L.A.
that they never had the opportunity to see him fight, but now they
will have it,'' says Arum.
</P>
<P>
   The fight itself should be a thriller, with the sport's reigning
Golden Boy, De La Hoya, whose sheen was somewhat tarnished with his
late follies against Felix Trinidad, trying to regain lost stature
against the quick-striking, quick-hitting bundle of energy that is
the undefeated Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'm glad De La Hoya is fighting Mosley rather than
Trinidad because I'm afraid De La Hoya would have employed the same
tedious, cautious tactics had he fought Trinidad again, whereas he
just might be willing to be slightly bolder and more aggressive
against the smaller Mosley. ...
</P>
<P>
   -The only complaint I have about Wayne Morgan's Long Beach State
49ers is that they unfortunately lost their three most important
games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   If the 49ers had beaten Utah State at the Pyramid , they would
have been the top-seeded team in the Big West tournament and would
have faced quite beatable Nevada in the semifinals instead of New
Mexico State.
</P>
<P>
   If the 49ers had beaten New Mexico State, they would have
advanced to the conference title game, and would have received an
automatic NCAA bid had they been able to win it.
</P>
<P>
   If they had beaten California the other night in their NIT
opener, they would have received the national exposure that Morgan
craves by next facing Georgetown on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Comeback College Basketball Coach Of The Year Morgan
should be commended for finally turning the desperately struggling
49er program around after three consecutive losing seasons. He soon
will be rewarded with a three-year contract extension from athletic
director Bill Shumard, once a fierce Morgan critic but now a
booster.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm sure it's only a matter of time when one of Morgan's
teams wins a game when it counts most. ...
</P>
<P>
   -Terrific investigative reporting this week in the
Press-Telegram on the Artesia High basketball program by Billy
Witz, Steve Irvine and Fausto Ramos, our own version of Woodward &AMP;
Bernstein. ...
</P>
<P>
   -I didn't shed a tear about the retirement of Dan Marino, a
multi-millionaire who's lived a charmed life the rest of us can
only wistfully envy. Indeed, anyone who watched his ghastly work
the past season for the Miami Dolphins wondered why he hadn't
already retired. ...
</P>
<P>
   -I, like everyone else, am rooting heartily for Sean Elliott,
while I, like everyone else, am wondering why in tarnation the San
Antonio Spurs' forward would be attempting a comeback fraught with
such physical risks. As one well-known doctor told me, ``No athlete
has ever tried to play professional sports seven months after
having a kidney transplant, and the medical field just doesn't know
for sure what will happen. I personally would be against Elliott
playing, but I certainly wouldn't stop him if he wanted to.''. ...
</P>
<P>
   -Long Beach public relations demon Mario Perez informs me two of
the best runners in the history of the Rams, Eric Dickerson and
Marhsall Faulk, are scheduled to participate in the first annual
Mazda Golf Tournament Monday at the Mesa Verde Country Club in
Costa Mesa. Proceeds will benefit the Orange Coast College
Foundation. ...
</P>
<P>
   -I'm not surprised Schea Cotton left Alabama prematurely, but I
will be surprised if I ever see him playing in the NBA. ...
</P>
<P>
   -The only thing I detest more than basketball players wearing
those silly headbands _ do they realize how goofy they look? _ is
coaches adorn in mustaches. ...
</P>
<P>
   -Bob Arum, on the future of boxing: ``The era of the big
megabuck events at casinos in Las Vegas is beginning to fade
because of the corporate consolidation in the gambling business.
Now that MGM has taken over the Mirage, Bellagio and Treasure
Island, do you think it wants to bring in its high rollers for
fights staged by Park Place, which owns Caesars Palace and the
Hilton properties? No way. And vice versa. The competition among
these groups for high rollers has grown bitterly fierce. And we
promoters have to change with the times. That's why you're seeing
more fights at Madison Square Garden and that's why you're going to
see some big fights at Staples Center.''
</P>
<P>
   -They were mourning this week at St. John Bosco High the passing
of one of the school's most passionate boosters, Tom Reilly, who
for more than 30 years was an active volunteer in the Braves'
athletic program. He was eulogized glowingly by St. John Bosco's
football coach, Kiki Mendoza, and many of the school's football
players attended Mr. Reilly's funeral mass wearing their jerseys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
