<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ ACKNOWLEDGES COMPUTER OVERLOAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nasdaq exchange, which has seen trading volume balloon as
investors have rushed into technology stocks, experienced computer
problems earlier this month, a Nasdaq official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although a March 6 computer glitch was not as severe as one that
effectively crippled the exchange and halted trades last November
for about 20 minutes, the recent malfunction has reignited concerns
among traders and investment managers about whether the nation's
hottest exchange can handle an unexpected and unprecedented rise in
volume of the computer stocks that are its primary business.
</P>
<P>
   The March 6 incident was ``like a hang nail,'' the Nasdaq
official said, compared with the November shutdown, which he
characterized as a ``heart attack.''
</P>
<P>
   But traders said it became very difficult to complete trades
during the entire 17-minute March incident, from about 2:55 p.m.
until 3:12, after a Nasdaq price-feeding system stopped working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped receiving prices from Nasdaq, and when you have no
prices, there is no trading,'' said one trader at a large Manhattan
firm who refused to be quoted.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is volume. The number of transactions on Nasdaq has
exploded, from less then 800,000 shares per day, on average, during
1998 to 1.7 million shares daily in January and February of this
year. In recent weeks _ as the Nasdaq index level soared to a
record 5,000-plus closing and then plunged 9 percent _ trading
routinely surpassed 2 million shares a day.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange, on its Web site, reported another minor system
problem Feb. 18 amid a surge in volume.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq official, who spoke on condition that his name not be
used, said a software problem on March 6 caused one of the
exchange's computer systems to ``get stuck in a loop'' for one
minute and 17 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Although trading was not disrupted, the official said the brief
glitch caused an interrupt in the feed of ``last sale prices'' on
completed transactions for a total of 17 minutes, as technicians
repaired the software problem.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices could not be fed into the workstations on traders'
desks or into the program that calculates the Nasdaq's index level.
``Rather than disseminate bad information, for a while we
disseminated no information,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Computers that process trades are separate from those that
provide pricing updates in the Nasdaq computer system, which has
layer upon layer of backup computers to ensure uninterrupted
trading. Nasdaq was ``accepting the trade reports, we were locking
in the trade reports,'' he added. ``Everything was functioning.''
</P>
<P>
   But while few investors or traders blame Nasdaq for the volume
crunch, it is no secret on Wall Street that Nasdaq has problems
keeping up with leaps in trading volume in a bull market for
technology stocks that no one had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how many trades there are,'' said Michael Ryan,
head of equity trading for State Street Resarch &AMP; Management, a
Boston investment firm. About Nasdaq, he said, ``They're
overloaded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 1942EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-ECOMMERCE-(TRIM     03-17 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECOMMERCE-(TRIMS)-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UBIQUITOUS JAPANESE CONVENIENCE STORES BRANCH INTO E-COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Tucked amid the instant noodles, pantyhose and canned
drinks at the local Lawson, Japan's second-largest convenience
store chain, customers now find a computer terminal that gives them
access to a system called Loppi. With a few stabs at the keyboard,
they can order concert tickets, make train and plane reservations
and pay at the cash register on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   Need a book? Seven-Eleven Japan, the country's largest
convenience store operator, lets a customer hop online to
eShopping! Books, a site owned by Softbank, Seven-Eleven, Yahoo!
Japan and Tohan, Japan's leading book distributor. A day or so
later, on the way home from work perhaps, the customer picks up the
selection and pays for it at the local Seven-Eleven.
</P>
<P>
   Seven-Eleven can also help with elderly parents. Just order a
meal online and the company will deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   With no further room to expand physically in this densely packed
country and with competition intensifying as new stores cannibalize
old, the neighborhood convenience store, or ``conbini,'' is betting
on the new economy in Japan, moving to embrace technology. Long
accustomed to adding some 50 new products to its merchandise mix
every week on average, the conbini is fast grabbing hunks of
cyberspace to expand its limited shelf space.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, deregulation that has been unfolding since the
mid-1990s is allowing Japanese convenience stores to encroach on
territory long out of their reach, like beauty and health aids and
banking.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last year, the convenience store has become an
indispensable part of the mosaic that is electronic commerce,''
said Kenyu Adachi, director of the distribution industry division
of the Ministry of Trade and Industry. ``Without the convenience
store, e-commerce in Japan would have more trouble taking off.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Adachi and his ministry express a more tempered
enthusiasm for e-tailing in Japan than do investors, who have, at
least initially, bid up the stocks of any Japanese company remotely
associated with the Internet and information technology to
astonishing levels.
</P>
<P>
   A study last year by the ministry and Andersen Consulting
concluded that while e-commerce in Japan would one day enjoy the
same market share it has in the United States, Japan's less
developed information technology infrastructure and its still
significant regulatory hurdles would mean a much slower rollout.
</P>
<P>
   But the big convenience store chains, which have the lion's
share of the market, are adding new ``virtual'' services and
connections at such a clip that analysts complain they cannot keep
track of it all. Almost simultaneously, the major chains have begun
introducing Internet strategies, raising questions about the
profitability of such ventures.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Convenience stores have a special place in Japanese society,
where tiny homes with space for only miniature refrigerators and
minimal storage make frequent shopping a necessity. Because of its
size, averaging about 100 square meters, the convenience store
escaped the reach of Japanese regulators and thus can be far
nimbler and more responsive to customer whims and fancies than its
larger brethren.
</P>
<P>
   At Seven-Eleven, inventory is controlled by some of the most
sophisticated inventory management and technology. Plus, unlike
other stores, most conbini are open round the clock.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 33,000 convenience stores throughout the
country and traffic in them is high: Some 900 people a day visit
the average Seven-Eleven store, while two other large chains,
FamilyMart and the Circle K Japan unit of UNY Corp., have about 700
customers a day. (Lawson, part of the Japanese retailer Daiei Inc.,
does not make its numbers available.) Makoto Usui, director and
general manager of information systems at Seven-Eleven, said the
average customer visits a Seven-Eleven store once every other day.
</P>
<P>
   The bonds are deep. When Hidetoshi Nakata, the Japanese soccer
star who plays for Rome, was asked an interview what he most missed
about home, he answered, ``Conbini.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Convenience stories' ubiquity and popularity make them
attractive partners to the many virtually unknown e-commerce
companies out there, whose biggest expense is likely to be
marketing. ``They have a huge advantage over the typical Internet
start-up,'' said Mike Allen, a retail analyst at ING Barings in
Tokyo. ``The biggest cost that has prevented dot-com companies from
making money is promotion, and convenience stores have almost no
promotional costs because customers flock to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The conbini have helped Japanese e-commerce pioneers like
Softbank Corp. and Rakuten Ichiba, an online bazaar, leap two major
hurdles: payment and delivery. Japanese consumers are more
reluctant than their American counterparts to send their credit
card account numbers out into cyberspace. And the product orders
can piggyback onto the stores' existing distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   The conbini also give consumers access to a computer terminal.
Though computers have been selling at a blistering pace here of
late, penetration is still lower than in the United States and
Internet access charges are still high in comparison with those in
other parts of the world. And though conbini customers cannot yet
surf the entire World Wide Web, they soon will be able to.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does a convenience store have that makes it attractive to
us and our customers?'' said Yasuhiro Suzuki, president and chief
executive of e-Shopping Information Corp., the Softbank unit that
manages e-commerce ventures. ``In a word, convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Operations like Suzuki's would, in turn, appear to solve a major
problem for Japanese convenience stores: the lack of space. The
only way they have kept sales moving forward is by opening more
stores; in general, sales in stores open at least one year are
falling. But there are few practical locations left.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The backdrop of expanding our business to include e-commerce
is the need to expand our current offering of goods and services
and increase our ability to meet the needs of customers without
expanding our space,'' said Usui of Seven-Eleven.
</P>
<P>
   Whether e-commerce will help the convenience stores become more
profitable is unclear. Take the introduction of so-called energy
drinks. Previously sold only in drugstores, convenience stores
started selling the vitamin- and herb-laced drinks last spring,
when deregulation opened the market to them.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the addition of beer and sake to the merchandise mix
five years ago, the introduction of energy drinks has not
significantly increased the stores' overall revenues. While sales
of the new product have met projections, they merely replaced those
of the other items that previously occupied the selling space.
</P>
<P>
   Though those constraints do not exist in cyberspace, there, too,
profitability may be a problem. E-Shopping! Books, the joint
venture, was billed as a baby Amazon.com, but sales so far are
minuscule: as of the end of January, each Seven-Eleven store was
selling four books every 10 days on average.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki said that represented a quadrupling in volume since the
service started in November, and added, ``The progress we've seen
in the business has been better than expected.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was confident the business would turn profitable, in
part because its cost structure may be lower than Amazon.com's.
E-Shopping! Books does not shoulder the costs of warehousing
merchandise, since it can use Tohan's and Seven-Eleven's
warehouses, and it pays for the books only after they have been
sold. The business will also share the e-shopping! name,
administrative functions and technological infrastructure with
Softbank's online toy and car parts businesses, as well as others
introduced in the future, cutting marketing and administrative
costs.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``A newcomer to the business would have a tough time finding
temporary warehousing for delivery to customers, but convenience
stores can act as the final pick-up point quite easily because of
their infrastructure,'' said Ken Sakamura, a professor at Tokyo
University. ``They already have warehouses.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But while such teamwork lowers costs, it also means that
profits, should they materialize, have to be divided.
</P>
<P>
   The same sort of division of the spoils has so far, in an
experimental stage, proven unprofitable for the conbini. Although
polls show that consumers here have long wished for automated
teller machines in convenience stores, they haven't used the ATMs
enough in the few months they have been available to make it
worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   The machines allow customers to do everything from arrange money
transfers to make deposits and withdrawals and even obtain small
consumer loans. Allen at ING Barings said 100 transactions a day
were needed to make store-based ATMs profitable. In test cases by
various convenience store chains, which have placed ATMs in their
bigger stores, transactions are running at 10 to 50 a day, a level
that generates a loss for the stores after they pay their banking
partner and their technology and software providers.
</P>
<P>
   To help overcome this barrier to profitability, Ito-Yokado Co.,
which controls Seven-Eleven, plans to apply for a banking license.
</P>
<P>
   The most promising area of new business for the convenience
stores is likely to be online services like ticketing and
reservations. Such services are popular _ and go quickly _ because
people typically know exactly what they are looking for, said
Hideki Tanaka, an e-commerce analyst at the Fujitsu Research
Institute. ``But I question whether the typical convenience store
customer is going to take 10 or 20 extra minutes to stand at a
computer terminal in the store browsing for goods they want to
buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the most popular use of Loppi, Lawson's online
system, is looking up one's horoscope, that is a question well
worth contemplating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
