<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETROLEUM PRICES PUSH CONSUMER PRICE INDEX TO A 3-YEAR HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surging petroleum prices pushed the Consumer Price Index in
February to its highest level in three years, the Labor Department
reported Friday. But beyond fuel and energy, the nation remained
remarkably free of the rising inflation that the booming economy
was expected to have produced by now.
</P>
<P>
   The index, the nation's best-known inflation gauge, has risen by
3.2 percent over the last 12 months, the first time the yearlong
rate had gone above 3 percent since February 1997. But with energy
excluded, the annual rate was only 2.1 percent, unchanged for many
months, although some economists had expected a much greater impact
from labor shortages and rising wages.
</P>
<P>
   The inflation rate remained at 2.1 percent when food was
excluded as well as energy. Prices in these sectors often jump
around from month to month, so economists subtract them to get a
``core'' inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a certain bizarre way, life would be easier for Alan
Greenspan and the Federal Reserve if there had been a bad CPI,''
said Robert Barbera, chief economist for Hoenig Group. ``They could
then have dealt with their real problem, an excessively high stock
market, and blamed their actions on inflation in goods and
services.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's policy-makers are expected to raise interest rates
when they meet on Tuesday, but not by enough to inhibit stock
market investors, many analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Most of last month's increase of 0.5 percent _ the largest
one-month rise since last April _ reflected the runup in petroleum
prices. Gasoline at the pump averaged $1.42 a gallon, up from $1.36
in January. Airline fares rose as airlines tacked on surcharges to
cover higher fuel prices. And the cost of running a home rose,
reflecting higher prices for heating oil and natural gas, whose
price fluctuates with that of petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   Natural gas is widely used to generate electricity, and
electricity rates jumped by 0.8 percent in February, the biggest
increase since July 1997. So far, however, the rise in petroleum
and natural gas prices has not spread to other products, like
plastics, which are made from oil or natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Toy prices, for example, did not rise, and vehicle prices,
adjusted for quality improvements, fell last month, the Bureau of
Labor Statistics reported. Even truckers have not managed to jack
up freight rates, although the squeeze on their earnings from
higher fuel prices has truckers protesting in Washington for
relief.
</P>
<P>
   That will change, says Chris Varvares, a partner at
Macroeconomic Advisers LLC in St. Louis, if the petroleum-producing
countries somehow manage to make the oil price increases stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``If companies expect the increase to be temporary, they will
eat the cost and squeeze profit margins temporarily,'' he said.
``But if energy prices stay high, firms will try to restore their
profits by raising prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond energy, there were scattered price increases, in
cigarettes, for example, and hospital rates. Meat and pork prices
rose by 1.7 percent, which is more than usual, and such increases
may repeat themselves because of a supply shortage, said Patrick
Jackman, a senior economist in the consumer price division at the
Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit and vegetable prices also rose last month, but the 0.7
percent increase mainly reflected an aberration in the way prices
are adjusted for seasonal factors, Jackman said.
</P>
<P>
   And some prices fell in February. Vehicle prices dropped by 0.1
percent after a 0.3 percent drop in January. Long-distance
telephone rates also fell, along with the cost of purchasing and
using a cell phone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
