<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0386 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-FAITH18-COX     03-17 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-FAITH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Program helps congregations clean up flooded churches
 &HT;    By Travis Fain
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRIFTON, N.C. _ Even when floodwaters rose up inside, the old
brick chapel was home for Janet Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   It had been for 42 years. No water was going to change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Been a lot of places and come back here,'' she said last
week, standing in the doorway of Grifton Chapel Church of Christ.
``Wouldn't take anything in the world for it still.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's church was hit hard by the flood. Waters took the
cushioned pews and ruined every one. Water warped the wood floors,
soaked the walls and rotted the joints of the building. Water took
the Bibles and hymnals. It stole the church piano and all the
electrical wiring.
</P>
<P>
   But it could not steal the faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the backbone of the community, especially in times of
devastation,'' Nelson said. ``There's just something about
exhibiting the faith. It just all extends from the churches.''
</P>
<P>
   Devastation came to eastern North Carolina through the clouds
Sept. 15. Prayers were lifted, but they did not keep the water out
of area churches. So the source of strength for many at the center
of recovery efforts in times past was faced with recovery itself.
</P>
<P>
   An exact count of how many churches were damaged doesn't exist,
but the number easily reaches into the hundreds. When the
floodwaters hit, no government programs existed to help
congregations rebuild. So the state organized the Church2Church
program, which matches funds and volunteers from donor churches to
the needs of flooded ones.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 eastern North Carolina churches have requested the
program's help since the water receded. Forty of them still have
major needs, according Sherrie Stutler, program coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve of the 100 churches are in Pitt County. One of them _ New
Covenant Holy Church in Ayden _ will probably have to be demolished
and relocated, Stutler said.
</P>
<P>
   The government side of Church2Church closes shop March 31, but
the hope is that the church partnerships will endure. Stutler said
members separated by distance and denomination find themselves
forging lifelong friendships through the program.
</P>
<P>
   Without these type of volunteer efforts, it would take some
churches years to recover, according to area pastors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be at a standstill, really,'' said the Rev. Jesse L.
Wilson of Grifton Free Will Baptist Church. ``Because 80 percent of
my membership lost their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's church is on Contentnea Drive. Up and down the street
near Contentnea Creek, mobile homes were floated off their
moorings, some deposited on their sides. The church building
remains, but not much else. Inside the chapel, volunteers and
congregation members are starting from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true across the street. There, Coley's Chapel is
vacant and unmarked. A few flood-soaked Bibles and ruined church
pews offer the only clues that the gutted building was once a house
of worship. Both churches are leaning on volunteers from the
Baptist Men Disaster Recovery effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't classify it as a tragedy,'' said Wilson. ``I would
classify it as an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am amazed, yet thankful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist Men are rebuilding 10 churches in Pitt County and
the surrounding area, mostly with volunteer help from outside of
eastern North Carolina. The organization is also repairing or
demolishing close to 400 homes, according to Beddie Tarlton of
Wingate, who is coordinating the effort from Grifton with her
husband, Billy.
</P>
<P>
   The couple is living in a camper while the work is done. They
slept on cots in a Sunday School room when they first arrived.
They'll stay as long as they can help, Tarlton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to see the desperation on the pastors' faces and hear
them talk, and we present them with a plan of help _ you can see
the weight lifted off their shoulders,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the churches Tarlton's group is helping are in Grifton.
They're rebuilding Zion Temple African Methodist Episcopal Zion
Church, which sits without a floor down the street from Grifton
Free Will Baptist. They're working on New Covenant Church and are
already finished at the Tabernacle of Prayer.
</P>
<P>
   And when they get done at Grifton Chapel Church of Christ,
members expect the sanctuary to be better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord has provided abundantly in terms of volunteer help,
as well as financial resources,'' said Clifton Manuel, rebuilding
project coordinator at the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things will get back to normal. I have no doubt. I never had
any.''
</P>
<P>
   What amazes Vernon Morris about the help that's come to eastern
North Carolina is how it cuts across denominational lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of God sanctuary, where he once pastored and will
still attend services once construction reclaims it from the flood,
wouldn't have stood a chance without help from a Baptist church in
Raleigh, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eight feet of water washed into the Mumford Road church in the
days following Hurricane Floyd. After the water receded, members of
Hayes Barton Baptist Church just walked right up and asked to help,
Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   That members of another denomination would volunteer so readily
has renewed Morris' faith in Christianity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Church that's not part of our denomination _ don't know us
from Adam,'' he said. ``They said they just want to be a
blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarlton and Stutler said the same is true of volunteers with
their programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work well with Methodists, Presbyterians ... We pick a lot
(on each other),'' Tarlton said. ``We have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   The floodwaters that flowed through Morris' church and turned
Mumford Road in to a river also took his mother's home in nearby
Tice Mobile Home Park. The congregation of about 30 has kept up
services, rotating between people's homes, but 77-year-old Ann
Morris misses the church.
</P>
<P>
   But both son and mother say they will rebuild and that things
will be better once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shocks you, but it didn't knock you down,'' Vernon said.
``You lean back on the Lord and say, 'Well, we built it once, we'll
build it again.'''
</P>
<P>
   The roof has already been replaced at the church. There's no way
the tiny congregation could have moved so quickly without help.
</P>
<P>
   ``God sent 'em here,'' Ann said of the volunteers. ``I believe
that. It's just a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
