<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RAIL-MERGER-(TRIMS)-N     03-17 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIL-MERGER-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AGENCY PUTS MORATORIUM ON RAIL MERGERS, BLOCKING A MAJOR
DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, N.D.)   (bl)  
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regulators in Washington imposed a 15-month moratorium on all
rail mergers Friday, abruptly blocking a plan to create an enormous
cross-border freight system but giving a boost to rail stocks that
have languished since the proposed North American rail merger was
announced in December.
</P>
<P>
   The three members of the Surface Transportation Board said the
delay would provide an opportunity to formulate new merger rules
that would tighten performance standards and prevent the kind of
service interruptions that have plagued recent rail mergers.
</P>
<P>
   They also agreed with competing railroads that a merger at this
time was likely to trigger a wild round of deal making and
consolidations that would limit competition and end, eventually,
with just two huge rail systems left to serve all of North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It simply makes no sense to attempt to develop new merger
rules in the middle of what could be the final round of major
railroad mergers,'' the board said in its decision.
</P>
<P>
   The rail companies that planned to merge, Burlington Northern
Santa Fe Corp. Railroad and the Canadian National Railway,
responded testily to Friday's decision, charging that there is no
justification for the board to delay their application based on
problems caused by their competitors' inability to complete their
own mergers smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian National on Friday filed an appeal at the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit challenging the
regulatory board's authority to issue a moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect of the STB decision is to deprive CN and BNSF of
their statutory right to a prompt and fair hearing,'' Paul M.
Tellier, the president of Canadian National, said in a written
statement from company headquarters in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   All railroad stocks have suffered since the merger was announced
last year, but none more so than Burlington Northern and Canadian
National. Both hit 52-week lows last week.
</P>
<P>
   But prices rose Friday after the board's decision was announced.
Shares of Burlington Northern increased $1.25, to $22.25, and
Canadian National shares jumped 93.75 cents, to $28.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gray cloud that has hovered over every railroad has been
lifted, at least temporarily,'' said Douglas W. Rockel, a railroad
analyst with ING Barings.
</P>
<P>
   What is not certain, said Rockel and other analysts, is whether
the moratorium and the change in rules will delay or kill the
planned merger between Burlington Northern and Canadian National.
</P>
<P>
   James J. Valentine, an analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
said the two railroads may be forced to rethink the terms of the
merger. ``What was valid six months ago when this deal was first
put together,'' Valentine said, ``may no longer be valid in about
three years, which would be the soonest the merger could happen
with this latest delay.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It can take the board up to 16 months to reach a decision on a
merger application.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing its first moratorium on mergers, the STB acted in
contradiction to Transportation Secretary Rodney E. Slater, who at
public hearings last week opposed a formal delay while encouraging
a comprehensive review of the rail industry.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, a spate of mergers had reduced the number of
large railroads in the United States and Canada to just seven. The
consolidations caused major shipping disruptions as the new
railroads tried to coordinate their activities.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Burlington Northern and Canadian National surprised
regulators by announcing plans to combine their lines and create a
50,000-mile international rail system that would provide
uninterrupted freight service in more than 30 states and 8 Canadian
provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Canadian laws governing Canadian National, which was
state-run until the early 1990s, the new company, to be called
North American Railways, would have its headquarters in Montreal. A
majority of its board members also would have to be Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives on both sides of the border questioned the
fairness of changing the rules after the two lines had already
begun the process of merging.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to believe that a federal agency can change the
rules and deny us a forum, established by law, to have our case
heard,'' Robert D. Krebs, chairman and chief executive of
Burlington Northern said in a statement from company headquarters
in Fort Worth. ``If the STB decision survives judicial review,''
Krebs added, Burlington Northern and Canadian National, as well as
shippers that rely on the line to transport their products, ``will
be denied the opportunity to realize service and efficiency
improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   In its written decision, the Surface Transportation Board, which
succeeded the Interstate Commerce Commission as regulator of the
rail industry, cited concerns from shippers and competing lines
that the rail freight industry has yet to recover from previous
mergers, a complaint repeated frequently during four days of
hearings before the board last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot in good conscience allow further actions to occur
that I believe would run the risk of creating more disruption and
instability,''said Linda J. Morgan, the board chairwoman, in a
commentary accompanying the decision.
</P>
<P>
   There was some disagreement within the board over the length of
a delay. Morgan indicated that she had initially favored a full
two-year moratorium, while another member of the board, the vice
chairman Wayne O. Burkes, argued that two years was too long.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., opposed the merger and favored a
moratorium of up to five years. He said the 15-month delay was ``a
good start'' and, along with the new standards, ``may well result
in no additional mergers in the rail industry.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
