<SLUG> BC-INVEST-CAR-DEALERSHIP-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET BUYS IN LEMONS OF CAR-DEALER STOCKS?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., N.Y., N.C.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE LEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, it hardly seems worth the effort to kick the tires of
beaten-up auto dealership stocks. Interest rates are rising,
gasoline is more than $1.50 a gallon at the pump, and competition
from online car dealers like Autobytel.com and Autoweb has scared
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, America's largest automotive dealership,
AutoNation, under its chairman, H. Wayne Huizenga, has put a chill
on the sector. Analysts say it overpaid for acquisitions, found
itself undercut on prices because of a misguided ``no haggle''
pricing policy and was forced to shutter 23 used-car superstores.
</P>
<P>
   Its rental car division, which includes Alamo and National, has
also suffered and is being spun off to shareholders. AutoNation's
stock is down 37.2 percent over the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Its rivals, the UnitedAuto Group, Lithia Motors and Sonic
Automotive have not had these same problems. Yet all of their
stocks have hit 52-week lows in the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   So, are any of these stocks good values? Well, Americans'
penchant for new cars shows few signs of easing. In February,
United States car and light truck sales rose 6.1 percent, putting
the nation on course to hit a record 17.7 million in vehicle sales
this year versus 16.96 million vehicles last year.
</P>
<P>
   And the dealership companies as a whole posted 37.5 percent
earnings growth in 1999 and should grow 20 percent to 30 percent
this year, said Tom Thomson, an analyst at First Union Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the industry remains ripe for consolidation. ``This is
a very fragmented market, with the top 10 players only accounting
for 5 percent of the market,'' said Timothy G. Fogarty, an analyst
at ING Barings.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is prompting some investors to take a closer look at
auto dealers. Juliet Ellis, manager of the Chase Vista Small Cap
Equity fund, said she considered Lithia of Medford, Ore., to be a
growth stock because the company's earnings rose 40 percent in
1999. But its sharp drop in price also makes the stock appealing to
value investors, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Lithia, with 101 dealer franchises, is focused on six Western
states and has been growing quickly through well-priced
acquisitions. ``They know what they are doing,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that Lithia is relatively well-insulated from a
possible downturn of the economy, because its fixed costs are low
and its margins are high. Lithia's Class A shares closed on Friday
at $15.50. Fogarty has a strong buy on the stock, and a 12-month
price target of $30.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of UnitedAuto, which is based in Manhattan but operates
104 franchises mostly in the South, hit a 52-week low of $7.4375
last Tuesday. But sales for franchises open at least a year were up
9.7 percent for the fourth quarter, and its financing and insurance
business revenues were up an impressive 22.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company is unloading underperforming dealerships and is
benefiting from the leadership, analysts say, of Roger Penske,
named chief executive last May. Penske, who is also chairman of
Penske Corp., the transportation giant, holds a stake of more than
40 percent in UnitedAuto. In December, the company announced plans
to buy back three million of its shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penske is a winner, or at least he has been in previous
business ventures,'' said Gordon Grender, manager of the GAMerica
Capital fund. Shares now trade at $8.6875, or 7.9 times his 2000
earnings estimate of $1.10 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Sonic Automotive, of Charlotte, N.C., operates 165 franchises in
12 states, mostly in the Southeast and California. The company's
earnings growth has been 50 percent or more for nine consecutive
quarters. The stock now trades at $8.5625.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonic is the best of the bunch,'' said N. Richard Nelson Jr.,
an analyst at Stephens Inc., who thinks the shares can hit $25 in
12 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
