u w BC-CLINTON-LAW-LICENSE-N     03-17 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LAW-LICENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S REQUEST FOR POSTPONEMENT DENIED BY ARKANSAS LAWYERS
PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The special lawyers committee in Arkansas that is
considering an ethics complaint against President Clinton that
could lead to the suspension or revocation of his law license
Friday rejected his request to postpone the case until after he
leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   The committee chairman, Ken Reeves, said in a letter that
Clinton has only until April 21 to answer the complaints that he
lied under oath about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky and
should be disciplined. Clinton's lawyer, David Kendall, said
Thursday that he had asked the committee to extend the time for the
president to file a response until one month after he leaves
office, or sometime in February 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves, who is chairman of the Committee on Professional
Conduct of the Supreme Court of Arkansas, said in a letter sent to
one of the parties who first brought the complaint that he has set
April 21 as the deadline to respond.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to L. Lynn Hogue, a lawyer with the Southeastern
Legal Foundation, the conservative group that brought one
complaint, Reeves said that the committee had considered Kendall's
request for an extension of nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``After consultation with the committee, I, as committee
chairman, have granted an extension until Friday, April 21, 2000,
for a response to be filed,'' Reeves added.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall did not return telephone calls Friday for comment.
Stephen Engstrom, a Little Rock lawyer who represents Clinton
before the disciplinary committee, declined comment when reached by
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves Clinton's statements under oath on Jan. 17,
1998, when he gave a deposition in the sexual misconduct lawsuit
brought against him by Paula Jones. In the presence of Judge Susan
Weber Wright, who was presiding over the civil lawsuit, Clinton
said that he had never engaged in a sexual relationship with
Lewinsky, a one-time White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton has continued to insist his answer was legally
accurate, Wright strongly disagreed and ruled that he was in civil
contempt of court. She said that the president had subverted the
rule of law and violated Jones' right to information in her civil
rights lawsuit, and she asked the disciplinary committee to
consider some kind of action against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew J. Glavin, the president of the Southeastern Legal
Foundation said Friday night that he was gratified that the
committee did not accede to Kendall's request for a delay of nearly
a year.
</P>
<P>
   The committee imposes some kind of sanctions on as many as 100
people a year who are licensed to practice law in Arkansas as is
Clinton. Typically, the seven-member committee recommends
disbarment, the most severe sanction, only in cases in which a
lawyer has stolen money from a client. Lesser punishments may
include suspension of a license for up to two years or a public
reprimand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
