<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESIASON SAYS ALL THE WRONG THINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The TV sports world according to me:
</P>
<P>
   Boomer Esiason isn't the first athlete with a lack of
perspective about his career. He is the most recent, though, to
announce it to the world.
</P>
<P>
   When the former NFL quarterback was fired as the analyst on
ABC's Monday Night Football, he lashed out at his employers and
play-by-play man Al Michaels, saying he did everything he was asked
and putting some of the blame on Michaels. ``Al has what ... he's
always wanted, a single-man booth,'' said Esiason.
</P>
<P>
   Esiason entirely misses the reasons why he was fired. He came
into games unprepared, and it showed in his shallow analysis. He
never improved in important areas, like making his points
succinctly. Late into his second year, he was still talking over
live plays and not matching his comments to replays or Michaels
comments between plays. His enthusiasm was all over the place, too.
</P>
<P>
   Esiason's smack at Michaels was cheap. Michaels is one of the
few play-by-play men who can offer astute analysis on games, yet
he's one of the best at setting up his colormen and creating
quality team broadcasting. The proof: Dan Dierdorf for a decade on
MNF, and Jim Palmer and Tim McCarver on baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels defended Esiason all season as critics and viewers took
shots at his partner, and he declined to be drawn into a
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, Esiason ignored the suggestions of the producer
(Kenny Wolfe) and director (Craig Janoff) and wound up taking them
down with him. ABC Sports President Howard Katz has named one-time
MNF producer Don Ohlmeyer as Executive Producer for MNF and handed
him the task of rebuilding the program.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer's mandate is to raise the entertainment level on the
telecast, which has waned some the last five years. While there's
plenty of candidates -- Bill Parcells, Jimmy Johnson, Dan Marino,
John Elway, Dick Vermeil -- they don't have the kind of charisma or
presence ABC is looking for.
</P>
<P>
   The one person ABC wants is Steve Young, who excelled as a
studio guest during ABC's Super Bowl coverage, but he's determined
to continue his career despite having suffered several concussions.
Joe Theismann, an analyst on ESPN's Sunday night telecasts, is also
a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Talk talk
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports' latest pre-emptive media move this week was to sign
a programming and licensing agreement with Premiere Radio, a
separate company within Clear Channel, which owns XTRA (690 AM),
KXTA (1150 am) and KIIS (102.7 FM). Premiere owns Jim Rome's show,
which is heard on both AM stations.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will provide talent and editorial content and Premier will
find affiliates for its sports-talk shows and handle the
advertising and sales end. Tony Bruno, who left ESPN Radio late
last year, has joined Premiere as a morning talk show host, and
Fox/Premiere hopes to create radio opportunities for Terry
Bradshaw, Howie Long, Cris Collinsworth and Keith Olbermann.
</P>
<P>
   The deal isn't likely to have an immediate impact on either XTRA
or KXTA. XTRA is happy with its current lineup, and most of the
on-air people at KXTA have contracts into 2001, including the
Indianapolis-based Bob and Tom morning show. Olbermann currently
has a separate radio deal with the Sports Fan Radio Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, we'd like to pickup some night and weekend
programming,'' said KXTA station manager Mike Thompson. ``We carry
a lot of ESPN programming now, but we don't have a contract with
them.'' ESPN talk shows and events are aired on an ad barter basis.
</P>
<P>
   Clear Channel has a pending deal to buy AMFM, another radio
power which owns KFI, KLAC and two FM stations. The launch of a
third sports talk station might be spreading things thin, but
having a relationship with KLAC could solve some game programming
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   And now the news
</P>
<P>
   One-on-One Sports (KCTD, 1540 am) will air Los Angeles Avengers
indoor football games beginning with an exhibition game March 27.
Larry Kahn and Mike Lamb, the one-time voices of USC football, will
handle the broadcasts ... CBS has paired former Laker star James
Worthy, who has done some special work at Fox Sports Net, with Dick
Enberg, replacing Al Maguire, who chose to retire on the eve of the
tourney for health reasons. He suffers from anemia, and felt he
couldn't handle the first weekend workload (six games). ... Regards
go out to the family and friends of Bill Daniels, the cable czar
who created Prime Ticket (now Fox Sports Net) and passed away March
7. Daniels was a terrific businessman and gentleman before the
current era of corporate ownership of cable companies and sports
franchises. ... Angels games will be heard on KRLA (1110 am) this
season, with KCTD and KIK (94.3 FM) taking games farmed out because
of programming conflicts. ... XTRA's Joe Tutino and partner Rick
Davis launch the new MLS season for the Galaxy with Saturday's
simulcast (7:30 p.m., Fox Sports Net, KRLA). ... Long Beach Grand
Prix COO Jim Michaelian guests on Irv Kaze's KIEV (870 am) talk
show Saturday (6 p.m.). ... ESPN2's ``Big League Challenge,'' a new
version of Home Run Derby, begins a two-week run Monday (2:30 p.m.,
with later repeats). Mark McGwire, ex-Dirtbag Jason Giambi, the
Dodgers' Shawn Green and former Dodger Mike Piazza are among the
participants. ESPN reruns the shows beginning April 6 (4 p.m.). ...
HBO's ``Real Sports'' Monday (10 p.m.) includes a piece on Bobby
Knight and ex-Indiana star Luke Recker. ... Howie Long's acting
career continues. He begins shooting ``3,000 Miles to Graceland''
this week with sports thespians Kevin Costner (three baseball
films) and Kurt Russell (one football flick).
</P>
</TEXT>
