<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0398 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS-BOS &LR;      03-17 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING THE GUNS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the gun-control propositions, one of the least
controversial is the gun buyback program, which several cities have
used to reduce the arsenal of firearms in closets, under
mattresses, or in car glove compartments. Even the most dogged
defenders of the right to bear arms cannot object to governments
paying $50 for guns that might otherwise end up in a first-grade
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a Republican congressman from New York has found a legal
basis to oppose a Clinton administration initiative to use Drug
Elimination Program money to allow public housing projects to
finance gun-buyback efforts. If Representative James T. Walsh of
Syracuse succeeds in blocking this effort on the grounds that
buying back guns does not qualify as an antidrug measure, the
Clinton administration should put him and others to the test and
fight for a straight appropriation for federal gun-buyback
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Under the contested program, Housing and Urban Development has
invited public housing authorities to use HUD grants to arrange
with their local police to buy up firearms _ from anyone, not just
public housing residents. Housing authorities in Worcester,
Springfield, and Malden have signed on.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh believes _ and says he has an informal opinion from the
General Accounting Office backing him up _ that HUD lacks legal
authority to spend antidrug money this way. HUD disagrees, pointing
to opinions from its lawyers backing this use of the money and
noting that funds from the Drug Elimination Program have been used
in other indirect ways to limit drug dealing, such as installing
fencing or organizing after-school activities for teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-buybacks are not a cure-all for lethal drug-related assaults
or for the casual availability of firearms in America's
communities, but money for them should not be stalled by a dispute
among lawyers. However they are funded, buybacks are a sensible way
for the federal government to help communities deal with a gun
problem made worse by Congress's feckless failure to pass other
gun-control measures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0401 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-ISRAEL-BOS &LR;      03-17 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ISRAEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST BACKSLIDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Political and military regressions in the Mideast peace process
this past week trace an all-too-familiar pattern. The moment
progress on the negotiating track is thwarted, the parties revert
to old habits of hostility. And because regional diplomacy
resembles Chinese checkers, a game usually played by more than two
players, each hesitation on the path to peace invites several
troublemaking parties to make whatever trouble they can.
</P>
<P>
   When Syrian dictator Hafez Assad, frustrated at not getting his
way in negotiations with Israel, gave a green light to the
Hezbollah militia in southern Lebanon for escalating attacks on
Israeli forces and their Lebanese proxies, Prime Minister Ehud
Barak responded by bombing civilian targets in Lebanon in early
February.
</P>
<P>
   The Arab League then moved a meeting from Cairo to Beirut in a
show of sympathy with Lebanon and its de facto colonizer, Syria.
Caught up in the spirit of Arab solidarity, the Arab League issued
a statement reiterating the rhetoric that Assad had coached his
Lebanese puppets to pronounce: an implausible threat that if Israel
had the temerity to withdraw unilaterally from Lebanon, the
government in Beirut would not be able to prevent radical
Palestinian groups in their tightly controlled refugee camps and
Syrian-monitored bases from attacking Israel.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Israel fell for the provocation and resumed bombing
and artillery attacks in Lebanon, killing Lebanese civilians. A
new, more pointed message was sent by Israeli bombing runs against
the camps of two Palestinian groups that reject Yasser Arafat's
peacemaking and have been under the wing of Damascus for many
years. These camps are located along the border between Lebanon and
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happens when negotiations are suspended; the
parties send messages to each other with bombs and rockets. Fringe
groups opposed to the compromises required for a negotiated peace
come to the fore. More than ever, there is no tolerable alternative
to negotiated peace agreements in the Middle East.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
