<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0404 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-ASIATRIP-BO     03-17 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ASIATRIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIVIDED SUBCONTINENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 19, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's trip this week to South Asia, the first
official visit to the region by an American head of state in 22
years, is an opportunity to build relations of trust and confidence
with India and Pakistan. Their nuclear tests in May 1998 and their
escalating clashes in the disputed territory of Kashmir make the
subcontinent the world's most dangerous flashpoint.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton flies out to India Sunday he will be heading toward
a region drenched in contradictions and dangers. Indian software
engineers are making their mark around the world while Hindu
fundamentalists exert more and more influence in India's social and
political life. In Pakistan, the Supreme Court has called for
Islamization of the economy, meaning that within a year it will be
forbidden to charge interest in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton can hardly affect the ebb and flow of tradition and
modernization in India or Pakistan, but there is a lot he can do to
reduce the risk of a nuclear calamity.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate peril he should confront is India's declared
intention to deploy its nuclear warheads. Once India does what its
new nuclear doctrine calls for _ makes its missiles operational _
Pakistan is sure to follow suit. At that point, the people of the
subcontinent will live under the threat of an accidental launch of
nuclear weapons. The deployed nuclear warheads will also create a
constant anxiety about surprise attack that could induce a
preemptive first strike by one side or the other.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's ability to persuade India and Pakistan to sign and
ratify the nuclear test ban treaty was compromised last October by
the refusal of the US Senate to ratify the treaty. Nevertheless, he
should urge both governments to maintain their voluntary moratorium
on further testing and persist in trying to convince them to sign
the test ban.
</P>
<P>
   India does not want to hear about third-party mediation of the
Kashmir conflict, but Clinton has a chance to begin a diplomatic
dialogue that may one day lead to a peaceful resolution of the
dispute. The effort is worthwhile because there can be no global
stability without a stable South Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0405 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-ORACLE-ART-$AD     03-17 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ORACLE-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORACLE POWERS AHEAD AS THE WEB'S SOFTWARE LOCOMOTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of stock prices for Oracle is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 888 603-1036 or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of the old Oracle Corp. traded last April for as little
as $10.50.
</P>
<P>
   The new Oracle closed Friday at $79.8125. But the thing for
investors to bear in mind is that there has been little or no
change in the company's fundamentals in the last year. Sure, last
week it reported that results for its 2000 third quarter exceeded
analysts' estimates by four cents, but in the three preceding
quarters it outperformed in two by more modest amounts, and fell
short in one. So why has Oracle's valuation gone up by a multiple
of nearly eight?
</P>
<P>
   The answer lies in positioning and perception, some of it real,
some of it still in the realm of hopes and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The old Oracle was the gorilla of relational database software,
popular corporate products that manage data in a simple format and
then analyzes them. Although a solid multibillion-dollar business,
it was nearing that stage of the corporate life cycle so dreaded by
growth investors: maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle, and rivals like Sybase and Informix, had done too good a
job selling database software to corporate America. Not only did
every company have one, most had more capacity than they needed.
</P>
<P>
   The new Oracle has positioned itself as the software locomotive
engine of the Internet. Companies embracing electronic commerce and
moving other business practices to the World Wide Web increasingly
use Oracle's database and application software. And Oracle has also
used the Internet internally to cut costs, centralizing tasks like
human resources that used to spread across many continents. To its
credit, Oracle began redesigning its software to embrace the
Internet as far back as 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oracle's database and e-business applications have become the
software standard for the Internet,'' said Larry Ellison, Oracle's
co-founder and chief executive. ``All 10 of the world's biggest Web
sites use Oracle. Ninety-three percent of the public dot-com
companies use Oracle. Now the leading companies in traditional
industries _ Chevron, Ford, General Motors, Carrefour and Sears _
are choosing Oracle to move them to the Internet. The faster the
Internet grows _ the faster we grow.''
</P>
<P>
   This is all true, although many of those dot-coms also use
products from Oracle competitors, like IBM, Ariba or Siebel
Systems. The problem is that all of Oracle's growth is reflected in
today's stock price, which is a staggering 124 times this year's
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Even some analysts who recommend buying Oracle, have
reservations at the current price. ``Frankly, Oracle has become a
concept stock,'' said Andrew C. Brosseau, an analyst with S.G.
Cowen. ``Its valuation has far outstripped its operating
performance,'' he said, noting that revenue growth of 14 percent is
not usually associated with trailing price-to-earnings multiples of
180. ``It's very difficult to talk about the stock in connection
with any fundamentals.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosseau said Oracle's series of e-commerce announcements, with
the likes of Ford and Sears, had given it a high profile in the hot
B2B, or business-to-business sector, but that it remained unclear
how these deals would contribute to revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in a conference call on Tuesday, Ellison said that these
exchanges were costing Oracle money because it had so many
consultants working on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been pushing out a new press release a week about the
next B2B model,'' Brosseau said. ``Unfortunately, there's not a lot
of `there, there,' and a lot of uncertainty about how it will pan
out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kevin Landis, a fund manager with Firsthand Capital
Management in San Jose, Calif., a big holder of Oracle shares, said
Oracle's valuation was easier to justify by evaluating sales growth
by unit, rather than looking at overall revenue. ``In a really big
company with pieces growing at different rates, usually the market
cap doesn't map to where the revenue is, it maps to where the
growth is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent quarter, Oracle's database software sales
increased 32 percent, to $778 million. Total applications software
sales rose 35 percent, to $199 million. Within that total, sales of
applications for customer-relationship management, or CRM, grew at
a 179 percent rate, to $49 million, and Internet purchasing
software, grew by 231 percent, to $26 million. But consulting,
education and support revenue grew just 10 percent, to $1.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Landis notes that the businesses most closely associated with
e-commerce, CRM and Internet purchasing had growth rates exceeding
Oracle's multiple to this year's earnings. ``In many cases, Oracle
is bigger, growing faster and better positioned than some of the
pure plays,'' in these areas, he said. If Oracle did not already
trade at such a high multiple, there would be pressure to spin off
its e-commerce business as a tracking stock, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Austrian, an analyst with Banc of America Securities, is
another enthusiastic supporter of Oracle. ``You recommend it
gingerly because the stock will be hard-pressed to do more than
double from here,'' he said. But he said Oracle was perhaps the
best positioned of all companies to benefit from electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent the run-up in Oracle shares reflects the blurring
of marketing and investor relations that characterizes all of the
Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a brilliantly orchestrated repositioning away from
being a slow-growth database provider toward being an Internet
enabler,'' said William Epifanio 2nd, an analyst with J.P. Morgan.
``Now they've got to start delivering on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
