<HEADLINE>
ENTERPRISING IN MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 19, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maine's governor, Angus King, is boldly going where no education
system has gone before. His idea is to give a computer and Internet
access to each of the state's 16,000 seventh-graders and then stand
back and watch Maine leap into the technological age. Computers
have been handed out in other school systems, but not on a
statewide scale. The governor wants to be able to go to Switzerland
or Silicon Valley and say that Maine is the most digitally literate
place on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Contrarians say money should be spent on books and school
buildings. Others say the computers could be lost, stolen, sold, or
go unused, giving students little more than a high-tech
paperweight.
</P>
<P>
   But even with these risks, the proposal is brilliant. To finance
it, King would take an unexpected one-time $50 million budget
surplus, add another $15 million in private and federal funds, and
set up a trust fund. The interest would pay for smaller computers
costing about $500. Even if the program failed miserably, the
original pot of money would remain intact.
</P>
<P>
   Maine would spend $1 million to train teachers on how to
incorporate computers into the curriculum. This is essential. Some
students have more technical know-how than their teachers. But it's
up to teachers to set high educational standards for how the
technology is used.
</P>
<P>
   By picking up half the tab, the state would help teachers buy
their own computers. Basic devices could block thieves from using
stolen computers. An existing state prison program that has inmates
refurbish computers could, ideally, handle repairs. By purchasing
new equipment each year, the state wouldn't have to maintain
obsolete computers.
</P>
<P>
   As for books and school construction, the state is already
investing millions of dollars. Given this, it makes sense to push
forward on the two fronts of traditional and new resources.
</P>
<P>
   To succeed, Maine will need to weather unforeseen glitches. That
will require learning from similar programs and devising its own
innovations. Doing this could propel Maine and the states that
follow into a new educational frontier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
