<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPBROWN-SCENE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Search for shooting suspect disturbs sleep, security in tidy
neighborhood
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The police dragnet in Hattie Stegall's neighborhood
lifted Friday almost as suddenly as it came down.
</P>
<P>
   Gone by noon were policemen with guns drawn and search dogs. The
thumping of helicopter blades faded when authorities concluded the
man they were after, a former black militant once known as justice
minister for the Black Panthers, was long gone.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say the suspect, Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, opened
fire with an assault rifle on two Fulton County sheriff's deputies
Thursday evening. One died. The other is in the hospital. Police
searched Stegall's neighborhood, where Al-Amin led a mosque and ran
a store and where the shooting happened, but came up empty. They
left by mid-morning to look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Stegall and her neighbors found a largely peaceful
neighborhood returned to them. As birds chirped and dogs barked,
they tried to reconcile their image of Al-Amin as a devout Muslim
who purged the neighborhood of drugs with a portrait that emerged
from police accounts of a man who ambushed two deputies and left
them to die.
</P>
<P>
   Stegall, 73, and her neighbors were encouraged in this
reflection by news reporters and photographers who went
door-to-door on Egleston Street and West End Place throughout the
day. By 2 p.m., five satellite TV trucks and 11 cars, pickup trucks
and minivans of reporters were parked on grass across from
Al-Alim's store. Several residents, particularly Muslims who
worshiped in Al-Amin's mosque, declined to talk publicly about him.
Others praised him as someone willing to help those in need.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether Al-Amin could have done what the police
allege, Stegall paused for seven seconds and stared at the front
door of her screened-in porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know. I just don't know,'' she said softly. ``He
looks like such a good person, but you just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   She lives around the corner from Al-Amin's mosque, a converted
house with lime green siding. She can look out her bedroom and
kitchen windows and see the mosque and a store down the street
where the deputies fell as they tried to execute a warrant for
Al-Amin's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``See that back door? That's where the shooting was. That's
where they knocked on the back door with that warrant,'' Stegall
said, tapping on the glass of her kitchen window.
</P>
<P>
   Stegall said she was awakened Thursday night by a series of
gunshots _ police said at least 35 bullets were fired. Two of her
grandchildren, ages 10 and 12, were in a bed beside her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them to jump up and run. Somebody's shooting!'' said
Stegall, who moved into her house in 1969 and has known Al-Amin
since he arrived in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   She said Al-Amin frequently checked on her and instructed other
Muslims to help her.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all call me Big Momma. He tells the rest of them to go
see about Big Momma,'' she said. ``When my sister died, he was
right here asking if there was anything he could do for me.''
</P>
<P>
   She cocked her head to one side for a moment when four speakers
atop the mosque began broadcasting a hypnotic chant just before 1
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's their music. I don't understand it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Most houses along Egleston Street and West End Place are small
but neatly maintained. A few are in disrepair, but contractors are
renovating others. Many residents, such as Stegall, are older, but
some young couples with children have moved in recently. Muslim
women with cloths covering their faces walk quietly from the mosque
to their houses.
</P>
<P>
   Stegall and her neighbor, Wendy Daniel, said they had a hard
time sleeping Thursday night and Friday morning because so many
officers with flashlights were marching through the neighborhood,
trying in the wee hours to root out their suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I laid down, but I just couldn't sleep,'' Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   Just after the shooting, she said, one of her two daughters was
awakened by the family dog, Disco, who began barking incessantly
after the gunfire. She said she had to tell her daughter that two
men had been shot near their house and that she had looked through
the kitchen window and seen one of them stagger and fall.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday morning, she let her other daughter walk to school
because she thought police had captured the gunman. When she
learned they had not, she said, she went to the school to make sure
her daughter had made it safely to her fifth-grade class.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
