<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0412 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-LIBEL-BOS &LR;      03-17 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-LIBEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TEST OF WEB SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, March 20, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   North Adams Mayor John Barrett III has every right to sue two
residents who set up a Web site in which they accuse him of
offenses he says are groundless and defamatory. Barrett goes too
far, however, when he seeks an injunction Monday remove material
from the site without benefit of a trial. This would set an ominous
precedent for throttling political commentary in this new medium.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Polk, Barrett's lawyer, narrowed the scope of his request
for an injunction Friday so that it no longer seeks to bar the two
defendants from putting future statements about the mayor on the
Internet. That request would have been an attempt at prior
restraint, which the courts wisely regard as presumptively
unconstitutional because it stifles speech before it can be
uttered.
</P>
<P>
   It is understandable that Barrett would wish to remove offensive
items from the Web site, (www.northadamsfree.com), but it is better
that they stay there for now rather than establish a precedent for
censorship. The US Supreme Court has made libel and defamation
against public figures hard to prove to encourage the freewheeling
discussions for which the Internet is an ideal and inexpensive
medium. The costs of a controversial Web site would soar if its
operators had to fend off injunctions. Barrett and Polk ought to
withdraw the petition for an injunction and instead seek a speedy
trial.
</P>
<P>
   John Choquette and William Davis, the defendants, accuse the
mayor of everything from theft to child abuse in a semi-coherent
attack. The Supreme Court has set a high standard for defamation
suits by public figures, but Barrett ought to prevail if he can
prove that false accusations were made maliciously, with knowledge
that they were untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Internet law is still in its infancy. Much work needs to be done
to develop sound precedents for statements made in e-mail and chat
rooms. But the World Wide Web, with its sites available to anyone
with a search engine, is like a television station or newspaper. If
Superior Court Judge Thomas Curley refuses to shut the Web site,
and sets an early date for trial, he will be applying
tried-and-true legal standards to a new medium of free expression.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
