<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Honeymoon's Over &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Which idiot in this company is responsible for hiring a temp
to work on mergers?''
</P>
<P>
   That shout from the audience greeted Henry M. Paulson, chairman
and chief executive of Goldman Sachs Group, all of five minutes
into the company's first shareholder meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The security breach that allowed a temporary employee to steal
and sell inside information on pending merger deals, which led last
week to criminal charges against 19 people, was just one of the
unpleasant topics Paulson had to discuss Friday morning when two
stockholders commandeered what might have been a short, sweet
gathering. The doubling of Goldman's stock price since it went
public in May was nearly lost amid the fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   As she often does at annual meetings, the woman who shouted,
Evelyn Y. Davis, did most of the talking, lambasting the board over
the affair of the temp. Another investor, Harry Korba, chimed in to
ask Paulson if he had considered declining his $16 million bonus
for 1999. ``No, I didn't,'' Paulson replied.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also griped that too little Goldman stock went to
individual investors. She said she had to call David H. Komansky,
chairman of Merrill Lynch, to obtain 100 shares. Paulson joked that
Komansky had done Goldman ``a big favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick McGeehan &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Can't Stay Out of the Headlines. The timing was just too
delicious. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a bizarre coup of sorts, The Financial Times last Monday
prominently featured a review of ``Sense and Nonsense in the
Office,'' Lucy Kellaway's new book about good management. The
reviewer was Robert J. Ayling, who just the previous Friday had
been ousted as chief executive of British Airways for poor
management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coincidence,'' said John Gapper, features editor of The
Financial Times. Ayling had written the review, titled ``Beware the
Bear Trap,'' about a week before his surprise dismissal, Gapper
explained, and the review had been scheduled to appear in last
Monday's issue before he knew ``all of the hoo-ha.''
</P>
<P>
   When the news broke, Gapper called the airline, worried that he
would have to kill the article. Perhaps with an eye toward future
career options, Ayling surprised Gapper by personally giving it a
green light. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Ross Sorkin &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some Risks Are Worth the Reward &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eric Seleznow may have been the only person in Maryland who was
not surprised when a team of young prison inmates took second prize
in a stock-picking contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in jail are risk-takers; people who play the market are
risk-takers,'' said Seleznow, spokesman for the Montgomery County
Detention Center in Rockville.
</P>
<P>
   The detention center team, competing against high school
students in Maryland and the District of Columbia, turned an
imaginary $100,000 into $196,000 in 10 weeks, second best behind
the $253,000 racked up by North Harford High School.
</P>
<P>
   One of the inmates, Ryan Green, 21, said their selections were
far from scientific. ``We were sitting around one day and Viagra
was in the news, and I asked, `Who makes it?''' he said. So they
``bought'' Pfizer, plus America Online ( Green subscribes), Nokia
(his father likes his cell phone), Yahoo, Amazon.com and Network
Solutions (``It seemed to be doing well'').
</P>
<P>
   Green was eligible for the team because of a drunken night
shooting out parked car windows with a BB gun. ``I'm not proud of
what I did,'' he said, meaning the BBs, not the stocks. ``I'm
trying to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin Molotsky
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
