<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0423 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-STPATS-GEORGIA18-COX     03-17 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STPATS-GEORGIA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Green space in Savannah
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Sogs and goats were dyed green, as were the
hooves of horses.
</P>
<P>
   The cheeks of marching cadets and the beer bellies of gamboling
Shriners also were smudged green from the lips of very friendly, or
very inebriated (or very both) women.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was just another typical St. Patrick's Day parade and
party for citizens of this South Georgia port city and maybe
400,000 of their closest, green-garbed friends.
</P>
<P>
   While as many as 600,000 revelers were expected along the
1.9-mile parade route, considerably fewer people lined Abercorn,
Bay and Broughton streets. Heavy rains and tornado watches on the
Georgia coast Thursday surely scared off many a partygoer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the weather turned perfect for the nation's second-largest
parade honoring the Irish and their culture.
</P>
<P>
   By midday, midway through the four-hour marathon, the skies
cleared and the temperature hit the mid-70s.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect weather for families, Spring Break exiles and others to
cheer on high school marching bands, Civil War re-enactors, honor
guards, Dalmatians and all those Shriners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just having a party, the usual St. Patrick's Day
party,'' said Gene Warren, 65, observing the whirl of pageantry
from an East Broad Street porch.
</P>
<P>
   Retired military, Warren embodied the spirit (and spirits) of
St. Paddy's Day. He wore a bright green jacket and green and white
stovepipe hat festooned with shamrocks. His newly reddened face was
nicely framed by white hair and moustache. His Bloody Mary, though,
was empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll have another,'' he said, and he did.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders' efforts to curtail the booze-fueled hijinks
associated with the parade and accompanying three-day Festival on
the River appeared to be working well Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 500 revelers were arrested or cited, mostly for
underage drinking, relieving themselves in public, and other
alcohol-related indiscretions. Early Friday, Savannah police had
arrested 50 people, the largest number of them for public
indecency.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the debauchery emanates from the festival, the music and
beer bash along the Savannah River.
</P>
<P>
   Yet organizers again this year are trying to ratchet down the
party by restricting the size of beer mugs (16 ounces); number of
beer trucks (seven); and shutting bars earlier (1 a.m.).
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of an effort to draw more hotel-staying,
restaurant-dining families and less booze-guzzling, money-conscious
young adults.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels and motels up to 100 miles away were booked this weekend.
Many Savannah hotels, requiring minimum two-night stays, were
filled before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family is key to the whole thing,'' said Joe Cetti,
general chairman of the St. Patrick's Day Parade. ``That's good for
the merchants. They'll do quite well. This is just going to have a
great dollar impact.''
</P>
<P>
   It was mostly families along the parade corridor's upper half.
Folks four, five and six deep watched a lot of old guys in shiny
old cars belonging to various Orders and Societies and Clans, wend
their way down Abercorn Street.
</P>
<P>
   The closer to the river, the rowdier the crowds. They lustily
cheered the Marching Dalmatians, the Irish Elvis, the Piggly Wiggly
float, the Budweiser Clydesdales, Miss Georgia and others as they
paraded past the centuries-old homes, green-dyed fountains and
moss-covered oak trees..
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' said Warren, ``is what makes Savannah special.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
