<HEADLINE>
GADZURIC MAKES BIG DIFFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ It took all of 182 seconds to see the biggest
change in UCLA's postseason picture. That's when center Dan
Gadzuric entered the Ball State game _ and when the Bruins'
frontline morphed from decent to dominant.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing quite like having a 6-11, 250-pounder with NBA
talent to repel upset nippings of first-round foes and protect the
basket against the best and biggest March Madness has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having Dan makes a huge difference,'' UCLA guard Earl Watson
said. ``Dan dominates the boards. His outlet passes help get us
easy shots. His presence intimidates the other teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric did not play in the first-round loss to Detroit Mercy
last year because of a knee injury. But he made an immediate impact
Thursday with 10 points, 12 rebounds and two blocks. He denied Ball
State second shots and made the Cardinals think twice about
entering the lane _ the things he must do against No. 3 seed
Maryland this afternoon for the Bruins to advance to the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to post-up hard and play defense,'' said
Gadzuric, who's averaging 10.4 points and 7.9 rebounds during
UCLA's seven-game winning streak. ``I had some butterflies since it
was my first (tournament) game. But I expected that. That's good.
If I didn't, there would be something wrong. But after a while, I
got in the flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric's appearance marked the first time in four years UCLA's
big man has been available for the crucial tournament game.
</P>
<P>
   Jelani McCoy missed most of the 1997 Elite Eight loss to
Minnesota because of a bruised sternum. McCoy quit the team weeks
before the 1998 tournament, leaving the tiny Bruins to face massive
Kentucky in the Sweet 16. Last year, Gadzuric missed the Detroit
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan will make life easier for the whole team,'' power forward
Jerome Moiso said. ``(Against Ball State), we were all over the
place until he came in and completed us. It's not just me. He helps
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins need Gadzuric's size and his fouls against Maryland,
which has five players 6-8 or taller, including all-ACC center
Lonny Baxter and 6-9 forward Terence Morris, who has Lottery Pick
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Like UCLA, the Terps are athletic and aggressive. Freshman point
guard Steve Blake generates much of their offense with penetration;
once the defense collapses, he passes to shooting guard Juan Dixon
for 3-pointers. What's more, they're an excellent offensive
rebounding team, snatching 53 percent of the rebounds available
under the opponent's basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a strong inside presence,'' Bruins Coach Steve
Lavin said. ``When a shot goes up, they get themselves second- and
third-opportunities. If we don't clean up the glass and limit them
to one shot, we're in for a long night.''
</P>
<P>
   The similarities don't end with frontcourt talent. Both teams
have replaced star point guards. (Maryland's Steve Francis was the
No. 2 pick in the NBA Draft. UCLA's Baron Davis was the No. 3
pick.) Both teams have super shooters (Maryland's Dixon, UCLA's
Jason Kapono). Both teams like to run and both are deep.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, both teams are playing well. The Bruins have won
seven straight games, while the Terps have won 12 of 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Bruins) are playing as well as anybody in the country,''
Maryland coach Gary Williams said. ``UCLA is one of those teams
that has great size and depth at most of (its) positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Including center _ for the first time in four tournaments.
</P>
</TEXT>
