<SLUG> BC-JEOPARDY-TREBEK18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta's game for `Jeopardy!'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ With the game show ``Jeopardy!'' taping in Atlanta
this weekend, host Alex Trebek swung over to Athens Friday to speak
to University of Georgia journalism students and take a few
good-natured swings at ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wonder about some of the contestants on that
program,'' Trebek said, launching into an imitation host Regis
Philbin and an imaginary player.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the usual color of Post-its?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uhhhhhhh. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Trebek also took a poke at Reege (the two are friends), pointing
out that Philbin has been on ``Celebrity Jeopardy!'' twice. ``And
he finished third both times.''
</P>
<P>
   His ribbing segued into an ode to ``Jeopardy!,'' still
considered to be the toughest game show despite the popularity of
``Millionaire.'' (``Millionaire,'' however, is averaging about 28
million viewers per show to ``Jeopardy!'s'' 18 million.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Granted our (prize) money is nowhere comparable to those other
shows,'' Trebek said, ``but so what? People on our program aren't
there for the money, they're there for the glory, to show off their
intellectual prowess.''
</P>
<P>
   That trivia firepower will be on full display today and Sunday
at the Atlanta Civic Center, when ``Jeopardy!'s''Tournament of
Champions tapes on the road for the first time. The show rarely
leaves Los Angeles because the large electronic board is so
difficult to move and set up.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterfinals start this morning for the 15 champions,
including Eddie Timanus, the blind USA Today sportswriter who is
the show's first blind champion, and Robin Carroll of Marietta,
Ga., who squeaked in by winning her fifth game Friday night. The
finals will wind up Sunday afternoon, and the shows will air the
weeks of May 8 and May 15 (at 7:30 p.m. on Channel 11).
</P>
<P>
   About 16,000 Atlantans will see the tapings live, in four
seatings of 4,000 each. All tickets were given out weeks ago to
people who wrote to ``Jeopardy!'' or won TV or radio contests.
``Jeopardy!'' producer chose Atlanta after taping ``Wheel of
Fortune'' here for the 1996 Olympics and being impressed with the
audience's enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Trebek, 59, estimated ``Jeopardy!'' has given away between $20
million and $30 million in the 16 years of its present version. A
Canadian broadcaster who had hosted several game shows, Trebek
launched the syndicated version in 1984; NBC ran the original
``Jeopardy!'' from 1964-'75, when it was hosted by Art Fleming.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started we had such a limited budget for our research
library that we called World Book Encyclopedia and asked if they
would send us a set in return for a mention on the air,'' Trebek
recalled. ``Now we make great use of the Internet in our research,
as well as having a full library.''
</P>
<P>
   Sporting a green pocket square in honor of St. Patrick's Day,
Trebek fielded questions from UGA journalism students, including
whether he had seen the vicious and hilarious spoofs of ``Celebrity
Jeopardy!'' that ``Saturday Night Live'' has run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen one or two of them,'' he said. ``I like them.
They're fun. When you become part of the American cultural scene,
you don't mind when people do take-offs. Hey, we're in show
business _ you can't take yourself too seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
