<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rapper's belongings moved from apartment
 &HT;    By David Pendered
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A rap artist has moved from the apartment complex
where five people were wounded Sunday in a limousine outside her
residence.
</P>
<P>
   Shawntae Harris, known professionally as Da Brat, was not
evident at the apartment as movers emptied it Friday.
</P>
<P>
   She was slated as an opening act Friday night for a Mariah Carey
concert in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Four moving men wheeled the contents from the fourth-floor
dwelling at Post Chastain in Buckhead, an upscale residential area
and entertainment district. The belongings were loaded into an
unmarked white truck. The men declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Two women packing items in the apartment said the residence was
not Harris' home. One said she was the occupant. The other wore a
yellow T-shirt with the So So Def record logo, Harris' record
label.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police and Post Properties officials have confirmed that
Harris resided in that apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The belongings in Harris' apartment included a big-screen TV, a
cat's scratching post covered in beige carpet and a large wall
display. There were more than 20 cardboard boxes, and a large
hanging wardrobe was marked ``Coats,'' while most others were
unmarked.
</P>
<P>
   Harris is slated to appear April 13 in Atlanta Municipal Court
on charges from a March 7 brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 25, allegedly struck a woman with either a pistol or a
shot glass after an argument in the Chili Pepper nightclub in
Buckhead. Harris was charged with battery.
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, two men shot 15 times at a limousine loaded
with nine passengers outside Harris' apartment, wounding five.
</P>
<P>
   There are conflicting accounts as to the relationship between
the limousine's passengers and Harris.
</P>
<P>
   The limousine occupants initially told police they were friends
and relatives of Harris, but later denied knowing her.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
