<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TROOPERS REPRIMANDED FOR WEARING KKK-TYPE HOODS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ One state trooper will be fired and five others
were suspended without pay for ``unprofessional conduct'' in
connection with a 1988 birthday party in which the officers donned
paper hats that looked like Ku Klux Klan hoods, Department of
Public Safety officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The reprimanded troopers have the right to appeal their
punishments, which were ordered by DPS Col. Thomas A. Davis Jr.,
after a two-month internal affairs investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The only other two officers who wore the makeshift hoods already
have left the force, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have completed our investigation into this unfortunate
incident and taken the disciplinary action we believe is proper,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The reprimanded officers are white; the former trooper being
honored at the party in the Livingston office is black.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, a city of 7,300 people, is about 70 miles northeast
of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The hood-donning, captured in a photograph that has been seen
around the world, was brought to light in January by former trooper
Darron Anderson. It showed him seated with a birthday cake in his
lap surrounded by eight hooded men.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson claimed he was traumatized by the incident 11 years
ago, when he was a rookie trooper and the only African-American
assigned to the Livingston office.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, a Houston native, was dismissed from the DPS last year
after being indicted for arson in connection with a fire that
destroyed his truck on April 19, 1999. He filed an insurance claim,
but later withdrew it, repaid his insurer and admitted torching his
own vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Anderson nor a spokesman could be reached for comment
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He disclosed the ``intimidating'' hood-donning incident on the
day before his still-pending arson charge initially was set for
trial. Later, colleagues said Anderson had asked the officers to
pose with the paper hoods, as officers had done for another
African-American trooper four years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Recommended for dismal was patrol Sgt. Darryl Wright of
Woodville, although it was not disclosed why he drew the harshest
penalty. He will remain suspended with pay while the appeal of his
recommended discharge runs its course, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Wright was suspended with pay on Jan. 11 after being accused of
making racist statements to a deputy in the Tyler County sheriff's
office on Jan. 6, the day after Anderson went public with his
complaint. He was later identified as one of the troopers in the
party photo.
</P>
<P>
   The others also were suspended with pay pending the outcome of
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The five reprimanded officers were suspended without pay for
periods ranging from three to five days, so all will be back on
duty next week, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Suspended for five days was Trooper Wilburn Glen Goodwin of
Livingston. Receiving three-day suspensions were Troopers Bobby
Perry, Ricky Thigpen and Larry Pitts, all of Livingston; and Cpl.
Paul Hearne of Lufkin.
</P>
<P>
   Two other troopers who appeared in the photograph had retired by
the time Anderson called attention to the incident, Davis added.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
