<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BMW-MOTORCYCLE-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING AN ``S'' SHAPE TO BMW'S MOTORCYCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19)  
 (af)  
 By PHIL PATTON 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When David Robb was a child, he spent much time at school
sketching cars and airplanes and much time at home putting together
plastic models of them. Today, Robb, who turns 45 in a few days,
directs motorcycle design for BMW, whose bike sales increased by
one-third last year, to a record 65,000 worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Robb's greatest success is the new luxury touring model, the K
1200 LT, built for two riders. In six months on the market, it has
become BMW's best-selling motorcycle. It is also its most
expensive, at just under $20,000, with options like a six-disc CD
player, a dual-control heated seat system, heated hand grips,
cruise control, an on-board computer, an intercom and cup holders.
</P>
<P>
   Before Robb came along, BMW motorcycles had a reputation for
sturdiness but not style.``They were like the CPA parents wanted
their daughter to marry,'' said Robb, who works in Munich.
``Meanwhile, she was dreaming of James Dean.''
</P>
<P>
   Although devoted to sports like hang gliding and skydiving, Robb
did not ride motorcycles until he was nearly 30. After studying at
the Art Center College of Design in Pasadena, Calif., he went to
work for Chrysler as a car designer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, his job became a casualty of the company's effort to
avoid bankruptcy, so Robb bought a Eurail pass, toured the
continent and returned with a half-dozen job offers. He took one at
Audi, then moved to BMW four years later.
</P>
<P>
   After being put in charge of bike design in 1993, Robb took on
the heart of the motorcycle market _ the cruiser. To differentiate
BMW, he narrowed the bike's ``waist'' and imparted a sinuous ``S''
shape to its frame and seat.
</P>
<P>
   A test-track accident several years ago did not diminish Robb's
enthusiasm for riding. On his Powerbook is a digital photograph
taken recently at a test track. It shows his bike cornering at an
acute angle; visible inside the helmet is a distinct smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EXP-BROWN-SHOOTING-NY     03-17 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXP-BROWN-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER ACTIVIST H. RAP BROWN SOUGHT FOR SHOOTING OFFICERS IN
ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
(dw) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Muslim cleric formerly known as H. Rap Brown, a
leader of the Black Panthers in the 1960s, was the subject of an
intense citywide manhunt Friday after a Fulton County sheriff's
deputy said the cleric shot him and another deputy near downtown
Atlanta late Wednesday. The second deputy died of his injuries
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The cleric, now known as Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, has lived in
relative peace in Atlanta's West End neighborhood after serving
five years behind bars in New York for attempted armed robbery.
Atlanta Police Chief Beverly Harvard said the deputy selected
Al-Amin's picture from a photo array as the man who fired an
assault rifle at the two deputies at close range. The department is
now seeking him on a murder warrant.
</P>
<P>
   One of the deputies, Ricky Kinchen, 35, lost most of his blood
at the scene and died at Grady Memorial Hospital on Friday
afternoon after undergoing three operations. The other deputy,
Aldranon English, 28, was less seriously wounded and was able to
describe the shooting incident to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   According to Harvard, the deputies, who are black, were
attempting to arrest Al-Amin on a warrant issued by suburban Cobb
County in January after Al-Amin failed to appear in court to answer
charges in connection with a traffic stop last May. Al-Amin had
been accused of driving a stolen Ford Explorer, having improper
insurance documents, and of impersonating a police officer by
flashing a fake badge and claiming he was a police officer in
Whitehall, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   The deputies were circling the area near his house and grocery
store when a black Mercedes pulled up near the rear of the store.
The deputies approached the car and asked the driver to get out,
which he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deputy then asked him to show his hands, and the person
responded by saying, `Okay, here they are,''' Harvard said,
explaining that the man opened fire. One of the deputies also
managed to shoot the gunman.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department later said a nationwide all-points
bulletin had been issued for his arrest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
