<SLUG> BC-SLUG-TITUS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIRD WORLD OF `TITUS'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; ``tonight'' refers to Mon., March 20) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By REPORTER NAME 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Normal people terrify me,'' proclaims Christopher Titus at the
beginning of his new sitcom, economically titled ``Titus.'' Normal
people may reciprocate and find his show's depiction of family life
equally terrifying. However, things tilt in ``Titus''' favor as he
cites a study suggesting 63 percent of the country is in
dysfunctional relationships _ meaning, of course, the majority of
the country will easily be able to relate to what sometimes can be
gallows humor here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titus,'' the situation comedy, is not to be confused with
Julie Taymor's cinematic atrocity exhibition, though the characters
here almost treat one another as viciously as in that Shakespearean
film. Based upon the life of stand-up comic Christopher Titus, the
show explores some of the grimmest parts of family dysfunction with
both insight and humor. Some of the jokes here will jolt you from
the typical sitcom complacency _ no slack-jawed viewing allowed
here _ and if each episode doesn't quite find a moment of
redemption after mining these hearts of darkness, they leave you
amused enough that you can continue soldiering on in your own
imperfect life.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Titus plays a version of himself who works as a
hotheaded hot-rod customizer. His world, whether he likes it or
not, revolves around his father Ken, equal parts gruff charm and
pure, heartless cluelessness when it comes to parenting (is it a
compliment to say that Stacy Keach is perfect in the role?).
</P>
<P>
   Christopher's dim-bulb brother Dave (Zack Ward) is even more
cowed by his pop but still lives with him. Episodes are filled with
flashbacks reflecting their dad's inhumanity to his young men _
flinging kids into lakes to teach them to swim, reading to his
poker buddies from his son's diary with mock teariness.
</P>
<P>
   Through the dysfunction, somehow, Christopher still manages to
hold on to his girlfriend Erin (played with charm and subtlety by
Cynthia Watros) without threatening the relationship too much.
Titus shares his thoughts and explains his and his family's twisted
motivations in black-and-white sequences set in what he calls a
``neutral space,'' suggesting that even though his life has been a
horror show, he's come out on the other side intact enough to find
the humor therein.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's episode, alas, is not the hilariously edgy pilot, in
which Christopher and his brother fear their father is dead simply
because he hasn't left his bedroom for a beer in four days but fear
him too much to actually intrude upon his privacy. Instead, it's
about his confusion over the fact that his girlfriend has seemed
distant and troubled lately, so he goes to her office to confront
her about what he assumes is an affair. Instead, when he finds out
that she's being sexually harassed, he crumples at her feet and
sighs, ``Thank God!''
</P>
<P>
   A future episode probes, with disarming candor, the mind-set of
a person whose discomfort with happiness forces him to torpedo a
relationship and focuses on a time the real Christopher and Erin
cheated on one another. ``Brave'' is a word used too often and
frequently fatuously when describing show-biz products or
performances, but ``Titus'' comes close, laying bare one man's
genuine pain and inviting the world to have a really good laugh at
it. &QL; 
_________ &QL; 
What: Comedy about a dysfunctional family. &QL; 
The stars: Christopher Titus, Stacy Keach, Cynthia Watros, Zack
Ward. &QL; 
Where: Fox (Channel 11). &QL; 
When: 8:30 tonight. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
