<HEADER>
A0446 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-ELLERBEE-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      03-17 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLERBEE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICK LETS KIDS PICK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: x stars 
BY VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kids can't go into the gym at all today. Some people came to
school this morning and put an extra American flag up outside, and
all day a bunch of grown-ups have been walking into the gym and
talking quietly. They don't stay long.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably what an election day looks like to a blissfully
unaware grade-schooler.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ellerbee, the veteran government and political
correspondent who anchors Nickelodeon's Nick News programs, wants
to get kids involved in the political process _ as more than
distant observers of polling precincts in their gyms and libraries
_ and to hear them out on what they want and need from their
national leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the top-rated cable network is airing Ellerbee's ``Nick
News Special Edition: Kids Pick the Issues,'' a town hall meeting
of sorts for U.S. citizens who will have to wait five to 10 years
before they can cast their first real ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The special kicks off the network's fourth ``Kids Pick the
President'' campaign culminating in October with a viewer
``voting'' poll, one which in past years has accurately
foreshadowed the actual winner.
</P>
<P>
   Ellerbee was relaxed, confident and enthusiastic about the
program, and probably about life in general, as she talked over
lunch on a Beverly Hills hotel patio.
</P>
<P>
   Ellerbee, who turns 56 this year, is healthy nearly eight years
after her breast cancer surgery and more than 10 years after
quitting drinking. She had changed her dark brown hair to sandy
blond and celebrated a 60-pound weight loss by starting the
interview in snug size 6 jeans, and later changing to a short slim
skirt and red spike heels for a TV appearance.
</P>
<P>
   She referred frequently to notes scrawled over nearly every
square inch of several sheets of paper and, like a good journalist
should, anticipated most of the questions and answered them well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real difference between this show and the other Nick
specials we've done is our other Nick specials are always about
kids, for kids,'' Ellerbee said. ``This one is also about kids, for
kids, but beyond that what we're saying is we want grown-ups to
watch this show, we want people in power to hear kids' voices on
this subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids have serious thoughts about what the issues are, and they
have some ideas about what ought to be done. And we think it would
be important for people in power to listen. Why? Right now kids are
20 percent of the population, but they're 100 percent of the
future. And elections are about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon doesn't expect political power brokers to tune into
the special by accident while looking for the latest episode of
``Little Bill'' or another kid-oriented series. The network is
sending tapes of the program to every member of Congress as well as
business leaders, children's activists, broadcasters and others.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the issues that have come up when Ellerbee talks with
kids about government include:
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!Schools feeling more like prisons under security
crackdowns imposed since the Columbine High shootings.
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!Budget cutbacks that have led to cancellation of art,
music, sports and other school programs.
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!Health concerns, ranging from peer pressure over drug and
alcohol use to the lack of medical insurance and its affect on
their families.
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!Technology, especially how to access the Internet for
educational or harmless uses while teachers, librarians and parents
are trying to shield kids from pornography and predators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basis of Nick News, and one of the ways we've always been
able to reach kids on serious issues, is that every kid has a
built-in, inborn sense of fairness,'' Ellerbee said. ``You'll hear
them say things like, `That's not FAIR.' That's as good a point to
start a political discussion as I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Nick News won journalism's coveted Peabody Award for
Ellerbee's special devoted to the Monica Lewinsky scandal. Nick
News had deliberately avoided the story for the sake of its mostly
sexually naive viewership until the very explicit Starr report was
released on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Ellerbee, not given to tooting her own horn, was proud not only
of the honor, but of the Peabody committee's reasoning in giving
its only Lewinsky-related award to Nick News.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said that in explaining it to kids, we had actually
explained it better to grown-ups than anyone else,'' she said,
noting there was no detailed discussion about the sexual affair
between the White House intern and President Clinton, only what
came after.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really all we said was the president had an inappropriate
relationship with a woman to whom he was not married, and when
caught, lied about it. And right there, instantly we were able to
move into issues: Is it ever OK for the president to lie? Is it
ever OK for you to lie? What happens when you lie? Do you know what
censure is? What is impeachment?
</P>
<P>
   ``And we explained all these various options, and then we asked
kids not what they thought would happen, because that implies a
broader political grasp. We asked them what they thought
!ital!should happen,'' Ellerbee said. ``And their answers were
fascinating and they made sense, although my one favorite was a
10-year-old boy who said, 'Couldn't we just put him in a time-out
until he says he's sorry?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ellerbee said adults often complain there shouldn't be news
shows for kids because children already are overwhelmed by the
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons Nick News exists is because we do believe
that kids are bombarded with a lot of information from a lot of
sources, and it's not being given to them in an age-appropriate
manner or in context,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the worries that we all have about kids being
overexposed, and they're legitimate, but what are you going to do?
Are you going to stand at the edge of the ocean and turn back the
tide? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you can do is teach your child to be media literate, and
that starts the day you stop pretending that, if you ignore it,
television will go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch TV with your children, watch a sitcom,'' Ellerbee said.
``Watch a commercial and ask, 'What are they selling here _
toothpaste or popularity?' ... Watch the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you work with your child and watch and do simple things
like that, you will raise a child who can use these technologies as
a tool rather than becoming a tool of these technologies,'' she
said. ``It's not that difficult, and it's a lot better than
throwing your hands in the air and saying it's all terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the kids on her Clinton-Lewinsky special believed the
Starr report should not have been put out on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a self-governing factor in there that you have to
admire,'' Ellerbee said. ``We tend to think of kids as dumb instead
of just smaller, and tend to think as we get older we get smarter.
And sometimes we just get older.'' &QL; 
__________ &QL; 
The show: ``Nick News Special Edition: Kids Pick the Issues.'' &QL; 
What: Anchored by Linda Ellerbee, iinfluential people hear what's
important to kids in this election year. &QL; 
The stars: Hillary Rodham Clinton, Sen. Ted Kennedy, Tom Brokaw,
Dan Rather, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchinson and others. &QL; 
Where: Nickelodeon. &QL; 
When: 8:30 tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
