<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GUNS18-COX     03-17 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawsuit against Smith &AMP; Wesson settled
 &HT;    By Julie B. Hairston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A settlement Friday between local governments and the
country's largest gun manufacturer is being hailed as a
breakthrough in controversial lawsuits against weapons makers.
</P>
<P>
   The governments announced they would drop Smith &AMP; Wesson from
their lawsuits, which seek to hold gun makers liable for the toll
of handgun violence. In return, the Connecticut-based company
agreed to ship its guns with safety locks installed and make other
safety improvements. Joining the deal were more than a dozen cities
and counties that have filed gun suits, as well as the federal
government, which has threatened to do so.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton declared the agreement an act of ``courage and
vision'' by Smith &AMP; Wesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a panacea. It will not solve gun violence, but it
is a great first step,'' said Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell, who was
present at the Washington, D.C., announcement. He said the city
would drop its gun safety suit against the other 16 companies named
as defendants if they agree to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal, brokered by the federal departments of the Treasury
and Housing and Urban Development, Smith &AMP; Wesson agreed to put
external safety locks on all new guns within 60 days and promised
that within 36 months its new guns will incorporate technology that
allows only their owners to fire them.
</P>
<P>
   Within 12 months, no new gun sold by Smith &AMP; Wesson will be able
to be fired by a child under 6 years old, the company pledged.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers and distributors of Smith &AMP; Wesson guns will be required
to perform background checks for all sales. They also will not
permit retail customers to take possession of more than one gun
within a two-week period.
</P>
<P>
   A dealer or distributor will face cancellation of its Smith &AMP;
Wesson contract if ``a disproportionate number'' of crimes is
committed with guns it has sold.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association declined to comment on the deal.
But the National Shooting Sports Foundation, a firearms industry
organization, condemned Smith &AMP; Wesson, saying it had ``violated a
trust with their consumers and with the entire domestic firearms
industry'' by entering the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ill-conceived action on the part of one of the most
revered names in the American firearms industry,'' said Robert
Delfay, the foundation's president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   But cities are likely to use the deal to leverage similar
concessions from other gunmakers. Campbell said Atlanta and other
state and local governments have pledged not to buy guns from
manufacturers who do not agree to abide by the terms of the deal.
Government agencies such as police departments are the largest
legal purchasers of guns.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton encouraged governments to use their economic clout to
support the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smith &AMP; Wesson stuck their neck out here,'' he said. ``I think
all of us, including the federal government, in our procurement
policies _ if we are really serious about making America safer _
ought to send a clear signal that we appreciate what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell _ who has pursued the city's lawsuit despite state
efforts to quash it _ noted that the deal affects only new guns and
will do nothing to improve the safety of ``the hundreds of
thousands of weapons already available.'' But he compared the
change to the introduction of cars with seat belts and medicine
bottles with child safety caps.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, he said, ``is a floor, not a ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   A Smith &AMP; Wesson spokesman said the agreement will affect how
the company does business but will not infringe on gun owners'
Second Amendment rights. The company's president said it will help
ensure ``the future viability'' of Smith &AMP; Wesson.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Blair Jr., a multiparty lawsuit specialist with the firm of
Baker, Donelson, Bearman &AMP; Caldwell in Memphis, Tenn., said the
settlement makes more sense than fighting the lawsuits, even if
Smith &AMP; Wesson could have won in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could win every case and still face a significant loss,''
Blair said. The expense of litigation would ultimately be as
expensive as any possible settlement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo said Friday's announcement
was the most important one he's made as a member of the Clinton
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard the statistics many times. ... A rate of firearm
deaths for children in this country is 12 times higher than the
other 25 industrialized countries combined,'' Cuomo said. ``So we
approached the process in the belief that reasonable gun
manufacturers could sit down ... to stop the senseless gun
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
