<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GASTON'S GREEN LIGHT KEEPS PITINO AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Pitino and Celtic owner Paul Gaston had a private/secret
meeting in New York last week to discuss the future. Gaston told
Pitino he wanted Rick to stay the course and continue to coach the
club. Pitino reportedly offered to quit coaching the Celtics if
Gaston wanted him to. Gaston said, although he had hoped the team
would be further along, he understood the problems Pitino was
having trying to make the team better and supported him as the
coach. Pitino has four years to go on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston Mayor Tom Menino is supposed to be looking for financial
numbers this weekend from the Red Sox. Menino met with Red Sox boss
John Harrington last week and said he wanted to know what the team
would want the city to put into the project and how the city gets a
return on the money. Menino told Harrington the city money is an
investment, not a donation, and wants the Red Sox to show him how
Boston financially benefits from this in the future. Menino wants a
deal out of a new Fenway Park, similar to what he feels the city
will get from the new convention center in South Boston when it is
finished. The city put $170 million toward the convention center
after its supporters showed Menino how the city would get the money
back from tourism spending.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Red Sox, their ticket sales passed 1.6 million
this week, which puts them 200,000 ahead of a year ago, an increase
of 14 percent. It is a major leap for a team that put 2.4 million
people into Fenway Park last year.
</P>
<P>
   Just to get it straight, here's what happened in the Dominican
Republic series between the Red Sox and Houston Astros last
weekend. Major League Baseball came to the teams and asked them to
play the two-game series because both of their lineups are stocked
with Dominican players. MLB paid the teams' expenses. That's all
they got. They didn't make any money. MLB cut the deals with the
Caribbean Winter League officials in the Dominican Republic to
promote the game and use whatever money they made to promote
baseball on the island. MLB and the Dominican baseball authority
set the ticket prices: $3.50 in the bleachers, $33 for the top box
seat. Supposedly, this is the same ticket price scale used for the
Caribbean World Series. So if there was any ticket scalping, it was
by the locals. They set the prices. They controlled the tickets.
Boston and Houston simply provided the entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   University of Massachusetts basketball coaches, who thought a
few weeks back they would be given another year, got the feeling
after losing to Siena Thursday night in the NIT that they might get
whacked over the weekend. UMass officials have been concerned about
the way interest in the men's varsity basketball team has dipped
and have to decide if keeping coach Bruiser Flint around another
year is going to turn the program around. Reportedly, the coaches
would like to know their fate immediately, because if they are
going to get fired some of them feel they can hook on with former
UMass coach John Calipari, who took over at Memphis last week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly, this is the reason Patriots coach Bill Belichick let
Terry Glenn off the hook for the fine levied on him last season by
former coach Pete Carroll: Chances were Glenn was going to win his
arbitration case and would have gotten the money back anyhow. We're
told the Management Counsel, the league's legal squad, advised the
Patriots they would most likely lose the upcoming appeal because
the team did not follow the proper procedure when Carroll suspended
Glenn and fined him a game check for not showing up to practice.
Reportedly, when Glenn showed this week for a head-to-head meeting
with Belichick, he was told the team would give up the case and
give him his money back _ but this was the last break he was
getting and that it was time to grow up and play football. It's not
that Belichick and the Patriots wanted to give him the money back
and let him think he got away with another one, but rather they
most likely weren't going to win anyhow, so why not make a deal
that could start Glenn and Belichick fresh.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coaching legend Bill Fitch feels the NBA's attempt to place a
microphone on coaches during games and to open the dressing room to
television cameras is a fool's errand. ``Coaches wearing mikes has
been optional for 20 years, so to demand it now and fine coaches
for not doing it is an insult. Coaches and players don't like
change. The locker room is the sanctuary for the players. This is
the one place they can go and have their own time. Coaches don't
want what they said taped. I can remember our (Celtics) playoff
series (NBA Final) with Houston in 1981. They asked me to be miked.
I said no. (Houston coach) Del Harris said OK. Even back in those
days, I was into taping games (off television), so I had someone
tape the game for me. The next day I was watching the tape, and I
heard Del telling Robert Reid to go into the corner as a ``decoy''
on this particular play. In that game, Mike Dunleavy killed us
scoring a bunch of points off the play they were talking about.
From hearing what Del said (in the privacy of a team huddle), I
told our guys the rest of the series not to worry about Reid on
that play. Don't even cover him. They never hurt us again with that
play, and we shut Dunleavy down after that. I'd like to see them
put a mike on (NBA commisioner) David Stern when he shows up two
hours late from dinner some night and see what his wife has to say
about it.'' Chris Ford, former Celtics coach, agrees with Fitch.
``Wearing a mike inhibits you as a coach, or having someone stick a
mike into the huddle does the same thing. There are things coaches
do in the heat of battle, they want to stay private between them
and the players. And I don't see what mikes on the bench or cameras
in the locker room add to a game.'' Fitch has retired and Ford was
fired by the Los Angeles Clippers this year. Snooping television
cameras and mikes led to K.C. Jones's being fired as the coach of
the Washington Bullets in 1976. Washington was involved in the
final game of a playoff series on national television. Close game,
handful of seconds left, Washington with the ball for one last
shot. As the camera is stuck into the Washington bench, assistant
coach Bernie Bickerstaff asks Jones if he wants him to ``draw up
the play.'' Jones says OK. The camera focuses on Bickerstaff
telling the players what to do. Jones just says a couple of words
before the team heads back on the floor. The play fails. The next
day, some in the Washington media called for Jones's head, saying
he didn't know how to coach, and Jones got fired. Red Auerbach
always maintained that the fallout from that bench episode was the
culprit. In reality, Jones told Bickerstaff what play to draw up,
which is done all the time in the NBA, and it was a play the team
had been using all year. But television gave the impression that he
didn't want to make the call under the pressure of a big game and
wasn't really coaching in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe's thoughts on the Patriots' disappointing finish
after a sparkling 6-2 start: ``What makes what happened so hard to
swallow is how well (offensively) we played the first half of the
year. Everything felt so great. Even when we started to lose a
couple at the start of the second half of the season, I kept
thinking we were going to start winning and turn this thing around.
I thought we were going to get on another (winning) roll, and we
never did. What happened to me is a nightmare. I keep looking back
on some of the individual plays I made, or some of the games I
played, and think if only I had done better, it wouldn't have been
that way. What happened should have never happened. I should be too
smart by now to turn the ball over as many times as I did, or throw
three, four interceptions in a game. I tried to force things to
happen, and I shouldn't have. The second half of the season teams
(defensively) started to go in our face. They disrupted our timing.
This gave their pass rushers a better chance to get to me. They
challenged us, and we didn't deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When I first heard McDonald's was going to bring its annual high
school all-star game to the FleetCenter, I thought it was going to
bomb. But no so. To date, more than 13,000 tickets have been sold
for the March 29 event. The seats available will be limited to
16,900, which might make the remaining seats very valuable. The two
highest-priced tickets this winter among the local ticket brokers
(scalpers) were not Bruins or Celtics game, but rather the last big
wrestling show in the building (WWF's ``Smackdown'' taping) and the
Beanpot finals featuring BC and BU. Those tickets sold in the $150
range or about five times face value. Smart people tell me three
NBA first-rounders are scheduled to play in this game, if these
kids opt to go pro rather than go to college. They are Eddie
Griffin (Roman Catholic High, Philadelphia), Darius Miles (East St.
Louis, Ill.), and Gerald Wallace (Childersburg, Ala.).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flyers general manager Bobby Clarke phoned this week to say that
his offer for Ray Borque was legitimate. ``We offered Boston four
players and a fourth-round draft choice. We wanted Ray. Ray wanted
us. But Harry (Sinden) didn't want to deal with us or Detroit.'' To
which Sinden responded, ``Six teams were interested. When we got
all of the offers in, Philly was last behind Detroit. Colorado had
the best as far as we were concerned. I didn't care where Ray
played. I wanted what I felt was best for the Bruins and thought
the Colorado offer was the best.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the three reasons the Celtics aren't better. First,
they don't have anyone to defend against a top center. Second,
their backcourt is terrible on defense. Third, as a team, they lack
speed. So if the Celtics meet a team that doesn't have a dominant
center, can't take advantage of their defensive weakness in the
backcourt, and isn't very athletic, they can win. Otherwise, let's
hope they miss the playoffs, get into the draft lottery, and get
lucky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks before he left for London to fight Shea Neary for
the world junior welterweight title last Saturday, Lowell's Micky
Ward said he found a way to win watching tapes of Neary's fights.
Ward said he could beat Neary with left hooks to the body, which
would eventually make him drop his elbow to protect against the
shots allowing Ward to come over the top with a left hook to the
head. And that's exactly what happened as Ward took the
previously-undefeated Neary out with two knockdowns in the eighth
round to win the title, and $100,000, for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bad news for local marathoners. The Kenyans are going to use
this year's Boston Marathon as their Olympic qualifier. This means
all of Kenya's best _ and it has almost all of the best _ will be
flying to the finish in Boston fighting to represent their country
in Sydney in September. To date, it will be the second-biggest
Boston Marathon ever, with 18,000 runners expected to participate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chris Herren is showing signs he can play in the NBA. The former
Durfee High flash has played well lately for the Denver Nuggets. He
had 12 points in 13 minutes vs. the Lakers, eight assists vs.
Orlando, and five assists in just 18 minutes vs. Miami. Herren has
been averaging just under 13 minutes coming off the Denver bench.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WBZ-TV general manager Ed Goldman tells us that professional
golf is spanking the Celtics and Bruins in the ratings game this
year. And when Tiger Woods is in the hunt, the edge is even
greater. It wasn't that long ago you'd be laughed out of town if
you said golf would get better television numbers than the Bruins
and Celtics, who are both dropping toward all-time lows on the
tube.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Boston Globe columnist.)
