<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0457 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SOUTH-WILDFIRES18-COX     03-17 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-WILDFIRES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern drought could fan wildfires
 &HT;    By John Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The U.S. Forest Service predicts the upcoming spring
could be one of the worst fire seasons on record in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions in Florida are worse than in the summer of 1998, when
wildfires devastated 500,000 acres and destroyed or damaged 300
homes, forestry officials warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drought conditions in the South are forecast to continue for a
third straight year,'' said Elizabeth Estill, a Southern regional
forester in Atlanta, on Friday. ``Already a higher number of fire
crews than normal have been dispatched to respond to fires
throughout the 13-state Southern region.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southern region stretches from Texas to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got drought conditions in South Georgia that are as bad
as Florida,'' said Ron Coats, director of the Southern region's
fire and aviation unit. Since the beginning of March, 6,981 fires
have burned 129,935 acres in Southern states, Coats noted.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, smoke from wildfires temporarily closed Interstate 75
near Valdosta, Ga. The odd thing about the Valdosta fire is that it
was burning in a swamp, a sign of trouble ahead, said Alan Dozier,
chief of fire protection for the Georgia Forestry Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are swamps in South Georgia that are just dry,'' he
said. ``These places are usually wet and won't burn. We usually use
the swamps as fire breaks. But that strategy isn't working this
year and it's burning bigger areas.''
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina last week, crews fought 50 fires in six
Southeastern counties, and crews remained dispersed in the region
waiting for more. In Harnett County, fires threatened homes and
destroyed 1,000 acres of woodlands. At least 30 small fires have
broken out in the state's four national forests since the beginning
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Already this year Georgia has seen 31,366 acres burned. Usually,
9,000 acres burn during January through March. Firefighters this
year have battled a 7,800-acre blaze in Charlton County and other
large fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not supposed to have fires that big in Georgia,'' Dozier
said. The worst conditions are in southeast Georgia, he said, while
the northern part of the state is less critical because of recent
rains.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for the fires, the Forest Service has brought in
additional staff, equipment and aircraft, Coats said. The region
may need to increase fire crews and equipment by more than 50
percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Division of Forestry has beefed up its fire-attack
capabilities with the formation of three wildfire management teams,
said Larry Woods, chief of fire protection. The six-person teams
are available at a moment's notice to assist a district fire crew
battling a blaze.
</P>
<P>
   The crews are still in training and will not be available for
the full season, he said. Also, Florida is reconditioning three of
its helicopters and has purchased two surplus military Cobra
choppers.
</P>
<P>
   The spring fire season normally runs from mid-February to
mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   But drought conditions last year kept firefighters busy
throughout the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on where you are in Florida we're 15 to 20 inches
below normal in rainfall,'' said Woods. ``It's worse than 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Coats urged people to take care with outdoor burning, noting
that 65 percent of Southern wildfires are caused by humans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
