<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0458 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GUNS-LOCKS-HNS &LR;      03-17 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-LOCKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH &AMP; WESSON TO INSTALL CHILD-SAFETY LOCKS ON GUNS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gunmaking giant Smith &AMP; Wesson said Friday that it
will put child-safety locks on its handguns as part of a landmark
agreement to stave off potential federal and local lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   No other gun maker joined the accord, which Smith &AMP; Wesson
reached under the threat of litigation and much to the dismay of
industry colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, speaking from the Oval Office, praised the
agreement as ``a major victory for America's families'' in the
fight against gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord, which ends threatened lawsuits from federal,
state and local governments, Smith &AMP; Wesson said it will put
external, unremovable trigger locks on new handguns within 60 days
and install internal locking devices on new firearms within two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The company, the largest U.S. firearms manufacturer, also
pledged to restrict sales at gun shows, a main provision of
Clinton's proposed firearm-control legislation that congressional
Republicans and the National Rifle Association have scorned.
</P>
<P>
   In lauding Smith &AMP; Wesson's ``socially responsible'' act, a
leading spokesman for House Republicans said the accord
demonstrates that federal laws are unnecessary to encourage gun
manufacturers to make their products safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though we hail Smith &AMP; Wesson for taking a pro-active approach
to the problem of violence in our country, this step does not mean
gun crimes will go away,'' said Rep. J.C. Watts Jr., R-Okla. and
chairman of the House Republican Conference. ``We must re-double
our efforts to enforce existing laws and prosecute all violent
criminals. In addition when it comes to kids and guns, our nation
must take a closer look at why kids are killing kids and ask why
our culture is adrift.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration reached the accord with Smith &AMP; Wesson amid
stepped up attacks on Clinton from the NRA, which has assailed the
president for endorsing restrictive anti-gun laws while failing to
enforce existing statutes prohibiting illegal firearms possession.
</P>
<P>
   NRA Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre this week accused
Clinton of being willing to ``accept a certain level of killing to
further his political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made no direct reference to the NRA in praising what he
called Smith &AMP; Wesson's bravery and urging other gun makers to
reach similar agreements with the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are responsible citizens in the gun industry,'' Clinton
said. ``The effort to reduce gun violence ... is not about
politics. It is about saving lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA declined to comment on the Smith &AMP; Wesson agreement,
referring callers to the National Shooting Sports Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, which represents gun manufacturers, assailed
Smith &AMP; Wesson for breaking ranks and reaching an ``ill-conceived''
settlement with the government. Group president Robert Delfay said
industry leaders have been discussing among themselves ways to make
their firearms safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smith &AMP; Wesson has taken a list of suggestions and initiatives
that have been discussed in confidential industry talks and run off
and cut their own deal with the Clinton administration and a list
of anti-gun government officials,'' Delfay added. ``We are
confident that no other major manufacturers will desert this
coordinated effort in favor of their own deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Smith &AMP; Wesson President Ed Shultz defended his company's
decision to reach the out-of-court settlement as a smart business
move. Speaking via telephone at a news conference with federal
officials, Shultz said the settlement saves the company the
potentially exorbitant costs of litigation and allows it to focus
on making its guns ``better and safer for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun violence kills more than 30,000 people annually in the
United States and injures another 100,000, the federal government
reported. About 13 children are killed each day by guns, a rate 12
times higher than the other 25 industrialized countries combined,
the government added.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement followed a series of recent school and workplace
shootings, including one that left a 6-year-old Michigan
first-grader dead, allegedly at the hands of a fellow pupil. Three
men are under indictment in the Feb. 29 shooting of Kayla Rolland,
including the uncle of the 6-year-old boy who police say killed the
girl in a Buell Elementary School classroom near Flint.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the Democratic minority in Congress have been
pressing federal lawmakers to pass legislation requiring trigger
locks and background checks at gun shows. The Democrats have set a
goal for passing the measure by April 20, the first anniversary of
the day Columbine High School students Dylan Klebold and Eric
Harris shot and killed 12 schoolmates and a teacher before fatally
shooting themselves in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican majority, however, has been resisting the
Democrats' effort, saying current gun-control laws are sufficient
but need to be more effectively enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Smith &AMP; Wesson agreed to limit unregulated
sales of firearms at gun shows by requiring sellers of company
weapons to be authorized Smith &AMP; Wesson gun dealers. Also, no Smith
&AMP; Wesson firearm may be sold at a gun show until the would-be
purchaser passes a federally mandated background check.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, gun shows are exempt from the federal
mandate.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to prevent gun buyers from stockpiling weapons, the
agreement also prevents purchasers of Smith &AMP; Wesson guns from
taking home more than one weapon at the time of purchase. The buyer
will have to wait two weeks before picking up any additional guns.
</P>
<P>
   The company also will have to enter digital images on bullet
casings to make it easier for law enforcement to trace bullets
fired during crimes. Smith &AMP; Wesson dealers also must have store
security plans, and weapons and bullets must be kept locked and
separated.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Smith &AMP; Wesson gun store employees must complete
annual safety training and pass an exam.
</P>
<P>
   The accord also calls for Smith &AMP; Wesson to place a ``hidden''
second serial number on its guns to thwart criminals who erase
visible serial numbers in an effort to prevent the weapons from
being traced.
</P>
<P>
   The company also agreed to fund a public service campaign to
inform people about the risk of guns in the house and proper home
storage.
</P>
<P>
   A special five-member commission will oversee the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, who oversees the bureau,
praised the accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of this breakthrough agreement, fewer parents will
have to bury their children,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
