<HEADER>
A0459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-LABOR-ART-960&AMP;AD     03-17 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-LABOR-ART-960&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S INDEBTEDNESS TO LABOR POSES CAMPAIGN CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having locked up the Democratic nomination with considerable
help from organized labor, Vice President Al Gore now faces the
tricky problem of showing his gratitude to the nation's trade
unions, while convincing voters that he is not in labor's pocket.
</P>
<P>
   In walking this fine line, Gore faces a big test over the
Clinton administration's trade agreement with China because other
administration officials and Gore's business allies are pressuring
him to lobby for it, even as unions mount a feverish campaign to
defeat it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is also aware that there is broad support for the trade
agreement among farmers and people in high-technology industries,
as well as among political independents, whose votes could be
critical in November.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Gore has done little to promote the trade pact,
prompting complaints from some business leaders that he is too
close to labor. Aides to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
presumptive Republican nominee, are also attacking Gore, saying he
is beholden to labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton, to his credit, is leading a bipartisan
fight on free trade, and especially on bringing China into the
World Trade Organization,'' said Ari Fleischer, spokesman for the
Bush campaign. ``But Al Gore has shown no leadership whatsoever in
helping the Republicans and the president advance the cause of free
trade.''
</P>
<P>
   After unions provided many of the ground troops that Gore needed
to win in the primaries, the vice president now confronts a
challenge similar to that faced by other recent Democratic
nominees: While being somewhat indebted to labor, they also had to
rebuff Republican charges during the general election that they
were controlled by the nation's union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1984 campaign, Vice President Walter Mondale, the
Democratic nominee, was hurt badly by President Reagan's criticisms
that he was toadying to labor.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers insist that he is not beholden to organized
labor, though they note that he shares many of labor's views on
issues ranging from protecting Social Security to improving
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that he is in their pocket is absurd,'' said Elaine
Kamarck, a senior Gore adviser. ``On the biggest issue of the day
for labor, he doesn't agree with them, and, of course, that is
trade. To try to make the Mondale accusation about Al Gore is just
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Many union leaders acknowledge that they have clear expectations
from Gore if he is elected president, though Gore's aides and labor
leaders insist that he did not make any promises in exchange for
the AFL-CIO's endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders say that they expect that Gore will, if elected,
pursue many policies supported by labor, like opposing school
vouchers and opposing the privatization of Social Security. But the
Gore camp said that Gore backed those policies not because of
labor's support, but because he believed in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a regular dialogue with the vice president on a
wide range of issues, on issues that are our priorities,'' said
John J. Sweeney, president of the federation. ``That's a major
reason why we endorsed him.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Gore has walked a tightrope, trying to please
his labor allies without upsetting other supporters. At last
month's AFL-CIO executive council meeting in New Orleans, in an
evident effort to solidify labor support, he said that he would
negotiate strong labor protections in future trade accords.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement normalizing trade relations with China _ a deal
that paves the way for China to join the World Trade Organization _
contains no such protections, and Republican and business leaders
quickly condemned Gore's remarks, saying that they undermined
support for the agreement. Gore then tried to placate his business
allies, sending a letter to the National Association of
Manufacturers reaffirming his support for the trade deal.
</P>
<P>
   Another example came this week when he said in newspaper
interviews that he would speak out on behalf of the China deal. Yet
on Wednesday he did not say a word about the pact when he addressed
2,000 union members and leaders in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides said they recognize that if he lobbies aggressively
for the China deal, he risks alienating union members and reducing
his chances of securing endorsements from two powerful unions that
have so far remained neutral: the Teamsters and the United Auto
Workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he lobbies a lot on this, that will of course make it
difficult to do an endorsement while the debate is going on,'' said
Mike Mathis, the Teamsters' political director. ``Another problem
is if we get our members fired up on this issue, they're not going
to forget it in November.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The New York Times last week, Gore
acknowledged that some unions had not endorsed him ``because of the
fact that I'm in favor of this legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he added, ``Others have endorsed me in spite of our
disagreement on this legislation because I agree with them on 90
percent of the issues. And George Bush disagrees with them on 100
percent of the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO endorsement in October gave Gore an important lift
at a time when Bill Bradley's campaign was picking up momentum. The
Bradley camp acknowledges that union foot soldiers played a key
role in Gore's victory over Bradley in the Iowa caucuses. In New
Hampshire, where Bradley hoped a victory would give him huge
momentum, exit polls showed that labor also contributed
significantly to Gore's triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor has been incredibly helpful to the vice president,''
said Al From, president of the Democratic Leadership Council. ``He
obviously has to keep their concerns in mind. He also has to show
he's not just running for president of labor, but running for
president of the country.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When Gore gained the AFL-CIO endorsement, he promised union
leaders who had assembled in Los Angeles that if he became
president, he, like Clinton, would veto any anti-labor legislation,
like proposals that would weaken overtime laws. Gore had made that
promise many times before to union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rivera, president of 1199, the National Health and Human
Service Employees Union, said, ``In terms of support for Al Gore,
the labor movement played a very dramatic role. I think that Al
Gore owes the labor movement, once he's elected president of the
United States, to maintain the same friendship and relations that
he has had for years with the labor movement and to help us on some
of the key issues we have, like the right to organize.''
</P>
<P>
   As evidence of Gore's deference to labor, Fleischer, the Bush
spokesman, cited the vice president's opposition to school
vouchers, to reforming teacher tenure and to merit pay for teachers
_ all issues on which he sides with teachers union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, the teachers union is the biggest soft-money
contributor to the Democratic National Committee,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Greenstein, a Princeton political scientist, said that
Bush's embrace of many conservative policies opposed by labor would
cause unions to campaign enthusiastically for Gore, despite his
support of the China trade deal _ a deal Bush also supports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bush is making it easy for Gore,'' Greenstein said.
``It seems to me that labor and the other core groups in the
Democratic party will be strongly motivated to rally around Gore,
so I don't think he's going to have to do a lot of groveling or
toadying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
