<HEADER>
A0462 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDIA-U.S.-640&AMP;ADD-NY     03-17 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-U.S.-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TRIP TO ASIA IS AIMED AT LESSENING TENSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also INDIA-CLINTON) 
(lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton first contemplated visiting
India three years ago, he was eager to open a relationship with the
vastly populated, democratic country that had remained outside the
Western fold during the Cold War. He was also gripped with the
ambition, his aides said, to display the fabric of modern India to
the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   But the fall of two Indian governments and the nuclear tests of
May 1998 conspired against Clinton's timetable.
</P>
<P>
   Now the president is embarking on a five-day, five-city journey
to India and a five-hour stop in Pakistan at a time when tensions
on the subcontinent are high. A confrontation between the two
countries over Kashmir, where their fighters clash on 15,000-foot
mountain tops, is seen as the most likely dispute on earth to spark
a nuclear clash.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the president hopes that with this trip he can somehow
defuse the situation in Kashmir. But he and his aides are
pessimistic about the chances for actual progress.
</P>
<P>
   With this trip, Clinton will also become the first U.S.
president to visit Bangladesh, when he makes a day trip to the
democratic Muslim country that is striving to emerge from deep
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   It may be an overwhelming task for Clinton to balance his desire
to support the India of trade and technology and at the same time
deal with the treacherous rivalry between India and Pakistan and
their nuclear weapons programs. Complicating the situation
considerably is the coming to power of a military government in
Pakistan last October, whose hold on power Clinton is eager not to
endorse but with whom he wants to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is making India the 62nd foreign country he has visited,
a position down the list that some Indians have noted unhappily,
and he arrives almost as a lame-duck president, with little
opportunity to capitalize afterward on diplomatic gains.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, some of his aides, as well as experts on the
subcontinent, fear that the original intention of displaying India
as the economic and strategic power of the region will be
undermined by the increasingly strong-willed attitudes of the
Indian government toward nuclear weapons, Pakistan and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will face an Indian government whose nuclear doctrine
calls for the development of a ``large strategic Indian capability
sometime in the future,'' said Stephen Cohen of the Brookings
Institution, who was one of a group of experts on South Asia who
met with the president at the White House on Thursday evening to
help him prepare for the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen added that there were prominent voices in New Delhi
calling for further tests, on the grounds that India did not
produce a thermonuclear explosion in May 1998. The government of
Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee was prepared, he said, to pay
the price of Washington's sanctions in order to keep its nuclear
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   After India's nuclear tests, which were followed by tests by
Pakistan, the Clinton administration initiated a round of talks
aimed at persuading India to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty. Led by Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, the talks
extended to 12 rounds with the Indian foreign minister, Jaswant
Singh, but so far to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech previewing Clinton's trip, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright cautioned that the lack of progress at a time
when Russia and the United States were moving toward deeper cuts in
their arsenals was a major stumbling block for a fuller
relationship with Washington than India might otherwise enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must accept that significant progress in this area is
necessary, before India and the United States can realize fully the
vast potential of our relationship,'' Albright told the Asia
Society here on Tuesday. ``We have not yet found a way to create
sufficient common ground on these issues.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At a discussion at the Carnegie Endowment for International
Peace this week, Gary Samore, a member of the National Security
Council staff who specializes in nonproliferation, said that in his
15 years working on India and Pakistan, ``I don't think the
situation has ever looked any worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospects were bleak, Samore said, because neither India nor
Pakistan really understood the instability provoked by the
strategic threat of their nuclear weapons and ``to make matters
worse, both sides are spoiling for a fight'' in Kashmir. Another
conflict over the territory _ Pakistan and India have already
fought three wars there _ carries the ``potential spark for a
nuclear confrontation,'' Samore said.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton met with the group of experts from the region at
the White House on Thursday evening, he seemed intensely interested
in how he could defuse the situation but also worried about the
limited prospects for success, several participants said. The group
included two former ambassadors, Frank Wisner and Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, now the senior Democratic senator from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from overcoming the enormous enmity between the two
countries, Clinton must face the fact that India has insisted that
it will not accept mediation.
</P>
<P>
   And although Pakistan has said it will accept mediation,
Clinton's clout in influencing the behavior of the new military
leader, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, appears limited, his aides say.
</P>
<P>
   In a briefing on Thursday to reporters who will accompany
Clinton, his national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said: ``The
president is not going to South Asia to mediate the dispute between
them. But he will urge them to exercise restraint and resume
dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   One fundamental request that Clinton is likely to put to
Musharraf is for a halt to the Pakistani incursions over the line
of control, the cease-fire line in Kashmir that divides the
territory.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian leadership has said there can be no discussion over
Kashmir until ``concrete steps'' are taken by the Pakistanis to
withdraw. Last July, Clinton successfully persuaded the last
civilian leader of Pakistan, Nawaz Sharif, to take such steps. But
three months later Sharif was overthrown by the general. Given this
history, administration officials said they were skeptical that
Musharraf would do what Sharif had promised.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Albright said in her speech that as a start
Pakistan must pledge to make no further incursions into the
Indian-held part of Kashmir. ``Nations must not attempt to change
borders or zones of occupation through armed force,'' she said.
``Tangible steps must be taken to respect'' the so-called military
line of control that separates the territory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
