<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0470 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-RAIL-MERGER-BAN-TEX     03-17 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIL-MERGER-BAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER MORATORIUM HALTS BURLINGTON-CANADIAN NATIONAL PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: Story is moving in ``a'' general news and
``f'' financial categories). 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Burlington Northern Santa Fe and Canadian
National Railways must wait 15 months before they can apply to
merge, federal regulators said on Friday in a decision that
jeapardizes the linkup of the two major rail systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Surface Transportation Board's announcement came after
competitors, shippers, and elected officials lined up to oppose the
$6 billion combination, which would create a system extending from
the Atlantic Ocean in Canada to the U.S. and Canadian west coasts.
</P>
<P>
   When the railroads file their application, the U.S. Surface
Transportation Board said, the agency might end up raising the bar
for approval of big rail mergers.
</P>
<P>
   The news is of particular interest in North Texas. Burlington
Northern's headquarters and network operations hub are in Fort
Worth, where the company employs 2,500 workers. Union Pacific,
based in Omaha, also has major rail operations in the area and had
opposed the merger. Many major commercial shippers, who suffered
after recent rail mergers resulted in snarled traffic nationwide,
also are wary of more big combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's announcement prompted an angry response from BNSF
Chairman Robert Krebs, who said his company will consider suing to
get the regulatory board to act on the proposed merger, which the
companies announced in mid-December.
</P>
<P>
   ``BNSF will thoroughly review today's decision to determine what
appropriate legal action we can take,'' Krebs said. He described
the moratorium as ``unheard of,'' in the railroad industry.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, however, responded favorably to the news.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market, which had reacted negatively to the merger
announcement, looked favorably on the latest news. The decision was
announced an hour before the New York Stock Exchange closed, and
BNSF shares traded late in the day at $22.32, up $1.32 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Since the announcement of the merger on Dec. 17, BNSF stock had
declined from $26 per share to less than $20 earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The decision of BNSF and CN to merge prompted other railroads to
warn that they would consider giant mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst James Valentine of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter told
Bloomberg News that ``the merger genie is out of the bottle.'' But
he said the board's decision effectively delays further mergers by
at least three years.
</P>
<P>
   In the decision, chairwoman Linda Morgan noted that rail stocks
had declined, ``taking a particularly sharp turn downward
immediately after the BNSF/CN merger proposal was announced.''
</P>
<P>
   Rail merger applications were once leisurely affairs, often
stretching over decades. The 1980 deregulation of the industry put
new time constraints _ as little as 12 months _ on applications.
The merger of Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Pacific Corp. was
accomplished in 15 months after it was announced in mid-1994.
</P>
<P>
   After the BNSF-Canadian National merger was proposed, opponents
pounced on the industry's Achilles heel, the service foulups that
have accompanied the two most recent mergers involving Union
Pacific and Southern Pacific railroads in the western United States
and the consolidation of Conrail by CSX and Norfolk Southern in the
east.
</P>
<P>
   The Union Pacific-Southern Pacific merger problems hit Texas
particularly hard in late 1997 and most of 1998. Chemical shippers
and utilities complained about delayed service, and the Federal
Railroad Administration temporarily assumed oversight of UP
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Shippers also complained that the reduction in the number of
major Class One carriers in the United States _ to four today, from
more than two dozen 25 years ago _ threatens competition and makes
customers vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Krebs had tried to counter objections by noting that the
BN-Santa Fe merger went relatively smoothly, and that the merged
company has rolled up record profits since.
</P>
<P>
   But Morgan said in the board's decision that ``the overwhelming
testimony at our hearing (held earlier this month in Washington,
D.C.) indicated that the shipping public has still not recovered
from those disruptions.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement with ominous overtones for future merger
applications, Morgan added that ``our existing merger policy
guidelines were adopted in 1980. The goals of that merger policy
have largely been achieved. It does not appear that there are
significant public interest benefits to be realized from further
downsizing or rationalizing of rail route systems.''
</P>
<P>
   The board's decision blocked BNSF and Canadian from filing later
this month for approval of their merger. The railroads planned to
ask for a decision on the merger within one year, and talked of its
completion by August 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the two carriers will be unable to even apply for
permission to merge until mid-June next year. A decision on the
application would take at least a year. Meanwhile, the board said
yesterday that it will write new guidelines for mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board seems to realize that most of the benefits of
rationalization have been realized,'' said Diane Duff, executive
director of the Alliance for Rail Competition, a network of
corporations and trade groups.
</P>
<P>
   Chemical shippers, whose members along the Texas Gulf coast were
particularly victimized by service fiascos after the Union
Pacific-Southern Pacific merger of 1997, also stressed the need for
more competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another avenue for us to talk about changing the
system to make it work for customers,'' said Mike Heimowitz,
spokesman for the Chemical Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
   BNSF's railroad rivals quickly lined up against the merger with
an unanimity that Krebs said surprised him.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific Railroad, which competes directly against BNSF in
the western half of the U.S., said the board's decision ``is in the
best interest of the railroad industry.''
</P>
<P>
   CSX Chairman John Snow said the decision ``is a recognition of
the fact that the proposed BNSF/CN merger is not in the public
interest at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow, whose railroad operates in the eastern half of the United
States, said ``a longer pause (between mergers) would have been
preferable.''
</P>
<P>
   The BNSF-CN merger would move the BNSF headquarters to Montreal
from Fort Worth. CN Chairman Paul Tellier would become chief
executive of the new company, and Krebs would take the title of
``nonexecutive chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month Krebs said he would ease out of executive
responsibility with the railroad and ``go relax.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
