<SLUG> BC-BOEING-STRIKE-RESPECT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BOEING PANEL AIMED AT SHOWING RESPECT FOR TECH EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. and its engineering union tackled one
of the thorniest demands of its striking engineers _ showing
greater respect for technical employees _ by creating a new joint
``Leadership Council'' under the proposed contract agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But it's unclear what the panel will actually accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and the Society of Professional Engineering Employees in
Aerospace agreed to create the Leadership Council to address
everything from healthcare matters to quality issues. Boeing
Chairman Phil Condit and Paul Almeida, president of the union's
parent, the International Federation of Professional and Technical
Engineers, will co-chair the panel.
</P>
<P>
   The council is an attempt to address two key demands of striking
employees: a greater partnership with the company and a clearer
definition of their future roles at the company.
</P>
<P>
   But, the idea of a joint union-executive panel isn't unique to
Boeing's latest contract offer. The provision has popped up in
other labor contracts and produced mixed results, according to Kate
Bronfenbrenner, director of labor education and research at Cornell
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joint councils, and the values and the power of (a) union
council really depends on what is done with it,'' Bronfenbrenner
said. ``You have to watch what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives say the council could play a key role in
building greater cooperation between the company's technical
community and management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to commit, very specifically, some of my time and
energy to a working-together task force that will allow us to sit
down and discuss what are the issues, how did they occur, how do we
take this company forward,'' Condit said in a news conference
addressing the broader contract agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The aerospace giant already is working with its most powerful
union, the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers, on several joint efforts. For example, the union says it
has already been able to preserve jobs within the company that had
been earmarked for subcontractors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, leaders of the union admit the effectiveness of the
council, which will meet every quarter, is an open question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be worth an awful lot to the union and the company or
it could be worth nothing,'' said Craig Buckham, president of the
engineering union, the second largest union at Boeing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
