<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0475 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-RAP-BROWN-MAIN18-COX     03-17 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAP-BROWN-MAIN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police continue search for suspect in officer's fatal shooting
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hundreds of police officers and FBI agents continued
to search Friday evening for a former Black Panther turned
neighborhood leader wanted in the killing of a Fulton County
sheriff's deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they believe Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, formerly known
as H. Rap Brown, is being harbored by someone who admires him for
his efforts to rid the southwest Atlanta enclave known as the West
End of drugs and prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will leave no stone unturned until we find this man,'' said
Capt. David Chadd, chief spokesman for the Fulton County Sheriff's
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell urged anyone with information about
Al-Amin's whereabouts to come forward. He warned that harboring a
fugitive in such a serious case is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Chadd said a 100-officer team searching West End for Al-Amin
early Friday morning was scaled back only after police determined
he was no longer within a four-block radius.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta homicide investigators and uniformed officers from the
precinct that covers that section of the city remained in the
neighborhood, however. That force was quadrupled after Deputy
Richard Kinchen died at Grady Memorial Hospital on Friday afternoon
of gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   An all points bulletin was issued before dawn advising that
Al-Amin could be driving a black, four-door Mercedes-Benz with
tinted windows and license plate 246MBG or a green Toyota
Four-Runner with Alabama plates 45AV431.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI issued a federal fugitive warrant for Al-Amin's arrest,
said FBI spokeswoman Celeste Armstead.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in 41 years that a Fulton County
sheriff's deputy had been killed by gunfire in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Aldranon English, the deputy who survived the attack, identified
Al-Amin as the shooter after Atlanta homicide investigators showed
him several pictures from a line-up as he lay in his hospital bed
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after identifying Al-Amin, English learned his
friend and partner had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are heartbroken,'' said a solemn Jacqueline Barrett, Fulton
County sheriff. ``The entire department is taking this very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta and Fulton sheriff's officials said Al-Amin used a .223
caliber assault rifle to attack Kinchen and English. The weapon is
similar to M-16 and AR-15 rifles. The bullets are about three
inches long and about half an inch in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only purpose to use a weapon like the one he used, is to
kill,'' Chadd said.
</P>
<P>
   Kinchen, a nine-year veteran who leaves behind his wife and two
children, died after several attempts to revive his heart failed,
Chadd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deputy's demise was due to the horrendous trauma he
suffered from the attack with the assault weapon,'' Chadd said.
``His heart stopped several times and he could not be revived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a shame he had to die in such a heinous fashion,
especially since the deputies were only trying to serve him with a
warrant that was so minor.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinchen and English were attempting to serve a warrant on
Al-Amin late Thursday evening for Cobb County Police. The warrant,
issued Jan. 28 after Al-Amin failed to appear in Cobb County court,
was for driving without proof of insurance and impersonating a
police officer. Thursday night, Atlanta police and Fulton County
sheriff's officials had said Al-Amin was wanted for aggravated
assault.
</P>
<P>
   Though Kinchen and English both wore protective vests, the gear
was no match for the powerful bullets that struck the deputies,
said Dr. Jeff Salomone, the surgeon for the Atlanta Police
Department. Salomone, associate professor of surgery at Emory
School of Medicine, said the slugs went under and around the vests.
</P>
<P>
   ``A vest offers no protection against a high velocity bullet,''
the surgeon said Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said another surgeon at Grady told her the injuries
sustained by the deputies _ especially Kinchen's _ ``looked like
those seen in Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police Detective Joseph Masterson Jr. said Al-Amin was
one of several suspects in 20 unsolved homicides in the West End
neighborhood. But Al-Amin was never charged after Deputy Chief C.B.
Jackson and other police commanders concluded they did not have
enough evidence against him or others.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin, 56, moved to the West End area in 1976 after he was
released from prison on a robbery conviction.
</P>
<P>
   He converted to the Muslim faith while in prison and changed his
name to Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin. He runs a grocery store about 100
feet from Al-Amin's mosque, which is housed in a large blue framed
building.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim community, which has helped revitalize West End,
showed support for Al-Amin on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Mosque member Nadim Ali, a spokesman for the Community Mosque of
Atlanta, read a prepared statement Friday afternoon. Ali refused to
answer questions from the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We the members of the Community Mosque of Atlanta would like
to state that the legal principal that a person is innocent until
proven guilty is also a concept that is consistent with the Islamic
belief. We ask you to avoid passing judgement until all the facts
are in and not use the media to accuse, try and convict Imam Jamil
Abdullah Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   He is a respected leader in the Islamic community and his works
are well documented, not only in Atlanta, but throughout the
Islamic world.''
</P>
<P>
   Local defense attorney Bruce Harvey, who once represented
Al-Amin, was surprised to hear the allegations against his former
client. In 1995, Harvey represented Al-Amin when he was charged
with weapons violations and aggravated assault on allegations he
shot a man in the leg as he walked through West End Park. The
charges were dismissed. The attorney said Al-Amin showed up for his
court appearances in that case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd put down the shotgun and picked up the Koran,'' Harvey
said. ``He's turned away from being a revolutionary and a radical
leader to being a spiritual leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why he would respond to these kinds of charges out of Cobb
County in that fashion would be unfathomable to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writers Joshua Good, Ernie
Suggs and Bill Rankin contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
