<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `We needed that': Gordon rolls to Darlington pole
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARLINGTON, S.C. _ Jeff Gordon took a big step in his trek back
to the top of NASCAR's Winston Cup Series by winning the pole for
Sunday's Mall.com 400.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was last driver on the track and turned a lap at 172.662
mph to bump Kevin Lepage to the outside pole. Gordon got cheers
instead of boos from the Darlington crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was definitely the high point of the 2000 season,'' said
Gordon. ``We needed that.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-time Winston Cup champion opened the season with a new
crew chief, Robbie Loomis, and several new crew members.
</P>
<P>
   After four races, Gordon's best finish is ninth _ at Atlanta
Motor Speedway last week _ and he ranks 17th in points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've run bad and we've been needing to run better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said winning the pole, his third in 15 Winston Cup races
at Darlington, is a confidence builder for his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the changes that have gone on, this team has done a
great job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's team owner, Rick Hendrick, said he was pleased with the
qualifying run and said people sometimes want too much from his
driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people expect Jeff Gordon to come out every week and sit
on the pole and lead every lap,'' Hendrick said. ``Nobody is going
to do that in this sport. There are too many good teams and good
drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of Gordon's 49 career victories have come at Darlington, a
track advertised as ``too tough to tame.'' Gordon has never won
more than four at any other track on the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Lepage said he and owner Jack Roush figured all along that
Gordon would be fastest.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm tickled pink,'' said Lepage, who started the season
without a sponsor, but now has one in FamilyClick.com. ``It's
disappointing that we didn't get the pole, but our team has been
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   No make of car appeared to have an aerodynamic advantage; the
top 10 consisted of three Chevrolets, three Pontiacs and four
Fords.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt, who beat Bobby Labonte by less than two feet to
win the Cracker Barrel 500, will start fourth Sunday in a car that
he describes as ``real drivable.''
</P>
<P>
   Four rookies earned starting spots, led by 10th place-finisher
Dale Earnhardt Jr., who has qualified in the top 10 for every
points race this season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
