<HEADER>
A0477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LIFE-MAGAZINE-1STLD-W     03-17 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-MAGAZINE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SECOND TIME, LIFE MAGAZINE WILL END REGULAR PUBLICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (subs for rewriting and additional information; new byline; story
grows by about 300 words)  
(bl) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At Time Inc., it's deja vu all over again. After at
least two years of speculation within the company, Time Inc.
announced Friday that it would cease regular publication of Life
magazine with the May issue _ the second time it has closed the
magazine since it was introduced in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Long a staple in American households of a certain era along with
other general-interest publications like Look magazine and The
Saturday Evening Post, Life became the illustrated chronicle of the
World War II period, and as a weekly magazine, offered
news-oriented photojournalism to the Vietnam War era. Partly in
reaction to the images available on television news, Time Inc.
discontinued Life in 1972, and reintroduced it as a monthly title
in 1978. Life magazine did not become profitable until 1986,
according to Time Inc. executives.
</P>
<P>
   Don Logan, the chief executive of Time Inc., said the market had
simply become too competitive for the survival of a
general-interest magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Circulation economics are changing for the whole industry,''
he said. ``It is tough for general-interest magazines which don't
have a fairly endemic advertising base to draw from over the long
term.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertising pages were down over all, to 665 total pages in 1999
from 730 in 1998, a drop of 8.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Logan said that the magazine's newsstand sales and circulation
had dropped to 1.5 million from 1.8 million in 1991, according to
the Audit Bureau of Circulations. And he said that the magazine's
subscriptions had dwindled as a result of legal proceedings against
American Family Publishers and Publishers Clearing House, the
so-called stamp-sheet houses that had once been a major source of
subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Time Inc., a unit of Time Warner Inc., said Life magazine would
publish special issues.
</P>
<P>
   According to Time Inc. executives, the decision to close the
magazine after more than a decade of profitability was made because
Life _ the magazine itself, not its ancillary products like books
and videos _ was operating at a loss.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other Time Inc. executives said that the magazine's managing
editor, Isolde Motley, a former editor of Martha Stewart Living,
had compounded the problems on the business side by taking
editorial risks that failed. Motley hired an art director who
boldly redesigned parts of the magazine, alienating longtime
readers unaccustomed to stark design. And Motley's choice of covers
performed poorly at the newsstand, especially in the last six
months; the magazine, which in 1996 sold between 250,000 to and
530,000 copies on the newsstand each month, according to a report
filed with the Audit Bureau of Circulations, has sold far fewer on
newsstands in the last year, even dipping perilously close to the
100,000 mark at one point, said one executive.
</P>
<P>
   Motley had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Logan said that Friday was ``a sad, sad day'' at Time Inc. ``The
name of our building is Time-Life,'' he said. ``We have an entire
division called Time-Life. There have been generations of people
who have worked and spent their entire lives and careers making
this a great magazine. And I feel like I personally failed in
finding a way to keep Life strong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0478 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-US-IRAN-HNS &LR;      03-17 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-IRAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT OFFERS NEW OPENNESS WITH IRAN AS U.S. EASES SOME
SANCTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Cautiously embracing Iran's move toward democracy,
the Clinton administration eased sanctions against Iranian rugs and
pistachio nuts Friday and signaled a willingness to normalize
relations with the Islamic republic.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging a history of U.S. interference in Iran's internal
politics, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright called for renewing
diplomatic and cultural ties that were shredded by Iran's 1979
revolution and the 444-day hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call on Iran to join in writing a new chapter in our shared
history,'' Albright said in a speech to the private
American-Iranian Council in Washington. ``Let us be open about our
differences and strive to overcome them. Let us acknowledge our
common interests and strive to advance them.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the start of the Iranian new year to signal a shift in
U.S. policy toward the oil-rich nation, Albright pledged to seek a
settlement of disputed financial claims between the countries. ``We
have concluded the time is ripe to broaden our perspective,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Albright urged Iran's moderate government to help
protect oil reserves and ease tensions in the Persian Gulf region.
``Iran lives in a dangerous neighborhood,'' Albright said. ``We
welcome efforts to make it less dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   While lifting the U.S. ban on importing Persian carpets, caviar,
nuts and fruit, the administration left in place its prohibition
against U.S. companies' involvement in Iran's oil industry. Before
those restrictions are eased, Albright said, Iran must end
development of nuclear weapons and its support of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Albright stopped short of apologizing for U.S. involvement in
Iran's internal affairs, but she acknowledged that Washington had
been ``regrettably shortsighted'' in supporting Baghdad in the
1980s Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she lamented the CIA's role in toppling the popular
leftist government of Mohammed Mossadegh in 1953, a coup that put
the U.S.-backed Shah, Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, into power.
</P>
<P>
   The Shah was driven from Iran in 1979 as the Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini took power and Iranian militants took 52 Americans
hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's landmark speech, the easing of some trade
restrictions and the pledge to resolve long-standing U.S.-Iranian
financial disputes, drew a positive, yet cautious, response from
the Tehran government.
</P>
<P>
   ``These steps, important and refreshing as they may be, are
insufficient to make a quick and drastic change in the state of
affairs between the two countries,'' said Iranian Ambassador Hadi
Nejad-Hosseinian.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Tehran's perception, one of the problems with the offer of
dialogue is that the U.S. has made it in an insolent and
domineering spirit and not in a real and practical spirit of mutual
respect and equality,'' Nejad-Hosseinian said.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was set for thawing U.S.-Iranian relations by
conciliatory remarks over the past two years by Iranian President
Mohammed Khatami and the victory last month of moderates over
Islamic hard-liners in Iran's parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Iran has begun reaching out to Europe trying to
negotiate lucrative oil deals that, under a prohibition renewed
earlier this week by President Clinton, U.S. companies are barred
from signing.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the Reagan and Bush administrations also tried to
cultivate moderates in Iran. The efforts failed, even after the
Reagan administration secretly sold weapons to Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no illusions that the United States and Iran will be
able to overcome decades of estrangement overnight,'' Albright
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't build a mature relationship on carpets and grain
alone, but the direction of our relations is more important than
the pace,'' she said. ``The United States is willing either to
proceed patiently on a step-by-step basis or to move very rapidly
if Iran indicates a desire and commitment to do so.``
</P>
<P>
   Iran remains on the State Department's list as a sponsor of
terrorism, along with Cuba, Syria and North Korea. While the United
States continues an unyielding boycott against Cuba, the Clinton
administration is courting Syrian President Hafez Assad and
counseling North Korea on what steps to take to get removed from
the list.
</P>
<P>
   Any restoration of ties between the United States and Iran would
require Congress to change tough sanctions laws, and at least a
dozen lawmakers criticized the administration's move.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., accused the administration of being
unprincipled and inconsistent. ``Principled foreign policy stands
up to terrorism,'' Mack said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., called the administration effort
premature, saying Tehran should compensate U.S. victims of Iranian
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Brad Sherman, D-Calif., and 10 other House Democrats wrote
Clinton condemning what they characterized as ``unilateral
concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
