<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0479 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-JAPAN-TELETECH-ART-3T     03-17 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-TELETECH-ART-3TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JAPAN, THE LEGACY OF A PHONE MONOPOLY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of profits for NTT in Japan in different business
areas; comparing phone services in major cities is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The jackhammers start their work at 10 p.m., and in this
case, their rat-a-tat-tat brings a machine gun to mind. For the
trench they are digging, which will be home to a state-of-the-art
fiber optic cable transmitting data and voices around the globe,
lies on the front lines of the battle for the heart and soul of the
Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
   Operating the jackhammers are Japanese construction workers
under contract to KVH Telecom, a fledgling telecommunications
company financed by a unit of FMR's Fidelity Investments. They are
laying a cable that KVH promises will provide better quality,
higher speed and cheaper service than anything Japan has ever seen.
And in doing so, they are creating a piece of the infrastructure
upon which a new Japan will rise after a decade of economic
decline.
</P>
<P>
   Dictating how the trench will be dug _ and in many ways,
discouraging the digging _ are Japanese regulators. They are only
the most recent in a line of officials who have single-mindedly
promoted the interests of Japanese business _ particularly those of
the mighty Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, by many measures Japan's
most formidable company and long its telephone monopoly. Their
rules, which add months to every project, have made Japan the most
expensive telecommunications market in the industrialized world.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, American trade negotiators will meet their Japanese
counterparts here in what may be the last in a long series of
skirmishes over Japan's regulation of the telecommunications market
before the United States takes its case to the World Trade
Organization. Other areas like energy, medical equipment,
pharmaceuticals and housing will also be under discussion, but the
bulk of the talks will be devoted to telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors and Washington contend that NTT has considerable
advantages beyond having been the only game in town for decades.
Government regulation, they say, favors NTT in the way that prices
are set, in limiting access to rights of way and in severely
circumscribing how various types of telecommunications carriers can
do business.
</P>
<P>
   The fight, however, is much more than a trade dispute. ``This is
not a battle between the United States, foreigners and Japanese,
small companies and large ones,'' said Harumasa Sato, a professor
of economics at Konan University in Kobe and a member of the
government's Telecommunication Council, an advisory board of
academics and experts. ``This is a battle between monopoly and
competition, old Japan and new Japan, the past and the future.''
</P>
<P>
   While similar fights are taking place throughout the Japanese
economy these days, perhaps none is so pivotal. After all, it is
the development and deployment of telecommunications systems, with
their delicate glass fibers and light-speed switches, that is
knitting the global economy into a seamless whole and playing a
bigger and bigger role in the prosperity of individual economies.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese insist they are intent on becoming a critical link
in the network and are working as fast as is practical to
deregulate their market. The Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications refused to make any of its officials available
for an interview, saying they were too busy.
</P>
<P>
   And it is, in fact, getting easier to compete here; NTT
officials point to the presence of KVH and many other competitors
as proof of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot understand why foreign competitors are saying NTT
gets preferential treatment,'' said Kanji Koide, a senior vice
president at NTT ``The reason they are here is that the Japanese
market is a level playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a general backlash against deregulation in Japan,
as evidence of the economy's growing openness sinks into the
popular psyche. Seeing a packed Starbucks shop on seemingly every
corner in Tokyo _ often across the street from a struggling
Japanese competitor _ raises fears among many that Japan is losing
its identity.
</P>
<P>
   So there are signs of foot-dragging, notably in the
telecommunications sector. In 1998, then Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto promised President Clinton that Japan would adopt a
method of calculating interconnection fees _ what NTT charges other
carriers to hook into its local network _ that would make Japan
competitive with other major markets around the globe by this
April. Yet now the government says it cannot live up to Hashimoto's
pledge, because dropping fees so far so fast would be
``devastating'' to NTT.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, practical impediments to competition here have not
been dismantled, adding immensely to the costs of any company
trying to build a telecommunications system that challenges NTT on
its home turf.
</P>
<P>
   Take KVH's trench. Construction costs average around $2,000 a
meter, roughly five times what they would be in Europe and 10 to 12
times higher than in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Why? The trench must be opened, dug and closed each night. All
the soil that is dug out of the trench must be hauled away, and new
dirt hauled in to replace it. Each night. The pit must be 55 inches
deep, compared with 31 inches in Europe; the greater depth means
steel plates must be used to reinforce the trench.
</P>
<P>
   The Ministry of Construction, which imposes these rules, says
they are necessary because Japan is earthquake prone and densely
populated and its cities ancient.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot, though, is that by the time KVH completes the first
66 miles of its network this month, construction will have
accounted for some 80 percent of its costs. ``It sometimes feels
like we're in the construction business instead of the telecom
business,'' said Akira Tada, KVH's director of corporate planning.
</P>
<P>
   Further, though KVH's goal is to give customers service that
bypasses NTT, it cannot provide such services without itself doing
business with NTT; the phone company, together with local power
companies, owns the conduits that feed into buildings here.
</P>
<P>
   So roughly 70 percent of the internal ducts that KVH will use
must be leased from NTT at an average cost of $70 a meter. In
building a phone system, ``speed is very important, and if we use
their ducts, we get speed,'' Tada said. ``We have to pay for
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the end of one year, KVH has completed less than 20 percent
of its network, far less than it expected. It has taken MCI
WorldCom three years and dozens of bruising battles with regulators
and building owners to wire two buildings. After trying to compete
with NTT for more than a decade, the Tokyo Telecommunications
Network, or TT Net, has captured only 0.8 percent of the nationwide
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to do business here, but still the situation is much
better than it was three years ago,'' said Mirei Kuroda, an
executive at MCI WorldCom who recalls being summoned to the
ministry at 11 one night when MCI was applying for its license.
``But the ministry is still not supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this, businesses are pressing hard for alternatives,
and in doing so are forcing NTT to respond. KVH, MCI WorldCom,
Japan Telecom and others are laying loops of fiber optic cable all
over Tokyo and Osaka, hooking up to buildings owned by major real
estate companies like Mori Building and Mitsui Fudosan.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings those developers own and manage were previously
served only by NTT, but times _ and tenants _ have changed. Foreign
financial service and law firms, proliferating thanks to
deregulation in the financial markets here, are demanding
high-speed, high-quality, fault-free telecommunications services at
a competitive cost.
</P>
<P>
   Mori Building is on the verge of offering its tenants
long-distance service using MCI WorldCom's lines; over the longer
term, it plans to give them a menu of carriers to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   Hiroo Mori, a director of Mori Building, figures the cost of a
long-distance call will drop by as much as 75 percent. ``We think
this will enhance our reputation and make us more appealing to
tenants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But as Koide of NTT notes, only business customers _ the most
lucrative market for any upstart phone company, whether in Japan,
the United States or elsewhere _ will benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are only planning to serve customers who use a lot of
international service,'' he said. ``We have to provide service to
everyone here, even when we don't make a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Japanese consumer has figured hardly at all in the
dreams of MCI WorldCom, KVH and the like, largely because the cost
of reaching her is so high. NTT is at both ends of 99 percent of
local calls, because it controls the critical wires into Japanese
homes. That means every time someone using MCI's network picks up
the phone and calls someone else here, MCI pays NTT an
interconnection fee that amounts to somewhere around 40 percent of
the revenue from the call.
</P>
<P>
   Those fees are the core of the fight between the United States
Trade Representative's office and Japanese regulators. Tokyo has
proposed cutting them by 22.5 percent over four years; Washington
wants a 41 percent reduction right away. Neither side is budging.
</P>
<P>
   To understand how interconnection fees affect carriers, take a
look at TT Net, to date the only company attempting to compete with
NTT in providing local phone service.
</P>
<P>
   Started in 1986 by Tokyo Electric Power in the wake of NTT's
privatization, it faces few of the challenges that foreign carriers
do, because it can use the conduits, ducts and rights of way owned
by its parent. For the first decade of its existence, it served
business customers and other telecommunications carriers that used
its system end to end, capturing almost one-third of the demand for
high-speed digital transmission in its service area.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1998, TT Net began offering telephone services to
households in Tokyo and eight surrounding prefectures, using a
high-speed optical fiber network laid alongside the electric
company's cables and distribution lines. It priced its service at 9
yen for three minutes, 1 yen lower than NTT's rate, and came up
with some catchy advertising. By the end of last May, it had
attracted more than two million customers.
</P>
<P>
   But to complete local phone calls, TT Net had to connect to
NTT's network _ and its profitability plummeted. Net income fell
from 2.5 billion yen in 1997 to 300 million yen in 1998, then
tumbled to 100 million yen in the fiscal year that ended last
March.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of interconnection is a real and harsh one,'' said
Hiroyuki Tsukamoto, deputy general manager of TT Net's corporate
planning department. ``It is the center of our problems.'' TT Net,
of course, knew from the start that interconnection fees were high.
But it started the service believing that the government planned to
cut them this year.
</P>
<P>
   Koide contends, though, that TT Net's problems are the result of
a flawed business strategy and an excessive reliance on NTT's
sites. ``Charging 9 yen is uneconomical,'' he said. ``We charge 10
yen and can hardly make money.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, lowering interconnection fees will be hard on NTT,
which has been trying to find its footing since being forced by the
government last year to spin off its two most promising businesses
and carve its remaining operations into three parts.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government estimates that its own proposal would
slice $4 billion out of the revenues of NTT's two local phone
companies, one of which is already losing money. Any further
reduction, it says, would force NTT to either charge its retail
customers higher rates _ which would be all but impossible,
politically _ or absorb the pain itself, since the law prohibits it
from simply eliminating unprofitable service.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, we must provide service to remote regional
areas at our own cost, and on the other hand, we are exposed to
harsh competition in the more lucrative urban areas,'' Koide said.
``We feel there's a contradiction in that system.''
</P>
<P>
   But Koide and the government are ignoring the experience of the
United States and other countries where interconnection fees have
been reduced. Competition has forced prices lower, and regulators
have set up mechanisms to ensure that deregulation neither reduced
service in unprofitable areas nor hampered the ability of local
phone companies to make money.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the United States and others have raised questions about
the numbers used in the model that Tokyo relied on in determining
the impact on NTT of cutting interconnection fees.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on who is right, the extra cost to consumers could be
as little as 56 cents a month, or a more unpalatable $3.15 monthly.
If the costs were absorbed wholly by NTT, they could be just $462
million annually _ or as much as $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While would-be competitors bicker over the costs of traditional
fixed-line phone service, Japanese consumers have been voting with
their pocketbooks, switching in droves to cellular phones. The cost
of wireless phones has dropped 78 percent over the last 15 years;
fixed-line phone rates have risen 13 percent in the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The irony, of course, is that the biggest beneficiary of the
switch to cellular has been NTT itself. The company has a 67
percent stake in Japan's largest mobile phone carrier, NTT Mobile
Telecommunications, or NTT DoCoMo, one of the two companies that
NTT spun off as part of its breakup last year.
</P>
<P>
   Demand has been huge for DoCoMo's i-mode phones, which provide
Internet access for about $2.83 a month. That is 96 percent less
than NTT charges for Internet service over fixed phone lines, a
differential that helps explain why only 12 percent of the Japanese
population has such service, compared with one-third or more of
Americans, for example.
</P>
<P>
   So in spite of the woes of its local phone subsidiaries, NTT is
a rich company. The value of its stake in DoCoMo alone is roughly
24.1 trillion yen, or $227.6 billion, and it also holds the
majority of NTT Data, the data transmission company that it spun
off with DoCoMo last year.
</P>
<P>
   If NTT were to sell just 20 percent of its DoCoMo stake _ which
would still leave it in control of the mobile phone operator _ it
would pocket some 2.5 trillion yen, or $23.6 billion, after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Sato, the homegrown critic, likes to daydream about ways the
company could use that windfall to promote competition. ``NTT could
adopt the U.S. proposal immediately using this money,'' Sato said,
referring to the call for a sharp cut in interconnection fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could even afford to create a special incentive program to
encourage early retirement, which would help it to streamline, cut
costs and become more competitive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His argument is simplistic _ liquidating a position of that size
would be tricky _ but it now looks like the ruling party may study
a similar proposal. And Sato has a point: Far from emasculating NTT
by creating a market value for its component parts, the government
gave the company a fat piggy bank it could use to numb the pain of
fundamentally reorienting its business.
</P>
<P>
   NTT is not thinking that way. Rather, it is resentful that it
was forced to sell even small parts of its prized subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that we could have done much better with DoCoMo
and Data if we had full control of them,'' Koide said. ``But NTT
had no choice in the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its foot-dragging, NTT can move at lightening speed to
cut costs when it is threatened. In the last two months, several
companies have announced plans to provide access to the Internet
using a technology called ADSL that ensures higher speed and better
quality than the system NTT offers over so-called ISDN lines.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of the first announcements, NTT said it would lower
the price of Internet access. In some parts of Tokyo, it will drop
its fixed-rate Internet access charge to 2,900 yen, or $27.36, a
month from 8,000 yen, or $75.47. NTT had previously resisted
widespread demands for lower Internet rates, saying they would be
unprofitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we consider unfair is that if NTT can afford to lower
rates that fast in that business, why can't they reduce
interconnection fees?'' TT Net's Tsukamoto said.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors believe NTT will similarly slash prices for phone
service by as much as 50 or 60 percent _ if and when they start to
pose a serious challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the more consumers flock to NTT's cheaper ISDN
service, the harder it will be for the new, higher-speed technology
to make inroads here.
</P>
<P>
   NTT is also starting to introduce the new technology, but given
its investment in ISDN, it cannot afford to have it become too
popular too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another bottleneck the Japanese economy must pass through
to get into the new world,'' Sato said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
