<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SEEKING REVENGE
</HEADLINE>
 GRAPHICS AT BOTTOM)-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS - The memories of Maryland's 16-point victory last
year are vivid and painful, but the lessons are few.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are speculating that it will be the same as
last year, but we're a totally different team,'' Bruins guard Earl
Watson said. ``We're much more well-rounded, and we have more
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Puerto Rico Classic in Nov. '98, the Bruins were neither
well-rounded nor experienced. Baron Davis was out with a knee
injury, they had no established scorers, and it was the third
career game for freshmen Dan Gadzuric, Jerome Moiso, JaRon Rush,
Ray Young and Matt Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins simply weren't ready for the No. 5 Terps and
high-flying guard Steve Francis, whose alley-oop dunks seemed to
come from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   After the 70-54 loss, UCLA coach Steve Lavin roasted his players
for failing to compete - the highest of athletic crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us, and they rubbed it in,'' UCLA forward Rico Hines
said. ``You could tell by their looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen months later, the No. 6 seeded Bruins (20-11) are
talking revenge. They are more equipped to handle the Francis-less
Terps this afternoon in a second-round matchup in the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is very mature,'' Watson said. ``A sign of that is
no one was too up or too down (before the Ball State game). It
seemed like everyone was acting like seniors. Nothing fazes us. The
tournament environment has not affected us.''
</P>
<P>
   Smells like '98: Two years ago, the No. 6 seeded Bruins played
No. 3 Michigan in Atlanta in the second round. The seed are the
same today. What about the outcome?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the name recognition of Maryland is the same today as
Michigan was then,'' UCLA assistant Michael Holton said. ``Everyone
expected they would win, and it's the same with Maryland.''
</P>
<P>
   Of slow starts and fast finishes: Freshman Jason Kapono was
scoreless in the first half against Ball State but had 17 points in
the second. It was the third time during the seven-game winning
streak that Kapono has scored at least 15 points in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   How? He doesn't stop shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't come out and try to force things,'' he said. ``I have
to stay patient and use my teammates. But I'm a shooter. A shooter
has a mindset: if you're missing, you keep shooting; if you're hot,
you definitely keep shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Old friends: Hines faced three Maryland players - forward
Terence Morris, guard Juan Dixon and center Lonny Baxter - during
his high school days at St. John's-Prospect Hall (Md.).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our coach (Stu Vetter) was always trying to recruit Terence,
but he wasn't interested,'' Hines said. ``I'm happy things have
worked out for him. He's cool, he works really hard, and he never
talks a lot of junk. He's just solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Watson had six turnovers Thursday, his highest
total since the South Florida game Dec. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were favored by eight points against Ball State. Dan
Gadzuric's dunk with 0.4 seconds left made the final score 65-57.
</P>
<P>
   Watch for senior Sean Farnham to start again today. The Bruins
are 15-1 with him in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has won 20 games for the 12th consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA vs. MARYLAND
</P>
<P>
   Tipoff: 5:10 p.m. (approx.) in the Metrodome
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Channel 2; KXTA-AM (1150)
</P>
<P>
   Series: UCLA leads 4-2, but Maryland won last year's meeting in
the Puerto Rico Classic 70-54.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA (20-11) update: Bruins have won seven consecutive games,
their longest streak since winning 12 straight in 1997. During the
current streak, they're shooting 42.6 percent from 3-point range.
Coach Steve Lavin, 6-3 in the NCAA Tournament, is seeking his third
Sweet 16 in four years. Bruins made 8 of 18 free throws against
Ball State and are shooting 58.3 percent from the line this season.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland (25-9) update: Terps beat Notre Dame, Illinois,
Kentucky and Duke this season and finished second in the ACC
(behind Duke). They have won 12 of their last 15 games, including a
74-59 victory over Iona in the first round Thursday. Their top
scorers are guard Juan Dixon (18.1 ppg), forward Terence Morris
(15.9 ppg) and center Lonny Baxter (15.4 ppg). They shoot 68.8
percent from the foul line. Opponents are shooting 39.5 percent
from the field.
</P>
<P>
   - Jon Wilner
</P>
<P>
   UCLA-MARYLAND MATCHUPS
</P>
<P>
   Backcourt: Maryland freshman Steve Blake has performed well in
place of departed star Steve Francis. Blake, 6-3, is creative, a
good shooter and outplayed Duke's Jason Williams. Off guard Juan
Dixon, 6-3, is one of the nation's top gunners (36.6 percent from
3-point range) and a first-team ll-ACC pick. Moves well without the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins point guard Earl Watson must play with more control than
he did against Ball State (six turnovers), but that won't be easy
against Maryland's tenacious defense. Billy Knight started
Thursday, but watch for JaRon Rush early and often. Edge: Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Frontcourt: Maryland junior Terence Morris hasn't played like
the first-team All-American many expected, but he's pretty good
(15.7 ppg). His size, 6-9, and quickness make him a difficult
matchup for the Bruins. Center Lonny Baxter (15.5 ppg, 8.7 rpg) is
a first-team ll-ACC pick and will give Dan Gadzuric all he can
handle. Power forward Tahj Holden is a complementary player.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins would be thrilled with another double-double from
Gadzuric. But they need first-half production from Jason Kapono,
who was scoreless for 24 minutes against Ball State, and more
physical play from Jerome Moiso, who was tentative Thursday and
made just 5 of 14 shots. Edge: Even.
</P>
<P>
   Bench: Maryland used a seven-man rotation in its first-round
victory. Guard Drew Nicholas and center Mike Mardesich are solid
players, but neither will turn a game. Forward Danny Miller (8.6
ppg) has started 33 games but didn't play Thursday (sprained ankle)
and is questionable today.
</P>
<P>
   Rush continues to shoot well from 3-point range and had 14
points in 27 minutes against Ball State. Forward Matt Barnes
sparked the second-half surge with deft passing. Rico Hines, Ray
Young and Ryan Bailey will play as needed. Sean Farnham might
start, but he'll be replaced early by Gadzuric. Edge: UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Intangibles: Bruins have won seven straight and are playing with
supreme confidence, much like the '97 team that reached the Elite
Eight. Terps didn't look like a No.3 seed against Iona, but they
have lost just three games since the Super Bowl: at Temple, at
Virginia (overtime) and Duke in the ACC finals. Not bad. Edge:
Even.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching: Maryland's combustible Gary Williams is approaching
his annual tournament fold. Despite good talent, he's never taken
Terps past the Sweet 16. UCLA's staff, like the players, has found
its groove. However, coach Steve Lavin must correct Thursday's
sloppiness for the Bruins to advance. Edge: Slight to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Outcome: Another good matchup for the Bruins in that Maryland is
an up-tempo team. Bottom line: UCLA has more weapons. As long as
the staff does its job, that's the difference. With each game,
these Bruins look more and more like the Elite Eight-bound 1997
team. Edge: UCLA by six.
</P>
<P>
   - Jon Wilner
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
