<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0484 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-VENZUELA18     03-17 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-VENZUELA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unusual home games for Braves' Venezuelan natives
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ So much for meaningless exhibitions. Games
the Braves will play against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays in Venezuela
today and Sunday may mean nothing in the standings, but will mean
everything in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The 25,000 fans packed into University Stadium will be
celebrating the healing of their country and their hero.
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga will play a baseball game in his native
Venezuela having recovering from lymphoma, and first in the past
seven years. He, Ozzie Guillen and Eddie Perez _ all Venezuelans _
will be playing for a crowd that has seen devastation in the deadly
December mudslides that killed thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball couldn't have seen this one coming. But
their efforts to reach out to the Latin American community that has
pumped so much talent into baseball _ giving Venezuela its first
taste of major league baseball in more than 25 years _ couldn't
have come at a better time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My country is one of the most important oil producers in the
world,'' said Alfredo Villasmil, assistant sports editor of the
Ultimas Noticias, one of seven major newspapers in Caracas. ``It's
potentially one of the richest countries, but it's one of the
poorest countries. Now we are in the most horrible catastrophe my
country has suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Galarraga, whom Perez said is revered in Venezuela like
Michael Jordan is in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cannot walk down the street,'' Perez said. ``Everybody
wants to talk to him, everybody wants to touch him.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga grew up in Caracas, the capital, and played for the
most popular team in the Venezuelan winter leagues. He's the
all-time leading home run hitter among Venezuelans who have played
in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   He came back from a miserable 1992 season to become the first
Venezuelan to win a major league batting title in 1993 with the
Rockies. He did it during terrible economic conditions in
Venezuela, when inflation had nearly doubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the face of bad news, he was good news,'' Villasmil said.
``Galarraga with his home runs made us smile. He has gathered all
of us. High class, low class, middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   Villasmil tells a story from 1990 when Galarraga had just
finished playing a winter ball game in Caracas. He was driving in
his Jeep Cherokee when a drunk man stumbled toward his car. He
muttered the words ``picture here.'' Galarraga stopped his he car,
got out, put his arm around the man and broke into one of his
patented smiles for a picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Andres Galarraga,'' Villasmil said. ``He's not a
legend anymore, he's a myth.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen for one, can't wait to see the fans' reaction to
Galarraga. Galarraga said he was nervous, but in a good way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be pretty special, not only for me but for the group,''
Galarraga said. ``I talked to my brother, my mother, everybody
can't wait to see it. For me (it means) a little more after the
cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga, Perez, Guillen and Venezuelan Braves minor leaguer
Fernando Lunar will help deliver 5,000 pounds of supplies _medical
supplies, food, clothing, and bottled water _ that the Braves are
bringing with them to those left homeless in La Guaira, the worst
hit section of the Venezuelan coast. The Devil Rays are making
similar efforts, and Major League Baseball and the players'
association are chipping in $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   For Guillen, it will be familiar ground. He was among the most
active major league players to help those in need, donating money
from his pocket, using his boat to deliver goods to people, and
bringing children who lost their parents in the flooding into an
orphanage that his foundation runs.
</P>
<P>
   He's hoping to have some of those children join the team on the
field for introductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be the only guy who knows how people feel,'' Guillen
said. ``I know what they went through, how much they appreciate
having two teams going here. ... You will see a lot of happy
faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the game sold out in two hours when they went on
sale last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my best friends called me (Wednesday night); he had
lost four tickets in the subway,'' Guillen said. ``He almost
committed suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
