<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0485 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-GUNS-SMITH-ART-2TAKES     03-17 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-SMITH-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER LEGAL SIEGE, GUNMAKER AGREES TO ACCEPT CURBS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Pa., Mo., La., Conn., N.J., Calif., Fla, Ga. Mich.)   (See also GUNS-SMITH-INDUSTRY) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Smith &AMP; Wesson, the nation's oldest and largest
manufacturer of handguns, agreed Friday to accept a wide array of
restrictions on the way it makes, sells and distributes hundreds of
thousands of handguns each year in exchange for ending some
lawsuits that had threatened to bankrupt it.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement represented a major splintering in the powerful
alliance of gunmakers and owners that has thwarted tough gun laws
in Washington and state capitals for years. And it opened a new
avenue for regulating the firearms industry without action from
Congress, where partisan gridlock has stalled even modest
gun-control legislation in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, which was immediately attacked by other
manufacturers Smith &AMP; Wesson will place a second, hidden set of
serial numbers in all its new weapons to make it harder for
criminals to scratch away those identifying marks. The company
promises to sell with each new handgun a small lock that prevents
the trigger from being pulled, something Smith &AMP; Wesson was already
doing. And the agreement requires, within three years, ``smart-gun
technology'' that will allow each of its new handguns to be fired
only by authorized users.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also establishes a ``code of conduct'' for Smith &AMP;
Wesson's authorized dealers and distributors that would prohibit
them _ under threat of losing their franchises _ from selling guns
at gun shows unless the buyers have passed background checks. That
issue is the major sticking point on legislation now stalled in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And in a provision intended to discourage illegal gun
trafficking, people who buy more than one gun from a Smith &AMP; Wesson
dealer will be allowed to take home just one firearm on the day of
the sale, and will have to return 14 days later to claim the rest.
</P>
<P>
   But the broader impact of the agreement will depend heavily on
whether other major manufacturers follow Smith &AMP; Wesson, which
produces roughly one-tenth of the 2.5 million handguns sold
nationwide each year. Friday, the president of the largest trade
association for gunmakers issued a statement fiercely denouncing
one of his most influential members for breaking ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident that no other major manufacturers will desert
this coordinated effort in favor of their own individual deal,''
said Robert Delfay of the National Shooting Sports Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some gun-control advocates raised sharp questions
about the significance of the pact, noting that Smith &AMP; Wesson is
already shipping trigger locks with its hand guns and is already
well on its way to developing smart-gun technology. And they
asserted that the agreement, which exempts weapons sold to
law-enforcement agencies or the military, would be next to
impossible to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than having a Smith &AMP; Wesson person posted in every gun
dealership in America, I don't know how they do it,'' said Kristen
Rand, senior council at the Violence Policy Center in Washington,
which advocates strict gun-control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which was negotiated with the help of the Clinton
administration, settled litigation by 15 cities that had sought to
collect damages from Smith &AMP; Wesson for gun violence. In addition,
the administration and the attorney generals of New York state and
Connecticut signed the deal, agreeing not to bring suits against
the company. The agreement does not end litigation by the cities
against other gunmakers.
</P>
<P>
   But 15 other cities and counties that had filed similar suits
had not signed onto the agreement by the end of the day. And while
several of those were expected to join the agreement soon, several
more _ including Chicago, whose mayor, Richard M. Daley, is a
staunch ally of Clinton _ were expected to pursue their suits
against Smith &AMP; Wesson and other manufacturers because the
agreement did not include monetary damages to compensate cities for
the law-enforcement and health-care costs associated with gun
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies are in the business of making money,'' said
Jennifer Hoyle, a spokeswoman for the Chicago city attorney's
office, whose suit seeks $433 million in damages from the gun
industry. ``Asking for serious financial damages sends a serious
message to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits against the gun industry were patterned after those
brought by cities and states against the tobacco industry. But,
unlike the tobacco industry, which had deep financial pockets and
which was dominated by a handful of big publicly-traded companies,
the gun industry is small and fragmented. There are dozens of small
privately-held gunmakers and the entire industry's revenues total
just around $1.5 billion, making it difficult for plaintiffs to
seek large financial settlements. Already, the threat of litigation
has caused one leading gunmaker, Colt's Manufacturing Co., to stop
making guns for retail sale.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference at the White House, Clinton hailed the
agreement as ``The very first time a gun manufacturer has committed
to fundamentally change the way guns are designed, distributed and
marketed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It says that gunmakers can _ and will _ share in the
responsibility to keep their products out of the wrong hands,''
Clinton said. ``And it says that gunmakers can _ and will _ make
their guns much safer without infringing on anyone's rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rand of the Violence Policy Center said that the agreement
contained loopholes that would allow Smith &AMP; Wesson to skirt the
smart-gun technology requirement by marketing its handguns as
collector's items.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disturbing to us that a gun manufacturer gets credit
for doing what they are already doing and basically obeying the
law,'' Rand said. ``To settle these lawsuits that have put a lot of
pressure on the industry and that had the potential of leading to
real regulations, it was a tremendous step backward.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   David Kairys, a professor of constitutional law at Temple
University who is a consultant for many of the litigants, said he
was disappointed that the agreement did not require Smith &AMP; Wesson
to turn over internal industry documents that might have shed light
on the gun industry's more avaricious marketing techniques.
</P>
<P>
   But Kairys said the agreement was important because it
represented a major crack in a once monolithic industry position
that gun manufacturers had no responsibility for the violence
caused by guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view it as generally positive, because this represents a
break with the past'' Kairys said. ``Smith &AMP; Wesson is the biggest
manufacturer and they are making some changes. They are at least
recognizing that what they do in marketing and distribution have an
effect on crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they thought that the
Smith &AMP; Wesson deal would have a domino affect on the industry,
just as the decision by the Liggett Group, a cigarette maker, to
settle a class-action lawsuit in 1996 pressured other tobacco
companies to reach settlements.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which came together in just the past two days,
was announced by Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and Housing
Secretary Andrew Cuomo, whose departments helped in the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The cities and counties that signed the agreement included New
Orleans, which brought the first suit, St. Louis, Bridgeport,
Conn., Newark, N.J., Los Angeles, San Francisco, Miami-Dade County,
Atlanta and Detroit. The communities that refused to join the
agreement include, in addition to Chicago, Camden County, N.J., and
Wayne County, Mich.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   During Friday's news conference, Cuomo and the other officials
went out of their way to praise Smith &AMP; Wesson's chief executive,
Ed Schulz, for signing the agreement in the face of intense
opposition from other gunmakers. Smith &AMP; Wesson has faced boycotts
from gun-owners groups in the past for voluntarily accepting gun
restrictions, and Cuomo said there were concerns that the company
would face similar repercussions this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``To boycott a company for responsible corporate citizenship and
a prudent business judgment to end a litigation risk would be
absurd,'' he said. ``I also believe there will be a flip side,
which is, educated consumers will say this is a responsible company
worth dealing dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   One possible method of rewarding Smith &AMP; Wesson was raised by
New York Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, who has begun urging
governors and big-city majors to buy guns solely from companies
that accept the code of conduct outlined in Friday's agreement.
</P>
<P>
   For the past week, President Clinton has been embroiled in a
vicious battle of words with Wayne LaPierre, the executive vice
president for the National Rifle Association. Clinton has hammered
the group for blocking gun-control legislation, while LaPierre has
accused the president of responsibility for the death of a college
basketball coach who was killed with an illegally acquired gun.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Cuomo suggested that the heated oratory had helped
create a climate that made it easier to prod Smith &AMP; Wesson into an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put the tragedies that we have seen in recent weeks
together with the gridlock in Washington and then the NRA's
hyperbole and rhetoric, the only positive outcome was going to be
through negotiations,'' Cuomo said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the NRA said the group would have no comment
Friday on the agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
