<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0488 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GA-CHAPLAIN-FIGHT18-C     03-17 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-CHAPLAIN-FIGHT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Atlanta minister at center of House flap
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Rev. Charles Wright is at the center of an
unprecedented political feud over his appointment to become House
chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has nothing to do with prayer and everything to do
with politics.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert's selection of Wright over a
Catholic priest who had more votes on a bipartisan selection
committee has unleashed a torrent of criticism of the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   There was been only one Catholic chaplain in the 211-year
history of the House, and none in modern times.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Republican lawmakers and Democrats want to know why the
Rev. Timothy O'Brien _ a Catholic priest and professor at Marquette
University who had the most support on the bipartisan panel _ was
passed over in favor of someone who finished lower on the finalist
list.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over the House chaplain continues amid other charges
of anti-Catholicism in the Republican Party. George W. Bush drew
criticism last month for speaking at Bob Jones University, a
conservative Protestant college in South Carolina known for its
hostility toward the Catholic Church. Bush later apologized for not
criticizing the anti-Catholic policy during his visit.
</P>
<P>
   Those two episodes are now testing the ties between the
Republican Party's Catholic and evangelical Christian branches.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Democrats are exploiting the situation for all
that it's worth.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the Republicans are charging that the Democrats are
unfairly portraying the GOP as anti-Catholic in an attempt to win
back Catholic votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a desperate Democratic Party that is dividing people
based on religion,'' said Ralph Reed, former head of the Christian
Coalition and now a political consultant at Atlanta-based Century
Strategies.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party has more Catholics than it has ever had,
Reed said. To say that the GOP is anti-Catholic is disingenuous at
best.
</P>
<P>
   But the controversy has practically paralyzed House Republican
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has indefinitely postponed the House vote to confirm
Wright out of concern that it would split his own caucus. Such a
split would surely help Democrats in the upcoming fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speaker has set up a bipartisan process and he wants
bipartisan results,'' said John Feehery, spokesperson for Hastert.
``This is what happens when you try to do good deeds in the House
of Representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Waxman (D-Calif.), a member of the selection
committee, said the GOP has only the GOP to blame for the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The issue erupted only after Hastert and Majority Leader Dick
Armey (R-Texas) ignored the panel's recommendation, Waxman said.
Until that point, the committee had worked in an unusually
bipartisan fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican leadership has a big problem with the chaplain
issue and it's all their own making,'' Waxman said. ``They chose
the guy who barely made the list. That's no one else's fault but
their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Wright and O'Brien declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   The vote tallies from the committee show that Wright had almost
no support among the nine Democrats on the selection panel. By
comparison, O'Brien had a majority of Democrats and Republicans
favoring his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert and Armey have both defended their choice, saying when
they interviewed the final three candidates they were unaware of
the vote tallies. They say they simply selected the person who
would do the best job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the truth is the truth,'' Feehery said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats and Republicans say they find that a little hard
to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Even the conservative Catholic League for Religious and Civil
Rights smells a ``fix.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's painfully apparent that the House leadership has made a
gigantic mess over this,'' said Patrick Scully, director of
communications for the league's 350,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an odor of anti-Catholicism here and there is
speculation that Wright was chosen to placate the evangelical
Christian groups in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Scully said the Republican leadership was told that O'Brien had
the most support on the selection panel. ``For the speaker and the
majority leader to maintain they didn't know is dishonest,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), a Methodist who attended Georgetown
University Law School, a Catholic institution, said this boils down
to the Democrats blowing the issue up for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never in the history of the House has one party chosen to make
the chaplain a partisan issue,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert went out of his way to involve the Democrats in the
selection process, Barr said. ``I'm not sure how much lower
(Democrats) could sink.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all Republicans see it in the same light. Republicans
from Catholic-heavy districts are concerned about how the
controversy will play out at home.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent meeting between Hastert and about 35 House
Republican Catholics, the issue was ``huge,'' said Rep. Greg Ganske
(R-Iowa), who attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this isn't handled right, it could prove the difference in
marginal districts,'' Ganske said.
</P>
<P>
   Ganske believes Wright should withdraw from the process. He said
the post should become a rotating job filled with people from all
faiths.
</P>
<P>
   Ganske does not think Hastert and Armey are anti-Catholic. He
thinks they merely ``selected the same old, same old,'' namely a
Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
