<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0493 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ST-PATRICKS-PARADE-AR     03-17 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ST-PATRICKS-PARADE-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUILIANI AND CLINTON BRING SENATE RACE TO ST. PATRICK'S DAY
PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT4, NYT5, NYT22 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There have been years when Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had
the political stage of the St. Patrick's Day parade in New York
City virtually to himself. Not Friday. For the first time, Giuliani
had to share Fifth Avenue with the woman who has inserted herself
into his political life, Hillary Rodham Clinton _ but who was booed
more than cheered as she strode up the center of Manhattan in a
mid-March snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton waved happily to the crowds and announced shortly
before the bagpipes started that ``it is just a great pleasure to
be here as a New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   To which the mayor almost immediately retorted: `Oh my goodness!
That's interesting. That's interesting! I hope she knows the way. I
hope she doesn't get lost on one of the side streets.''
</P>
<P>
   The St. Patrick's Day parade has always been a must stop for
candidates on New York's political circuit, but Friday it turned
into the Rudy and Hillary show as the two contenders for the U.S.
Senate marched in separate contingents on a raw day that turned the
knees of bare-legged majorettes bright red. They also held dueling
news conferences on Fifth Avenue, one block and 15 minutes apart,
and sat several pews apart in St. Patrick's Cathedral at the same
Mass, without the ailing Cardinal John O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal's absence dampened the parade _ ``I felt terrible
about the cardinal not being there,'' the mayor said _ as did
weather that reduced the crowd in kilts, Irish knit sweaters and
green hair to only one or two deep as the procession reached 86th
Street, the end of the route. But the stalwarts were there, among
them Mary Clifford, a 59-year-old statistical analyst at IBM, who
has been standing on the same corner of Fifth Avenue and 86th
Street on St. Patrick's Day for the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I used to watch the parade downtown near 59th Street,
there were too many drunks, so I came up here and I've been
standing here ever since,'' said Clifford, of Little Falls, N.J.
``Every year it's special because being Irish is more than green
beer and green bagels; it's this parade. The parade is a
manifestation of our pride in our heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the two Senate candidates provided a new focus this year,
even though they never got close to each other. But they did speak
through sound bites relayed by reporters in the moving scrimmages
following them up Fifth Avenue. ``Maybe I can show her the way to
Chappaqua,'' Giuliani cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's press contingent was bigger than the mayor's, but so
were her jeers. Many came from freezing watchers who shouted out
for her to ``Go home!'' even though a number were themselves not
from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go back to Arkansas!'' yelled Patrick Bermingham, a cemetery
groundskeeper from North Arlington, N.J., as Clinton clambered into
her waiting black van at the end of the parade route at 86th Street
and Madison Avenue. Outside the Plaza Hotel, a small group of gay
protesters shouted ``Shame! Shame!'' as Clinton passed, angry at
her participation in a parade that bars an organization of gay and
lesbian Irish-Americans from marching under their own banner.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, dressed in a black raincoat and a sea-green scarf at
her neck, smiled cheerfully back as supporters marching with her
yelled out ``We love Hillary!'' to drown out the jeers.
</P>
<P>
   One of those with the first lady was former Mayor Edward I.
Koch, who pronounced the Irish ``a lovely, gracious and supportive
people,'' said that the boos ``test her mettle'' and called
Giuliani ``bush league'' and ``a doofus'' for making fun of the
first lady's ability to navigate New York's streets. Others in
Clinton's entourage included a large group of Secret Service agents
_ more than the usual _ who constantly looked up at the spectators
watching from the buildings lining one of New York's busiest
streets.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of Irish-Americans and Irish fans clearly belonged to
the mayor, although many of them were also from out of town. ``Oh
my God!'' said a thrilled Amy Converse, a 27-year-old Montessori
teacher from West Palm Beach, Fla., who was standing at 47th Street
and Fifth Avenue when the mayor ran over to greet people on the
sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love what he's done for the city,'' Converse added. ``It's
my first time here, and I feel very safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, dressed in a green vest, green tie and green baseball
cap, began marching near the start of the parade around 11 a.m.
with a contingent of New York City Police officers, whom he
vigorously defended after another police shooting of an unarmed
black man in Manhattan early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to give the police a break,'' the mayor said
to reporters at his news briefing on Fifth Avenue at 44th Street,
before the parade. ``These are men and women that are out there
protecting us.'' He added, ``Let's give them at least the benefit
that most of you usually give common criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spoke minutes later at her own news conference on
Fifth Avenue at 43rd Street, was more measured. ``I would think all
of us are concerned about another police shooting, and we'll wait
to see the investigation and results of that investigation,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended her participation in a parade that excludes the
gay organization. ``When you're in public life, you have to balance
a lot of different values, and today we're marching on behalf of
Irish-Americans and in favor of the peace process,'' she said. But
she also said that ``I would hope that this parade would become
inclusive'' and ``I will certainly speak out for that.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton finished marching, she went back to the White
House for a reception with Irish leaders, including Prime Minister
Bertie Ahern and Gerry Adams, the president of Sinn Fein, who were
in Washington for Northern Ireland peace settlement talks. When
Giuliani finished marching, he remarched the route, as he usually
does, three more times, with contingents from the Fire Department,
the sanitation workers and his alma mater, Manhattan College.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
