<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSAIR-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'98 SWISSAIR CRASH INQUIRY SEES COCKPIT MAP LIGHT AS SPARK SOURCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Canadian investigators looking into the deadly
crash of Swissair 111 in 1998 say a pilot's map light, built into
the cockpit ceiling, may be a source of ignition in that model
airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing responded by urging airlines flying that model to make
frequent checks until the light can be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration is considering whether to
make that procedure mandatory. Boeing also told the airlines to
install fire-resistant tape to protect insulation.
</P>
<P>
   The point is moot for Canadian regulators because there are no
planes of that model, the MD-11, registered in that country. They
found the problem by inspecting MD-11s outside Canada that were
being stripped down for maintenance. The MD-11s were made by
McDonnell Douglas, which Boeing has acquired.
</P>
<P>
   But Canadian officials say they are still far from determining
the cause of the crash, which killed 129 people off Nova Scotia.
``We haven't ruled out anything, yet,'' Jim Harris, a spokesman for
Canada's Transportation Safety Board said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He said following the discovery of the problem, investigators in
a military base began sorting through boxes of fractured debris to
see if they could find the map light from the plane that crashed.
</P>
<P>
   In the months since the crash, the Transportation Safety Board's
most important recommendation has been to reduce the amount of
material on board that can fuel a fire, by replacing the
insulation. It has also called for looking into another potential
cause of fire, wiring near the main cabin door, which it said could
be damaged and provide a spark.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the crash, the crew reported smoke in the
cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   Examinations of about a dozen MD-11s still in service have found
various problems with the lights, including heat damage of the
adjacent insulation. The Transportation Safety Board has
recommended replacing the insulation, and some of the damage from
map lights was found by airlines doing that work.
</P>
<P>
   The lights use halogen bulbs, which operate at hotter
temperatures than standard incandescents.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Boeing, Laurie Gunter, said that the lights
are used on other planes and elsewhere on the MD-11, but that the
damage has only been observed in the captain's and first officer's
map lights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0495 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-IRAN-U.S.-1STLD-WRITE     03-17 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MAKES OVERTURE TO IRAN, LIFTING BAN ON SOME IMPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to expand and rewrite throughout, e.g, Tehran reaction,
congressional reaction, what Albright did NOT say, etc.; expands to
2 takes; note byline change)  
(HLW) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright ended a
narrow slice of America's economic sanctions against Iran on
Friday, and declared a commitment to take extensive steps toward
ending two decades of hostility ``if Iran indicates a desire and
commitment to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Her comments describing a map for normalizing economic ties came
in a speech on Friday that Clinton administration officials
described as their most explicit overture to the moderates who
triumphed in Iran's parliamentary elections last month.
</P>
<P>
   Without specifying them, Albright held out the prospect of
ending such sanctions as the bans on American investment in Iran's
oil industry and the blocking of large loans to Tehran by the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But she made no mention of a resumption of full diplomatic
relations.
</P>
<P>
   In Tehran, the Iranian government issued a muted but moderately
positive response.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also acknowledged _ without apologizing _ a variety of
American errors in past dealings with Iran, including Washington's
support of the 1953 coup that restored Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi
to power, and of Iraq during its war with Iran in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Albright made clear that forces in Iran that she
said support terrorism and try to obtain nuclear weapons technology
would have to loosen their hold on the security apparatus before
there would be a deeper removal of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions ended on Friday are chiefly symbolic, and aimed at
small businesses. The United States will end restrictions on
Iranian-made carpets _ a law that was widely flouted anyway _ and
reduce prohibitive tariffs on pistachios and caviar. Those areas
were chosen, Albright said, ``to show the millions of Iranian
craftsmen, farmers and fishermen who work in these industries, and
the Iranian people as a whole, that the United States bears them no
ill will.''
</P>
<P>
   But she acknowledged that it would take more than pistachio
diplomacy to remove what President Mohammad Khatami _ whose
moderation she praised at some length _ calls the ``wall of
mistrust.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To date, the political developments in Iran have not caused
its military to cease its determined effort to acquire the
technology, materials and assistance needed to develop nuclear
weapons,'' she said. Nor have the intelligence services chosen ``to
get out of the terrorism business,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until these policies change,'' she continued, ``fully normal
ties between our governments will not be possible and our principal
sanctions will remain.''
</P>
<P>
   Under American law, for instance, Washington cannot support
loans for Iran through the IMF or the World Bank until Iran is
removed from the State Department's terrorism list.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's speech received mixed reviews in Congress, just as
small overtures toward Cuba and North Korea have in recent months.
Sen. Connie Mack of Florida, a Republican, called the
administration's move ``unprincipled'' and said ``American victims
of terrorism deserve justice, not pistachios and caviar.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Pat Roberts, a Republican who represents the farm state
of Kansas, said: ``A failed U.S. sanctions policy has forced Iran
to purchase a substantial amount of commodities from our
competitors.'' He urged a far greater removal of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department took some unusual steps to amplify its
message in Iran. It faxed advance copies of Albright's speech to
the pro-reform newspapers that have blossomed in Tehran, to enable
them to print the text in their Saturday issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian government was also briefed in advance, and
afterward the Foreign Ministry spokesman, Hamid Reza Asefi, said:
``We welcome the ability to export Iranian foodstuff and carpets
and see it as positive,'' according to a report from the country's
official news agency, IRNA.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Washington, however, Hadi Nejad Hosseinian, Iran's
representative to the United Nations, said that while his country
would find a way to reciprocate for Albright's gesture, ``these
steps, as important as they may be, are insufficient'' to bring
about official talks between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has periodically made modest moves to reach
out to moderates in Iran, but Khatami has been locked in a struggle
with hardliners who appear to control the security apparatus, and
the gestures have not borne fruit.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Albright's effort to convey a new openness to Iran, without
offering many concrete concessions, came after what senior
officials said was a long debate in the State Department and the
National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone recognized that there had been a massive change in
the internal dynamics in Iran,'' one official said, ``but good as
the changes have been internally, they have not affected those with
the levers of power on the issues of greatest importance to us _
terrorism and weapons of mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Another element of that debate, officials said, centered on how
Albright should word her description of America's troubled
encounters with Iran throughout the Cold War. She chose, in the
end, to acknowledge the facts and hint at American wrongdoing or
errors of judgment, but to neither apologize nor explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1953, the United States played a significant role in
orchestrating the overthrow of Iran's popular prime minister,
Mohammad Mossadegh,'' she told the audience, touching briefly and
lightly on what almost everyone in her audience of
Iranian-Americans knew as Operation Ajax, the Central Intelligence
Agency's first major success in overthrowing a foreign government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Eisenhower administration believed its actions were
justified for strategic reasons,'' she continued. ``But the coup
was clearly a setback for Iran's political development. And it is
easy to see now why many Iranians continue to resent this
intervention by America in their internal affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the overthrow, the Mossadegh government had acted to
legalize the Iranian Communist Party, and had also nationalized the
Anglo-Iranian Oil Co.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to go ahead with the coup was made by Allen Dulles,
the first head of the postwar CIA, and his brother, John Foster
Dulles, the secretary of state at the time. And it was executed
chiefly by Kermit Roosevelt, a grandson of Theodore Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   While Friday's reference to those events fell far short of an
apology, it appears to be the closest to one any senior American
official has publicly offered.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also briefly acknowledged that the shah, installed
after the coup, ``brutally repressed political dissent.'' And she
added, with a reference to the president of Iraq, that ``aspects of
U.S. policy toward Iraq during its conflict with Iran appear now to
have been regrettably shortsighted, especially in light of our
subsequent experiences with Saddam Hussein.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Among those in the audience Friday was Robert C. McFarlane, the
national security adviser under President Reagan, who made a secret
trip to Iran in 1986 bearing a key-shaped cake and a Bible in a
failed effort to get Iran to use its influence to win the release
of hostages held in Lebanon by Iranian-backed Shiites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better late than never,'' McFarlane said of Friday's
initiative. ``This is not an administration known for
risk-taking.'' He said he assumed that Iran must have made ``some
private assurances'' to the United States about cutting off support
for terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues left deliberately vague in the speech was how
to handle financial disputes between the countries that date back
to the taking of American hostages in Tehran in 1979. At the time,
Iranian assets in the United States were frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a tribunal set up at The Hague has resolved a number
of disputes. But others remain, such as the issue of reimbursing
Iran for American military equipment that was never delivered, and
the disposition of diplomatic properties in the United States. Iran
puts the value of what it terms ``frozen assets'' _ the United
States does not use that phrase _ at upwards of $10 billion, while
Washington says the figure is in the hundreds of millions of
dollars.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Resolving those disputes would have far less economic impact on
Iran than a lifting of the sanctions on oil and development aid.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's Caspian Sea oil policy has been directed at
preventing any pipeline from traveling through Iranian territory.
</P>
<P>
   The prohibition on American investment and technology in Iran's
oil industry has meant European countries have a competitive edge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
