<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AOL-EUROPE-NYT &LR;      03-17 0293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL TO BUY OUT BERTELSMANN IN THEIR JOINT VENTURES IN EUROPE,
AUSTRALIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ America Online Inc. will purchase Bertelsmann AG's 50
percent stake in their joint ventures AOL Europe and AOL Australia
for more than $8 billion, the companies said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move had been expected ever since AOL reached a deal to
acquire Time Warner Inc. in January for $165 billion. The deal
would put the combined companies in direct competition with
Bertelsmann, a leading global media conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann will continue a relationship with AOL through a
four-year agreement that makes the German media company a preferred
content provider for AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they were not surprised by the Bertelsmann sale
because the AOL-Time Warner deal had put the German company in an
awkward position. After the merger was announced in January, Thomas
Middelhoff, chairman of Bertelsmann, stepped down from the board of
AOL, saying ``you can't have a competitor sitting on the board.''
</P>
<P>
   However, in a conference call with reporters, Stephen M. Case,
chief executive of AOL, said the Time Warner merger was not the
reason for Friday's deal. ``The discussions happened well before we
had serious discussions with Time Warner,'' he said. Case also said
the rationale for buying out Bertelsmann's stake in the joint
ventures was simply strategic. ``Guiding people on the Internet is
our core business. We really need maximum flexibility to do this
around the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Bertelsmann, a closely held company controlled by the family
of Reinhard Mohn, the sale will provide a cash infusion that it can
use to expand its other Internet holdings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
