<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0499 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DONUTS-DONUTS_SFCHRON     03-17 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONUTS-DONUTS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Doughnuts Are on Dessert Menus All Over the Place  &HT;     By Sylvia Rubin 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The last time Joyce Thomas ate a doughnut was four years ago. On
Thursday night at Gordon's House of Fine Eats in San Francisco, she
had another.
<P>
   ``Doughnuts are something you eat by yourself and you don't
admit it to anyone,'' said Thomas, who was celebrating her birthday
at the restaurant. ``It's pretty gutsy to put them on a dessert
menu. I think it's fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of the strip malls and into some of the finest dining
establishments in the country, the lowly doughnut has evolved into
the coolest dessert around.
</P>
<P>
   Hot, yeasty doughnuts dusted in cinnamon and sugar have been
served at the exalted French Laundry in Yountville since opening
day four years ago _ so don't even think about calling them trendy,
said chef Thomas Keller. ``I hate that word.''
</P>
<P>
   Too late. The treats are on dessert menus all over the place,
including Le Cirque 2000 in New York, don't you know, and at least
a half-dozen upscale restaurants in the Bay Area. Last Thursday,
Peter Jennings and his crew were at Spago in Palo Alto to cover the
stylishness of it all.
</P>
<P>
   The trend may have had its start in the early '90s after Keller,
considered one of the best chefs in the country, created a
cinnamon-sugar doughnut dessert for a prestigious James Beard
dinner. But credit ultimately must go to the Krispy Kreme doughnut
chain. On the rebound from enormous debt, the Winston-Salem, N.C.
company opened a shop in downtown Manhattan in 1996 that quickly
became a shrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about Krispy Kremes,'' Keller said, ``is that
when they are warm, it's like eating cream. That richness in your
mouth. The pure richness.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, stop. ``They melt in your mouth. I can eat two or three in a
heartbeat.'' More about arteries later.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've worked hard all day, it's nice to sit down with
something that reminds you of your mom and when life was easier,''
said pastry chef Anna Niederholzer of Gordon's, who created a
heaping plate of six doughnut varieties ($9). The Black Cat in San
Francisco serves ping pong ball-sized doughnut holes covered in
powdered sugar with a hint of orange ($6).
</P>
<P>
   At Gordon's the other night, Monica Cardanini-Callahan, there
with her mother, Linda, pulled apart the sticky and sugary
Pennsylvania funnel cake and licked her fingers. ``You can call
them doughnuts, but these are not doughnuts,'' Cardanini-Callahan
said. ``They're not Winchell's, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hands-on eating,'' said Kelly Slaven, who was at Gordon's
with three friends. ``We've all been so health conscious lately.
We're done with healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, eat a couple. A month. That's nutritionist Carol
Potter's recommendation, a woman who apparently rarely takes leave
of her senses. ``Pay attention to good nutrition, but you don't
need to be vehement about it,'' said Potter, the director of
nutritional services at the University of California at San
Francisco. ``Lighten up. Enjoy life a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Every culture has its version of fried dough, said Jacques
Torres, the pastry chef at Le Cirque 2000 in New York. His version
is based on the Italian bombolini. ``I sent another pastry chef to
Italy to take a look at how they are made, and now we make them
here the way they are made in Italy.'' His fried brioche doughnuts
are filled with a bit of raspberry or apricot jelly and served with
whipped pastry cream and kirsch ($10). They are served piping hot,
with a drizzle of zabaglione. Torres put them on the menu four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Spago's doughnuts, available as a special dessert item for a
little over a year, are also made of fried brioche and filled with
white chocolate mascarpone, rolled in vanilla sugar and served with
strawberries sauteed in Grand Marnier with candied orange ice cream
on the side ($8.50).
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fun and whimsical,'' said Spago's pastry chef
Christine Law.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0500 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-KRISPY-KRISPY_SFCHRON     03-17 1490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KRISPY-KRISPY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Krispy Kreme Plant Opening in Bay Area  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Bobbling along in a lake of hot oil, a platoon of half-cooked
doughnuts makes the rounds of the Krispy Kreme doughnut machine.
<P>
   Each day, in rows of six, hundreds of thousands of doughnuts
spend exactly two minutes in the fryer, then undergo a dousing of
liquid sugar glaze.
</P>
<P>
   The result: 1.5-ounce rings of oil, sugar and flour that have
appeared in more than 80 movies and television shows, from Rosie
O'Donnell to ``Primary Colors,'' and attracted a cult following
hundreds of miles from their Southern roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the best little glazed doughnuts I've ever had in my
life,'' said San Francisco resident Venetia Washington. ``Whenever
I visit my family in Alabama, I take an extra trunk to bring back
Krispy Kremes.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting next week, Washington will be able to get her fix
closer to home. The Bay Area's first Krispy Kreme shop opens
Tuesday in the Union Landing Shopping Center, across from an
Albertson's supermarket. Mountain View and Sacramento locations are
slated to open this summer, and the company is scouting for sites
in San Francisco, the East Bay and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   While not every doughnut lover warms up to Krispy Kremes, dozens
of fans are expected to be in line at 5 a.m. to get the first Hot
Original Glazed rings out of the Union City fryer.
</P>
<P>
   Existing Bay Area doughnut shops, meanwhile, are wondering
exactly how much of a bite Krispy Kreme will take out of the local
doughnut, er, pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just a small family business,'' said Rashpal Dhillon,
manager of Dee's Bakery &AMP; Doughnut, an 11-year-old shop located
about a mile from the Krispy Kreme.
</P>
<P>
   Dee's can't afford the staff to operate its fryer all day and
serve doughnuts warm, Dhillon said. ``Time will tell'' what will
happen when the Krispy Kreme opens, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Krispy Kreme Doughnuts Inc., founded in Winston-Salem, N.C., in
the 1930s, sells a hefty dollop of nostalgia with its pastries.
</P>
<P>
   Black-and-white photographs of early Krispy Kreme shops decorate
each store. Orange neon signs reading ``Hot Doughnuts Now'' glow
from the windows, and the company loves to tout the ``secret
recipe'' behind its signature Hot Original Glazed rings that Krispy
Kreme founder Vernon Rudolph bought from a French chef in New
Orleans in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   But Krispy Kreme is no mom-and-pop shop. The 144-store chain,
which generated revenues of $220 million in 1999, expects to net
$52 million in an initial public offering next month, which will
help grease its wheels of growth.
</P>
<P>
   Krispy Kreme (ticker: KREM) is still in its ``infancy,''
according to papers filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission. Its goals are ambitious: It hopes to become ``the
recognized leader in every market we enter.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the dough from the IPO will be invested in franchise
joint ventures like the one launching in the Bay Area, which
eventually is expected to open about 25 stores.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Krispy Kreme's advantages, restaurant experts don't
expect the chain to dunk the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not a doughnut shop, they're a cult,'' said Ron Paul,
a consultant with Technomic Inc., a Chicago firm.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the chain's customers drive miles specifically for
Krispy Kremes. To maintain an aura of specialness, the company
keeps a 10-mile cushion between stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're going to upset the competitive balance
in new markets,'' said Paul. ``They're still such a small player in
the scheme of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington, a customer service representative for the Internal
Revenue Service, is a good example of the Krispy-Kreme-or-nothing
customer. ``I don't eat doughnuts now because there are no good
doughnuts around here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While most doughnuts are cakey and thick, Krispy Kreme's
yeast-raised rings ``are light and small, almost like a stick of
butter melting in your mouth,'' said Washington.
</P>
<P>
   (According to the Chronicle mail scale, a Krispy Kreme glazed
ring's 1.5 ounces compares to 2.4 ounces for its counterpart from a
Union City Yum Yum Doughnut. Each Hot Original Glazed contains 170
calories and 10 grams of fat, Krispy Kreme says.)
</P>
<P>
   Washington plans to trek from San Francisco to Union City once
or twice a week for Krispy Kremes. ``That's just a hop, skip and a
jump on the San Mateo Bridge, not far at all to travel for
something good,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Allison Wallach, doughnut category manager for industry-leader
Dunkin' Donuts, said Krispy Kreme's entry into new markets ``has
helped our business. Because of the PR they put behind a new store
opening, it brings awareness to doughnuts in general.''
</P>
<P>
   The 3,600 Dunkin' Donuts stores have a whopping 77 percent _ and
growing _ market share in the United States, .S.,  &LR; according to
Technomic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard of one instance where somebody's closed''
because of a Krispy Kreme moving in, said Brad Bruckman, Krispy
Kreme's Northern California franchisee. ``We'd rather increase the
segment and get people eating more doughnuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales at doughnut specialty stores are rising fast _ 8.5 percent
annually, according to market researcher NPD Group. That should
leave plenty of room for new stores. Krispy Kreme, which operates
in 27 states, accounted for a tiny 3.7 percent of doughnut shop
sales in 1998, according to Technomic.
</P>
<P>
   While Krispy Kreme expands, its growth plans are relatively
modest. The company plans 22 new stores nationwide this year, and
another 100 or so over the next three years, according to the SEC
filing.
</P>
<P>
   That would bring Krispy Kreme's total to 260, the approximate
current size of Orange County's Winchell's Donut Houses.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its long heritage, Krispy Kreme is a company in
transition, and it has suffered from recent missteps.
</P>
<P>
   The doughnut-maker posted a net loss of $3 million in 1998 due
to restructuring costs and the closure of several experimental
``double drive-through'' locations. It has earmarked $30 million
from its IPO to pay off debt.
</P>
<P>
   While Krispy Kreme's sales are growing fast _ revenues rose 22
percent in 1999 _ its margins remain thin. Last year's earnings of
$6 million yielded a shallow net margin of just 2.7 percent of
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-1990s, Krispy Kreme stores were more like
wholesale bakeries than sit-down restaurants. In fact, most Krispy
Kreme stores sell doughnuts to grocery stores and other retailers,
something the Northern California stores plan to do eventually.
</P>
<P>
   New stores are designed as ``doughnut theaters'' where customers
can watch their crullers being made.
</P>
<P>
   That means stores like the one in Union City remain unproven,
noted Neil Stern, a restaurant consultant with McMillan/Doolittle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly some uncertainty'' about the company's
future, Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   A Krispy Kreme spokeswoman declined comment, citing legal
restrictions related to the impending IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Stern says Krispy Kreme's prospects look good. Its daily
sales per store are about $54,000, which is about 50 percent more
than a McDonald's and many multiples higher than the average
doughnut shop, said Stern. ``That's huge, that's unbelievable,
that's an amazing amount of doughnuts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Krispy Kreme can maintain similar volumes as it expands,
``they should see net margins of 6 to 8 percent, which would make
them the best in the fast-food industry,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   The Union City store will be open 24 hours a day, seven days a
week, and will pump out an extraordinary 650,000 doughnuts daily,
said Bruckman. About 60 percent will be glazed rings while the
remainder will be divided among 14 other varieties.
</P>
<P>
   A Mountain View store is slated to open in July and a Sacramento
location in August.
</P>
<P>
   Bruckman, who is a minority investor in the local franchise
while Krispy Kreme is the majority partner, has been scouting for
sites in San Francisco. But restrictions on drive-through windows
have made it difficult, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The only likely area is in the southern part of the city where
Highway 101 connects with Interstate 280 and Bayshore Boulevard, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone is excited about Krispy Kreme's Bay Area
debut.
</P>
<P>
   Yountville resident Dan Goldberg, a fan of cakey doughnuts and
editor of a food newsletter, described Hot Original Glazed rings as
``a lot of grease with very little substance. It's not a serious
doughnut experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The current issue of Gourmet magazine is no more generous,
referring to ``incomprehensibly overpraised'' Krispy Kreme
doughnuts as ``greasy sinkers. ... cloying and dwarfish, leaden not
long after being cooked, and about as interesting as a brick of
sucrose.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some Krispy Kreme fans see a downside. ``I recently lost
over 100 pounds, so maybe I can only eat two at a time,'' said
Washington. She used to eat six per trip.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
