<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER17-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING ON THE FLY AT SFO  &HT;      
</HEADLINE>
   By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ I applaud Mayor Willie Brown's decision to head up
the campaign to build those two new SFO runways. But I'm not sure I
like the idea of the shopping mall between 'em.
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW  &LR; airport runways will come in handy when we have to fly in
troops to rescue folks floating in the bay after the Bay Bridge
collapses during the upcoming earthquake because the bridge never
got fixed because Willie Brown wants a brew pub and Jerry Brown
wants a postcard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; RAISE YOUR  &LR; hand if you wish to contribute more money to the reward
fund for the capture of the San Jose dogflinger.
</P>
<P>
   I'll assume the rest of you are on the other side: Those who
want to form a huge lynch mob and parachute into Virginia and
interrogate every last man jack with a ball cap and goatee and
fluffy dog hair under his fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HEY, I OPPOSE &LR;  the death penalty, but I'm betting that right about
now, Young Elk has all the hot rocks and sweat he can handle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; WHO WANTS  &LR; to collect a million dollars? Nobody. The 49ers have
owed the city a mil for a couple of years, but neither the 49ers
nor the city shows any interest in an actual exchange of money.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Eddie DeBartolo would be more comfortable handing it over
in small bills in a briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   Next time you owe somebody big bucks and want them to let you
slide indefinitely, for no good reason, just ask your man, ``Can
you give me an Eddie D?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HEY, THAT  &LR; composite sketch of the dogflinger _ different facial
hair, eyes, nose, hair, ears ... but otherwise, I swear, man,
that's Richard Jewell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DARVA GETS  &LR; naked! Yes, Darva Conger says she's going to nude up
for Playboy.
</P>
<P>
   Proving, damn it, that Darva's really  &LR; not  &LR; just a bimbo looking
for money and attention and willing to sell her body and dignity to
get it.
</P>
<P>
   Who would believe it: A woman becomes instantly famous for some
cheesy reason, rips off her clothes and jumps in front of a camera
for money. You just never see that happen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHAT WOULD  &LR; Jesus drive? Yes, now it's a regular feature of this
column. And soon to be a major motion picture!
</P>
<P>
   Fredrick James says that since Jesus was a carpenter, he'd drive
a pickup truck with his dogma in the back.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Richard Leslie of St. Mary's Episcopal Church in
Pacific Grove says he's not sure of Jesus' ride, but the Bible
clearly states that the Disciples would drive a Honda. The Rev
cites the book of Acts, 2:46, to wit:
</P>
<P>
   ``And they, continuing daily with one accord in the temple ...
.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE DEVIL  &LR; would drive an old Pinto and dare you to rear-end him.
</P>
<P>
   And you know the SOB wouldn't be insured.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IF THE  &LR; mysterious dogflinger is smart, he'll turn himself in,
swear that he was only trying to apologize to the woman driver when
the pooch suddenly leaped for his throat, take his 30 days in jail,
pocket the $109,000 reward, sue the dog owner for defamation of
character and walk off whistling, because what the hell does he
care what you and I think of him?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; OSCAR TIME,  &LR; and the city's cinema buffs are getting fired up.
</P>
<P>
   At Whitehall Tavern on the Embarcadero, bartender Michael
McCourt is campaigning hard to have Gabby Hayes honored for
``lifetime achievement as a toothless sidekick.''
</P>
<P>
   Who can forget Gabby uttering, in any one of a dozen roles,
``Why, you sidewinder ...''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; STARRING SOON  &LR; in ``The Gabby Hayes Story'': Rick Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IF THERE  &LR; be a ground zero for St. Paddy's celebration, it might be
the Oyster and Beer Festival at Washington Square Park.
</P>
<P>
   Aye, the folks at O'Reilly's just around the corner will be
servin' up the old Colcannon and Dublin Coddle, and oysters up the
cadoodle, and live Irish music.
</P>
<P>
   So bring your brogue and your brogans and your lassie and your
bonnie and your shillelagh, 2-10 p.m. tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; LIZA, BABY,  &LR; I'm sorry.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; You  &LR; didn't complain, but many of your loyal fans expressed
anger over my comment that you are ``old.'' I meant it in the
context of a compliment, and you did sing ``I'm Glad I'm Not Young
Anymore'' in your show here. But for the record, you'll always be a
hot young babe to me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WE CAN  &LR; put a man on the moon, you say, so why can't we have
talking ATMs?
</P>
<P>
   Now we do; our very own BofA is coming out with the talkies.
This is the coolest thing since Al Jolson in ``The Jazz Singer.''
</P>
<P>
   But what will the ATMs say? Lotta Dotz leaked me this secret
bank memo of ATM phrases:
</P>
<P>
   - Psst, buddy, can you spare a Windex buffing and a shrubbery
trim?
</P>
<P>
   - Is that your final answer?
</P>
<P>
   - Nothin' could be finer than your cash in Carolina in the
morrn-ning!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; E-MAIL &LR;  letter of the week:
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, thanks for the reply. I didn't really mean you were
repugnant, just delirious.'' (Roberta Wright)
</P>
