r f BC-HP--E-COMMERCE-SFCHRO     03-17 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HP--E-COMMERCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HP LOOKING TO OFFER EASIER E-COMMERCE  &HT;     BY HENRY NORR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Hewlett-Packard is promising to make it as easy for businesses to
get the technology required for Internet commerce as it is to get
electricity for their offices.
<P>
   Under a new program called ``Infrastructure-on-Tap,'' which the
Palo Alto company will announce next week, HP seeks to play the
role of power plant, owning and managing all the underlying
technology that customers need to realize their e-ambitions.
Instead of having to develop the skills and spend the money
normally needed to build an e-business infrastructure, customers
will simply pay HP a monthly fee for all the necessary facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Countless ``Web hosting'' services already provide sites where
companies can set up electronic storefronts. But HP said its new
program will be different in several ways:
</P>
<P>
   Customers won't need any technical knowledge, such as how much
computing power, data storage and network bandwidth they'll need, &LR; 
to start up or expand their online operations. They'll simply tell
HP how much business they expect and HP will guarantee to support
it. If traffic to the site increases, HP can allocate the
additional resources required.
</P>
<P>
   Customers won't have to pay up front or make long-term
commitments for the servers, hard drives and other equipment their
sites require. HP will simply charge a monthly fee based on the
number of ``hits'' on the customer's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Infrastructure-on-Tap'' customers will be responsible for
providing the application software that actually runs their online
business, but HP will provide all necessary back-end services,
servers, security and network management.
</P>
<P>
   In its initial form, the program is not designed for mom-and-pop
retailers who want to start selling online, but rather at companies
setting up ``business-to-business hubs'' that link large
organizations to its suppliers or bring together multiple buyers
and sellers. The Gartner Group estimates that between 300 and 600
such hubs already exist, and the number is increasing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The market for outsourcing of information technology projects is
expected to be worth $160 billion by 2003, and HP projects that the
``Internet utility computing'' model it is pioneering could attract
10 percent of that business.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
