r f BC-PHONE-RULING-SFCHRON &LR;      03-17 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-RULING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE SERVICE RULES ARE FINE, STATE PUC SAYS 
 &HT;     BY TODD WALLACK
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Consumer advocates blasted the California Public Utilities
Commission for unanimously voting down a proposal yesterday to
update customer service rules covering Pacific Bell and other local
phone companies.
<P>
   Critics complained that the current rules, drafted in 1983,
before the advent of automated answering systems and other
technology, are woefully out of date.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell, for instance, is required to answer 80 percent of its
calls within 20 seconds. But the phone company isn't penalized if
it routes calls to a busy signal or forces callers to weave their
way through several layers of computerized menus before reaching a
live person.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a message that (Pac Bell) can get rate increase after
rate increase, while customer service quality goes down,'' said
Regina Costa of The Utility Reform Network.
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Billingsley, who works for the PUC's Office of Ratepayer
Advocates, called the vote ``very disappointing. ... It leaves
customers with nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Costa and Billingsley also said the current rules don't
always require Pac Bell and other local phone companies to repair
or install new phone lines in a reasonable period of time.
</P>
<P>
   But Lester Wong, an aide to Commission President Richard Bilas,
said new rules are not needed because Pac Bell is drawing fewer
complaints and facing growing competition from rivals, particularly
in the business and high-speed Internet markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want more regulation, we want more competition,''
said Wong.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Commissioner Henry Duque said he thought the
commission could better improve the current rules as part of a new
Telecommunications Consumer Bill of Rights, which would cover all
phone companies, including wireless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are on a much stronger path as far as consumers are
concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell also complained that the latest proposal didn't make
sense because it applied only to Pac Bell, GTE and other local
phone companies that historically had monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   It's unfair, said spokesman John Britton, ``to single out
companies like Pac Bell and GTE and say you cannot use technology
(like automated answering systems) to become more efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
