<HEADER>
A0507 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH17-PERSONALS-SFCH     03-17 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH17-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON  

</HEADLINE>
   By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
 A MODERN WOMAN'S COMPLICATED PROBLEMS 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brand-new bright and shiny Golf Digest Woman magazine solves
what it calls the ``mystery'' of why 58 percent of female golfers
find bad weather ``distracting and discouraging, compared with only
28 of the men?'' The answer: ``Men don't have to worry about their
hair!''
</P>
<P>
   Another result of the survey: ``Married men prefer to play with
almost anybody else but their wives.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Brand-new bright and shiny Real Simple magazine, which is
brimming with precise instructions to help ``simplify every aspect
of your life,'' suggests that once a month ``you empty the contents
of your medicine cabinet _ every last pumice stone and zucchini
mask _ into the sink. Use ... all-purpose cleaner to spritz the
shelves and walls of the cabinet. Then, as you replace the
toiletries, dust them.'' There now, doesn't that sound simple?
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. Us magazine asked  &UR; Julia Roberts &LR; , ``If you had to have
sex with one girl, who would it be with?''  &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR; , said
Roberts, `` 'cause I don't think she's getting her fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GEORGETTE'S POST-MARITAL COMPLAINT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Robert Mosbacher &LR;  has cut off the $32,064-a-month alimony he
was paying to his former wife, Georgette, and now she's filed suit
to get it reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   According to the New York Post, the former Commerce secretary
stopped payments because his ex-wife gave an interview in the New
York Observer saying that when he told her he wanted a divorce,
``it was the first time in my life I had known betrayal. ... I feel
like I've been permanently harmed.'' This, he told the Houston
Chronicle, was a violation of their divorce settlement, which had
specified that they wouldn't disparage one another.
</P>
<P>
   Georgette's suit claims she was cut off because Robert didn't
like her support of John McCain, a charge he denies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WHILE THE CAT'S AWAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A cat-loving consumer who recently received a Kitty Tease Deluxe
toy for her birthday found a notice inside signed by its
``inventor/owner.''
</P>
<P>
   He is shutting down the operation but will try to fill as many
orders as possible. The reason for the shutdown is a series of
financial reversals. ``Though the bank OKs me for an equity loan on
the home that I owned, they required that my wife co-sign the note
which she would not do,'' said the note tucked into the toy's box.
</P>
<P>
   ``She does not consider this a worthy job. My inventory is now
depleted and I do not have the $4,500 necessary to order more stock
even though there sits over $30,000 in useable home equity I can
not touch. The wife and I are now separated and a divorce looks
emanate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord works in strange ways and maybe this is just a test.
... In any case I wish to thank all of you for having taken a
chance on my cat toy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Sen.  &UR; Jesse Helms &LR; , R-N.C., has been awarded the Order of
Grand Duke Gediminas by the Republic of Lithuania, reports the
Hill. Helms was cited for ``his contributions to the
re-establishment and strengthening of the independence'' of
Lithuania, which broke from the Soviet Union 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Mary Matalin &LR;  and  &UR; James Carville &LR; , political consultants,
authors, TV stars and razzle-dazzle political celebrities, have a
new money- &LR; making scheme in mind. The Hill reports that they are
planning to open a restaurant in Washington, serving ``a mixture of
Northern and Southern regional cuisine'' (but perhaps not Eastern
and Western). The place will be called Emerson's, after their
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been interactive with my audience. I used to send,
like, close-ups of me throwing up to people who wrote me letters.
But I'm older now; I'm a mom. I have all these clothes in the
garage, and we were thinking that ... if you send a Polaroid of
yourself dressed up ... we'll send you something of my cruddy old
stage dresses.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Courtney Love  &LR; unveils plans for her Internet portal, in
Mademoiselle magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
