<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-STRIKE-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING, ENGINEERS AGREE TO END STRIKE PENDING UNION VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Boeing Co., battered by a 5 1/2-week strike by its
engineers union that had delayed jet deliveries and helped send its
stock price tumbling, announced a tentative agreement Friday to end
the action, which was one of the largest white-collar strikes
against a private company in years and was trumpeted by national
labor leaders as a crucial sign of their ability to organize
professional workers.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of things, the engineers, whose sole previous act of
defiance in the 56-year history of their union was a one-day
walkout in 1992, appeared to have scored a remarkable victory for
their efforts, which included manning the picket lines with signs
proclaiming: ``No Nerds, No Birds.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-year contract offers average wage increases of 8
percent to engineers this year and 4.5 percent in the next two
years, as well as cash bonuses of up to $2,500. The company also
agreed to extend health coverage to workers' domestic partners and
withdrew an earlier demand that workers contribute toward their
health-insurance coverage. The offer is still subject to
ratification by the 13,300-member union in a vote Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing management did secure the ability to target part of the
pay increases, with about half of the overall pool for wage
increases to be divided at the company's discretion. Such merit
raises are anathema to many unions, and many engineers on the
picket lines had opposed the idea, saying they did not trust the
company to distribute the raises fairly. Agreement on the issue
appeared to be a rough compromise between that opposition and the
company's opening proposal to exercise nearly complete discretion
over raises.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the engineers and the company had grown
increasingly bitter in recent days, and Alan Mulally, head of the
company's commercial airplanes unit, said on Monday that some
engineers were ``maliciously attacking our company and deliberately
trying to destroy our reputation'' by telling airlines and
government officials that new airplanes were unsafe for delivery.
But on Friday both sides offered conciliatory words after hammering
out the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us have a greater understanding of what is meant by the
issue of `respect,''' Philip M. Condit, Boeing's chairman and chief
executive, said in announcing the agreement. ``One day I hope we
can all look back on this as a turning point, a time when we more
clearly recognized the importance of listening to and seeking to
understand one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bofferding, executive director of the union, the Society
of Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace, said the
agreement would make ``a strong company stronger'' and showed the
company's ``respect for our contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials said Friday that they expected the company to
recover quickly from the effects of the walkout, and to meet its
announced goal of delivering 491 commercial jetliners this year. It
had already missed at least 15 of 42 such scheduled deliveries in
February, and problems were only expected to worsen since some of
the striking engineers were needed under federal law to certify new
airplanes as flightworthy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The company also clearly hoped that the news would help bolster
its stock price, even as it announced that it would evaluate the
impact of the strike, the new contract benefits and the overtime
necessary to get back on schedule, and possibly offer revised
earnings estimates later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Boeing, which had hit a 52-week low of $32 on March 10
before climbing back up, rose $1.5625, to close at $37.1875 Friday.
The stock had closed at $41 the day before the strike began on Feb.
9.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers and technical workers represented by the union had
been incensed by Boeing's initial offer, arguing among other things
that it paled in comparison with the relatively generous contract
worked out with the machinists' union late last summer, which
included 10 percent cash signing bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   The company's announcement Friday depicted the pact as a
compromise by both sides. But many analysts, on Wall Street and
elsewhere, clearly saw it as a victory for the union, with Boeing
offering apparent concessions on nearly all major issues on the
table.
</P>
<P>
   Ratification of the deal, while considered likely, is by no
means a sure thing. Some engineers, who had come to picket Friday
near company headquarters before the deal was announced, said they
remained adamantly opposed to any company control over the size of
individual engineer's raises, and thus threatened a ``no'' vote on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But many others seemed jubilant over the pact and said they
would vote for it enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   The broader impact on other white-collar workers remains to be
seen, but some experts thought the union's victory would resonate
far beyond the halls of Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The engineers and the technical people took a very big risk,
and they've come out on top,'' said Tom Juravich, director of the
Labor Center at the University of Massachusetts. ``And they seem to
have gained through the strike some newfound respect from the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Union membership among the roughly 20,000 people in the overall
bargaining unit represented by the union had jumped from about 40
percent before contract negotiations began to nearly 65 percent
now.
</P>
<P>
   And engineers, many of whom were on strike for the first time in
their lives, said the experience had changed their views about
organizing such activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us will ever look at a picket line in quite the same
way again,'' said Bofferding, the union director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
