<HEADER>
A0514 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WACO-REENACT-ADVANCE1     03-17 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-REENACT-ADVANCE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Re-enactment of Branch Davidian fiasco set
 &HT;    By Mark England
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Mount Carmel will spring to life for at least one
more day Sunday. In theory, at least.
</P>
<P>
   The rambling free-form structure that loomed over the prairie
east of Waco won't be rebuilt for the court-ordered test. The
re-enactment has been ordered to determine if government agents
shot at the Branch Davidians on the day of a fire that led to the
deaths of David Koresh and 75 followers.
</P>
<P>
   But at 10:30 a.m., weather permitting, a re-creation staged at
Fort Hood will bring back images forever linked to Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   A Bradley fighting vehicle and a combat engineering vehicle will
rumble over the test site. Armed men in camouflage will roam about.
Debris such as hubcaps, broken glass and insulation will be strewn
on the ground. And two aircraft with Forward-Looking Infrared, or
FLIR, video cameras will fly overhead.
</P>
<P>
   What may or may not be different _ weapons will be fired.
</P>
<P>
   In two hours or so, videotapes will be ready for comparison with
the FLIR videos from April 19, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Caddell, lead attorney in the wrongful-death lawsuit filed
against the government by surviving Davidians, believes the test
will prove the flashes on the original FLIR videos are FBI agents
firing weapons _ creating an atmosphere of fear that he thinks may
have kept many Davidians from fleeing a burning Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these FLIRs can show a lighted cigarette, they sure as hell
can show flashes from a machine gun,'' Caddell said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Michael Bradford of Beaumont, helping defend the
government, said he's hopeful the re-creation will end speculation
about government gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important, if possible, to put that to rest,''
Bradford said. ``It didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradford also said that things may not be any clearer once
the smoke clears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that at the end of the day, we're going to have
a test tape that will have to be compared to the FLIR tapes of the
19th,'' Bradford said. ``To some extent, it will be a subjective
comparison by both sides' experts, so it's subject to the potential
for continued debate and dispute. Because several different issues
are going to be covered, the results may be clear on some and in
dispute on others.''
</P>
<P>
   The test Sunday stems from Caddell's breathtaking challenge:
restage the final day. The loser of the contest pays all expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Government attorneys balked, arguing that it was impossible to
recreate the conditions _ from the weather to the soil content _ at
Mount Carmel. The FBI also pointed out that the FLIR camera had
been upgraded in the intervening years. Furthermore, the agency
insisted that any information about it was classified.
</P>
<P>
   However, the FBI offered to stage a private field test for
Special Counsel John Danforth.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, however, declined and asked U.S. District Judge Walter
Smith Jr. of Waco to order a test with independent experts
analyzing the results. Smith asked Danforth's office to set it up,
with the videos to be studied by a British firm, Vector Data
Systems LTD. Their analysis, however, won't be made public until
after the upcoming civil trial.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, at Danforth's request, barred the media from the test
site, likening it to a crime scene, ``which unquestionably may be
closed to the public and the press in order to preserve the
integrity of the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many crime scenes, however, have 34 people looking over
authorities' shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Smith and Danforth, there will be eight members of
Congress (or congressional staff) present, and representatives from
the FBI, Department of Justice, the Department of Defense and the
Office of Special Counsel. Eight slots are set aside for the
plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   If no rain falls and the temperature doesn't drop below 65
degrees or soar above 85 degrees, the re-creation will start at
10:30 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Before the test, military track vehicles will run over the test
site _ which will be equipped with targets, designated shooting
areas, video points and a debris field _ to create ruts similar to
those found at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Six men, without weapons, will assume prone positions behind the
Bradley fighting vehicle and the Combat Engineering Vehicle 20
minutes before the test. Between them, they will wear a
fire-resistant Nomex flight suit with camouflage; camouflage
fatigues; a camouflaged rainsuit; and a full sniper suit with face
paint and vegetation adornment.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs argue that there are two explanations for why no
people are seen near the flash points in the Mount Carmel FLIR
videos. Government agents may have worn FLIR-resistant clothing.
And if they were lying down, their body temperature may have been
too close to that of the ground.
</P>
<P>
   A FLIR camera detects the relative temperature of objects and
processes the information to produce a monochromatic image.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford thinks the shooters Sunday will show up in the FLIR
images.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the tapes from the 19th, there are no signs of any people
or weapons around the flashes,'' Bradford said. ``The people in the
test will wear the same type of clothing as the agents wore on the
19th. If we can see them, that will be a clear distinction. It will
establish the flashes are not people shooting weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell, however, has a different perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get flashes from guns and we don't get flashes from
trash, then what else can the flashes be but gunfire?'' Caddell
said. ``I'm not saying we won't get flashes from the space tent,
but it won't be the precise repetitive flashes seen on April 19th.
The only thing that can duplicate that is gunfire.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the shooters will rise on command, go to the first
shooting position, pick up their weapons and fire five spaced
single shots at a target 10 yards away. The weapons fired will be
an M-16 rifle, a CAR-15 rifle, two 9 mm MP-5 submachine guns (one
suppressed), a Remington automatic shotgun and a Browning 88 9 mm
pistol.
</P>
<P>
   The shooters will then move to the next firing position, crouch
and fire three-shot bursts at a 10-yard target. Those shooting the
pistols and shotgun will fire single shots three times in rapid
succession.
</P>
<P>
   Four shooters (those carrying the M-16, the CAR-15 and the two
MP-5 submachine guns) will move to a forward shooting position.
There they will be joined by shooters with an M60 machine gun and
an MK-19 automatic grenade launcher. The shooters will fire three
12-round bursts of automatic fire at a target 30 yards away. One
shooter will fire the M-203 grenade launcher on the M-16.
</P>
<P>
   The shooters will place their weapons at pre-position locations
and go to the rear of the vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   From inside the Bradley fighting vehicle, a shooter armed with
an M-79 grenade launcher will appear, stand next to the vehicle and
fire two ferret rounds of tear gas, two M-651 rounds and two
flashbang rounds at the farthest target. Recording each stage of
the test will be an FBI Nightstalker airplane and a British Royal
Navy Lynx Mk 8 helicopter equipped with a Sea Owl FLIR camera
identical to the one used by the FBI at Mount Carmel. The
Nightstalker will carry an updated version of the camera. Each
aircraft will do flyovers at 4,000 and 6,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the test starts, there has been controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs received permission to test fire the MK-19
grenade launcher, a weapon the government claims wasn't at Mount
Carmel. However, one of the plaintiffs' experts believes some of
the flashes on the original FLIR videos could only come from an
MK-19, which has a fast rate of fire.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford believes the weapon could skew the test results.
However, he defends the decision to let the government set up a
dome tent covered with aluminum-coated space blankets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be virtually impossible to capture where the debris
was on the 19th or put the aircraft in the position it was then,''
Bradford said. ``We wanted to create something we know is glare to
see if it shows up on camera. If we create glare, then we can see
what it looks like and if it's similar to what shows on the FLIR
(videos) of the 19th.''
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs, however, portray what Caddell dubbed ``Space Blanket
Bingo'' as a government gambit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My suspicion is the government ran tests at Quantico and
determined the tentlike structure was their best chance to show
glint off something other than weapons,'' said Houston attorney
James Brannon, who represents several plaintiffs. ``I think the
government has figured out the weapons are going to show, and
they're trying to spin it. They don't mind it being suspicious.
Suspicious is a win for them. At least they'll have some story.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
