<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-NTT-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL A BIG FISH, EVEN IN A BIG POND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This is a sidebar to JAPAN-TELETECH)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ As Japan's government-owned telephone monopoly until
1985, Nippon Telegraph and Telephone presided over the world's
second-largest phone market unchallenged. The heft it attained in
the process still gives it immense economic and political clout.
</P>
<P>
   Along with its subsidiaries, NTT Mobile Telecommunications and
NTT Data, NTT employs some 224,000 people directly; it keeps
perhaps as many more working in affiliates, joint ventures and
other related companies. Employees at NTT's two local phone service
subsidiaries and its long-distance unit make an average of 10
million yen, or $93,458, a year, one of the highest average
salaries in Japan, and their average age is 43.
</P>
<P>
   NTT's procurement budget _ the number is not disclosed, but can
be safely estimated at well beyond $20 billion a year _ provides
further largesse. That keeps tens of thousands of people employed
at various suppliers _ themselves titans of the Japanese economy
like NEC, Hitachi and Fujitsu. One of NEC's four sales divisions is
devoted exclusively to NTT.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those business and employment relationships mean that even
if we offered a cheaper rate, NTT will get the business,'' said
Ryuichi Kinoshita, a managing director at DDI, a long-distance
carrier, and a former official at the Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications. ``It's unfortunate, but that's Japanese
business practice.''
</P>
<P>
   NTT's political power is expansive, too. Many of Kinoshita's
former colleagues in the ministry now work for NTT, and its
powerful union both raises money for political campaigns and urges
its members to vote for candidates backed by the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   The company says critics exaggerate its clout. ``No player can
dominate the market that is changing and expanding so rapidly,''
said Kenya Nakatsuka, a spokesman for NTT.
</P>
<P>
   The government is NTT's largest shareholder, owning a 59.1
percent stake now worth 13.7 trillion yen, or roughly $130.3
billion. ``We are a very unique company,'' acknowledges Kanji
Koide, a senior vice president. ``Having such a company in a
competitive market is extraordinary and a little odd.''
</P>
<P>
   Regulators and politicians arguably have little incentive to
force more competition on NTT, particularly now, with a tough
parliamentary election looming and NTT looking a bit like the
Titanic in the wake of a government-imposed overhaul last fall.
</P>
<P>
   NTT was forced to spin off its crown jewels, the mobile phone
and data units; break its bread-and-butter local service into two
pieces and create a separate unit for a long-distance service it
intended to start.
</P>
<P>
   Except in the lucrative Tokyo market, NTT's local services are
bleeding red ink. And its plans for building a long-distance
service were shattered when Britain's Cable and Wireless succeeded
in acquiring International Digital, a struggling long-distance
carrier with loose ties to NTT.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, many analysts regard these problems _ which NTT has
been highlighting in advance of the discussion on interconnection
fees _ as little more than bumps in the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an incentive right now for NTT not to appear to be
doing too well, because they are currently in these negotiations,''
said Kate Lye, a telecommunications analyst at Warburg Dillon Read
in Tokyo. ``In fact, the fundamentals are strong. We're certainly
looking for earnings growth on a group basis this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
