<HEADLINE>
PEREZ GETS REPRIEVE; HERSHISER SHARP
</HEADLINE>
 GRAPHICS AT BOTTOM)-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. -- The battle for the fifth spot in the
Dodgers' rotation was supposed to become more clear Friday.
Instead, it remained murky.
</P>
<P>
   Lefty Carlos Perez showed the type of improvement manager Davey
Johnson wanted to see. Then, Orel Hershiser showed how to be
masterfully dominant.
</P>
<P>
   And it means Perez gets a reprieve -- for now. Perez still has a
chance to win a spot in the rotation and bump Hershiser to the
bullpen, but he' ll have to do it with roles reversed. When they
pitch Wednesday against Montreal, Hershiser will start and Perez
while relieves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we both succeed, he'll be in the rotation,'' Hershiser
said. ``If I falter, he'll be in the rotation. If we both pitch
poorly, they'll toss it up. If we both pitch well and he's in the
rotation, that's fine. It makes us a deeper team.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez allowed three runs (two earned) in four innings. His
velocity was in the 87 to 89 mph in his first three innings, but it
dropped to 84 to 89 in the fourth inning, when he allowed all three
runs. He walked a batter and struck out five, used his change-up
effectively and mixed in a bunch of split-finger fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   But his second time through the order was different, even before
shortstop Kevin Elster booted a ball to allow the final run to
score. Perez's pitches were higher in the zone and balls were hit
harder, including a long homer by Ray Lankford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can show more than that,'' said Perez, whose ERA dropped
from 14.40 to 10.00. ``It was only for four innings. What I really
want to show is when the season starts. I have to keep saying,
`It's spring training.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Just wait until April comes. I can't wait. I'm hungry. I want
to see some numbers out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez's outing was better than the eight earned runs in five
innings he allowed in his first two spring outings, but it's not
enough to declare Perez the fifth starter. In fact, he remains in
consideration only because he's guaranteed $12.5 million over the
next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mechanics (Friday) were so much better for me,'' Johnson said.
``A big improvement on what he did the other day. I can tell from
the way the hitter reacted. He wasn't pulling the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hershiser allowed three hits and struck out six in
four innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was as sharp as I've seen him at times,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield's scare: Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield figures
to miss the next few days with a left pinkie injury, but it
could've been much worse. Sheffield suffered a cut on the finger
while diving into third on an attempted stolen base. His finger was
sliced by the cleat of Craig Paquette. It required one stitch to
close and his availability is day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm done running forever,'' Sheffield said jokingly. ``Never
stealing another base.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre saga continues: Dodgers managing partner and CEO Bob Daly
was supposed to give Scott Boras, Beltre's agent, the club's final
offer. Instead, the sides agreed to keep talking. There remains
hope on both sides a decision can be made Monday or Tuesday on
whether to sign Beltre to a three-year deal or go through the
arbitration process. Beltre's seeking free agency for because he
was signed at age 15.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Nicole Menz, assistant state attorney of Indian
River County, said Perez would be charged with driving under the
influence of alcohol. ``I will be filing a charge. It will be done
first thing Monday morning,'' Menz said. ...Catcher Todd Hundley
returned after missing five games with back spasms. ...Third
baseman Adrian Beltre was scratched from today's trip to play
Detroit in Lakeland. It's the third straight game he'll miss with a
sore wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers weekly box
</P>
<P>
   Best storyline: The battle for the fifth spot in the rotation
between Orel Hershiser and Carlos Perez. Hershiser is the clear
leader, but organization wants Perez involved.
</P>
<P>
   Best sub-plot: Perez' off-field problems continued when he was
arrested for suspicion of driving under the influence of alcohol
late Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Progress was made with: Strengthening the bullpen. Righty Mike
Fetters threw a perfect inning in his first appearance, giving the
Dodgers more depth.
</P>
<P>
   Progress wasn't made with: The Adrian Beltre situation. Both
sides want it done, but they can't agree on a three-year deal. And
the closer it gets to the season, the more tenuous the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Spring surprise: That rookie right-hander Eric Gagne hasn't come
in pitched well. HE has a 15.58 ERA in three appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The week ahead: Kevin Elster could challenge Alex Cora for the
starting shortstop job. Cora's played better lately, but if Dodgers
need more offense Elster could fight his way in.
</P>
<P>
   -- Brian Dohn
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers vs. Detroit
</P>
<P>
   When/Where: 10:05 a.m., Marchant Stadium, Lakeland, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Radio: XTRA 1150 AM
</P>
<P>
   Today's game: The Dodgers make the cross-state trip to play
Tigers and see an old friend for the second time this spring.
Right-hander Dave Mlicki starts for the Tigers. Righty Kevin Brown,
who has a 2.45 ERA in three outings, makes his fourth appearance of
the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's result: Lefty Carlos Perez allowed three runs in four
innings as the Dodgers were beaten by St. Louis 4-2 in Vero Beach.
Orel Hershiser pitched four shutout innings. Mark Grudzielanek and
Gary Sheffield each had two hits for the Dodgers, who are 3-13-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
