<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRIDIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACKING BUYER, IRIDIUM IS SET TO SHUT DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Unable to find new investors willing to step in after
Motorola Inc. and other founding partners declined to bail it out,
Iridium LLC moved Friday to shut off the innovative portable phone
and messaging service it designed to reach the remotest regions of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium told Judge Arthur Gonzalez of the U.S. Bankruptcy Court
in the Southern District of New York that it wanted to end
commercial service to its remaining customers by Saturday and start
the tricky process of destroying its constellation of 74 satellites
as early as next week. Lawyers for Iridium, which is based in
Washington, said it would take up to $50 million and the rest of
this year to program the destruction of the network of satellites
Iridium spent billions to create. Some of the satellites might take
up to two years to re-enter the atmosphere and burn up.
</P>
<P>
   Once heralded as a symbol of Motorola's far-sightedness and a
dramatic step forward in the globalization process, Iridium ended
up as a financial fiasco highlighting many of the various ways
businesses can go astray as they struggle to convert new technology
into popular products. More than $5 billion was invested.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that's left is the litigation,'' said Armand Musey, an
analyst at Banc of America Securities in New York, referring to
shareholder lawsuits already filed and other actions anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   That is a bit of an overstatement for now. Some of the
independent companies providing the ground gateways for the system
intend to continue to make emergency connections for a period of
time, including Iridium North America, which serves the entire
Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't guarantee that every call will work but it should be
there for several weeks for humanitarian needs,'' said Jim Walz,
president and chief executive of Iridium North America, which is
owned by Motorola, Sprint and Bell Canada. Meanwhile, Walz's
company, vendors it works with and others are working to help
customers migrate to other communications services.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium has said in recent weeks that it has 55,000 customers
but analysts said that far fewer than that would be affected.
Thousands of the customers have little use for Iridium but signed
up last fall to have a backup to conventional phone networks in the
event of Year 2000 computer breakdowns. Others have already begun
converting to other services.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have just had it with the uncertainty,'' said
Michael Smith, a Washington area representative for Stratos Global
Corp. who was working Friday with a major oil company he declined
to identify to switch links to its employees in Africa from Iridium
to Inmarsat, a British-based satellite system that has a
laptop-sized receiver for remote telephone users. Stratos and
others are offering trade-in credits for Iridium handsets, which
were made by Motorola and Kyocera of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium was first envisioned by Motorola engineers in Phoenix in
the mid-1980s as demand for cellular phones began to rise. The
proposal to use a ring of 66 low-orbit satellites to create
``anyone, anywhere, anytime'' telecommunications was turned down by
the engineers' superiors but when senior managers visited from
Motorola's headquarters in Schaumburg, Ill., the engineers got a
chance to take their vision straight to the top. They won the
support of Robert Galvin, then the chairman and chief executive.
The story became part of Motorola lore and was often cited in the
years that followed as a symbol of the company's openness to bold
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But the Iridium that finally emerged was hobbled by clunky
phones, difficulty in maintaining clear connections in many
circumstances and high costs. Iridium LLC, the partnership Motorola
set up to run the satellite system, carried a huge debt load.
</P>
<P>
   The complex arrangements between Iridium LLC, the gateway
companies like Iridium North America and major investors, including
some foreign governments, made every strategic decision nearly as
complex as Mideast peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium lost money steadily from the day it handled its first
calls in September 1998 and it never came close to attracting the
millions of subscribers it needed to fulfill its creators' visions.
Shares in Iridium LLC that were sold to public investors peaked at
$70 in the spring of 1998, long before the first call was made.
They closed at 65.625 cents on Friday after the news that Iridium
would shut down. Motorola and the other investors that built the
system sank more than $5 billion into it, mostly to design, build
and launch the 66 satellites and the 8 backups that also are in
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium filed for bankruptcy protections last August in an
effort to reorganize its operations and debts but a complete
shutdown became inevitable, according to industry analysts, two
weeks ago when Craig O. McCaw, the billionaire cellular phone
pioneer, said that his investment group had dropped its plan to try
to acquire Iridium.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium is not alone in its problems. ICO Global Communications,
a second satellite phone network, filed for bankruptcy protection
shortly after Iridium. McCaw bought ICO and is trying to meld it
and Teledesic, a third ambitious satellite plan scheduled to begin
service in 2004, into ``an Internet of the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Iridium's major investors have already written off their
losses. Kyocera said yesterday that it would record a 10 billion
yen ($93.7 million) Iridium write-down in the current quarter.
Motorola set aside more than $2.5 billion last year and said Friday
that Iridium's demise would have no further impact on its earnings.
Motorola's shares fell $2.25, to $149.50, in trading on the Big
Board.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
