<SLUG> BC-BUSH-AD-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: BUSH ON EDUCATION
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ky., Ill., Iowa, Mo.)  (rk) 
 By DAVID ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bush campaign began running this 60-second commercial Friday
in parts of Kentucky, Illinois, Iowa and Missouri
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Maverick Media
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: Clips of students of different ages, mostly in
classrooms or on playgrounds, with Bush in some shots.
</P>
<P>
   VOICE-OVER: Is the status quo in America's schools good enough?
</P>
<P>
   Under Al Gore and Bill Clinton, national reading scores
stagnated. America's high school students place almost dead last in
international math tests. The achievement gap between poor and
nonpoor students remains wide. Gore and Clinton had eight years,
but they've failed.
</P>
<P>
   As president, George W. Bush will challenge the status quo with
a crusade to improve education. He'll fight for reforms hailed as
the most fundamental in a generation, demand high standards and
accountability for students and teachers, restore local control of
schools, increase funding but change the system so successful
schools are rewarded and failing ones must improve.
</P>
<P>
   He'll turn Head Start into a reading program and close the
achievement gap that hurts those on the edges of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   His goal? Teach every child to read because there are no
second-rate children, no second-rate dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush: a fresh start for education.
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: Reading scores are generally measured by the National
Assessment of Educational Progress, a test given to American
students in the fourth, eight and 12th grades. The latest results,
released last July, showed that the average scores of fourth and
12th graders, which had fallen from 1992 to 1994, rose in 1998
approximately to where they were in 1992. Scores for eighth graders
were higher in 1998 than they were in 1992 or 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The gauge of math scores is the Third International Mathematics
and Science Study. The latest results showed that American fourth
graders were near the top internationally, eighth graders were
below average and 12th graders were near the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The statement about the wide gap between poor students and
others is incontrovertible.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: Scores in reading and math are little different from
what they were when Republicans were in the White House. But it is
safe to say that no one is satisfied with them.
</P>
<P>
   Tests show that students in Texas have improved in reading since
Bush became governor. His central campaign proposal is to require
all students to sit for annual tests administered by their states.
Schools would be held responsible for student performance. Students
in schools that consistently did poorly would be given a check, or
voucher, by the federal government that they could use to attend a
private school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0380 </DOCNO>
