<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASDAQ CONTINUES TO RISE BUT DOW INDUSTRIALS DROP
</P>
<P>
   The stock market returned to a calmer mode as the Nasdaq
continued to climb, while blue-chip shares retreated one day after
Thursday's 499-point gain in the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose 80.74 points, or 1.7 percent, to
4,798.13, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was up 6
points, at 1,464.47. The Dow fell 35.37 points, to 10,595.23.
</P>
<P>
   GUN MAKER SETS SAFETY MEASURES
</P>
<P>
   The gun manufacturer Smith &AMP; Wesson has agreed to put safety
locks on its handguns within 60 days and to make them
child-resistant within a year in a deal with federal and state
agencies. The government agreed to withdraw pending legal action
against the gun maker in return.
</P>
<P>
   IMF CANDIDATE OUTLINES HIS GOALS
</P>
<P>
   Horst Koehler, the likely new managing director of the
International Monetary Fund, gave a general outline of his goals at
a news conference in Washington. He promised to listen to criticism
from outsiders and to make the fund ``a cornerstone for promoting
growth and stability.''
</P>
<P>
   ENERGY PRICES FUEL INFLATION GAIN
</P>
<P>
   Surging oil prices pushed the inflation rate in February to its
highest level in three years, the Labor Department said. The
Consumer Price Index, the best-known inflation gauge, rose 3.2
percent over the last 12 months. That is the first time the
yearlong rate went above 3 percent since February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   HEARST SELLS SAN FRANCISCO PAPER
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Corp. sold the San Francisco Examiner to Ted Fang, the
owner of two local newspapers and part of a well-connected family
with a strong political base in San Francisco's Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA ONLINE TO BUY OUT PARTNER
</P>
<P>
   America Online plans to buy out Bertelsmann's 50 percent stake
in their joint ventures, AOL Europe and AOL Australia, for over $8
billion. The move had been expected since AOL agreed to acquire
Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE MAGAZINE TO CEASE PUBLICATION
</P>
<P>
   Time Inc. said it will cease regular publication of Life
magazine, the illustrated chronicle of America for more than six
decades, with the May issue, because the market for magazines has
become too competitive for a general-interest publication. It was
the second time the company had stopped regular publication of the
magazine since it was introduced in 1936. Time will continue to
publish Life for special events.
</P>
<P>
   ROVER WORKERS FEAR FOR THEIR JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 9,000 employees at the Rover manufacturing plant in
Longbridge, England, fear that they will lose their jobs now that
BMW has sold the plant. The reverberations extended also to the
50,000 people who depend on the auto industry for their livelihood
in the region, which was once the heart of the British auto
industry. BMW's move also drew criticism from the British
government.
</P>
<P>
   BANK ONE TO ELIMINATE 5,100 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Bank One said that it would eliminate 5,100 jobs, or about 5.6
percent of its work force, to lower costs as the bank struggles to
raise earnings and its share price. The bank also said it gave its
chairman and chief executive, John B. McCoy, a $10.3 million
severance payment and a $3 million annual pension when he resigned
in December after profit problems.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT TIES IN TO MEXICAN COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS, the mobile telephone unit of Sprint, paid $200
million for an undisclosed stake in Pegaso PCS, the first cellular
phone company to offer 100 percent digital services in Mexico, in a
deal that will offer cross-border telephone services.
</P>
</TEXT>
