<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0530 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-WRITERS-PORTRAITS-     03-17 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WRITERS-PORTRAITS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STROKES OF A PAINTBRUSH CAPTURE STROKES OF A BLACK WRITER'S PEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT33 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a few false starts, the real work began in
1997. On weekend nights, usually around midnight, Gilbert D.
Fletcher would ascend to his art studio in the attic of his home in
the Bronx. The studio would be dark, but for a spotlight on a blank
canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher would sit in a director's chair before the canvas. He
would reach for a book, perhaps a James Baldwin, or an Alice
Walker, or a Langston Hughes, but always a black writer. And then
he would read, patiently, waiting for a word or a phrase or an
image to strike the fire within.
</P>
<P>
   When it happened, he would begin. With his brush, he would work
his oil paints as fast as he could, faster and faster, past the
point of exhaustion, until his canvas was full. This is how, over
the span of four intense months, Gilbert Fletcher finished the
portraits of 20 great black writers, from Ralph Ellison to Maya
Angelou to August Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, those portraits _ vividly colored, richly symbolic
_ were put on display in the grand lobby of the Central Library in
Brooklyn. Fletcher, 51, a professional art designer whose nostalgic
paintings of his New Orleans childhood sell for thousands of
dollars, titled his series ``Painted Voices: An Artist's Journey
Into the World of Black Writers.''
</P>
<P>
   The series, on display until April 15, is part of the library's
participation in the fifth National Black Writers Conference, which
runs from March 30 to April 2 at Medgar Evers College in Brooklyn.
It is also part of the Brooklyn Public Library's effort to bring
art and sculpture to its branches to stimulate interest in reading.
The thinking is that someone who sees, say, Fletcher's ghostly
rendering of Ralph Ellison might then feel compelled to pick up
``Invisible Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, right beside Fletcher's portraits, the library has set
up display cases where people can pick from books by these authors.
In connection with the writers conference, the library has bought
1,500 new books by black writers, 100 audio books and dozens of
videos related to the writers. Valerie J. Geiss, a spokeswoman for
the library, called the purchase ``a substantial expansion'' of the
library's African-American collection.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher, who will give an artist's talk at 2 p.m. Saturday in
the third-floor trustees room of the Central Library, deliberately
packed his portraits with words and symbols drawn from the lives of
the writers. In an interview, Fletcher said, ``I wanted to share my
experience, through my paintings, about what I had learned about
these writers.''
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher said he had painted Baldwin with a shimmering martini
glass etched on the front of his pink shirt ``because I know he
loved to drink.'' He painted flaming basketballs zooming like
surreal comets past a scowling John Edgar Wideman to symbolize
Wideman's focus on inner-city conflagrations. Bodies of drowned
slaves float across the chest of Robert Hayden because of his
writings about the trans-Atlantic ``middle passage'' of the early
slave trade.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher knows these details because in addition to collecting
all 311 books written by his 20 authors, he has assembled hundreds
of articles, essays and reviews about them, as well as archive
photographs. ``I wanted to get inside of them, to get to know
them,'' Fletcher said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was a difficult, sometimes frustrating endeavor, he
said. He would try one approach to a portrait, then another, and
then another. He still believes that his Sterling Brown portrait is
too stiff and gray, nor is he fully satisfied with his Ishmael
Reed. The turning point, he said, came one night when he came
across a Langston Hughes poem, ``The Negro Speaks of Rivers.''
These are the words he found:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known rivers ancient as the world and older than the flow
of human blood in human veins.''
</P>
<P>
   It was then, he said, that he found the singular image that
connected each of his subjects. ``The river is a metaphor of pain,
sorrow,'' he wrote in an essay about his portraits. ``It turns and
flows into a river of black consciousness. It becomes joy, hope,
spirit and identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a river of song, of culture, of community, with a
strength that resists oppression and destructive stereotypes. The
river is folklore, jazz, blues and gospel. It is Mother Africa,
Harlem, Watts, Birmingham, Mississippi and the Middle Passage. From
our ancestors, the river flows through our veins.''
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, Fletcher said, the portraits are not for
sale. He intends first to spend several years showing them in
galleries and exhibitions, although he has turned them into
greeting cards and posters. He also intends to add to the series,
which he acknowledges is far from complete. Where's Terry McMillan,
or Stanley Crouch, or Walter Mosley?
</P>
<P>
   And so Fletcher continues his attic sojourns, waiting for the
magic to spring from the writers' words to his brush. ``It is a
celebration,'' he said. ``You look at these writers, what they have
done. This is total dedication, and total commitment, and
incredible courage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
