<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, March 13,
about a school voucher program in Florida misidentified the school
where students were unable to identify a predicate after singing a
song that referred to one. It was A.A. Dixon Elementary in
Pensacola, not Spencer Bibbs.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ONLINE-UNIVERSITY-NYT (moved on Wednesday, March 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, March
15, about plans by Michael Saylor, chief executive of
MicroStrategy, to donate $100 million to establish a free online
university gave an incorrect spelling in some copies for the
surname of the billionaire investor who Saylor hopes would be a
lecturer on investing. He is Warren Buffett, not Buffet.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-DIABETES-DRUG-NYT (moved on Wednesday, March 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, March
15, about a possible investigation by the Food and Drug
Administration into the manufacture of the diabetes drug Rezulin
misspelled the name of an agency spokeswoman in some editions. She
is Laura Bradbard, not Bradbart.
</P>
<P>
   BC-COOPER-DESIGN-NYT (moved on Thursday, March 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, March 9,
about the National Design Triennial at the Cooper-Hewitt Museum in
Manhattan misstated the surname of the exhibition designer. He is
Michael Gabellini, not Gambelli.
</P>
