<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-REBELFLAG18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia school votes down state flag
 &HT;    By Jennifer Brett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSWELL, Ga. _ The day he surrendered at Appomattox, Confederate
Gen. Robert E. Lee shined his boots, put on his finest uniform and
accepted defeat with grace. Soldiers on both sides were relieved to
be heading home at last.
</P>
<P>
   Friday brought a different kind of relief to Centennial High
School in Roswell after principal Leonard Box announced the
school's students, faculty, PTA executive board and local school
advisory committee all voted to no longer fly the Georgia state
flag.
</P>
<P>
   The school will fly the U.S. flag only.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of debate and flagpole rallies by students who
disagree on the issue, students on both sides now say they are glad
to finally have the controversy behind them. Just one Fulton County
school, Roswell High School, now flies the Georgia state flag.
</P>
<P>
   Some Centennial students who voted to not fly the flag said they
hope their school can now come together.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no problem with the flag,'' said freshman Jaclynn
Bridges, 14. ``Keep it up, keep it down, whatever. Just don't show
any hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Tevia Holliday, also a 14-year-old freshman, was pleased with
the vote, but said the matter had not impassioned her.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the flag was up, it didn't really bother me,'' she said.
``It's just a flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Kim Zanone, 15, voted to keep the flag up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our state flag and it's our history,'' she said as she
surveyed the line of television trucks parked near her school.
``This whole thing's been blown out of proportion. I voted yes but
I'm glad it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Box said the school's state flag is now in the possession of the
school's Junior ROTC, which is responsible for hoisting the U.S.
flag each day. He said it would be ``set up in a respectful place
for use on appropriate occasions,'' but isn't yet sure exactly what
role, if any, the flag will play at Centennial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a week of democratic action here at Centennial
High School,'' Box told students over the school's intercom.
``There has been freedom of expression throughout this issue. It is
time for us all to accept the decision. It is time for us to come
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
