<SLUG> BC-LOSTDOG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING DOG FROM TEXAS COULD BE IN VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Miniature schnauzer Bo for more than 14 years led a good life with
the Ealey family of suburban Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Ealeys hoped to see their little dog, now in failing health
with only months to live, through his final days.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, Bo disappeared. And now Sharon Ealey believes a
crew of television cable workers installing lines in their
neighborhood snatched the dog and transported him to _ of all
places _ Tempe. The story of the Ealeys and their dog shows just
how far a family will go to retrieve a lost pet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bo turned up missing Feb. 18 while the Ealeys were away from
home and children chasing a ball into their yard accidently let the
dog out. Ealey had no idea where the salt-and-pep per schnauzer had
gone until she received an anonymous phone call Feb. 29. She traced
it to a pay phone in an industrial area around Wash ington Street
and Price Road in northern Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   A nervous man told Ealey that his cable crew had taken the dog
and brought it to Arizona. Saying he feared losing his job, the man
refused to reveal his name or the name of his company but promised
to send Bo back to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would call back in 15 minutes. Ealey never heard from
him again.
</P>
<P>
   Why someone would want to steal Bo is unclear. He is nearly
blind, deaf and suffers from back problems that cause his hind legs
to drag. He is on medication for a skin condition that has now gone
untreated for eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Ealey believes the motive may have been sheer meanness.
She considers Bo special in a way that many people wouldn't
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a super little dog. He deserves the right and the
dignity to die at home with people who love him,'' she said from
her home in Mesquite, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Ealey fears the dog will die if he is not returned soon _ no
questions asked. She and husband Jim have sent fliers to a friend
in Scottsdale, corporate pilot Ted Morton. He plans to post them in
the area where Bo is believed to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody knows something. . . . There's no reason for these
people not to return that dog,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no request for ransom.
</P>
<P>
   Though in poor health, Bo is still a lively and handsome
purebred dog, Ealey said. He would not have appeared feeble to his
captors.
</P>
<P>
   Ealey contacted a Dallas representa tive of AT&AMP;T Cable Services,
who she said confirmed that three cable crews had been installing
lines in her area Feb. 18. However, AT&AMP;T spokeswoman Angel Biasatti
said her company employs only local cable crews and has found no
evidence to confirm Ealey's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ealey has had the schnauzer since he was six weeks old and
daughter Janelle was 14. He slept at Janelle's side until she went
off to college at Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Now 28, Janelle has a 17-month-old daughter whose first word was
``Bo'' and can't understand where Grand ma's dog has gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has absolutely torn us up,'' Ealey said, her voice
breaking. ``Bo has so much heart. He deserves to be home. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people are afraid of reprisals. Little do they know I
don't care. I just want the little fellow back.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with information about Bo can call Morton after 6 p.m. at
(480) 991-7765 or Ealey at (972) 226-4885. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0390 </DOCNO>
