<HEADER>
A0541 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-(GRAPHICAT     03-17 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-(GRAPHIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHMID MUST SIT OUT GALAXY OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 AT BOTTOM)-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid will be forced to watch
tonight's Major League Soccer season opener against Colorado from
the Rose Bowl press box after league officials Friday denied his
appeal of a one-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   The match starts at 7:30 p.m. Tickets remain available at the
stadium office.
</P>
<P>
   The league suspended Schmid and fined him $1,000 after he
criticized the referees and dared MLS to fine him following the
Galaxy's loss to D.C. United in November's MLS Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid complained about the lack of fouls in the Galaxy's 2-0
loss to United, particularly the non-call when United's Roy
Lassiter shoved Robin Fraser to the turf, resulting in Fraser
suffering a broken collarbone. Schmid also was upset when no foul
was called when Cobi Jones was taken down in the penalty area.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid earlier paid the fine, but he had appealed the
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suspension is consistent with past instances concerning
verbal abuse of the referees,'' Joe Machnik, vice president of MLS
game operations, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid said he felt the suspension should have been overturned.
</P>
<P>
   ``My point on the appeal is that it was something last season so
why start off the new season with a cloud over us?'' Schmid
explained. ``We're trying to look optimistically at a new season.
I've learned my lesson and I'll be quiet in the future with the
referees.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Ralph Perez will assume control of the team
tonight as the Galaxy tries to erase the bad memories of the United
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado enters the match in miserable shape. The Rapids were
swept by the Galaxy in the first round of last season's MLS
playoffs and bring an MLS-record 679-minute scoreless streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Rapids acquired Adin Brown, Jason Moore and Henry Zambrano
in the off-season, but at least nine of their 20 players are
injured.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy will probably be without Fraser, a four-time MLS
All-Star. He is nursing a groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid said he will likely start Ezra Hendrickson and Joey
Franchino as the outside backs, with Greg Vanney and Paul Caligiuri
at central defense.
</P>
<P>
   Midfield playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos enters in terrific shape.
He'll be joined by Danny Pena, Simon Elliott and Roy Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Up front, Clint Mathis will play alongside Jones. Newcomer Sasha
Victorine from UCLA is expected to get plenty of playing time as a
substitute in an attacking midfield role.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he'll have a view from high above, Schmid said
season openers are tough to gauge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always an uncertainty because nobody's quite sure what
the other team has, so you're guessing a little bit about your
opponents,'' said Schmid. ``Everybody's not sure what stage they're
at physically, mentally and so forth.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Schmid isn't worried about Cienfuegos.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be with the team from the beginning helps, especially for
me because I need to read people,'' said Cienfuegos, who was a
training camp holdout last season. ``Last year I didn't produce my
usual output. Hopefully I can get off to a good start and get eight
to 10 goals this season and my usual assists.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mexican striker Carlos Hermosillo finishing his career in
Mexico and without a replacement from the league Schmid's biggest
concern is scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see us score goals on a consistent basis,'' said
Schmid. ``Goals change the complexity of the game, it makes
everything else sort of fit into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping Cobi can have the type of year he had in 1998 (19
goals, 13 assists) and have the great finishing he's had with the
(U.S.) National team recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also need Clint to get 10 to 15 goals and we need five to
10 goals from Roy.''
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S GAME: Colorado Rapids vs. Galaxy, Rose Bowl, 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SERIES: Galaxy won it in 1999, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   RADIO: KTNQ 1020-AM (Spanish); LA talk 1110-AM (English)
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION: Fox Sports Net
</P>
<P>
   GALAXY UPDATE: Team officials expect a crowd of 15,000 to 20,000
for tonight's season opener. The Galaxy is the consensus pick to
win the Western Division, despite the lack of a top quality foreign
striker. Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid, who will serve a one-game
suspension for his comments about the officiating in November's MLS
Cup, said league officials are close to signing a striker from
Mexico. However, deals for Luis Hernandez, Jose Manuel Abundis and
Franicisco Palencia have apparently fallen through.
</P>
<P>
   RAPIDS UPDATE: After a great start in 1999, Colorado finished
the season with a 679-minute scoreless streak, which included
back-to-back shutout losses to the Galaxy in the first round of the
playoffs. Colorado's biggest acquisition in the off-season was
midfielder Henry Zambrano, but injuries in the preseason will make
the first month tough for the Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   Fred J. Robledo
</P>
</TEXT>
