<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Old Man And the Sette &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ernest Hemingway Collection of home furnishings broke new
ground when it was introduced last May. It was the first in memory
to be named for a literary figure. Sales were so hot that Brian
Carroll of Furniture Today, a trade publication, called it one of
the most successful new lines in industry history. Since then,
consumers have frequently stopped in to Ethan Allen stores to ask
about the line.
</P>
<P>
   The only trouble is, it is made by Thomasville Furniture, not
Ethan Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Adams, Thomasville's senior vice president for marketing,
can laugh about the confusion because sales are so strong: $100
million retail in the first year, twice the industry benchmark for
a big success and by far the best ever for Thomasville.
</P>
<P>
   He said the mix up might be attributable to Ethan Allen far
outspending Thomasville's $25 million annual advertising budget and
the fact that Ethan Allen is better known to consumers. Ethan Allen
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Licensing is hot in home furnishings, but the licensed names are
usually those of designers like Alexander Julian. Hemingway was far
from an obvious choice: ``Let's face it, the guy's got some
baggage,'' Carroll said. ``But the romance of it took off.''
</P>
<P>
   So is an F. Scott Fitgerald line far behind? Marla A. Metzner,
president of Fashion Licensing of America, the New York agency that
works with both authors' estates, said she was already working on
it.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Winters Lauro &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How You Know It's Time to Sell &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That BMW was able to find someone willing to take Rover off its
hands surprised many in the auto industry. But few captured its
motivation quite as succinctly as Car, the British auto magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Its March issue, printed weeks before a deal was in sight,
observed: ``It's a scary thought, but if BMW had paid each of
Rover's employees 30,000 pounds to stay at home last year, the
company would have lost less money.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine also said BMW had an offer from Volkswagen to swap
Rover for equity stakes in Seat, Audi and Skoda, but no cash.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence M. Fisher
</P>
</TEXT>
