<SLUG> BC-FRUIT-IRELAND-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD TIMES PROVE BRIEF FOR AN IRISH FACTORY TOWN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This is a sidebar to FRUIT-OF-THE-LOOM)  
 (af)  
 By BRIAN LAVERY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILFORD, Ireland _ The old Fruit of the Loom plant here is a
short walk from the center of town, just past an elementary school,
on a winding country road lined with stone walls and tumbling
yellow gorse bushes.
</P>
<P>
   Employees used to joke about how the factory windows overlooked
the white and black crosses of the local cemetery. Now the
symbolism is too rich to mention without a bitter grin.
</P>
<P>
   The plant is one of four Fruit of the Loom sites that closed
last year in County Donegal. More than half of the company's
roughly 2,000 Irish employees have lost their jobs in the turmoil
that has accompanied its Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its remote location in the north of Ireland and its
proximity to sectarian violence, Donegal has seldom enjoyed
prosperous times. But Fruit of the Loom's arrival in 1987 seemed a
godsend.
</P>
<P>
   ``People saw a light at the end of the tunnel,'' said Bridie
Burns, who worked for 12 years at the principal location, in the
town of Buncrana. ``There was nothing else there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the locals' role as a tiny cog in the global economy has
hit home. ``The rag trade is a risky business,'' said Jim Sheridan,
a county councilor in Buncrana. ``People came to terms with the
fact that a multinational has a certain life span.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything started on the right foot, as Fruit of the Loom
acquired W.P. McCarter &AMP; Co., a textile manufacturer. John
McCarter, who with his brother Willy had taken over the company
from their uncle, described the combination as ``a very willing and
good match'' _ a partnership to jump-start the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   By maintaining impeccable labor relations and a commitment to
local communities, Fruit of the Loom tied itself to the region. It
sponsored soccer teams and St. Patrick's Day parades.
</P>
<P>
   McCarter and his brother were ousted from the company six years
later in an episode that Burns compared to ``a death in the
family.'' But workers and union officials attribute the company's
woes to vague management issues like poor communication and a
failure to motivate workers, not on William F. Farley and his
executive team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't criticize Farley, because he came from America and
put this here, and we got 12 good years out of it,'' said Nuala
Lynch, a union steward at the plant in Malin Head.
</P>
<P>
   Only sewing plants have been closed _ leaving behind industrial
operations like dyeing and spinning. Nearly all who lost their jobs
are women. Now living on generous severance packages, most families
have yet to feel the economic impact. But they are anxious about
the future.
</P>
<P>
   When she was laid off in January, Eithne Fullerton, 60, had
spent 28 years working for the McCarter Co. and Fruit of the Loom,
earning a little over $300 a week. Her 27-year-old son, Patrick,
who has worked at the Buncrana plant since he was 14, sometimes
brings home more than $375 a week, but he is moving out soon to get
married. Her husband hasn't worked in 18 years, after two hip
replacements.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment in Donegal at 22 percent _ compared with a
national average of less than 5 percent _ emigration again
threatens to depopulate the region. The Irish government, which
owns the closed plants, is busily courting new employers and hopes
to retrain residents to work in tourism and information
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, some of the laid-off workers, aware that Irish
cities are thriving, say Dublin's efforts are too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that the government have forgotten about this part of
the world,'' said Lynch, 47, now working part time as a substitute
clerk in the post office in Malin. ``They promised us the sun, the
moon, and the stars, and we haven't seen any one of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
