<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRUIT-FARLEY-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOTSTRAPPING ACQUISITIONS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This is a sidebar to FRUIT-OF-THE-LOOM)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1976, William F. Farley took over his first company, buying
the Anaheim Citrus Corp. for $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Just $25,000 was his own money; the rest was borrowed. In 1985,
he vaulted into the pantheon of corporate raiders when, backed by
Drexel Burnham Lambert, he bought Northwest Industries Inc., the
Chicago-based conglomerate that owned Fruit of the Loom.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, again with backing from Drexel, he undertook a
$3 billion hostile takeover of West Point-Pepperell Inc., the
textile maker in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Farley won control of the company, but the deal ended in
disaster after the collapse of the junk bond market in the early
1990s. Both West Point-Pepperell and Farley's holding company,
Farley Inc., were forced into Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was that his only setback. Condec, a defense contractor he
controlled, sought bankruptcy protection in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   And the Acme Boot Co., which Fruit of the Loom sold to Farley in
1987, suffered huge losses in the late 1990s, before Farley sold it
off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2218EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
