<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-17 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION: REFLECTING ON A PAPAL APOLOGY IN VIEW OF AN ABIDING
TENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Certain images stand out in the long stretches of papal history:
Henry IV of Germany barefoot in the snow begging pardon from Pope
Gregory VII at Canossa in 1077. Pope Urban II preaching at Clermont
in France and opening the era of crusades in 1095. A reluctant Pius
VII pressed to officiate in 1804 as Napoleon crowned himself
emperor of the French in the Cathedral of Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Five decades ago, before the genial John XXIII and the
globe-trotting John Paul II, those were formative images in the
Roman Catholic memory, telling a story of medieval triumph and
modern frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Will the image of Pope John Paul II praying before a
15th-century crucifix in St. Peter's Basilica and asking
forgiveness for the sins of the church over two millennia _ an
image so contradictory to those earlier conjunctions of papacy and
political power _ earn a similar place in Catholicism's history?
</P>
<P>
   Roman Catholic leaders hope so. But they are up against a
culture that tosses such moments into a media blender and reduces
them to a mixture of spectacle and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the immediate response to the papal confession was not
at all hostile, just utterly predictable. It was almost
choreographed, the way presidential debates and election nights
have become, with the commentators chattering and the spinmeisters
quick to nudge the event into their particular agendas, from
condemning Pope Pius XII to promoting abortion rights, gay rights
and the ordination of women.
</P>
<P>
   Was anyone really to blame for this? It is just the way the
system works, and wouldn't it be irresponsible to fail to get a
word in while the opportunity was there? The church, too, had to
have its spokesmen and spinmeisters at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one longed for an interval of reflection, a time to let the
deed simply be itself before it was digested and explained and
criticized and enlisted in various causes. Perhaps the pope's act
might have even inspired other institutions to re-examine their own
historical consciences rather than congratulate themselves on their
own essential correctness.
</P>
<P>
   There was no question that the pope was breaking new ground. In
a lengthy treatise, ``Memory and Reconciliation: the Church and the
Faults of the Past,'' the Vatican's International Theological
Commission could find few precedents for the papal apology, even in
Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   One senses more than a little nervousness in that treatise,
especially on a point that also ran through much of the public
reaction: the pope expressed contrition for sins Christians had
committed in the church's name without ascribing sin to the church
itself. To critics, this was a bit of an evasion. To the Vatican
theologians, it was crucial. Perhaps it merely reveals the need for
new language in thinking about the church.
</P>
<P>
   From New Testament times, Christians have recognized sinfulness
in their ranks, even among their leaders. The idea that there had
been ``bad popes,'' for example, was long ago commonplace among
Catholic schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   But Christians have also believed that the church is more than a
purely human institution useful for individual religious purposes;
it is somehow a body infused with the very spirit of God, a
corporate extension of Christ on earth. The struggle to reconcile
the sinfulness of Christians with the holiness of the church has
produced a good many of Christianity's theological divisions.
</P>
<P>
   If a committee of Nobel Prize winners set out to apologize for
the sins of science, they would face a similar difficulty, although
on a more mundane level.
</P>
<P>
   They might examine the destructive power of military
technologies based on scientific knowledge. They might consider how
scientific theories bolstered racism and imperialism, how social
Darwinism contributed to Nazism, how popular notions of scientific
laws were used to justify Marxist dictatorship. They would have to
go beyond the craven or self-aggrandizing acts of individual
scientists. But they would almost certainly want to distinguish
between the scientific quest itself and specific distortions of it.
</P>
<P>
   At what point would that distinction become a way of relieving
science from the obligation to detect similar distortions in its
contemporary practice? That is the problem today for the Catholic
Church, and other religious groups like it. Though the bonds
linking members of the scientific community appear almost religious
at times, the church believes that those linking Christians are of
a far tighter sort that can properly be called mystical. This
magnifies the church's concern for the sins of its members
throughout history but can also distract it from exposing some
important sources of that sinfulness.
</P>
<P>
   The International Theological Commission's document, for
example, tends to describe the church only in terms of that
mystical dimension, on the one hand, or of individual members, on
the other. It leaves out the intermediate level of institutions and
practices that the social and political sciences have explored over
the last three centuries: the art, the lore, the customs, the
texts, the hymns, the preaching themes and catechism answers, the
structures of authority and decision making. These are no longer
exactly deeds, good or bad, they are the extensions of deeds in
time, or what the commission's study calls, very weakly,
``influences.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, a group of French bishops issued their own
``Declaration of Repentance,'' known as the Drancy Statement after
the train station from which Jews had been deported to
concentration camps. In it, they found much stronger language for
such institutionalized evils, referring, in connection with
anti-Semitism, to ``an underlying basic religious culture which
shaped and deformed peoples' attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   For Catholics and other Christians, the tension between
affirming the holiness of the church as Christ's body on earth and
confessing the sinfulness of individual Christians may never be
fully resolved. But the French bishops' language of ``basic
religious culture'' captures a reality that the International
Theological Commission's treatise misses. Catholics thinkers might
take note when they pursue the significance of Pope John Paul II's
unprecedented act.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
