   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- March 17, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 19 --
NITEOUT-LIFESTYLE-FILM -- David Schisgall, director of ``The
Lifestyle,'' a new documentary about swingers in the suburbs that
opened Thursday night at the Pioneer Theater in the East Village.
The premiere and the post-screening celebration at Two Boots
restaurant drew a large crowd from the independent film scene.
Young men in heavy black spectacles, and the young women who love
them, were everywhere. (Norman Y. Lono/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- March 17, 2000 -- GUNS-SMITH -- President
Clinton announces an agreement between the federal government and
Smith &AMP; Wesson, the nation's largest gun manufacturer, on gun
safety, Friday in the Oval office. Smith &AMP; Wesson agreed to provide
safety locks on its handguns within 60 days and to make them
child-resistant within a year. Looking on are, from left front row,
Treasury Secretary Larry Summers, Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart
Eizenstat, Domestic Policy Advisor Bruce Reed, and Housing and
Urban Development Secretary Andrew Cuomo. (Susana Raab/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- March 17, 2000 -- ST-PATRICKS-PARADE-2 --
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York, center, running for the U.S.
Senate, greets parade watchers as he marched up Fifth Avenue during
the St. Patrick's Day parade, Friday. Behind Giuliani is Gov.
George Pataki of New York. Taking a swipe at his Democratic rival
for the Senate, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, Giuliani told
reporters that he hoped she did not get lost during her march in
the parade. (Ruby Washington/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- March 17, 2000 -- ST-PATRICKS-PARADE-1 --
First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, center, running for the U.S.
Senate seat from New York, waves to the crowd as she takes part in
the St. Patrick's Day parade, Friday. Clinton is flanked by Peter
Valone, speaker of the New York City Council, left, and former
Mayor Ed Koch, right, in white sweater and cap. (Ruth Fremson/New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- March 17, 2000 -- CIA-PROPAGANDA-B&AMP;W -- Many
people remember reading George Orwell's ``Animal Farm'' in high
school or college, with its chilling finale in which the farm
animals looked back and forth at the tyrannical pigs and the human
farmers but found it ``impossible to say which was which.'' That
ending was altered in the 1955 animated version, which removed the
humans, leaving only the nasty pigs. Another example of Hollywood
butchering great literature? Yes, but in this case the film's
secret producer was the Central Intelligence Agency. (RD-DR
Corp./The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ATLANTA -- March 17, 2000 -- RAP-BROWN-MAIN-COX -- Police
search for a gunman in downtown Atlanta late Thursday night after
two sherrif's deputies were shot while serving a warrant. The two
deputies were seriously wounded while serving a warrant at the home
of Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, known in the 1960s as H. Rap Brown, a
leader of the Black Panther party now a Muslim cleric. The gunman
escaped after the shooting, and sheriff's officials said they were
looking for Al-Amin. (Sunny Sung/Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ATLANTA -- March 17, 2000 -- RAPBROWN-SHOOTING -- Jamil
Abdullah Al-Amin, known in the 1960s as H. Rap Brown, a leader of
the Black Panther party now a Muslim cleric, in a 1999 file photo
during a court appearance on charges involving aggravated assault
and gun possession in connection with a shooting. Two sheriff's
deputies were shot and seriously wounded near downtown Atlanta late
Thursday night while serving a warrant at Al-Amin's home. Officials
said they did not know whether Al-Amin shot the two deputies. The
gunman escaped after being wounded by one of the deputies, and
sheriff's officials said they were looking for Al-Amin. (Phil
McCollum/Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
