<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS MAY LEARN FROM LATEST SETBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. - Now that the Lakers' incredible 19-game
winning streak is over, the focus again moves from consistency to
resiliency.
</P>
<P>
   When their 16-game streak ended in January, the loss spun the
Lakers into a 3-6 slide. Did they learn enough from that experience
to avoid a repeat?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tune in. Tune in, you'll see,'' said Rick Fox. ``I think we've
made strides from that point in our season. That's why they play
the games. Because nothing is given or guaranteed. The Washington
(Wizards), a team that struggled all year, can beat you. And
there's other teams out there that if you give the same effort,
they'll beat you too.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood after the Lakers arrived in Michigan, just hours after
Thursday night's streak-busting loss at Washington, was generally
upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, the focus of winning a championship has
kind of overshadowed any focus in here on the streaks, the two
streaks,'' Fox said. ``We really didn't talk about it. I don't mean
to disappoint anybody, we were aware of it, but it wasn't a focal
point for us every time we stepped on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you'd like to finish the season undefeated. That would
have gotten us the ultimate streak. But I think we were well aware
that there was going to be a point where we had to learn another
lesson the hard way.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson doesn't see anything to be gleaned from how
the Lakers responded, or failed to, when the 16-game streak ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you just have to play,'' he said. ``I don't think there's
anything that remotely resembles it. This is a road trip and a trip
that very obviously (includes) all qualified teams, playoff teams
that we play from here on out.''
</P>
<P>
   The five-game, eight-day trips wraps up with back-to-back games
in New York and Miami on Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Shaquille O'Neal continues to play through the
discomfort of a sore right hamstring, with little opportunity for
rest, but Jackson said he's not concerned about it long-term.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's moving pretty well. I think he knows where to take a
little less energy in the game and what to use as an offensive
thrust in the game,'' Jackson said. He called the nature of the
injury ``something that could ebb as time goes on, but it shouldn't
be recurring.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jackson is weighing whether to put Ron Harper on the
injured list to give resuscitate him for the postseason. Harper's
minutes and production are down lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've done in the past with Ron, if he feels
that it's necessary to do that,'' Jackson said of putting him on
IL. ``We'll discuss that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
