<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- March 17, 2000 -- ST-PATRICKS-PARADE-4 --
Bagpipers, majorettes and the two candidates for a United States
Senate seat marched up Fifth Avenue in the St. Patrick's Day
parade. It has always been a must stop for candidates on New York's
political circuit, but Friday the parade turned into the Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and Hillary Rodham Clinton show as the two
contenders for the United States Senate marched in separate
contingents on a raw day that turned the knees of bare-legged
majorettes bright red. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) UNDATED -- March 17, 2000 -- GUNS-SMITH-2 -- Smith &AMP;
Wesson, the nation's oldest and largest manufacturer of handguns,
agreed Friday to accept a wide array of restrictions on the way it
makes, sells and distributes hundreds of thousands of handguns each
year in exchange for ending some lawsuits that had threatened to
bankrupt it. One stipulation of the new agreement is that all of
its new revolvers, like this one, will come with a lock that
prevents the trigger from being pulled. (Phillippe Diederich/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
