<P>
   (NYT28) WATERBURY CENTER, Vt. -- March 17, 2000 -- VT-GAYS --
The Vermont House of Representatives approved a bill creating
``civil unions'' for same-sex couples Thursday night. If the bill
is passed into law as expected and takes effect in September, gay
couples - like Robert Dostis, left, and Chuck Kletecka of Waterbury
Center - would be granted virtually all the state rights, benefits
and responsibilities that heterosexual spouses have, in areas from
child custody to probate law. (Paul O. Boisvert/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) SAN FRANCISCO -- March 17, 2000 -- TECHNOLOGY-FUTURE --
Bill Joy wrote ``Why the Future Doesn't Need Us,'' an article which
appeared in Wired, a magazine that is more used to celebrating the
brave new wired world. Joy, who is a co-founder and chief scientist
of Sun Microsystems and one of the most respected idea men in the
computer field, argues that risks are not only latent in
technology, but in certain celebrations of technology. The dangers
lie not in our technology but in ourselves. (Thor Swift/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) MIDDLETOWN, Conn. -- March 17, 2000 --
CLOTHING-OPTIONAL-DORM --Martha Reicher, a freshman at Wesleyan, in
the hallway of her residence hall, which is often dubbed The Naked
Dorm. Reicher was ecstatic when Wesleyan accepted her, and doubly
thrilled when she was assigned to her first choice for a residence
hall, a place called West College. She had been particularly drawn
to West College because it advertised itself as a diverse,
multicultural, politically active dorm. Reicher thought it would be
a welcome change from her hometown. Just how different was clearly
evident within her first 24 hours. (James Estrin/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- March 17, 2000 -- PAINTINGS-PHOTOS -- ``The
