<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLS-PREVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEASON BEGINS, WITH CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
A remodeled and restructured Major League Soccer will start its
fifth season Saturday with four games, but a number of the league's
international players will not be on display until next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After operating with two conferences for four years, the league
has divided its 12 teams into three divisions, a development that
should inject some excitement into what had become a predictable
regular season, with teams like D.C. United and Chicago regularly
qualifying for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Under Don Garber, who replaced Doug Logan last summer as
commissioner, the league has taken drastic steps to play soccer the
way it is elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans in America follow soccer the way it is played across the
globe,'' he said. ``Our core audience has spoken, and we
listened.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no longer shootouts, which means there will be tie
games if no team scores in a 10-minute sudden-death overtime.
Another major change is that the clock will run from zero upward
instead of from 45:00 down, and the referee will keep the official
time on the field, with injury time added.
</P>
<P>
   The new division alignment is intriguing because five wild-card
teams will join the division winners in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars, who had the league's worst record (7-25) last
season and missed the playoffs, have undergone the most drastic
renovation. Their biggest acquisition is Lothar Matthaus of
Germany. They will open the season March 26 in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars are in the Eastern Division with D.C. United,
Miami and New England. The Central Division has Chicago, Columbus,
Dallas and Tampa Bay; Colorado, Kansas City, Los Angeles and San
Jose make up the Western Division.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago will open the season Saturday afternoon in Dallas. The
three other games will be played Saturday night, with Colorado at
Los Angeles, Columbus at Tampa Bay and New England at Miami.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
