<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0669 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-STUDENT-ATTACKPLOT18-     03-17 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-ATTACKPLOT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida student avoids jail in plot to kill
 &HT;    By John Pacenti
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Shoulders slumped and eyes downcast,
Derik Lehman held his mother's hand in the back of the courtroom
until his name was called.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the bulky teen-ager _ reportedly tormented by his peers
because of his weight _ lumbered forward and, in a voice barely
above a whisper, told a judge why he planned meticulously to kill
dozens of his classmates, why he wished to re-create the massacre
of Columbine High at his own school in Royal Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very angry,'' Lehman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At who?'' asked Circuit Judge Howard Berman.
</P>
<P>
   ``At everyone,'' the 17-year-old responded as his parents,
Christine and John Lehman, looked on.
</P>
<P>
   It was a prelude to Lehman pleading guilty ``in his own best
interest'' Friday to solicitation to shoot into a building in
exchange for five years of probation packed with special
conditions. If he successfully completes probation, he will have no
criminal record. If not, he could face up to five years in prison
for the third-degree felony.
</P>
<P>
   The dozen conditions imposed on Lehman include six months of
house arrest, mandatory psychological counseling, court-imposed
expulsion from Royal Palm Beach High School, no access to the
Internet and a curfew until his 19th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he wanted the teen monitored by GPS, a satellite
tracking system, while he's on house arrest ``because I want to
make sure we know where he is at all times.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a nationwide epidemic of school shootings like
Columbine's in Colorado last year, Lehman's attorney said she felt
it would have been impossible to seat an impartial jury for
Lehman's trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a troubled young man and this is a cry for help,''
attorney Michelle Suskauer said. ``He never intended to hurt
anyone. They were just words.''
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager, a junior, was charged as an adult after several
of his friends said he approached them in early February for
weapons and help in carrying out a siege of the school. He has been
ordered to stay away from those friends as well.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman eventually turned over his diary _ titled with the German
phrase meaning ``No Mercy'' _ in which he praised Adolf Hitler and
the suicidal gunmen responsible for the 12 student deaths at
Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Palm Beach teen-ager also possessed a detailed map of
the school building with notes in the margins, such as:
``Objective: Destroy every human in the way. Purpose: for cleansing
and for the sheer hell of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a factor of many things that built up and I exploded in
this wrong way,'' he told the judge Friday, adding he wished that
he had reacted ``in a more peaceful way, not (with) such a violent
attitude toward people.''
</P>
<P>
   NO `WELCOME BACK' BY SCHOOLS
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors decided to charge Lehman as an adult because it was
the only way to keep him on probation for five years, Assistant
State Attorney Al Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a thin line between thinking about a crime, fantasizing
about a crime and committing a crime,'' he said. ``If there is a
silver lining here, it is that the other students came forward. The
students who came forward were the real heroes of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman's praise of Hitler led prosecutors to demand as part of
his probation that he attend a Holocaust education program. His
parents have already been trying to find such a class, Suskauer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's sentence leaves open the door that Lehman could attend
another Palm Beach County school, possibly an alternative one, if
invited.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it, said Jake Sello, associate superintendent of
the school district. ``I don't think you'd have a school that would
say you're welcome to come here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   MOM: `I CAN'T TAKE THIS'
</P>
<P>
   The district has begun the process to expel the boy from all of
its schools, Sello said. The expulsion, which must be voted on by
the school board, would bar Lehman from school from the day of the
vote through the end of that school year and up to one more school
year.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman might be a candidate for a proposed program monitored by
the sheriff's office in which expelled students would take classes,
possibly at the jail, Sello said.
</P>
<P>
   Suskauer said the Lehmans simply want to get their only child
the help he needs so he can move on to college and eventually a
productive life. She said the ordeal has put the close-knit family
through a tremendous strain.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Lehman was very protective of her son as he left
court, screaming at television cameras to leave him alone. ``I
can't take this anymore,'' she told her husband, John, as they
entered the elevators to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post staff writer Sonja Isger contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   PROBATION TERMS
</P>
<P>
   _ Have no contact with Royal Palm Beach High School.
</P>
<P>
   _ Have no 'uninvited' contact with any Palm Beach County school.
</P>
<P>
   _ Write an apology to the administration and students of Royal
Palm Beach High School.
</P>
<P>
   _ Honor a 10 p.m. curfew on weeknights, midnight on weekends
until his 19th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make every effort to obtain high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   _ Possess no weapons of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pay $361 in court costs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
