<SLUG> BC-BOEING-STRIKE-AHEAD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING WILL NEED TIME TO HEAL AFTER STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ One of largest white-collar strikes in U.S. history
left scars on The Boeing Co. that will not soon fade away.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts don't expect any shakeup of top management
because of the strike, but they agreed with striking engineers that
it will take time to heal the wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Far more than Boeing's production system was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Some engineers and technical workers on strike said Friday that
resentment toward top management will linger long after they return
to work, assuming the proposed contract is approved.
</P>
<P>
   They also expressed anger and ill-will toward some colleagues
who crossed picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that will still be lingering by the end of
the year,'' said Christopher Matthews, a technical designer.
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight other people he worked with, Matthews said, six
went back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be hard to work with them,'' he said. ``But it will be
doubly hard because no one will want to associate with my group
because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron Callan, an analyst with Merrill Lynch who closely follows
Boeing, said the strike could have been far more damaging to Boeing
had it continued for several more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing dodged a bullet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Had the strike continued for five or six more weeks, he said,
there likely would have been calls for a management shakeup by
concerned shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But Callan doesn't see that happening now.
</P>
<P>
   What happens over the next couple of weeks will be crucial if
Boeing is to put the strike behind it and get on with the business
of building airplanes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will have to do a little hand holding,'' he said of the
company. ``I would hope they can get things going again. They were
showing good momentum in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   But he noted that while he and other analysts looked at Boeing's
financial results and saw improvement, it's now clear that not
everyone in the company had gotten on the Boeing bandwagon and was
enjoying the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the numbers but we don't see the people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The most lasting benefit of the strike, he said, may be that the
engineers finally got Boeing's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Or as a senior engineer on Boeing's 777 program put it Friday:
``We are not the center of the universe, but this strike showed we
drive parts of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The engineer, a veteran of 22 years with Boeing who asked not to
be quoted by name, has been with the 777 program from the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started the program Phil and Alan ran the show,'' he
said, referring to Boeing Chairman Phil Condit and Alan Mulally,
head of the company's commercial airplane operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a family attitude back then. It felt like we were
all part of a family.''
</P>
<P>
   That has changed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upper management today seems to be profit driven,'' he said,
reflecting a view shared by many other striking engineers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To run this company, they need the employees,'' he said. `They
have to look past the profits. ... They seem to have forgotten what
it's like to be a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Matthews, the engineer said he will find it difficult to
work alongside some colleagues who crossed the picket line for
reasons other than economic hardship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know who went back,'' he said. ``Some went back to work
the next day. They talked loud and didn't do anything. There were a
couple guys in my work group who said they were for the strike but
then they went back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be animosity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
