<HEADLINE>
EL-AMIN INJURED AS UCONN ELIMINATES UTAH STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Connecticut savored a tangible size advantage
over Utah State in its first-round tournament game Friday, but that
was not all. The Huskies were quicker, better rebounders, craftier
shooters and, certainly, more tournament-tested.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder that, except for a hiccup or two, the Huskies won
their first game in the South Regional of the NCAA tournament,
75-67, before 11,061 fans at the Birmingham-Jefferson Civic Center.
Connecticut easily took a first step toward defending its national
title, but its next one could be more wobbly.
</P>
<P>
   That is because it might advance without its commandeering point
guard, Khalid El-Amin, who injured his right ankle late in the
game, left, returned to play on it for a few moments and then left
for good. After the game, El-Amin had the ankle on ice and in
thick, brown, elastic bandages that made his right foot look nearly
the size of a basketball.
</P>
<P>
   With Tennessee looming _ it advanced by frustrating
Louisiana-Lafayette, 63-58, in the opening game here Friday _
Connecticut hopes that El-Amin can quickly recover for what should
be a ferocious fling with the Volunteers here on Sunday. Tennessee
is 25-6. Connecticut is 25-9. Power teams from the Southeastern and
Big East Conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get hit, I just tried to reverse pivot and dribble
back out,'' El-Amin said, explaining his injury. ``I heard and felt
something snap and I called a timeout. They called it a high ankle
sprain. It is hurting right now, but hopefully I will be ready
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin was injured with 3 minutes 57 seconds left and with his
team ahead, 65-54. Why did he return? ``It was still sore, but you
know how coach is,'' El-Amin said. ``I just tried to go back in,
and I really wanted to see how bad it was.''
</P>
<P>
   His coach, Jim Calhoun, said his team would prepare two game
plans for Tennessee: one with El-Amin, one without. ``If Khalid
cannot play, the game plan will be different,'' Calhoun said. ``The
plan is going to be predicated on Khalid. We thought he was well
enough to go back in, and you never know about those kind of
injuries unless you play on them. We just beat a team that was
small and quick, and now in Tennessee we have to face a team that
is big and physical. We did some good things today at the start of
the game. Utah State, regardless of who it was playing, had been
able to create tempo. Today, we did that. We played the kind of
game we're capable of on defense and we had a couple of veterans
who know how to defend and lead us at the end. Tournament
experience helps.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior forward Kevin Freeman (13 points) made 6 of 8 shots
and grabbed eight rebounds. His put-back basket _ a leap in the
lane and a twisting, flying rebound and dunk off guard Tony
Robertson's missed shot _ put Connecticut ahead by 11 points with
5:26 left. The senior center Jake Voskuhl made 4 of 5 shots and
finished with eight points.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Edmund Saunders complemented both with nine points and
eight rebounds in the best bench play of the game. El-Amin scored
14 and so did guard Albert Mouring in a game-high 38 minutes
played.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut made 10 steals, forced 15 turnovers and won in
rebounds (37-22) and in floor shooting (48.3 percent to 45.5
percent). Forward Troy Rolle led Utah State with 18 points, but
like most of the Aggies he nearly always had a hand in his face or
a grinding bump on his hip when attempting to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had mini-runs but we couldn't pull even or get ahead,''
said coach Stew Morrill of Utah State.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut sped to a 31-16 lead en route to a 39-29 lead at
halftime. Utah State (28-6) rallied to trail by only 39-37 in the
opening minutes of the second half, but Connecticut quickly
increased the lead again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
