<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE IGNORED IN KNIGHT'S SHADOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. - Pepperdine might be the most obscure team
playing in the East Regional. The fact that the Waves played
Indiana, one of the giants of college basketball, on Friday night
in the first round just seemed to illustrate that point even more.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Buffalo News described Pepperdine as ``a virtually
anonymous regional program that every once in awhile receives an
(NCAA) invitation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waves' lack of national recognition was never more evident
then their Thursday media session, which followed Indiana's.
</P>
<P>
   When Hoosiers coach Bob Knight addressed the press, 200
reporters were present. However, when Pepperdine coach Jan van
Breda Kolff spoke a few minutes later, only about 20 stuck around
to listen.
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff, who stood in the hallway near the media room as
Knight held court, couldn't help but notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where'd everybody go?'' van Breda Kolff asked as he sat down.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy hitters: One writer Knight likely avoided was John
Feinstein, author of the controversial ``A Season on the Brink: A
Year with Bob Knight and the Indiana Hoosiers.'' Knight was upset
with the book because Feinstein did not omit Knight's foul
language.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein is working on a book about the Patriot League. That
brings him to Buffalo with Lafayette University, which fell on
Friday to Temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I did the book on Army-Navy, I was struck by the kids and
their lack of feeling of entitlement that you usually find with
college athletes,'' Feinstein said. ``I was at Layfayette the day
of the New Hampshire primary and the kids in the locker room were
saying `Wow, did you really think McCain was going to beat Bush by
that much?' If I was in an ACC locker room they wouldn't care about
McCain or Bush unless they could shoot the 3.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no truth to the rumor that Bush can take his man off the
dribble, but is an average outside shooter, at best.
</P>
<P>
   Surf's not up, dude: When Pepperdine left California on
Wednesday, it was sunny and warm. But it's still winter in most of
America, and the Waves found that out Thursday when more than four
inches of snow fell on Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a mild winter in these parts, so even residents of
Western New York were surprised at the snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to adjust and deal with it,'' said Pepperdine
forward Tommie Prince, who must have forgotten for a second that
basketball is played indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Late start: Knight was not happy with the scheduled 10:20 p.m.
EST tipoff Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any college basketball game should start after 9
p.m.,'' Knight said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
