<HEADLINE>
WHILE MLS CHANGES, BURN MAINTAINS A SOLID FOUNDATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday's kickoff of the 2000 season brings a mini-makeover for
Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   A new commissioner. Coaching changes. A revised format and a
shortened schedule. An influx of international players.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one team is keeping an early focus on what's
staying the same. The Dallas Burn has six players from its original
roster, the most of any team in the league, in hopes of finally
cracking into the MLS title game. The path to that goal begins
Saturday with the Burn's 3:30 p.m. season opener against the
Chicago Fire at the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Such thinking is necessary, Burn coach Dave Dir says, because he
is depending on as many as 10 players who have been with the team
for two seasons or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the most difficult part of change,'' said Dir, the
league's only coach with his original team. ``We have a certain way
we expect things here, and when you have a lot of new players,
sometimes they don't bring that to practice. Things have to be
learned from the veterans, and that's part of the reason that
veterans are so critical to the makeup of teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Kreis, Ted Eck, Brian Haynes, Brandon Pollard, Richard
Farrer and Mark Santel remain from the original Burn squad. Dir
said leadership will be their most important role as the Burn comes
off its best season in franchise history _ a 19-13 overall record
and a trip to the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us are really vocal leaders,'' said Kreis, the league
most valuable player and scoring champion last season. ``We're just
guys that like to lay it down on the field and hopefully other
players can take the example from that. I think players respect
that more than us harping about what Dallas Burn soccer is all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to MVP Kries, the Burn also has Matt Jordan, who was
selected as one of three finalists for the league goalkeeper of the
year. Jordan finished with a team-record 1.08 goals-against average
with 11 shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   Two more young players _ Aleksey Korol and Bobby Rhine _ should
have plenty of opportunities to contribute at forward.
</P>
<P>
   Rhine scored two goals in his first MLS start last season and
played well off the bench, setting a team record with five goals
for a rookie. Dir has liked what he has seen so far from
first-round draft pick Korol. The Burn will need the young duo's
offense, particularly with Graziani and Kreis likely to miss
several games this season for U.S. national team duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``When myself and all the rookies last year saw how intense all
the training sessions were,'' Rhine said, ``we know now we have the
responsibility to contain that in matches and show guys that are in
their first year that they're responsible for that foundation as
well. Put together, everyone can learn.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
