<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0697 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BROWN-SHOOTING-2NDLD-     03-17 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-SHOOTING-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER ACTIVIST H. RAP BROWN SOUGHT FOR SHOOTING OFFICERS IN
ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Changes ``Wednesday'' to ``Thursday'' in 1st graf.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 1 and 2 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Muslim cleric formerly known as H. Rap Brown, a
leader of the Black Panthers in the 1960s, was the subject of an
intense citywide manhunt Friday after a Fulton County sheriff's
deputy said the cleric shot him and another deputy near downtown
Atlanta late Thursday. The second deputy died of his injuries
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The cleric, now known as Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, has lived in
relative peace in Atlanta's West End neighborhood after serving
five years behind bars in New York for attempted armed robbery.
Atlanta Police Chief Beverly Harvard said the deputy selected
Al-Amin's picture from a photo array as the man who fired an
assault rifle at the two deputies at close range. The department is
now seeking him on a murder warrant.
</P>
<P>
   One of the deputies, Ricky Kinchen, 35, lost most of his blood
at the scene and died at Grady Memorial Hospital on Friday
afternoon after undergoing three operations. The other deputy,
Aldranon English, 28, was less seriously wounded and was able to
describe the shooting incident to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   According to Harvard, the deputies, who are black, were
attempting to arrest Al-Amin on a warrant issued by suburban Cobb
County in January after Al-Amin failed to appear in court to answer
charges in connection with a traffic stop last May. Al-Amin had
been accused of driving a stolen Ford Explorer, having improper
insurance documents, and of impersonating a police officer by
flashing a fake badge and claiming he was a police officer in
Whitehall, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   The deputies _ who knew nothing of Al-Amin's background _ were
unable to find him at his house or his nearby grocery store when
they arrived at about 10:30 Wednesday, Harvard said, and were
circling the area when a black Mercedes pulled up near the rear of
the store. The deputies approached the car and asked the driver to
get out, which he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the deputies was concerned that he could not see the
person's hands after he had asked him to get out of the vehicle,''
Harvard said, apparently referring to the gunman's long coat. ``The
deputy then asked him to show his hands, and the person responded
by saying, `Okay, here they are.' And at that point in time, the
two sheriff's deputies were fired upon.'' One of the deputies also
managed to shoot the gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Police investigators later found shell casings from a
.223-caliber semi-automatic assault rifle and a 9-mm handgun. The
rifle's immense power apparently tore through the deputies'
bulletproof vests; one doctor at Grady told the sheriff's
department that the wounds reminded him of those seen in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   English was able to radio for help, but by the time the police
arrived, the gunman and the Mercedes were gone, and the deputies
could not get a license number. Harvard said police also found a
blood trail leading to a vacant house a block and a half away, but
no one was in the house. She said the deputies did not know whether
the bleeding gunman had fled on foot, or driven away, or whether a
second person might have moved the car. Late Friday, the police
said they were also looking for a green Toyota in connection with
the case, but would not explain the car's connection.
</P>
<P>
   Police and sheriff's investigators searched the four-block area
for hours last night with SWAT teams, dogs and helicopters, but the
gunman was not found. Now the search has been extended throughout
the city, she said, including airports and transportation hubs. The
Police Department later said a nationwide all-points bulletin had
been issued for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, H. Rap Brown's beret, goatee, and direct,
confrontational language made him one of the best-known leaders of
the Black Panther party. The Baton Rouge native had earlier been a
leader of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee,
registering voters in Alabama, but grew disenchanted with civil
disobedience and began advocating violence as justice minister of
the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be trying to love that honky to death,'' he told a crowd
in Cambridge, Md., in July 1967. ``Shoot him to death. Shoot him to
death, brother, because that's what he is out to do to you.'' A few
hours later, a riot began in the town during which police officers
and black residents exchanged gunfire. Brown was charged with
inciting a riot, and after being freed on bail, was later charged
with carrying a gun across state lines while under indictment. He
went underground and was captured in 1971, after a shootout with
police in a New York City bar in a botched robbery.
</P>
<P>
   He converted to Islam while serving time on the robbery charges
at Rikers Island in New York City, and moved to Atlanta after he
was paroled in 1976. Since then, he has become one of the city's
most prominent Muslim clerics, opening a Sunni mosque known as the
Community Masjid in a ramshackle house across from the shooting
site, and working with neighborhood leaders to help clean up the
impoverished area. His friends and colleagues said they thought he
had renounced violence, and found it hard to imagine that he would
have gunned down two law enforcement officers,
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a principled man, a no-nonsense man with strong beliefs,
but not a violent man,'' said William Abdur-Rahim, imam of the
Masjid Al-Muminun and a member of the city's police Civilian Review
Board who has known Al-Amin for 20 years. ``There are those who
believe he's been pursued for years by entities of law enforcement
who held grievances against him. But we just do not know what could
have happened here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
