</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: 2 POINT GUARDS, HAPPY TO BE IN BUFFALO IN MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Time is always running out on the point guard.
He is the one handling the ball with the clock winding down _ or
the game, or the season, or the career.
</P>
<P>
   Time was running out Friday for Shaheen Holloway and Speedy
Claxton, two point guards from Queens, paired in separate
doubleheaders.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway extended his career with a marvelous swerving jaunt
through the Oregon defense for a 72-71 overtime victory for Seton
Hall, which set up Sunday's meeting with Temple. Hours later,
Claxton's superb career at Hofstra ended with an 86-66 mismatch
loss to Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   When the pairings were announced last Sunday, it was immediately
evident that Buffalo was the bracket of the point guards. There was
Pepe Sanchez from that basketball hotbed of Bahia Blanca,
Argentina, leading Temple to a 73-47 victory against Lafayette
Friday with a 15-assist, zero-point tour de force.
</P>
<P>
   There was Doug Gottlieb, from that subway-deprived wasteland of
Orange, Calif., running Oklahoma State's offense against Hofstra.
And there was Michael Lewis from Jasper, Ind. (``I didn't know what
the word `pass' meant''), now the career leader in assists at
Indiana, playing in the nightcap against Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway and Claxton were the obvious bookends, two little guys
who talk fast and move fast, who learned the game in the
playgrounds of Queens, and then went their separate ways to the
suburbs. They come from the borough that produced Bob Cousy of
Andrew Jackson and Al Seiden of Jamaica and Kenny Anderson of
Molloy and a lot of other diminutive artistes.
</P>
<P>
   Claxton's family eventually moved to the suburbs of Hempstead, a
few miles farther out on Long Island, but he commuted to Christ the
King High in Queens, where he was a teammate of Erick Barkley, now
with St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   The other day somebody asked him if he was from the suburbs, and
Claxton blurted: ``I'm from Queens. That's where I learned to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged off the whispered offers of transfers to larger
so-called programs and he waited the full complement of four years
before he and Hofstra finally reached the tournament Friday night.
He scored 20 points, most of them when it was much too late.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway was a child prodigy. His uncle Eugene Holloway and his
brother, DeShawn, would escort him to games at St. John's, up on
the glacial hill above his own neighborhood, or take the E train
into the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing about Queens,'' he said. ``You can get
places. It's not like the suburbs.''
</P>
<P>
   People would introduce him to Boo Harvey and other players from
St. John's. One year, David Edwards from Andrew Jackson High played
for Georgetown, before John Thompson grew tired of his flash Queens
mentality. (In those pre-Iverson days, Thompson referred to point
guard individualism as ``doing the boogaloo.'') These players
greeted the little man named Shaheen as a prospect, and then his
family sent him to St. Patrick's in Elizabeth, N.J., to avoid the
pitfalls of playing at home.
</P>
<P>
   In his first three years at Seton Hall, Holloway did not play in
the national tournament, a major hole in his life. Last summer he
took a working vacation at another basketball outpost in
Bloomington, Ind., living with a relative and working out with a
few friends, never laying eyes on the Indiana coach, whom he
admires. Holloway came back in better shape than his own coach,
Tommy Amaker, had ever seen him.
</P>
<P>
   This year Seton Hall won 20 games, was chosen for an at-large
berth, and Holloway came up here bubbling. Other people might gripe
about snow-encrusted Buffalo, but for Holloway this was the town
where he would finally achieve his dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids cheering for me yesterday, that was great,'' he said.
``We watched St. John's on television last night, pulling one out.
It's just great to be part of the NCAA tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday he fell on his wrist late in the first half, iced it
up, and came back. With seconds left in overtime, the ball was in
his hands, and true to his roots, Holloway was going to perform the
boogaloo, take it from end to end, with the full blessing of his
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed three gamers this year,'' Holloway said later. ``I
had a shot like that against St. John's but coughed it up.''
</P>
<P>
   This time he darted around defenders like a man running to catch
the E train. He plunked the ball high off the backboard, whirled to
defend against Oregon's desperate heave and then exulted. He had
reversed the sand in the hourglass, but time is always running out
for point guards. They would have it no other way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
