<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ADS-685&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TV AD ATTACKS GORE, WHO SWIFTLY ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first engagement of what may be a long and nasty air war,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas unveiled a television commercial
Friday that attacked the Clinton administration's education
policies, saying that President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore
had failed in their effort to raise standards and close the
``achievement gap'' between rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the campaign's announcement, Gore's aides said
they would immediately begin running a spot answering the Bush
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush commercial says, ``Gore and Clinton had eight years,
but they've failed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore spot strikes back with an announcer saying: ``On the
issue of education, America deserves a real debate, not more
negative ads from George W. Bush. Al Gore is ready. Is George W.?''
</P>
<P>
   The 60-second Bush commercial was scheduled to be broadcast
Friday in six small and medium-size media markets in downstate
Illinois, which holds its presidential primaries on Tuesday. Gore's
aides said his advertisement would run with about the same
frequency in the same markets as the Bush spot.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said exposure
in the markets would spill over to viewers in three neighboring
states _ Iowa, Kentucky and Missouri _ that are considered to be
both significant and up for grabs in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer acknowledged that the amount and cost of the air time
was relatively small, which suggested to some political analysts
that the real target for the spot's message was the national press
corps, and the wider audience it commands.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of the advertisement, less than two months into
the primary election season, indicated how swiftly Bush and Gore
were moving to a full-throttle general election campaign. The early
attack and response is in part a function of the lessons learned in
previous contests, when candidacies suffered after the opposition
succeeded early in a campaign in defining a rival in unsympathetic
terms in the minds of many voters.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Warfield, a Republican consultant who was Bob Dole's
press secretary in the 1996 race, recalled on Friday the juncture
in the presidential contest when Dole began running spots for the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking much later,'' Warfield said. ``I think we're
talking late summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole did not respond quickly to the early television commercials
run on behalf of Clinton and Gore. The advertisements, for
instance, linked the Republican candidate to the policies of the
increasingly unpopular speaker of the House, Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went up very early with those issue ads that attacked
Dole and Gingrich together,'' Warfield said. ``It defined Dole very
effectively, and painfully, for the general election. They
destroyed our fighters on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign, eager to repel anything resembling a
pre-emptive strike, put together a responding advertisement in a
couple of hours on Friday, said Christopher Lehane, the campaign's
press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's telling and interesting,'' Lehane said, ``that the Bush
campaign with its first commercial of the general election launched
a negative ad. I think there is a bit of an irony here when Texas
is ranked 45th out of 50 in SAT scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's spot begins with a series of characterizations about the
ways in which the Clinton administration had ``failed'' on
educational issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Al Gore and Bill Clinton, national reading scores
stagnated,'' a narrator says. ``America's high school students
place almost dead last in international math tests. The achievement
gap between poor and nonpoor students remains wide.''
</P>
<P>
   It then describes Bush as being committed ``to challenge the
status quo with a crusade to improve education.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's commercial defends the administration's education record,
saying that he has fought for smaller classes and for the resources
to hire 100,000 new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   And it asserts that as an overseer of education in Texas, Bush
created ``an accountability system so full of cheating it's under
investigation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bob Chase, president of the National Education Association,
which endorsed Gore in the Democratic primary and made no
endorsement on the Republican side, said he was disturbed that
``the first ad out of the blocks is a negative ad,'' and that
education was the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer contended, however, that the Bush spot was generally
positive in tone and that it was never too early in a race to draw
distinctions on a critical social issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think eight months is that long a period to
discuss our nation's children,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
