<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0704 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-MIDWEST-ADVANCE-T     03-17 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIDWEST-ADVANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKY COULD BE VULNERABLE TO SYRACUSE COUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Kentucky has what Syracuse wants.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats, self-proclaimed team of the century, has one of
college basketball's most sparkling pedigrees. Kentucky has won 85
NCAA Tournament games, more than any program. Kentucky has made 41
NCAA appearances, winning seven titles.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse is the NCAA Tournament's answer to Avis. The Orangemen
have made it to the Final Four three times, reaching the
championship game twice under coach Jim Boeheim. Syracuse has more
NCAA victories (38) than any team that has never won a title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans will love to see Syracuse vs. Kentucky,'' said Orangemen
senior forward Ryan Blackwell. ``They're both well-recognized
schools, they have great traditions both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second round of the Midwest Region on Saturday,
fourth-seeded Syracuse (25-5) faces fifth-seeded Kentucky (23-9)
(KTVT/Channel 11 at noon). In the second game, top-seeded Michigan
State (27-7) takes on depleted Utah (23-8), the No. 8 seed.
</P>
<P>
   Both Syracuse and Kentucky believe that a deep tourney run is
possible. But the Orangemen would dearly love to become this year's
dark horse. Syracuse won its first 19 games and was the nation's
last undefeated team before going 5-5 to close the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're capable of pulling off some wins,'' said
Syracuse senior point guard Jason Hart. ``In the tournament, to win
it all you only need to win six straight. We won 19 straight; we
can get through six.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen, with three senior starters and solid depth, would
appear to have the edge on the Wildcats, who start one senior, a
junior, two sophomores and a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Hart averages 12.2 points and 6.4 assists per game. Senior
center Etan Thomas averages 14 points, 9.4 rebounds and 3.8 blocked
shots per game. They'll present serious challenges for Kentucky
junior point guard Saul Smith and senior center Jamaal Magloire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our heart has won games for us this year,'' said Magloire, who
averages 13.2 points and 9.1 rebounds per game. ``We've shown a lot
of character all season, and we're going to make a serious run in
this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people would agree with that statement. Kentucky has lost
nine players from its roster since the end of last season. The
latest was starter Desmond Allison, who was suspended before the
NCAA Tournament after being arrested on suspicion of driving under
the influence. The Wildcats have only two scholarship players on
their bench who have seen significant playing time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at us as Goliath,'' Kentucky coach Tubby Smith
said. ``We think we're more like David.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Syracuse's Boeheim said with a tired smile, ``if
that's true, they're pretty big Davids.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah relates to the whole David-Goliath analogy. The Utes lost
starting guard Jeremy Killion to a knee injury in their first-round
victory over Saint Louis. Starting center Nate Althoff re-injured
his back and is listed as questionable. That makes Michigan State a
daunting challenge for Utes coach Rick Majerus, who has a 17-8
record in NCAA Tournament games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sitting here with seven scholarship players, one of whom
has a stress fracture (Mike Puzey) in his leg,'' Majerus said. ``I
need to rally the troops, make sure they don't take a woe-is-me
posture. We've got to buck up and play with who we have. We know
what the task is.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
