<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-CREDITCARD-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN INDICTED IN WEB FRAUD AFTER LOSSES OF $1 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (js) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Brooklyn man known by his e-mail identities,
``Nestle Quik'' and ``Tha Baker,'' was indicted Friday on charges
of bilking online travel agencies out of at least $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Using free, hard-to-trace e-mail addresses, the man, Ashley
Simmons, 29, used stolen credit card numbers to purchase electronic
airline tickets, according to the federal indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Posing as a travel agent, Simmons, who has a history of credit
card fraud, then sold the tickets at a fraction of their value to
people he contacted via e-mail, the indictment says. Either he or
the purchasers would pick up the tickets at airports including La
Guardia and Kennedy International.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking into whether or not other people are involved,''
said Marshall Miller, an assistant U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The case came to light after the owners of the credit cards
found charges on their bills for unauthorized airline ticket
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Mukesh Chandrani of the Secret Service said the scheme worked in
part because Simmons' e-mail addresses, including
quik55(at)hotmail.com, thabaker(at)hotmail.com and
dabaker(at)gotoworld.com, were not easily traceable to his real
name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the larger lesson is to be wary of businesses using
free e-mail addresses,'' said Chandrani, special agent in charge of
the Secret Service office in New York. ``If you're a legitimate
business, and someone is able to do thousands, or even hundreds of
thousands of dollars in commerce with you, would that person need a
free e-mail address?''
</P>
<P>
   According to federal authorities, Simmons stole from several
Internet travel agencies. One of the victims was Expedia Inc.,
which is mostly owned by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   After discovering the fraud, Expedia began using software that
made it easier to detect suspicious activity, said Erik Blachford,
Expedia's vice president for marketing. The company also about
doubled its quarterly reserve to $1.1 million to cover such fraud.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of recent frauds like the one in which Simmons is
charged, Expedia announced earlier this month that it needed a
one-time reserve of $4 million to $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Blachford estimated the number of people who received fraudulent
credit card charges in the hundreds, not thousands, and he noted
that the security of the Expedia.com site and the information it
keeps on its customers had not been compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Under the indictment, Simmons was charged with unauthorized
credit card use and trafficking in unauthorized credit cards. If
convicted of both counts, he could be sentenced to 25 years in
prison and fined at least $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear where Simmons had obtained the credit card
numbers, said Bob Weaver, a Secret Service official and head of the
New York Electronic Crimes Task Force, although investigators
suspect he got them on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, who was convicted in 1996 of illegal use of credit
cards and mail fraud, was arrested on Feb. 18 in Miami as he
boarded a plane with an electronic ticket purchased with a stolen
American Express card number, according to the U.S. attorney's
office. He is in custody in southern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver said the agencies investigating the scam received a lot
of help from credit card companies and online travel agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these types of Internet e-commerce investigations, that's
the trick,'' he said. ``Who did it? Who's the real person? And
where is he?''
</P>
</TEXT>
