<HEADLINE>
BLUE SPRINGS MAN CHARGED WITH THREATENING PEOPLE ON JETLINER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICA WOOD, DONALD BRADLEY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Relatives and neighbors know Peter Bradley as a family man,
friendly neighbor and hard-working carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   But federal authorities said Friday the Blue Springs man was
responsible for a bizarre incident Thursday night aboard an Alaska
Airlines jet flying over the West Coast. Authorities accused him of
threatening to kill passengers and crew members before breaking
into the cockpit and attacking the crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to kill all of you...keep away from me,'' Bradley
reportedly said, simulating the shape of a gun with his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, 39, was tackled by fellow passengers and later charged
in U.S. District Court in San Francisco with assaulting flight crew
members and interfering with their duties. He could face up to 20
years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   He was being held late Friday in a San Francisco jail. Police
had no motive for the attack, which occurred Thursday night on a
flight from Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had traveled to Mexico for a reunion with male members
of his family, said his Kansas City attorney, John P. O'Connor. The
men had taken a similar trip the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who witnesses said muttered threats and shed some of
his clothes during the ordeal, had no history of mental illness,
O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   According to O'Connor, Bradley's wife, Laura Bradley, insisted
that her husband's reported activities were totally out of
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she got the phone call from the San Francisco hospital,
she thought it was a prank phone call,'' O'Connor said. ``She was
having a hard time believing it. Even after it was reported in the
news, she was having a hard time believing this same man was her
husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had called his wife the day before his flight, O'Connor
said. The couple discussed such things as his trip and flight
times, and there was nothing to indicate anything was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bradley and the couple's 19-year-old son, Travis, flew to
San Francisco on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One hour into the Alaska Airlines flight Thursday, Peter Bradley
began doing odd things such as standing up after crew members told
him to sit down, said Alaska Airlines spokesman Lou Cancelmi.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Missouri said they had no record of problems with
Bradley other than two traffic violations in 1979. The citations
were not drug- or alcohol-related.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors were surprised by the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd characterize him as a laid-back kind of guy. I never saw
any behavior that would make me think otherwise,'' said neighbor
Earl Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bresnahan visited with Bradley on occasion and waved to him
nearly every day. He described Bradley as a ``normal, hard-working
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The person I heard about on the news was not the person I saw
out in the yard,'' Bresnahan said. ``I'm curious to find out what
happened...what would make someone do something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor was talking Friday with prosecutors and a public
defender in San Francisco, trying to get the case moved to federal
court in Kansas City. Usually, if federal prosecutors in both areas
agree, federal cases can be transferred.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said it would benefit Bradley to be near his family and
any necessary care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
