<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BARKLEY LOOKS FOR THE NEW ENEMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Erick Barkley walked down a long, winding
corridor of the McKale Center Friday afternoon, a corridor nearly
splattered with St. John's tears just hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the highest-seeded teams had barreled through the NCAA
tournament's first round. St. John's had not. Playing a listless,
tentative game, St. John's trailed Northern Arizona by a point with
10.9 seconds to play. Only a leaning shot in the lane by Lavor
Postell and his subsequent free throw had boosted St. John's to a
second-round matchup with Gonzaga Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley had played unevenly. He had attempted 12 shots and made
just two and had hit 3 of 4 free throws. But he had also handed out
six assists, had not turned the ball over and had made three
steals, including one that sealed the victory with 2.6 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really think I had a bad game; I just didn't shoot the
ball that well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley wondered why he had come out so flat Thursday night. Had
it been first-game blahs, or was there something more? All Barkley
knew was that for an evening he had lost the sense of mission that
had driven him _ nearly over the edge _ for the last month.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley thought about the rough first game. Maybe it had
something to do with a meeting this week with NCAA enforcement
officials. They had been on Barkley's trail like bloodhounds since
the first part of February, forcing St. John's to suspend him twice
_ once five minutes before a home game at Madison Square Garden.
Back home, there were large back-page photos of Barkley in tears, a
towel over his head as he watched helplessly.
</P>
<P>
   Then, during the Big East tournament, the NCAA intimated that it
was widening the investigation into circumstances surrounding
Barkley's college entrance exam taken while he attended prep school
in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   After the Big East semifinal game eight days ago, Barkley
stunned teammates and coaches by announcing that he would take a
leave of absence. He changed his mind and led St. John's to its
first Big East tournament championship in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the emotional wounds from the humiliation and embarrassment
had closed and formed a callus where lighthearted feelings used to
be. The NCAA, in Barkley's mind and in the minds of his teammates,
had become the enemy, the fuel for his ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA became the inspiration that drove Barkley, and
subsequently his team, to victory after victory. St. John's wasn't
just playing Connecticut or Syracuse or Duke or Miami. They were
playing the director of enforcement, his staff of investigators,
the news media who kept it all going.
</P>
<P>
   So this week, when Barkley actually had a cordial meeting with
investigators and they told him that they were mostly satisfied,
that he was mostly clear, that the assault was all but over,
Barkley said he felt an odd sense of relief with a sense of loss.
</P>
<P>
   The emptiness didn't really hit him until Thursday's game with
Northern Arizona. Something was missing in his game, a certain
inner anger. The NCAA was missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I kind of thought about that last night,'' Barkley said.
``After the game I was kind of thinking, `Dag, I probably need the
NCAA to mess with me some more in order for me to play good.'''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley doesn't need the headaches and heartaches of an NCAA
inquiry to make him play better. The pressure took more out of him
than he probably realized; the anger siphoned off the
once-in-a-lifetime joy of simply being here, of reveling in the
glow of a national spotlight and of feeling the natural highs and
lows, in Barkley's case, of being reunited with good friends.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Barkley will face Matt Santangelo, the Gonzaga point
guard who was his teammate last summer on the American team for the
World University Games. They hung out together in Spain. They
played cards well into the night, crushing their opponents by day.
``He's a cool guy,'' Barkley said. ``We talked a lot, not about
basketball but about school, our neighborhoods, where we grew up.''
Santangelo, a senior from Portland, Ore., had good memories as
well. He said he felt for his new, old friend as Barkley endured
the national scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   For Erick Barkley, at least, the NCAA inquiry is part of history
that is rapidly fading to black. He said he no longer needed the
false motivation of us against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being here, being in the tournament alone _ I'll thrive off of
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the game is enough.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Gonzaga will do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
