<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0712 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CENSUS-WORKERS-ART-56     03-17 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-WORKERS-ART-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS TAKERS MOVED BY MONEY AND CIVIC DUTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT31 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's not a job with a future, but the future of many
neighborhoods in the United States may be affected by how well the
job is done.
</P>
<P>
   Every 10 years the Census Bureau hires an army of census takers
_ enumerators, in bureau parlance. For the 2000 count, which has
just begun, the bureau needs about a half-million of them.
</P>
<P>
   The job lasts only six weeks or so. It involves knocking on the
doors of strangers _ people who do not return the forms that were
recently sent to every household in the nation _ and asking them
personal questions: their ages, their races, the names of their
children and, in many cases, whether they are married and how much
money they make.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, it pays $18.50 an hour _ not bad for a temp
job. It requires math, reasoning ability and an FBI background
check.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and there's also a quiz.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning, two dozen would-be census takers were
hunkered down over the test in a conference room at a Brooklyn
building, answering _ or vainly puzzling over _ the 28 questions,
which were intended to measure their mathematical, reading,
clerical and organizational skills. (Sample question: ``Ms. Jones
can't remember the year of her birth, but she knows she was born in
the month of September. If it is now May 1990, and Jones tells you
she is 78 years old, in what year was she born?'' Answer: 1911.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the thriving economy and low unemployment, many people
seem eager for the work, either because they need the money or
because they believe it is their civic duty.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, at least two applicants were there because of
population pressures in their own families. Damark Mitchell, 34,
said that he already had a full-time job as a carpenter, but that
he was willing to work nights and weekends knocking on doors. ``I
need extra money,'' he explained. ``I've got three small kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Another applicant, Jerry Schultz, 68, said he had worked as an
actor, a welfare investigator and a market researcher, among many
pursuits, but he was retired now and struggling to meet expenses
from his wife's illness. He added: ``I enjoy meeting people, so it
should be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jasmine Lozada, 20, the goal was ``saving money for
college.''
</P>
<P>
   Bureau officials say those hired will be assigned as far as
possible to the areas they live in.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials said this week that they had met 90 percent of
their goal of testing 3 million applicants nationwide for the
enumerator jobs. They want a pool of 2.4 million qualified
applicants across the country, five times the number they expect to
hire, because experience indicates that many who are found eligible
will not accept the jobs. Some will have found permanent jobs.
Others will have had second thoughts about knocking on strangers'
doors.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990 census, 35 percent of the New York region's 6.1
million households at the time failed to return the form _ the same
percentage as in the country generally.
</P>
<P>
   In its intensive effort to recruit census takers, the bureau has
announced the job openings in letters and cards mailed to every
residence in the country. Lozada said she learned about the jobs
through television announcements and fliers that the bureau had
posted on lampposts and other highly visible places, giving local
numbers to call or a national number reachable anywhere in the
country: 1-888-325-7733.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Census takers must be at least 17. They need not be citizens,
though they must be in the country legally and permitted to work.
The pay varies across the country, with the range this year _ from
a low of $8.25 an hour in Duncan, Okla., to a high of $18.50 in New
York City _ ``more competitive with local labor rates than 10 years
ago,'' said Clifton Taylor Jr., chief of recruiting. Those assigned
as crew leaders will receive somewhat more.
</P>
<P>
   The census was once handled entirely by door-to-door
enumerators. But since 1970 the bureau has relied on the
questionnaires, followed by visits to those who did not respond to
them. This time the surveys were mailed in recent days to 98
million homes. In the case of an additional 20 million homes,
mostly in rural areas where people pick up their mail at post
offices and other central locations, the forms are being delivered
to the residences.
</P>
<P>
   The forms are due back by April 1. Near the end of April, the
census takers will begin making their rounds. If nobody is home,
they are supposed to return as many as three times, and make up to
three telephone calls, said Peter Sefton, the Census Bureau's chief
of household enumeration. If those efforts fail, he said, ``they
are to try to get the information from a neighbor'' or someone like
an apartment-house manager.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990 census, not all the enumerators were so diligent;
some made up the information instead. In northern New Jersey,
census workers said some supervisors told them to fabricate data
for thousands of households in response to pressure from the
Philadelphia regional office to finish the count. As a result, the
bureau sent new enumerators to 18,000 homes at an additional cost
of several hundred thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Sefton said, the bureau is taking ``proactive steps''
to combat falsification, including checking a random sample of each
census taker's work by sending another enumerator back to the homes
in the sample.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the census say the real accuracy problem is not the
few instances of faked forms, but the undercount. In recent years
there have been politically and racially charged debates and
lawsuits about the accuracy of the census, which is used for
apportioning seats among the states in the House of Representatives
and for redistricting state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Those disputes have stemmed from the difficulty of achieving a
full and accurate count because of people who, out of fear,
suspicion or the belief that some of the questions are intrusive,
refuse to return the surveys, or provide false or incomplete
information, or try to avoid the census takers. For this reason,
census takers have a crucial role to play in persuading people to
cooperate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
