<HEADLINE>
THE WOODLANDS OPERATORS DENY REPORTS TRACK COULD CLOSE IN AUGUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Operators of The Woodlands have no plans to close the facility
on Aug. 31 or any other date, track lawyers told the Kansas Racing
and Gaming Commission during a meeting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no intention to close in August,'' said Dan Denk, a
lawyer for TRAK East, the track's nonprofit group that holds the
state racing license.
</P>
<P>
   During The Woodlands' annual relicensing review Friday at the
Kansas City, Kan., track, commission Chairman Gene Olander asked
officials to explain recent public comments by co-owner Bill Grace
that unless the Kansas Legislature approves a bill paving the way
for legal slot machine gambling, the track would be closed. Grace
was vacationing and not present.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his opinion,'' said Larry Seckington, a lawyer for
Grace's Mid Continent Racing and Gaming III company. ``Financially
we're getting stronger every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Seckington said the issue of closing has never been formally
discussed by track directors.
</P>
<P>
   Betting has been up since the first of the year by 15 percent on
dog races and 17 percent on horse races broadcast from other
tracks, Woodlands General Manager Allan Meyers said. ``We're not
closed,'' Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers said more aggressive marketing and improved food and
beverage offerings under the Grace group's management have
increased attendance by nearly 11 percent this year and spurred a
turnaround in revenues that had declined every year for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an improved balance sheet, Seckington said, ``We're
still at a break-even position. Investors deserve a return on their
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Seckington said he expects a bill to be introduced Monday in the
Kansas Senate that would permit local option voting to allow slot
machines and other electronic gambling devices at state-licensed
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Draft versions of that legislation call for the state to receive
a 20 percent share of slot revenues for education and other
purposes. The horse and dog racing industries also would receive
shares for larger purses to attract more and better-quality racing
to the state.
</P>
<P>
   The commission Friday also:
</P>
<P>
   - Deregulated the use of cell phones by track patrons. Woodlands
security chief Dave Johnson said the proliferation of cell phones
in recent years had made the rule unenforceable.
</P>
<P>
   .'' ] Johnson said security officials will continue to monitor
cell phone use at the track and enforce other state rules that
prohibit proxy betting and other gambling activities via telephone.
</P>
<P>
   - Authorized the Kansas Gaming Agency to enter arbitration to
resolve a dispute with Harrah's Prairie Band Casino near Topeka
over alcohol service on the gaming floor, which had been
prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   A $7.5 million remodeling of the tribal gambling hall was opened
to the public Friday. It added a brew pub and expanded the gaming
floor by around 250 additional slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   Gaming Agency Executive Director Tracy Diel said the casino
plans to allow alcoholic beverages to be served and consumed in
that area.
</P>
<P>
   An arbitrator now will be asked to interpret language in the
agreement between the state and the Prairie Band of Potawatomi
Tribe and decide whether beverage service must be limited to casino
bar areas only. Harrah's Entertainment Inc. operates the casino for
the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   - Heard plans from Phil Ruffin, the proposed new owner of the
long closed Camptown Racetrack in Frontenac, Kan., to reopen for
year-round simulcast betting and weekends-only live dog racing
starting July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The commission Friday granted conditional approval on Ruffin's
license application. Track officials said simulcast betting could
begin as early as next month.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffin also owns Wichita Greyhound Park and casinos in Las Vegas
and the Bahamas.
</P>
</TEXT>
