<SLUG> BC-NY-CARDINAL-ILLNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING O'CONNOR SKIPS ST. PATRICK'S EVENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While New Yorkers wondered this week whether Cardinal
John O'Connor would appear at the St. Patrick's Day Mass and
parade, his strength surged and ebbed as he struggled through the
limitations of an illness that seemed to take aim at the activities
he loves most.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, for the first time in 16 years, the cardinal was
unable to publicly celebrate Mass for St. Patrick's Day, or to
greet marchers on Fifth Avenue as they filed past the cathedral
that is named for the saint. At the cathedral, where the altar was
bedecked with green carnations, the cardinal's absence was
palpable.
</P>
<P>
   It has grown difficult for him to keep up with the daily dramas
in the city where he has played such a prominent role, said Joseph
Zwilling, a spokesman for the archdiocese. The cardinal's hearing
is weakening along with his strength, and he is having trouble with
his eyesight. An ardent reader who regularly consumed two to three
books a week, he can no longer make out the print in newspapers or
books.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was dressed and received visitors in the sitting room
at his residence, O'Connor was not strong enough to attend Mass in
the cathedral Friday, said Zwilling. ``His sense of humor is there
as always, but he was very weak,'' said the spokesman, who visited
the cardinal during the parade. ``Even if the weather had been
beautiful, he couldn't have made it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal celebrated Mass privately Friday morning in the
chapel at his residence, which is behind the cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Until his surgery last summer to remove a brain tumor, which was
followed by radiation therapy, O'Connor was an energetic, outspoken
leader of the New York archdiocese's 2.4 million Roman Catholics.
Beyond the 10 counties his archdiocese covers, the cardinal became
the best-known Catholic cleric in the country next to Pope John
Paul II, and seemed at times to be the unofficial spokesman for the
Vatican in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But as the cardinal's health has weakened, he has grown more
private. While bidding farewell to his fellow bishops in moving
letters during the last six months, the cardinal has avoided
publicly discussing the details of his illness or his prognosis.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Patrick's Cathedral on Friday, worshippers like Ed
Maloney said they missed O'Connor. Maloney, 67, a former New York
City police officer who founded the police bagpipe band in 1960,
has been coming to the St. Patrick's Day Mass for 20 years. On
Friday, he remembered the cardinal's introducing dignitaries in the
pews each St. Patrick's Day.
</P>
<P>
   One or two years ago, the cardinal surprised and delighted
Maloney, who uses a wheelchair, by introducing the retired officer
and his wife. ``I felt like I was the only guy in church,'' Maloney
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, nobody introduced the politicians and luminaries in
the audience. Maloney, for one, said he missed the showmanship of
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the spark plug that made it move,'' Maloney said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
