<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-TRAINING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERCOVER POLICE TRAINING INCLUDES IDENTIFICATION RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-POLICE-SHOOTING, NY-POLICE-PROSECUTOR)  
 (bl)  
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Undercover narcotics officers, like the detective who
fatally shot an unarmed security guard Thursday, receive several
weeks of special training to prepare them for the contingencies of
street encounters, including specific instructions on when to drop
their guise and identify themselves as officers, police officials
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of whether plainclothes officers clearly identified
themselves has figured in several recent incidents, including the
shooting of Amadou Diallo. Police critics have questioned whether
officers in civilian clothes have too often been involved in deadly
cases of confusion.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's incident, a man who was standing with the security
guard has told investigators that the guard, Patrick Dorismond,
never knew he was scuffling with the police because none of the
three plainclothes officers identified themselves during the
struggle that preceded the shooting. But the officer who fired the
fatal shot, Detective Anthony Vasquez, has said through his lawyer
that he shouted that he was a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Officers learn the department's policy on when to identify
themselves during the formal training they receive when they accept
an undercover narcotics assignment, Deputy Chief Thomas Fahey said.
</P>
<P>
   Fahey described the policy: ``If during the course of his
activities, an undercover sees someone at risk or in danger of
being killed, naturally he has got to become a police officer. And
if announcing the fact that he is a police officer would improve
the situation or help the situation, we would expect him to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Vasquez's account of the incident, he identified
himself and began fighting with Dorismond after rushing to the aid
of an undercover colleague who signaled for help when the incident
escalated into a violent argument. The two officers with Vasquez
have acknowledged to Internal Affairs investigators that they did
not identify themselves, law enforcement officials said. But the
officers said they did hear someone else, possibly Vasquez, yell
``Police'' during the scuffle.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior investigator has said that, hours after the
incident, a friend of Dorismond who was with him during the
encounter, Kevin Kaiser, still did not appear to know that it had
been a police officer who fired the fatal shot.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez has said through his lawyer that his gun discharged
accidentally during a struggle with Dorismond. Unlike patrol
officers, who are usually equipped with pepper spray and a
nightstick to subdue a suspect, most plainclothes officers often
carry only a gun, a tactic that helps them appear inconspicuous but
also means the stakes can rise rapidly during a violent
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Fahey said the rules that governed when an officer may pull his
weapon were taught to all recruits at the Police Academy. ``You are
allowed to draw your gun when you think the gun is necessary to
defend yourself or others,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fahey would not detail the rest of the training undercover
officers received because, he said, the department did not want to
do anything that might expose them to the risk of identification.
</P>
<P>
   But other officers who have received or been involved in the
training described in broad terms the strategies covered in the
three-week course, which is taught at the Brooklyn Army Terminal by
the Special Projects unit of the Narcotics Division in tandem with
senior undercover officers and other law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   The curriculum includes sessions on how to dress, how to signal
for help, what to do if you are forced to take drugs (it is allowed
if an officer believes his life is in jeopardy), verbal judo and
other street tactics, including a glossary of street terms and
values for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Casper, the prosecutor in charge of narcotic trial
operations for the Brooklyn district attorney's office, said he
often taught a part of the course that instructed undercover
officers how to prepare for trial and that the police officials who
ran the program were concerned that the training be thorough.
``Whenever I make a suggestion they have been nothing but
supportive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But one narcotics supervisor who has been involved in the
training said the team that tangled with Dorismond did not appear
to have followed one important guideline often cited during
training sessions: if a confrontation appears to be escalating,
move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want the undercovers to get hurt,'' the supervisor
said, ``so in a buy and bust we just tell them to leave if there is
any sign of a confrontation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
