<HEADLINE>
BOEING, STRIKING ENGINEERS REACH TENTATIVE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. and its engineering union struck a
tentative deal yesterday on a new contract for 22,000 employees,
setting the stage for the end to a 39-day strike that has crippled
the region's largest private employer.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative pact, which must still be approved by union
members on Sunday, contains a host of concessions sought by the
engineering union, including greater guaranteed wages, preservation
of health care benefits and a lump-sum bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Both camps are now hoping the agreement will resolve the longest
engineering strike in Boeing history and bring between 15,000 and
18,000 engineers and technical workers back to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very significant victory for (the Society of
Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace). It is a capstone
to a remarkable event in the ongoing history of labor in Seattle,''
said David Olson, a political science professor at the University
of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides assembled the proposal after a flurry of meetings
with regulators, federal mediators, and finally each other in
Washington, D.C. this week. By early Friday morning, both
negotiating teams unanimously endorsed the contract offer.
</P>
<P>
   But, the dispute isn't over yet. Union members will cast their
votes on the proposal Sunday. They already have rejected two offers
from Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, union leaders praised the latest company offer Friday,
saying it addressed many of their concerns. They also said they
were hopeful union members would eventually endorse the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got one helluva deal,'' said Tom McCarty, a member of the
union's negoatiating team.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, many rank-and-file members gave the offer a more
moderate reception. Many said they were particularly disspointed
with the company's bonus proposal, which promises $1,000 30 days
after the contract is ratified. Employees would qualify for two
other payments totaling $1,500 if the company reaches two airplane
delivery targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am teetering on the fence like I think many people are. I
don't know how I will vote until I attend the meeting tomorrow
night,'' wrote Ken Johnson, a striking union member wrote in an
e-mail response to questions from the Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   The strike also has created some bitterness among Boeing's
technical workers, who say their salaries lag far behind their
peers in the aerospace community. That sentiment and the walkout is
leading some striking employees to seek work elsewhere, according
to some union members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last few weeks many have looked around at what is
available in the market and found they can do better, in some cases
much better,'' Gerry Buss responded in an e-mail sent to the P-I.
</P>
<P>
   Members will spend Saturday and part of Sunday studying the fine
print and attending union-sponsored meetings designed to explain
the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders expected some members to be critical after they
spent an emotional 38 days on the picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (members) wanted us to come and sweep the table clean,''
Stan Sorscher, chairman of the engineering negotiating team. `` It
does takes awhile to settle down.''
</P>
<P>
   The union spent Friday highlighting the company's new
concessions, including a boost in the guaranteed wage increases
that both engineers and technical workers would receive.
</P>
<P>
   Under the contract, a technician is guaranteed a four percent
raise in the first year, and a three percent raise in each of the
next two years. Overall, the company created a pool to finance 5.5
percent in raises in the first year and 4.5. percent increases in
each successive year.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers, on the other hand, would receive a guaranteed three
percent raise every year of the contract. The company set side
another five percent in raises for merit increases, targeted
professions and a special promotion fund.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest disappointments for union negotiators was
the company's bonus proposal. They were seeking a simple payment,
similar to the 10-percent bonus members of the International
Association of Machinists received last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they settled for a bonus tied in part to company
performamce and less than the IAM payments, which averaged $4,400.
</P>
<P>
   The union did secure one of its top priorities: preservation of
much of the existing benefit package, including the absence of
co-payments by workers for health care premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has paid a steep price for the longest engineering strike
in its history. It only made three airplane deliveries in March,
and the delays forced airline customers to begin canceling flights
this week.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Boeing has seen its stock price plummet during the
strike, from 44.63 a week before the strike began to 35.63 on
Thursday. Friday, the proposed settlement gave the stock a boost,
as it rose 2.38 to close at 38.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing Wall Street does not like is ambiguity,'' said
Boeing Chairman Phil Condit at a press conference Friday. ``Now
that agreement is there, it begins to make the future a little less
cloudy.''
</P>
<P>
   Condit defended the company's latest offers as fair. He also
admitted the strike represented a major shift in relations between
Boeing managers and the company's second largest union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we can look back at this as a turning point, a
time when it was clearly recognized how important it will be to
listen carefully and understand each other,'' Condit said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Boeing executives are turning their attention to the
financial impact of the strike. They are also striving to hit their
original target of delivering 491 airplanes in 2000, assuming union
members endorse their offer. Some financial analysts, however, said
they face a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are obviously behind. Our plan is now that we have our team
back is to do everything we can to meet our committments for the
year,'' said Alan Mulally, the head of Boeing's commercial airplane
division.
</P>
<P>
   While the tentative pact holds the promise of peace at Boeing,
it's also poised to deliver a major victory to organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO played a key role in supporting the strike and in
brokering the final deal. The federation's leaders have a lot at
stake, because they have targeted white-collar workers as fertile
ground in a renewed push for new members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their victory is a win for respect and health care and pension
security for all workers,'' AFL-CIO President John Sweeney said in
a statement. ``With the largest strike of private sector
professional workers in history, they proved again the oldest of
lessons: when people join together, they can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides praised the work AFL-CIO's Secretary-Treasurer
Richard Trumka in bringing the two sides together.
</P>
<P>
   But, Trumka wasn't alone in applying pressure. Thomas
Buffenbarger, head of the International Association of Machinists,
called Boeing officials personally to stress that the company's
most powerful union stood firmly behind striking engineers and
technicians.
</P>
<P>
   UW's Olson said the region's pronounced labor shortage, the
surprising solidarity of strikers and their key role at Boeing
increased pressure on the aerospace giant.
</P>
<P>
   While labor negotiators from both sides expressed satisfaction
with the final product when they returned from Seattle on Friday,
they said the process was wearing and at times ugly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a pretty process,'' said SPEEA's Sorscher.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   The union: www.speea.org
</P>
<P>
   The company: www.boeing.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-17-00 2356EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
