<DOCNO> NYT20000317.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0725 &Cx1f; kan-z
b x BC-FETAL-TISSUE-KAN &LR;      03-17 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FETAL-TISSUE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANNED PARENTHOOD INVESTIGATING WHETHER DOCUMENTS STOLEN FROM
CLINIC  
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Planned Parenthood is investigating reports that
documents were stolen from its Overland Park clinic, possibly as
part of a national campaign against collection of aborted fetal
tissue for medical research.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. House subcommittee may have used financial documents
stolen from the clinic as evidence at a hearing March 9, Planned
Parenthood lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, Eric Harrah, a former employee of Life
Dynamics Inc., a Texas anti-abortion group, alleged in a sworn
affidavit that patient and physician records, as well as financial
spreadsheets, were taken in January from Comprehensive Health. The
Overland Park clinic is affiliated with Planned Parenthood of
Kansas and Mid-Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   While it is not clear the two allegations concern the same
documents, Roger Evans, a lawyer for Planned Parenthood in New
York, said, ``It's about as serious an allegation as you can
make.''
</P>
<P>
   No complaint has been filed with Overland Park police because it
is not certain how or what records were acquired from the thousands
of patient files, he said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus far we have not gotten anything to corroborate these
stories that there were crimes,'' he said. '
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to move heaven and earth to see what happened,
but you don't do it overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit sworn out March 7, Harrah alleged that $1,500
was paid to a former clinic employee, who entered the clinic after
hours and took records relating to tissue extraction.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Crutcher, Life Dynamics president, characterized Harrah's
allegations of stolen records as ``nonsense'' on Thursday. ``He's
lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Crutcher said any documents Life Dynamics acquired on abortions
or fetal tissue work came from ``infiltrators'' and
``whistle-blowers in the abortion industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning Harrah's charges, Life Dynamics posted a
general denial of ``burglary or any other criminal activity'' on
its Web site Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   According to Harrah's affidavit, he saw the documents, which
included originals with names of patients, employees and doctors as
well as addresses, phone numbers and Social Security numbers. He
also described financial spreadsheets and a training manual.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah alleged that anti-abortion activists might contact
patients in the files to see if they had consented to donate fetal
tissue after the abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Planned Parenthood said all women sign consent forms, all
according to the law. Peter Brownlie, president and chief executive
officer of Planned Parenthood of Kansas and Mid-Missouri, said he
has not heard from any clients that they have been contacted about
the fetal tissue issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We place the highest value on patient confidentiality, privacy
and trust and we are going to investigate just as quickly as we
can,'' Brownlie said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's affidavit surfaces in the midst of an FBI investigation
into whether fetal tissue extracted at the Overland Park clinic was
improperly marketed by companies that had contracts with Planned
Parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   Fetal tissue is used in research to find cures for diseases from
juvenile diabetes to Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   Two companies, Anatomic Gift and Opening Lines, paid rent to
Comprehensive Health to use its facilities to extract tissue, such
as brain matter or livers. The clinic ended its contracts with the
companies and says the practice is not occurring at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Current federal law prohibits anything but ``reasonable'' fees
to be charged for the collection of organs and their transport to
medical researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-abortion activists contend that companies may be profiting
off the abortion trade. They also argue that women do not have a
clear understanding of the procedures and that some might be
influenced to put off abortions until the fetal tissue is more
developed, a charge Planned Parenthood rejects.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah, who once operated East Coast and Midwest abortion
clinics, was a national spokesman for a woman's right to choose
before switching sides in the debate a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He still opposes abortion, he said in an interview, but believes
that Crutcher's tactics are setting the cause back. ``He has caused
the pro-life movement harm in an election year.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrah said he warned a member of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, which had planned last month to look into fetal tissue,
that some documents being offered had been stolen. The Senate
hearing never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah said he did not make the same call to the House, where
the Health and Environment subcommittee also planned to hold
hearings. There, some financial records from Comprehensive Health
were entered as evidence, according to James Fitzpatrick, another
Planned Parenthood attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick wrote a March 9 letter to the House panel's
Republican chairman and the senior Democrat informing them that he
was asked by the subcommittee to authenticate 17 pages of
spreadsheets and other accounting reports.
</P>
<P>
   His letter recounted his question to Republican staff on the
House subcommittee whether the records ``were stolen from our
Planned Parenthood clinic in Overland Park, Kan. The majority staff
answer was in the affirmative.''
</P>
<P>
   Planned Parenthood found the originals of some of the documents
in its files, Fitzpatrick's letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican staff spokesman Steve Schmidt, however, denied Friday
that staff knew whether the documents were stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Crutcher's Web site says his group worked with the subcommittee
staff, which he criticized for ultimately mishandling the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provided them with orders for baby parts, price lists for
baby parts, ...internal abortion industry financial records related
to the sale of baby parts... Then we spent hours and hours going
over each of these documents with them to make certain they
understood their significance.''
</P>
<P>
   Crutcher acknowledges having hired people to work undercover to
gather information about fetal tissue work at the clinic. One of
them, Lawrence Dean Alberty Jr. of Lee's Summit, testified at the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty, who once worked as a medical technician for the two
companies collecting the tissue, also admitted taking some records
from one of the firms. He is not the person to whom Harrah's
affidavit refers in the alleged January record pilfering.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Jones, a Lee's Summit pathologist who heads a fetal tissue
extraction company, last week wrote the Justice Department, asking
it to investigate Alberty and Life Dynamics for corporate
espionage. Jones, meanwhile, could be cited for contempt by the
House for failing to answer a subpoena to testify before the
subcommittee last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had other infiltrators in there besides Dean Alberty,''
Crutcher said Thursday. ``We got copies just like we did with
Dean.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrah said he went to work for Life Dynamics on Dec. 28 to
explain how abortion clinics operate and market its anti-abortion
materials. Crutcher offered no details about Harrah's departure
from the group last month, other than he was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah, who now lives in New York, said he approached Planned
Parenthood with his allegation of stolen records because of his
concern for the patients. He contacted Evans, senior director of
public policy litigation and law at Planned Parenthood Federation
of America in New York.
</P>
<P>
   At a Feb. 14 meeting, he said, Evans prepared a 17-paragraph
affidavit based on their conversation. Harrah signed it and had it
notarized in New York on March 7. Harrah provided a copy of the
affidavit to The Kansas City Star.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
